<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-SECESSION-STUDY-LADN </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
L.A. SECESSION PETITIONERS REJECT PROVISO TO SHOULDER LAWSUIT
BILLS
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
BY MICHAEL COIT  
 c.1999 Los Angeles Daily News  
<TEXT>
<P>
   LOS ANGELES -- Valley Voters Organized Toward Empowerment flatly
rejected demands Wednesday that it agree to pay the cost of
defending Los Angeles County in any lawsuits arising from a
secession study sought by one-fourth of the suburban San Fernando
Valley's voters.
</P>
<P>
   The issue surfaced at a meeting of the county's Local Agency
Formation Commission and stalled the formal application for the
unprecedented secession study.
</P>
<P>
   LAFCO officials never sought such an indemnity clause for
lawsuits before in considering cityhood proposals in unincorporated
areas. Officials said they borrowed the idea from provisions used
in other California counties, which, in cases such as subdivision
boundaries, require applicants to pay for defending lawsuits that
might be filed in response to agency approvals.
</P>
<P>
   ``Talk about a chilling affect -- it's worse than ice cubes.
We're in the deep arctic freeze here,'' said John Walker, a
Woodland Hills attorney and one of the trio of suburban San
Fernando Valley residents who became the ``chief petitioners'' by
signing the first petition.
</P>
<P>
   Walker, speaking for fellow applicants Carlos Ferreyra and Marie
Harris, charged that the county added the provision in July, two
months after the cityhood drive began. He said it forces the
applicants to risk their personal assets and life's savings and
either shouldn't apply or should be changed.
</P>
<P>
   LAFCO members said the county needs to protect itself from
lawsuits filed against an agency merely doing its job.
</P>
<P>
   ``There needs to be some kind of provision to protect us as a
governmental entity. We're talking about something here that
involves billions and billions and billions of dollars, massive
interests,'' said Supervisor Yvonne Brathwaite Burke.
</P>
<P>
   The indemnity provision is the latest obstacle in the path of
the secession movement.
</P>
<P>
   Wednesday's debate was similar to one over the question of who
should pay to verify the more than 200,000 signatures Valley VOTE
collected on cityhood petitions. Los Angeles County ultimately
paid, yielding to challenges that citizens shouldn't be charged to
petition government.
</P>
<P>
   Valley VOTE tallied 132,490 signatures from registered Valley
voters, which was 719 signatures over the total required.
</P>
<P>
   The cityhood study, however, can't go forward without an
application following the successful petition drive.
</P>
<P>
   Walker told LAFCO the three chief petitioners represented those
voters who want a study and the agency shouldn't deny them. ``We
are the agents for those people. That's all we are able to do.''
</P>
<P>
   LAFCO called on attorneys representing the county and the
petitioners to seek a compromise.
</P>
<P>
   ``We need to clear the air on this thing,'' said Valley
Councilman Hal Bernson who represents the Los Angeles City Council
on LAFCO. ``I think we need to protect ourself, but we've never
required anybody to be personally liable.''
</P>
<P>
   Burke was particularly critical of Valley VOTE's opposition to
the indemnity provision. Similar to her opposition to the county
paying for the signature verification cost, Burke said secession
supporters should have considered potential costs associated with
the effort.
</P>
<P>
   ``This cannot be handled in what we call an `Amos and Andy' way.
You need to think about it carefully and decide what you're
doing,'' Burke said.
</P>
<P>
   Bernson countered that Valley VOTE was a citizens group and not
some sort of ``government in exile'' that can anticipate every step
in such an unprecedented process.
</P>
<P>
   Valley VOTE leaders said the petitioners and the organization
recognize they might face lawsuits. Indeed, Valley VOTE is forming
a foundation to raise money for such costs.
</P>
<P>
   But they won't commit to paying the county's legal costs.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's a blank check that the applicants are signing. It's just
not right, it's not fair, it's not constitutional to require a
person to take on that responsibility,'' said Valley VOTE attorney
John Isen.
</P>
<P>
   Taking issue with Valley VOTE's charge that the county was
putting up another roadblock, LAFCO Executive Director Larry
Calemine noted that the commission changed its policy on the
signature verification fee and pushed for the county to pay the
costs.
</P>
<P>
   ``This commission has bent over backwards. And it seems that
they . . . are constantly coming in, month after month, to request
changes to policy issues,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   Calemine also questioned why the group raised the issue for the
first time this week.
</P>
<P>
   Supervisor Zev Yaroslavsky, who chairs the LAFCO committee
overseeing the study process, defended Valley VOTE.
</P>
<P>
   ``They were obsessed with getting the requisite number of
signatures.''
</P>
<P>
   X X X &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
