<HEADLINE>
MAVERICKS FANS RAIN BOOS UPON NASH IN LOSS TO ROCKETS
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By DWAIN PRICE 
c.1999 Fort Worth Star-Telegram 
<TEXT>
<P>
   DALLAS _ The long-suffering Mavericks fans took a hard stance in
the third quarter. They booed one of their own _ point guard Steve
Nash.
</P>
<P>
   In the midst of the Mavericks' 88-78 loss to the Houston Rockets
last night at Reunion Arena, the Mavericks fans booed Nash as if he
were an enemy player. The intensity of the jeering toward a player
perhaps has not been heard in this building since Mavericks fans
booed Kiki Vandeweghe after he refused to play for Dallas when the
Mavericks made him the franchise's first draft pick in 1980.
</P>
<P>
   Nash said he noticed the booing right away, when he rechecked
into the game late in the third period. At the time, Nash was
scoreless and was 0-of-8 from the field in a game the Mavericks
trailed at one point by 16 points.
</P>
<P>
   ``The fans pay money to come watch us play, and they have every
right to cheer us, to boo us, or to have any reaction that they
please,'' Nash said. ``I didn't play well, I didn't shoot the ball
well and they weren't happy about it, and they showed their
displeasure and that's fine.
</P>
<P>
   ``I've never seen anything quite like that, but it's just the
nature of the business. \RLast\S Saturday night I had a big game
\Rwith 22 points against Sacramento\S and the crowd cheered, and
now I had a poor game and the crowd voiced their displeasure, and
they have every right to do that.''
</P>
<P>
   Not so, said guard Michael Finley, who took exception to the
crowd's reaction to Nash's poor game.
</P>
<P>
   ``I didn't appreciate that at all,'' Finley said. ``True fans of
any sport, you don't boo the home team. When things are going
downhill like they were _ for not only Steve, but for the team _
that's the time when fans should be behind a team or an individual
and cheer for them more.
</P>
<P>
   ``But to hear them boo our own player, I was very disappointed.
Hopefully that was just a spur of ignorance on the side of the fans
who were booing.''
</P>
<P>
   Rockets forward Charles Barkley, who was a teammate of Nash's
when the two were in Phoenix, gave Nash a hug before the fourth
quarter started. After the game, he criticized the fans.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'm very disappointed in the Dallas fans,'' Barkley said.
``He's a good kid. I like him a lot.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'm disappointed they treated him like that. Why don't they
send him to down to Houston? We'll take him.''
</P>
<P>
   After the initial verbal assault on Nash, the fans booed him
every time he touched the basketball, except when he drilled a
3-point basket with 6:02 left. Nash finished the game 1-of-10 from
the field with three points, five assists and no turnovers.
</P>
<P>
   The booing also could have been perceived as a direct slap at a
Mavericks organization that gave up this summer's first-round draft
pick to Phoenix for Nash. And, before this season, the Mavericks
signed Nash to a six-year, $33 million contract extension, and all
but labeled him as this team's cornerstone point guard.
</P>
<P>
   ``We know he's a much better player than he's playing,''
Mavericks coach/general manager Don Nelson said. ``He's got to
toughen up, that's all.
</P>
<P>
   ``He's got to prove to people that he's a player. If it takes
hitting the bottom of the barrel, which maybe he did tonight, then
let's see. Let's grow up and get some skin under our nose and let's
prove to people we can play this game.''
</P>
<P>
   Nash said his confidence is not shattered.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'd always sort of been a fan favorite, and not really the
goat,'' he said. ``It's a new challenge for me.
</P>
<P>
   ``But at the end of the day and the end of your life, if you
have the opportunity to take the easy street, or take the tough
path and actually learn and grow and face a little adversity, I
think you'll learn a lot more and you'll become a stronger
person.''
nn
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
