<HEADLINE>
L.A. SERB IMMIGRANTS WORRY ABOUT NATO ATTACK
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
BY SHARLINE CHIANG  
 c.1999 Los Angeles Daily News  
<TEXT>
<P>
   LOS ANGELES -- Serbians and Albanians living in the San Fernando
Valley watched and listened nervously as newscasts showed exploding
airstrikes in Kosovo all day Wednesday.
</P>
<P>
   Many said they felt helpless witnessing the bombings from
halfway across the globe, all the while fearing for the lives and
well-being of family and friends.
</P>
<P>
   Woodland Hills resident Veroljub Radivojevic, 61, a Serbian
immigrant, wondered how the war would affect his sister and
brother-in-law still who live in Belgrade. Airstrikes reportedly
struck outside the city limits.
</P>
<P>
   ``Oh yeah, I'm worried. Not only for them but for all Serbian
people,'' said Radivojevic, a retired civil engineer. ``If they
continue like this they will destroy Serbia. It is a small
country.''
</P>
<P>
   Majlinda Gjikuria, 26, was keenly aware that Wednesday she would
have still been in her home outside the Albanian capital of Tirana
-- a city only about 50 miles away from the Kosovo-Albania border
-- if she hadn't won a U.S. green card in a lottery that allowed
her to move permanently to America just three weeks ago.
</P>
<P>
   ``I am really scared. I have friends all over Albania,'' said
Gjikuria, whose family left Albania and now lives in Greece. ``This
war is too much for them. Everyone is trying to get out of Albania
but they can't get visas.''
</P>
<P>
   Nora Hughes, who has invited Gjikuria to stay at her Granada
Hills home, lived in Albania for two years on a Fulbright
scholarship and worked to improve the justice system there.
</P>
<P>
   ``It is very hard. (Tirana) is 50 miles from the border of
Kosovo so you are not talking about any great distance,'' she said.
``The Serbs have been coming over the board for a year and people
are scared to death. They're saying, how can we get out?''
</P>
<P>
   Serbians, Albanians and supporters of both ethnic groups
expressed sorrow over the violence.
</P>
<P>
   ``NATO is for defense, not for attack,'' Radivojevic said.
``Yeah, Milosevic is a bad man but it's the Serbian people who are
the victims. If they have something against Milosevic, they should
go against him. Use other ways, diplomatic ways, pressuring way . .
. something better than this.''
</P>
<P>
   Radivojevic said he is helping to organize a protest by area
Serbs and Serbian-Americans for 2 p.m. Saturday in front of the
federal building in Westwood. David Hartsough, executive director
of the Peaceworkers organization in San Francisco, spent the past
two and a half years supporting Albanians working toward nonviolent
solutions for peace in Kosovo.
</P>
<P>
   ``Our first response (to Wednesday's airstrikes) is really great
sorrow that during nine years of very significant nonviolent
movement the whole international community stood by and did
nothing,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   He said he couldn't help sensing a sad irony in the airstrikes.
</P>
<P>
   ``I don't think that our message that killing civilians is wrong
can be gotten across by killing civilians ourselves,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   X X X &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
