<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BKN-LAKERNOTES-LADN </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
REID TAKES TURN AT FORWARD ROULETTE
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By HOWARD BECK  
 c.1999 Los Angeles Daily News  
<TEXT>
<P>
   INGLEWOOD, Calif. _ J.R. Reid now knows how Corie Blount felt.
And how Robert Horry feels. And what Rick Fox has gone through.
</P>
<P>
   On a roster where seven of 12 players are forwards, and with
four guys who could arguably start at the big forward slot, no
one's minutes are certain. And now Reid, who started all 16 games
with Charlotte and led the Hornets with 15.2 points per game, is
just another guy struggling for minutes in the Los Angeles Lakers'
rotation.
</P>
<P>
   Reid averaged 17.4 minutes and 4.4 points in his first five
games here, then watched his next two from the bench once Dennis
Rodman returned from his Las Vegas vacation.
</P>
<P>
   And just when Reid had resigned himself to the role of high-paid
spectator, coach Kurt Rambis sent him in for Shaquille O'Neal just
four minutes into Wednesday's game against Phoenix.
</P>
<P>
   Just another day in the life of a Lakers power forward. Fifteen
minutes one day, DNP the next.
</P>
<P>
   ``I kind of expected it,'' Reid said. ``I kind of thought
something like this would happen. But I just try to stay positive
and be ready when I get my opportunities again.''
</P>
<P>
   He's made the most of limited playing time and made an instant
impact Wednesday. Reid had four points and four rebounds in his
first eight minutes, helping the Lakers rebound from an early
double-digit deficit.
</P>
<P>
   A free agent this summer and in search of a raise from his
$700,000 contract, Reid said he's OK with the situation.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's tough going from playing a lot to not playing, but that's
just a transition you have to make going to a championship team,''
he said. ``Hopefully, I've played enough so far that teams know
what I can do.''
</P>
<P>
   Rambis has been impressed with Reid and said his sporadic
playing time _ like Horry's and Fox's _ is no reflection on the job
he's done.
</P>
<P>
   ``That's the aspect of my job, is there's absolutely nothing
those guys have done wrong to not deserve time,'' Rambis said.
``They all deserve time.... We have a very talented ballclub and
it's hard to go 12 deep in a game.''
</P>
<P>
   Breather: After surviving a brutal six-game, nine-day road trip,
the Lakers were more than a little relieved to take Tuesday off. No
game, no practice.
</P>
<P>
   Kobe Bryant still played some hoop but found time to visit with
his niece as well.
</P>
<P>
   ``It definitely felt good. When (Rambis) said `day off,' you
just heard everybody go like, `Whew,''' Bryant said. ``It feels
good to just kind of mellow out a little bit, catch up on life,
other things besides basketball.''
</P>
<P>
   Then again, the time off didn't give Rambis much time to relax.
</P>
<P>
   ``One kid was sick, the other was home _ I played some ball with
him _ watched a bunch of videotape, unpacked, did about five loads
of laundry and bada-boom, bada-bing, it was time to go to bed,''
Rambis said.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
