<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-03-25 01:06 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A3392 &Cx1f; tic-z
r a &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-MEDICAL-DEATH-AZR &LR;      03-25 1443
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-MEDICAL-DEATH-AZR </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
DOCTOR DENIES OFFICE TURNED AWAY TEEN WHO DIED 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by N.Y. Times News Service clients)  
 By GRACIELA SEVILLA  
 and JODIE SNYDER  
 c.1999 The Arizona Republic  
<TEXT>
<P>
   A Mesa doctor denied Wednesday that he refused to treat a
13-year-old girl who died hours later of a ruptured appendix.
</P>
<P>
   As hundreds of people poured out their support and expressed
outrage over the death of Gricelda Zamora, Dr. Stuart Agren, in a
written statement, said Gricelda did not appear critically ill when
she came into his office last Thursday, and had been at a hospital
emergency room only minutes before.
</P>
<P>
   His account contradicts that of the child's family.
</P>
<P>
   Antonio Zamora Quintero, the girl's father, maintains that he
carried a very sick and weak Gricelda into Agren's office where
they waited for 45 minutes without medical attention while office
workers questioned the family's medical coverage, ability to pay
and Gricelda's immigration status.
</P>
<P>
   Zamora also disputed Agren's statement late Monday, saying
Gricelda did not go from the emergency room to Agren's office.
</P>
<P>
   Some three hours after leaving Agren's office March 18, Gricelda
was airlifted to Good Samaritan Regional Medical Center, where she
died.
</P>
<P>
   Agren stated that his office staff worked with the family
members to see if their insurance was valid before saying that they
did not need to have money upfront before Griselda was treated.
</P>
<P>
   But, according to Zamora, the clerks did not accept his
insurance cards and told him the doctor would see Gricelda if he
had $65 to pay for the visit. Zamora said he did not have the cash.
</P>
<P>
   An angry Zamora disputed Agren's version saying, ``Everything
they say is false. I have repeated my story many times and I have
witnesses.``
</P>
<P>
   Through his employer, Gallo Insulation, Zamora has medical
insurance for his family. Russ Bonsall, personnel manager for
Gallo, confirmed that the Zamora family was covered by a health
care plan with Principal Life Insurance. Both Bonsall and Principal
Life Insurance verified that Agren is an approved plan doctor.
</P>
<P>
   Patients covered by the plan can see Agren with a $10
co-payment, according to Principal Life.
</P>
<P>
   The death of the sixth-grade cheerleader set off an outpouring
of support and outrage in the community. Many grieved over the dead
teenager and asked how it could happen.
</P>
<P>
   On Wednesday, the Mexican government pledged to hire an attorney
to represent the Zamora family. Antonio Zamora immigrated from
Mexico with his wife, Inez, and Gricelda when the girl was an
infant. He is now a legal resident.
</P>
<P>
   ``We are looking at those medical personnel who rejected this
girl while she was in pain,'' said Miguel Angel Isidro, acting
chief of the Mexican Consulate in Phoenix. ``This is a very, very
confused case in which some bad decisions were made.`'
</P>
<P>
   Gricelda's death came after an appendicitis attack went
undetected by emergency room doctors at Mesa Lutheran Hospital and
hours after her family sought care in Agren's office three days
later.
</P>
<P>
   ``The family thanked them and then left. That was the last
information the office had on them,'' said Barry Halpern, an
attorney representing Agren.
</P>
<P>
   Halpern said that he did not know if Agren saw Gricelda in the
waiting room.
</P>
<P>
   Agren's version of the events surrounding Gricelda's final hours
differ from the family's on several points, according to Halpern:
</P>
<P>
   Zamora had been in Mesa Lutheran's emergency department a second
time, minutes before she had gone to Agren's office. If she had
been gravely ill, why had the emergency department let her leave?
Under federal law, they are obligated to treat her, Halpern said.
</P>
<P>
   When the office staff tried to verify the insurance cards that
the family gave, they couldn't determine if the family was covered.
That's why the office staff asked about their Social Security
numbers.
</P>
<P>
   ``My staff, my family and I share the Zamora family's grief over
the loss of Gricelda Zamora. We hope that with the passage of time
and after further reflection, there will be more fair and balanced
account of the events which are now subject to considerable
discussion and speculation,'' Agren's statement reads.
</P>
<P>
   The family went to Agren after being referred to him by the
hospital emergency department.
</P>
<P>
   Because the family didn't initially contact Agren until two days
after the emergency-room visit, that may mean Agren is not
responsible for care, Halpern said.
</P>
<P>
   But the Arizona Board of Medical Examiners is taking a different
view.
</P>
<P>
   ``If you are a doctor on the on-call roster and you are assigned
patients for follow-up, you shouldn't be refusing those patients
care,'' BOMEX spokesman Eric Nickell said.
</P>
<P>
   BOMEX is gathering information about the case to determine if
they should file a complaint against Agren.
</P>
<P>
   Nickell said the board will be investigating if Gricelda's
treatment at Agren's office fell short of medical standards.
</P>
<P>
   The board also will look at how much Agren and his staff knew
about the family in the waiting room, especially Gricelda's
condition, and at what kind of protocols they had for turning away
patients, Nickell said.
</P>
<P>
   ``There are a number of different theories. There is the captain
of the ship theory that a doctor is responsible for what goes on in
his office. There is also theory that a doctor should treat a
patient if that patient needs treatment,'' Nickell said.
</P>
<P>
   Agren, who has been licensed in Arizona since 1985, has received
one letter of complaint concerning false advertising from the
Arizona Board of Medical Examiners.
</P>
<P>
   Around the Valley, ``Republic'' readers reacted with sympathy
and generosity for the Zamora family, who could not afford to pay
for Gricelda's funeral and burial. Hundreds of people pledged
donations and several individuals, mortuaries and community groups
offered to pay for funeral expenses.
</P>
<P>
   Peoria pawn shop owner Alex Gonzalez offered to pay for the
funeral after crying when he read Gricelda's story in the paper
Wednesday morning.
</P>
<P>
   ``I was told they didn't have money and that's one pressure they
don't need right now. I thought I would try to be a blessing to
them,'' he said. ``But it's nothing compared to what they lost.''
</P>
<P>
   Gonzalez won a $1.4 million judgment against the Phoenix Police
Department last year when a jury ruled in his favor in a malicious
prosecution case.
</P>
<P>
   Gricelda was a popular cheerleader at Eisenhower Elementary
School in Mesa. After learning of her death over spring break, the
school began raising money to help her family.
</P>
<P>
   ``On Saturday, we did a carwash with parents, teachers and kids
washing cars in the front parking lot. They raised about $400,''
said Principal Phelps Wilkins.
</P>
<P>
   When classes resumed Monday, a battery of counselors was on hand
to help students cope with the loss.
</P>
<P>
   ``Some of the kids took it very hard,'' Phelps said. ``She had
been here since the first grade.''
</P>
<P>
   Gricelda's death also inspired others to mobilize.
</P>
<P>
   A group of medical workers from a hospital emergency room in
Williams also took up a collection.
</P>
<P>
   Debbie Donoho, who manages a jazz club in Scottsdale, wants to
organize a benefit concert to help the Zamoras.
</P>
<P>
   ``I am extremely angered by what happened to this little girl,''
she said. ``It is just inexcusable. There's no reason that little
girl should've died.''
</P>
<P>
   Meanwhile, at the family home grief and exhaustion were taking
their toll. Antonio Zamora spent hours recounting the story for a
parade of television, radio and newspaper reporters who came to the
door of his wooden bungalow.
</P>
<P>
   Other family members made arrangements for the funeral Mass,
which is set for Friday at Queen of Peace Catholic Church in Mesa.
</P>
<P>
   Jennifer Lopez, who accompanied the Zamoras when they took
Gricelda to Agren's office and later to the emergency room,
recalled her neighbor's last words with sadness.
</P>
<P>
   ``She was laying in the emergency room bed waiting for the
helicopter to come take her away and she asked her dad to give her
a kiss,'' Lopez said.
</P>
<P>
   Gricelda, she says, seemed to know she would not survive.
</P>
<P>
   ``She told her father she had three wishes. She wanted her
cheerleading outfit to be picked up at school and brought home. She
wanted all her uncles and aunts to come, and she asked her father
to take care of her (five younger) brothers and sisters,'' she
said.
</P>
<P>
   Two hours after the helicopter flew her to Good Samaritan,
Gricelda succumbed to infection.
</P>
<P>
   ``I didn't see that she was scared,'' said Lopez.
</P>
<P>
   ``I think she died with dignity of all the good stuff she did
here. Her head was held up knowing she was a good kid.'' &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-03-25-99 0106EST &QL; 
