<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-03-25 01:13 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A3395 &Cx1f; tth-z
u s &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-BKC-BENDER-SPI &LR;      03-25 1042
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BKC-BENDER-SPI </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
UW'S BENDER TURNS DOWN VANDERBILT JOB OFFER 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients.)  
 By JIM MOORE  
 c.1999 Seattle Post-Intelligencer  
<TEXT>
<P>
   In contrast to speculation about his future, Bob Bender was not
all over the map Wednesday. He gave straight-forward responses.
Once the Final Four concludes on Monday, the University of
Washington basketball coach will be headed in one direction _ home.
</P>
<P>
   In a telephone news conference Wednesday from St. Petersburg,
Fla., Bender announced that he is spurning the job offer at
Vanderbilt and staying at Washington. He said the decision was made
Tuesday night after discussions with his wife, Alice, and revealed
Wednesday morning to Vanderbilt athletic director Todd Turner.
</P>
<P>
   ``With what we still want to accomplish, it became very obvious
that Washington is a place where we need to be and want to be,''
Bender said.
</P>
<P>
   On his list of factors, Bender did not list any ``cons'' with
the Commodores, just many more ``pros'' with the Huskies.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's all to do with Washington,'' he said. ``No way does it
reflect negatively on Vanderbilt. Motivation is also a big part of
the decision. We want to prove where we brought the program can be
expanded and built upon. Now we need to get to it.''
</P>
<P>
   Bender was contacted by Vanderbilt last week. He spent Monday
and Tuesday in Nashville touring the campus, talking to Turner and
the chancellor. Bender was intrigued by the private-school status
of Vanderbilt, which is similar to Duke, where he was a player and
an assistant coach.
</P>
<P>
   He said Vanderbilt's rigid academic standards were not an issue
and kept coming back to the qualities at Washington simply being
more attractive.
</P>
<P>
   Input from his wife figured prominently, he said. Even though
her father graduated from Vanderbilt's medical school, Alice Bender
favored a return to Washington. Bender was reminded of all their
great friendships in Seattle, a city where their children (Mary, 3,
and Robert Jr., 7 months) were born.
</P>
<P>
   ``She had a very important role,'' Bender said of Alice. ``She's
a rational person. Many times wives have to take the brunt of so
many things. In an instance like this, there are very difficult
emotions to deal with. A place like Seattle becomes much more
ingrained in what a family is all about.''
</P>
<P>
   The Benders also felt loyalty to the Huskies themselves.
</P>
<P>
   ``Her relationship with the players is very much like mine,''
Bender said. ``What players mean to you always enters into it.''
</P>
<P>
   For the second straight year, Bender flirted with another
university, and Florida State even showed modest interest in 1997.
Last year Texas called.
</P>
<P>
   Bender has been criticized for having a supposedly wandering
eye. But he says he is just checking out opportunities, each
fact-finding mission taking him back to Washington.
</P>
<P>
   ``He is being unfairly ridiculed by some of the fans,'' said
Husky assistant coach Byron Boudreaux. ``Just because he's being
courteous to Vanderbilt, people thought that showed a lack of
commitment.
</P>
<P>
   ``When you're as desirable as he is and all these people (Texas
and Vanderbilt) want to pay you all this money and you still come
back _ that's commitment.''
</P>
<P>
   Bender said he can't control the timing of the openings but does
not want to be perceived as an unsettled coach, realizing the
strain he is putting on athletic director Barbara Hedges.
</P>
<P>
   ``I can't predict the future, but I don't want to put her
through this every spring,'' he said. ``I'd be very cautious to
ever say five to 10 years from now I will still be coaching at
Washington. I hope I will. That means we're doing things the right
way.''
</P>
<P>
   Said Hedges: ``It would have to be something exceptional for Bob
to look at anything in the near future.''
</P>
<P>
   Vanderbilt never formally offered the job to Bender, but it was
understood that he was the leading candidate. No one else had been
asked to come to Nashville for an interview.
</P>
<P>
   Wednesday, Bender refuted many conjectured reasons why he might
want to leave Washington. Criticism of his coaching in the
first-round game of the NCAA tournament game did not bother him.
</P>
<P>
   ``It shows people care,'' he said. ``It's been a positive for
the program. It's shown that we've progressed from a point where
people didn't pay much attention.''
</P>
<P>
   Bender did not use his dalliance with Vanderbilt as a way of
sweetening his own contract at Washington. He told Hedges that he
did not want his contract changed at all.
</P>
<P>
   ``There was no ulterior motive,'' Bender said. ``It was a unique
institution I wanted to learn more about. It meant in no way that I
was leaning toward leaving Washington.''
</P>
<P>
   The fact that football reigns at Washington is viewed as an
asset.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's been a huge bonus and ally in rebuilding the (basketball)
program,'' Bender said. ``The vision Barbara Hedges has for
Washington is the same that Todd Turner has at Vanderbilt _ in
today's age you can be successful in all sports you offer.''
</P>
<P>
   Said Hedges: ``I definitely have a vision for the program and
Bob Bender is such an important person in that vision. I told him
that.''
</P>
<P>
   In the short term, the vision is blurry. The Huskies lost their
two best players, Todd MacCulloch and Donald Watts, to graduation.
Next year's starting center likely will be a junior college
transfer. The best returning scoring threat is Deon Luton, who
varies between fantastic and erratic.
</P>
<P>
   The Huskies signed two players in November _ Ben Coffee, a
6-foot-6 guard from Benson Tech High in Portland, and Will Perkins,
a 6-9 JC transfer from Iowa Western.
</P>
<P>
   They have two more scholarships to offer. The most likely
candidates are all JC players _ David Dixon, a 6-10 center from
Tyler, Texas; Julius Hicks, a 6-9 forward from West Valley in
Saratoga, Calif.; and Livan Pyfrom, a 6-11 center from East
Oklahoma State.
</P>
<P>
   At Vanderbilt, Bender could have had nine of the top 10
returning Commodores. But that job will be someone else's, perhaps
going to Quin Snyder, the Duke assistant and Mercer Island graduate
who appears to be the No. 1 candidate now.
</P>
<P>
   Bender recognizes and relishes the challenges ahead.
</P>
<P>
   ``Sometimes you have to follow your heart,'' he said.
``Washington is where I need to be.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
