<SLUG> BC-FBN-KITNA-CARD-SPI </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
SEAHAWKS' KITNA TOPS TRADING CARD HOT LIST 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients.)  
 By CLARE FARNSWORTH  
 c.1999 Seattle Post-Intelligencer  
<TEXT>
<P>
   KIRKLAND, Wash. _ Jon Kitna thought it was strange just having a
football card of himself. Now, the Seahawks quarterback has the
hottest card in the NFL.
</P>
<P>
   Kitna's 1997 Pacific Crown Royale rookie card is listed atop the
``What's Hot'' list in the April issue of Beckett Football, a
magazine and price guide that has become the bible of card
collecting. Kitna vaulted past Randy Moss, who was an All-Pro
receiver in his rookie season with the Minnesota Vikings.
</P>
<P>
   ``They must not have made very many of them,'' Kitna said
Wednesday, displaying a typical low-key approach to his growing
popularity.
</P>
<P>
   That is part of it.
</P>
<P>
   Pacific Trading Cards, based in Lynnwood, was the only card
manufacturer to make a rookie card for the undrafted passer from
Central Washington University, and it produced an extremely limited
number.
</P>
<P>
   But Beckett also points to the arrival of Mike Holmgren as
Seahawks coach and general manager, which has sparked the obvious
comparisons of Kitna to a young Brett Favre and a young Steve Young
_ two quarterbacks who blossomed into All-Pro status under
Holmgren's tutelage in Green Bay and San Francisco.
</P>
<P>
   Then there is Kitna, who's as likable as he is unassuming, as
talented as he is inexperienced and on the verge of a breakout
season for himself and his team.
</P>
<P>
   An entire nation of card collectors is noticing. Not only has
Kitna's rookie card jumped from off the chart in February, to No. 4
in March to No. 1 in April, its value has increased from $2.50 in
December, to $12 in February to $30 in April. And his 1997 Pacific
Revolution card has jumped from No. 10 on the hot list in March to
No. 4 in April.
</P>
<P>
   The rest of the ``What's Hot'' list for April includes two cards
each for Moss, 49ers wide receiver Terrell Owens and Ravens running
back Priest Holmes; and rookie cards for Broncos quarterback John
Elway, running back Terrell Davis and wide receiver Ed McCaffrey,
Colts running back Marshall Faulk, Falcons running back Jamal
Anderson, Jaguars running back Fred Taylor and Seahawks wide
receiver Joey Galloway.
</P>
<P>
   Illustrious company, but all this hoopla over cards and their
worth is somewhat lost on Kitna. He never collected them while
growing up in Tacoma. Instead, Kitna used to hang out at Tacoma
Tigers games while Mark McGwire and Jose Canseco were playing for
the Pacific Coast League club.
</P>
<P>
   ``I never cared about that stuff,'' Kitna said. ``We'd have
balls that were signed or bats with their names on them, and we'd
just go out and play with them. I should have kept them. But, oh
well.''
</P>
<P>
   Still, it is a bit strange when the face staring at you from the
card is yours. Kitna has a complete set of his cards, thanks to the
efforts of Karl Payne, the chaplain at the church Kitna attends.
Payne gave Kitna a complete set of his cards for Christmas last
year.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's weird to see the cards. I just never pictured this
happening,'' Kitna said. ``People are making a big deal out of what
I'm doing, but I feel like I'm doing the same thing I've been doing
since high school. Little things have changed here and there, but
all in all I feel like I'm just playing still.''
</P>
<P>
   If the people at Beckett are correct, and Holmgren can mold
Kitna as he has other young quarterbacks, the glut of glory could
just be starting.
</P>
<P>
   ``I hope it gets worse,'' Kitna said with a smile. ``That's the
goal. If it gets worse, that means I'm doing my job.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
