<P>
   CIR-FILM-RESTORATION (Undated) _ Until a few years ago, it was
nearly impossible to fix motion picture film that had been
scratched or stepped on or chewed up by machinery.The development
of high-definition videotape, which can reproduce an image that is
virtually as sharp as that possible with motion picture film, gave
film archivists the tools they needed to do more than just get rid
of scratches. The new technology allows them to virtually recreate
missing frames. By Eric A. Taub.
</P>
<P>
   CIR-Q&AMP;A (Undated) _ What is the `blue screen'? By
J.D.BIERSDORFER
</P>
<P>
   CIR-VOICE-TECHNOLOGY (Undated) _ Computer-generated voices are
starting to sound a bit more human. Soon the classic robotic
monotones of synthetic speech will have tinges of the sad, the
happy, the polite, the warm and even the frightened. By Anne
Eisenberg.
</P>
<P>
   CIR-HISTORY-CDROMS (Undated) _ I AM no expert in the field of
history CD-ROM's. After spending a week playing with The Library of
Congress: Eyes of the Nation, a new CD-ROM exploring the American
experience through documents selected from the world's largest
archive, I've been partly converted. By David M. Oshinsky.
</P>
<P>
   CIR-ABE-LINCOLN (Undated) _ A Web site is being developed that
will offer the complete multivolume ``Works of Abraham Lincoln'' _
all 2,048,683 printed words. By Herbert Mitgang.
</P>
<P>
   &UR; HOME (Moved in ``l'' category) &LR;
</P>
<P>
   MAMMOTH-MANSIONS (Palm Beach, Fla.) _ As the Florida sun beats
relentlessly on the perfect palms and spotless thoroughfares, the
residents of this Mediterranean-style mecca are losing their cool
over big houses. Bad feelings are whipping through the banyan
trees, as hundreds of newcomers from the north, younger than ever
before, put down roots in the sand. By Tracie Rozhon.
</P>
<P>
   DECORATING-RELATIONSHIPS (New York) _ Like a marriage, the
relationship between decorator and client goes through phases. By
Lucie Young.
</P>
<P>
   BLENDER-CULTURE (Undated) _ From the 16-button blender models of
the '60s _ back when buttons represented space-age convenience _ to
the cordless models that came out a couple of years ago to the most
up-to-date versions that feature soft illuminated keypads, the
blender changes to mirror our passing technological obsessions. By
Karrie Jacobs.
</P>
<P>
   PICTURE-FRAMES (Undated) _ A picture frame, usually the final
fillip, the last deft gesture, is many things to many people. By
Elaine Louie.
</P>
<P>
   (ART ADV: Photos [NYT12,13) have been sent to NYT photo
clients.)
</P>
<P>
   BASEMENT-DREAMING (Undated) _ The ambiance might charitably be
described as early 20th-century American dungeon: the cobwebbed
walls are made of thick slabs of Manhattan schist set in brown
mortar, which over the last century has shed enough sand and lime
to form an inch-high berm at their base. This is a basement, my
basement, and I love it. An essay by Michael Segell.
</P>
<P>
   GARDEN-FURNITURE (Undated) _ It's not too soon to think about
outfitting the garden or terrace. And this spring, the incentives
to refurnish are plentiful _ like Martha Stewart's new garden
collection for Kmart and Michael Graves' for Target. By Marianne
Rohrlich.
</P>
<P>
   &UR; NYT News Service &LR;  &QL;
