<DATE_TIME> 1999-03-25 01:30 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A3402 &Cx1f; taf-z
u s &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-BKN-KNICKS-KINGS-NYT &LR;      03-25 0830
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BKN-KNICKS-KINGS-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
KINGS DEFEAT KNICKS, 92-91 
</HEADLINE>
  (sw) 
 By SELENA ROBERTS   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   SACRAMENTO, Calif. _ The New York Knicks took another blow to
their self-esteem and mental stability on Wednesday night. They
took another crushing loss in a tight finish.
</P>
<P>
   The Knicks lost their fourth game in five tries after Patrick
Ewing's potential game-winning jumper bounded off the rim with 3
seconds left. The Sacramento Kings walked away with a 92-91 victory
at Arco Arena.
</P>
<P>
   Ewing led the Knicks with 23 points, while Vernon Maxwell led
the Kings with 19 points off the bench. The Knicks, playing the
first game of a three-game trip, fell to 15-13 and are 3-9 on the
road.
</P>
<P>
   As is their habit, the Knicks allowed a 9-point fourth quarter
lead to disappear in a flurry of mistakes. The biggest occurred
when the score was tied, 91-91, with 59 seconds left. After a
jumper by Ewing missed and went off the Kings and out of bounds,
and another miss by Chris Childs was rebounded by Larry Johnson,
Latrell Sprewell had the ball in his hands at the top of the key
when he was stripped by the rookie Jason Williams.
</P>
<P>
   Williams was instantly fouled by Sprewell with 11.5 seconds
left. Williams missed the first free throw and then, after it
bounded around the rim, the second one fell in to give the Kings a
92-91 lead. The Knicks were hyperventilating as they traded miss
for miss in a flurry of botched fast breaks midway through the
fourth quarter. And still, the Knicks held a 77-74 lead after
Sprewell opened the quarter with two quick scores.
</P>
<P>
   The Knicks, playing smarter and more in control than the Kings,
opened a 81-74 lead after Childs drove and kicked the ball out to
an open Charlie Ward for a 3-pointer with 6 minutes 54 seconds left
in the game. The Knicks' lead was cut to 85-83 on two free throws
by Vlade Divac. Ewing, mustering all of his energy, managed a layin
and then tapped in a missed runner by Ward. But Ewing's efforts
were matched on back-to-back 3-pointers _ one by Divac and one by
Williams _ to keep the Kings close, 91-89, with 1:23 left in the
game.
</P>
<P>
   The Knicks were up against a team that played loose and with few
thoughts of defense. Once it was clear that the Knicks were not
going to be able to put their foot down on the fast break, they
decided to dip their old toes in the fountain of youth and take off
with the Kings. Making up a 7-point second-quarter deficit, the
Knicks ran and ran until they came up with a 52-51 halftime lead.
Both teams shot 48 percent from the field.
</P>
<P>
   Neither team kept up that pace in the third quarter. It was too
hard on the Knicks' aging bodies, so they slowed it down, ran the
offense through Ewing and tightened their defense.
</P>
<P>
   As the tempo of the game dragged, the Knicks played a game of
slow motion back and forth. The score was tied, 62-62, with six
minutes left in the third when the Kings pulled a few tricks _
including an alley-oop from Divac to Tariq Abdur-Wahad _ to put
them ahead by 68-64 with 1 minute 14 seconds left. Johnson came up
with a 3-pointer to pull the Knicks back to within a point. The
Kings' lead stood at 68-67 going into the fourth quarter.
</P>
<P>
   This was another test for the team that had proven mentally
fragile. But at least the Knicks appeared game and were able to
keep up with the fleet Kings from the start.
</P>
<P>
   It was like old times for Sprewell. He was playing the kind of
free-wheeling West Coast style he thrived in at Golden State. But
as fast as Sprewell was running up 9 points on 11 shots in 16
minutes off the bench in the first half, Maxwell was tagging him
right back. Maxwell collected 13 points in 13 minutes as sixth man.
</P>
<P>
   Something had to give, and it was Williams. He was getting a
little too fancy, a little too free, and he turned the ball over
six times in the first half. Ward could not stick with him when he
was dribbling between his legs and around his back, but the brash
display inspired Ward.
</P>
<P>
   And Ward is at his best when he is inspired. Too often this
season, his familiar detached look on his face has turned into a
vacant stare. After re-signing for five years and $26million, Ward
has regressed from a year ago. With one of the league's worst
assist-to-turnover ratios standing at 150 to 84 entering the game,
Ward had only had a single night when he seemed into a game.
</P>
<P>
   That game was against Stephon Marbury, the name most mentioned
to upgrade the Knicks' point guard weakness before the trade
deadline. Ward did not like it, and he took great satisfaction in
his 18-point, 13-assist game against Marbury one month ago. But
since that night, Ward has vanished, and the Knicks have become
increasingly desperate for some court guidance.
</P>
<P>
   ``I thought last year he had the right mixture between being
aggressive _ particularly on the break and trying to make plays _
but not being careless,'' Coach Jeff Van Gundy said. ``I think it
that way, he needs to get back on top of that.''
</P>
</TEXT>
