<HEADER>
A3416 &Cx1f; tab-z
r a &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-RUSSIAN-IMPOTENCE-KOS     03-25 0859
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-RUSSIAN-IMPOTENCE-KOSOVO-INDEPENDENT-NYTSF </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
BOMBING MARKS NEW LOW IN U.S.-RUSSIA RELATIONS  
 
</HEADLINE>
  
 (ATTN: Commentary Editors)   (This TIMELY 625-word ``separate buy'' article is from The
Independent newspaper in London.)  
  
 (EDITORS: We regret that this material is NOT available to clients
in Canada EXCEPT to The Hamilton (Ontario) Spectator.)  
  
 (To publish this article, it must be purchased from the New York
Times Syndicate's sales representative DEBRA WEYDERT at
732-390-4480, or fax her at 732-390-4697. If unable to reach Ms.
Weydert, please call 800-444-0267, or fax us at 816-822-1444.)  
  
 (PLEASE NOTE: This article has been transmitted twice _ into the
``a'' domestic/general news and ``k'' commentary news files.)  
  
 By PHIL REEVES  
 c.1999 The Independent, London  
 (Distributed by New York Times Special Features)  
<TEXT>
<P>
   MOSCOW _ The first NATO bomb to crater Yugoslav soil will stand
in history as the moment when Russia realized exactly how far it
has fallen since the days it stood astride the planet as a
superpower capable of counterbalancing American might.
</P>
<P>
   The alliance's refusal to listen to Moscow's pleas to spare its
Slavic cousins in Serbia marks a new low in an increasingly
ambivalent relationship with the United States, in which Russia _
to its horror _ finds itself cast not so much an enemy as a
sponging lightweight.
</P>
<P>
   The warmth of the early post-Soviet era faded long ago, but
Kosovo has turned Russian reservations about the West _ and, in
particular, the supremacy of NATO _ into concrete resentment, shot
through with deep suspicion which is likely to influence policy for
years.
</P>
<P>
   Wednesday in Moscow outrage echoed across the political
spectrum, moderated only by the humiliating recognition that Russia
must turn again to the West for loans.
</P>
<P>
   After eleventh-hour calls to U.S. President Bill Clinton and
Jacques Chirac of France, Boris Yeltsin appeared on national TV to
appeal to Nato to stay its hand. He spoke ominously of the world
facing ``a war in Europe and possibly something greater.''
</P>
<P>
   According to the White House, Clinton's message was: ``We should
not allow a dispute on a single issue to derail the important work
we're doing on a wide variety of issues.'' Those issues include
nuclear weapons reduction, and peacekeeping in Bosnia.
</P>
<P>
   The Russian Foreign Minister, Igor Ivanov, dropped hints about
arming the Serbs _ arguing that a NATO attack could render the U.N.
arms embargo null and void (although the Kremlin distanced itself
from these).
</P>
<P>
   Marshal Igor Sergeyev, Russia's Defense Minister, even talked
about Yugoslavia becoming a ``second Vietnam,'' as the he placed
the armed forces on a state of ``higher alert.''
</P>
<P>
   From the newly ascendant Communists, there were calls for
Russian military assistance; from the nationalists, blusters about
restoring a Stalinist dictatorship so that Russia should not be so
humiliated again.
</P>
<P>
   The mood is one of deep grievance, and it is not without cause.
This week Clinton was to meet the Russian premier Yevgeny Primakov,
but the latter's plane _ in a pure piece of Cold War theatre _
turned around over the Atlantic on Tuesday after he concluded NATO
bombing was imminent.
</P>
<P>
   Beforehand, the American president made a speech about the need
for ``the right kind'' of relationship with the Russians, who could
be ``great partners.''
</P>
<P>
   But there is not much evidence he is willing to back his words
with actions. These days Washington mixes hardball, with a strategy
of ignoring Moscow altogether.
</P>
<P>
   Russian protests over the Anglo-American bombing of Iraq fell on
deaf ears, a response which undermined its treasured status as a
permanent member of the U.N. Security Council.
</P>
<P>
   Moscow has been hectored by the U.S. _ including having
sanctions slapped on research institutes _ over weapons technology
transfers to Iran. And the International Monetary Fund has lectured
them tirelessly over how to run a market economy after last
August's crash _ this, despite the fact that the fund was partly to
blame.
</P>
<P>
   Washington's policy is perhaps based on the reality that
Russia's economy has shrunk to the size of Belgium's. But Moscow's
legacy of 30,000 nuclear warheads, its lake of chemical weapons,
and a time-tested ability to currying favor with the planet's
pariahs cannot be overlooked.
</P>
<P>
   Bill Clinton recognized as much in his speech. He would like
Russia's 40,000 nuclear scientists to do ``peaceful, good things
and not bartering their services to other countries to cause
trouble.''
</P>
<P>
   A fine sentiment, but one which will not be furthered by NATO
bombing runs in Yugoslavia. &QL; 
 &UR; ___________________ &LR;  &QC; 
 &UR; (To publish this TIMELY 625-word article, it must be purchased from
the New York Times Syndicate's sales representative DEBRA WEYDERT
at 732-390-4480, or fax her at 732-390-4697. If unable to reach Ms.
Weydert, please call 800-444-0267, or fax us at 816-822-1444.) &LR;  &QL; 
 &LR;  &QL; 
 &UR; (EDITORS: We regret that this material is NOT available to clients
in Canada EXCEPT to The Hamilton (Ontario) Spectator.) &LR;  &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
