<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-03-25 01:48 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A3424 &Cx1f; taf-z
u a &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-BKN-NETS-PISTONS-NYT &LR;      03-25 0613
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BKN-NETS-PISTONS-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
PISTONS DEFEAT NETS, 84-71 
</HEADLINE>
  (sw) 
 By CHRIS BROUSSARD   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   EAST RUTHERFORD, N.J. _ The New Jersey Nets thought they had
momentum. They had won two straight home games, routed a hot
Toronto club and, in getting way ahead of themselves, begun
thinking playoffs. But the Detroit Pistons _ a mediocre, slumping
team that had lost its last four road games _ came into Continental
Arena on Wednesday night and proved that nothing had changed for
the Nets. Appearing unstoppable on offense and impenetrable on
defense, Detroit drilled the Nets by 84-71 before a crowd of
16,896.
</P>
<P>
   The 13-point gap was misleading. This one lost all competitive
value after the Pistons held New Jersey to 29 first-half points in
taking a 17-point lead.
</P>
<P>
   The deficit was 26 less than five minutes into the third
quarter, and the Nets, whose futility seemingly has no end, were
threatening to set franchise lows.
</P>
<P>
   But after going 11 minutes 45 seconds, spanning the third and
fourth quarters, without a basket, the Nets saved face with a late
charge that cut the final margin and kept them out of the annals.
At least most of them. As it was, the Nets tied a franchise mark
for fewest field goals in a game with 23, just four more than the
league's low.
</P>
<P>
   ``This kind of knocked the wind out of us,'' Kerry Kittles said.
``When we came out at the beginning, we were just playing in a
funk. They came out aggressively, played hard, and we didn't
respond. We got so far behind so quickly that it was tough to come
back. This season has been frustrating all around the table.''
</P>
<P>
   The Nets, who are 2-4 under their interim coach, Don Casey, and
5-21 over all, thought they were beginning to turn it around. After
overpowering Toronto by 106-87 on Monday to end the Raptors'
five-game winning streak, Jayson Williams talked as if the Nets
were still in the post-season picture. And many of his teammates
knew they were only eight and a half games out of the eighth and
final Eastern Conference playoff spot, leaving them a mathematical
possibility.
</P>
<P>
   But though such aspirations would seem to incite energy and
fire, the Pistons (15-12) were the only ones exuding intensity.
</P>
<P>
   ``They defended us strongly, physically,'' Casey said. ``I won't
say intimidated, but they were initiating and we were reacting.''
</P>
<P>
   The Nets, who were led by Keith Van Horn's 27 points, were
manhandled so fiercely that their 31.9 percent shooting was low
even by New Jersey standards. And while the Nets spoke proudly
afterward about holding Detroit to 84 points, the truth is that the
Piston offense was clicking on all cylinders.
</P>
<P>
   With five players scoring in double figures _ led by Bison
Dele's 18 points and Jerry Stackhouse's 17 _ Detroit shot 50.7
percent. The Pistons attempted 3 fewer field goals than the Nets
but made 12 more.
</P>
<P>
   The Nets, who made just nine first-half shots, played offense
that was hard on the eyes.
</P>
<P>
   If they weren't battering the rim while missing open jump shots,
they were losing the ball in creative ways.
</P>
<P>
   Once, Kittles drove for a layup on the right side against
Stackhouse only to have the high-flying Piston swat his attempt;
then, in adding insult to infamy, he knocked the ball away from
Kittles and out of bounds: Detroit basketball. Moments later,
Kendall Gill nullified another open-court opportunity by charging
uncontrollably into a stationary Pistons.
</P>
<P>
   Minutes later, as the Nets exited for intermission, the fans
began booing loudly.
</P>
<P>
   ``I can understand the fans being upset,'' Casey said. ``They
truly want to jump on the wagon and get things rolling. But there's
no easy way out.'' &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
