<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BKN-LAKERS-SUNS-LADN </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
SUNS BEAT LAKERS
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By HOWARD BECK  
 c.1999 Los Angeles Daily News  
<TEXT>
<P>
   INGLEWOOD, Calif. _ And so, 6,795 miles later, the Los Angeles
Lakers docked once again in a safe harbor, no worse and no better
for the wear after a road trip that netted as many wins as losses.
</P>
<P>
   The smoggy skies over crowded highways never looked better. The
Forum never felt more friendly. But the comforts of home were
deceiving. And the one day off maybe wasn't enough. Or maybe the
Lakers could have used an extra practice after all.
</P>
<P>
   Looking every bit the jet-lagged bunch they were, the Lakers
spotted the Phoenix Suns a 14-point lead in the first quarter
Wednesday night before finally unpacking their game faces. But by
late in the game, the Lakers were again playing like a team with
its head in three time zones.
</P>
<P>
   The final result, a 106-101 loss to the Phoenix Suns. Home
seemed less attractive after the Suns had snapped the Lakers' Forum
winning streak at nine games and dealt them their first loss with
Dennis Rodman in the lineup.
</P>
<P>
   Shaquille O'Neal and Kobe Bryant scored 24 and 25 points
respectively, but O'Neal missed 11 of 20 shots.
</P>
<P>
   By the ugly conclusion of an ugly game, the Forum crowd had
turned downright nasty, sarcastically chanting ``Ed-die'' upon
watching a Glen Rice air ball fly two feet short of the basket in
the final minute.
</P>
<P>
   After playing six games in six cities in nine days, the Lakers
certainly had a plausible case for the loss. It was exactly what
their resident sage, longtime assistant Bill Bertka, had warned
them about earlier in the day.
</P>
<P>
   ``Bertka made a great point at shootaround this morning,'' Kobe
Bryant said. ``He said you notice after a long road trip a team
comes home and has a tendency to kind of slack off, and there's a
good chance for the (visiting) team to sneak out a win. And he's
also seen teams come home and just totally kick a team's butt
because they're happy to be home.''
</P>
<P>
   The Lakers showed a bit of both.
</P>
<P>
   Combining careless turnovers with rushed shots, the Lakers
watched the Suns take a 16-4 lead. But as they proved Sunday at
Orlando, the Lakers can make such ugliness disappear rather
quickly.
</P>
<P>
   With an unconventional lineup of J.R. Reid at center, Dennis
Rodman and Rick Fox at forward and Derek Fisher and Bryant in the
backcourt, the Lakers started an 18-6 run that cut the gap to 24-22
by the end of the first quarter.
</P>
<P>
   The starters returned for the second quarter and O'Neal quickly
went to work, giving the Lakers their first lead four minutes into
the period with eight quick points. The Lakers built as much as an
eight-point cushion before settling for a 54-49 halftime lead.
</P>
<P>
   Then things got nasty.
</P>
<P>
   With the Lakers leading 75-69, Fox tossed Gerald Brown to the
hardwood to stop a fast-break layup in progress. Brown leaped to
his feet and was met by an inexplicable shove from an intervening
Rodman. Tom Gugliotta and a handful of others jumped in for a quick
scrum at the baseline.
</P>
<P>
   Fox got a flagrant foul, Brown and Rodman got a double-technical
and when it was all over Brown had made two free throws, and the
Suns, retaining possession, got Clifford Robinson to the line for
another pair of foul shots.
</P>
<P>
   The margin was suddenly an iffy 75-73, and the Suns used the
momentum to mount a 14-2 run to close out the quarter and take an
83-77 lead to head into the final period.
</P>
<P>
   Before tipoff, coach Kurt Rambis was hopeful the Lakers' recent
defensive resurgence, in the second half at Orlando and in Dallas,
would return home to L.A. with the team.
</P>
<P>
   ``It definitely feels good to be back, but it's not gonna solve
all of our issues,'' he said. ``We still have to build upon the
advances we made in the last game and a half.''
</P>
<P>
   Instead, they took two steps back.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
