</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BKC-LAKEY-USC-LADN </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
FORWARD LAKEY LEAVES USC
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By SCOTT WOLF  
 c.1999 Los Angeles Daily News  
<TEXT>
<P>
   LOS ANGELES _ USC forward Greg Lakey has quit the basketball
team, the third Trojans player to leave since December, and there
remains a possibility of further defections.
</P>
<P>
   Lakey, who is attempting to transfer to Loyola Marymount,
informed USC coach Henry Bibby on Tuesday he would transfer. Last
week, guard Quincy Wilder quit the team. And in December, point
guard Kevin Augustine quit and enrolled at Fullerton College.
</P>
<P>
   According to sources, reserve forward Shannon Swillis is also
considering transferring, possibly to Fresno State. There has been
speculation that junior forward Jarvis Turner might transfer to
either Fresno State or Loyola Marymount, but Turner said Wednesday
he intended to stay at USC.
</P>
<P>
   The latest moves mean that five scholarship players have quit
the USC basketball team in the past 19 months. Shooting guard Danny
Walker and center Philip Von Backstrom quit prior to the start of
the 1997-98 season.
</P>
<P>
   The departures of Lakey and Wilder were attributed to a lack of
playing time.
</P>
<P>
   ``I already spent two years here and I haven't accomplished what
I wanted to accomplish,'' Lakey said Wednesday. ``I did what I
could and I couldn't get in there. I really just thought about
(transferring) two days ago.''
</P>
<P>
   Lakey said he was frustrated over the unpredictable nature of
his playing time. In USC's last three games, Lakey played 21
minutes against Arizona, nine against Arizona State and one against
Wyoming in the National Invitation Tournament.
</P>
<P>
   Lakey averaged 4.8 points and 3.0 rebounds this season and led
the Trojans in free-throw shooting (87 percent).
</P>
<P>
   USC coach Henry Bibby was upbeat Wednesday, saying that he only
determined playing time based on practice performances.
</P>
<P>
   ``You play two hours of practice a day. If you can't show me two
hours a day you can play, I can't play you in the basketball
game,'' Bibby said. ``If you talk to most coaches, they say
basketball games are won and lost in practice.
</P>
<P>
   ``I don't determine who plays. (Players) determine who plays.''
</P>
<P>
   Bibby said he was not worried about the program's image being
hurt by losing three players in such a short time span.
</P>
<P>
   ``My concern is the guys that are here,'' he said. ``My concern
is `Are we fair?' My concern is `Are we doing what's best for the
program?' There's no reason for anyone to leave. It's not
complex.''
</P>
<P>
   Lakey said two other factors caused him to transfer. He was
unhappy when it was suggested he redshirt next season _ a charge
denied by USC _ and he was bothered by Turner's role on the team.
</P>
<P>
   One of USC's most experienced players before the season, Turner
played sparingly, with eight games in which he played less than 10
minutes and five games in which he did not play at all.
</P>
<P>
   ``I was thinking about it a lot. I saw what happened to Jarvis,
the way he didn't get into the game. And Shannon didn't either,''
Lakey said. ``That really was on my mind. (Jarvis is) one of my
best friends on the team. I can't have that happen to me.''
</P>
<P>
   Although USC has lost two of its point guards and a key
center-forward, players seemed undaunted Wednesday.
</P>
<P>
   ``I don't know why they're leaving,'' sophomore guard Jeff
Trepagnier said. ``The coaches are cool. I'll be here.''
</P>
<P>
   None of the players were really sure, however, if Lakey would be
the final player to transfer.
</P>
<P>
   ``I guess it would keep surprising me if people leave,'' center
Brian Scalabrine said. ``I thought we had an OK season. But you
have to look at each individual person. Maybe it didn't work out
for them.''
</P>
<P>
   After being short of scholarships, USC suddenly has three for
the spring signing period. Bibby said Wednesday he would like to
sign a point guard and at least one post player.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
