<SLUG> BC-HKN-BRUINS-SENATORS-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
BRUINS, DAFOE BLANK OTTAWA 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By NANCY L. MARRAPESE  
 c.1999 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   KANATA, Ontario _ In the standings, the two points were no more
important than if they had come against the Tampa Bay Lightning or
the Chicago Blackhawks or the New York Islanders.
</P>
<P>
   However, psychologically, the Bruins picking up a pair of points
against the team that sits in first place in the Eastern Conference
and could very well be the Bruins' first-round opponent in the
playoffs did provide a bigger boost than if they had come at the
expense of the worst teams in the league.
</P>
<P>
   Parts of Wednesday &UR;  &LR; night's 3-0 win over the Ottawa Senators was
as exciting as any postseason matchup could've been. Goalie Byron
Dafoe stopped all 28 Ottawa chances, picking up his eighth shutout
of the season and 15th of his career.
</P>
<P>
   The Bruins took a 1-0 lead in the first and then scored on
back-to-back shots in the second, the first of which was a
successful penalty shot by center Jason Allison.
</P>
<P>
   Allison made Ottawa defenseman Jason York suffer not once but
twice. The first time York pulled him down, it led to the Bruins'
first goal _ scored on the ensuing power play. The second time, it
meant a penalty shot for Allison at the 3:30 mark.
</P>
<P>
   Allison took off from center, switched several times from his
backhand to his forehand, used a double head fake to throw off
goalie Ron Tugnutt, then lifted in a backhand shot at the left
post.
</P>
<P>
   Just 39 seconds later, forward Landon Wilson, who was still
smarting from his missed penalty shot against Toronto March 17,
looked as if he'd been watching Allison. The puck pinballed off
several players and Wilson found himself with the puck and nothing
between him and the net but Tugnutt. He skated in, made a similar
move that Allison made, and tried a backhander from the same place.
Tugnutt made the stop but Wilson stopped, too, and managed to whack
the rebound over the goalie for a 3-0 lead.
</P>
<P>
   Coach Pat Burns said he didn't let Wilson advise Allison before
his penalty shot. When told of this, Allison laughed. ``I didn't
even go to the bench,'' said Allison. ``I didn't want anyone
talking to me. I played with Ron before and I know he knows I like
to sometimes go high. I've had success with that deke before, but
he played it great. I just got it to squeeze by him.''
</P>
<P>
   The first period started off very slowly with the game looking
more like a chess match than hockey. Both teams were content to
dump the puck and wait for their chances. Ottawa's best opportunity
came at 15:33 when York, positioned at the right point, blasted a
shot that clanged off the left post. The siren sounded but it
clearly wasn't in. Left wing Marian Hossa chased after the puck but
missed it with his stick and it bounced off his right skate.
</P>
<P>
   A little more than three minutes later, the Bruins took a 1-0
lead on the power play. Defenseman Ray Bourque carried the puck
across the blue line. At the left point, he dished it to Dmitri
Khristich, who blasted a shot from high between the circles that
went over Tugnutt's glove at 18:53.
</P>
<P>
   Prior to Allison's goal, the Senators mustered a decent scoring
bid off the stick of center Alexei Yashin less than two minutes
into the second period. Yashin picked up a loose puck behind the
net and skated out to the left circle, firing a shot that
disappeared into the body of Dafoe.
</P>
<P>
   After Wilson's goal, the Senators hit another snag when ex-Bruin
Ted Donato, who was traded to Ottawa from the Islanders Saturday,
teed up a shot from the right circle that went through Dafoe but
rang off the post.
</P>
<P>
   Despite all the excitement and success of Wednesday &UR;  &LR; night's
win, Bruins assistant general manager Mike O'Connell said if the
teams meet again in the first round of the playoffs, all bets will
be off.
</P>
<P>
   ``We're not out of the woods yet but when you get into the
playoffs, the whole picture changes, everything changes,'' said
O'Connell. ``The pressures change. You've got a home-ice advantage
team against a non-home-ice advantage team. One finishes so many
odd points ahead of another team. Those pressures aren't there
right now. I think every team in our conference has a chance, one
through eight, every team has a chance.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
