<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BKN-CLIPPERS-WARRIORS-REWRITE-LADN </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
CLIPPERS FALL TO WARRIORS
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
(OPTIONAL: Adds quotes, details) 
By RANDY HILL  
 Long Beach Press-Telegram  
<TEXT>
<P>
   LOS ANGELES _ If you're planning an excursion to hell, don't
pack that sweater. Temperatures are normal.
</P>
<P>
   Wednesday's climate also remained much the same inside the
Sports Arena (which only seems like hell), where _ witnessed by
6,180 _ the Los Angeles Clippers surrendered to the Golden State
Warriors 92-80, terminating the home team's winning streak after
one in a row. Instead of victories back-to-back, a 13-point fourth
quarter made them settle for back to bad.
</P>
<P>
   ``We just ... missed,'' said forward Maurice Taylor, defining
his team's 5-of-12 marksmanship in the fourth quarter.
</P>
<P>
   Clippers coach Chris Ford thought this explanation would sound
good in stereo. ``You gotta put the ball in the basket,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   Because they didn't, a plausible victory _ the game was tied
71-71 with 10:08 remaining _ became the Clippers' 23rd loss in 25
games; they now are on pace to complete the Cliffs Notes version of
this NBA season at 4-46.
</P>
<P>
   And the hits keep comin'. Point guard Darrick Martin
hyperextended his left knee just moments before the agony of defeat
was official. The Clippers, who already have two playmakers on the
injured list, scheduled an MRI for Martin today.
</P>
<P>
   Considering that fourth quarter, they might be wise to hire a
bus and make it a field trip.
</P>
<P>
   ``We just didn't make the plays when we had to,'' guard Charles
Smith said. ``They outhustled us late in the game.''
</P>
<P>
   That's a damning declaration for a team with two victories.
</P>
<P>
   After Sunday's epiphany at Minnesota _ where they finally found
an `A' game at the bottom of a suitcase _ the Clippers at least
began Wednesday's game like a team responding to an intervention.
</P>
<P>
   Behind six points from Taylor and a bit of backboard bullying by
rookie center Michael Olowokandi (two blocked shots, three
rebounds), the Clippers jumped out to a nine-point lead. Guard Eric
Piatkowski capped the rally, finishing a fast break off a feed from
Martin to put the Clippers ahead 13-4 with 7:07 left in the opening
quarter.
</P>
<P>
   The Warriors (11-15) _ who lost Tuesday night in Portland _
countered with an 11-0 surge, featuring Donyell Marshall's
fast-break slam to complete the run at the 5:03 mark.
</P>
<P>
   Golden State _ whose wounded starting forwards Jason Caffey
(Achilles) and Chris Mills (ankle) turned out in civilian clothes _
limped into a three-point lead, but the Clippers limped back to tie
the score at 24 when the period ended.
</P>
<P>
   Taylor finished the quarter with eight points. Olowokandi (13
points, nine rebounds for the game), who snagged a career-high 16
rebounds in Minnesota, had six boards in round one. Both teams shot
more than 50 percent _ from the field. The middle quarters were a
competitive warm-up for the Clippers' signature fourth-quarter
collapse. Rookie forward Antawn Jamison had nine points in the last
period and finished with a team-high 22.
</P>
<P>
   ``Things weren't going as smoothly in the fourth quarter,''
Taylor decided.
</P>
<P>
   No, but things certainly looked familiar. &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
