<HEADLINE>
LAKERS FALL TO SUNS
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
(OPTIONAL: Adds quotes, details) 
By HOWARD BECK  
 c.1999 Los Angeles Daily News  
<TEXT>
<P>
   INGLEWOOD, Calif. _ And so, 6,795 miles later, the Los Angeles
Lakers docked once again in a safe harbor, no worse and no better
for the wear after a road trip that netted as many wins as losses.
</P>
<P>
   The smoggy skies over gridlocked highways never looked better.
The Forum never seemed more fabulous or friendly. But the comforts
of home were deceiving. So, too, was the apparent progress the
Lakers had made in road-trip-ending victories at Orlando and
Dallas.
</P>
<P>
   If anything, they took another backward step Wednesday night in
a sloppy 106-101 loss to the Phoenix Suns. Make that two backward
steps, long enough to stretch back to their previous meltdowns in
Cleveland and Philadelphia.
</P>
<P>
   As always for this team, progress is fleeting.
</P>
<P>
   ``There's no explanation for it,'' Shaquille O'Neal said. ``None
whatsoever.''
</P>
<P>
   The six-city, nine-day road trip could have sufficed for an
explanation, especially on a night in which the Lakers spotted the
visiting team a 14-point lead in the first quarter. But that was
immediately dismissed by all as a lame excuse.
</P>
<P>
   They had their chance to win this game, with an eight-point lead
late in the third quarter, but old habits returned. Several
turnovers and ill-conceived shots later, their nine-game home
winning streak, and their 11-0 Dennis Rodman streak, were toast.
</P>
<P>
   Maybe the day off they took to rest up from the road trip would
have been better spent practicing after all. And maybe somewhere
back at LAX, a purple-and-gold duffel bag containing the Lakers'
cohesion and basketball smarts is sitting on a baggage-claim
conveyor belt, going in circles.
</P>
<P>
   ``We didn't come out ready to play and we turned the ball over
way too many times,'' coach Kurt Rambis, visibly upset, said
afterward. ``It's just mental mistakes. The way we turned the ball
over are just mental mistakes.''
</P>
<P>
   Eighteen turnovers negated the Lakers' 48-44 rebounding edge and
superior shooting (46.1 percent to the Suns' 43.5 percent). Kobe
Bryant committed five turnovers and hit 10 of 22 shots to mar his
25-point performance. Rodman's 13 rebounds came with four
turnovers.
</P>
<P>
   Jason Kidd did the rest, scoring 21 of his 23 points in the
second half to go with 10 assists and seven rebounds.
</P>
<P>
   And all the Lakers could do was shake their heads in disgust.
</P>
<P>
   ``We're sitting here discombobulated,'' Derek Harper said.
``Sort of looking for an answer. Here I am trying to explain what
happened and what didn't work.... We have to play together. I don't
think there's any way around it. We have to play together, we have
to play as a group and we have to be tied together.''
</P>
<P>
   No further analysis was needed. The home crowd had already
delivered its own editorial on the subject. In the closing seconds,
after a Glen Rice airball that missed the rim by three feet, they
broke out the sarcastic ``Ed-die'' chants, in homage to the traded
Eddie Jones.
</P>
<P>
   After recovering from the early deficit, the Lakers controlled
the game through most of the second and half the third quarter. But
then things got nasty.
</P>
<P>
   With the Lakers leading 75-69, Rick Fox tossed the Suns' Gerald
Brown to the hardwood to stop a fast-break layup in progress. Brown
leaped to his feet and was met by an inexplicable shove from an
intervening Rodman, which nearly started a brawl.
</P>
<P>
   Fox got a flagrant foul, Brown and Rodman got a double-technical
and when it was all over Brown had made two free throws, and the
Suns, retaining possession, got Clifford Robinson to the line for
another pair of foul shots.
</P>
<P>
   The margin was suddenly an iffy 75-73 and the Suns used the
momentum to mount a 14-2 run to close out the quarter and take an
83-77 lead to head into the final period. The Lakers never got
closer than three points the rest of the way.
</P>
<P>
   Rambis was so disgusted, his postgame sermon to the players
consisted of just three terse thoughts: ``We've got practice
tomorrow. Meeting's over. Get dressed and go home.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
