<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-KASICH-CALIFORNIA-SFCHRON </SLUG>
  
 KASICH'S CALIFORNIA PRIMARY STRATEGY  &HT;     By MARC SANDALOW 
 &HT;     c.1999 San Francisco Chronicle  
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON _ The best way to compete in California's early
presidential primary may be to spend a lot of time in Iowa or New
Hampshire, Rep. John Kasich, R-Ohio, suggested Wednesday.
</P>
<P>
   ``I have to make it through Iowa and New Hampshire,'' said
Kasich, or else ``you'll never see me in California except on
vacation.'' Kasich will visit the Bay Area this weekend for the
first time since he announced the formation of his presidential
exploratory committee.
</P>
<P>
   The energetic 46-year-old chairman of the House Budget Committee
_ who once compared himself to the double-caffeinated soft drink
Jolt _ discussed his longshot quest for the presidency with
California reporters over lunch, dismissing polls that show Texas
Gov. George W. Bush far ahead.
</P>
<P>
   ``Where people are today could be 180 degrees from where they
are tomorrow,'' Kasich said, adding that he is not losing sleep
over the rush of California Republican activists to the Bush
campaign. ``I don't worry about who signed up for who in
California,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   If he manages to surprise people in the Iowa caucus in early
February or in the New Hampshire primary, the nation's first,
Kasich said, he will get the attention needed to win California's
March 7 primary.
</P>
<P>
   He said his unscripted style would play well in the West, but he
could offer no specific reasons why he might hold any particular
appeal to Californians.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'm not going to tell you that I like the Lakers or
something,'' he said. ``My message is the same wherever I go. No
matter what state I'm in, no matter who I'm talking to, the message
is the same.''
</P>
<P>
   Kasich said he would have voted in favor of California's
Proposition 187, which limited public assistance to illegal
immigrants, but said he was unfamiliar with the details of
Proposition 209, which ended many of the state's affirmative action
programs.
</P>
<P>
   He said his campaign message will center on giving people ``more
control over their lives,'' whether that be through less
government, tax cuts, private retirement accounts or giving parents
more of a say on where their children go to school.
</P>
<P>
   A devout Christian, Kasich said opposition to abortion would be
a requirement for a potential running mate, and for a Supreme Court
nominee, if he is elected president.
</P>
<P>
   Kasich will travel to the Bay Area this weekend for fund raisers
in San Francisco and San Jose.
</P>
<P>
   Though conservative by reputation, Kasich has worked well with
Democrats during his 16 years in Congress. He is a good friend of
former Rep. Ron Dellums, a Democrat from Oakland, Calif. His
scheduled appearance last year at a breakfast fund raiser for Rep.
Gary Condit, a Democrat from California's Central Valley and
another close friend, so angered the Republican Party establishment
that the leadership barred him from addressing the party's
convention last month.
</P>
<P>
   His campaign style so far has included bowling earlier this
month with voters in Iowa, and ``mushing'' on a dogsled in New
Hampshire last week.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'm going to get the nomination,'' he said. You think that's
just a flip comment. It's not. I believe if I get the money, I will
be president.''
</P>
<P>
   Kasich was at times vague about the details of his California
strategy. He said he was not even up to date on his travel schedule
in the state. ``Frankly, I don't look ahead at the schedule,'' he
said. ``I have better energy when I focus on the wood in front of
me.''
</P>
<P>
   Asked how he would fare better than California Republicans did
last November, Kasich bristled.
</P>
<P>
   ``I don't have a clue what they did. I didn't watch that
campaign,'' he said.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
