<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-03-25 09:51 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A3586 &Cx1f; tad-z
u k &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-KLEINBERG-COLUMN28-CO     03-25 0670
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-KLEINBERG-COLUMN28-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    COMMENTARY: Yeltsin mighty involved _ after the fact
 &HT;    (For release Sunday, March 28, 1999.)
 &HT;    By Howard Kleinberg
 &HT;    c. 1999 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   Were I Bill Clinton (and I'm delighted that I'm not) here's what
I would have done _ quite some time ago:
</P>
<P>
   I would have picked up the phone and placed a call to Boris
Yeltsin in the Kremlin, or whatever rest home he was occupying at
the time.
</P>
<P>
   ``Boris,'' I would begin, ``this guy Milosevic, with whom we've
had trouble in the past, is murdering a lot of ethnic Albanians and
we need to put a stop to it.''
</P>
<P>
   ``What do you plan to do about it, Bill?''
</P>
<P>
   ``Well, if it isn't stopped, we're going to get NATO to put the
muscle to them.''
</P>
<P>
   ``Again with the bombs? Don't you know anything but bombs?
You're still bombing Iraq!''
</P>
<P>
   ``Boris, I'll tell you what. Every time we get some tinhorn
dictator going around murdering innocent people, we talk to them
until we're blue in the face. When that is exhausted, we have no
other choice.''
</P>
<P>
   ``We will never accept indiscriminate bombing of sovereign
territories.''
</P>
<P>
   ``Boris, let me put it to you. What would you do?''
</P>
<P>
   ``What would I do?''
</P>
<P>
   ``Yes, the Serbs are killing the ethnic Albanians, destroying
their homes, forcing them across their borders. It is close to
genocide, Boris. I've had enough of you sitting on your hands until
we are forced to make a bold move, then listen to you criticizing
it.''
</P>
<P>
   ``Mr. Clinton, I've got my hands full here in Russia; I can't
get too involved in Yugoslavia.''
</P>
<P>
   ``Mr. Yeltsin, do you think I've had an easy time the last year
or so? I got a mess on my plate that won't go away but I can't look
the other way when ethnic cleansing is going on. You and the
Russian people should know as well as anyone else. Look what the
Nazis did to you.''
</P>
<P>
   ``Bill, we've got a good relationship with the Serbs.''
</P>
<P>
   ``Great! That's a start. How about you, Milosevic and me _ just
the three of us _ sitting down somewhere, anywhere, and working
this out; make him stop the slaughter.''
</P>
<P>
   ``Bill, these flare-ups happen everywhere. I had it in Chechnya,
remember?''
</P>
<P>
   ``Boris, they're slaughtering people because of their
ethnicity.''
</P>
<P>
   ``But you have to understand, there was a revolt. The Kosovan
Liberation Army is much like terrorists. Milosevic had to take a
stand.''
</P>
<P>
   ``Taking a stand is one thing; slaughtering is another.''
</P>
<P>
   ``So, you're going to bomb?''
</P>
<P>
   ``Tell you what, Boris, the next time we send an envoy to
Belgrade to talk with Milosevic, why don't you send one with us?
All we want to do is stop the ethnic cleansing. I presume you don't
accept ethnic cleansing, either, so we can agree on that before we
start. I really don't care if there is a separate state of Kosovo,
although I must remind you that it once was autonomous and that was
taken away by Milosevic. And also that Milosevic agreed to a treaty
that included allowing NATO troops into Yugoslavia to keep the
peace.''
</P>
<P>
   ``I'm not NATO, Bill, and I don't like NATO. Why should I do
something with NATO?''
</P>
<P>
   ``Because no one else is doing anything, Boris. The U.N., as
usual, is tossing lilacs into the air, you guys are doing _ what?
Did you even utter a sound about the slaughters in Kosovo? No, you
didn't. Instead, you just sat back and crabbed about NATO going
beyond its purview.''
</P>
<P>
   ``So you want me to be involved in the talks with Milosevic?''
</P>
<P>
   ``Why not, you seem to want to get involved, or you wouldn't be
shooting off your big mouth.''
</P>
<P>
   ``Mr. Clinton, I have had health problems and great internal
problems here in Russia. I have neither the time nor the personnel
to do it.''
</P>
<P>
   ``Then stay out of it when we start bombing, Boris. You don't
play the game, you don't make the rules!''
</P>
<P>
   (Howard Kleinberg, a former editor of the Miami News, is a
columnist for Cox Newspapers. His e-mail address is
hkmiami(at)aol.com.)
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
