A3587 &Cx1f; tad-z
u k &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-TEEPEN-COLUMN28-COX     03-25 0570
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-TEEPEN-COLUMN28-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;    
 &HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    COMMENTARY: U.S. right to tread softly on land-mine issue
 &HT;    By Tom Teepen
 &HT;    c. 1999 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   First Donald Steinberg gets five years as U.S. ambassador in
Angola, which is not altogether jolly duty, and now, for his pains,
he's a point man in land mine policy, with most of the world
hissing Washington's refusal to join 135 nations in a treaty
banning the weapons.
</P>
<P>
   Steinberg, however, has a pretty good product.
</P>
<P>
   The United States is taking a bad rap on this issue, sometimes
from friends _ Canada is appalled _ but more often from nations to
which the issue offers easy posturing and even from nations so
blithely evil they'll sign anything virtuous-sounding without the
slightest intention of honoring the deal. Some half-dozen
signatories already are violating the pact that went into effect
only March 1.
</P>
<P>
   Land mines are especially pernicious weapons. They stay live for
decades _ mines from World War I remain in Europe _ and claim
civilians as their long-term victims, very often heedless children.
Most are designed to maim rather than to kill. (A dead solider can
be left where he falls; the wounded must be tended. A mine
incapacitates at least two combatants.)
</P>
<P>
   There are some 70 million mines buried in the fields and
roadways of 70 countries, especially dense in 25. They are a daily
fact of life in, for instance, Cambodia and Bosnia, and in Angola
mines laid in the interminable civil war have maimed 80,000 and
driven 100,000 from their homes, so far.
</P>
<P>
   Though largely to deaf ears, President Clinton has pleaded
reasonably that the United States, with unique superpower
responsibilities, needs a few years to adjust policy and to perfect
military alternatives before it can honestly sign the international
ban. An effective option is needed, for instance, to the mine field
that helps to keep rash and radical North Korea at bay on the
politically sundered Korean peninsula.
</P>
<P>
   While all of that hangs fire, the United States remains the
world's leader in the crucial and difficult task of demining, and
here Steinberg speaks with a missionary's zeal born of his Angola
experience.
</P>
<P>
   Washington has increased funding in recent years to $120 million
a year, about half of the world effort. U.S. programs train
deminers abroad, pinpoint mines through satellites and other
sophisticated means, teach populations, especially kids, how to ID
suspicious sites, and provide medical backup to victims.
</P>
<P>
   Monthly mine casualties in Cambodia have been cut from 500 to 50
and 4,000 miles of road in Mozambique have been cleared; 3.3
million mines were destroyed from 1996 to '98. And innovative
programs are attracting private help.
</P>
<P>
   The United Nations Association of the USA manages an
Adopt-a-Minefield program; donors alone or by pooling contributions
can clear a whole field. Other groups will deploy a mine-sniffing
dog, still the best detector, for as little as $250.
</P>
<P>
   The U.S. effort to get square with the ban seems genuine if
slow, and meantime the United States is, as a practical matter,
overwhelmingly more a part of the solution than of the problem.
Much of the contrary umbrage is more righteous than right.
</P>
<P>
   Tom Teepen is national correspondent for Cox Newspapers. He is
based in Atlanta. E-mail: teepencolumn(at)coxnews.com.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
