<HEADER>
A3630 &Cx1f; tad-z
u w &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-ARMY-BOX-$ADV28-COX     03-25 0266
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-ARMY-BOX-$ADV28-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    AT-A-GLANCE, RUSSIA'S TROUBLED MILITARY
 &HT;    EDS: With RUSSIA-ARMY-$ADV28, RUSSIA-RECRUIT-$ADV28.
 &HT;    Moving in (i) international and (w) Washington categories
 &HT;    By CHARLES W. HOLMES
 &HT;    c.1999 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   MOSCOW _ The U.S. State Department in February issued an
extraordinarily detailed report to Congress on the status of
Russia's military. It estimated that Russia's Defense Ministry is
operating with a $9 billion debt, which includes about $2.5 billion
in back pay and pensions to active and retired servicemen.
</P>
<P>
   Here are some of the findings:
</P>
<P>
   An internal Russian military analysis found that ``the average
Russian soldier is only marginally combat capable,'' as chronic
economic problems faced by the government have curtailed training
of the country's 1.2 million soldiers, sailors and airmen.
</P>
<P>
   Last year, sea duty for Russian submarines was reduced by 25
percent, while surface ships spent 33 percent less time at sea.
</P>
<P>
   Russian air force pilots in 1998 got only 15 to 40 percent of
normal flying time.
</P>
<P>
   In 1998, the government was three-to-four months behind in
paying salaries to servicemen.
</P>
<P>
   The wage arrears and decline in living standards on Russian
bases has placed the military ``at the low end of the country's
economic scale.''
</P>
<P>
   The result as been an increase in crime, ``particularly theft,
and corruption in the armed forces, as well as suicides among
service members and widespread evasion of military service.''
</P>
<P>
   ENDIT
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
