<HEADER>
A3644 &Cx1f; tad-z
r k &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-BORDERS-COLUMN26-COX     03-25 0749
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BORDERS-COLUMN26-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    It's hard to weed out the hot buttons
 &HT;    By Gary Borders
 &HT;    c.1999 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   NACOGDOCHES, Texas _ After nearly 17 years of writing a column,
the one thing I've learned is that you never know what is going to
set people off. I have written pieces that I was sure would bring
in loads of nasty mail and gotten nary a word. I have written other
columns that seemed utterly innocuous, only to discover that I have
somehow pushed someone's hot button.
</P>
<P>
   Still, it's good to hear from the customers even if they're not
exactly calling to bestow laurels upon you.
</P>
<P>
   One of the first columns I ever wrote, back in the summer of
1982, had to do with my cats, who were having to adapt from living
in the big city of Austin to making do in tiny San Augustine,
population 3,000. I mentioned that my cats were being visited by a
black cat who had taken offense at these big-city cats moving into
town. There had been a few minor skirmishes, the typical antics of
territorial creatures.
</P>
<P>
   The piece was meant to be lighthearted. You want serious, read
George Will.
</P>
<P>
   The morning it appeared, I was visited by a woman who was
convinced I was talking about her cat, even though she lived two
miles down the road. She threatened to sue me. I pointed out it's
hard to libel a cat. Dogs maybe, but truth is always a defense, and
cats are guilty of just about anything you could write about them.
</P>
<P>
   She could not be consoled or calmed. I had ruined her reputation
by talking about her cat. She might have to move or go into the
witness protection program. To this day I have no idea what exactly
caused her to turn into a raving lunatic that Wednesday morning.
She promised her attorney would be in touch, but a few days later
she called to apologize. She had decided it wasn't her cat I was
talking about after all.
</P>
<P>
   I tell this story because a few weeks back I wrote another
allegedly lighthearted column about what the three teen-age boys I
take to school each morning talk about: girls, tongue piercing,
rock videos, which teachers are mean, and which are cool, etc. The
three teens in question had no objection to the piece, though they
requested veto power over future columns that used them as topics.
Tough luck, I told them. Catch another ride if it bothers you.
</P>
<P>
   I have gotten several e-mails and even a handwritten letter from
a few teachers and one teen who read the piece in other newspapers
as far away as Pennsylvania. Two teachers from out of town took the
time to write and tell me that I was:
</P>
<P>
   &QR;  Full of beans.
</P>
<P>
   &QR;  Didn't know anything about teen-agers.
</P>
<P>
   &QR;  Obviously have not been in a classroom in years, and
</P>
<P>
   &QR;  Ought to stick to my knitting, as the saying goes.
</P>
<P>
   Yeech. Lighten up, fellas. I'm on your side. I was simply
recounting what the teens I transport had to say. As for knowing
nothing about teen-agers, all I can say in my defense is that this
is the third set of teens I've helped raise. That doesn't mean I
understand them anymore than I have figured out cats or women, but
I do have some on-the-job experience.
</P>
<P>
   My favorite critique came from a young man in Newville, Pa. I
was impressed he took the time to write, even though he was a tad
critical. He wrote, in part:
</P>
<P>
   ``We (teen-agers) could care less about body piercing. Why
should we care about our government? They do whatever they please.
The electoral college elects the president. Then the president does
whatever he feels he wants to do. We have no influence.
</P>
<P>
   ``I don't know if you were trying to write an informative essay
on this topic, but if you were, it was a horrible one. My friends
and I can write better essays and articles. We shall be very glad
if you respond to my letter!
</P>
<P>
   Cordially yours,
</P>
<P>
   John Lehman.''
</P>
<P>
   Young Mr. Lehman's letter was flawlessly written, with nary a
misspelling or grammatical error. He must have some good teachers.
</P>
<P>
   I am a bit saddened that he is already so cynical about
politics, and I hope he soon realizes that people do have influence
and voting does matter.
</P>
<P>
   As for whether I was trying to write an informative essay on
teen-agers, the answer would be no. I'll leave that to others more
qualified.
</P>
<P>
   Maybe I'll stick to cats from now on. At least they can't sue
me.
</P>
<P>
   Gary Borders is editor and publisher of The Nacogdoches Daily
Sentinel. His e-mail address is gborders(at)coxnews.com.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
