<SLUG> BC-ERNESTMURRAY-COLUMN26-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    A work in progress
 &HT;    By Ernest Murray
 &HT;    c.1999 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   LUFKIN, Texas _ The preacher, the other Sunday morning, was well
into his sermon about the work of God. ``Notice how God works in
all our lives,'' he said. ``We must allow God to work everyday for
us.''
</P>
<P>
   My 8-year-old daughter leaned into me and whispered, ``Why is
that everything about God is about work?''
</P>
<P>
   I wish I could have asked such a smart question.
</P>
<P>
   She's right of course. We are told so much about how God works
that seldom do we hear about the God who plays.
</P>
<P>
   All work and no play would make this world pretty dull.
</P>
<P>
   Walking out of church it was easy to see the whimiscal side of
God. The trees were putting on new, leafy coats and the azaleas and
dogwoods were in full bloom.
</P>
<P>
   It's the time of year when we shake off the gray, muddy days of
winter and watch in wonderment as the earth renews itself.
</P>
<P>
   Sometimes it takes the wisdom of an 8-year-old to bring it into
focus.
</P>
<P>
   God does work in mysterious ways.
</P>
<P>
   Ernest Murray is managing editor of The Lufkin Daily News.
E-mail: emurray(at)coxnews.com.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-03-25-99 1119EST &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> NYT19990325.0060 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-03-25 11:19 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A3646 &Cx1f; tad-z
r k &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-GARCIA-COLUMN26-COX     03-25 0716
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-GARCIA-COLUMN26-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Split-second decisions that can last a lifetime
 &HT;    By Arnold Garcia
 &HT;    c.1999 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   AUSTIN, Texas _ It all happened so fast. I don't even remember
drawing or aiming the weapon. It was as if the pistol jumped into
my hand and fired itself.
</P>
<P>
   The next thing I remember was the other guy laying face down in
the street. It was shown later that I fired three times and hit him
twice. One round would have given him a bad stomach ache if the
round to his head hadn't killed him.
</P>
<P>
   The training officer had a question and a prediction.
</P>
<P>
   The question: ``Why did you do that?''
</P>
<P>
   ``He ran over my partner,'' I replied.
</P>
<P>
   The prediction: ``You just bought yourself a trip to the grand
jury.''
</P>
<P>
   It just happened so fast, I didn't think. I reacted. If it had
been real life, I would have a lot of explaining to do and probably
plenty of free time to work on those explanations.
</P>
<P>
   It wasn't real, though. The scene played out on a sophisticated
piece of machinery used to train Austin police officers on
shoot/don't shoot situations.
</P>
<P>
   A weapon converted to shoot laser ``bullets'' is hooked to a
computer that tracks the way the weapon is aimed, counts rounds and
scores hits. A video gives you the perspective of a police officer
and puts you in a situation in which you have only seconds to
decide whether to shoot.
</P>
<P>
   In the scenario played for me, my partner and I stopped a van. I
was in the passenger seat and my screen colleague told me to cover
the passenger side of the vehicle we had stopped. As he approached
the van, the driver threw it in reverse, knocking my partner down.
</P>
<P>
   Then the driver got out and approached. Everything from then on
was reaction driven by adrenaline. The next thing I know, I fired
and the driver of the van went down.
</P>
<P>
   The computer gives the training officer providential power. With
a mere push of a button, he can show what would have happened had
the weapon not been fired.
</P>
<P>
   In my scenario, the van driver raised his hands in surrender. A
diplomatic butt chewing followed.
</P>
<P>
   ``He was not a threat to you when he got out of that van,''
Detective Jerry Staton noted. He didn't have to say the rest: I
killed him anyway.
</P>
<P>
   It was but a taste of the firearms training cadets receive as
they prepare to take a place on the police force. Once on the
force, officers are periodically trained on the system.
</P>
<P>
   Staton was just one of dozens of officers who volunteer their
time to the Citizens Police Academy, a program designed to give
civilians insight into the making of an Austin police officer.
</P>
<P>
   It is an extensive course, but the Firearms Training Systems (or
FATS) is a curriculum highlight _ the ultimate video game and about
as close to real as technology can get.
</P>
<P>
   The scenarios vary. A drunken man waves a machete. Complicating
things, a baby is involved. A woman throws a knife at you in
another. In yet another, a man is choking a woman. None of the
situations is easy. Each is designed to test restraint and
judgment.
</P>
<P>
   Before and after time on the FATS, there are lectures about
handling a weapon and a briefing on department's policies on using
deadly force. There is also attention paid to the luxury of time.
Time is always on the side of the Monday-morning quarterback.
</P>
<P>
   Don't read this as an endorsement of police shootings or a
justification of the three incidents this year in which Austin
police officers fired at civilians. Two of those were fatal.
</P>
<P>
   Do read this for what it is intended to be _ a glimpse, however
fleeting, of what it feels like to be on the spot where your
information and field of vision are limited and a decision needs to
be made immediately.
</P>
<P>
   For me, the FATS was a real eye-opener. I think of a firearm as
a tool that came with a job (in the U.S. Army) I don't have
anymore. I like to think of myself as a peaceable kind of guy now,
one who wishes that no physical harm befall others.
</P>
<P>
   I was amazed at how easy it was for me to fire and keep firing
until the bad guy went down. He was, by the way, holding a knife.
</P>
<P>
   Arnold Garcia is editorial page editor of the Austin
American-Statesman. He may be reached at agarcia(at)statesman.com.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
