<DATE_TIME> 1999-03-25 11:20 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A3648 &Cx1f; tad-z
r l &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-HIGH-FASHION26-COX     03-25 1487
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-HIGH-FASHION26-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    At the top of haute couture
 &HT;    By Cara Anna
 &HT;    c. 1999 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   WEST PALM BEACH, Fla. _ France Goldman runs a hand over a
late-model purchase and smiles.
</P>
<P>
   She has yet to take it on the road, but it looks good.
Well-built. Polished exterior. Handles well on the curves.
</P>
<P>
   The cost? Let's just say it was in the five-figure range. With
the proper maintenance, it can last years, even decades.
</P>
<P>
   Perfect. She gives one last approving look.
</P>
<P>
   Then she steps out of it, grabs a white plastic hanger and goes
into her bedroom closet for another.
</P>
<P>
   France Goldman doesn't know how many five-figure gowns she has
in her Boca West home, and it's better that way.
</P>
<P>
   ``I don't count,'' she says. ``I don't want to count. Otherwise,
I would panic.''
</P>
<P>
   In a one-year buying spree _ January 1998 to January 1999 _
Goldman zipped to the top of the haute couture, or high-fashion,
world.
</P>
<P>
   Shopping for couture is nothing like buying khakis at the mall.
The clothes are hand-made only in Paris and tailored, again in
Paris, for individual clients. Design houses are discreet about
costs, which can balloon several thousand dollars on the strength
of a few well-placed beads.
</P>
<P>
   Goldman, eager to have it, now sits in the front row of
designers' semiannual runway shows. She picks the clothes she
likes, then consults with her husband, who carries the checkbook.
</P>
<P>
   She is a very new, very good customer. On her second trip to
Paris last July, she says, she ``went wild'' and bought an entire
wardrobe of the hand-tailored, one-of-a-kind, made-only-in-Paris
creations. How many dresses? She won't say.
</P>
<P>
   But designers said, ``Bonjour!'' For the March issue of W
magazine, both Christian Lacroix and Givenchy picked Goldman to
model their clothes for a story on haute couture clients. Goldman
was a natural choice _ she is a size 4, a former model, a perfect
fit for some designs.
</P>
<P>
   And ``reportedly the single largest buyer of couture,'' W wrote
under Goldman's name.
</P>
<P>
   That distinction is hard to prove. Even the number of couture
clients is fuzzy. Some say 300, some say 3,000. Anyone who can
afford a $20,000 ``business'' suit _ or how about a $100,000
evening dress? _ is welcome.
</P>
<P>
   But enough about money, says Goldman, who says she doesn't keep
track of price. She goes to Paris because, after years as a single,
struggling model with two young boys and one good pair of shoes,
she has the chance to pursue her passion _ beautiful, hand-made
clothes designed especially for her.
</P>
<P>
   So far, her husband approves. And why not? It was his idea.
</P>
<P>
   Enter France and David Goldman's home and make a quick right.
There, beside the piano, is a slightly larger-than-life statue of
France Goldman herself, wearing a turquoise strapless dress.
</P>
<P>
   The dress is the first couture outfit Goldman ever owned. ``It
was almost a perfect fit except the length,'' she says.
</P>
<P>
   And the statue is a gift from her husband of one year, David. He
asked France's brother, a sculptor in Montreal, to make it before
the couple was married last March.
</P>
<P>
   ``I thought it was a little ostentatious,'' France says, ``but
my husband liked it.''
</P>
<P>
   It was David who said, ``Let's try'' when they came across an
Ungaro couture trunk show at a ski resort in St. Moritz. She tried
on the turquoise column dress _ ``It looked a little Egyptian'' _
and he bought it.
</P>
<P>
   It was David who said, ``Come on, we'll go together'' when
France said she couldn't go to the Paris fashion shows because it
was during the school year, and her boys might need her. He
insisted, and she went for the first time last January.
</P>
<P>
   Now, though, it's David who says, ``What do you need it for?''
and ``When are you going to wear it?'' and ``Do you really need
three gowns?'' when they make their twice-a-year trips to Paris.
</P>
<P>
   But he hardly ever says ``No.''
</P>
<P>
   ``I'm sure he has a limit, but I haven't heard it yet,'' France
says.
</P>
<P>
   David Goldman is proud of his wife. ``When you're with somebody
you care about, you're sensitive to their desires,'' he says. ``I'm
with France. She loves fashion, she eats fashion. Going to the
couture shows is something she dreamt about.''
</P>
<P>
   And that's that.
</P>
<P>
   France is 40. David is 57. Friends introduced them four years
ago.
</P>
<P>
   At the time, France was a model in Boca, working the
country-club and resort fashion shows that she now attends and
hosts.
</P>
<P>
   Her life was this: daughter of an interior decorator in
Montreal, an upper-middle-class childhood, lessons in dressmaking
from her mother's seamstress. She started learning English,
reluctantly, at age 21 when she started modeling. She did
television commercials, catalog work, ads for beer and wine.
</P>
<P>
   With two children and her first husband, she moved to Boca about
10 years ago and continued modeling. Divorce was tough, money-wise,
and she raised the boys alone. Eager to remain elegant, she adopted
an all-black wardrobe, shopped at boutique sales and got discounts
when she modeled for department stores. She had one good pair of
shoes and one good bag. Then she met David.
</P>
<P>
   His life: the first of seven children, son of a small
manufacturer in Boston, entrepreneur. He borrowed money to buy a
series of businesses, including machine-tool companies that make
car and airplane parts. Now he imports cobalt and is president of
the Goldman Financial Group, based in Boston.
</P>
<P>
   He moved to Boca in 1993 after looking at 200 homes around the
state. It was this place _ a two-story home with Venetian decor
that looks deceptively small from the road _ or Fisher Island in
Miami, he says. But Fisher Island's golf course had only nine
holes.
</P>
<P>
   Goldman worries about fitting in down here, which is why he
won't talk about the Paris shopping trips in dollars and cents.
</P>
<P>
   ``They'll think we're brash, gross people,'' he says.
</P>
<P>
   And, ``It ruins it if the person's only looking at the money.''
</P>
<P>
   Remember, these are the most beautiful, best-made clothes in the
world, he says earnestly. ``Why spend the money? I can see people
saying that,'' he adds. ``If I was 21, I wouldn't understand it. I
was making $50 a week. This is not understandable for someone who
was never part of this world.''
</P>
<P>
   But hey. He's part of it now.
</P>
<P>
   France Goldman does not bounce around the house in $40,000
dresses.
</P>
<P>
   But she's not in a T-shirt and flip-flops, either.
</P>
<P>
   She wears tennis clothes, or today's ``Boca uniform'' of Armani
khakis and pink Chanel top. She is a room mother at her boys'
private school, helping with field trips and parties. She spends
every Sunday through Thursday evening with Jonathan, 12, and
Matthieu, 10.
</P>
<P>
   She keeps a stash of Barbies at the house to give to young girls
who might visit. She contributes to charities. Last Christmas, she
and David donated 50 Furbies for a Ballet Florida fund-raiser.
</P>
<P>
   Couture, she says, is not their life.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's our little treat,'' she says.
</P>
<P>
   She stands in her dressing room-slash-office, looking through a
rack of recent buys. The sun through the skylight touches her Louis
Vuitton day planner and fashion books and Diana and Monica Lewinsky
bios. In the living room, Celine Dion sings from hidden speakers.
</P>
<P>
   Here. Goldman holds up some of her favorites. A Gaultier jacket
made of fur and antique embroidered purses. A Christian Dior dress
of woven ribbon. A Pierre Balmain gold jacket and olive pants with
fur trim. A Givenchy black sleeveless embroidered dress with train.
</P>
<P>
   She wears them to the opera, perhaps, or to a special party.
She's careful. She's done nothing more than lose a few beads.
``Don't jinx me,'' she says.
</P>
<P>
   When Goldman decides to buy a couture outfit, this is what
happens:
</P>
<P>
   She consults with her husband. If they argue, she usually wins.
</P>
<P>
   She visits the design house while they are in Paris.
</P>
<P>
   She stands while as many as seven people take her measurements
in front of a three-way mirror. David watches from a nearby couch,
sipping coffee. A fitting can take hours.
</P>
<P>
   She gets a discount of 35 percent to 40 percent if she fits the
outfit shown on the runway, because another does not have to be
made from scratch. (If it has to be made, she must wait several
weeks before a package marked ``Paris'' arrives at her door.)
</P>
<P>
   She rarely meets the designers. ``They're artists. They're never
around.''
</P>
<P>
   She flies back to Paris or New York for fittings.
</P>
<P>
   She gets free alterations.
</P>
<P>
   She gets free delivery.
</P>
<P>
   She gets the name of a good Paris dry cleaner.
</P>
<P>
   Then, once she wears the outfit for an event, she puts it away
for the rest of the season, packed full-length in acid-free paper.
</P>
<P>
   She might wear it the next season. Or the one after that.
</P>
<P>
   Some outfits, Goldman says, she still hasn't found the occasion
to wear.
</P>
<P>
   And the next trip to Paris is just four months away.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
