</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-LOW-FASHION26-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Collecting the fine art of couture
 &HT;    By Cara Anna
 &HT;    c. 1999 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   WEST PALM BEACH, Fla. _ You'll have to excuse Iris Apfel today.
She has the flu.
</P>
<P>
   She was going to model a few of her hundreds, no, ``hundreds and
hundreds and hundreds'' of haute couture outfits, but she's just
not up to it.
</P>
<P>
   She offers a glass of water instead.
</P>
<P>
   (Note the coaster. It is a piece of plastic made to look like a
slice of ham.)
</P>
<P>
   Apfel, of Palm Beach, is a collector. ``One of the greatest
shoppers in the Western world,'' she calls herself.
</P>
<P>
   If she were feeling better, maybe she'd show off her stashes of
spinets, or antique church vestments or 18th-century dog beds.
</P>
<P>
   But not today. She rifles through the fat rack of clothing that
crowds her entryway and lifts out a coat.
</P>
<P>
   ``Oof,'' she says.
</P>
<P>
   Haute couture is heavy. It has linings and interlinings and
padding to make it fit perfectly. That's why she's bought so much,
Apfel says. Couture is art.
</P>
<P>
   Too bad it's dying, she says.
</P>
<P>
   Apfel started collecting clothes in the 1950s, with a few pairs
of beaded pantyhose from the French design house Lanvin.
</P>
<P>
   She has Japanese obis, outfits from every major designer and
rows and rows of Geoffrey Beene, who happens to be a friend.
</P>
<P>
   Museum curators admire Apfel because she was at it long before
vintage clothes were cool. And they love to watch her style, from
her ``Is that the Old Navy gal?'' glasses on down.
</P>
<P>
   Apfel, for example, once converted a Middle Eastern slingshot
into a dandy necklace. She liked the wooden wishbone shape.
</P>
<P>
   ``Iris will never look like anyone else in the room,'' says
Ellen Shanley, costume curator at the Fashion Institute of
Technology.
</P>
<P>
   ``In terms of thinking of couture as art, she's really unique,''
says Richard Martin, curator of the Metropolitan Museum of Art's
Costume Institute. ``She's one of those women whose closets we're
most likely to raid.''
</P>
<P>
   Martin and friends make a game of describing her outfit after
parties. ``There's always a bracelet under her sleeve you don't
notice until halfway through dinner,'' Martin says.
</P>
<P>
   Apfel, a New York native and former art history major, is
flattered. ``Fashion is social history,'' she says. ``I don't think
it should be put out to pasture. And if I can wear it as well,
that's a double whammy.''
</P>
<P>
   But damned if she's going to pay today's sky-high couture
prices. ``Do I look like I'm certifiable?'' she snaps.
</P>
<P>
   How old are you, Ms. Apfel? ``I'm a lady of a certain age.
Whatever that means.''
</P>
<P>
   How much do you spend on these clothes? She sidesteps. ``Couture
gets more and more costly,'' she says. ``It never made money for
any of the design houses. It's done to perpetuate the name and
glamorize the perfumes and the ready-to-wear clothes.''
</P>
<P>
   But really, how much? She won't say. She remembers chasing a
gray Lanvin coat down the Rue St. Honore in Paris in the late '50s
and paying just $300. No small amount back then, but compare it to
today's prices!
</P>
<P>
   In the past two years she hasn't bought a thing. She asked about
a nice Galliano skirt recently. ``They said they'd give it to me
for $38,000. I said, `Thank you very much.' '' She nearly sniffs.
(Of course, she said no.)
</P>
<P>
   Bravo, says her husband of 51 years, Carl. He supports her
scrounging and bargaining, and complains only when she indulges her
weakness for feathered coats. They're ``so impractical,'' she says.
</P>
<P>
   Together, the Apfels run Old World Weavers, a company based in
New York that provides textiles for top interior decorators.
They've worked for the White House, the Flagler Museum, the Norton.
They honeymooned in Palm Beach and have lived here more than 20
years.
</P>
<P>
   Now, quite frankly, they are running out of room for Apfel's
clothes. ``I have more than I need or want,'' she says.
</P>
<P>
   And it's not even her favorite collection.
</P>
<P>
   ``If push comes to shove,'' she says pertly, ``I'll go with my
accessories.''
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
