<HEADER>
A3651 &Cx1f; tad-z
r e &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-KILBORN-LATESHOW26-CO     03-25 0523
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-KILBORN-LATESHOW26-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Craig Kilborn goes big-time network with `Late Late Show'
 &HT;    By Kevin Thompson
 &HT;    c. 1999 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   WEST PALM BEACH, Fla. _ Arrogant. Sexist. Good hair.
</P>
<P>
   That's how Craig Kilborn, the one-time host of Comedy Central's
``The Daily Show,'' is often described.
</P>
<P>
   ``Yeah, the hair has been consistent,'' Kilborn cracks. ``I wash
it everyday and use a little bit of gel.''
</P>
<P>
   And the other adjectives?
</P>
<P>
   ``Aw, it's just a little act I do,'' he shrugs. ``As a viewer,
it's somebody I'd like to see. But I'm actually kind of boring in
real life.''
</P>
<P>
   If you like your humor served up with a
I-know-it-all-and-you-don't smirk, Kilborn's your man. Starting
this week, that sometimes annoying smirk goes big-time network. For
2 1/2 years, the 36-year-old acid-tongued host made ``The Daily
Show'' one of TV's funniest programs. No wonder. Pretty-boy Kilborn
possesses two made-for-TV attributes: He's ladies-man smooth and
has a killer delivery.
</P>
<P>
   ``He's a plastic gun,'' a ``Daily Show'' writer once said,
``shooting cop-killer bullets.''
</P>
<P>
   Now the former SportsCenter anchor is firing those bullets as
host of ``The Late Late Show with Craig Kilborn.'' The lanky
Minnesota native replaces Tom Snyder, one of TV's few remaining
dinosaurs. That's like yanking ``I Love Lucy'' and replacing it
with, say, ``Dawson's Creek.''
</P>
<P>
   The new ``Late Late Show'' will look nothing like Snyder's. For
starters, Kilborn will have a studio audience. Nothing ``Tonight
Show''-ish, though. Only 80 people. The producers say they want a
show that looks very intimate.
</P>
<P>
   You can also expect a drastic set change. The show is supposed
to take place in the den of Kilborn's lavish Hollywood Hills home.
That means you'll see big leather chairs, closets, a bar (!) and a
spectacular Hollywood view. Like Mister Rogers (or maybe Playboy's
Hef), Kilborn will often stroll over to his closet and take out a
jacket. If ratings are pretty bad, expect Kilborn to walk over to
the bar a lot, too.
</P>
<P>
   Unlike Jay Leno or David Letterman, Kilborn will have no band
and no goofy sidekick. But he will have his Daily Show signature
piece ``5 Questions.''
</P>
<P>
   I played ``1 Question'' with Kilborn.
</P>
<P>
   Which is the better network? CBS or Comedy Central?
</P>
<P>
   ``Obviously CBS, because of Sammo Hung!''
</P>
<P>
   Kilborn is a welcome addition to the late night arena and should
keep college-aged kids _ and probably countless baby boomers _ up
late. You know, it's funny how the mold of a late night talk show
host has evolved from IBM conservative to smart-mouthed MTV cool.
Kilborn is certainly the latter. But he's also a cocksure, loose
cannon who doesn't know when to keep his mouth shut.
</P>
<P>
   In fact, ``The Daily Show'' once suspended Kilborn for making
sexist remarks in Esquire about one of the show's female
co-creators.
</P>
<P>
   ``It was a bad joke,'' he admits.
</P>
<P>
   Listen up, Craig. Sometimes the wisecracking bit is screamingly
funny. But sometimes it's just downright mean. You'll do well at
CBS if you learn the difference.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
