<HEADER>
A3652 &Cx1f; tad-z
r e &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-MODSQUAD-REVIEW26-COX     03-25 0514
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-MODSQUAD-REVIEW26-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Gen X cats can't claw way out of `Squad' script
 &HT;    By Kevin D. Thompson
 &HT;    c. 1999 Palm Beach Post-Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   WEST PALM BEACH, Fla. _ How bad is ``The Mod Squad''?
</P>
<P>
   It's so bad, it's funny. You'll scream when you hear '90s
characters spout such super-bad '70s phrases as ``Ya dig,'' ``Right
on!'' and ``pig.'' You'll howl at the garish hippie clothes
(vision-impairing plaid pants, dusty Levi jeans jackets and too
many brown and orange shirts). You'll crack up whenever one of the
uninspired actors intones such time-worn cop cliches as, ``I had to
call for backup.''
</P>
<P>
   Uh, how about calling for a better script?
</P>
<P>
   A more appropriate title for this film would've been The Odd
Squad. Everything about this mess of a movie is odd. The oddest
thing of all is that ``The Mod Squad'' got made.
</P>
<P>
   Where are Michael Cole, Peggy Lipton and Clarence Williams III
when you need them? The original Mod Squad stars certainly could
teach this woeful Gen X crop (Claire Danes, Omar Epps and Giovanni
Ribisi) a thing or two.
</P>
<P>
   You probably remember the premise: Three cats, er, we mean, kids
were on their way to the joint. Linc Hayes (Epps) is the cool,
angry one from the 'hood who likes to burn up stuff. Pete Cochrane
(Ribisi) is the snarling, wild (and most annoying!) one who likes
lifting stuff. And Julie Barnes (Danes) is the blond hottie who
likes beating up people and drinking bottles of rum.
</P>
<P>
   Instead of doing time, the three get tapped to serve as
undercover cops. After all, as their tough-talking captain (Dennis
Farina) barks, ``These kids can get into a thousand places we
can't.''
</P>
<P>
   Their first case: Bust up a seedy club that's a front for a
teen-age prostitute ring. But, before you can say, ``Solid,'' our
pimply-faced heroes are up to their turtlenecks (yes, we see '70s
turtle necks in hot L.A.!) in dirty cop scandals, missing drugs and
secret meetings in abandoned warehouses. If you squint, you can see
Starsky and Hutch, Mannix and Columbo in the background.
</P>
<P>
   ``The Mod Squad'' fails on all levels and is the clear
front-runner for the worst film of 1999. Epps and Danes are
particularly disappointing. While talented, both were unable to
elevate the weak material they were handed. (Send angry letters to
screenwriters Stephen Kay, Scott Silver and Kate Lanier.)
Meanwhile, Ribisi, fresh from ``Saving Private Ryan'' and perhaps
best known as Phoebe's brother on ``Friends,'' is the kind of
smart-alecky kid you don't mind slapping upside the head a few
times.
</P>
<P>
   The film's only bright spots are Eddie Griffin as one of Linc's
former running buddies and ``The Practice's'' Steve Harris as an
Internal Affairs investigator. The problem: Both only get about
three minutes of screen time.
</P>
<P>
   Odd, indeed.
</P>
<P>
   ``THE MOD SQUAD''
</P>
<P>
   Rated R: Violence, profanity, sexual situations
</P>
<P>
   Running time: 1 hour, 34 minutes
</P>
<P>
   The verdict: A laughably bad mess of a movie that trashes ``The
Mod Squad's'' good name.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-03-25-99 1121EST &QL; 
</TRAILER>
