<DOCNO> NYT19990325.0065 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-03-25 11:21 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A3653 &Cx1f; tad-z
r e &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-ROLLERDERBY26-COX     03-25 0937
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-ROLLERDERBY26-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Wreck 'n' roll
 &HT;    By Phil Kloer
 &HT;    c.1999 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   ATLANTA _ The crowd is screaming, the announcers are
hyperventilating, the skaters are rolling around on the floor
pulling each other's hair. Roller derby _ that blue-collar brawler
of a quasi-sport (and television staple) _ has returned, billed as
``Rollerjam.''
</P>
<P>
   The updated version features a more ``Baywatch'' approach to the
female skaters (tight zippered tops and flowing locks) and some of
the Springer-esque feel of professional wrestling _ a potent brew
of cleavage and carnage.
</P>
<P>
   Or as Brian Gamble, the goateed blocker from the black-clad,
bad-boy New York Enforcers, shouted at the end of a recent match,
``We're the baddest team in the whole (gosh-darned) league, and
we'll bust anybody's (rear end) that wants to get up on the track
with us!''
</P>
<P>
   Oh, those Enforcers are so b-b-b-bad to the bone. Recently, in
fact, Gamble found himself in Atlanta with Laura Hyzer of a rival
team, the Texas Rustlers. He reached into his gym bag and pulled
out ... not brass knuckles, but a Ziploc bag full of Rice Krispies
marshmallow treats. The Enforcer broke off a gooey chunk and shared
it with the Rustler, who smiled sweetly and gave him a back rub as
thanks.
</P>
<P>
   ``He's supposed to be the mean one, I'm supposed to be the nice
one,'' explained Hyzer, nicely.
</P>
<P>
   OK, so we're not talking blood feuds. We're talking '90s
marketing applied to a competition that ran out of gas in the '70s,
and now features children and even grandchildren of some of the
original rollers.
</P>
<P>
   The revival is the work of the Nashville Network, which has seen
its ratings rise about 50 percent overall since ``Rollerjam''
debuted in January, and up to 300 percent among teen-age boys. Some
country music fans are outraged, but the country music channel is
attracting advertisers such as Sony PlayStation and the hit teen
movie ``Varsity Blues.''
</P>
<P>
   ``We're hitting a real young audience that TNN doesn't reach,
which is what we really wanted,'' says Rick Cornish, research
manager for CBS Cable, the parent company of the Nashville Network.
There are already plans to sell the show around the world.
</P>
<P>
   The shows, which air from 8 to 10 p.m. Fridays and are repeated
from 5 to 7 p.m. Saturdays, are taped at an arena at Universal
Studios Florida in Orlando, Fla. There are six teams of five men
and five women each. Women skate against women for a quarter, then
men against men. There are bad teams and good teams, and the
``rules'' seem to involve getting one skater, a ``jammer,'' to
skate through a knot of the opposing team's ``blockers.'' But the
real bloodlust from the fans seems to come when somebody throws in
a quasi-wrestling move like ``the Eliminator,'' sort of a body slam
on skates.
</P>
<P>
   ``Most parents are proud if their kids are doctors or lawyers,''
says Hyzer, a former Atlantan who's rollin'. ``My dad's proud cause
I beat people up.''
</P>
<P>
   There are many roads to ``Rollerjam'' _ some skaters are former
Olympic speedskaters, some played hockey or kickboxed, one's a
former ``American Gladiator'' and Gina Lombardo is a ``cream corn
wrestling champion'' (two years running) at Daytona Beach's Bike
Week.
</P>
<P>
   Hyzer is an odd duck in this flock. A former Junior Olympics
skater (her proud dad, Walter, owns a skating center in Cumming,
Ga.), the 20-year-old was on an academic scholarship at the
University of Georgia when she auditioned for ``Rollerjam.'' She
moved to Orlando, but continues her UGA studies in chemical
engineering via computer.
</P>
<P>
   ``You've got to really be in great shape,'' she says. ``It's
physically demanding. Some mornings I wake up, I feel like I've
been in a car wreck.''
</P>
<P>
   ``If you don't know how to land right, you're history,'' agrees
Gamble.
</P>
<P>
   Unlike such break-from-the-pack ``Rollerjam'' stars as the
200-pound Jeannet Abraham, aka ``The Minister of Pain,'' or some of
the women like the self-styled ``Bod Squad,'' whose zippers seem to
get lower as the matches go on, Hyzer radiates wholesomeness.
</P>
<P>
   ``I smile too much,'' she says, smiling broadly. ``They told me
that I've got to stop smiling so much.'' And she adds, in reference
to some of the other queens of the rink, ``I'm out there to skate.
I'm not out there to flash myself to the crowd.''
</P>
<P>
   The original roller derby was invented in 1935, but it was the
new medium of television that made it so popular. In the late '40s,
before ``I Love Lucy'' or ``The Honeymooners,'' it was one of the
most-watched TV shows in prime-time on both CBS and ABC. The
sports' popularity peaked in the early '70s, when Joanie Weston
reigned as a San Francisco Bay Bomber and Raquel Welch starred in
the movie ``Kansas City Bomber.''
</P>
<P>
   After the sport folded and laid dormant for 25 years, it was
revived by Jerry Seltzer, son of Leo Seltzer, roller derby's
inventor. The younger Seltzer now holds the title of commissioner
of the World Skating League, although the league exists mainly in
the one rink at Universal Studios.
</P>
<P>
   Hyzer wasn't even born when the original roller derby took its
final fall in 1973. Although some original rollers are now coaches
and trainers, Hyzer is part of the new generation, at home on
inline skates and Polymax floors instead of wooden rinks. But some
things never change.
</P>
<P>
   She recalls her ``Rollerjam'' debut, which airs Friday night.
``I got a bloody lip after a fall. The cameraman was right in my
face, filming. I said, `No, don't shoot me with blood on my face.'
</P>
<P>
   ``He said, 'No, this is great!'''
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
