<DATE_TIME> 1999-03-25 11:22 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A3656 &Cx1f; tad-z
r e &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-BOOKS-GRISHAM26-COX     03-25 0571
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BOOKS-GRISHAM26-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Preachy release from Grisham good, but not his best
 &HT;    By Jay Milner
 &HT;    c.1999 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   John Grisham, the Mississippi lawyer who writes a best-selling
semi-mystery novel every year, is something of a phenomenon in more
ways than one. In this time of almost anything goes in the way of
sex and violence in our entertainment media forms, Grisham's
stories never delve into either, but still sell like the proverbial
hotcakes.
</P>
<P>
   That is to say, his heroes and heroines never wind up in bed
together and there are no car chases or exploding buildings and
that sort of thing that's so prevalent in today's books and movies
and TV action shows. Grisham's most recent books, in point of fact,
make me wonder if perhaps he hasn't been ``born again'' in a
religious sense.
</P>
<P>
   Last year there was his ``Street Lawyer,'' in which the
protagonist quit his high-powered job with one of Washington,
D.C.'s most prominent law firms to take on cases of street people
who couldn't afford to pay.
</P>
<P>
   Now along comes Grisham's 1999 book, ``The Testament''
(Doubleday) with a recovering alcoholic D.C. attorney who risks his
life in a search for a missionary lady who has inherited billions
from her eccentric father, who leaped from his office window to his
death, after writing his last will and testament leaving his long
lost daughter, the missionary, all his billions and disinheriting
his other seven children who are spoiled rotten and mean.
</P>
<P>
   As the story begins, Nate O'Riley, a litigator par excellence,
has just completed a term in an addiction clinic. He is a
recovering alcoholic, recovering for the third or fourth time, in
fact, after falling off the wagon each time he is released back
into the real world to practice law. This time, his boss lawyer
convinces him to take on the task of finding the heir to a recent
client's mega fortune after said client has leaped to his death
immediately after writing a new will leaving everything, meaning
billions, to his illegitimate daughter who is somewhere in the
swampy wilds of Brazil catering to the spiritual and medical needs
of the Indians there. She is a doctor missionary, who apparently
doesn't want to be found by the outside world.
</P>
<P>
   Nate's journey into the snakey, alligator and
I-don't-know-what-all infested swamps is filled with many
unexpected adventures and, when he finally finds her, she refuses
to come back with him or even sign the necessary papers to denounce
her inheritance.
</P>
<P>
   But Nate and Rachel bond in a strange manner as the story moves
along. She exerts an influence on Nate's attitude toward life and
he, apparently, reaches her in ways he cannot understand, but
senses.
</P>
<P>
   Grisham doesn't exactly preach in this book, but he comes close.
Since he has the knack for moving the story along at an absorbing
clip, this doesn't really get in the way. I read this one straight
through, just as I have other Grisham books, but I'd have to say it
isn't my favorite by any means.
</P>
<P>
   But what the hey, the man turns them out year in and year out
and they all keep selling big, so any complaints, especially from
someone who tries to write books himself now and then has to come
out sounding like sour grapes.
</P>
<P>
   So, I won't say some things I might feel like I'd like to say.
</P>
<P>
   Jay Milner writes for Cox Newspapers.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
