<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-03-25 11:22 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A3657 &Cx1f; tad-z
r e &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-STEVIEVAUGHN26-COX     03-25 1093
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-STEVIEVAUGHN26-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    A fresh take on Stevie Ray Vaughn
 &HT;    By Don McLeese
 &HT;    c.1999 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   AUSTIN, Texas _ Over the course of his recording career, Stevie
Ray Vaughan didn't alter his musical convictions so much as
transform the musical climate surrounding him. Amid the reverence
with which Vaughan is almost universally held today, it might be
hard to remember what a daunting challenge it was for him to rescue
the blues from cliche, to revitalize the music in a manner that
would transcend revivalism. It's hard to recall a time when he
wasn't a guitar god immortalized with a statue by the river, but a
skinny kid, sweet and shy, whose entire life was wrapped up on
those six strings.
</P>
<P>
   These days, Vaughan is memorialized as much for his mythic image
_ the guitarist as border gunslinger in the Clint Eastwood/Sergio
Leone mode _ and his tragic end as he is for his artistry, but the
reissue of his recording studio catalogue with Double Trouble
offers the opportunity once again to approach this music fresh.
Each of the four albums he cut with the band in the '80s comes in a
remastered, expanded edition with previously unissued bonus tracks,
an interview segment and new liner notes. There is also a new
compilation titled ``The Real Deal: Greatest Hits Volume 2,''
though its selection largely will be redundant for Vaughan
diehards. Initiates will find ``Volume 1'' to be a better sampler.
</P>
<P>
   By the time Vaughan and band released their ``Texas Flood''
debut in 1983, the blues had long been considered a musical
anachronism in rock circles, a spent force, an indulgence of
guitarists who had nothing new to say and took way too long to say
it. More than 10 years after the guitar group Ten Years After, the
very notion of blues-rock sounded like a bad Woodstock flashback.
The power-trio format imposed additional limitations, along with
the inevitable comparisons to Cream and Hendrix. That Vaughan would
ultimately be embraced as an equal _ or even an inspiration _ by
the likes of B.B. King, Buddy Guy and Eric Clapton seemed about as
likely as the Black Crowes one day being hailed as trailblazers by
the Rolling Stones.
</P>
<P>
   It's little wonder, then, that the guitarist who asserts himself
so aggressively with the flurry of notes opening ``Love Struck
Baby'' sounds like a man on a mission, an artist with something to
prove, knowing that he has to be better than good to put the charge
back into the blues. Though Vaughan's major claim to fame beyond
the clubs of Texas was his guest guitar on David Bowie's ``Let's
Dance,'' 1983's ``Texas Flood'' debut offers no concession to rock
fashionability. Instead, the music hits so hard that it cannot be
denied, while daring the listener to resist the punch.
</P>
<P>
   Though his singing is merely serviceable at this point and the
material hit-and-miss, the music exists for only one purpose: to
allow Stevie to play his guitar. It is plain that he has already
mastered every trick in the book, and that he can't resist the
temptation to cram practically everything he knows into every solo.
It's a blessing, then, that the rhythm section of drummer Chris
Layton and bassist Tommy Shannon plays with so much focus and
efficiency, supporting the guitar rather than competing with it.
Highlighting the four bonus additions is a live performance of
Lonnie Mack's ``Wham'' that all but reduces the stage to cinders.
</P>
<P>
   While Vaughan's command of tone and bluesy focus remained
consistent throughout his career, each subsequent album represents
a progression, an improvement upon its predecessor. With the next
year's ``Couldn't Stand the Weather,'' both the title track and
``Cold Shot'' reflect a subtlety that was little in evidence on
``Texas Flood,'' while the expanded edition shows his voracious
appetite for all manner of bluesiness, from the jazzy
sophistication of ``Stang's Swang,'' reminiscent of Kenny Burrell,
to the raw assault of Hound Dog Taylor's ``Give Me Back My Wig'' (a
bonus studio outtake).
</P>
<P>
   Where his emulation of Jimi Hendrix had long played a larger
part in his live performance, the cover of ``Voodoo Chile'' shows
his confidence in inviting such comparison on album. Once fearful
of being dismissed as just another Hendrix imitator, it's as if he
were saying, ``Yes, I can do this. But it isn't all I can do.''
</P>
<P>
   Like Hendrix with the Experience and Clapton with Cream, Double
Trouble had its limitations for Vaughan, who'd spread the
possibilities of the power-trio format pretty thin over the course
of two albums. Thus the recruitment of keyboardist Reese Wynans
during the recording of 1985's ``Soul to Soul'' proved crucial,
allowing Vaughan to pick his spots instead of filling all available
space and giving the music the interplay of another soloist. From
the sweet lyricism of the ``Goin' Home'' instrumental to the
prophetic anthemry of ``Change It,'' the album shows the band
soaring beyond the shuffles and slow blues that had previously
dominated its repertoire. Highlighting the bonus selections is an
extended medley of Hendrix's ``Little Wing''/``Third Stone from the
Sun.''
</P>
<P>
   Following three albums in three years, and the ceaseless grind
of the touring schedule to promote them, ``In Step'' sounds like a
lifeline. It was the first music from Vaughan since he had left the
touring treadmill, entered rehab and kicked drugs, and the
reflectiveness of its material reflects a survivor's maturity.
Songs such as ``Crossfire,'' ``Tightrope'' and ``Wall of Denial''
are plainly about so much more than just playing guitar, while the
album-closing ``Riviera Paradise'' instrumental showed just how
much he had grown as guitarist as well. Where his playing once had
all the subtlety of a fistfight, this sounds like a whispered
prayer. Among the four bonus live tracks from an '89 concert,
``Texas Flood'' brings Vaughan's musical progression full circle.
</P>
<P>
   The albums thus document Vaughan's development from an
instrumental virtuoso into a well-rounded, triple-threat artist, as
powerfully expressive in his songs and vocals as he was on his
guitar. With his final sessions for the ``Family Style'' album that
he recorded with brother Jimmie, he never got around to cutting his
``Electric Ladyland'' or his ``Layla,'' but the progression of his
studio work with Double Trouble suggests that he was headed in that
direction. He seemed to be on the verge of reaching his creative
peak when that 1990 helicopter crash cut his life short.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
