<HEADER>
A3659 &Cx1f; tad-z
r k &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-MCNEELY-COLUMN26-COX     03-25 0757
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-MCNEELY-COLUMN26-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Bullock's iron grip on Texas Senate is not mourned
 &HT;    By Dave McNeely
 &HT;    c.1999 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   AUSTIN, Texas _ Sen. David Sibley purposely kept quiet on his
proposal to name the new Texas State Museum for former Lt. Gov. Bob
Bullock. Sibley (R-Waco) didn't tell anyone the proposal was coming
until he put forward his suggestion on the Senate floor Monday.
</P>
<P>
   Had Bullock known, Sibley said, ``I'm afraid he'd come down here
and whip all of us ...''
</P>
<P>
   ``If you get a drive-by chewing,'' shot back Sen. Rodney Ellis
(D-Houston), ``we're all on your side.''
</P>
<P>
   Until January, Bullock ruled the Senate with an iron hand _ and
legendary temper. Now that he and his occasional
middle-of-the-night phone calls are a thing of the past, senators _
slowly at first _ are beginning to stretch their arms under the
leadership of Republican Rick Perry.
</P>
<P>
   While some say the Senate seems less focused, and a top House
official called it ``rudderless,'' the senators seem happier.
</P>
<P>
   ``The will of the Senate is better reflected when there isn't
just one person there, enforcing it with terror,'' said another
senator. ``Under Bullock, there wasn't anything that wasn't
scripted.''
</P>
<P>
   Bullock was the state's tax-collecting comptroller for 16 years
before his election as lieutenant governor in 1990. Even before he
took his hand off the Bible, he had intimate knowledge of and
enormous control over everything that happened in the Senate.
</P>
<P>
   He also had a temper that could melt a statue _ and many a
senator, lobbyist and occasional journalist. Even two months after
he left the Senate _ he now hangs his hat at Public Strategies
Inc., where he counsels business clients _ almost all of the
senators would talk about his style only after reporters swore a
blood oath that they wouldn't be identified. Bullock, when he
learned the subject of this column, refused _ in characteristically
profane, insulting terms _ to be interviewed.
</P>
<P>
   When he headed the Senate, Bullock was up early and personally
set the Senate's daily order of business. When the Senate conferees
on the appropriations bill met with their House counterparts, the
Senate chairman carried a telephone to the meeting table, so he
could quickly report to Bullock.
</P>
<P>
   Perry delegates more to senators and staff. And he has farmed
out more of the power for controlling the flow of legislation,
senators say.
</P>
<P>
   While Bullock worked through committee chairs, and Perry also
meets with his chairs on a weekly basis, ``more power has evolved
to the other senators,'' said one of them. ``It allows senators to
be senators.''
</P>
<P>
   ``We're seeing some new talent emerge,'' said another. ``I'm
pleasantly surprised. I think we've got the same level of effort,
if not better.''
</P>
<P>
   A former House member who served the past eight years as
agriculture commissioner, but never in the Senate, Perry emulates
the consensus leadership style of House speakers like Pete Laney
rather than Bullock's dictatorial model, one senator said.
</P>
<P>
   Perry on Perry: ``I'm no Bob Bullock. I mean, Governor Bullock
had his style, which was very much hands-on, from the concept of
controlling a great deal of the ebb and flow of the Senate. I'm a
bit more of allowing the Senate and the senators to conduct their
business.''
</P>
<P>
   Bullock was known for calling lobbyists on various sides of an
issue into a room and telling them not to leave until they had come
up with a deal.
</P>
<P>
   ``Perry calls people in and holds their hands,'' one senator
said. ``Bullock was more into breaking hands.''
</P>
<P>
   A lobbyist and former legislator said Bullock's absence is
``infinitely better for the system, because now the dynamics of the
system can work without an oppressive influence.''
</P>
<P>
   Bullock so controlled the Senate that his influence ``repressed
ideas and the system functioning in a spontaneous way.''
</P>
<P>
   ``Bullock did a lot of fine things,'' the lobbyist acknowledged.
``I think they could have been done with a lot less
heavy-handedness. I think the same goals could have been
accomplished with a lot less bodies along the trail.
</P>
<P>
   ``Frankly, I would think that those senators would be enjoying
their emancipation'' _ pursuing their own agendas _ ``and they're
getting to do that without having to stop and ask if they can have
a bathroom break,'' the lobbyist said. Dave McNeely writes about
politics for the American-Statesman. You may contact him at
dmcneely(at)statesman.com.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-03-25-99 1123EST &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> NYT19990325.0069 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-03-25 11:24 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A3660 &Cx1f; tad-z
u i &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-RUSSIA-RECRUIT-$ADV28     03-25 0692
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-RUSSIA-RECRUIT-$ADV28-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    ARMY STORE' HOSTESS CONNECTS WITH YOUNG RECRUITS
 &HT;    With Photos.
 &HT;    With RUSSIA-ARMY-$ADV28; ARMY-BOX-$ADV28.
 &HT;    For Use Sun. March 28 And Thereafter.
 &HT;    Moving in (i) international and (w) Washington categories
 &HT;    By CHARLES W. HOLMES
 &HT;    c.1999 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   MOSCOW _ The Russian army offers dismal pay, wretched living
conditions and a reputation stained by its disastrous experiences
in Chechnya and Afghanistan.
</P>
<P>
   It is a bleak world for army recruiters. Fortunately, Dana
Borisova is on their side.
</P>
<P>
   Blonde and lithesome, Borisova, 22, was hired five years ago to
host a television show called ``Army Store.'' She has gone on to
become a Playboy cover model and wildly popular pinup girl for a
deteriorating army that needs all the morale-boosting it can get.
</P>
<P>
   ``Mention the army and the first thing people used to think
about was a bunch of old generals. Now, they think of Dana,'' said
Alexander Ilyin, the show's producer and co-host.
</P>
<P>
   ``Army Store'' is part MTV, a dash of Saturday Night Live and a
dose of defense-promotional films featuring the gee-whiz machinery
of a modern army -- jet fighters, tanks and helicopter gunships.
</P>
<P>
   But the half-hour belongs to Borisova, in miniskirt and an
abbreviated version of the blue-striped T-shirt worn by Russian
soldiers and sailors.
</P>
<P>
   While they love her in the ranks, the brass is not as charmed.
</P>
<P>
   Last year, the Defense Ministry dropped its financial support
for the show and banned Borisova and her crew from military bases.
But ``Army Store'' continues to survive with private sponsors and
high ratings.
</P>
<P>
   ``Army Store'' began in 1994 as an updated version of a
monotonous Soviet-era military show. That show, ``To Serve the
Soviet Union'' was nicknamed ``Fairy Tale'' by soldiers because of
its distance from reality.
</P>
<P>
   The officers in olive drab who hosted that show, with its boring
lectures and war documentaries, are gone, succeeded by the
fresh-faced Borisova, a 17-year-old university student when she was
hired. She had no TV experience, but became an instant sensation
among servicemen and civilians alike.
</P>
<P>
   Three years later, in February 1997, she posed seminude atop a
tank for the Russian edition of Playboy, and her fame soared.
</P>
<P>
   ``I may be the reason they are watching. But the secret of why
the program has lasted is that we're simply talking about common
problems in a common language that soldiers identify with,'' she
said.
</P>
<P>
   ``Army Store'' offers a rapid-fire 30 minutes of rock-music
videos, skits by a couple of comic regulars doing Gomer Pyle
routines and video of Borisova's base visits, where she chats
sympathetically with eager young conscripts.
</P>
<P>
   Borisova's celebrity has brought marriage proposals and modeling
offers. There also have been negotiations with a Russian
manufacturer to produce a Barbie-like Dana doll.
</P>
<P>
   She also represents the only outward sign that Russia is seeking
to stem the rising rate of draft-dodgers and deserters, the result
of the country's economic woes and chronic problems of hazing and
corruption inside the military. Borisova posed last year for an
Uncle Sam-like poster with the message: ``Your Country Needs You.''
</P>
<P>
   Meantime, the peppery show became even more irreverent, taking
up normally taboo subjects. It featured pictures of lavish country
houses built for generals by the army while soldiers in the ranks
were going unpaid. It also showed young female officers
moonlighting at a strip club to earn extra money.
</P>
<P>
   Unamused, the brass discharged Ilyin, a career officer, when he
balked at giving the generals more control over the show's content.
The Defense Ministry eventually pulled its support for ``Army
Store'' last summer.
</P>
<P>
   Yet the show endures. Base commanders still allow Borisova and
the crew to film, against orders from the top. When contacted, a
Defense Ministry spokesman declined to discuss ``Army Store.''
</P>
<P>
   ``We're their best propaganda tool,'' said Ilyin of the show and
the army, ``but they don't realize it.''
</P>
<P>
   ENDIT
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-03-25-99 1124EST &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> NYT19990325.0070 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-03-25 11:24 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A3661 &Cx1f; tad-z
u w &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-RUSSIA-RECRUIT-$ADV28     03-25 0692
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-RUSSIA-RECRUIT-$ADV28-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    ARMY STORE' HOSTESS CONNECTS WITH YOUNG RECRUITS
 &HT;    With Photos.
 &HT;    With RUSSIA-ARMY-$ADV28; ARMY-BOX-$ADV28.
 &HT;    For Use Sun. March 28 And Thereafter.
 &HT;    Moving in (i) international and (w) Washington categories
 &HT;    By CHARLES W. HOLMES
 &HT;    c.1999 Cox News Service
