</P>
<P>
   Meantime, the peppery show became even more irreverent, taking
up normally taboo subjects. It featured pictures of lavish country
houses built for generals by the army while soldiers in the ranks
were going unpaid. It also showed young female officers
moonlighting at a strip club to earn extra money.
</P>
<P>
   Unamused, the brass discharged Ilyin, a career officer, when he
balked at giving the generals more control over the show's content.
The Defense Ministry eventually pulled its support for ``Army
Store'' last summer.
</P>
<P>
   Yet the show endures. Base commanders still allow Borisova and
the crew to film, against orders from the top. When contacted, a
Defense Ministry spokesman declined to discuss ``Army Store.''
</P>
<P>
   ``We're their best propaganda tool,'' said Ilyin of the show and
the army, ``but they don't realize it.''
</P>
<P>
   ENDIT
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
