A3662 &Cx1f; tad-z
r s &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-BBN-BRAVES-AJONES26-C     03-25 0483
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BBN-BRAVES-AJONES26-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    A. Jones feels secure, mature
 &HT;    By Carroll Rogers
 &HT;    c.1999 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   LAKE BUENA VISTA, Fla. _ When Andruw Jones was hitting around
.200 last spring, there was a collective groan at Braves camp.
</P>
<P>
   Jones, following the success of Marquis Grissom and Kenny Lofton
in previous years, was getting a long look at the leadoff spot, so
the scrutiny was severe. And the experiment went nowhere.
</P>
<P>
   So Jones begins this spring 2-for-22, and it's no big concern
for the Braves. Last year's concerns have been replaced by the
knowledge that slow starts don't necessarily equal slow finishes.
</P>
<P>
   Jones, 21, proved after last year's horrendous start that he
could hit 31 home runs in the No. 8 hole. He also hit .271, had 90
RBIs and stole 27 bases to became the youngest 25-25 player in
major-league history.
</P>
<P>
   The Braves have found other leadoff hitters _ most recently Otis
Nixon _ and a new-found confidence in Jones, who has responded.
</P>
<P>
   ``I feel really more comfortable this year than last year,
because a lot of people were talking about leadoff hitter and this
and that,'' said Jones, who probably will bat seventh this season.
``All that just kind of messed me up. This year, I really don't
think about it. I know I'm making the team; I know the center-field
job is mine; I've just got to do the job and get myself mentally
and physically prepared for the season.''
</P>
<P>
   Jones has improved recently, getting seven hits in his past 15
at-bats and improving his average from .091 to .243.
</P>
<P>
   ``I feel good,'' Jones said. ``I feel like I have my swing
right. I'm seeing the ball pretty good. Hopefully, I'll keep doing
that until the season starts.''
</P>
<P>
   Jones said he came into camp in better shape _ he's 13 pounds
lighter _ and smarter.
</P>
<P>
   ``I think I've got better instincts,'' Jones said. ``I got more
mature with what's going on around the baseball field and in the
clubhouse. And I think I know the league just a little bit
better.''
</P>
<P>
   And he learned a good bit about himself, facing the first real
adversity of his career. It might have been an unfair amount of
pressure, but he has learned to handle it.
</P>
<P>
   ``From the point that my season was so bad, to get a good
season, I think that made me really strong mentally,'' Jones said.
``I just kept working hard and thinking positive. I know what my
ability is. I just had to put it in my mind. Just do it and don't
think about it much.''
</P>
<P>
   Hitting coach Don Baylor said Jones still has the tendency to
try to crush fastballs and chase breaking balls, but they're
working on it.
</P>
<P>
   ``He's going to figure it out,'' Baylor said. ``I'm going to
help him figure it out _ how good he can really be. He has a very,
very bright future, as far as being one of those rare young players
that come along.''
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
