<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-03-25 11:29 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A3663 &Cx1f; tad-z
r e &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-BLACKCROWES26-COX     03-25 0571
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BLACKCROWES26-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    They're back to `Black': Crowes return to rock
 &HT;    By Charles Passy
 &HT;    c. 1999 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   WEST PALM BEACH, Fla. _ In 1997, the Black Crowes were hitting
rock's bottom.
</P>
<P>
   The Atlanta group's psychedelic-flavored album, ``Three Snakes
and One Charm,'' had garnered some decent reviews but confounded
much of the hard-rock audience that constituted the band's core
following. A stint on the Grateful Dead-inspired Furthur tour
placed the Crowes more out of their element: Other than the Dead,
what outfit could compete against all that tie-dye?
</P>
<P>
   ``That wasn't about the music, and we were always about the
music,'' says Crowes lead singer Chris Robinson. ``At the end of
the day, we're a rock band, and we didn't fit in.''
</P>
<P>
   These days, Crowes' fans can rest assured: The boys are back in
their element _ and back in town.
</P>
<P>
   With their latest _ and fifth _ release, ``By Your Side,'' the
Crowes return to their glory days as what Melody Maker magazine
dubbed ``the most rock 'n' roll rock 'n' roll band in the world.''
</P>
<P>
   ``By Your Side'' was made in collaboration with Aerosmith
producer Kevin Shirley (Nine Lives), and it's easy to see the
connection: Both groups favor a raunchy, classic-rock sound. In the
Crowes' case, they spice it to a further degree with a gospel
influence, which is most prominent on ``Go Tell the Congregation,''
arguably the album's best cut. Other songs include ``Horse Head,''
a pull-no-punches look at heroin addiction, and ``Go Faster,'' a
rev-it-up rocker.
</P>
<P>
   ``This album is up compared to `Three Snakes,''' admits
Robinson. As for the raw feel of the recorded sound _ at times,
you'd swear it was a live album _ the singer credits that to
Shirley. ``We just wanted to strip it down and he said, `Cool.' He
came in the first day and said, `We're going to have fun.'''
</P>
<P>
   The band also got a boost from some new members, most notably
bassist Sven Pipien, who stepped in for Johnny Colt. (Also missing
in action is guitarist Marc Ford: ``We couldn't depend on him,''
says a nonplussed Robinson.)
</P>
<P>
   But much of the energy of ``By Your Side'' comes from the same
source it always has since the Crowes' inception in 1990, namely
the love-hate relationship between Chris and his brother, Rich, the
band's lead guitarist.
</P>
<P>
   ``This is my stock answer,'' says Chris when the subject
inevitably arises. ``I know how talented he is. I love him with
everything in my body. I just don't like him all the time. That's
something about family.''
</P>
<P>
   Another thing Robinson doesn't like is the majority of today's
bands. He has little use for what's left of the grunge or
alternative movement: ``There's no dimension in that. It's just
heavy metal without the big hair.'' Nor does he care for groups
that head in a pop direction, although he admits to being good
friends with Hootie and the Blowfish's Darius Rucker and his
bandmates: ``They're super nice guys but our music is more on the
other side of the tracks.''
</P>
<P>
   Most of all, Robinson hates trend-watchers. After surviving a
decade in rock, he's convinced it takes true talent to make it.
Those who want to keep on latching to the next big thing need not
apply.
</P>
<P>
   ``You might sell a couple of million records, but you're not
going to have a career,'' he says. ``The next big thing is usually
washing cars.''
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
