layout will be available Tuesday by 2 p.m. EST)
</P>
<P>
   GETAWAY-FESTIVALS _ Southern happenings. (Thrasher, Atlanta
Journal-Constitution) MOVED.
</P>
<P>
   MILLENNIUM-CRUISE _ WEST PALM BEACH, Fla. _ A cruise to seven
continents, 27 countries, 34 ports. Sheila Duthie of Delray Beach,
Fla. is going. Her husband, Tony, a retired engineer for Siemens,
is going. Hellen and Donald Nicol of North Palm Beach are going.
Unlike the Duthies, whose longest cruise has been one week, the
Nicols have been on six round-the-world cruises. And 60, and
counting, other people from Palm Beach County are going, too.
They'll leave Athens, Greece, Nov. 20, 1999, on the small Ocean
Explorer I and return to Athens March 25, 2000. Along the way, they
will celebrate the millennium in Santiago, Chile. (Blackerby, Palm
Beach Post). MOVED TUESDAY.
</P>
<P>
   FASHION
</P>
<P>
   HIGH-FASHION _ France Goldman of Boca is reportedly, and
suddenly, the world's single largest buyer of couture (where one
dress can cost $30,000). We visit her home, have her model, talk
about the statue of her wearing her first couture dress. (Anna,
Palm Beach Post). 30. MOVED.
</P>
<P>
   WITH
</P>
<P>
   LOW-FASHION - Apfel, of Palm Beach, is the opposite. She has
been quietly collecting couture as art since the 1950s, and the
director of MOMA's Costume Institute is dying to get into her
apartment. (Anna, Palm Beach Post). 20. MOVED.
</P>
<P>
   SPRING-DRESSES _ WACO, Texas _ Choices, choices, choices. A
cornucopia of colors and clothing combinations is cropping up this
spring, delighting fashion finders with new options and fresh looks
for work and play. (Mays, Waco Tribune-Herald) MOVED MONDAY.
</P>
<P>
   FASHION-MCFADDEN _ WEST PALM BEACH, Fla. _ Some people you just
can't see curling up with a bowl of Froot Loops. Mary McFadden is
one of them. McFadden is a debutante, a Sufi dervish, a former Palm
Beacher, a world traveler, a multiple divorcee, a collector of
Buddhist art, a size 2, a New York ``living landmark,'' a speaker
of French and a little Zulu, a two-hour-a-day tennis player and,
incredibly, a pitchman on the QVC shopping network. (She also
designs clothes.) (Anna, Palm Beach Post). MOVED TUESDAY.
</P>
<P>
   ENTERTAINMENT/ARTS
</P>
<P>
   COXNET ENTERTAIN _ 0325 _ One of the most important figures in
Southern folk art, Lonnie Holley started his career 20 years ago by
carving the soft sandstone that steel mills use as molds. He's
known a world of trouble in his 49 years. He has been beaten, shot,
jailed. He has been abandoned, cheated, stolen from. He has watched
as his home of 18 years _ along with much of the art and debris he
carefully placed around it _ was bulldozed into a trench to make
way for an airport expansion. But nothing in a life of Job-like
tribulations has prepared him for the misfortunes of the past few
months. (Auchmutey, Atlanta Journal-Constitution) Art includes
4-column color photo of Lonnie Holley, a 1-column color photo of
artist standing by a sandstone art and a 1-column photo of a Holley
painting.
</P>
<P>
   WITH: PHANTOM MENACE COUNTDOWN _ A 2 column graphic ``Countdown
to `Star Wars''' outlining the number of days remaining until ``The
Phantom Menace'' opens. (Staff, Cox News Service)
</P>
<P>
   WITH: VIDEO REVIEWS _ In ``Pleasantville,'' two '90s kids are
zapped into a '50s sitcom and slowly bring sex, color and rock 'n'
roll to the black-and-white world. The movie's lustrous mix of
monochrome and color is a marvel of digital wizardry. (Staff,
Atlanta Journal-Constitution) With 2 column color studio photograph
from the film.
</P>
<P>
   WITH: CD REVIEWS - Not an easy concept to wrangle, Cassandra
Wilson's latest project is at once seductive and a little
frustrating. The vocalist finds a kindred soul in Miles Davis: the
iconographic, iconoclastic jazz trumpeter who was among American
music's great conceptualists, and a master of soulful cool who knew
the gestural power of a single, sustained note. (Staff, Atlanta
Journal-Constitution)
</P>
<P>
   (EDS: This is the CoxNet ENTERTAIN page for the current week.
This layout is available at 2 pm EST.)
</P>
<P>
   BOOKS
</P>
<P>
   COXNET _ BOOKS 0330: Maureen Orth, best-known for her work in
Vanity Fair, has written an exceptionally good account of suspected
serial killer Andrew Cunanan's spree in 1997, and odds are that
very few people will notice _ or be able to recall just who Andrew
Cunanan even was: a monster, that's who. (Guinn, N.Y. Times News
Service) Art includes 18 pica color photo of designer Gianni
Versace and a 2-column B&AMP;W photo of Andrew Cunanan taken from his
high school yearbook. Also half-column color art of book cover.
</P>
<P>
   WITH: REVIEW _ Which is the real Bill Gates? Is it the author
who insists, in his new book, ``Business (AT) the Speed of
Thought,'' that all interoffice communications should flow ``over
e-mail so workers can act on news with reflex-like speed'' or is it
the witness who testified in the government's antitrust case
against his company that he could not remember dozens of e-mail
messages he wrote or received in recent years, (Brinkley, N.Y.
Times News Service) Art includes 2-column color photo of Gates
testifying at a Congressional hearing and a 6 pica color photo of
book jacket.
</P>
<P>
   WITH: REVIEW _ Just how many lives did Janis Joplin lead? Joplin
has been variously cast as tragic bluesmama, lesbian lover, loving
sister, junkie maneater. Now here comes Alice Echols with Janis
Joplin, feminist icon. (McLeese, Austin American-Statesman.) Art
includes 6 pica color photo of book jacket.
</P>
<P>
   WITH: REVIEW _ New readers from Random House and Grove Press
offer selected chapters, routines, short stories and passages from
