<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-03-25 11:48 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A3681 &Cx1f; tad-z
r e &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-EDTV-REVIEW-COX     03-25 0638
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-EDTV-REVIEW-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    You can tune out `EDtv,' and rent `Truman Show' instead
 &HT;    By Hap Erstein
 &HT;    c. 1999 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   WEST PALM BEACH, Fla. _ If you were asked to turn your life into
a 24-hour-a-day media event, to star in a continuous broadcast of
your every action, chances are you'd be smart enough to decline. If
so, you'd be way ahead of Ed Pekurny, the poor schmo who learns too
late in Ron Howard's ``EDtv'' that celebrity has its drawbacks.
</P>
<P>
   The more important question: If you were offered a chance to see
a less interesting, slightly altered replica of ``The Truman
Show,'' would you care enough to bother?
</P>
<P>
   No, you're right, reviewing movies by comparison is not fair,
but neither is life. If there were no ``Truman Show,'' then
``Edtv'' could be greeted as a pleasant enough, though overly
obvious, entertainment. Instead, its entire premise seems
unoriginal and stale. And you diehard optimists who hope ``EDtv''
will take the cameras-in-your-face dilemma to new, intriguing
levels are going to be disappointed.
</P>
<P>
   The key difference between the two movies, of course, is that Ed
(Matthew McConaughey), a 31-year-old video store clerk, actually
volunteers for this exercise in national voyeurism. It's a ratings
stunt dreamed up by an insecure cable programmer (Ellen DeGeneres)
and ridiculed by the snide top executive (Rob Reiner), until the
show becomes a hit.
</P>
<P>
   Suddenly, the station starts dangling renewal bonuses in front
of Ed to get him to continue the electronic abuse. And the suits
begin fiddling with Ed's life, trying to shape and alter it to make
better television. When a newspaper poll finds the public doesn't
approve of Ed's whiny girlfriend Shari (Jenna Elfman), she gets
dumped and a slinky British actress with her own agenda (Elizabeth
Hurley) takes her place.
</P>
<P>
   Like many studio movies, though, ``Edtv'' is all set-up, little
follow-through. Once the gimmick gets established, the screenplay
by Lowell Ganz and Babaloo Mandel _ longtime collaborators of
Howard's _ has nowhere to go. The movie cuts away from Ed
occasionally to show groups of fans glued to the tube, following
his every move like a reality soap opera. And when he's had enough,
Ed has to find a way to break his contract with the station. That's
it, folks.
</P>
<P>
   Along the way, we meet Ed's family and see how they cope with
peripheral fame. Someone had the clever idea to cast Woody
Harrelson as Ed's conniving brother, drawing on a physical
resemblance that is awfully persuasive. But brother Ray turns out
to be a one-joke liability. The same goes for Ed's mother (Sally
Kirkland) and a wheelchair-bound stepfather (Martin Landau), whose
lives are disrupted by the return of Ed's biological father (Dennis
Hopper).
</P>
<P>
   Another squandered angle concerns the way Ed's show is packaged
and sold. A strip at the bottom of the television screen features a
parade of sponsors, but only occasionally do they tie in with
events in the program to create a joke. Mostly, they seem like a
new approach to product placements _ actual ads within feature
films. Certainly that's the case with Pepsi, which gets the most
blatant mentions.
</P>
<P>
   The cast is fine, but there are no real standouts and
McConaughey's star power remains questionable. When you find
yourself looking forward to seeing more media personality cameos
instead of the main character, that's not a good sign.
</P>
<P>
   ``The Truman Show,'' by the way, is now available on video.
</P>
<P>
   ``EDtv''
</P>
<P>
   1 1/2 stars
</P>
<P>
   Rated PG-13: Language, non-graphic sexual situation
</P>
<P>
   Running time: 2 hours., 2 minutes.
</P>
<P>
   The verdict: A less interesting, sitcom-deep satire built around
a voluntary ``Truman Show'' which grows tiresome for the subject
and the audience.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
