<HEADLINE>
EDITORS:
</HEADLINE>
  
 Thursday, March 25, 1999      The Hearst News Service will file the following stories for
Friday and Sunday. If you have questions, please call Tim Spence at
202-298-6920.  
    (Slugline includes the ``HNS'' tag.)
    NATIONAL NEWS (``a'' category)
<TEXT>
<P>
   CALIF-MISSING (Mi-Wuk Village, Calif.) _ An intense sweep by
police searching for suspects in the murder of a Eureka, Calif.,
woman and possibly one of two teenagers traveling with her have not
yielded any arrests, but it has had some beneficial side effects.
Authorities have recovered about 15 stolen cars, arrested a handful
of parolees and probation violators and may have caused other
criminals to lay low or leave town. By JIM HERRON ZAMORA and ERIC
BRAZIL.
</P>
<P>
   HERBICIDE-HUMANS (San Francisco) _ Herbicide sprayed along state
roadsides may be threatening public health and the environment,
according to an environmental group that tracks chemical use around
the state. By TYCHE HENDRICKS.
</P>
<P>
   CATHOLIC-PROTEST (San Francisco) _ Trhough 20 years of street
theater and social activism, the Sisters of Perpetual Indulgence
have never been the type to duck controversy. The group of 30 gays,
lesbians, bisexuals, straights and transgender people who dress up
as nuns _ assuming names like Sister Helen A. Handbasket and Sister
Reyna Terror _ has raised the ire of Catholic Church officials with
its plans to hold a 20th anniversary party on Castro Street on
Easter Sunday. By The San Francisco Examiner.
</P>
<P>
   ENTERTAINMENT (``e'' category)
</P>
<P>
   COMPUTER-GAMES (San Francisco) _ ``European Air War'' is typical
of a growing number of World War II fighter computer flight
simulators that have been gathering more shelf space at software
stores and finding their way onto the computers of an audience that
normally shuns computer gaming. By MATT BEER.
</P>
<P>
   TV-REVIEW-MUTINY (Undated) _ NBC tells the story Sunday night of
the mutiny of black American sailors in World War II. The sailors
balked at their dangerous job of loading ammunitions ships after
320 men were killed and 390 injured on the night of July 17, 1944,
when a transport ship anchored and being loaded at the Port Chicago
Munitions Base just outside of San Francisco exploded. By MARK
McGUIRE. (For release Sunday, March 28.)
</P>
<P>
   FOOD (``d'' category)
</P>
<P>
   MAPLE-SYRUP (Albany, N.Y.) _ Maple syrup is the perfect topping
for pancakes and waffles. But don't limit maple syrup to breakfast
topping. Be creative and regard it as a substitute for sugar. Maple
syrup is also well suited for marinades, and because of its
viscosity, a half-cup goes a long way. By DOUG BLACKBURN.
</P>
<P>
   COMMENTARY (``k'' category)
</P>
<P>
   MORSE-COLUMN (San Francisco) _ Stand at a Muni station with
Clint Reilly for two hours and you learn some things: First, it's
cold out there. Reilly has been accused of having a super-heated
ego, but most other parts of him were freezing at the entrance to
Castro station early Wednesday. This guy is serious about running
for mayor. He's burning calories as well as his own money. By ROB
MORSE.
</P>
<P>
   LYNCH-COLUMN (Albany, N.Y.) _ The messed-up case of two police
officers accused of roughing up a young black man is all but over.
It has been the scummiest episode I've seen played out in more than
three decades of watching the criminal system operate. By DAN
LYNCH.
</P>
<P>
   CAMPAIGN-FINANCE (Albany, N.Y.) _ For columnist and commentator
George Will, democracy is a great system for those who can afford
to buy it with political soft money _ those huge unregulated
contributions from corporations, labor unions and wealthy
individuals that are at the heart of the scandals during the last
presidential campaign. By ANN McBRIDE and DONALD SIMON.
</P>
<P>
   PARTY-LOYALTY (Santa Maria, Calif.) _ What separates the
Republicans and Democrats is loyalty. To a Republican, the party is
merely an instrument that works for him about half the time. A
Democrat, on the other hand, sees his party as something of a
religion and the party's leader as practically infallible. By
DONALD G. SMITH.
</P>
