<HEADER>
A3730 &Cx1f; ttx-z
r e &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-FILM-20DATES-TEX     03-25 0461
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-FILM-20DATES-TEX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
A FUNNY MOCKUMENTARY ON THE MISERY OF DATING
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By ROBERT PHILPOT 
c.1999 Fort Worth Star-Telegram 
<TEXT>
<P>
   Myles Berkowitz's docucomedy ``20 Dates'' has already opened in
several markets, so it's mere coincidence that it hits Fort
Worth-Dallas on the same weekend as ``EDtv.'' But the parallels are
there: Both movies have a normal schmo dealing with his love life
on camera, in front of scores of strangers.
</P>
<P>
   Two differences, though: ``20 Dates'' is nonfiction, and
Berkowitz, unlike the my-life's-a-TV-show Ed in ``EDtv,'' has
trained his camera upon himself.
</P>
<P>
   Berkowitz explains this blatant bit of self-involvement:
Recently divorced and struggling to break into movies, he decided
to film his quest for love, killing two birds with one stone.
</P>
<P>
   Great idea, right? Well, to a point. If you're a veteran of the
dating scene, recall all your misfires and disasters, all those
times that you knew from the first few lines of conversation that
the person across the table wasn't for you. Now imagine filming all
that. Unless you're Berkowitz, the correct response to this is
``ugh.''
</P>
<P>
   Hence, your response to ``20 Dates'' depends on how much you can
take of Berkowitz's self-absorption. At least he has a sense of
humor about it; he includes interviews with many friends who
correctly assess him as a pushy, annoying, sexist pig. But a little
of him goes a long way, and even at a brief 88 minutes, ``20
Dates'' is about 20 minutes too long.
</P>
<P>
   Berkowitz takes side trips to discuss financing with his vulgar,
foul-mouthed producer (we never see the producer, leading to the
suspicion that his character is largely fictionalized), and to
listen to film historian Robert McKee's pompous discourses about
love and movies. But mostly, ``20 Dates'' is all about Berkowitz,
and the women he dates, some of whom are good sports about being
filmed, some of whom react with unusual although not totally
unexpected violence.
</P>
<P>
   If this sounds audacious, realize that however amusing it is, it
amounts to a ``Seinfeld'' episode that features nothing but Jerry.
And Woody Allen explored the dating scene to much more amusing
effect nearly 30 years ago in ``Play It Again, Sam.'' If you're in
the right mood, though, ``20 Dates'' could still work as a ``date''
movie _ but only if you've already established a relationship with
your companion.
</P>
<P>
   _
</P>
<P>
   Film: ``20 Dates''
</P>
<P>
   Rating: 3 on a scale of 5
</P>
<P>
   Director: Myles Berkowitz
</P>
<P>
   Featuring: Myles Berkowitz
</P>
<P>
   Length: 88 minutes
</P>
<P>
   Rated: R _ strong language and frankly sexual dialogue
</P>
<P>
   _
</P>
<P>
   (Robert Philpot is film critic for the Fort Worth Star-Telegram.
Visit the Star-Telegram's online services on the World Wide Web:
www.star-telegram.com) nn
</P>
</TEXT>
