<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-FILM-THEHARMONISTS-TEX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
`THE HARMONISTS' FALLS A BIT FLAT
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By ELVIS MITCHELL 
c.1999 Fort Worth Star-Telegram 
<TEXT>
<P>
   ``The Harmonists,'' a period piece about a German singing group,
has a classical directing style and a pictorial beauty _ each scene
has a slight sepia burnish, as if glazed in honey - that
contradicts its subject.
</P>
<P>
   Harry Frommermann (Ulrich Noethen), who has the wide, high
forehead of Roberto Benigni, but hurting eyes that take in
everything, is a struggling performer. A devotee of American
popular singing groups, specifically the jaunty Revellers _ he
spends hours at the local record store, listening to the sounds and
romancing long-necked clerk Erna _ he decides to form his own
version of such a group.
</P>
<P>
   When Bob (Ben Becker) reads about Harry's auditions, he pops
right over, still wearing the monk's costume he was wearing during
a rehearsal. Pushing to the front of the line past his would-be
competitors, he declares, ``I have to administer last rites.''
</P>
<P>
   Director Joseph Vilsmaier's heavy, portentous staging of ``The
Harmonists'' almost does that anyway. Though the storytelling is
simple, the picture itself is weighty and slow _ like an opera
singer forcing a light pop style.
</P>
<P>
   Harry and Bob find their four fellow group members, but their
success, starting almost immediately after their first job in 1927,
butts up against the rise of the Nazi movement. And because the
group includes three Jews, they learn that the Reich will not allow
them to continue.
</P>
<P>
   Harry is all too aware of the ripening anti-Semitism, while the
ambitious and hardheaded Bob _ who's also competing with Harry for
Erna's hand _ refuses to acknowledge what's going on around them.
</P>
<P>
   Harry, with his pained face, doesn't look like the kind of guy
who goes for the quick, improvisatory feel of jazz. He's not
particularly daring _ at one point, when brownshirts trash the
record store, Harry stands watching while Bob crashes through the
window to try to stop the carnage.
</P>
<P>
   It might make a little more sense if Harry were turned on when
he hears music, or if he got some kind of a jolt out of performing.
But he seems to have been cast because of his sufferer's face. Both
``The Harmonists'' and its protagonist lack the the audacity, the
bone-deep hunger to challenge, that would really affect us. (It
doesn't help that the movie also doesn't provide the anything-goes
decadence of Weimar Republic Berlin, in which it's set.)
</P>
<P>
   ``The Harmonists'' has an interesting subject _ how the power of
popular art won't set you free _ though we get a lot of scenes with
allegorical weight. In the end, it's a movie with its feet planted
too firmly on the ground.
</P>
<P>
   _
</P>
<P>
   Film: ``The Harmonists''
</P>
<P>
   Rating: 3 on a scale of 5
</P>
<P>
   Director: Joseph Vilsmaier
</P>
<P>
   Featuring: Ulrich Noethen, Ben Becker
</P>
<P>
   Length: 115 minutes
</P>
<P>
   Rated: R
</P>
<P>
   _
</P>
<P>
   (Elvis Mitchell is film critic for the Fort Worth Star-Telegram.
Visit the Star-Telegram's online services on the World Wide Web:
www.star-telegram.com) nn
</P>
</TEXT>
