<HEADER>
A3770 &Cx1f; ttx-z
r e &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-FILM-EDTV-TEX     03-25 0674
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-FILM-EDTV-TEX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
OPIE'S OPUS IS A LOT LIKE OPIUM
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By ELVIS MITCHELL 
c.1999 Fort Worth Star-Telegram 
<TEXT>
<P>
   ``EDtv'' director Ron Howard has gone out of his way to tell
interviewers that his movie, about a man who finds himself the
center of the world when his life is televised almost 24/7 by a
documentary cable outlet, is nothing like last year's ``The Truman
Show.''
</P>
<P>
   He aptly described ``Truman'' as being like a ``Twilight Zone''
episode, which means Howard is out to create a movie for those who
thought ``Truman'' was too intellectual. And there must be four or
five of them out there. ``EDtv'' exults in its superficiality, as
any movie in its right mind starring Matthew McConaughey would.
</P>
<P>
   McConaughey slides through on his smoky Texas charm, obviously
relieved that he doesn't have to carry the weight of saving the
world. Or, for that matter, to act like he graduated from college.
He's Ed, an amiably aimless video-store clerk who has no
inhibitions about recommending ``Smokey and the Bandit'' - ``the
good Burt (Reynolds),'' as he puts it. And then shooing customers
away from the store as unworthy when they're reluctant to follow
his suggestion.
</P>
<P>
   His cocky grin is trashily beatific, so even his raunchy
behavior seems honest. McConaughey's flyweight appeal _ he's
essentially the luckiest frat boy who ever staggered away from a
kegger _ is perfectly suited to comedy. Even one as shaggy and
earnest as ``EDtv,'' in which he's forced to learn a valuable
lesson about the perils of media.
</P>
<P>
   McConaughey auditions for the slot as the star of the
live-as-it-happens documentary along with his brother, Ray (Woody
Harrelson), a half-lazy schemer with a head full of get-rich-quick
plans. The shooting immediately catches Ed in a bad position,
starting with capturing him in early morning scratch in an area
best suited for cable TV.
</P>
<P>
   When it turns out Ed is falling in love with Shari (Jenna
Elfman), the girlfriend of his undeserving brother, the camera
films that, too. ``EDtv'' gets off a few funny lines and bits, but
it's way too long and simple-minded.
</P>
<P>
   You get the point early on, despite an engaging turn from Martin
Landau as Ed's stepfather. (There's a mildly funny visual motif,
too _ in a movie about television, most of the supporting roles are
filled by people we've seen on TV: Rob Reiner, Donny Most, Ellen
DeGeneres, Elfman, Harrelson, etc. And Harry Shearer _ who appeared
in ``Truman'' and co-wrote ``Real Life,'' Albert Brooks' comedy
about a documentary crew shooting ordinary people _ shows up with a
panel of pundits assessing Ed's plight.)
</P>
<P>
   Once Ed is legally trapped in the show, which even its creator,
desperate network executive Cynthia Topping (DeGeneres) feels
guilty about, you'll find yourself getting a headache from trying
to check your watch in the dark. But you also know he'll pull
through, because in Ron Howard's world, the nice guy always
triumphs.
</P>
<P>
   Howard, who probably understands as well as anyone the problems
of living one's life in the public eye, brings his brand of sticky,
predictable problem-solving to ``EDtv.'' Ironically, a movie about
the dangers of TV made by a man who was raised as a product of TV
suffers from the conservatism of TV thinking.
</P>
<P>
   No one ever really suffers in Howard's movies, and after
``Apollo 13,'' the first movie he ever made that was all about
adults, it's sad that he's gone back to two-ply comedies about
losers. McConaughey's ease and ability to make fun of his own
vanity add a couple of laughs. But ``EDtv'' might as well be a TV
show _ the kind that's pretested and doesn't want to hurt anyone.
</P>
<P>
   _
</P>
<P>
   Film: ``EDtv''
</P>
<P>
   Rating: 2 on a scale of 5
</P>
<P>
   Director: Ron Howard
</P>
<P>
   Featuring: Matthew McConaughey, Jenna Elfman, Woody Harrelson
</P>
<P>
   Length: 122 minutes
</P>
<P>
   Rated: PG-13 _ adult language and situations
</P>
<P>
   _
</P>
<P>
   (Elvis Mitchell is film critic for the Fort Worth Star-Telegram.
Visit the Star-Telegram's online services on the World Wide Web:
www.star-telegram.com) nn
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
