<SLUG> BC-FILM-DOUGS1STMOVIE-TEX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
THROW THIS ONE BACK INTO THE SWAMP
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By TODD CAMP 
c.1999 Fort Worth Star-Telegram 
<TEXT>
<P>
   Well, there aren't any rampaging 3-D dinosaurs in ``Doug's 1st
Movie,'' but there is a silly-looking, gap-toothed, reptilian swamp
monster.
</P>
<P>
   It's a pity, really. Some man-eating carnosaurs might have been
just the ticket to salvage this big-screen treatment of the popular
Nickelodeon kid cartoon, particularly if they devoured most, if not
all, of the main characters.
</P>
<P>
   Almost painfully unwatchable for adults, this sloppily animated
outing features Doug and the gang trying to keep a lid on their
discovery of a creature lurking in the nearby bog.
</P>
<P>
   Whereas Nickelodeon's last effort (''The Rugrats'') at least
attempted to boost the quality of the animation, ``Doug'' looks to
have been a long episode of the TV series projected on the big
screen. It even has a number of musical crescendos and blackouts
that might send some youngsters strolling to the bathroom thinking
there's a commercial coming.
</P>
<P>
   Disney's acquisition of the Nick library probably seemed like a
slam dunk at the time, and considering the success of ``Rugrats,''
it was. But poor-quality cartoon products like this one only suffer
by comparison to the studio's feature work _ the trailers for
``Tarzan'' and ``Inspector Gadget'' were more entertaining than all
of the main feature.
</P>
<P>
   And don't be sucked in by the promise of a new Donald Duck short
feature, ``Donald's Dynamite `Opera Box.''' Donald's attempts to
extinguish a bomb inexplicably found in Daisy's purse is a
ridiculously unworthy return for the classic quacker.
</P>
<P>
   _
</P>
<P>
   Film: ``Doug's 1st Movie''
</P>
<P>
   Rating: 1 1/2 on a scale of 5
</P>
<P>
   Director: Maurice Joyce
</P>
<P>
   Featuring: Voices of Thomas McHugh, Fred Newman
</P>
<P>
   Length: 77 minutes
</P>
<P>
   Rated: G _ suitable for all audiences, though parents have been
warned
</P>
<P>
   _
</P>
<P>
   (Todd Camp is film critic for the Fort Worth Star-Telegram.
Visit the Star-Telegram's online services on the World Wide Web:
www.star-telegram.com) nn
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-03-25-99 1259EST &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> NYT19990325.0101 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-03-25 12:59 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A3772 &Cx1f; ttx-z
r e &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-FILM-TINSELTOWN-TEX     03-25 0540
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-FILM-TINSELTOWN-TEX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
AN INSIDE JOKE NOT WORTH GETTING
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By ROBERT PHILPOT 
c.1999 Fort Worth Star-Telegram 
<TEXT>
<P>
   In the press notes for ``Tinseltown,'' there's a synopsis that
starts off like this: ``A black comedy that illustrates the lengths
to which no-talent people will go in order to make a movie.''
</P>
<P>
   Oh, don't give us an opening line like that. Whatever you say
can and will be used against you, especially if your movie is a
Hollywood satire that's more self-indulgent and pretentious than
the movies it seeks to lampoon.
</P>
<P>
   ``Tinseltown,'' the directorial debut of screenwriter Tony
Spiridakis (''Queens Logic''), plays like a sour-grapes screed from
someone who's frustrated that he can't get his ``good'' movies made
even though Hollywood keeps churning out junk.
</P>
<P>
   This might be OK if the movie weren't junk itself _ if it were
dark enough, or comical enough, or if its red herrings made much
sense. Arye Gross and Tom Wood play Max and Tiger, aspiring
screenwriters so down at their heels that they live in a storage
shed (the movie is adapted from a stage play, ``Self Storage'').
While looking for shelter, they discover Cliff, an actor who may or
may not be a serial killer who injects his victims with window
cleaner, dresses them like the cast of ``Gilligan's Island'' and
suffocates them with plastic bags. Ron Perlman, with his lantern
jaw and simian teeth, doesn't just chew the scenery in this role _
he bites it in half.
</P>
<P>
   Somehow, Max and Tiger convince a shady _ and homeless _
producer (''Bound's'' Joe Pantoliano, looking like he's auditioning
to play Trotsky) that they can turn Cliff's story into a movie,
with Cliff's collaboration. The producer, begging for ``fresh''
stories, apparently hasn't seen the past 10 years' worth of
serial-killer movies, and agrees. Along the way, a USC film student
(Kristy Swanson, moving into Elisabeth Shue ``I'm cute, but I can
be edgy'' territory) signs on as a director.
</P>
<P>
   One of the complaints frequently lobbed at critics, especially
when we pan mainstream films, is that we forget that many people go
to the movies simply to relax and be entertained. ``Tinseltown,''
hardly a mainstream film, is an example of a movie that forgets
that; moreover, it forgets that there are people in the audience
who don't live in Hollywood or make movies, and its anemic satire
doesn't make up for its overall air of self-pity.
</P>
<P>
   In its brief running time, it pulls the rug out from under the
audience many times, but it doesn't play fair in doing so,
disregarding common sense to give us plot twists that shouldn't
happen. Pseudo-cutting edge, deceiving itself about its
courageousness, it's a movie made by people who make low-budget
movies for people who make low-budget movies. Unless you count
yourself among that number, skip it.
</P>
<P>
   _
</P>
<P>
   Film: ``Tinseltown''
</P>
<P>
   Rating: 1 1/2 on a scale of 5
</P>
<P>
   Director: Tony Spiridakis
</P>
<P>
   Featuring: Arye Gross, Joe Pantoliano
</P>
<P>
   Length: 84 minutes
</P>
<P>
   Rated: Not rated _ an R equivalent for strong language and
violence
</P>
<P>
   _
</P>
<P>
   (Robert Philpot is film critic for the Fort Worth Star-Telegram.
Visit the Star-Telegram's online services on the World Wide Web:
www.star-telegram.com) nn
