<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-FILM-THEMODSQUAD-TEX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
THREE YOUNG, HIP COPS ... YEAH, YEAH, WE'VE SEEN IT ALL BEFORE,
ONLY BETTER
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By TODD CAMP 
c.1999 Fort Worth Star-Telegram 
<TEXT>
<P>
   You know it's a bad sign when during MGM's ``The Mod Squad,''
even the characters are cracking wise at the hackneyed
predictability of the plot.
</P>
<P>
   ``I keep thinking one of us should say, `I'm getting too old for
this s---,'' jokes Giovanni Ribisi's Pete, referring to Danny
Glover's tagline in the Cadillac of hackneyed, predictable movie
series, ``Lethal Weapon.''
</P>
<P>
   Oh, Pete, you don't know the half of it.
</P>
<P>
   Based on the late '60s TV series starring Peggy Lipton, Michael
Cole and Clarence Williams III as a trio of down-and-out criminals
turned undercover cops, this ``Mod Squad'' comes off as a
half-baked retread at best, a mushy TV dinner that could have used
another couple of minutes in the microwave.
</P>
<P>
   Not that the ingredients weren't right. The three young stars
are capable enough _ Claire Danes made a name for herself with the
groundbreaking TV drama ``My So-Called Life'' and has consistently
pulled off strong performances on the big screen. Ribisi's recent
win as ShoWest's male star of tomorrow is a testament to memorable
turns in pictures like ``Saving Private Ryan'' and ``The Other
Sister.'' And Omar Epps, last seen in ``Scream 2,'' just oozes
cool.
</P>
<P>
   But nobody gave these kids any characters to play with. Danes'
Julie is an insecure waif with puppy-dog eyes who hardly seems
capable of surviving the streets. Ribisi's take on Pete isn't much
of a stretch from his portrayal of Phoebe's half-wit brother on
``Friends,'' and Epps' Linc is so cool he's almost frozen.
</P>
<P>
   The attempt to fuse '90s Gen X club-kid mentality with the
hippie counter-culture of the original TV series consists mainly of
a techno rehash of the old show's theme music blaring loudly in the
background. Cool, huh?
</P>
<P>
   Dennis Farina adds a little heat to the mix as Capt. Adam Greer,
the team's reluctant police force supervisor, but his disappearance
early on drains the last shreds of interest in this by-the-numbers
story of bad police officers peddling junk.
</P>
<P>
   ``Don't tell me this is a whole corrupt-cops-and-drugs thing,''
Pete asks incredulously at one point.
</P>
<P>
   Sigh. Yeah, Pete, we know how you feel.
</P>
<P>
   _
</P>
<P>
   Film: ``The Mod Squad''
</P>
<P>
   Rating: 2 on a scale of 5
</P>
<P>
   Director: Scott Silver
</P>
<P>
   Featuring: Claire Danes, Giovanni Ribisi, Omar Epps
</P>
<P>
   Length: 94 minutes
</P>
<P>
   Rated: R _ violence, profanity, adult situations and subject
matter
</P>
<P>
   _
</P>
<P>
   (Todd Camp is film critic for the Fort Worth Star-Telegram.
Visit the Star-Telegram's online services on the World Wide Web:
www.star-telegram.com) nn
</P>
</TEXT>
