<HEADLINE>
CLINTON'S LIES MUCH MORE THAN `ONE NEGATIVE'  
 (ADV: THIS EDITORIAL APPEARED IN THE MARCH 25 ARIZONA REPUBLIC) 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by N.Y. Times News Service clients)  
 c.1999 The Arizona Republic  
<TEXT>
<P>
   PHOENIX - For the first time, President Clinton found himself
confronting the inglorious consequences of his most disgraceful
public act. Will the Clinton legacy ``be about lying?'' he was
asked at his first press conference since the awful cacophony of
the impeachment and Lewinsky scandals began.
</P>
<P>
   There will be a ``box score,'' the president angrily responded
last Friday. ``And there will be that one negative.''
</P>
<P>
   That one solitary, comparatively pathetic, little lie, he
argued, ``pales before the hundreds and hundreds and hundreds of
times when the record will show that I did not abuse my authority
as president, that I was truthful with the American people, and
scores and scores of allegations were made against me and widely
publicized without any regard to whether they were true or not.''
</P>
<P>
   You can't really blame the president for grasping at whatever
straw may rescue his heritage, but the plain fact is, his ``one
negative'' constituted one of the greatest whoppers of all time.
And if he wishes to build a box score, he'll need to do a better
job with the players and their positions.
</P>
<P>
   His lie was not a single, finger-wagging, scolding of the
American people for believing he ``had sex with that woman, Ms.
Lewinsky.''
</P>
<P>
   It was a series of lies told over and over _ to his staff, his
Cabinet officers, the courts, and ultimately, to the American
people. His lies to his aides bought political cover for past and
future lies; his lies under oath bought time; and, his lie to the
American people bought him sympathy, patience and pity. ``One
negative''? It was a cold and calculated pattern of deception.
</P>
<P>
   To compare this transgression to a shortstop bobbling a ground
ball completely ignores the lasting impact his ``one negative''
will have on the presidency for years to come.
</P>
<P>
   Already, the tone of this presidential election cycle is that of
a scouting jamboree. Elizabeth Dole, in particular, has staked out
territory as the one candidate who voters can trust to never tumble
into tawdry dalliances.
</P>
<P>
   At the same press conference, the president declined to comment
on the rape accusations of Juanita Broaddrick, who contends that
Clinton, as Arkansas Attorney General in 1978, assaulted her in a
Little Rock hotel room.
</P>
<P>
   All things considered, it was just as well he let that little
``negative'' be. &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
