<HEADLINE>
HOW MANY WRITING ROBIN COOKS ARE THERE?
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By ROGERS CADENHEAD 
c.1999 Fort Worth Star-Telegram 
<TEXT>
<P>
   Q: I heard that the writer Robin Cook had died. Can you verify
this?
</P>
<P>
   _ D.M.N., Fort Worth
</P>
<P>
   A: There have been two successful authors named Robin Cook.
</P>
<P>
   One, a Boston doctor who writes medical thrillers, is on tour
this month promoting ``Vector,'' a new book that was published
March 1. His novels include ``Coma,'' ``Toxin,'' ``Contagion'' and
``Outbreak.''
</P>
<P>
   Several of his books have been made into TV movies or
miniseries, including ``Robin Cook's Virus'' and ``Robin Cook's
Terminal.''
</P>
<P>
   The other Robin Cook, a British mystery writer, died in 1994 of
cancer at age 63. He used the pen name Derek Raymond and wrote
``The Crust on Its Uppers,'' ``I Was Dora Suarez'' and 13 other
books.
</P>
<P>
   You can write to Dr. Cook in care of Penguin Putnam Publicity,
375 Hudson St., New York, NY 10014.
</P>
<P>
   Q: I am doing a project for my eighth-grade journalism class at
Colleyville Middle School and need to reach Bob Woodward and Carl
Bernstein. How can I contact them via e-mail, regular mail or
phone?
</P>
<P>
   _ A.G., Colleyville, Texas
</P>
<P>
   A: Bob Woodward serves as the assistant managing editor of
investigative reporting for The Washington Post. Write to him at
The Washington Post, 1150 15th St. N.W., Washington, DC 20071.
</P>
<P>
   Carl Bernstein has been a contributing editor at Vanity Fair
since 1996. Write to him in care of Vanity Fair, 350 Madison Ave.,
4th Floor, New York, NY 10017.
</P>
<P>
   Aug. 9 marks 25 years since President Nixon resigned in the wake
of the 1972 Watergate Hotel break-in, which ``Post'' reporters
Bernstein and Woodward first linked to the White House. Woodward is
working on a new book about Watergate's impact on the presidency.
</P>
<P>
   Q: What ever happened to Jodie Sweetin, who played Stefanie on
``Full House,'' and where can I write to her?
</P>
<P>
   _ J.P., Fort Worth
</P>
<P>
   A: Write to Sweetin in care of Savage Agency, 6212 Banner Ave.,
Los Angeles, Calif. 90038.
</P>
<P>
   Sweetin, now 17, was 5 years old when ``Full House'' premiered
in 1987. Since the show went off the air in 1995, she has made
guest appearances on ``Brotherly Love,'' ``World's Funniest Home
Videos'' and an ABC special, ``All Star Magic.''
</P>
<P>
   In September, Sweetin appeared at a Phoenix elementary school as
part of Box Tops for Education, a program through which General
Mills redeems cereal box tops sent in by schools.
</P>
<P>
   (Rogers Cadenhead writes a trivia column for the Fort Worth
Star-Telegram. He can be reached at the Star-Telegram, Box 1870,
Fort Worth, Texas 76101; or by E-mail at trivia(at)prefect.com.
Visit the Star-Telegram's online services on the World Wide Web:
www.star-telegram.com)
</P>
</TEXT>
