A3786 &Cx1f; tic-z
r k &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-EDIT-NATOGAMBLE-AZR &LR;      03-25 0572
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-EDIT-NATO </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
CLINTON'S BIG GAMBLE MUST WORK  
 (ADV: THIS EDITORIAL APPEARED IN THE MARCH 25 ARIZONA REPUBLIC) 
</HEADLINE>
 GAMBLE-AZR   (For use by N.Y. Times News Service clients)  
 c.1999 The Arizona Republic  
<TEXT>
<P>
   PHOENIX - President Clinton and NATO are betting _ hoping,
really _ that the launching of airstrikes Wednesday will force
Yugoslav President Slobodan Milosevic to halt his killing and
aggression.
</P>
<P>
   In winning Senate support for a bombing campaign, the Clinton
administration argued that it was left with little choice but to
mount an air campaign after exhausting negotiations and essentially
running out of threats.
</P>
<P>
   Nobody questions the humanitarianism of this mission, that
thousands of Kosovar Albanian lives may be at stake and more
villages destroyed if something is not done. But Americans may wake
up to find this foray against a sovereign nation to be a bigger,
bloodier campaign than they expected.
</P>
<P>
   Clinton has scarcely briefed the nation on what critics of
American intervention insist is an attempt by the Serbs to quell a
secessionist rebellion. In other words, what business is this of
the United States? The United States has chosen not to involve
itself in similar confrontations in at least a dozen other
countries.
</P>
<P>
   Sen. Jon Kyl, R-Ariz., is among those who believe Clinton has
not made a convincing case that U.S. national security is
threatened by the conflict in Yugoslavia. Kyl doubts whether the
bombing campaign proposed by Clinton will force the Serbs to agree
to a peace settlement and says he can't support putting American
troops in harm's way.
</P>
<P>
   Clinton is banking that airstrikes will prove so devastating
that Milosevic will sign a cease-fire agreement and give the
Albanian rebels limited authority over their own affairs. But what
happens if the Serbs refuse to buckle to cruise missiles and bombs?
What if an air campaign winds up strengthening the resolve of
Milosevic?
</P>
<P>
   What then? Do we send American ground troops into combat with
those from NATO? What option is left?
</P>
<P>
   History suggests conventional air campaigns typically are
followed by the use of ground troops. Witness the Persian Gulf War
in 1991, where American ground troops routed the Iraqis after heavy
bombing. The massive bombing of North Vietnam failed to produce a
U.S. victory.
</P>
<P>
   The U.S. and NATO attack against an array of Serbian military
targets must be so strong, so convincing, that the Serbs yield
under the pressure. However, Sen. John McCain, R-Ariz., fears that
the U.S.-led strikes may not be strong enough.
</P>
<P>
   ``Will the airstrikes be robust or will they be the classic
Clintonian action which is pinprick in nature and not nearly
sufficient to persuade our adversaries to act in a manner which we
want them to?'' McCain asks.
</P>
<P>
   There are other potential ramifications from NATO involvement
that worry observers. While seeking to force the Serbs to the
bargaining table, the allies must guard against the Albanians
pushing for all-out independence. There are fears that an
independent Kosovo would destabilize the Balkans. Further, NATO
must reckon with Russia's opposition to the alliance's military
campaign.
</P>
<P>
   In raising the stakes in Kosovo, it is not at all clear whether
America can achieve its aims without paying some high costs. But by
keeping channels of communication open with Milosevic, it may still
be possible to reach an agreement without too much bloodshed. &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-03-25-99 1310EST &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> NYT19990325.0107 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-03-25 13:12 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A3787 &Cx1f; tab-z
r a &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-CNS-SAKE-BARS &LR;      03-25 1182
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-CNS-SAKE-BARS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
FOR GOODNESS SAKE: NEW YORKERS DISCOVER RICE WINE 
</HEADLINE>
   For use by New York Times Syndicate/News Service clients as
desired.  
 By ANDREW GLAZER  
 c. 1999 Columbia News Service  
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEW YORK _ The microbrew revolution has come and gone. Martini
madness is so two years ago.
</P>
<P>
   But there's a new drink in town. It's clear. It's dry. It's
cool. It's ... sake.
</P>
<P>
   Although the rice wine has been around since 200 A.D., it's only
in the past two decades that Japanese brewers have been making sake
that appeals to Western palates. Last year, two ultra-hot New York
nouveau-Japanese restaurants, Nobu and Bond Street, began
advertising their extensive sake lists, where the price range for a
glass of sake is comparable to that of red wine. And New York's
sake bars, previously visited only by Japanese tourists,
businessmen and a few curious non-Japanese drinkers, in the last
year have begun filling up with New York hipsters and curious
drinkers.
</P>
<P>
   But hey, Slick, don't ask for peanuts or popcorn with your
drink.
</P>
<P>
   ``Cold sake and spicy squid go down good together,'' said
Michael Lonergan, one of the few non-Japanese kimono-clad servers
at Sake Bar Decibel, which was one of the first of its kind in New
York when it opened in the East Village six years ago.
</P>
<P>
   Lonergan said it's a part of the fusion of cuisine, styles and
culture that have become hot in the city. ``First there was sushi
in the 1980s,'' he said. ``Now there's sake. It's just part of
it.''
</P>
<P>
   Decibel has two small dark rooms no bigger than an East Village
one-bedroom apartment, with a number of private booths _ a perfect
hangout for people who want to see and to be seen _ sort of. On a
Monday night, three young Japanese hipsters _ one man wearing
red-tinted glasses and a woman with her hair twisted into
Coolio-style braids _ sat huddled at the bar, chatting in Japanese
with the bartender, who had bleached hair.
</P>
<P>
   ``We have a lot of musicians, artists and supermodels coming
by,'' said Katsushi Takahashi, Decibel's droopy-eyed and bearded
manager.
</P>
<P>
   Lonergan said he recently served musicians Patti Smith and Todd
Rundgren and actor Joaquin Phoenix.
</P>
<P>
   Decibel's ambiance initially attracted a crowd of regulars who
were mostly sake-illiterate. Or they had tasted the generic hot
sake served at many of the city's sushi bars.
</P>
<P>
   ``Most people have never tried the good stuff,'' said Takahashi,
a self-proclaimed ``heavy drinker'' who said he has tasted all 70
of Decibel's sakes. Most sushi bars and restaurants serve only one
type of sake, Takahashi said. ``The Budweiser. We don't serve the
Budweiser stuff.''
</P>
<P>
   Soon Decibel regulars grew to appreciate its variety of 70
different sakes, which range from $6 to $28 a glass. The taste of
the wine can vary from subtle and fruity to pungent and grassy.
Sake is served either warm or cold and has an alcohol content of
about 16 percent, compared to 12 percent for regular wine and 5
percent for beer. Patrons at Decibel drink sake out of traditional
Japanese clay pots, glasses or wooden boxes, depending on which
sake is served.
</P>
<P>
   Joe Martin, spokesman for one New York's largest sake
distributors, Paramount Brands, said sales have gone up since the
newer, more nuanced sake hit the U.S. market. ``Before, the sake
was made with a gritty taste and a hard aftertaste,'' he said.
``Now there are more perfumy, light sakes, with different
qualities.'' But Martin said sake would always remain in a somewhat
niche market. ``Is it going to sweep the nation like Merlot? I
don't think so.''
</P>
<P>
   Lonergan said part of sake's appeal is the way it's consumed.
``It's social,'' he said. ``It comes in these little cups or boxes
and you share. Or you pour the warm sake from the clay flask.''
</P>
<P>
   One patron wearing a tight red thrift-store ski sweater said he
has developed a sophisticated appreciation of sake. ``I drink vodka
by the gallon,'' said Lower East Side resident Gary Shteyngart, 27,
a grant writer. ``But the sweetness and dryness of sake make you
not realize that you're getting drunk.''
</P>
<P>
   Although connoisseurs describe sake with the same adjectives
used to discuss wine _ flowery, fragrant, deep, full-bodied _
Decibel isn't that kind of place.
</P>
<P>
   ``I say sake goes from sweet and light to heavy and sour,''
Lonergan said.
</P>
<P>
   In midtown is Decibel's more conservative younger sister bar,
Saka Gura. At Saka Gura, a row of gray-, black- and brown-suited
Japanese businessmen, like Masao Wada, an advertising executive
from Himeji, sat at the well-lit and well-stocked sake bar. Wada
was drinking cold sake he described as light. ``I recommend cold
sake because there is no headache in the morning.''
</P>
<P>
   The large room also has booths where a mixture of Japanese
visitors and native New Yorkers go after work to unwind, eat spicy
radishes _ another typical sake side _ and sip sake.
</P>
<P>
   When Saka Gura opened three years ago, its clientele was almost
exclusively Japanese tourists and expatriates. But in the past
year, the after-work and weekend crowds have mixed. More upper
middle-class Americans who enjoy wine and spirits have started to
notice the variety of quality sake.
</P>
<P>
   ``I think before, sake was not regarded as a wine,'' said Masa
Omichi, Saka Gura's 27 year-old spiky-haired manager from Osaka.
``But it is a rice wine.''
</P>
<P>
   Omichi said he also thinks health-obsessed Americans feel
drinking sake might not be so bad for them.
</P>
<P>
   ``Many Americans ask me how healthy sake is,'' Omichi said. ``I
think many people think Japanese food is healthy,'' Omichi said.
``And they figure, it's made from rice.''
</P>
<P>
   Like grape wine, different sakes are best enjoyed with certain
foods. ``Drinking sake with grated radishes prevents hangovers,''
Omichi said. And aged sake, a sweet brown variety, is best with
cheesecake, he added.
</P>
<P>
   Recently, trendy non-sake-exclusive bars like Bond Street have
started to serve sake and sake-based cocktails including the sweet
``saketini,'' a mixture of plum sake, grapefruit juice and
vermouth. ``It's by far the most popular drink we serve,'' said
Bond Street's black-clad manager, Andrea Marciani, 28, about the $8
drink. ``An updated Cosmopolitan without the harsh aftertaste.''
</P>
<P>
   ``It's kind of equivalent to California rolls and sushi,'' said
Mito Yamada, 24, who is originally from Tokyo, but now works as an
analyst at KPMG Peat Marwick in Manhattan. ``It's an American
version of a traditional part of Japanese culture.''
</P>
<P>
   Meanwhile, thousands of miles away in Japan, she said, another
cool, exotic drink has hit the scene: California red wine.
</P>
<P>
   &UR; (EDITORS: Andrew Glazer is a master's degree candidate at the
Graduate School of Journalism at Columbia University. There is no
charge for use of this story, but please send a tearsheet to Prof.
Wayne Svoboda, Columbia News Service, Graduate School of
Journalism, Columbia University, 2950 Broadway, New York, N.Y.
10027) &LR;  &QC;
</P>
</TEXT>
