<HEADER>
A3788 &Cx1f; tab-z
r a &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-CNS-PIGEON-RACING &LR;      03-25 1277
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-CNS-PIGEON-RACING </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
DIE-HARDS DETERMINED TO KEEP PIGEON RACING FLYING 
</HEADLINE>
   For use by New York Times Syndicate/News Service clients as
desired.  
 By HANNAH MITCHELL  
 c.1999 Columbia News Service  
<TEXT>
<P>
   STATEN ISLAND _ Vinnie Raia adores his thoroughbreds.
</P>
<P>
   Take King Nick, named for his grandson. Last year, King Nick
finished 11th in a race of 6,823 pigeons. That's right, pigeons.
</P>
<P>
   The bird sped 300 miles nonstop from Carlyle, Pa., to Raia's
Staten Island home. And he wasn't even winded.
</P>
<P>
   Pigeons don't get much respect in New York. But a small circle
of old-timers still compete in a sport that makes champions of
perhaps the world's most despised bird. They may look slow, but
pigeons can fly at speeds of up to 70 mph. It doesn't matter where
you drop them off, they come back like a boomerang.
</P>
<P>
   ``There is a huge percentage of the American population that is
not aware of us,'' said Rick Phalen, director of the American
Racing Pigeon Union. ``It's an excellent recreational option. These
are just incredible athletes.''
</P>
<P>
   While pigeon racing was once a favorite pastime of working-class
men and young boys across New York City, the hobby is now
struggling to hold its own. In its peak in the 1970s, New York had
1,325 racers, said Val Matteucci, secretary of the International
Federation of American Homing Pigeon Fanciers. Today, only 700
racers are left.
</P>
<P>
   Few young people are replacing older pigeon racers who die or
become too feeble. Most racers are retirees like Raia. ``In 25 or
30 years, this sport is going to be almost nonexistent,'' said
Raia, who is 62.
</P>
<P>
   Not if the American Racing Pigeon Union can help it. The group,
based in Oklahoma City, is developing an advertising campaign, the
first since the organization formed more than 80 years ago, Phalen
said.
</P>
<P>
   Organized pigeon racing began in Belgium in the mid-1800s.
European immigrants brought the sport to the United States in the
1880s. In its heyday, 18,000 racers, known as flyers, were active.
Pigeon racing is still popular in Belgium and Holland.
</P>
<P>
   Here's how a race works. Pigeons are taken by truck 100 to 600
miles from their homes and released. Each bird wears a rubber band
stamped with a number. The pigeons immediately speed for home. A
100-mile race takes about two hours, while a 600-mile race can
stretch to 14 hours.
</P>
<P>
   When the birds arrive, their owners pull off the band and put it
in a special clock that records the arrival time, guaranteeing
flyers don't cheat. (Owners insist they do not bet.) The speed of
the bird is measured in yards per minute.
</P>
<P>
   ``I've lost races in seconds,'' Raia said.
</P>
<P>
   Some birds don't make it back alive. Hawks pick them off, they
get sick or collide with a wire or other obstacle.
</P>
<P>
   So why do pigeons come home?
</P>
<P>
   It's mostly instinct, but intelligence plays a part, said Mindy
LaBranche of Project PigeonWatch, a research program at Cornell
University's Lab of Ornithology. Like a compass, the birds sense
direction magnetically. Their strong vision and hearing also helps.
</P>
<P>
   But not all pigeons are created equal. Some won't race and
couldn't possibly find home. ``It could be because we've bred it
out of the species,'' LaBranche said. ``And you have to develop
that sense a bit, even if it's in the genes.''
</P>
<P>
   No one seems to know how people discovered pigeons' homing
ability. East Mediterranean grain farmers who kept them for food
domesticated the birds 5,000 to 10,000 years ago. During World War
II, thousands of donated American pigeons carried messages for the
Allies. One pigeon, GI Joe, saved a battalion of soldiers by flying
from France to Holland to warn of a German advancement.
</P>
<P>
   Pigeons race no farther than many migratory birds. They are just
more focused. They don't stop, even to eat, unless the weather is
very bad. Home means safety, ample food and their nest _ the
answers to their subconscious desire for survival, LaBranche said.
</P>
<P>
   They are also fascinating. As a young boy growing up on Staten
Island, Raia helped an adult neighbor with his pigeons.
</P>
<P>
   ``To see them come home from such a tremendous distance and land
on a three-by-three-foot board,'' Raia said. ``To fly 500, 600
miles and come home, that was amazing to me as a child.''
</P>
<P>
   Fifty years later, he still loves the sport. The retired
construction company owner rises each day by dawn to feed King Nick
and the rest of his 200 birds. During the racing season, he loads
them in crates and drives his prized team away from his home and
lets them loose. In the evenings, he feeds them and cleans.
</P>
<P>
   While Raia loves his birds, those who tarry don't last long.
Every two years, he takes the slowpokes to his basement and, one by
one, puts them in a knapsack and rings their necks. It hurts him to
do it, but he doesn't have room to keep them all.
</P>
<P>
   It takes more than dedication to be a flyer, Matteucci said. It
takes money.
</P>
<P>
   ``You can spend three to five hundred dollars a year on
medication alone,'' he said. ``It used to be a poor man's hobby,
but if you dabble in it now, you need quite a few dollars.''
</P>
<P>
   When Rudy Cherney was growing up in a mostly Italian
neighborhood in lower Harlem, a good fancy pigeon, which doesn't
have the homing instinct, sold for 15 cents apiece. He started with
an eight-crate loft of the pigeons on his parent's fire escape.
</P>
<P>
   ``Every other apartment house would have pigeons on the roof,''
Cherney said.
</P>
<P>
   Cherney, who is now 75 and living in New Jersey, still races
pigeons, although the prices have changed in the past 60 years.
Today, a good racing pigeon costs $300 to $500.
</P>
<P>
   Still, Phalen calls the sport reasonable. One survey found that
40 percent of racers spend between $50 and $100 a month. ``Is golf
cost-prohibitive? Is bowling cost-prohibitive?'' Phalen said. ``You
can spend about what you want to spend.''
</P>
<P>
   Raia and Cherney want to see their beloved pastime live on.
Cherney takes his birds to classrooms and children's clubs to
encourage the next generation. His racing club donates free pigeons
to new racers. ``We'll do whatever it takes,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   Yet Cherney knows today's children have more ways to pass the
time than he did. That's a shame, he says, because bird racing is
more than just a hobby. ``It kept us out of trouble when we were
children in New York,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   None of Raia's four children shows interest in the sport. He
figures he will have to sell his birds when he gets too old to
race. That makes him sad. To promote the cause, he recently slapped
a bumper sticker on his blue pickup that reads, ``Need a hobby? Fly
pigeons.''
</P>
<P>
   ``Hey kids! You want to eat?'' Raia called to the adult
contingent of his loft. He was answered with much cooing and
flapping of wings. He skipped the adults to feed the babies first.
</P>
<P>
   ``Come on, come on, come on, come on,'' he said, his hands, with
fingers thick as hotdogs, pouring a mixture of beans, safflower
seeds, Brewer's yeast and corn oil into a wooden trough. He moved
on to the adults, staying around to hand-feed them peanuts for a
treat. ``I would never think about getting rid of the birds,'' he
said.
</P>
<P>
   &UR; (EDITORS: Hannah Mitchell is a master's degree candidate at the
Graduate School of Journalism at Columbia University. There is no
charge for use of this story, but please send a tearsheet to Prof.
Wayne Svoboda, Columbia News Service, Graduate School of
Journalism, Columbia University, 2950 Broadway, New York, N.Y.
10027) &LR;  &QC;
</P>
</TEXT>
