<HEADER>
A3792 &Cx1f; ttj-z
r e &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-TV-REVIEW-MUTINY-$ADV     03-25 0920
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-TV-REVIEW-MUTINY-$ADV28-HNS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
WARTIME RACISM EXPOSED IN NBC STORY ON BLACK MUTINEERS 
</HEADLINE>
  
 (For release Sunday, March 28)   (For use by New York Times News Service clients.)  
 By MARK McGUIRE  
 c.1999 Albany Times Union  
<TEXT>
<P>
   As the World War II generation gracefully exits the stage to a
final and deserved round of applause, you wonder what stories could
be left to tell about the conflict that defined this century.
</P>
<P>
   Then you are shocked, and in many ways saddened, to just learn
of an incident that killed so many men, ruined so many careers, and
for no good reason.
</P>
<P>
   For all that was right about America in leading that fight
against totalitarianism, our government was still mired in the sin
of racism. It was an ugly contradiction, fighting for the united
good with segregated armed forces, liberating the concentration
camps of Europe while Japanese Americans were incarcerated here in
the States solely because of their race.
</P>
<P>
   So the story of what happened near San Francisco one night in
the summer of 1944 faded underneath the bright light of glory.
Eventually, a nation forgot about Port Chicago, the tragedy and the
injustice, an injustice that lingers today. Thankfully, television
is reminding us.
</P>
<P>
   Last month the History Channel did an excellent documentary on
the Port Chicago Mutiny. Now NBC and actor Morgan Freeman, this
time behind the scenes as an executive producer, bring the story to
dramatic light in ``Mutiny'' (Sunday at 9 EST, NBC, check local
listings). It is a powerful and cautionary tale, one that even
Freeman did not know much about until he undertook the project.
</P>
<P>
   ``I think ideas float,'' Freeman said recently. ``This story,
yeah, has been around. It is just one of millions, thousands,
waiting to be told. It just spontaneously combusts.''
</P>
<P>
   The story once made headlines, how 320 men were killed and 390
wounded _ the overwhelmingly majority black sailors _ on the night
of July 17, 1944, when a transport ship anchored and being loaded
at the Port Chicago Munitions Base just outside of San Francisco
exploded.
</P>
<P>
   It was one of the largest man-made explosions in history.
Everyone and everything within 1,000 feet of the blast site was
obliterated in an explosion that sent smoke and fire 12,000 feet
skyward. How devastating? A locomotive engine on train tracks on
the dock simply disappeared.
</P>
<P>
   It was the worst home-front disaster of World War II. The 202
black sailors killed (in addition to the 233 wounded) amounted to a
staggering 15 percent of all blacks killed in the war.
</P>
<P>
   Why so many blacks? Because in the segregated Navy, blacks were
given jobs filled with danger but none of the accompanying glories
of combat. Blacks, none with adequate training, were responsible
for loading the munitions ships. This was under white officers, of
course, some of whom, evidence suggests, were betting between
themselves as to which unit could load transports faster.
</P>
<P>
   Three weeks after the disaster, 50 black sailors refused to go
back to work until they received proper training. The stage was
then set for the biggest mutiny trial in the history of the Navy.
All were convicted in a court-martial, despite the protests of a
courtside observer, NAACP attorney _ and later Supreme Court
justice _ Thurgood Marshall.
</P>
<P>
   The Navy tribunal took all of 80 minutes of deliberations to
convict, and the sailors were given various prison stretches
ranging from eight to 15 years. Two years later, the sentences were
commuted, and the sailors were discharged a year later. And while
some credit the incident for playing a role in President Harry
Truman's decision to integrate the armed forces, the convictions
were never overturned, even though there is evidence racial
prejudice played a role in the case.
</P>
<P>
   Efforts to expunge the blight on the sailors' records continue
to this day in Washington (for more information, visit the Web site
www.portchicagomutiny.com).
</P>
<P>
   So who or what was blamed for the blast? Lack of training? An
untenable schedule to keep supplies flowing to the Pacific? Racist
officers? Try the victims, at least in a Pentagon report that never
pinpointed the exact cause of the blast.
</P>
<P>
   ``The consensus opinion of the witnesses is that the colored
enlisted personnel are neither temperamentally nor intellectually
capable of handling high explosives,'' according to a portion of
the Navy report excerpted in the History Channel documentary. ``It
is an admitted fact that there was rough and careless handling of
explosives being loaded at Port Chicago.''
</P>
<P>
   ``Mutiny,'' in which Freeman does not appear, is made up of a
capable cast of mostly unknowns and several familiar faces, with
several real-life stories melded into composites because of
dramatic purposes and time. It is not fun television, but it is
important television, and well done.
</P>
<P>
   ``It is history. It is time to be dealt with ... and close the
books on it,'' Freeman said of the Port Chicago Mutiny.
</P>
<P>
   Let the postscript be written by Freddie Meeks, a black Port
Chicago ammunition loader and one of the 50 involved in the mutiny,
as he told the History Channel: ``And now it is out and I can talk
about it. Thank God. Long time. It hurts.''
</P>
<P>
   He then bowed and shook his head slowly.
</P>
<P>
   It's out. And as a nation, we can't afford to forget again, or
say it is too late to right the wrong.
</P>
<P>
   &LR;  &QL;
</P>
<P>
   (Mark McGuire is the television and radio writer for the Albany
Times Union, P.O. Box 15000, Albany, NY 12212. E-mail:
mmcguire(at)timesunion.com)
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
