<SLUG> BC-MAPLE-SYRUP-HNS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
SYRUP ISN'T JUST FOR BREAKFAST ANYMORE 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients.)  
 By DOUG BLACKBURN  
 c.1999 Albany Times Union  
<TEXT>
<P>
   ALBANY, N.Y. _ Maple syrup is the perfect topping for pancakes
and waffles. But don't limit maple syrup to breakfast topping.
</P>
<P>
   Be creative and regard it as a substitute for sugar. Maple syrup
is also well suited for marinades, and because of its viscosity, a
half-cup goes a long way.
</P>
<P>
   Finally, don't forget how well maple syrup works for glazing.
Want to add a sweet glaze to a ham as it finishes baking? Baste it
with maple syrup during the final half-hour. Likewise, pork chops
almost sing with sweetness when a quarter-cup of maple syrup is
added to the pan during the last five minutes of frying.
</P>
<P>
   There are three grades, or colors, of syrup _ light amber,
medium amber and dark amber.
</P>
<P>
   Light amber, which has a delicate flavor, is considered premium
maple syrup. It retails for approximately $40 per gallon, when it's
available.
</P>
<P>
   Medium amber maple syrup sells for about $34 per gallon, or $4
for an 8-ounce container.
</P>
<P>
   Sap harvesters often sell in bulk their dark amber to commercial
operations such as Log Cabin syrup.
</P>
<P>
   If you are eager for inspiration when it comes to using maple
syrup, try either of these recipes:
</P>
<P>
   &UR;  &QL;
</P>
<P>
   MAPLE SYRUP CREME BRULEE
</P>
<P>
   Heat 2 cups heavy cream almost to a simmer. In a medium bowl,
stir 8 large egg yolks (or 3 large eggs) and 2/3 cup maple syrup
with a wooden spoon until blended. Gradually stir in the hot cream.
Strain through a fine-mesh sieve into a bowl or large measure with
a pour lip. Stir in 3/4 teaspoon vanilla.
</P>
<P>
   Pour into 6 or 8 custard cups and place all cups in a large pan.
Add enough hot water to the pan to come halfway up the sides of the
custard cups. Set the pan in the oven and set the temperature at
250 degrees. Bake until the custard is set but still slightly
quivery in the center when the cups are gently shaken, 1 to 1 1/2
hours.
</P>
<P>
   Remove the custards from the water bath and let cool to room
temperature. Cover each one tightly with plastic wrap and
refrigerate for at least 8 hours and up to 2 days. Shortly before
serving, gently blot any liquid that has formed on the surface with
paper towels, then caramelize the surface by sprinkling the custard
with sugar and the melting the sugar under the broiler or with a
propane torch.
</P>
<P>
   &UR;  &QL;
</P>
<P>
   MAPLE SYRUP CHICKEN
</P>
<P>
   (Makes 4 to 5 servings.)
</P>
<P>
   1 (2 1/2- to 3-pound) chicken, cut up, or equivalent chicken
breasts
</P>
<P>
   1/2 teaspoon grated lemon rind
</P>
<P>
   Dash pepper
</P>
<P>
   2 teaspoons lemon juice
</P>
<P>
   1/4 cup butter, melted
</P>
<P>
   1/2 cup maple syrup
</P>
<P>
   1/2 teaspoon salt, optional
</P>
<P>
   1/4 cup chopped onions
</P>
<P>
   Heat oven to 400 degrees. Butter a shallow baking dish.
</P>
<P>
   Place chicken pieces in baking dish. Mix remaining ingredients
and pour evenly over chicken. Bake uncovered 50 to 60 minutes,
basting occasionally. Serve on a bed of rice.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
