<DOCNO> NYT19990325.0113 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-03-25 13:23 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A3798 &Cx1f; ttj-z
r k &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-CAMPAIGN-FINANCE-HNS &LR;      03-25 0931
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-CAMPAIGN-FINANCE-HNS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
GEORGE WILL'S LONELY STANCE ON CAMPAIGN FINANCE 
</HEADLINE>
   Commentary  
 (For use by New York Times News Service clients.)  
 By ANN McBRIDE  
 and DONALD SIMON  
 c.1999 Albany Times Union  
<TEXT>
<P>
   ALBANY, N.Y. _ Newspaper columnist and commentator George Will
works himself into high dudgeon over the fact that Common Cause and
other political reformers don't share his peculiarly elitist vision
of democracy.
</P>
<P>
   He's right. We don't. In Will's world, democracy is a great
system _ for those who can afford to buy it. One of his recent
columns celebrates the growth of political soft money _ those huge
unregulated contributions from corporations, labor unions and
wealthy individuals that are at the heart of the scandals during
the last presidential campaign.
</P>
<P>
   Of course, Will has a strange way of discussing soft money. He
notes that the almost $200 million of it raised by the two
political parties in the last election works out to a piddling 50
cents per voter. What could be more innocent than that?
</P>
<P>
   Not much, of course, if every voter had really given 50 cents of
it. Instead, 12 tobacco companies together donated more than $5.4
million in soft money during the 1998 election cycle. That's not 50
cents per voter. That's an average of $455,000 per tobacco company.
</P>
<P>
   Will may be naive enough to think that tobacco companies donate
that kind of money simply to express their civic enthusiasm for
participatory democracy. Maybe so. But those contributions also
just might have had something to do with the tobacco industry's
success in killing the tobacco bill that would have regulated the
sale of cigarettes.
</P>
<P>
   But for Will, it seems that's what democracy is all about. Every
citizen should have the same right as every tobacco company to buy
a million dollars' worth of influence on Capitol Hill.
</P>
<P>
   So Will's problem with campaign finance reform is that he just
doesn't get it. If you don't see a problem in mushrooming amounts
of big money being used in Washington to openly buy access and
influence with our national leaders in order to distort policy
outcomes in government, then you don't see the need for any
solution. From Will's lofty perspective, that's good old-fashioned
democracy at work. A great system for those who can afford it.
</P>
<P>
   Most Americans can't. And thankfully, most Americans don't share
Will's vision of democracy. That's why polls show nine out of 10
Americans want significant political reform to reduce the influence
of big money in politics. That's why voters in Arizona,
Massachusetts, California, Colorado, Arkansas and Maine _ every
state where there was a reform proposal on the ballot in the last
two elections _ have enacted campaign finance reform at the state
level.
</P>
<P>
   And that's why a majority in Congress supports reform. Last
year, a bipartisan majority in both the House and the Senate voted
for a bill to end soft money. The legislation died only when a
minority of Senators used a filibuster to block the bill from a
final vote.
</P>
<P>
   The symmetry must have been perfect for Will _ a minority of
legislators using obstructionist tactics to preserve a system that
best serves the interests of the tiny minority of wealthy citizens
who can afford to participate in it. Elitist democracy at work.
</P>
<P>
   It's not just the usual suspects who disagree with Will. A
growing number of business leaders, like Warren Buffett, are
calling for an end to soft money. And when he left Congress, former
Sen. Alan Simpson, a conservative Republican from Wyoming, said
that the role of bid money in politics today is ``poisoning the
system, it is prostituting ideas and ideals. It is demeaning
democracy and debasing debate.''
</P>
<P>
   The Supreme Court, thank goodness, also does not share Will's
vision. More than 20 years ago, the court correctly recognized that
bid money causes corruption in politics. And because of that, the
court said that the First Amendment does not bar efforts to reduce
the pernicious influence of money by limiting the size of
contributions, by banning corporate and union money in campaigns,
by providing for public financing, by requiring full disclosure and
by enacting voluntary spending limits.
</P>
<P>
   Had Will bothered to check, he also would have found that the
Supreme Court has upheld limits on contributions made by an
individual to a political party.
</P>
<P>
   There is still a debate in the lower courts about the role of
money in politics. Some lower courts have said that certain reform
efforts have gone too far in trying to rein in money. Others have
upheld these efforts.
</P>
<P>
   To be sure, there are some tough questions here. But Will is
dead wrong about defining the soft money issue as an effort to ban
speech about issues or limit participation in politics. Rather it
is an effort to protect democracy from the corrosive effect of big
money and to preserve public confidence in the institutions and
ideals of government. That's hard to do when a quarter of a billion
dollars of soft money is sloshing around the White House and the
halls of Congress, as it was in 1996.
</P>
<P>
   But Will doesn't care about that. He's too busy getting the
vapors whenever he thinks about Common Cause working with a growing
list of reformers in Congress to make the political process more
open and democratic. That will happen _ sooner, rather than later.
When it does, someone better fetch smelling salts for George Will.
</P>
<P>
   &UR;  &LR;  &QL;
</P>
<P>
   (Ann McBride is president and Donald Simon is executive vice
president of Common Cause, an advocacy group that supports the
overhaul of the campaign finance system.)
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
