<HEADER>
A3803 &Cx1f; ttj-z
r k &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-PARTY-LOYALTY-HNS &LR;      03-25 0607
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-PARTY-LOYALTY-HNS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
FOR DEMOCRATS, THE PARTY IS THE BOSS 
</HEADLINE>
   Commentary  
 (For use by New York Times News Service clients.)  
 By DONALD G. SMITH  
 c.1999 San Francisco Examiner  
<TEXT>
<P>
   SANTA MARIA, Calif. _ The impeachment trial is now a memory.
Those who wanted to put it all behind us have succeeded, at a
terrible price, and we are back to normal. House managers are
congressmen again and we have determined that something despicable
really wasn't all that bad.
</P>
<P>
   In retrospect, I am left with a thought that is more affirmation
than revelation. This is the essential difference between a
Republican and a Democrat. The great gap between the parties is far
more than ideological. Republicans and Democrats are of different
mentalities and show signs of being two distinct species of human
being.
</P>
<P>
   What separates them is party loyalty. To a Republican, the party
is merely an instrument that works for him about half the time.
</P>
<P>
   It is better than the alternative _ but this is as far as any
deep feelings exist. The Republican is basically a conservative and
this is what he cares about, where his passions lie. The Republican
Party is nothing more than a means of making it work, although it
hasn't really served him all that well.
</P>
<P>
   A Democrat, on the other hand, sees his party as something of a
religion. He sees himself as a Democrat rather than as a liberal.
</P>
<P>
   He will deny being a liberal even though he has just voted for a
candidate who is somewhere to the left of Leon Trotsky.
</P>
<P>
   Democrats are good at looking the other way. When forced to look
at blatant corruption and immorality on the part of their leaders,
they brush it off with such phrases as, ``He is guilty only of
being human,'' ``Everybody does it,'' and the ever popular, ``That
is the way the game is played.''
</P>
<P>
   Big city political machines have invariably been Democratic. The
political bosses have ruled over their fiefdoms with the full
knowledge and consent of the Democratic voters who put them in
office and kept them there. Throughout this century, and even
before, these corrupt, larcenous individuals have had the full
approval of the peasants in the field, people who honestly believed
that they were better off because these old pirates were enriching
themselves.
</P>
<P>
   Republicans resented the obscenity, but Democrats applauded.
</P>
<P>
   This attitude has spilled over into modern times and has given
the Clinton administration a free ride. Those who repeated the
vapid inanity that Clinton's indiscretions did not ``rise to the
level of impeachment'' are the children and grandchildren of those
who smiled upon the corrupt big city machines and permitted the
pillaging to continue. To a Democrat, one's leaders are not to be
questioned. It is the Roman Catholic doctrine of infallibility,
transferred to Chicago and Kansas City.
</P>
<P>
   When Republicans bid a dry-eyed farewell to Spiro Agnew, Richard
Nixon and Robert Packwood, they did so knowing that the country
would be better off without them. In one way or another, they had
all violated a trust and were not worthy of public office. It would
be unthinkable for Democrats to react the same way about one of
their own.
</P>
<P>
   It has all descended from those days of big boss politics when
stealing was all right as long as your guy was doing it. When
reminded that Big Ed has looted the parks department payroll to buy
himself a yacht, the loyal supporter will counter with the case for
the defense: ``When my old man died, this man sent flowers. You
can't fault a guy like that.'' It makes sense to a Democrat.
</P>
<P>
   &UR;  &LR;  &QL;
</P>
<P>
   (Donald G. Smith is retired from corporate communications.)
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
