<P>
   EDITORS: The New York Times is planning four pages of stories on
the NATO air strikes in Yugoslavia for the paper of Friday, March
25. The New York Times News Service plans to move these stories
tonight in the ``i'' news file. For more information, call toll
free at (888) 346-9867. The day supervisor is Ned Kilkelly. The
night supervisor is Pat Ryan.
</P>
<P>
   KOSOVO-RDP (Washington) _ Lede-all; more attacks are expected
tonight and Friday. By Francis X. Clines. With photos.
</P>
<P>
   KOSOVO-MILITARY-ASSESS (Washington) _ A military analysis: What
are NATO's objectives? What are Serbia's objectives? Why aren't
they firing surface-to-air missiles? By Eric Schmitt.
</P>
<P>
   KOSOVO-GERMANY (Berlin) _ For the first time since the end of
World War II, German fighter jets have gone to war, attacking
Yugoslavia as part of a NATO force and marking this country's
definitive emancipation from post-war pacifism. By Roger Cohen.
</P>
<P>
   KOSOVO-MILITARY (Washington) _ Targets hit, targets to be hit,
and the response by Serb forces. By Steven Lee Myers.
</P>
<P>
   KOSOVO-POLICY (Washington) _ A look at the behind-the-scenes
struggle in the Clinton administration leading up to the decision
to join the NATO attack on Yugoslavia. By Jane Perlez.
</P>
<P>
   KOSOVO-BELGRADE (Kievo, Yugoslavia) _ Even after the air raid
sirens wailed, Sara, nearly 5, refused to go down to the basement
shelter until the ``Ninja Turtles'' program was over. Then the
night sky turned orange over this southern suburb of Belgrade, and
on a hill just a mile or so away, where a radar antenna sits, a
NATO missile or bomb exploded. ``There was a big cloud of dust and
a huge pressure of the air,'' said Sara's father, Mile. ``I told
Sara, `Where are our Ninja turtles to help us now?' and then we
went to the shelter.'' By Steven Erlanger.
</P>
<P>
   KOSOVO-PRISTINA (Pristina, Yugoslavia) _ The scene there and
developments. By Carlotta Gall.
</P>
<P>
   KOSOVO-MILOSEVIC (Belgrade) _ Why losing Kosovo can save face
for Milosevic. By Blaine Harden.
</P>
<P>
   KOSOVO-REFUGEES (Skopje, Yugoslavia) _ With refugees in
Macedonia. By Alessandra Stanley. With a map.
</P>
<P>
   KOSOVO-REPORTERS (Undated) _ Foreign journalists from NATO
countries were ordered out of Yugoslavia by the Serbian government
Thursday at nearly the exact hour that they were assured by the
Yugoslav government that they could stay, travel freely and do
their job. Byline to be determined.
</P>
<P>
   KOSOVO-CHINA (BEIJING) _ China pressed an all-out verbal assault
on the NATO air strikes against Serbian forces Thursday, issuing
multiple demands that the attack be halted, while the flagship
state newspaper called the operation a ``dangerous precedent of
naked aggression.'' By Erik Eckholm.
</P>
<P>
   In addition, The Times is pursuing President Clinton's view of
history as viewed by historians; the combat debut of the B-2
bomber; a look at Gen. Wesley Clark, supreme NATO commander, who
has been granted his long-held wish to attack Serbia; European
reaction to the attack; and what Americans are saying.
</P>
<P>
   Also, The New York Times Graphic Service expects to have a
graphic on damage assessments in Yugoslavia.
</P>
<P>
   NYT-03-22-99 1805EST
</P>
