<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-IVOR-GWYNETH-PALTROW-ART-NYTSF </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
GWYNETH PALTROW WOULD LIKE HER LIFE BACK 
</HEADLINE>
  World rights except Great Britain and Australia 
 Color slide of actress Gwyneth Paltrow in a scene from
``Shakespeare in Love.'' 
 By IVOR DAVIS 
 Distributed by New York Times Special Features)  
 &HT;    At 25, Gwyneth Paltrow virtually stole the Oscar show.
 &HT;    She's the new Grace Kelly_''the Meryl Streep of the '90s'' as
one critic put it, both tearful and radiant on Oscar night in her
pink Ralph Lauren gown.
 &HT;    Winning her first best actress Oscar for her role romancing
William Shakespeare, Paltrow has Hollywood at her feet. However
Paltrow, whose victory puts her into the $10-million-a-film
bracket, is single again after breaking up from her ``Shakespeare
in Love'' costar Ben Affleck.
 &HT;    ``I'm eager to remain single,'' Paltrow says. ``Today far too
many young people get married and those marriages end in divorce.''
 &HT;    Paltrow, who has worked nonstop for the past three years in
England, Italy and Canada, says she has been trying ``to get my
life back.''
 &HT;    Her blonde hair pulled severely back, and looking like a sexy
and very glamorous model, she admits she's glad to be back in
America: ``I just want a little quiet time_to enjoy life. There's
nothing wild planned. I just want to be normal again, to do my
thing. I missed American football all that time in Europe.''
 &HT;    She worked in Italy shooting ``The Talented Mr. Ripley'' with
Matt Damon and in Vancouver doing ``Duets'' for her father, Bruce
Paltrow, who directed the film.
 &HT;    ``I want to do the normal things, hang out, see my friends,
read, wander through the bookstores and stay home and cook. I just
want to get my life back together and decorate my home in New
York.''
 &HT;    She's hardly been out of the spotlight since she broke up with
her fiancee Brad Pitt and then again very publicly split with
Affleck_whom she thanked on Oscar night, referring to him as ``my
friend.''
 &HT;    During her time with Pitt she had turned down some big pictures,
including ``The Avengers,'' so she wouldn't be separated from him.
But he fell into the arms of Jennifer Aniston_and Paltrow teamed up
offscreen with Affleck.
 &HT;    ``I've done a lot of movies during a short period of time,'' she
says. ``When you first get movies you say I'd better just work
because they're gonna pay me really well. But now I've changed my
priorities. I want to get my personal life together so I'm slowing
down.''
 &HT;    While ``Shakespeare'' won seven Oscars, including best picture,
fans of the film were surprised when Paltrow went topless in a love
scene with Joseph Fiennes as the young Will Shakespeare. (She
seemed to be naked opposite Ethan Hawke in ``Great Expectations,''
but a body double was actually used.)
 &HT;    ``My grandfather might be shocked,'' says Paltrow, ``and I think
some people were taken off guard by my nudity. Anytime someone gets
comfortable with the way they perceive me, or how I should behave
in a film, I think it's time for me to reverse it.''
 &HT;    In ``Shakespeare'' Paltrow plays a rich and titled Englishwoman
who disguises herself as a man to audition for a role on stage. In
Elizabethan England, only men and boys could act in stage roles.
 &HT;    ``It was exhausting,'' she says. ``It took so much out of me. I
had to dress like a boy, walk like a boy, speak in a low, deep
voice, all the time speaking in verse with an English accent.''
 &HT;    It gave her, she says, a whole new look at life from the other
side. ``It's so unbelievable to see how differently men treat me
when I'm dressed like a man. They say things to me they'd never
think of saying when I was in a wig and long dress.''
 &HT;    Though her refined good looks have made her a natural for period
films, Paltrow says she'd now like to do what she calls, ``a
grossout movie.''
 &HT;    ``I really want something different to the kind of roles they
send me. I get the same scripts as Claire Danes and Winona Ryder.
People don't think of me as Sandra Bullock or Nicole Kidman.
They're the ones who get the big movies. I just get the little
ones.''
 &HT;    Her next picture, ``The Passion,'' is a love story set in the
Napoleonic era.
 &HT;    ``I feel very fortunate to have the career I have,'' she says.
``Winning the Oscar is like a fairy tale come true. I'm happy
because I really believe I'm a centered person. Let's be realistic.
I've been happier at other times in my life, for different reasons.
It's all relative, of course. But yes...you can say Gwyneth Paltrow
is happy again.''
 &HT;     c.1999 Ivor Davis 
<TEXT>
<P>
   (Ivor Davis is a Hollywood-based reporter.) &LR;  &QL;
</P>
<P>
   ------
 &UR; (Nonsubscribers: To publish this article, contact New York Times
Syndicate sales representative DEBRA WEYDERT at 1-732-390-4480, or
by fax at 732-390-4697.) &QL; 
 &UR; (She also has information on how to subscribe to Hollywood Stars, a
weekly column with color art.) &QL;
</P>
