<HEADER>
A3835 &Cx1f; ttj-z
r k &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-LYNCH-COLUMN-HNS &LR;      03-25 0979
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-LYNCH-COLUMN-HNS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
PROTECT AND SERVE? 
</HEADLINE>
   Commentary  
 (For use by New York Times News Service clients.)  
 By DAN LYNCH  
 c.1999 Albany Times Union  
<TEXT>
<P>
   ALBANY, N.Y. _ Can I say for sure? No, not really.
</P>
<P>
   But I deem it a reasonable presumption that the voice mail
message I got Wednesday came from one of the off-duty cops I'd seen
in the courtroom the day before. That was when I'd dropped by the
Albany County Courthouse to catch the close of the trial of
Officers Sean McKenna and Bill Bonanni.
</P>
<P>
   They were accused of beating up a suspect in handcuffs, a
belligerent college basketball player named Jermaine Henderson. A
good two dozen Albany cops were in that courtroom Tuesday. I
couldn't say if they were there to support their comrades, to
intimidate jurors or some combination of the two. But I will
recount the voice mail message for you.
</P>
<P>
   ``It was wonderful of you to show up at the brutality trial
yesterday,'' the caller said. ``I saw you there in the back of the
courtroom for, what? Maybe two minutes after the jury had left and
the charges had been read?
</P>
<P>
   ``These are the words I want to see in your next column: `I
never attended one minute of the trial.' Then you can go ahead and
write all you want about how you think the verdict is just or
unjust. `I never attended one minute of the trial. Therefore, I
have no idea of what the facts in this case were.'''
</P>
<P>
   Naturally, this guy never approached me to say his piece to my
face while I was standing just a few feet away from him. And,
naturally, he didn't leave his name or number when he called.
</P>
<P>
   On the other hand, neither did the other guys who'd called me
earlier complaining about what I've written about this case _ the
ones who made crude, anonymous death threats. Were any of those
guys in that courtroom Tuesday? I can only speculate. My guess is
that they were.
</P>
<P>
   Once it got rolling, I made it a point not to write about this
trial. I wanted nothing I might write to be construed as having
affected the jury's verdict. What I wanted from the start here was
to see Jermaine Henderson on the stand. I wanted him telling his
story and subjected to cross-examination while jurors watched,
listened and evaluated his credibility.
</P>
<P>
   But District Attorney Sol Greenberg wouldn't permit that. He
firmly refused to give the Henderson kid immunity in exchange for
his testimony in this case. Greenberg seemed to bend over backwards
to guarantee that the complainant never would enter that courtroom
to tell his story and have it fairly challenged.
</P>
<P>
   What I thought McKenna and Bonanni deserved _ and what this
community deserved as well _ was a fair trial. But the callers who
threatened my life _ as well as that nameless, craven bozo who
called me the other morning _ weren't at all interested in a fair
trial. They weren't prepared to settle for fairness.
</P>
<P>
   The fact is that I've followed this case closely. I understand
the evidence. In fact, the only people who didn't have all the
available evidence were the jurors. That's because Greenberg saw to
it that Henderson wouldn't testify.
</P>
<P>
   The district attorney behaved horribly throughout this whole
slimy adventure. So did some of the Albany cops. Most of the 350 or
so members of the Police Department are devoted public servants
with a strong desire to protect and a sharply honed sense of
justice. Some of them, though _ the ones I've heard from, anyway _
seem to be cowardly thugs and bullies who think it's perfectly fine
to kick around suspects in handcuffs.
</P>
<P>
   Did McKenna and Bonanni actually do that? As I've said
repeatedly, I don't know. I wasn't there. A jury has determined
that there's reasonable doubt as to whether they did it. Fine.
That's the system _ although wouldn't it have been nice if this
jury had included just one of the six minority folks who were
methodically knocked out in jury selection?
</P>
<P>
   Whether they did it or not, however, nobody can argue that
McKenna and Bonanni haven't suffered. They still face perjury
charges. They still face administrative charges that could end
their careers. You can also bet that their lawyers, Steve Coffey
and Tommy Neidl, already have separated them from serious sums of
money.
</P>
<P>
   And Jermaine Henderson, who does seem to have started all this
by punching one of the cops in a bar dispute, is off in Illinois
somewhere with a $60,000 civil settlement from the city when he
probably should be doing time.
</P>
<P>
   So, maybe all that, taken together, constitutes rough justice _
at least to some people, if not to me. The problem is that so many
people involved in this seemed to view justice as their lowest
priority. Greenberg seemed much more interested in protecting
McKenna and Bonanni. And the cops marching on city hall and making
nasty phone calls to me seemed more interested in seeing their
comrades escape justice than in whether McKenna and Bonanni really
might have done what they were accused of doing.
</P>
<P>
   So, we're pretty much left with this:
</P>
<P>
   _ A minority community that constitutes two-thirds of arrestees
in a city 75 percent white;
</P>
<P>
   _ A minority community that now has seen white cops accused of
beating up a black suspect in cuffs effectively protected by a
district attorney who seems not to have a clue as to why that's
unacceptable conduct;
</P>
<P>
   _ A minority community whose widely documented fear of the
police and distrust of the criminal justice system can only be
intensified by the vile behavior of some of the people within that
system.
</P>
<P>
   _ A certain number of white cops in New York's capital city _ I
can't say precisely how many _ behaving like redneck skinheads.
</P>
<P>
   All in all, this has been the scummiest episode I've seen played
out in more than three decades of watching the criminal system
operate.
</P>
<P>
   &LR;  &QL;
</P>
<P>
   (Dan Lynch is a columnist for the Albany Times Union, P.O. Box
15000, Albany, NY 12212.)
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
