<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-03-25 14:06 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A3839 &Cx1f; tth-z
r l &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-FASHION-SPRING-SPI &LR;      03-25 0678
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-FASHION-SPRING-SPI </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
CHOOSE YOUR OWN MIX TO MATCH THE STYLE 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients.)  
 By SUSAN PHINNEY  
 c.1999 Seattle Post-Intelligencer  
<TEXT>
<P>
   ``Eclectic'' became a buzzword in home furnishings several years
ago. This spring it's a perfect description of fashion offerings.
</P>
<P>
   Eclectic means to gather items from several sources _ twin sets
(a 1950s look) worn with military-like cargo pants, for example.
</P>
<P>
   Eclectic style is easy to spot in a room arrangement that
includes a classic sofa, an antique armoire and perhaps a high-tech
plexiglass table. With clothing, it's not so easy.
</P>
<P>
   When designers previewed their spring '99 collections last fall,
they paraded everything from '60s hippie looks to paramilitary garb
_ sometimes simultaneously.
</P>
<P>
   Free-flowing shift dresses, color-blocked costumes resembling
Mondrian paintings, kimonolike jackets, skirts or tops resembling
aprons, and tops with three-quarter-length sleeves were all part of
the shows.
</P>
<P>
   While little white shirts and capri pants, a la early Audrey
Hepburn, are in the spring '99 picture, it's more of a
Cher-inspired, or rich-hippie happening with ethnic fabrics and
embroidery.
</P>
<P>
   And if the mere thought of bellbottoms, capris, daisy prints or
gypsylike mixes brings on a headache rather than an urge to shop,
there are options galore.
</P>
<P>
   That's the nice thing about eclecticism. It doesn't have to
involve a head-to-toe makeover. With the addition of a few pieces,
a wardrobe can appear updated.
</P>
<P>
   Take twin sets. These trendy twosomes of pullover _ this season
it's a tank or shell shape _ paired with a cardigan can give a
fresh look to pants and skirts already on hand.
</P>
<P>
   The cardigan also can be worn over a sheath or shift dress in
lieu of a jacket, or tied around the shoulders as a fashion
accessory. When weather warms, the shell or tank top can go solo.
</P>
<P>
   Another easy update would be a pair of flat-front (that means
pleat-free) long or cropped pants _ extra fashion points if they're
cropped.
</P>
<P>
   Adding pink _ and there's a shade of it for everyone _ is
another way to demonstrate fashion savvy this spring. Ralph Lauren
uses strawberry pink. Max Azria, designer for the BCBG label is
showing a vivid raspberry. But pale or bright, pink is powerful.
</P>
<P>
   So is white. Nordstrom is promoting a spectrum of whites _
stone, ecru, ivory, cement and bright white _ for lightening and
brightening the season.
</P>
<P>
   Carol Steele, Nordstrom fashion director for the Pacific
Northwest, calls the whites ``a refreshing counterpoint to last
season's dark shades.'' She also refers to white as ``an instant
mood-booster.''
</P>
<P>
   Caroline Gilmore, a divisional vice president at The Bon Marche
in Seattle, says gray, pink and white are the three dominant shades
for spring, with pink being more popular with so-called ``junior''
shoppers, a word that denotes an attitude, not necessarily an age.
</P>
<P>
   For a working woman, Gilmore suggests gray from head to toe, in
a linen or silk, for example. She bought a gray pantsuit, along
with a white cotton shirt blended with Lycra spandex.
</P>
<P>
   ``Stretch for comfort is key,'' Gilmore says. It doesn't
necessarily mean a garment fits like a second skin, but it is
closer to the body. And stretch fabrics are showing up in capri
pants, shirts and T-shirts.
</P>
<P>
   In addition to stretch, we're going to see a lot of wrinkle-free
and easy-care clothing _ linens that can be washed, dried and worn
without ironing, Gilmore predicts. ``That's one reason linen will
become more important this year.''
</P>
<P>
   Boatnecks and three-quarter-length sleeves are other signs of
spring '99, along with cargo pants adorned with big pockets,
drawstring pants and hooded sweaters.
</P>
<P>
   For evening, designers favor hip-slung skirts and pants with
cropped tops that let skin show. Linda Allard, designer for the
Ellen Tracy label, pairs tube tops or halters with hip-riding pants
and skirts.
</P>
<P>
   Don't want to join the navel show? Close the gap with a longer
top, and pull the drawstring in at the waist, instead of the hips.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-03-25-99 1406EST &QL; 
