state newspaper called the operation a ``dangerous precedent of
naked aggression.'' By Erik Eckholm.
</P>
<P>
   EUROPEAN-UNION (Berlin) _ European Union winds up summit
intended to resolve budget disputes and pave way for enlargement.
By Roger Cohen.
</P>
<P>
   COLOMBIA-VIOLENCE (Quito, Ecuador) _ For more than three
decades, Colombia has been forced to endure a conflict in which
both sides regarded the civilian population as targets. But now, as
a result of recent developments in Colombia and in neighboring
countries, there are signs that the scope of the strife is
widening. By Larry Rohter.
</P>
<P>
   BOLIVIA-CAR-BLESSINGS (Copacabana, Bolivia) _ They drive from
all over Bolivia, Peru and even northern Argentina to this remote
town on the shore of Lake Titicaca _ taxi drivers, truck drivers
and other motorists seeking a priest's blessings for protection
against drunken drivers, landslides, bad brakes and broken axles.
By Clifford Krauss.
</P>
<P>
   CUBA-BASEBALL (Havana) _ A look at Cuba and baseball, from
inside the country, setting up Sunday's widely anticipated
exhibition game between the Baltimore Orioles and the Cuban
national team. By James McKinley.
</P>
<P>
   &UR; NATIONAL &LR;  &QL;
</P>
<P>
   NUCLEAR-WASTE (Sante Fe, N.M.) _ After 25 years, hundreds of
studies, countless hearings and innumerable protests, the U.S.
Department of Energy loaded a truck with radioactive waste
Wednesday and prepared to send it to an underground dump in
southern New Mexico's salt beds. The rig will travel from Los
Alamos National Laboratory, birthplace of the atomic bomb, to the
$1.8 billion Waste Isolation Pilot Plant near Carlsbad. By James
Brooke.
</P>
<P>
   KEVORKIAN (Pontiac, Mich.) _ Dr. Jack Kevorkian rested his
defense without witnesses Thursday after a judge refused to let him
call the widow and brother of the man he is accused of murdering;
case could go to the jury by Thursday afternoon. By Pam Belluck.
</P>
<P>
   &UR; WASHINGTON &LR;  &QL;
</P>
<P>
   BUDGET (Washington) _ The House is expected to vote on the
budget bill today; the Senate will debate the measure today, with a
vote expected Friday. By William Stevenson.
</P>
<P>
   NURSING-HOMES (Washington) _ President Clinton signs legislation
that prohibits nursing homes from evicting Medicaid patients, as
some have done (so they can take other patients who pay more than
Medicaid). By Robert Pear.
</P>
<P>
   &UR; SCIENCE &LR;  &QL;
</P>
<P>
   GAMMA-BURST (Undated) _ In January an explosion rated as the
largest since the big bang ripped across the universe, tripping
detectors on satellites and triggering telescopic observations from
earth. Now a series of papers being published in Science and Nature
are shedding light on some characteristics of this violent event
and what it might or might not have been. Among other things, it
appears now that the explosion was not a fireball but some kind of
directed beam, which means it was only about a hundredth as
powerful as originally estimated. Even then, however, it still
ranks as the most violent event in nature, more powerful than a
supernova. By John Noble Wilford.
</P>
<P>
   &UR; FINANCIAL &LR;  &QL;
</P>
<P>
   CHINA-TRADE (Washington) _ Developments in China's effort at
getting into the World Trade Organization. By David E. Sanger.
</P>
<P>
   POOR-BANKS (Undated) _ One family in eight nationwide has no
bank account, according to government estimates, despite laws in a
number of states requiring banks to offer low-cost accounts. By
Richard A. Oppel Jr.
</P>
<P>
   MICROSOFT-ANTITRUST (Washington) _ With Bill Gates in town, the
Justice Department and state attorneys general react to Microsoft's
settlement proposal. By Joel Brinkley.
</P>
<P>
   DIABETES-DRUG (Undated) _ A look at the diabetes drug market, in
which one drug, Rezulin from Warner-Lambert, is about to be run
over. By David J. Morrow.
</P>
<P>
   MORGAN-STANLEY (New York) _ Morgan Stanley Dean Witter reported
its operating earnings soared 50 percent in the first quarter to a
record $1.037 billion, as global markets improved and its
securities businesses surged. By Joseph Kahn.
</P>
<P>
   ERICSSON-QUALCOMM (Undated) _ Ending a long-running feud,
Ericsson and Qualcomm settle a patent litigation dispute and
potentially clear the way for a universal global standard for the
next generation of wireless technology. By Seth Schiesel.
</P>
