<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-CPT-WEEKLY-BUDGET-NYT </SLUG>
  
<TEXT>
<P>
   EDITORS, attention features, technology page editors:
</P>
<P>
   Here is a list of selected computer-related stories from the
past week from  &UR; The N.Y. Times News Service &LR;  and its partners.
</P>
<P>
   These stories are being repeated with a distinguishing ``CPT''
in the slugline and an ``a'' general news category code.
</P>
<P>
   Similar stories that were in Thursday's New York Times were
listed on  &UR; BC-CIRCUITS-BUDGET-NYT &LR; , which moved Thursday afternoon.
</P>
<P>
   BC-MICROSOFT-ANTITRUST-NYT (Washington) _ The way the Justice
Department sees it, if Microsoft Corp. and the government are to
begin talks to settle the antitrust suit now at issue in federal
court here, Microsoft will have to make the first move. So far,
that has not happened. By Joel Brinkley.
</P>
<P>
   BC-INTERNET-GAMBLING-HNS (Washington) _ Under pressure from
state law enforcement officials, lawmakers on Tuesday renewed a
push to enact legislation that would ban gambling over the
Internet. Internet gambling is estimated to be a $600 million per
year business and is growing. By Jennifer Corbett Dooren. (Hearst
Newspapers).
</P>
<P>
   BC-ONLINE-PRIVACY-NYT (Washington) _ On Monday, a nonprofit
watchdog group founded to monitor online privacy policies scolded
but declined to pursue an audit of one of its biggest donors,
Microsoft Corp. It was an awkward decision, both because of
Microsoft's contributions to the group, TRUSTe, and because it
comes at a crucial point in negotiations between the United States
and the European Union over whether companies can effectively
police themselves in cyberspace. By Jeri Clausing.
</P>
<P>
   BC-GATES-BOOK-CHAMELEON-NYT (Washington) _ Which is the real
Bill Gates? Is it the author who insists, in his new book,
``Business (AT) the Speed of Thought,'' that all interoffice
communications should flow ``over e-mail so workers can act on news
with reflex-like speed''? Or is it the witness who testified in the
government's antitrust case against his company that he could not
remember dozens of e-mail messages he wrote or received in recent
years, dismissing one long internal message full of market data, by
saying ``I don't know what we're talking about'' and ``I mean, who
knows?'' By Joel Brinkley.
</P>
<P>
   BC-SOFTWARE-FOR-GIRLS-NYT (San Francisco) _ Small and unknown,
Purple Moon faced an unforgiving battle for shelf space with Mattel
as it sought and failed to make a viable business out of computer
games for girls _ titles that in contrast to current top-sellers,
were not about eyeshadow selection, nail-polish tricks or
adventures around the pressing question, ``Where's Ken?'' By Amy
Harmon.
</P>
<P>
   BC-COMPUTER-BRIEF-NYT (Undated) _ New evidence that the rise of
electronic commerce is a wave, not a bubble, comes from Odyssey, a
market research firm. By Steve Lohr.
</P>
<P>
   BC-INDUSTRIAL-DESIGN-NYT (Undated) _ Without question, this has
been the decade in which software moved, big time, into the
industrial designer's world. It was just a matter of time before
engineers would aim their computers at designing and refining the
assembly lines on which products are made. By Claudia H. Deutsch.
</P>
<P>
   BC-PRIVACY-MARKETPLACE-NYT (Undated) _ Novell hopes its new
Internet technology, called Digital Me, will gain acceptance as a
standard means of controlling identity on the World Wide Web,
permitting network users to reveal or retain as much personal
information as they wish. By John Markoff.
</P>
<P>
   BC-MICROSOFT-SETTLEMENT-BLOOM (Washington) _ Microsoft Corp. has
signaled the U.S. Justice Department it is willing to discuss a
settlement of the landmark antitrust suit, according to people
familiar with the case. By James Rowley.
</P>
<P>
   BC-CYBERCROOKS-HNS (Washington) _ The Internet has provided a
new tool for stock schemes and its fast-moving technology is making
the scams more widespread and making it harder for state and
federal authorities to keep pace. By Jennifer Corbett Dooren.
</P>
<P>
   BC-APPLE-SOFTWARE-HNS (San Francisco) _ The computer industry
welcomed Apple Computer Inc.'s decision to give away the software
coding for its new Macintosh server operating system. By Wendy
Tanaka.
</P>
<P>
   BC-COMPUTER-SNAFU-REVIEW-NYT (Undated) _ Computer glitches are a
pain, but they can be especially embarrassing when they strike an
American institution of higher learning. Consider the following
form letter from Arizona State University, in which a prospective
student's Social Security number was inadvertently substituted for
his name.
</P>
<P>
   BC-COMPUTER-COLUMN-AZR (Phoenix) _ PHOENIX - Back in February,
we ran a list of your favorite Web sites for 1998. If you missed
the list, it can still be found at
www.azcentral.com/computing/viewpoint/0215hoyewebsites.shtml. The
idea of creating such a list proved so popular with readers, that I
continued to receive recommendations long after the submission
deadline. By David Hoye.
</P>
</TEXT>
