<HEADLINE>
SIMULATORS TAKE WORLD WAR II DOGFIGHTS TO NEW HEIGHTS 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients.)  
 By MATT BEER  
 c.1999 San Francisco Examiner  
<TEXT>
<P>
   SAN FRANCISCO _ When Mitch Varner isn't writing instruction
manuals for Silicon Valley software companies, he's usually trying
to shake a couple of Focke-Wulfs off of his tail, hoping he makes a
friendly runway, as oily smoke pours from his wounded P-38
Lightning.
</P>
<P>
   ``It really gets the juices flowing,'' said Varner, 38. ``It
puts you in the mood to attack the rest of your life.''
</P>
<P>
   Varner is talking ``European Air War,'' just one of a growing
number of World War II computer flight simulators that have been
gathering more shelf space at software stores and finding their way
onto the computers of an audience that normally shuns computer
gaming.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's definitely a growing category,'' said Christian Svensson,
editor and chief executive of MCV, a Redwood City-based gaming
trade magazine. ``It's pulling in people who wouldn't normally play
`Quake' or `Doom.'''
</P>
<P>
   The draw of these computer games, which immerse a user in a 3-D
world battling Messerschmitts and Mustangs, is their ability to
re-create, at least for a home computer pilot, the heart-pounding
experience that seems be lost in the more popular modern jet
fighter simulations.
</P>
<P>
   Games such as ``Falcon,'' a best-selling, complex F-16 simulator
that contains some of the same technology used in real fighter jet
simulators, are really an exercise in cockpit information control.
In the World War II games, on the other hand, propeller-driven
fighters approximate the twisting and turning agony of a dogfight
over 1940s Europe.
</P>
<P>
   ``You don't really fight in `Falcon,''' said James Lynn, a vice
president of computer gaming research at Los Angeles-based Wedbush
Morgan Securities. ``The enemy is a blip on the screen. With these
WWII simulators, the planes are slower, you get closer to your
enemy. You really get the feeling like you're in combat.''
</P>
<P>
   Also contributing to the computer dogfighting trend, said Lynn,
is Hollywood's renewed infatuation with World War II, evidenced by
the release last year of ``Saving Private Ryan'' and ``Thin Red
Line.''
</P>
<P>
   ``Anytime you have some kind of craze on the movie screen, you
get a similar interest in related computer gaming titles,'' Lynn
said. ``People want to continue the experience they have in the
theater.''
</P>
<P>
   Here is a run-down on some of the games:
</P>
<P>
   _ Combat Flight Simulator: This program is based on the
venerable Microsoft Flight Simulator program. But instead of
bringing in Cessnas on an instrument landing, you can drop
Spitfires into the River Thames.
</P>
<P>
   The program excels in its customization abilities, letting you
reduce the difficulty to a simple, arcade-like level. The ground
effects are rich, though they can slow down game play.
</P>
<P>
   _ WWII Fighters: This is one tough simulation game. While you
can dial down the difficulty, the fighting doesn't get good until
you've invested several hours in training.
</P>
<P>
   The planes stall easily, and turning them around in the heat of
battle can actually seem like heavy lifting. The cockpit interiors
are hyper-realistic, and damage graphics _ like bullet holes and
flaming explosions _ are uncomfortably authentic. And ground
targets are chilling: You can actually send deer scattering in the
woods with a low pass.
</P>
<P>
   There also is a ton of auxiliary content in the program,
including a virtual aircraft museum and video interviews with
veteran fighter aces. This is the game to get if you have a lot of
free time.
</P>
<P>
   _ European Air War: This is the best of the three as far as
simply getting up there and dogfighting, and it strikes a good
balance between authenticity and ease of use. The battles against
computer-generated airplanes are dizzying scrums.
</P>
<P>
   Among the game's highlights are the giant bomber squadrons that
power through the theater of play. Whether defending the formation
or picking off the strays, they form one of the more incredible
sights I've ever seen on a computer monitor.
</P>
<P>
   _ Joysticks: Microsoft's Sidewinder Force Feedback Pro and
Logitech's WingMan Force have the ability to give you physical
feedback while you're flying.
</P>
<P>
   Fire a gun, the stick jiggles in your hand. Crash, it gyrates
wildly. Get hit, you have to provide more force to get the plane to
maneuver. Very slick.
</P>
<P>
   Microsoft's stick was responsive, and you could twist it to get
control of a plane's rudder, allowing you to fine-tune the gun
sight to get a more accurate shot. Logitech's Wingman Force
excelled because it would immediately snap a plane into a roll.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
