<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-COX-BOOKNOTES25 </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    `Gump' author makes room for Pancho Villa
 &HT;    By Don O'Briant
 &HT;    c. 1999 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   Reading Winston Groom's books is like eating a box of assorted
chocolates: You never know what you're going to get. Fans of
``Forrest Gump'' were surprised by his next book, ``Shrouds of
Glory,'' a history of the South's last major Civil War offensive.
There was a Gump sequel, ``Gump &AMP; Co.,'' but then the Alabama
writer followed that with ``Such a Pretty, Pretty Girl'' (Random
House, $23.95), a Raymond Chandler-type mystery about a beautiful
Los Angeles television anchorwoman who's being blackmailed.
</P>
<P>
   And that novel was simply a diversion from his big book in
progress, ``In Fields Where They Lay,'' a sweeping saga about
Pancho Villa and the kidnapping of a wealthy American's two
children in 1916.
</P>
<P>
   Groom says he is happy with ``Such a Pretty, Pretty Girl''
despite several negative reviews, but his heart clearly is in the
Pancho Villa saga.
</P>
<P>
   The novel is based on a true story about the Mexican
revolutionary's kidnapping of a wealthy American's two children.
When President Woodrow Wilson refuses to do anything, the father
takes matters into his own hands.
</P>
<P>
   ``The mix of characters is wonderful,'' says Groom, 55.
``Ambrose Bierce was down there. B. Traven, the guy who wrote `The
Treasure of the Sierra Madre' was there. Tom Mix, the cowboy actor,
was down there as an aide to Pancho Villa. So if you weave all
these characters in along with the manhunt all through the Sierra
Madres, it's going to be a big tale. It's a lot of fun, but there's
so much reading I have to do. I've got 280 pages (written) and it's
only about half done.''
</P>
<P>
   As for Forrest Gump, Groom doesn't foresee any more installments
unless the movie sequel is as successful as the first. ``They're
writing the screenplay now and they're trying to reassemble
everybody who worked on the original, from the cameraman to the guy
who did the music. If they succeed, who knows what will happen? I
think I'm finished with Gump, but never say never.''
</P>
<P>
   &QR;  Into the woods: Nevada Barr's fictional sleuth Anna Pigeon is
a forest ranger, but her mysteries are no walk in the park. Whether
they are set on Georgia's Cumberland Island (``Endangered
Species'') or in New Mexico's Carlsbad Caverns National Park
(``Blind Descent''), somebody always dies violently.
</P>
<P>
   Her latest work, ``Liberty Falling'' (Putnam, $23.95), is no
exception. Set on Liberty Island, Ellis Island and Manhattan
Island, the mystery pits Anna against a deranged killer determined
to eliminate anyone who is not a ``real'' American. Part of the
backdrop is an abandoned 19th-century hospital that's now covered
with vines. ``It's a perfect place for a crime,'' Barr says.
</P>
<P>
   A native of Nevada who lives in Clinton, Miss., Barr, 47, did
not intend to become a writer. Originally, she aspired to be an
actress and performed in several off-Broadway shows in New York. By
age 36, though, she realized she had reached her limits as an
actress and took a job as a park ranger.
</P>
<P>
   During a tour of duty in the Guadalupe Mountains of Texas, Barr
conceived the idea of Anna Pigeon. Barr worked in each of the parks
in which her novels have been set. ``Track of the Cat'' was in the
Guadalupe Mountains, ``A Superior Death'' took place in Isle Royale
National Park in Michigan, and ``Firestorm'' was in Lassen Volcanic
National Park in California. Her next novel will be set on
Mississippi's Natchez Trace.
</P>
<P>
   Like her protagonist, Barr has fought fires, flown planes and
hiked through wilderness areas. Unlike Anna, she didn't get to
solve any murders when she was a ranger. ``Most of my time was
spent writing tickets and saving visitors from themselves.''
</P>
<P>
   Barr will sign her novel at 6 p.m. Monday at the Science Fiction
&AMP; Mystery Bookshop, 2000-F Cheshire Bridge Road N.E. 404-634-3226.
</P>
<P>
   &QR;  The Big Prize: American writers Don DeLillo (``Underworld''),
Francisco Goldman (``The Ordinary Seaman'') and Cynthia Ozick
(``The Puttermesser Papers'') are among the eight worldwide
nominees for the Impac Dublin Literary Award. The $150,000 award,
given for a work of fiction published in the English language, is
the world's richest literary prize. Other nominees are Ian McEwan
(``Enduring Love''); Andrew Miller (``Ingenious Pain''); Haruki
Murakami (``The Wind-Up Bird Chronicle''); Jim Crace
(``Quarantine''); and Bernard Schlink (``The Reader''). Winners
will be announced May 17 in Dublin.
</P>
<P>
   E-mail: dobriant(at)ajc.com
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
