A3869 &Cx1f; ttj-z
r a &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-CATHOLIC-PROTEST-HNS &LR;      03-25 0290
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-CATHOLIC-PROTEST-HNS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
CATHOLIC CHURCH WON'T INDULGE THESE SISTERS 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients.)  
 c.1999 San Francisco Examiner  
<TEXT>
<P>
   SAN FRANCISCO _ Through 20 years of street theater and social
activism, the Sisters of Perpetual Indulgence have never been the
type to duck controversy.
</P>
<P>
   The group of 30 people representing homosexuals, bisexuals and
heterosexuals who dress up as nuns _ assuming names like Sister
Helen A. Handbasket and Sister Reyna Terror _ has raised the ire of
Catholic Church officials with its plans to hold a 20th anniversary
party in San Francisco on Easter.
</P>
<P>
   The event will feature a bonnet competition, gay performers,
information booths and a ``Hunky Jesus'' contest for the
best-looking Jesus costume.
</P>
<P>
   After the city Board of Supervisors approved a plan to block off
Castro Street for the party, a San Francisco Catholic Archdiocese
spokesman called it tantamount to allowing a group of neo-Nazis to
close a street on Passover.
</P>
<P>
   But members of the group vow to party on.
</P>
<P>
   ``We are not backing down,'' said Ken Bunch, a founding member
of the group. ``The whole reason we celebrate on Easter is not
because it's a Christian holy day. It's our anniversary.''
</P>
<P>
   The ``sisters'' got their start on Easter of 1979, when they
used a set of nuns' habits acquired from a convent in Iowa _ they
told the real nuns they wanted to stage ``The Sound of Music'' _ to
dress up in drag. Just for fun.
</P>
<P>
   ``It was so electric,'' Bunch said.
</P>
<P>
   Along with appearing in the city's gay pride parades and other
community events, members of the group have organized AIDS
benefits, handed out free condoms, visited AIDS hospices and
spearheaded anti-gay-bashing campaigns.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
