<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-03-25 14:51 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A3894 &Cx1f; tad-z
u v &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-SPOT-BJT26-COX     03-25 0876
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-SPOT-BJT26-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    The Cox News Service spot news budget for XXXday, XXX. XX, 1999.
 &HT;    c.1999 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   Photo and graphics information and editors' names can be found
at the end of this budget.
</P>
<P>
   INTERNATIONAL
</P>
<P>
   KOSOVO-STRIKES _ AVIANO AIR FORCE BASE, Italy or WASHINGTON _
U.S.-led NATO forces are expected to begin a second day of bombing
of Serb military targets in an effort to force Yugoslav President
Slobodan Milosevic to accept a peace plan with the Kosovar
Albanians. Developing. (Deans-Holmes, Cox News Service)
</P>
<P>
   KOSOVO-B2 _ WASHINGTON _ This is the maiden combat mission for
the B-2 stealth bomber. What's the story behind this $2.1 billion
aircraft? What was the catalyst that finally brought it into combat
after 11 years? Developing. (Shepard, Cox News Service)
</P>
<P>
   KOSOVO-B2-BOX _ WASHINGTON _ The vital statistics on the B-2
Spirit long-range stealth bomber. Developing. (Shepard, Cox News
Service).
</P>
<P>
   KOSOVO-CLARK _ WASHINGTON _ Supreme NATO Commander Wesley Clark
is a guy who looked down the hatch at his friends burned alive
after their APC tumbled over Mt. Igman outside Sarajevo in August
1995. The reason they were on the mountain at all was that the
Serbs wouldn't grant safe passage to Clark _ then the military
attache on a diplomatic mission headed by U.S. Sepcial Envoy
Richard Holbrooke _ that would have allowed them to travel by
helicopter. In other words, Clark _ who negotiated, if that's the
word for it _ the military occupation annex to the Dayton accords _
has a long and unhappy relationship with Milosevic. He's far
closer, though, to his fellow Arkansan and Oxford scholar, Bill
Clinton. (Deans, Cox News Service)
</P>
<P>
   KOSOVO-CLARK-BIOBOX _ WASHINGTON _ A biobox on NATO Supreme
Allied Commander Gen. Wesley Clark. (Deans, Cox News Service).
</P>
<P>
   WASHINGTON
</P>
<P>
   GATES _ WASHINGTON _ Microsoft Chairman Bill Gates and state
attorneys general with a stake in the Microsoft antitrust case are
in Washington. Gates is in town to tout his book,''Business (at)
The Speed of Thought'' at Georgetown University. The attorneys
general apparently are going to talk about a proposed settlement
offer by Microsoft. (Glass, Cox News Service). WITH PHOTO.
</P>
<P>
   TUTU _ WASHINGTON _ Archbishop Desmond Tutu will come to the
Hill to engage in a conversation about race at the invitation of
Faith &AMP; Politics, the group headed by Rep. John Lewis. The lunch is
Thursday around noon. (Carr, Cox News Service).
</P>
<P>
   NATIONAL
</P>
<P>
   ADAMS-BUSH _ AUSTIN, Texas _ George W. Bush says he didn't grow
up wanting to be president. Neither did the only son of a president
who grew up to be president. Hell, the job didn't even exist until
John Quincy Adams was 22 years old. A look at the life and failed
presidency of J.Q. Adams, a man whose accomplishment GWBush is
trying to match. (Herman, Austin American-Statesman)
</P>
<P>
   JASON _ WEST PALM BEACH, Fla. _ Once he played Jason in ``Friday
the 13th, Part 2,'' victimizing hapless teens. But F. Warrington
Gillet III, the actor behind Jason, says he's a victim now _ and
he's pointing a finger at a Fort Lauderdale law firm that he says
cheated him, and his Palm Beach friends, out of millions. (Clough,
Palm Beach Post)
</P>
<P>
   VOUCHERS _ The Florida Legislature was expected to vote next
week on Gov. Jeb's school voucher program. It's a limited program
that would allow vouchers only in districts where schools are
chronically underperforming, and at this point only a couple of
schools around the entire state might qualify. But it would be
precedent-setting in the South. Depending on when they take this
up, we either advance the vote or cover it. (MWilliams, Atlanta
Journal-Constitution) TENTATIVE
</P>
<P>
   COXNET BUDGET INFORMATION FOR SUBSCRIBERS OF THE NYT NEWS
SERVICE
</P>
<P>
   Spot news budgets move daily at 2 p.m. and 6 p.m. Eastern.
Additionally, separate features and commentary budgets move at 10
a.m., and sports and business budgets at 6 p.m. Additional updates
are possible if news developments warrant.
</P>
<P>
   All times are Eastern unless otherwise noted. If stories will
move after 8 p.m., an ETA will be given.
</P>
