<HEADER>
A3911 &Cx1f; ttc-z
r e &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-CELEBRITY-EDTV-LADN     03-25 1177
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-CELEBRITY-EDTV-LADN </SLUG>
 
RON HOWARD, CAST HAVE EXPERIENCED `EDtv' FOR REAL 
(For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By GLENN WHIPP 
c.1999 Los Angeles Daily News  
<TEXT>
<P>
   LOS ANGELES _ &UR;  &LR; Twenty-odd years ago, while on hiatus from
``Happy Days,'' Ron Howard was bumping around Texas, scouting
locations for a television movie he planned to direct. Hungry, he
and some friends stopped in at an old-fashioned cafeteria where
they feasted on fried chicken, vegetables and pie. Howard, who has
been famous almost since the day of his birth, signed several
autographs and posed for a few pictures, routine stuff for the
popular star.
</P>
<P>
   ``Then something a little different happened,'' Howard says. ``I
was getting up with my tray to leave, and these people came running
after me and said, `Can we ask one more favor?' And I said, `Sure,'
thinking they wanted another picture. Instead, they asked, `Can we
have your chicken bones?' And, well, what could I say, but,
`Absolutely, you can have my chicken bones.' ''
</P>
<P>
   ``And I wonder,'' Howard muses, ``if those chicken bones still
exist somewhere ... Something tells me no.''
</P>
<P>
   The fact that he's not sure, much less still pondering the
question, makes Howard an ideal person to tackle the nature of
celebrity and all of its strange side effects. Howard's new movie,
``EDtv,'' does just that, working as sort of ``The Truman Show'' in
reverse. A white-trash slacker named Ed (Matthew McConaughey)
volunteers to have every aspect of his life documented for a
round-the-clock television show and becomes a media sensation in
the process.
</P>
<P>
   The spotlight soon shines on Ed's family and girlfriend, Shari
(Jenna Elfman), who suffer harsh scrutiny, fickle fans and public
opinion polls that border on the inhumane. (Should Ed dump Shari?
Vote now!'')
</P>
<P>
   The film humorously comments on our insatiable fascination with
the private, mixing in elements of MTV's ``The Real World,'' Albert
Brooks' ``Real Life'' and the famous 1970s PBS documentary on the
Loud family.
</P>
<P>
   Comparisons to ``The Truman Show'' are inevitable as well, but
``EDtv'' actually is more reminiscent of Howard's own
``Parenthood'' in the affectionate way it looks at family foibles.
Both movies were written by Lowell Ganz and Babaloo Mandel, who
also collaborated with Howard on ``Splash'' and ``Night Shift.''
</P>
<P>
   ``The tone of `The Truman Show' is completely different, which,
I must say, was a complete relief,'' says Howard, who saw the Jim
Carrey movie with his wife last year as he was putting the
finishing touches on ``EDtv.'' ``Certainly, this film is about fame
and the double-edged sword of celebrity. That's a given. But I love
playing with the myth of the functional family, too, because I
don't think it exists. We're all nuts, and I love showing that in
movies.''
</P>
<P>
   Offers writer Mandel: ``Enough about `The Truman Show.' It
wasn't an audience-friendly movie like this is. It left me cold.''
</P>
<P>
   Howard and his longtime producing partner Brian Grazer
intentionally cast the film using actors with intense experiences
in the spotlight's white glare, giving the film yet another level
of subtext in its look at fame. It's impossible to watch Ellen
DeGeneres (playing a TV executive) giving the finger to her network
executive bosses without thinking of her highly publicized battles
with the ABC brass over her sitcom, ``Ellen.'' (``I think she
enjoyed that scene,'' Howard says smiling.)
</P>
<P>
   Likewise, McConaughey's sudden rise to fame in 1995 (Vanity Fair
put him on the cover before his first big movie, ``A Time to
Kill,'' opened in theaters) neatly parallels Ed's instant
notoriety. ``Matthew's story is really Ed's story,'' says co-star
Sally Kirkland, who plays Ed's befuddled mother. Adds co-star
Martin Landau (Ed's stepfather): ``I think it's very courageous for
him to do this film because the material hits so close to home.''
</P>
<P>
   For his part, McConaughey brushes off such talk of courage but
doesn't deny the fact that instant celebrity made his life
infinitely more complicated.
</P>
<P>
   ``I remember the Friday the movie (`A Time to Kill') came out in
theaters, and I was walking down the Third Street Promenade in
Santa Monica with a thousand other people, all of whom were
completely oblivious to me,'' McConaughey says. ``Monday afternoon,
I'm walking down the same street, and 999 out of 1,000 are staring
at me. I was a little more self-conscious off the bat, but mostly I
was thinking, `OK. This is pretty cool.'''
</P>
<P>
   ``And I still think that,'' McConaughey continues, ``although it
can get a little much sometimes, where you let the fame control you
instead of you controlling it. Mostly, you just learn to choose
your battles and have fun with it.''
</P>
<P>
   Other cast members bring their own peculiar baggage to their
roles. Elizabeth Hurley has endured the snipes of British tabloids
for years and famously went through the wringer when police caught
her boyfriend Hugh Grant with a prostitute. Woody Harrelson has
taken flak for his political activism; DeGeneres for her outspoken
homosexuality. And on a slightly less profound note, Elfman took
some heat for her spiky hairstyle at the recent Golden Globes.
</P>
<P>
   ``It was amazing how many people were angry _ I loved it!''
Elfman says. ``But then I think, `If people were more literate and
were reading books, they would have more to think about than what I
am doing with my hair.'''
</P>
<P>
   Producer Grazer agrees, but he doesn't think we'll be seeing a
run on library cards any time soon. And in a way, he wouldn't want
that. It would probably mean less business for his movies.
</P>
<P>
   ``Celebrity has had the mystery taken out of it during the past
decade,'' Grazer says. ``There's so much media accessibility now
that the public thinks they know you. I've seen drunk guys come up
to Ron and ask him to come over to their tables and kiss their
wives. I've been with Tom Hanks, standing in line for takeout, and
heard women say, `Can I go out with you?' Completely serious. And
Tom says, `Um ... don't you know? I've got a wife and kids.'''
</P>
<P>
   Howard believes such episodes are inevitable and, like bad
reviews, part of the deal you make when you go into show business.
</P>
<P>
   ``Of course, you don't imagine that going in,'' he says. ``It's
like when I was making `Apollo 13' and talking to the men who had
walked on the moon. They tried like hell to explain it to me, but
they couldn't. It's the same thing with fame. It's impossible to
communicate exactly what it's like.''
</P>
<P>
   And that's saying something because Howard, who still gets
called Opie and Richie _ and Opie Cunningham (``Eddie Murphy coined
that one,'' he says) _ has spent his whole life thinking about the
subject.
</P>
<P>
   ``I still feel a little strange when somebody asks for an
autograph,'' he says. ``And every once in a while, somebody will
kind of sum up my career in a sentence or two, like, `Hey, Opie,
have you seen the Fonz? You did a good job directing `Apollo 13.'
</P>
<P>
   ``But I take it as a compliment,'' he continues good-naturedly.
``At least they've been paying attention.'' &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-03-25-99 1507EST &QL; 
