<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-03-25 15:10 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A3919 &Cx1f; ttc-z
r e &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-RUGRATS-LIVE-LADN     03-25 0805
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-RUGRATS-LIVE-LADN </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
BIGGER-THAN-LIFE `RUGRATS' STAND BY THEIR FRIENDS
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients)  
(``Tonight'' refers to Friday, March 26)  
By NANCY HEWITT  
 c.1999 Los Angeles Daily News  
<TEXT>
<P>
   LOS ANGELES _ First they had their own TV show. Then they became
movie stars. Now those adorable darlings, the Rugrats, have taken
over the musical stage.
</P>
<P>
   The fame of those irrepressible babies who share their pint-size
view of the world on an animated weekday TV series continues to
grow.
</P>
<P>
   ``Rugrats: A Live Adventure'' comes to the Universal
Amphitheatre for six days beginning tonight. A special performance
to benefit the Children Affected by AIDS Foundation was held
Thursday night.
</P>
<P>
   The theme of the 1}-hour production is simple: Friends stand by
friends. When Chuckie Finster gets really scared by a thunder
storm, Tommy Pickles decides to ``imbent something for my bestest
friend that'll make things not so scary!''
</P>
<P>
   The end result is a People-ator _ a machine that brings
inanimate objects to life. Tommy tests the People-ator on some
tools, they come alive _ and the adventures begin.
</P>
<P>
   But putting together a stage show didn't happen overnight.
</P>
<P>
   For almost five years, Jonathan Hochwald, executive producer and
president of PACE Entertainment Inc., has worked with Nickelodeon
using his expertise as a Broadway and rock 'n' roll tour producer
to develop a show that would translate to the stage. ``Nickelodeon
has a hipness with what kids want,'' he says.
</P>
<P>
   But choosing a kids' show that could work on stage was tough.
After considering some possibilities, they took a leap of faith and
decided on ``Rugrats.'' ``It's the best possible show for kids.
It's very theatrical,'' Hochwald says. ``It's been on the air since
1991 and continues to grow. But the biggest challenge was to take a
two-dimensional show on the small screen and make it
three-dimensional on stage.''
</P>
<P>
   Since most kids have never seen a live show, he continues, ``the
goal was to create a new kind of live theatrical experience'' for
them. One that ``would speak to kids.''
</P>
<P>
   Watching 6-foot-2-inch babies on stage is believable and makes
sense to the younger audiences. ``(The Rugrats are)
larger-than-life characters and the audience accepts them,''
Hochwald says.
</P>
<P>
   The stage production also relies on the talents of Mark
Mothersbaugh, formerly of the '70s pop group Devo, and composer of
the music used on the Rugrats series.
</P>
<P>
   According to Hochwald, ``Mike has brought a Rugrats sound _ from
reggae to opera to disco. It crosses all genres. But the music
sounds true to Rugrats.''
</P>
<P>
   Mothersbaugh says he enjoys composing for children's TV. ``It's
less restrictive for me. (It's) not precensored by MTV,'' he says,
``and (I can) go into new territory with kids music because I'm not
looking for a hit.''
</P>
<P>
   Mothersbaugh has been composing for children's television for
about 10 years. He began his career creating music for ``Pee-Wee's
Playhouse.'' In preparing for the stage version of ``Rugrats,'' he
juggled both pacing and technical demands to keep the action
moving.
</P>
<P>
   ``When reading the script, I picked the logical places to place
the music to drive the story,'' he says. He also had to consider
how the music would affect the choreography and sets.
</P>
<P>
   But he is pleased with the selection of songs. In fact, he even
attended a show to gauge crowd reaction. ``Kids were singing songs
coming out of the matinee,'' he says proudly. ``It was a good
feeling.''
</P>
<P>
   Ideas for his songs come from odd sources, he reveals.
``Nightmares, bad food, stress _ everyday experiences,'' give him
inspiration. And he really enjoys the kid-show experience. ``What I
like is the kid is treated like a person instead of just like a
kid.''
</P>
<P>
   Mothersbaugh says youngsters will really like the songs. Judging
by the reactions he heard at the performance he attended, he
believes kids like the songs that go with the character they
identify with. ``If I Were Princess of the World' '' is Angelica's
song. And ``If I Could Count to Two'' shares the special friendship
of Tommy and Chuckie, he says.
</P>
<P>
   It took approximately four months to put the musical part of the
show together. But it was well worth it, he says. ``It's great to
watch a show with young kids. It's their first time seeing a live
show.'' &QL; 
 &QL; 
 &QL; 
INFORMATION: &UR;  &QL; 
The  &LR; production &UR; : &LR;  ``Rugrats: A Live Adventure.'' &UR;  &QL; 
The stars: &LR;  Angelica Pickles, Chuckie Finster, Susie Carmichael,
Tommy Pickles, Phil and Lil DeVille, Reptar. &UR;  &QL; 
Behind the scenes: &LR;  Directed and choreographed by Danny Herman. &UR;  &QL; 
Running time: &LR;  One hour, 45 minutes. &QL; 
Where &UR; : &LR;  Universal Amphitheatre. &QL; 
How much: $20, $28 and $33. &QL; 
Performance times: 7:15 tonight; 11:15 a.m., 3:15 p.m. and 7:15
p.m. Saturday and Sunday; 7:15 p.m. Monday, Tuesday and Wednesday. &QL;
</P>
