<SLUG> BC-HERBICIDE-HUMANS-HNS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
GROUP SAYS HIGHWAY HERBICIDES POSE HEALTH RISK 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients.)  
 By TYCHE HENDRICKS  
 c.1999 San Francisco Examiner  
<TEXT>
<P>
   SAN FRANCISCO _ Herbicide sprayed along roadsides may be
threatening public health and the environment, according to an
environmental group that tracks chemical use in California.
</P>
<P>
   The California Department of Transportation, or Caltrans, and
county agencies last year sprayed roadsides with more than 132,000
gallons of liquid and 93,000 pounds of solid chemical weed killers,
some of which may cause cancer and birth defects, according to a
report by Californians for Alternatives to Toxics.
</P>
<P>
   ``We wouldn't drive our cars into an agricultural field while it
was being sprayed,'' said Patricia Clary, the organization's
executive director, ``but Caltrans and the county road agencies
spray along these incredibly heavily used public facilities: our
roads. They don't warn us and we have to drive right through it.''
</P>
<P>
   Caltrans contends that the chemicals are necessary to keep down
brush that can become a fire hazard and weeds that crack pavement
and obscure visibility for drivers. In addition, said Caltrans
spokesman Greg Bayol, the state transportation agency has strict
safety standards for how the herbicides are applied.
</P>
<P>
   ``I would be more concerned about my next door neighbor than I
would be about Caltrans,'' he said. ``We use herbicides in the
safest possible manner. You can go into a hardware store and buy
stuff that's much more potent than what we use.''
</P>
<P>
   The study by Californians for Alternatives to Toxics found that
Los Angeles, Orange and Contra Costa counties had the highest
concentrations of herbicides used.
</P>
<P>
   Henry Clark, director of the West County Toxics Coalition in
Richmond, said Contra Costa residents were so concerned about toxic
releases from the county's numerous oil refineries that the issue
of herbicides was overlooked.
</P>
<P>
   ``The report is of concern to me in terms of the exposure people
would have living near the freeways that are sprayed,'' he said.
``I'm especially worried about children, who are much more
vulnerable to chemicals than adults.''
</P>
<P>
   Clary, who has also studied chemical use in California's
agriculture and timber industries, said the use of herbicides by
Caltrans is small in contrast, but still potentially dangerous.
</P>
<P>
   Five of Caltrans' eight most frequently-used weed killers have
been listed as possible cancer agents by the U.S. Environmental
Protection Agency, Clary said.
</P>
<P>
   Clary said she was very concerned about spraying around school
bus stops and in sensitive watersheds, especially near drinking
water reservoirs.
</P>
<P>
   Bayol countered that the poisons Caltrans uses breakdown into
harmless, inert ingredients, and thus pose no health hazard.
</P>
<P>
   ``They've developed pesticides that are pretty tame, really, and
still can do what we need them to do,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   All the same, Caltrans has committed to reducing its herbicide
use, in response to pressure from Californians for Alternatives to
Toxics and other environmental groups.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
