<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-VETERAN-TEST-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
HALT ORDERED TO STUDIES AT LOS ANGELES VA CENTER
</HEADLINE>
  (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By DOLORES KONG  
 c.1999 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   In the most sweeping federal action ever taken against
violations of research rules, the US government is suspending all
studies at the nation's largest Veterans Affairs medical center, in
Los Angeles, where researchers have done experiments that worsened
the mentally ill, among other controversial studies.
</P>
<P>
   The joint action by the Department of Veterans Affairs and a
division of the National Institutes of Health means that more than
500 psychiatric and medical studies will be suspended, effective
Friday, until further notice.
</P>
<P>
   While the suspension order referred only to procedural
violations and not to the ethics of specific tests, the West Los
Angeles VA is among the facilities highlighted in a Globe series on
psychiatric research abuses in November, specifically for being
part of a 1987 study that gave amphetamines to the mentally ill to
induce psychosis in order to study the disease's biology.
</P>
<P>
   The facility has also been one of the key sites for
pharmaceutical industry-funded tests of potential new
antipsychotics in which some mentally ill patients were given a
dummy sugar pill, or a placebo, instead of medications known to
work. As a result of such placebo testing, up to 70 percent of
mentally ill patients enrolled in these studies in the United
States and Canada experienced such a worsening of their symptoms
that they dropped out of the research, according to a Globe review
of the scientific literature.
</P>
<P>
   ``So disabled veterans wind up as laboratory guinea pigs for
academic researchers, and the federal government has been
supporting, approving and funding and _ until now _ looking the
other way at the harmful consequences,'' said Vera Hassner Sharav,
co-founder of the New York-based Citizens for Responsible Care in
Psychiatry and Research.
</P>
<P>
   She credited the Globe series with helping to prompt these
developments, ``because it brought out the fact that the problem is
not a few, isolated, unrelated instances.'' Sharav Wednesday called
for an independent investigation of psychiatric research, at VA
hospitals and elsewhere, by the US Department of Justice.
</P>
<P>
   Dick Wannemacher, a disabled veteran and associate national
legislative director for Disabled American Veterans, said that
while he believes most VA research is properly conducted, the news
about the West Los Angeles VA raises concerns with him and his 1.1
million-member organization, ``that veterans could be put in
additional harm's way.''
</P>
<P>
   And while Wannemacher said he supports VA headquarters's actions
to suspend research there, ``we're saddened that this would have
been allowed to occur.''
</P>
<P>
   The suspension means that hundreds of researchers, many of them
affiliated with the University of California at Los Angeles, ``will
be unable to do their research until these issues are resolved,''
said Dr. Dean Norman, acting chief of staff at the West Los Angeles
VA, which is now known officially as the VA Greater Los Angeles
Healthcare System.
</P>
<P>
   In rare instances, however, where patients might be harmed if
research they are already enrolled in were abruptly halted, studies
would be allowed to continue with pre-approval.
</P>
<P>
   Norman stressed that the federal agencies have not documented
any harm to research subjects, only procedural problems. He added
that care for patients who are not in research will continue as
usual at the 1,056-bed center.
</P>
<P>
   ``First and foremost, I'd like to make the point that we're
confident that no patients or research animals have been harmed by
these administrative deficiencies. Second, we provide excellent
care to our patients,'' Norman said.
</P>
<P>
   In letters this week to the West Los Angeles VA and affiliated
research organizations, the NIH's Office for Protection from
Research Risks and VA headquarters did not identify any harm or
cite specific experiments, according to documents obtained by the
Globe.
</P>
<P>
   Instead, the focus was on repeated violations of US regulations
designed to protect research participants, which came after several
years of warnings that the agencies had given the West Los Angeles
VA.
</P>
<P>
   For instance, in its March 22 letter, OPRR found that the West
Los Angeles VA failed to include on its board for reviewing
psychiatric research a representative of people with mental
illness, as OPRR had required as far back as 1994.
</P>
<P>
   In an inspection of minutes from nine institutional review board
meetings held over a three-month period by the West Los Angeles VA
last year, OPRR found seven instances of meetings held without a
quorum, or without a non-scientist representative, such as an
ethicist, as required by federal regulations.
</P>
<P>
   As a result of these and other similar findings, OPRR suspended
the ability of the West Los Angeles VA and two affiliated research
organizations to conduct federally funded research on human
subjects, until all research projects have been reviewed by the
agency. OPRR has no authority over state or privately funded
research, a weakness in the regulatory system that has been
criticized before.
</P>
<P>
   But adding to the scope of the action against the West Los
Angeles VA is the VA headquarters's two-page memorandum, also dated
March 22, suspending all research activities no matter what the
funding source. The memo is signed by Dr. Kenneth W. Kizer,
undersecretary for health for the Department of Veterans Affairs.
</P>
<P>
   Dr. John R. Feussner, chief research and development officer for
the Department of Veterans Affairs, said Wednesday that VA
headquarters independently found some of the same concerns as
uncovered by OPRR, beginning as far back as 1997.
</P>
<P>
   ``We have found no evidence at all that any human research
participants have been harmed, or that animals have been harmed,''
said Feussner, adding that this is the first time the VA has ever
had take such action at one of its facilities.
</P>
<P>
   ``But given the process violations, we're concerned, and we're
not willing to wait,'' he said. ``We have to take action to prevent
harm.''
</P>
<P>
   There was no specific issue precipitating this action, Feussner
said. ``This is one of those situations where you don't have one
huge problem,'' but many small ones.
</P>
<P>
   ``The suspension will last until these problems are fixed to our
satisfaction. We hope to do that within the next 30 to 90 days,''
Feussner said. But because of the West Los Angeles VA's track
record, headquarters will probably not remove probationary status
for as long as a year, even if the suspension is lifted.
</P>
<P>
   Robert Aller _ whose son Gregory was enrolled in schizophrenia
research at UCLA, and who filed complaints with OPRR several years
ago about the research practices at the West Los Angeles VA and
elsewhere _ Wednesday said of the actions against the VA facility:
``They just apparently never cleaned it up.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
