<BODY>
<HEADLINE>
STUDENTS DEBATE OPENING JOURNAL TO ALL
</HEADLINE>
 BC - YALE-JOURNAL-BOS  (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By KATE ZERNIKE  
 c.1999 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   For 109 years, the Yale Law Journal has chosen the top students
to edit its pages, giving them the chance not only to set the
national legal debate but also to score the plummiest clerkships
and jobs.
</P>
<P>
   But now, amid complaints that membership has become too elitist,
students have launched a vigorous campaign to open up admission to
anyone who wants to join.
</P>
<P>
   It has set off a debate between excellence and inclusion at the
nation's top-ranked law school.
</P>
<P>
   Those fighting to change the process say membership at the
journal, published monthly during the school year, has become too
much a determinant of self-esteem and success; students who don't
make it on the staff believe they are automatically shut out of the
best jobs, and stigmatized among their classmates.
</P>
<P>
   The journal editors, though, defend the process as a matter of
standards. Students who edit the journal are choosing articles
written by prominent professors and scholars that can have national
influence; it only makes sense that those students would be chosen
with rigor. Competition is part of life, they say, and certainly
part of law school.
</P>
<P>
   The debate has been carried out on postings and petitions on
``The Wall,'' a free-speech bulletin board in the narrow main
corridor of the law school in New Haven.
</P>
<P>
   About 100 first-year students have signed a petition vowing to
boycott the competition for journal membership if the publication
does not agree to open up admissions. And at a meeting last week,
the editors of the review faced blistering criticism from law
students who accused them of being snobbish.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's a complete booster rocket for your legal career; that's
what makes it objectionable,'' said Wesley Kelman, a staff member
in his second year who unsuccessfully ran for president of the
journal last year on a platform of open admissions. ``People who
don't make it feel awful. It stigmatizes you with employers. If
employers want to look at grades, fine, but this shouldn't be an
exclusive thing at all.''
</P>
<P>
   Law review membership is highly coveted at any law school, but
even more so at the oldest and most prestigious schools. The Yale
Law Journal literally helped write the book on law reviews; the
so-called blue book, a thick guide that sets standards for
citations in legal publications, is published by the law reviews at
Yale, Harvard, Columbia, and the University of Pennsylvania.
</P>
<P>
   At Harvard, the oldest law review in the nation, admission is
based on grades. At Yale, the law school itself abandoned a grading
system years ago, trying to ease competition among students. So
journal membership is now based on a three-part test that students
take over a period of several weeks during the summer before their
second year. One part measures blue-book knowledge. The two other
parts ask students to read and edit three articles submitted by
professors and to choose one for publication, explaining their
reasons in a memo.
</P>
<P>
   Each test is graded by three law journal staff members. Journal
editors say that in each class of 180 law students, about 100 apply
for the journal and about half are accepted.
</P>
<P>
   But critics _ those who are on journal staffs as well as those
who were rejected _ argue it is not fair to have students
administering and grading a test that can ultimately turn into a
resume credential.
</P>
<P>
   Stories about journal membership's heavy influence on future job
offers abound. One student tells how a past journal editor was
named a clerk for the US Supreme Court the day she was named
editor; another tells how some judges categorically weed out any
resumes that don't include journal membership.
</P>
<P>
   ``Everyone at Yale is capable of doing the type of work the
journal requires,'' said Rohit Khanna, the first-year student who
started the petition. ``Having a test is creating an arbitrary
elite that is unnecessary. If you want to make the journal
prestigious, don't do it on a method that has subjective judgments.
My own preference is, don't have the prestige of the Yale Law
Journal. That way, it would no longer distinguish students in a job
interview, and it shouldn't.''
</P>
<P>
   But journal editors say it would be unwieldy to simply admit
anyone. Aside from guaranteeing quality, a test also guarantees a
degree of commitment. Students who are willing to spend so much
time on the test, the editors argue, demonstrate a willingness to
work long hours to see the journal to press.
</P>
<P>
   The debate over admissions has raged before, and at other law
schools. At Penn, one top editor quit three years ago, saying that
attempts to diversify the staff by easing requirements on the
admissions test had led to poor quality. That same year at Yale,
editors allowed students to retake the test as often as it took to
pass, and let in anyone who did.
</P>
<P>
   The result, said this year's editor-in-chief, Laura Ahn, was
that the journal had too many voices, and too many mistakes, and
ultimately spent thousands of dollars to correct last-minute errors
in the publication. Yale abandoned that system.
</P>
<P>
   ``You could argue that the process produces resentment, but I
don't think that divisiveness is a necessary result,'' Ahn said.
``That has more to do with how people interact.''
</P>
<P>
   Ahn and others on the journal say the critics overstate the
connection between journal membership and getting a job.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's ridiculous coming from Yale Law students,'' said Michelle
Mello, a second-year journal member. ``This is the number-one law
school in the country; I don't know anyone who wasn't completely
satisfied with the job search this year. It's hard for me to
believe someone would be denied for not being on the journal.''
</P>
<P>
   ``There is competition,'' she added. ``Of course there's
competition, and there's always competition. My point is,
everyone's going to do well. There's no reason to get nasty,
there's no reason why we can't have a process where not everyone
makes it and still get along, and still get good jobs.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-03-25-99 1515EST &QL; 
