<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-ROSIE-FLORES-LADN </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
SLEEP TAKES A BACKSEAT FOR HONKY-TONK SINGER
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
(Story for release Friday, March 26) 
By REED JOHNSON  
 c.1999 Los Angeles Daily News  
 
LOS ANGELES _ Rosie Flores needs caffeine. And she needs it now.
<TEXT>
<P>
   ``It goes from zero to 100 every morning for me,'' says the
honky tonk singer-songwriter, speaking by phone from Austin, Texas.
``I'm awake with a cup of coffee and ready to talk.''
</P>
<P>
   Ah, the glamorous road life. The previous night, Flores
explains, she was rehearsing with her band until, oh, around 2 in
the morning. The night before, it was 1 a.m.
</P>
<P>
   This evening she'll be back in Los Angeles sharing a triple bill
with Katie Moffatt and Lily Hayden at the Moondog Cafe on Melrose
Avenue. Then Saturday it's on to the annual Cowboy Poetry &AMP; Music
Festival in Santa Clarita, where Flores will headline a late-night
honky tonk hootenanny.
</P>
<P>
   At each stop, she'll do her best to boost her latest release,
``Dance Hall Dreams'' (Rounder Records). Then Flores will begin the
cycle all over again.
</P>
<P>
   ``I started managing myself back around the middle of last
year,'' she says, ``and all of a sudden I started taking on the
huge overload of trying to get phone calls and all the e-mails that
come through and the offers. And then somewhere in there you try to
write songs and work on your guitar.''
</P>
<P>
   Still, reckoning by the percolating warmth and candor in her
voice, you wonder what Flores sounds like when she's really awake.
</P>
<P>
   Those trademark qualities permeate ``Dance Hall Dreams,'' a disc
that derives its kick from its live recording setting _ at the
Cibolo Creek Country Club, a San Antonio dance hall _ and its
quietly reflective tone from some recent losses in Flores' life.
</P>
<P>
   ``Who's Gonna Fix It Now?'' is a tribute to her late father,
Oscar, and his habit of pasting little notes above his tool bench,
reminding himself to ``fix bathroom sink'' or ``fix shower door.''
Now that he's gone, Flores asked herself, who'll take care of those
things? Flores says she finished the song, which she co-wrote with
Don Henry, in a candlelit room in Amsterdam, tears streaming
cathartically down her face.
</P>
<P>
   ``I think in losing my father, it changed my life probably more
provocatively than anything else has in 20 years,'' she says. ``So
I had to kind of look at life and put different priorities in
place. I've gotten closer to my family because there was a need _
there was a loss, more of a need for me to be around.''
</P>
<P>
   Flores also is coping with the loss of her longtime drummer Don
Lindley, who died of lung cancer in February at age 47.
</P>
<P>
   ``I know there's some talented drummers out there, and I'll find
one, but it won't be the same.''
</P>
<P>
   The quiveringly beautiful ``Tremolo,'' the bluesy ``The Man
Downstairs'' and the self-explanatory ``This Ol' Honky Tonk'' are
the other standout tracks on an upbeat record gently tinged with
melancholy. Flores' musical guests include Radney Foster doing
harmony vocals and Tammy Rogers playing viola and mandolin and
singing backup.
</P>
<P>
   Born in San Antonio in 1950, Flores was 12 when she moved with
her family to San Diego. There, she formed Penelope's Children, a
``psychedelic country-rock'' band and the first of several
all-female outfits that included the '70s rockabilly group Rosie
and the Screamers and, in 1984, the cow-punk ensemble Screaming
Sirens. Lately she's been touring with country-rock godmother Wanda
Jackson, a woman who, like Flores, has never fit neatly into
conventional radio or music marketing genres.
</P>
<P>
   ``I believe that Nashville kind of needs to reinvent itself, and
I believe it may be looking toward kind of different songwriters,''
Flores says. ``I think even the top executives in Nashville know
radio's in trouble because not everybody's buying that stuff. Not
to say there isn't some good stuff, when you wade between the muck.
I for one have never not enjoyed a good Vince Gill record. I
appreciate Trisha Yearwood's voice _ I think she knows what a good
song is. So there are the gems.''
</P>
<P>
   Underlining those remarks, Flores is contemplating relocating to
Nashville after nearly a decade in L.A., now that such
progressive-country songwriters as Duane Jarvis, Jim Lauderdale and
Lucinda Williams have colonized middle-of-the-road Music Row.
</P>
<P>
   ``You know, I'm very famous for trying to reinvent myself
constantly, and I think I'm a bit of a chameleon. I take what I've
learned, and I reshape my little life and try to start over again.
I think in life you do have to start over again.
</P>
<P>
   ``Maybe I'm only lucky and capable of doing that because I'm a
single woman. But the only thing that keeps me going is change,
because I can get moldy if I stay in one place.'' &QL; 
 &QL; 
 &QL; 
INFORMATION &UR;  &QL; 
What: &LR;  Rosie Flores. &UR;  &QL; 
Where: &LR;  Cowboy Poetry &AMP; Music Festival, Melody Motion Picture
Ranch, Santa Clarita. You must take a shuttle to the ranch from the
corner of 13th and Arch streets in downtown Santa Clarita. &UR;  &QL; 
When: &LR;  9:30-11:30 p.m. Saturday. Regular festival hours are 9 a.m.
to 7 p.m. Saturday, 10 a.m. to 6 p.m. Sunday. &UR;  &QL; 
Tickets: &LR;  $9, or free with purchase of festival general admission
tickets ($7). Call (661) 255-4910. &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
