<SLUG> BC-ELLIS-COLUMN-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
MONICA LEWINSKY ON THE DOWN ELEVATOR OF AMERICAN CELEBRITYHOOD
</HEADLINE>
  (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By JOHN ELLIS  
 c.1999 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   Monica Lewinsky's 14 months of fame are over now. They came and
went in the blink of an eye. Her life, in the sense of a normal
life, is finished, though no one seems to have the heart to tell
her. She's riding the down escalator of celebrity, medications in
her purse. A Hollywood Square awaits.
</P>
<P>
   She is, remarkably, the most despised public figure in modern
American life. Her personal favorability rating, as measured by the
Fox News/Opinion Dynamics poll, is 10 percent positive and 76
percent negative. We now like everyone else better than we like Ms.
Lewinsky. Even O.J. Simpson, at the time of his murder trial, had
better numbers than hers.
</P>
<P>
   What does this say about us? Much of the last year has been
given over to thrashing President Clinton for exploiting Lewinsky
in the way that he did. That was fair enough. His conduct toward
her was in every way irresponsible, reprehensible, and inexcusable.
But Clinton was hardly the only one who used and exploited Monica
Lewinsky.
</P>
<P>
   The media feasted on her. Is there a difference between Linda
Tripp and Barbara Walters, really? It is true that Tripp taped
Lewinsky without her knowledge or consent. It is also true that
Tripp manipulated Lewinsky to do and say things that Tripp knew
could only make Lewinsky's legal stance more perilous.
</P>
<P>
   But on a human level, Tripp's treachery isn't really
distinguishable from Walters's faux empathy. They were both after
the same thing. By the time of the ``exclusive'' interview,
Lewinsky was a young woman in desperate need of adult guidance. She
needed one true friend, preferably a worldly woman, to help her get
her act together. Her mother had come undone. Her twenty-something
friends were too young. The handlers were interested only in their
billable hours. She was alone in the shark tank.
</P>
<P>
   Walters's interview with Lewinsky _ all that phony concern and
feigned intimacy _ was in its way every bit as despicable as Bill
Clinton's conduct. Clinton at least tried to keep her servitude
secret, not because he cared about her but because he feared the
political cost. Walters's intentions were entirely mercenary. She
would wring from Monica every last drop of Nielsen blood.
</P>
<P>
   And for this Walters was celebrated, unlike Lewinsky, who was
reviled. The press pronounced Barbara the queen of the ``get.''
Anchormen like Dan Rather and talk-show hosts like Charlie Rose
genuflected at Walters's altar of celebrity journalism. Only
Barbara could have done it, said Rose. This is what makes her the
premier television interviewer of her time, said Rather.
</P>
<P>
   And there wasn't a trace of irony in their voices.
</P>
<P>
   Not one ranking member of the media _ not one _ said that what
Walters did in getting the interview and during the interview
itself was irresponsible, reprehensible or inexcusable. The ratings
were great _ better than the Academy Awards, as it turned out _ so
Walters reigned, and everyone fell into line.
</P>
<P>
   At about the same time as the Lewinsky interview, Paul Weyrich,
a leading political strategist, sent an open letter to his friends
and acquaintances in the conservative movement. Therein he wrote:
``Politics has failed because of the collapse of the culture. The
culture we are living in becomes an ever-wider sewer. In truth, I
think we are caught up in a cultural collapse of historic
proportions, a collapse so great that it simply overwhelms
politics.''
</P>
<P>
   Weyrich's letter was a declaration of defeat in what we have
come to call the culture wars. As such, liberals greeted it with
satisfaction, conservatives with consternation. The superior forces
of the media culture would win, said Weyrich. They already have
won, he admitted later. There was no longer any point in pretending
otherwise.
</P>
<P>
   So whose view of the culture is right? Dan Rather's or Paul
Weyrich's? Over the course of the last year, the mainstream media
devoted an extraordinary percentage of their time and energy to the
cause of exploiting Monica Lewinsky for profit. NBC News had as an
explicit strategy ``all Monica, all the time.'' And it worked.
MSNBC's ratings improved. CNBC's prime-time ratings improved. NBC
News did better on nights when Monica was prominently featured. And
it wasn't just NBC (where I once worked). ABC News, CBS News, Fox
News, National Public Radio, The Washington Post, The New York
Times _ all of these media empires mainlined Monica every day.
</P>
<P>
   They'd like you to forget that now. They'd like you to believe
that Monica was an aberration. But it was hardly an aberration.
Sunday night, in prime time during the Academy Awards ceremonies,
the host simulated masturbation while introducing a ``presenter.''
And the show went on as if nothing unusual had happened.
</P>
<P>
   Paul Weyrich may be cranky, but he's not wrong. The cultural war
has been lost. The only question left is how much worse it will
get. Monica Lewinsky, at the age of 25, has already lived the
answer to that question.
</P>
<P>
   John Ellis is a Globe columnist.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
