<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-MORSE-COLUMN-HNS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
THIS CAMPAIGN RIDES ON TRANSIT SYSTEM'S TROUBLES 
</HEADLINE>
   Commentary  
 (For use by New York Times News Service clients.)  
 By ROB MORSE  
 c.1999 San Francisco Examiner  
<TEXT>
<P>
   SAN FRANCISCO _ Stand at one of the city's Municipal Railway
stations with Clint Reilly for two hours and you learn some things:
First, it's cold out there. Reilly has been accused of having a
super-heated ego, but most other parts of him were freezing at the
entrance to Castro station early Wednesday.
</P>
<P>
   This guy is serious about running for mayor. He's burning
calories as well as his own money.
</P>
<P>
   Reilly is paying the price of his transformation from political
consultant to political supplicant. He spends most mornings passing
out copies of his plan to fix the transit system called ``Riders
First!''
</P>
<P>
   Streams of commuters passed as he kept saying, ``Hi, Clint
Reilly, running for mayor.''
</P>
<P>
   Some commuters smiled. Others blew him off.
</P>
<P>
   ``There's a certain amount of making a fool of oneself,'' he
said. ``Real people are rough.''
</P>
<P>
   Sometimes entire crowds of people would blast by.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's funny. If the first person in a bunch takes a book, they
all do,'' Reilly said, probably the first time this minor bit of
mass behavior has ever been noticed by a high-powered political
consultant.
</P>
<P>
   I kept wondering how the public would react if Mayor Willie
Brown were standing at a station handing out his plan to fix Muni.
</P>
<P>
   The second and most important thing you learn standing with an
insurgent candidate for mayor at a Muni station is that San
Franciscans are serious about making city services work, especially
Muni, a subject on which they're all experts.
</P>
<P>
   Steve Hall told Reilly he'd already read his Muni book. ``It's a
great compilation of what everyone knows,'' he said. ``If the Board
of Supervisors and mayor used Muni and cabs, they'd know what was
wrong, too.''
</P>
<P>
   ``You know what Muni's motto is, don't you?'' said Annie Jew.
``Their motto is: `We're already at work.'''
</P>
<P>
   And the heck with everyone else trying to get there.
</P>
<P>
   ``I gave up on Muni a long time ago,'' Jew said. ``No way you
can make arrangements to meet people. We don't make our own time.''
</P>
<P>
   She told Reilly: ``You're going to do it.''
</P>
<P>
   Another woman passing by looked at Reilly's Muni book and said,
``Oh, yeah, fix it, baby.''
</P>
<P>
   In the middle of the rush hour, there was a breakdown and
hundreds of commuters were stuck on the platform. Reilly went down
to work the packed crowd.
</P>
<P>
   John Preckel, who commutes a mere five stops, said: ``It's the
kind of commute that sucks the life out of you.''
</P>
<P>
   ``If management hasn't improved over the years, then it's the
mayor's fault,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   I kept thinking about the reception Brown would get on the
platform. It probably wouldn't be as bad as it was during the great
Muni meltdown last year when he was booed and cursed.
</P>
<P>
   Many people say the service has improved since the big meltdown
(and how could it not?). Many also are encouraged by Brown's hiring
of a professional transit director from Philadelphia, Thomas Burns.
</P>
<P>
   The question is why Brown waited three years to hire a real pro.
As Marc Gofstein put it sardonically, ``Suddenly we get a Muni
director.''
</P>
<P>
   Reilly said everyone he spoke to in Philadelphia told him Burns
is first-rate. The question is what Burns can do squeezed between
the unions and their friend, the mayor.
</P>
<P>
   One of Reilly's problems is that only 30 percent of the people
know who he is. Brown's problem, though, is that 100 percent of the
people know who he is.
</P>
<P>
   In the past, Reilly has gotten a lot of bad press, not least
from me, but I'll say this. The whole two hours we were at the
Castro Muni station, no one offered a cheer for Brown, or called
Reilly a political consultant.
</P>
<P>
   Just wait. We'll hear worse.
</P>
<P>
   &UR;  &LR;  &QL;
</P>
<P>
   (Rob Morse is a columnist for the San Francisco Examiner, P.O.
Box 7260, San Francisco, CA 94120.)
</P>
</TEXT>
