<SLUG> BC-BEAUTYQUEEN-FILM-LADN </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
OSCAR-WINNING DOCUMENTARIAN IN FRONT OF CAMERAS AGAIN
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients)  
(Corrects Tom Snyder's ``Late Late Show'' sted ``Late Night'') 
 
  
By BOB MCCARTHY  
 c.1999 Los Angeles Daily News  
<TEXT>
<P>
   LOS ANGELES _ Keiko Ibi is one of the beautiful people, though
she's probably too modest to admit it.
</P>
<P>
   In case you missed it Sunday night, this former Miss Japan Grand
Prix won an Oscar for her 37-minute documentary, ``The Personals:
Improvisations on Romance in the Golden Years,'' and became an even
bigger part of academy history in the process. With the short
documentary category being eliminated, her name closes the book on
that genre.
</P>
<P>
   Ibi's route to filmmaking started when she won her country's
equivalent of the Miss America Pageant at age 19. That led to the
expected promotional tours and personal appearances, after which
she studied acting, singing and dancing in anticipation of starting
a career in front of audiences. But, alas, she found herself less
than satisfied with it all.
</P>
<P>
   ``My adventurous nature and wanting to do unexpected things led
me to learn more about writing screenplays,'' she says. ``I decided
to enroll in film school in the United States.''
</P>
<P>
   Off she went in 1993 to New York University's film school, where
she eventually made ``The Personals'' as a senior thesis. She's the
first to admit that her making a film about a senior-citizen troupe
of actors (the subject of her winning documentary) produced an
unlikely pairing.
</P>
<P>
   ``I become curious how the performance fits into their lives and
thought to follow them on and off stage until the next
performance,'' she says. ``Jewish seniors and a Japanese girl is
almost as opposite as it can get. ... I didn't know their stories,
but somehow I had a whole movie in my head.''
</P>
<P>
   The production was a collaboration with cinematographer and
fellow NYU alum Greg Pak (a Student Academy Award winner in 1998),
and the original version ran 79 minutes _ nearly twice what it
ended up being. Her film drew acclaim at the San Francisco
International Film Festival, Film Fest New Haven, the National
Educational Media Festival and the Jewish Video Competition and
received an honorable mention at the Philadelphia International
Film Festival.
</P>
<P>
   Her story of growing old in America with grace and humor will be
televised in June on HBO. She is currently in preproduction on her
next documentary being shot in Dallas and is working on a
screenplay for a full-length feature.
</P>
<P>
   ``Who would've thought a girl from Japan can make a film about
senior citizens and get nominated for an Academy Award!'' she
marveled. ``When I set foot in the United States seven years ago,
it was inconceivable.''
</P>
<P>
   The phone at her publicist's office hasn't stopped ringing since
Sunday night's Oscars, and a now-weary Ibi has appeared on ``CNN
Live,'' Tom Snyder's `Late Late Show,'' taped a ``Roseanne''
segment and talked with practically every major publication in
Japan in the days since. While her status as a former Miss Japan
certainly makes people sit up and take notice, Ibi doesn't want to
be stereotyped by her past accomplishment.
</P>
<P>
   ``She wants people to know she's not just another pretty face,''
says her publicist, Tom Chen.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
