<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-ANDERSON-COLUMN-TEX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
STEAKS AND MARRIAGES ARE BEST WITH A LITTLE SEASONING
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By MONICA ANDERSON 
c.1999 Fort Worth Star-Telegram 
<TEXT>
<P>
   It has been said that longevity has its place. Obviously, that
is an old aphorism. We are all aware that the trend today is toward
youth, youth and more youth. However, it is true that there are
times when even the most progressive among us would prefer a
seasoned veteran.
</P>
<P>
   For example, on an airplane I would prefer a pilot with 20 years
of experience over one who just got his or her license yesterday.
In the operating room, the title of chief of surgery has a
reassuring resonance to it, don't you think? And, of course,
there's marriage, where a few years under the belt can make the
union seem more like a wonderful, well-seasoned steak instead of a
sizzling stake through the heart. (If you're not a meat eater, that
analogy doesn't work, but just work with me anyway.)
</P>
<P>
   See, when we were first married, my husband was bluntly honest.
Not that truth is bad, but when a woman asks her husband, ``Do I
look fat in this skirt?'' she really does not want to hear, ``Yes,
it is kind of tight around the hips.''
</P>
<P>
   A veteran, elderly husband would say, ``You look nice in
everything you wear, but I prefer the blue skirt because it matches
your hair.'' Of course, he knows that the skirt is too tight and
she knows that the skirt is too tight, but he also knows that the
blue skirt is pleated and a size larger than the one she's squeezed
herself into.
</P>
<P>
   At times, we simply need reassurance from our spouses. The skirt
question really boils down to, ``Do you find me unattractive
because my hips have spread since I bore those children for you?''
OK, the chocolate had something to do with the hips also, but
children make mothers eat chocolate. It relieves stress. Really.
</P>
<P>
   Conversely, when my husband asks me, ``Will you still love me
when I'm bald?'' I now know not to start making jokes about that
3-foot-long strip of hair that some men use to disguise their
smooth domes. Nope. I say, ``Honey, I think bald men are sexy. I
loved you with that big Afro, and I'll love you when you wear your
hair like Caesar or Michael Jordan.''
</P>
<P>
   And I will. Hair loss is the least of my worries. There are
worse things.
</P>
<P>
   And while I'm not privy to the male psyche, I think the hair
question boils down to, ``Am I the man?''
</P>
<P>
   And I think, ``Yes, you work hard to provide for our family, you
come home every night, you're a pretty nice guy and you never tell
me that I look like a fat cow even when I do. Heck, yeah, you're
The Man!''
</P>
<P>
   So, yes, like aged cheese and I Love Lucy reruns, some things do
improve with time. Although the idea of old cheese has never
appealed to me. I like to think of it as being new when I purchase
it, and then I toss it out when it turns green. Forget the cheese;
Lucy is good, though. Wait, didn't she divorce Desi Arnaz?
</P>
<P>
   Oh, never mind.
</P>
<P>
   (Monica Frazier Anderson is a wife, mother and dentist in
Arlington, Texas. You can call her at (817) 548-5564, or write in
care of the Arlington Star-Telegram at 1111 W. Abram St.,
Arlington, TX 76013. Visit the Star-Telegram's online services on
the World Wide Web: www.star-telegram.com) nn
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
