<HEADLINE>
STAIRWAY RUNNERS: INSTALL THEM YOURSELF, SOMETIMES 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By PETER C. HOTTON  
 c.1999 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   Who has never had problems with his stairs _ indoor stairs, that
is. It never fails that the nicely-varnished treads look good for a
month, if you're lucky.
</P>
<P>
   Such treads always get badly treated by feet walking up and
down, scuffing the varnish down to the bare wood. You just can't
help sort of sluffing your feet on stairs, so the problem is not
solved by having everyone climb the stairs flat-footed.
</P>
<P>
   And the risers, those nice, white-painted risers, also look good
for a month or so; after that, they too get scuffed or scarred by
the toes of those walking feet. It is unavoidable.
</P>
<P>
   So what to do, what to do?
</P>
<P>
   Is there something that will protect the treads and risers? One
solution is to do what a friend of mine did many years ago; he
applied a marbleized contact paper to the risers. It lasted many
years, scuffing of the marble pattern didn't show, and when the
paper got too messy, all my friend had to do was replace the paper.
It did no good for the treads, however.
</P>
<P>
   The ultimate in protecting both treads and risers is a stair
carpet, or runner. There is a bonus; it muffles the sound of feet
galumphing up and down. And, they may even prevent you or anyone
else from being caught coming home in the wee hours. And, you can
argue that it makes the stairs safer.
</P>
<P>
   You can buy stick-on pads for the treads only, even in an
Oriental pattern. This is a quick and easy fix, but will not help
the risers.
</P>
<P>
   These stick-ons might be good for another friend of mine, who
needed an easier way for his old dog to get up the stairs. It seems
the dog could not get a good grip on the stairs, and ended up
sprawling up as best he could. The stick-ons would give him
something to really dig his paws into.
</P>
<P>
   Such stick-ons are sold in some catalogs, the Improvements
Catalog, for one (800-642-2112).
</P>
<P>
   But for good looks, comfort, and safety, a stair carpet is the
way to go. And, you can do it yourself, if your stairs do not take
funny turns with pie-slice-shaped treads. If your stairs do take
funny turns, pay the bucks and let the pros do it. A runner has to
be cut and fitted to make those funny turns, so it is worth
spending the money for a professional installation.
</P>
<P>
   But if you have a straight run or your stairs turn a corner with
one or more square landings, you can do it yourself.
</P>
<P>
   Buy a quality runner: A thick, all-wool, Oriental design is
best. Adding a pad will extend the life of the runner. Such quality
runners cost up to $27 a running foot at standard stores; you can
get them for much less at discount, salvage, and surplus stores.
</P>
<P>
   The Improvements Catalog and Renovator's (800-659-2211) carry
runners of various synthetic fabrics. They are less expensive than
those of wool and, in this handyman's opinion, are not as good as
the wool ones.
</P>
<P>
   First, measure your stairs. Measure a tread and multiply by the
number of treads. Then measure a riser and multiply by the number
of risers. Add them together and add two feet for good measure. The
two extra feet allow for wastage and also allow you to double the
runner at the high riser; that way, when the runner wears, you can
unfold that doubled runner and reinstall the runner, exposing fresh
runner at no cost at all, except the labor.
</P>
<P>
   In most stairs, all risers are the same height and all treads
are the same depth. If you are in doubt about that, measure each
riser and tread individually.
</P>
<P>
   Standard runn
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
