<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-03-25 16:14 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A4019 &Cx1f; tdt-z
u e &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-BOOK-FRANKEL-BOS &LR;      03-25 0866
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BOOK-FRANKEL-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
EDITOR RECOUNTS DISTINGUISHED CAREER AT THE TIMES
</HEADLINE>
  (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By MARK JURKOWITZ  
 c.1999 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   The biggest problem with ``The Times of My Life: And My Life
With The Times,'' is that its author saves the best for first. This
worthy memoir from retired New York Times executive editor Max
Frankel opens with the breathtaking tale of his family's
nick-of-time escape from Germany and the Holocaust. After that, his
distinguished career as a journalist who works his way to the top
of the Times masthead _ surmounting the paper's byzantine
bureaucracy and opening its gray pages to livelier journalism _
seems like an afterthought.
</P>
<P>
   Well, not quite. After one is finished marveling at Frankel's
mere survival, ``The Times of My Life'' succeeds as a sharp
analysis of US miscalculations during the Cold War. (Frankel, who
became the Times's man in Moscow at age 27, had a bird's-eye view
of world leaders toiling under the burden of mutually assured
destruction.) It also provides a reasonably candid look at the
internal machinations of America's newspaper of record.
</P>
<P>
   All this is skillfully executed by an author whose craftsmanship
certainly exceeds that of the average journalist. Today, Frankel
continues to write an eminently readable column in the New York
Times Magazine that _ in contrast to his predecessor A.M.
Rosenthal's op-ed pleadings _ proves that former Times editors can
go gracefully into that long goodnight.
</P>
<P>
   The primary historical significance of Frankel's book is his
insistent portrayal of Soviet boss Nikita Khrushchev as the
original Gorbachev, a quasiheroic figure struggling to ``overhaul .
. . the Soviet political structure'' and to trade guns for butter
long before it was politically feasible.
</P>
<P>
   ``I considered Khrushchev the most robust politician of my
time,'' he writes. And Frankel did ply his trade in interesting
times. A firsthand tale of Khrushchev, Fidel Castro, and Malcolm X
all converging on Harlem's Hotel Theresa one night in 1960 suggests
just how bland our news landscape seems these days.
</P>
<P>
   Frankel traces a series of American missteps during the Cold War
_ including the ``domino theory,'' which helped justify the Vietnam
quagmire. (Unlike Oliver Stone, he believes that had John Kennedy
lived, he would have become fully involved in the ``Vietnam
muck.'') He also suggests that the press began its ``gradual,
fitful estrangement'' from the government during the dark days of
Cold War duplicity _ well before Walter Cronkite saw the light in
Vietnam.
</P>
<P>
   Frankel's discussion of his career at the Times is most notable
for what he is noted for: expanding the definition of ``all the
news that's fit to print.'' This idea goes back as far as an early
Frankel dispatch from Cuba, speculating that the communists were
winning the heart of the newly ascendant Castro, ``that barely fit
the conventions of newspaper language.'' And it extends to this
famous 1994 Page 1 story on Bill Clinton's visit to Oxford written
by Maureen Dowd at the end of Frankel's tenure as executive editor:
``President Clinton returned today for a sentimental journey to the
university where he didn't inhale, didn't get drafted and didn't
get a degree.''
</P>
<P>
   Frankel's reasoning is disarming. The decision to publish this
``apt spoof of an otherwise inconsequential presidential photo op''
was partial revenge for the Times's refusal to publish a poem he
once wrote lampooning Richard Nixon's travels to Limerick, Ireland,
in search of his Irish ancestry.
</P>
<P>
   Frankel uses the book to make an unapologetic case for
redefining news, proudly recounting how he green-lighted front-page
Times stories on everything from country music to shorter hemlines.
And to his credit, he addresses some of the more significant
controversies that arose as part of the so-called
``tabloidization'' of the Times during his tenure.
</P>
<P>
   Despite a longstanding policy against naming victims of sexual
assault, he is unrepentant about the 1991 Times story that
identified Patricia Bowman as the woman who accused William Kennedy
Smith of rape, a story that triggered in-house protests.
</P>
<P>
   Conversely, Frankel acknowledges that another Dowd Page 1
blockbuster _ a 1991 summary of Kitty Kelley's Nancy Reagan
biography featuring allegations that the first lady had bedded
Frank Sinatra _ ``was not appropriate news for the Times.''
</P>
<P>
   Lest anyone think Frankel's Times actually tumbled down the
slippery tabloid slope, he defends the paper's hands-off treatment
of Gennifer Flowers's ``alleged escapades'' with Clinton and other
affairs of the flesh. ``Whenever we were somehow forced to delve
into people's private lives, we preferred not to be first with lewd
and lurid details,'' he writes, describing a philosophy still
evident in the Times's gingerly handling of recent allegations that
Clinton sexually assaulted an Arkansas woman 21 years ago.
</P>
<P>
   It's a long way from divining the workings of Khrushchev's
Kremlin to deciding whether to detail the hormonal urges of
presidential hopefuls. But then, Frankel's ``Life With The Times''
spanned the equivalent of several sociopolitical eons.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
