<SLUG> BC-CALIF-MISSING-HNS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
SEARCH GROWS FOR SUSPECTS IN CALIFORNIA KILLINGS 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients.)  
 By JIM HERRON ZAMORA  
 and ERIC BRAZIL  
 c.1999 San Francisco Examiner  
<TEXT>
<P>
   MI-WUK VILLAGE, Calif. _ An intense two-county search for
suspects in the killing of a California woman and possibly one of
two teen-agers traveling with her has not led the police to any
suspects, authorities said Thursday.
</P>
<P>
   But the sweep has had some beneficial side-effects. Authorities
in Tuolumne and Mariposa counties have recovered about 15 stolen
cars, arrested a handful of parolees and probation violators and
may have caused other criminals to lay low or flee.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's great. They're driving away everybody with a criminal
record,'' said Louise Guthmiller, the owner of a Chevron station in
Sierra Village, a hamlet in Tuolumne County. ``I don't know if
they're going to find the person they want up here, but they're
making all the other bad guys nervous.''
</P>
<P>
   The FBI descended on the rural are in eastern California last
week after a badly burned rental car used by Carole Sund, 42, her
daughter Julie, 15, and family friend Silvina Pelosso, 16, was
found in a densely wooded area about two miles from Guthmiller's
gas station.
</P>
<P>
   The charred remains of two people, one of them Carole Sund, were
found inside the trunk on March 18. The other body has not been
identified, but investigators expect it to one of the girl's. The
third person has not been found.
</P>
<P>
   The car was found hidden in a ponderosa pine forest some three
hours north of the Cedar Lodge in El Portal, the town near the
Yosemite National Park where the woman and two teen-agers had been
staying before they disappeared in mid-February.
</P>
<P>
   Investigators said Thursday they had not made any arrests in the
case.
</P>
<P>
   The FBI and other investigators are said to be looking at about
10 to 15 men as possible suspects. Among them are convicted sex
offenders.
</P>
<P>
   ``They are talking to people, they are following leads, they are
verifying alibis,'' said Tuolumne County sheriff's Lt. John Steely.
``They are checking through all the thousands of tips that we have
received.''
</P>
<P>
   Although the car was found more than three hours from where the
woman and two children were last seen, investigators believe the
three met violence in or around Yosemite National Park.
</P>
<P>
   Nevertheless, people here have been rocked by the developments.
Mariposa and Tuolumne counties have very low crime rates. Tuolumne,
with 52,000 residents, had one homicide last year and none in 1997.
</P>
<P>
   The last homicide in Mariposa County, with about 16,000
residents, was in 1997.
</P>
<P>
   John Engel, a resident of Tuolumne County, said the mountains
are a good place for someone to hide from the law.
</P>
<P>
   ``Back in these hills there are a lot of people who don't want
law enforcement to know about them,'' said Engel, who moved to the
area in 1995. ``It's kind of natural for them to come here.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
