A4060 &Cx1f; tdt-z
u f &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-EMC-IBM-BOS &LR;      03-25 0562
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-EMC-IBM-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
$3 BILLION DEAL EXPECTED TO BOOST BOTH COMPUTER GIANTS
</HEADLINE>
  (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By ROSS KERBER  
 c.1999 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   EMC Corp. said it may buy up to $3 billion in computer parts
from IBM Corp. over five years in an unusual deal that also gives
the Hopkinton company access to technology developed by Big Blue.
</P>
<P>
   The pact announced Wednesday comes despite that the two
companies are archrivals in the market for large disk drive
systems. They compete fiercely to sell the systems used by
airlines, banks, and other corporations to track accounts and
customer data.
</P>
<P>
   EMC already buys many disk drives from its competitor in Armonk,
N.Y. Now, by moving into a closer alliance, EMC hopes to attract
new customers who want more assurances that parts made by the two
companies would mesh, said EMC spokesman Mark Fredrickson.
</P>
<P>
   Among customers, ``there's still an element of `FUD', or fear,
uncertainty, and doubt, that's erased'' by the technical
cooperation, Fredrickson said.
</P>
<P>
   It was unclear how much of the $3 billion in potential purchases
by EMC represents fresh orders for IBM.
</P>
<P>
   Fredrickson said the figure represents little change from EMC's
previous purchase plans.
</P>
<P>
   EMC also emphasized that the $3 billion figure was ``a target''
and said that it made no firm commitments to buy the entire amount.
</P>
<P>
   Tom Beermann, an IBM spokesman, said the agreement will produce
``significant'' new revenues for IBM, but declined to specify how
much.
</P>
<P>
   For IBM, the cooperation is part of a broader strategy shift in
which the company plans to increase its focus on producing parts
for other computer companies. Last year, such operations accounted
for $6.6 billion of IBM's total revenue of $81.7 billion.
</P>
<P>
   Earlier this month, IBM said it would sell $16 billion worth of
parts to Dell Computer Corp. over seven years, even though it plans
to continue to sell personal computers in competition against Dell.
</P>
<P>
   Some analysts said that the technical cooperation between EMC
and IBM was the most noteworthy part of Wednesday's agreement.
</P>
<P>
   EMC said its engineers will begin cooperating with their
counterparts at IBM, sharing technical details on storage
technology to ensure IBM parts run smoothly within EMC systems.
</P>
<P>
   Under their agreement, EMC gains access to 30,000 IBM patents,
Fredrickson said. EMC pledged not to compete against IBM in areas
such as the production of chips or certain computers.
</P>
<P>
   Tighter relations between EMC and IBM will help the latter
attract orders for mainframe computers from current EMC customers,
said John McArthur, senior analyst at International Data Corp. in
Framingham.
</P>
<P>
   ``This lets IBM move forward with their (mainframe) solution
quickly, and that's very important to them,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   EMC is the biggest supplier of large information-storage
systems. Last year, it accounted for 35 percent of sales in the
market, according to Dataquest, a California research firm. IBM,
which once dominated the market, last year had 22 percent.
</P>
<P>
   The agreement doesn't mean IBM is throwing in the towel for its
storage business.
</P>
<P>
   Big Blue will still compete against EMC in selling disk drives,
maintenance services and other areas, said B.T. Alex Brown analyst
Phil Rueppel.
</P>
<P>
   EMC shares closed at 118 7/8, up 5. IBM stock rose 4 1/8 to 169
1/2.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
