A4074 &Cx1f; tdt-z
u f &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-CRUISE-MISSILE-BOS &LR;      03-25 0540
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-CRUISE-MISSILE-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
CRUISE MISSILES HAVE IMPORTANT BENEFIT OF REDUCING RISK TO PILOTS
</HEADLINE>
  (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By ROSS KERBER  
 c.1999 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   A new generation of cruise missiles deployed for use against
targets in the Balkans has proven effective during recent raids
against Iraq, the Pentagon says, where they struck 80 percent of
their targets.
</P>
<P>
   That would mark a significant improvement for the Navy's
long-range Tomahawk missile, built by Lexington-based Raytheon Co.,
and could give NATO forces an important advantage during the air
campaign that began Wednesday.
</P>
<P>
   The Tomahawk received mixed reviews for its performance during
Gulf War, and some military observers remain skeptical because past
claims about the pilotless Tomahawk proved overblown.
</P>
<P>
   But even these people agree the Tomahawk and other so-called
``standoff'' weapons also serve a valuable domestic mission:
reducing the likelihood of pilot casualties while creating the
impression of powerful military action.
</P>
<P>
   ``I think the reason the Pentagon is touting these things is
because they don't want to use people'' to deliver bombs against
Serb targets, said Richard Shultz, a professor at Tufts
University's Fletcher School of Law and Diplomacy.
</P>
<P>
   But even a lower success rate does not mean the weapons are not
valuable, said Chris Hellman, senior analyst at the Center for
Defense Information, a nonprofit group in Washington and a frequent
Pentagon critic. ``Even if they work just half the time, that's
good enough if it means we don't have to put people in harm's
way.''
</P>
<P>
   No NATO losses were reported in the first day of the air
campaign, a combination of missile strikes and attacks by manned
aircraft. That could may change over the course of a longer
campaign, Hellman said, because Yugoslav air defenses are likely to
be more robust that those fielded by the Iraqi military.
</P>
<P>
   In Serbia, ``You've got a lot of mobile targets in moutainous
terrain, and that's an attacker's nightmare,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   The Tomahawk, which can carry up to 1,000 pounds of explosives,
is generally launched from US Navy vessels in attacks on
infrastructure like buildings and airfields. A larger cruise
missile built by Boeing and used by the Air Force can carry twice
as much payload.
</P>
<P>
   The Tomahawk received much attention during the Gulf War. But a
Pentagon study that came to light in 1997 suggested the missile
reached just half its intended targets.
</P>
<P>
   At the time, the main builder of the Tomahawk was Hughes
Electronics Corp., which has since been acquired by Raytheon. Both
Raytheon and the Pentagon decline to discuss criticism of the
weapons' previous performance. But of more than 300 missiles that
were fired on Iraq in December, 80 percent reached their target,
Navy spokeswoman Lieutenant Meghan Mariman said Wednesday.
</P>
<P>
   Another new munition available to NATO forces is the Joint
Standoff Weapon, essentially a winged glider bomb that can travel
long distances to a target after been dropped from an aircraft.
</P>
<P>
   So far 17 of the Raytheon-built bombs have been launched against
targets in Iraq and all 17 have hit their targets, according to
Navy officers quoted in trade publications.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
