<P>
   KOSOVO-CLARK _ WASHINGTON _ Supreme NATO Commander Wesley Clark
is a guy who looked down the hatch at his friends burned alive
after their APC tumbled over Mt. Igman outside Sarajevo in August
1995. The reason they were on the mountain at all was that the
Serbs wouldn't grant safe passage to Clark _ then the military
attache on a diplomatic mission headed by U.S. Sepcial Envoy
Richard Holbrooke _ that would have allowed them to travel by
helicopter. In other words, Clark _ who negotiated, if that's the
word for it _ the military occupation annex to the Dayton accords _
has a long and unhappy relationship with Milosevic. He's far
closer, though, to his fellow Arkansan and Oxford scholar, Bill
Clinton. (Deans, Cox News Service)
</P>
<P>
   KOSOVO-CLARK-BIOBOX _ WASHINGTON _ A biobox on NATO Supreme
Allied Commander Gen. Wesley Clark. (Deans, Cox News Service).
</P>
<P>
   KOSOVOTV _ While CNN journalists covering Kosovo were not
detained for more than a few minutes when NATO forces began their
offensive, they remain in danger - as are any journalists working
in those conditions. This afternoon, it's expected that CNN will
broadcast a special report about their coverage. Phil will cover
this event and also speak to Eason Jordan about the impact of the
danger and diplomacy involved in covering actions such as these.
(Kloer, Atlanta Journal-Constitution)
</P>
<P>
   WASHINGTON
</P>
<P>
   GATES _ WASHINGTON _ Microsoft Chairman Bill Gates and state
attorneys general with a stake in the Microsoft antitrust case are
in Washington. Gates is in town to tout his book,''Business (at)
