   NATIONAL
</P>
<P>
   SEABASS-SHORTAGE _ The fish of the moment is sweet, snowy white
and impossible to overcook. It has never met a treatment it doesn't
like. It is higher than any fish in beneficial omega-3 fatty acids.
With its high oil content, it feels luxurious in your mouth. With
its lack of pinbones poking through the fillets, it feels safe. And
no surprise that it is quickly becoming so overfished that the
commercial harvest will soon become unviable. Prices are up, supply
is way down, and experts predict that Chilean sea bass will in the
next 2-3 years go the way of redfish. (Kessler, Atlanta
Journal-Constitution)
</P>
<P>
   ADAMS-BUSH _ AUSTIN, Texas _ George W. Bush says he didn't grow
up wanting to be president. Neither did the only son of a president
who grew up to be president. Hell, the job didn't even exist until
John Quincy Adams was 22 years old. A look at the life and failed
presidency of J.Q. Adams, a man whose accomplishment GWBush is
trying to match. (Herman, Austin American-Statesman)
</P>
<P>
   JASON _ WEST PALM BEACH, Fla. _ Once he played Jason in ``Friday
the 13th, Part 2,'' victimizing hapless teens. But F. Warrington
Gillet III, the actor behind Jason, says he's a victim now _ and
he's pointing a finger at a Fort Lauderdale law firm that he says
cheated him, and his Palm Beach friends, out of millions. (Clough,
Palm Beach Post)
</P>
<P>
   VOUCHERS _ The Florida Legislature was expected to vote next
week on Gov. Jeb's school voucher program. It's a limited program
that would allow vouchers only in districts where schools are
chronically underperforming, and at this point only a couple of
schools around the entire state might qualify. But it would be
precedent-setting in the South. Depending on when they take this
up, we either advance the vote or cover it. (MWilliams, Atlanta
Journal-Constitution) TENTATIVE
</P>
<P>
   SCIENCE/MEDICINE
</P>
<P>
   PHYSICS-HEAT _ ATLANTA _ Scientists are examining ways to
mitigate the so-called ``heat island'' effect that raises
temperatures in places like metro Atlanta, where development has
led to a loss in tree cover. The research was presented at the
final sessions of the American Physical Society's annual conference
in Atlanta Thursday. (Seabrook, Atlanta Journal-Constitution)
</P>
