<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-DOWNTOWN-SURVIVOR-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
RESENDING TO FIX BYLINE 
HOLOCAUST SURVIVOR THINKS PUBLISHER MORE DANGEROUS THAN WOLVES
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By Steve Bailey 
c.1999 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   In her book, Misha Defonseca, a Holocaust survivor, tells an
extraordinary tale of walking 3,000 miles across Europe in search
of the parents she would never find. It was the wolves that
befriended her that allowed her to survive, she says.
</P>
<P>
   American publishers, she says today, are a much more dangerous
breed of animal.
</P>
<P>
   Just 7 when her parents were taken by the Nazis in war-torn
Belgium, Defonseca spent four years living as a beggar child,
sleeping in the woods, sometimes reduced to eating worms or her own
scabs. She says she saw Nazis murder dozens of children; she killed
a Nazi soldier in self defense.
</P>
<P>
   What makes her story so compelling _ and not everyone believes
it _ is her account of her life and travels with a family of
wolves. From a chance encounter in the woods of Poland, she came to
be accepted by the wolves, she writes, sharing scraps of deer meat
and sleeping against their warm fur on freezing nights. She called
one of them ``Maman,'' French for mother. And it was the wolves who
taught her about freedom. After years of silence, Defonseca told
her story in ``Misha: A Memoire of the Holocaust Years,'' published
two years ago. It has turned into a second nightmare: Nazis, she
says, robbed her of her family; her publisher has robbed her of her
story.
</P>
<P>
   In a lawsuit, Defonseca has charged that tiny Mt. Ivy Press LP
has withheld royalties and underreported sales. In a complaint, she
alleges that Mt. Ivy appears to have transferred the book's foreign
rights to an off-shore entity for $1 ``in a transparent attempt''
to hide their activities. Her probono lawyer, Larry L. Varn of
Sullivan &AMP; Worcester in Boston, also says Mt. Ivy has blocked one
potential movie deal in France, where the book was a bestseller,
Varn says.
</P>
<P>
   Mt. Ivy and its lawyers deny all. They say Defonseca doesn't
understand the publishing business; they say they have disclosed
fully her royalty payments and that things like book-store returns
have reduced sales. The foreign entity is for tax reasons, Ivy
says. In all, Defonseca has earned if not received roughly $100,000
from the book, a number she disputes.
</P>
<P>
   Mt. Ivy is hardly Random House. Its other titles include:
``Gigolos: The Secret Life of Men Who Service Women''; ``Main Dish
Salads''; and ``Venus: A Lover's Guide to Charms, Potions &AMP;
Aphrodisiacs.'' The company's lawyer says Mt. Ivy's headquarter's
address is a post office box in Newton. Mt. Ivy's chief executive,
Brett Kates, says the office in is Blue Belle, Pa. _ in his Dad's
house. Kates, 42, complains that Defonseca has run through several
lawyers in this suit; Kates says he hasn't practiced law since he
was suspended from practice.
</P>
<P>
   Defonseca, 65, blames the whole mess on Mt. Ivy's publisher,
Jane Daniel, who is also being sued by Defonseca's former
colaborator, Vera Lee of Newton. Defonseca says she and her
husband, Maurice, are in danger of losing their Millis home and
have been reduced to taking food from Jewish charities.
</P>
<P>
   ``I would like to see Jane Daniel and Brett Kates eating dog
food, as we had to, while they were withholding at least $27,000
owned to me for several months, somewhere on a bank account in the
West Indies,'' Defonseca says.
</P>
<P>
   Daniel says she feels bad, but says there would have been no
book if not for her. ``People get star struck,'' she says of
Defonseca. An Oprah Winfrey TV crew was filming a segment on the
story _ complete with wolves _ when Defonseca stopped cooperating,
Daniel says. What would that have done for sales?
</P>
<P>
   It's all a shame, Daniel repeats. But the rights belong to Mt.
Ivy. And that's that.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
