<DATE_TIME> 1999-03-25 17:04 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A4097 &Cx1f; tdt-z
u f &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-BOSCAP-FIDELITY-BOS &LR;      03-25 0832
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BOSCAP-FIDELITY-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
RESENDING TO FIX BYLINE 
FIDELITY'S VENTURE CAPITAL OPERATION LOOKING FOR ANOTHER WINNER
</HEADLINE>
  (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 bY STEVEN SYRE AND CHARLES STEIN 
c.1999 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   Is there another Colt in this stable?
</P>
<P>
   Fidelity Ventures, the low-profile venture-capital arm of money
management giant Fidelity Investments, would do well to find
another winner on the scale of Colt Telecom Group PLC in its
portfolio.
</P>
<P>
   For years, the venture arm was one part of Fidelity Capital, the
investment unit that also controlled wholly owned and operated
businesses like the company's newspaper, limousine, and
executive-recruitment subsidiaries. It split off on its own two
months ago and Fidelity Capital's president, Tim Hilton, became the
head of Fidelity Ventures.
</P>
<P>
   Hilton declined to talk to us this week. But a review of
Fidelity Ventures materials in print and on the Internet shows that
the company has more than $300 million invested in young companies
and their emerging technologies. Fidelity's portfolio of
investments now includes nearly four-dozen companies.
</P>
<P>
   Fidelity ranks as a top 20 player among the 200 or so venture
capital firms in New England, according to PriceWaterhouseCoopers,
the accounting firm that tracks the venture business.
</P>
<P>
   Fidelity Ventures may not be the biggest player in the venture
field, but unlike many other venture capital firms it is
bankrolling all of its own investments and not raising funds from
outsiders.
</P>
<P>
   The jewel of the Fidelity Ventures portfolio remains the famed
Colt, a European telecommunications success story that went public
in 1996. Fidelity still owns about half of the company, which has a
market value of $9.5 billion.
</P>
<P>
   The rest of the Fidelity venture portfolio has a decidedly
high-tech flavor. Most of its money is sunk into software,
telecommunications, or health care businesses.
</P>
<P>
   It has also dabbled in modest-size leveraged buyouts and a few
new interests, including education and employer services. Advantage
Schools Inc. of Boston, the charter-school operator,  &UR; yesterday &LR; 
announced a new $25 million round of venture funding from a pack of
firms including Fidelity Ventures, which was one of the company's
original backers.
</P>
<P>
   But beyond Colt, you won't find many well-known names with
wildly successful initial public stock offerings to their credit in
the Fidelity Ventures portfolio. It is stocked with smaller
ventures with relatively obscure names like PakNetX, Future Tense,
and Verbind.
</P>
<P>
   An exception: GeoTel Communications of Lowell, a Fidelity
venture investment that dates back to 1995. GeoTel, which makes
computer telephony software, went public at 12 in 1996 and traded
above 42  &UR; yesterday &LR; .
</P>
<P>
   Executives at other venture firms and the small companies that
seek investment capital say Fidelity can offer a few unique
advantages. Tops on the list: name recognition.
</P>
<P>
   ``The venture business is an almost unbranded business,'' said
Chris Gabrieli of Bessemer Venture Partners in Wellesley, who has
co-invested with Fidelity in Advantage Schools and several other
deals.
</P>
<P>
   ``If you were to ask even sophisticated investors to name any
venture firm, few would know any. Fidelity has enormous brand
value. Compared to a potentially fine venture firm no one has heard
of, the Fidelity name helps companies more with employees, vendors,
and customers.''
</P>
<P>
   Some technology companies can also get something more than the
usual venture offerings _ money and some management help _ from
Fidelity. They can sometimes land a big customer, or even more
importantly, a high-tech site to test new technology inside an
organization that spends hundreds of millions of dollars on
hardware and software every year.
</P>
<P>
   Fidelity has also loaned out a handful of executives from its
huge lineup of technology employees to venture companies in need.
</P>
<P>
   Foundation Technologies of Waltham, a company that develops
Internet software for human resource departments, ran into just
that problem last fall. Fidelity, which was one of the company's
two original venture investors, provided an executive with
specialized Internet skills to step in as the company's active vice
president of engineering.
</P>
<P>
   Foundation chief executive Tod Loofbourrow said his company
selected Fidelity from a field of nearly two dozen interested
venture firms. He said Fidelity was already involved in the
company's field and didn't need a quick payoff to pass through to
other investors.
</P>
<P>
   ``They are very patient capital,'' said Loofbourrow, who hopes
Foundation can go public next year.
</P>
<P>
   Patience aside, there is still the payoff question. Before
Loofbourrow got his money, he had to meet with Fidelity chairman
Edward C. ``Ned'' Johnson III for two hours. For all of his
longterm perspective, Johnson doesn't like to be disappointed.
</P>
<P>
   Steven Syre (929-2918) and Charles Stein (929-2922) can also be
reached by e-mail at boscap(at)globe.com.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
