<HEADER>
A4099 &Cx1f; tad-z
r i &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-B2-BOX-0326-COX     03-25 0348
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-B2-BOX-0326-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    FINALLY, THE B-2 GOES INTO COMBAT
 &HT;    With KOSOVO-B2-0326.
 &HT;    By BOB DEANS 
 &HT;    c.1999 Cox News Service 
<TEXT>
<P>
   B-2 SPIRIT
</P>
<P>
   Overall Mission: The B-2 manned bomber was designed to deliver
both conventional and nuclear bombs over long distances virtually
undetected by radar.
</P>
<P>
   First Combat Mission: The current NATO air campaign against Serb
military targets in Yugoslavia.
</P>
<P>
   Features: The B-2's stealth characteristics allow it to
penetrate the most sophisticated radar defenses and destroy the
most important targets from high altitudes. This increases its
range and provides a better field of view for the B-2's sensors.
Its range is about 6,000 nautical miles without refueling. The
primary aspects of its ``stealthiness'' are classified, but the
B-2's materials, coatings and wing design all contribute. It also
has a crew of only two pilots.
</P>
<P>
   History: The first B-2 was rolled out for public display on Nov.
22, 1988 at Air Force Plant 42 in Palmdale, Calif. Its first flight
was July 17, 1989. Whitman AFB, Mo., is the B-2's only operational
base. The first aircraft, Spirit of Missouri, was delivered Dec.
17, 1993.
</P>
<P>
   Characteristics:
</P>
<P>
   &QR;  Primary function: Multi-role heavy bomber
</P>
<P>
   &QR;  Prime Contractor: Northrop Grumman Corp.
</P>
<P>
   &QR;  Contractor Team: Boeing Military Airplanes Co., General
Electric Aircraft Engine Group and Hughes Training Inc., Link
Division.
</P>
<P>
   &QR;  Power Plant: Four General Electric F-118-GE-100 engines;
17,300 pounds thrust each.
</P>
<P>
   &QR;  Length: 69 feet
</P>
<P>
   &QR;  Height: 17 feet
</P>
<P>
   &QR;  Wingspan: 172 feet
</P>
<P>
   &QR;  Speed: High subsonic
</P>
<P>
   &QR;  Ceiling (altitude): 50,000 feet
</P>
<P>
   &QR;  Takeoff Weight: 336,500 pounds
</P>
<P>
   &QR;  Range: Intercontinental, unrefueled
</P>
<P>
   &QR;  Armament: Conventional or nuclear weapons
</P>
<P>
   &QR;  Payload: 40,000 pounds
</P>
<P>
   &QR;  Crew: Two pilots
</P>
<P>
   &QR;  Unit Cost: $2.1 billion
</P>
<P>
   &QR;  Date Deployed: Dec. 1993
</P>
<P>
   &QR;  Inventory: 21 active
</P>
<P>
   Source: Air Combat Command, Office of Public Affairs, Langley
AFB, Va.
</P>
<P>
   ENDIT
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
