<DOC>
<DOCNO> NYT19990325.0175 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-03-25 17:10 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A4120 &Cx1f; tad-z
u i &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-RUSSIA-ARMY-$ADV28-CO     03-25 1150
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-RUSSIA-ARMY-$ADV28-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    RANK AND FILING OUT: RUSSIA'S ONCE-MIGHTY MILITARY BATTLES ITS
OWN DECAY
 &HT;    With Photos.
 &HT;    With RUSSIA-RECRUIT-$ADV28; ARMY-BOX-$ADV28.
 &HT;    For Use Sun. March 28 And Thereafter.
 &HT;    Moving in (i) international and (w) Washington categories
 &HT;    By CHARLES W. HOLMES
 &HT;    c.1999 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   ST. PETERSBURG, Russia _ He is the embodiment of today's Russian
army: pale, thin and weak.
</P>
<P>
   Anatoly, know by his nickname ``Tolek,'' has been on the run
from the army for three years. During his short few weeks in the
service, he says, he and other recruits were ill-fed and terrorized
by violent hazing within the ranks, and their rations and uniforms
were stolen by officers looking to sell them and pocket the money.
</P>
<P>
   ``I was afraid, everyone was afraid, because you didn't know who
to trust,'' he said, explaining why he ran away.
</P>
<P>
   The once-proud army has been demoralized by its painful
experiences in Afghanistan and Chechnya. Since the breakup of the
Soviet Union in 1991, the military has been hobbled by the same
economic and social problems affecting all of Russia.
</P>
<P>
   The country's economic crisis last August reduced soldiers to
foraging for potatoes in the fields and begging for change in
subway stations. With the ruble's steep evaluation, a new recruit
earns only about $5 a month.
</P>
<P>
   The Russian Defense Ministry estimates about 40,000 deserters
are roaming the country. There are no reliable figures for draft
dodgers, but some 80 percent of the eligible pool of men can obtain
deferments on health grounds or to attend school or family needs.
Inside the army, the suicide rate is high.
</P>
<P>
   As U.S. and NATO warplanes launched strikes this week on Serbia,
Russia ruled out using force to assist its Slavic ally. But there
is little Russia could do, even if it so wished.
</P>
<P>
   Respected military analyst Pavel Felgenhauer, who writes for the
daily Sevodnya, has warned that the current rate of decline in
Russia's ranks leaves the country with a credible nuclear deterrent
with some 6,000 warheads, but vulnerable to attack by a force of
1,000 well-trained guerrillas because of the weakened conventional
forces.
</P>
<P>
   Russia's twice-a-year draft began this month, in which the
government will induct 150,000 new soldiers by the end of May. Many
more who are eligible will be seeking ways to avoid military
service.
</P>
<P>
   Scores of ``mothers' committees'' operate in cities across
Russia seeking to help young men like ``Tolek'' avoid the draft or
leave the army. They sprouted during the war with the breakaway
republic of Chechnya, from 1994-96.
</P>
<P>
   Since the economic squeeze last August, the number of deserters
and draft dodgers has doubled, according to advocacy groups who
work with disaffected soldiers. In a partial amnesty for draft
dodgers last year, some 12,000 young men came out of hiding.
</P>
<P>
   Because of chronic shortages in recent years of supplies and
cuts in training, Russia could fully field only one or two of its
some 70 divisions, analysts say. Airplanes remain in their hangers
for lack of spare parts and fuel. Ships are rusting in port for the
same reason.
</P>
<P>
   The only way to strengthen Russia's army is to reduce its size,
many officials contend. In recent years President Boris Yeltsin has
advocated severe cutbacks in military spending and manpower to
reform a military still bloated from the Soviet era.
</P>
<P>
   ``There is a basic problem: Russia cannot afford the size of the
military it maintains,'' said Valentina Meylnikova, leader of the
mothers' committee in Moscow and an outspoken advocate for an
all-volunteer army. ``We cannot allow this to go on. Russian
soldiers are in tattered uniforms and are going hungry. This is not
what life is supposed to be like in a professional army.''
</P>
<P>
   Russia trimmed its forces by 400,000 in 1998 to 1.2 million
troops, down from a high of 2.5 million earlier this decade.
</P>
<P>
   But the reduction is more akin to desperation layoffs and
no-shows than a well-considered restructuring of the force.
</P>
<P>
   The Chechen War was fought with units that had little or no
field training and struggled with shortages of fuel and spare
parts.
</P>
<P>
   An internal study by Russia's general staff and reprinted in the
respected Russian Independent Military Review said the current
force strength must be cut in half, to no more than 600,000 troops.
The country simply cannot afford more, it said.
</P>
<P>
   Yeltsin's stated intention to convert the military to an
all-volunteer force by the spring of 2000 has been delayed ``until
well into the next decade,'' because Russia lacks the will and
coherent plan to carry it out, according to a recent State
Department report.
</P>
<P>
   Meanwhile, the decline in military living standards has put the
military ``at the low end of the country's economic scale,'' the
study said.
</P>
<P>
   It's an uneasy policy task: soothing generals outraged by the
plan to pare their forces, holding off opposition political leaders
from Communist and nationalist parties attempting to capitalize on
the dissatisfaction and convincing the public that their
morale-battered army can be improved by cutting it back further.
</P>
<P>
   ``Our problem is the world's problem,'' said Alexander Zhilin, a
retired air force colonel and now military analyst for the Moscow
News. ``Russia's military might depends on its strategic nuclear
forces and because of that the more we dismantle our conventional
forces, the more this reliance on nuclear force grows.''
</P>
<P>
   To be sure, Russia places an emphasis on maintaining its aging
nuclear force. Also, selected airborne units and interior ministry
forces in and around Moscow continue to be well supplied and
trained.
</P>
<P>
   Ironically, some of its best troops are not in Russia. Those
serving in United Nations peacekeeping roles in the Balkans and
elsewhere, are equipped and financed by the international
community, not cash-poor Moscow.
</P>
<P>
   As for ``Tolek,'' he hopes to build a case around his medical
history -- underweight and with persistent headaches -- to
demonstrate that he never should have been drafted in the first
place.
</P>
<P>
   But the army, he says, is no place, even for an able-bodied man.
</P>
<P>
   ``Our army is for building dachas for the generals and digging
useless holes,'' he says.
</P>
<P>
   His bitterness aside, independent analysts also question whether
Russia would be able to fight a war if, for instance, the simmering
ethnic troubles on its southern border in the Caucasuses were to
explode.
</P>
<P>
   ``At best, it will take a decade or more to create an efficient
military machine; at worst, the new-found will to tackle the
problems will not survive the difficulties that beset the country
in general and the reform process in particular,'' concluded a
recent report by the respected defense publication, Jane's
Intelligence Review.
</P>
<P>
   ENDI
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
