<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-FAMILY-COLUMN-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
CATCHING UP ON SCIENCE EDUCATION
</HEADLINE>
  (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By LINDA WELTNER 
c.1999 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   Idon't believe how smart I'm getting.
</P>
<P>
   Go ahead. Ask me what e(EQ)mc2 means.
</P>
<P>
   Well, c is the speed of light, and this formula reveals how much
energy is released, not only in nuclear explosions, but in any
energy event. Einstein was driven to develop this equation by the
inadequacies of previous theories, and I know what those
shortcomings were because my husband and I are taking a course
called ``Einstein's Relativity and the Quantum Revolution: Modern
Physics for Non-Scientists.''
</P>
<P>
   You have to understand that I needed a private tutor to pass
high school geometry, that I dropped out of high school chemistry
after three classes because I was already lost, and that I passed
high school physics only because a sympathetic teacher coached me
in the areas he ended up asking about on the final exam. I
concluded from this evidence that I was not gifted in science or
math. Not only did I never dream I could understand this stuff, I
couldn't imagine wanting to understand it.
</P>
<P>
   Until I saw a 12-part video series called ``Canticles of the
Cosmos'' as part of a Unitarian-Universalist Church's adult
education program.
</P>
<P>
   The video introduced me to creation spirituality, an approach to
religion in which science is no longer at war with religious dogma.
In exploring the spiritual dimensions of current scientific
knowledge, cosmologist Brian Swimme divined a direction, even a
spiritual meaning, to the unfolding of the universe. As a result, I
began to feel connected to the stars in a new way. If billions of
years of history was one of God's means of revelation, I wanted to
know everything I could about it.
</P>
<P>
   Jack and I began reading Chet Raymo's ``365 Starry Nights,'' a
self-taught, one-concept-a-night handbook on the magic and the
mystery of the universe. Every night before bed, we'd read a page
and then step outside to take a look for ourselves. It was
impossible to do that on a regular basis and not become fascinated
by the world circling overhead. First we saw double stars with our
binoculars. When our kids gave us a telescope for our anniversary,
we got to see the rings of Saturn and the Great Nebula in Orion's
sword. Jack and I began showing up at Harvard's Smithsonian
Observatory, where monthly talks on subjects like black holes and
spiral galaxies are offered to the public free of charge.
</P>
<P>
   Though I understood less than half of what was said, I
understood enough to want to understand more.
</P>
<P>
   Three years ago, we began attending the Lowell Lecture Series on
astronomy at the Museum of Science, held without charge every
spring. While viewing glorious photos from the Hubbard Telescope, I
listened to speakers who'd actually made the discoveries they were
sharing with us. Soon I was using phrases like ``event horizon''
and ``dark-line spectrum'' with ease. I thought I'd gone just about
as far as I could go, until I stumbled upon the Superstar Teachers
Series in the audio section of our library.
</P>
<P>
   The cassette case describes Middlebury College professor Richard
Wilson as a ``high energy particle,'' and promises that he will
take the listener effortlessly from Copernicus, Newton, and
Einstein to Planck, Heisenberg, and Schroedinger in 12 easy
lectures. Despite the fact that I'd never heard of the last three,
how could I not accept the invitation ``to hold a universe in the
palm of your mind''?
</P>
<P>
   These winter nights, we curl up in bed and listen. My poor
husband, who majored in nuclear physics, struggles to overcome a
head full of obsolete preconceptions while I have no problem at all
imagining speed shrinking and space stretching while the speed of
light races across the sky, constant as, well, constant as the
speed of light.
</P>
<P>
   This is the wonderful part about becoming a lifetime learner, no
matter what topic you choose. You have everything to gain and
nothing to prove. When you're learning for yourself, you decide
when you know enough. You can visit one Web site or read every
available book on the topic. There is no pressure; there are no
tests. You pick your own topic and set your own schedule. Free to
skip over the parts that don't interest you, free to quit in the
middle without losing face, free, on tape at least, to go over the
material as many times as it takes, you can tackle those subjects
you've been afraid of all your life.
</P>
<P>
   You also get to measure your own success. And at the end, you
receive the most prestigious degree there is, in my book, at least.
</P>
<P>
   An immeasurable Degree of Satisfaction.
</P>
<P>
   Linda Weltner is a freelance writer whose column appears each
week in the Globe. Her Web site is http://www.shore.net/weltner.
</P>
</TEXT>
