<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-VIDEO-COLUMN-LADN </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
NEW ON DVD: THE DUKE, BRUNO AND MUSICALS 
</HEADLINE>
  (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By ROB LOWMAN  
 c.1999 Los Angeles Daily News  
<TEXT>
<P>
   LOS ANGELES _ The sales of DVD players continued on a brisk pace
after Christmas with 102,000 sold in January, five times the number
sold last year at the same time. This corresponds with dropping
sticker prices. Low-end models are selling for about $300, while
the average player sold for $422 in 1998.
</P>
<P>
   So, to keep feeding these new machines, studios have been
rolling out truckloads of DVD titles. Here's a look at some of the
more interesting ones that have hit stores in the last month. Most
of them include a number of options _ such as wide-screen formats
and interactive menus _ not available on videotape.
</P>
<P>
   We'll start with the tough guys first. This week, Artisan
released the John Wayne video collection, including three of the
Duke's best on DVD _ ``The Quiet Man (1952),'' ``Rio Grande''
(1950) and ``The Sands of Iwo Jima'' (1949).
</P>
<P>
   ``Quiet'' and ``Rio Grande'' are two films by legendary director
John Ford; in both, Wayne's leading lady is Maureen O'Hara. Ford,
known for his westerns, returned to his Irish roots for ``Quiet,''
a romantic comedy about an American prizefighter and a
strong-willed woman. Filled with blarney, it nevertheless is Ford
and Wayne's most charming film. The DVD includes a featurette on
the making of the film hosted by Leonard Maltin. In ``Rio Grande,''
Wayne and O'Hara battle each other and the Apaches. That film,
along with ``Fort Apache'' and ``She Wore a Yellow Ribbon''
(neither is available in this set) make up Ford's excellent Cavalry
trilogy. ``Iwo Jima,'' directed by Alan Dwan, features one of
Wayne's best performances. He plays tough Sgt. John Stryker, a
battle-hardened Marine who has to train and take a bunch of
recruits into action. Wayne got an Oscar nomination. He didn't win
but eventually bagged a statuette for ``True Grit (1969).''
</P>
<P>
   One tough guy who hasn't muscled his way into an Oscar nod yet
is Bruce Willis. But fans who think he deserves one can take their
frustrations out by watching the ``Die Hard'' trilogy, which was
released by Fox Home Entertainment earlier this month. Actually,
this trio of films is among some of the better action films of the
last decade, and Willis' sarcastic demeanor helps keep the films
lively, even more so than the explosions. The first and third
movies also benefit from having terrific villains _ Alan Rickman in
the original, and Jeremy Irons. The triple pack lists for $79.98 or
$29.98 each.
</P>
<P>
   If your taste runs more to dynamite song-and-dance numbers,
there are a number of new classic releases on the market. The 1962
release ``The Music Man'' (Warner; $24.98), starring Robert Preston
and Shirley Jones, is a corny treat. Led by ``76 Trombones,'' the
score also includes ``Till There Was You,'' a song even covered by
the Beatles. The DVD has a documentary hosted by Jones about the
film.
</P>
<P>
   Jones also co-stars with Gordon MacRae in two of the Rodgers and
Hammerstein musicals released on video by Fox Home Entertainment _
``Carousel'' (1956) and ``Oklahoma!'' (1955). The others are ``The
King and I'' (1956), starring Yul Brynner and Deborah Kerr; ``State
Fair'' (1945) with Dick Haymes and Jeanne Crain; and ``South
Pacific'' (1958) with Mitzi Gaynor and Rossano Brazzi.
</P>
<P>
   The films, which are digitally remastered and THX certified, are
out on VHS but will be released on DVD on April 27. Considering the
added quality and extras you get, it might be worth the wait. The
videos list at $14.98 for pan and scan, $19.98 wide-screen, and the
DVDs are expected to go for $24.98 each.
</P>
<P>
   While all of them were great successes on stage, their film
translations didn't always capture their essences. Still, there are
just so many wonderful Rodgers and Hammerstein songs that any lover
of musicals probably will be willing to forgive any of the films'
weaknesses. &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
