<DATE_TIME> 1999-03-25 17:23 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A4157 &Cx1f; tth-z
r e &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-FILM-EDTV-SPI &LR;      03-25 0538
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-FILM-EDTV-SPI </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
LIKE IT OR NOT, `EDTV' IS STILL NO `TRUMAN SHOW' 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients.)  
 By WILLIAM ARNOLD  
 c.1999 Seattle Post-Intelligencer  
<TEXT>
<P>
   The publicity blitz for Ron Howard's new comedy, ``EDtv,'' is
making a larger-than-usual amount of noise about the fact that the
film is actually a remake of an ``obscure'' French-Canadian film
called ``Louis XIX: King of the Airwaves.''
</P>
<P>
   Curiously, when the same studio, Universal, and same director
remade the 1927 MGM film ``The Fire Brigade'' as 1991's
``Backdraft,'' they didn't feel any need to mention it all, and
conveniently left the fact out of the credits and publicity.
</P>
<P>
   But since their new film is the story of a handsome young man
who becomes the rage of the nation as the hero of a reality
television show, they're understandably a little paranoid. Clearly,
they don't want people to think they're ripping off ``The Truman
Show.''
</P>
<P>
   Still, no one is likely to be fooled. The film seems to be a lot
closer to the high points of ``Truman'' than it is to my memory of
``Louis'' _ which may be obscure, but still managed to score a slot
at the 1994 Seattle International Film Festival.
</P>
<P>
   The Ed of the title is a charming 31-year-old San Francisco
video store clerk (Matthew McConaughey) picked by the True-TV
network to have his unscripted, unrehearsed life put on 24-hour
display to satisfy America's voyeuristic curiosity.
</P>
<P>
   In no time, America falls in love with Ed; his various romances
become a national obsession, and his family and friends all become
media celebrities. Gradually, however, the loss of privacy gets
oppressive. And, as you might expect, Ed's life goes all to heck.
</P>
<P>
   The movie gets by mostly on the laid-back, good-ole-boy, Texas
charm of Matthew McConaughey. Never very convincing as cerebral
types (as in ``Contact,'' ``Amistad'' or ``A Time to Kill''), he's
at his best playing dim-witted slackers (as in ``Dazed and
Confused,'' ``The Newton Boys'' and here.)
</P>
<P>
   It also scores when it stops trying to be hilarious for a moment
to show us the unique corruption of fame, and the agony of what
it's like to be famous and not rich _ to have a face that's
instantly recognizable while not having the protection that only
money can buy.
</P>
<P>
   But most of the action is grindingly familiar, and it's only
so-so as a comedy: overloaded with hundreds of reaction shots of
anonymous people oogling the show; too many bits with Howard's
brother, Clint (a dead-time fixture of every Ron Howard movie); and
too many low-humor gags about private body parts.
</P>
<P>
   Thematically and structurally, it's so similar to ``The Truman
Show'' that it's impossible not to compare them, and ``EDtv'' loses
out. ``Truman'' actually made us believe its outlandish premise to
the point where we gave a considerable emotional investment to its
characters. ``ED'' never does. It is amusing, but finally tiresome
and then instantly forgettable.
</P>
<P>
   EDTV. Directed by Ron Howard. Screenplay by Lowell Ganz &AMP;
Babaloo Mandel. Cast: Matthew McConaughey, Jenna Elfman, Woody
Harrelson, Ellen DeGeneres, Martin Landau, Rob Reiner, Dennis
Hopper. Universal. 123 minutes. Rated PG-13 for some bad-taste
humor.
</P>
<P>
   Grade: C+
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
