<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-CAR-NASCAR-COLUMN-NYTR </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
SPORTS COLUMN: BILL FRANCE STILL PULLS THE STRINGS 
</HEADLINE>
  (mk) 
 By PATRICK ZIER   
 The Ledger, Lakeland, Fla.   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   For Bill France, it's a matter of taking a small step back so he
can move NASCAR a giant step forward.
</P>
<P>
   Prior to this year's Daytona 500, France took himself out of the
day-to-day operation of NASCAR, the governing body of stock car
racing, naming Mike Helton to run the show.
</P>
<P>
   But France remains very much involved in stock car racing's
future as NASCAR's president, and there is no doubt who has final
say.
</P>
<P>
   Based on recent happenings, it appears that NASCAR is on the
verge of unprecedented expansion once 2000 arrives.
</P>
<P>
   First, NASCAR announced it will now negotiate all TV deals for
the Winston Cup, Busch and Craftsman Truck series.
</P>
<P>
   At present, individual tracks negotiate their own TV contracts,
so NASCAR won't be heavily involved until after 2000, when most
current contracts expire.
</P>
<P>
   But with NASCAR dictating terms and playing the various networks
against each other for different packages, rights fees are expected
to skyrocket.
</P>
<P>
   Financial analysts are saying that NASCAR could pull in anywhere
from $300 million to $400 million for the Winston Cup series alone.
</P>
<P>
   To justify that kind of money, NASCAR is going to have to create
a demand for stock car racing in the country's major markets.
</P>
<P>
   By 2002 or 2003, France or business interests closely allied to
the France family will have tracks in operation in all key markets.
</P>
<P>
   France recently entered into an agreement with Donald Trump to
build a track outside New York.
</P>
<P>
   He and Tony George, who owns the Indianapolis Motor Speedway,
are proceeding with plans to build an oval outside Chicago.
</P>
<P>
   And France owns 12 percent of Roger Penske's operation, which
already has tracks running near Los Angeles and Detroit.
</P>
<P>
   Additionally, France is building a track outside Kansas City,
Mo., which could be open by the end of next year, and he controls a
facility in Homestead, Fla., which will host its first Winston Cup
event this season.
</P>
<P>
   France also owns tracks in Daytona, Fla.; Talladega, Ala.;
Darlington, S.C.; Phoenix, Ariz.; and Watkins Glen, N.Y., all stops
on the Winston tour, while Penske owns Rockingham, N.C. George has
Indy.
</P>
<P>
   What all this means is that by the time France gets ready to
negotiate his TV deal, he should be able to deliver an audience in
most major markets throughout the country.
</P>
<P>
   And he has also eliminated the possibility of a split in stock
car racing by outflanking his only potential rival, Bruton Smith,
who simply doesn't have enough tracks now to fight France. Smith
owns tracks in Charlotte, N.C.; Atlanta; Dallas-Fort Worth;
Bristol, Tenn.; and Sears Point, Calif.
</P>
<P>
   So while France may not be as visible as he once was, he still
pulls the strings. And anybody who doesn't think so is likely to
get a good, hard yank.
</P>
<P>
   (The Ledger of Lakeland, Fla., is part of the New York Times
Regional Newspaper Group.)
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
