<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-DAYS-FILM-REVIEW-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
`HEAVEN OF HEAVEN' REVISITED 
</HEADLINE>
   (af)  
 By JANET MASLIN   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEW YORK _ In 1978 Terrence Malick, who had once worked as a
wheat harvester, made a rapturously beautiful film well remembered
for its golden fields and sublime magic-hour light. But ``Days of
Heaven,'' now opening for a two-week revival at the Film Forum,
looks different today.
</P>
<P>
   Its thematic and stylistic resemblances to ``The Thin Red Line''
are striking, and hindsight casts much of it in a nostalgic glow.
This film is nominally about a pastoral idyll in an all-too-fragile
paradise, but now it brings to mind another kind of heaven: the era
when films this eccentric, daring and original were not unexpected,
and not the flukes they would be today.
</P>
<P>
   The casting alone is enough to make ``Days of Heaven'' a special
curiosity. In his first film role, Sam Shepard broods
charismatically as a rich, lonely farmer whose fate becomes
intertwined with those of three migrant workers from Chicago. And
as one of those workers, the pre-``American Gigolo'' Richard Gere
cuts an incongruously alluring figure, bristling with sexual energy
and managing to do his farm work in well-tailored black.
</P>
<P>
   Gere's Bill poses as the brother of Abby, the fetching prairie
goddess who is played by Brooke Adams, though in fact they are
lovers. Their little quasi-family is completed by teen-age Linda
Manz, with her feisty New York accent and angelic look.
</P>
<P>
   Malick sentimentalizes these laborers in ways that would seem
naive if the film's visual sophistication were not so phenomenal.
And he uses Ms. Manz's unforgettable voice-over narration to fill
gaps among characters not given to small talk. Dialogue here seems
deliberately stiff and spare.
</P>
<P>
   As ``Days of Heaven'' creates a rivalry between Bill and the
farmer for Abby's attentions, it works in ways very similar to
those of ``The Thin Red Line.'' Here too is the sense of a
pristine, exquisitely sensitive Eden that falls victim to mankind's
darker passions. (``Nobody's perfect,'' Ms. Manz intones. ``There
was never a perfect person around. You just got half Devil and half
angel in you.'')
</P>
<P>
   And here is the same peculiar verbal naivete offset by
astonishing visual poetry. From the foreboding that accompanies the
workers' arrival to one of the most Biblical-looking calamities
ever captured on film, ``Days of Heaven'' (shot by both Nestor
Almendros and Haskell Wexler, scored by Ennio Morricone, and
featuring Jack Fisk's inspired art direction) is as haunting as its
vision of a crystal glass dropped into moonlit water. It lives up
to its title.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
