<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-DOUG-FILM-REVIEW-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
`DOUG'S FIRST MOVIE': IN WHICH HERMAN MELVILLE, A BLUE MONSTER,
WEARS WIG 
</HEADLINE>
   (Eds: Production notes are at end of review)  
 (af)  
 By ANITA GATES   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   Children who go to see ``Doug's First Movie'' will come home
knowing the name Herman Melville. Of course they will know it only
as the name of the gentle, soulful-eyed blue monster from Lucky
Duck Lake, but that's better than nothing. (The monster gets the
name because while visiting a human family's house it tries to eat
``Moby-Dick.'' In hardcover.)
</P>
<P>
   ``Doug's First Movie,'' based on the ABC Saturday morning series
now known as ``Disney's Doug'' (on Nickelodeon, it was just
``Doug''), is not inspired children's entertainment, but it has a
certain charm. Actually the animated world inhabited by Doug
Funnie, a likable 12{-year-old with a flat head and pin-dot eyes,
is more appealing in still photographs than in much of the film.
</P>
<P>
   Doug lives in Bluffington, which is pretty much owned by Bill
Bluff, the owner of Bluffco Industries and the richest man in town
(in the tradition of Potter in ``It's a Wonderful Life''). The most
popular hangouts for young people are Swirly's, for hamburgers and
ice cream, and Funkytown, an amusement park stuck in the '70s. In
this world, dogs _ at least Doug's dog, Porkchop _ play the piano.
</P>
<P>
   The plot involves Doug's discovery of the Lucky Duck Lake
monster, which turns out to have the personality of E.T. Doug and
his best friend, Skeeter, try to protect the monster (which hides
out at Doug's house, often under the bed, where monsters are meant
to live) while exposing Bluffco's criminal pollution of the lake.
At one point, this involves plopping a blond wig on Herman and
passing him off as an exchange student named Hermione.
</P>
<P>
   In a romantic subplot, Doug tries to win the heart of his
longtime pal Patti Mayonnaise. The town's bad boys are busy
building a robot called Robocrusher, which inexplicably turns into
a British nanny. And everything comes together at the big
Valentine's Day dance.
</P>
<P>
   ``Doug's First Movie'' is the voice of good advice. ``It's
important to do the right thing,'' Doug says at the end, no matter
what other people think. To the credit of the screenwriter, Ken
Scarborough, the film sometimes makes fun of its own guidance:
``Violence is only for those who have run out of good ideas,'' Doug
announces during a fantasy in which he's a superhero. After which a
monster, a bad one, promptly swallows him.
</P>
<P>
   There are also some nice visual images, including a crowd of
reporters in identical beige raincoats, brown fedoras and black
sunglasses.
</P>
<P>
   You couldn't call Bluffington multiracial, but the characters do
have a variety of skin colors. Doug is beigey-pink, Skeeter is sort
of aqua, Patti is light brown and Roger (the leader of the bad
boys) is green. Let's hope Jerry Falwell's people don't see this
film; several characters' faces and the entire Beebe Bluff School
building are lavender. &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   PRODUCTION NOTES
</P>
<P>
   `DOUG'S FIRST MOVIE'
</P>
<P>
   Directed by Maurice Joyce; written by Ken Scarborough, created
by Jim Jinkins, based on original characters developed by Jinkins
and Joe Aaron; animator, Kieran Dowling; edited by Alysha Nadine
Cohen and Christopher K. Gee; music by Mark Watters; produced by
Jinkins, David Campbell, Melanie Grisanti and Jack Spillum;
released by Walt Disney Pictures.
</P>
<P>
   WITH THE VOICES OF: Thomas McHugh (Doug Funnie, Lincoln), Fred
Newman (Skeeter, Dink, Porkchop, Ned), Chris Phillips (Roger Klotz,
Boomer, Larry, Chiminy), Constance Shulman (Patti Mayonnaise),
Frank Welker (Herman Melville), Doug Preis (Funnie, Bluff, Willie,
Chalky, Bluff Agent No. 1), Guy Hadley (Guy Graham), Alice Playten
(Beebe Bluff, Elmo), Eddie Korbich (Al and Moo Sleech,
Robocrusher), Bruce Bayley Johnson (Swirley) and Becca Lish (Judy
Funnie, Mrs. Funnie, Connie).
</P>
<P>
   Running time: 87 minutes.
</P>
<P>
   This film is rated G. &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
