<HEADER>
A4175 &Cx1f; tab-z
r l &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-EASTER-GROWN-UP-FAITH     03-25 0781
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-EASTER-GROWN-UP-FAITH-NYTSF </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
EASTER IS ABOUT GROWN-UP FAITH 
</HEADLINE>
   (Commentary)  
 &HT;    
 &HT;    (Editors: This very popular Easter column by Diana Butler Bass
was also offered last year.)
 &HT;    
 &HT;    (To purchase this ``separate buy'' article from the New York
Times Syndicate please contact syndicate sales representative DEBRA
WEYDERT at 732-390-4480)
 &HT;    
 By DIANA BUTLER BASS  
 (Distributed by New York Times Special Features)  
 &HT;    
 &HT;    When I was a girl, Christmas far eclipsed Easter as my favorite
holiday.
 &HT;    Anticipation gripped me for weeks as I awaited Santa's visit and
all those presents.
 &HT;    Easter paled by comparison. Although my parents bought me a new
dress and spring coat, the Easter Bunny and his basket of candy
appeared Scrooge-like compared to Santa.
 &HT;    Then there was church. At Christmas, the baby Jesus, his
beautiful mother, the angels, shepherds and wise men entranced me.
Christmas' simplicity spoke to my childhood world.
 &HT;    But Easter? It made no sense. Although the baby grew up and
helped some people, others got so angry with him that they killed
him. God didn't like this, so he raised him from the dead.
 &HT;    Apparently, Easter doesn't make sense to many Americans.
Although 66 percent of us attend church on Easter Sunday, fully 20
percent admit to not understanding Easter's message.
 &HT;    The holiest day for Christians, Easter is about grown-up faith.
Jesus Christ, loving and sinless, suffers and dies at the hands of
fearful people. To prove the power of love, God raises Jesus from
the grave.
 &HT;    Easter's message startles: Christ has died. Christ has risen.
Death and resurrection.
 &HT;    Grown-up faith? Yes. Believing in a virgin birth, a cute baby,
and angelic hosts is easy stuff in comparison. But new life out of
death?
 &HT;    Mature faith gazes into the mystery of suffering and
resurrection. Only from life's unwanted pain and darkness can new
insight, wisdom and unconditional love arise.
 &HT;    Fifteen years ago, a friend suffered a terrible car accident.
Wrapped around a tree, his Volkswagen encased his twisted form
until paramedics cut him loose and rushed him to the hospital.
 &HT;    Amazed that he lived, the doctors said he would never regain
consciousness. Poised between life and death, he slept in a coma.
We anointed him with oil and prayed.
 &HT;    Unbelievably, he recovered _ even to the point of graduating
from college. As a result of his experience, he became a nurse who
treated those dying from AIDS.
 &HT;    For him, suffering brought forth compassion and service.
 &HT;    A few years ago, he died of AIDS. In the midst of his own pain,
he worked to heal others. No miraculous recovery this time. He
suffered only to suffer again.
 &HT;    Trying to come to terms with his death, I realized existence
moves from one death to another. Without the hope of new life, the
human story is little more than senseless tragedy.
 &HT;    But Easter insists upon _ indeed, Easter shouts _ triumph over
an endless cycle of suffering.
 &HT;    Hanging on the cross, Jesus suffered. In his pain, he cried out,
``Father, forgive them. They know not what they do.''
 &HT;    Breathing his last, he sighed, ``It is finished.'' Then he died.
 &HT;    Finished. Death is the ultimate end. As I grew up and began to
understand death, I reeled under its terror. Eternal nothingness.
It is finished.
 &HT;    The heart of the Easter story lies in Jesus' suffering. Good
Friday and Easter Sunday embrace in joyful triumph as the cross
leads to the empty tomb. Resurrection overcomes death.
 &HT;    Little children, charming in their Easter finery, chase each
other around the churchyard and hunt for colored eggs. They enjoy
Easter, but they don't grasp its power because, for the most part,
they haven't suffered.
 &HT;    Adults often do everything possible to escape pain and
suffering. But not until we grow up and face ``it is finished,''
can Easter have any meaning.
 &HT;    For Jesus it wasn't finished. After three days, God overcame the
horrifying injustice of the cross and raised him from the dead.
 &HT;    This fundamental theological insight _ that suffering brings
forth new life _ is adult faith. Although hard to believe, once it
is embraced, we find true freedom.
 &HT;    As the old hymn reminds us, ``He is risen! Death is conquered,
we are free!''
 &HT;    
 &HT;    ----
 &HT;    
 &HT;    c.1999 Diana Butler
<TEXT>
<P>
   (Diana Butler Bass, Ph.D., writes a religion column for the
Santa Barbara News-Press and is associate professor of religious
studies at Rhodes College in Memphis, Tenn. Her latest book is
``Standing Against the Whirlwind: Evangelical Episcopalians in 19th
Century America,'' published by Oxford University Press.)
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-03-25-99 1735EST &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> NYT19990325.0186 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-03-25 17:37 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A4176 &Cx1f; taf-z
u e &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-JUDY-FILM-REVIEW-NYT &LR;      03-25 0998
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-JUDY-FILM-REVIEW-NYT </SLUG>
  
 `JUDY BERLIN': LOVE IN A SUBURB OF THE '50s  
 (Eds: Production notes are at end of review)  
 (af)  
 By STEPHEN HOLDEN   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEW YORK _ Much of ``Judy Berlin,'' Eric Mendelsohn's
evocatively eerie meditation on modern suburbia, takes place during
what may be the longest solar eclipse known to movies. That solar
event in the middle of a sleepy late September afternoon draws the
lonely, withdrawn inhabitants of a middle-class Long Island town
out of their immaculate houses to wander through the deserted
streets like zombies stirring to life after a long, silent sleep.
</P>
<P>
   As they encounter one another in an apocalyptic gloom, in which
the street lights seem to cast a nuclear glow, they tentatively
reach out to reconnect with one another in ways they haven't done
in years.
</P>
<P>
   The first feature film of Mendelsohn, a former costume design
assistant to Woody Allen, ``Judy Berlin'' is set in Babylon on Long
Island, but it feels more like that eternal television limbo of
dark shadows and anxious faces, ``The Twilight Zone.''
</P>
<P>
   Suburban alienation and boredom may have been done to death by
movies and by ``The Twilight Zone'' itself, many of whose episodes
were saturated in suburban angst. But Mendelsohn's fusion of
science fiction and Chekhovian melancholy finds a fresh perspective
on a familiar theme.
</P>
<P>
   The black-and-white cinematography helps give this contemporary
story a timeless aura. Like ``Pleasantville,'' which ``Judy
Berlin'' sometimes resembles, the movie has the stifling ethos of
an eternally rerunning 1950s sitcom whose characters are either
tranquilized or sleepwalking.
</P>
<P>
   The movie feels especially '50s when it goes indoors and the
camera lingers over furniture, kitchen appliances and cabinets full
of neatly arranged bric-a-brac.
</P>
<P>
   It is the filmmaker's subtly drawn characters that keep ``Judy
Berlin'' from becoming mired in suburban-angst cliches. Madeline
Kahn and Bob Dishy are Alice and Arthur Gold, a compulsively talky
housewife and her taciturn husband, an elementary school principal
who exudes a deep unspoken disappointment and fatigue.
</P>
<P>
   The couple have a 30-year-old son, David (Aaron Harnick), an
aspiring filmmaker recently returned from Los Angeles who wanders
around the house in a state of agitated depression, fighting back
tears.
</P>
<P>
   The movie crosscuts among members of the Gold household, their
neighbors and the school where Arthur presides as principal. The
fall term has just begun, and Sue Berlin (Barbara Barrie), an
excessively polite and buttoned-up teacher, is instructing the
pupils on how to view the imminent solar eclipse without hurting
their eyes.
</P>
<P>
   In the middle of her demonstration a retired teacher, Dolores
Engler (Bette Henritze), with Alzheimer's disease, wanders into the
classroom and momentarily commands the children's attention. The
clash of authority, in which Arthur intercedes, leaves Sue in
tears. As Arthur comforts her, their unexpressed romantic feelings
well up unexpectedly.
</P>
<P>
   Adding to Sue's unhappiness is the imminent departure of her
spunky daughter Judy (Edie Falco), an aspiring actress who has been
working in period costume as a milkmaid in a historical village,
for Los Angeles.
</P>
<P>
   The movie's wittiest scene follows a group of tourists around
this make-believe 1857 farm as a guide explains in wooden tones the
grueling rituals of mid-19th-century agricultural life on Long
Island. The comparison between then and now is tacit. Life may not
be as hard today, but it is just as boring.
</P>
<P>
   Judy, whom Ms. Falco plays with a winning verve, is the only
live wire in this heap of downed power lines. Garrulous and
optimistic, she is about to undertake the same journey westward
that David made. And when the two, who were high school classmates,
run into each other on the street you can feel the attraction of
opposites. Her optimism rushes to fill his despair, while his gloom
tugs her down to earth.
</P>
<P>
   Much of the dramatic tension of a movie that at times moves too
slowly derives from a sense that the filmmaker is biting his tongue
to keep from turning these people into biting satirical
caricatures.
</P>
<P>
   At first Ms. Kahn's Alice seems like the kind of insufferable
yammerer who would drive anyone mad. But as the movie goes along
her inane chatter seems more like a desperate psychic survival
tool. And at a moment when she fears she has lost her husband, she
shows a flash of insight. ``I ground him down,'' she observes
bluntly.
</P>
<P>
   Dishy gives the film's deepest performance as a man so weary and
long-suffering that all his dialogue comes in carefully measured
murmurs. ``Judy Berlin'' is the rare movie in which the pauses,
silences and things that remain unsaid by the characters are as
eloquent as anything that comes out of their mouths.
</P>
<P>
   If ``Judy Berlin,'' which New Directors/New Films is showing at
the Museum of Modern Art Friday evening at 6 and 6:30 and Saturday
afternoon at 3:30, is an impressive exercise in cinematic mood, it
is a very small movie whose narrow, claustrophobic vision
concentrates on only a single aspect of suburban life. The film
would become tedious if it lasted even a minute longer. &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   PRODUCTION NOTES
</P>
<P>
   `JUDY BERLIN'
</P>
<P>
   Written, directed and edited by Eric Mendelsohn; director of
photography, Jeffrey Seckendorf; music by Michael Nicholas;
production designer, Charlie Kulsziski; produced by Rocco Caruso.
Friday night at 6 and 6:30 and Saturday at 3:30 p.m. at the Roy and
Niuta Titus Theater, Museum of Modern Art, as part of the 28th New
Directors/New Films series of the Film Society of Lincoln Center
and Department of Film of The Museum of Modern Art.
</P>
<P>
   WITH: Barbara Barrie (Sue Berlin), Bob Dishy (Arthur Gold), Edie
Falco (Judy Berlin), Madeline Kahn (Alice Gold), Bette Henritze
(Dolores Engler), Anne Meara (Bea), Julie Kavner (Marie) and Aaron
Harnick (David Gold).
</P>
<P>
   Running time: 93 minutes.
</P>
<P>
   This film is not rated. &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
