<DATE_TIME> 1999-03-25 17:42 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A4179 &Cx1f; tad-z
r a &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-PHYSICS-HEAT26-COX     03-25 0546
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-PHYSICS-HEAT26-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    SCIENCE/HEALTH: Scientist's cure for hot summers: Paint it white
 &HT;    The American Physical Society's 100th annual meeting
 &HT;    By Charles Seabrook
 &HT;    c. 1999 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   ATLANTA _ A partial solution to the summertime ``urban heat
island'' that plagues Atlanta and other big cities might be to use
lighter-colored materials in buildings and paving.
</P>
<P>
   The urban heat and discomfort ``can be relieved by as much as 4
degrees Fahrenheit if everyone installed whiter materials during
new construction and resurfacings,'' said researcher Melvin
Pomerantz of the Lawrence Berkeley National Laboratory in
California.
</P>
<P>
   ``We recommend that engineering and building standards adopt
cooler materials,'' he said in Atlanta at the 100th-anniversary
meeting of the American Physical Society.
</P>
<P>
   Pomerantz said it is ``well-documented'' that major cities are
warmer than their rural surroundings, an effect known as urban heat
islands. Researchers with the National Aeronautics and Space
Administration and the University of Georgia have found that the
city of Atlanta can have temperatures up to 10 degrees Fahrenheit
above surrounding areas, disrupting weather patterns and causing
thunderstorms south of the city.
</P>
<P>
   In Atlanta, the loss of trees is a major reason for the urban
heat island. But, as in other cities, the causes also include the
use of dark-colored materials for roofs and pavement, which absorb
sunlight.
</P>
<P>
   Dark materials ``can become very hot, more than 70 degrees above
the air temperature,'' Pomerantz said. The hot surfaces then heat
the air, which increases demand for air conditioning and can cause
smog to form.
</P>
<P>
   Whiter surfaces reflect sunlight, causing surfaces to stay
cooler. Pomerantz and his colleagues estimate that if all possible
surfaces nationwide were cooler, the energy and smog savings would
be about $10 billion per year. Cooler surfaces in Chicago might
have prevented many of the 700 heat-related deaths of mostly
elderly people in that city during a heat wave in the summer of
1995, Pomerantz said.
</P>
<P>
   Researchers with NASA's Global Hydrology and Climate Center in
Huntsville, Ala., are working with several groups in Georgia to
help roofers, builders, paving contractors and others learn about
the benefits of using lighter materials.
</P>
<P>
   In another report at the APS meeting Thursday, Princeton
University physicist Freeman Dyson said that many of the climate
models used to make long-range weather forecasts are unreliable
because they still use ``fudge factors'' rather than physics to
represent important things such as evaporation, clouds and
rainfall.
</P>
<P>
   One major shortcoming, Dyson said, is that the climatic models
do not predict the existence of the phenomena known as El Nino.
``Since El Nino is a major feature of the observed climate, any
model that fails to predict it is clearly deficient,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   ``This does not mean that climate models are worthless; they are
not yet adequate tools for predicting climate.''
</P>
<P>
   ON THE WEB: Our site offers full daily coverage by the
Journal-Constitution.
</P>
<P>
   www.ajc.com.links/
</P>
<P>
   Charles Seabrook writes for the Atlanta Journal-Constitution.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
