</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-GIANTS-FILM-REVIEW-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
`AMONG GIANTS':THE UNEXPECTED CHARMS OF A CRAGGY KIND OF GUY 
</HEADLINE>
   (Eds: Production notes are at end of review)  
 (af)  
 By STEPHEN HOLDEN   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   The free-spirited daredevils who cavort through ``Among Giants''
are about as close to American cowboys as you are likely to find in
a British film set in contemporary England. Rugged rock climbers
from the working class, they earn their living taking risky
free-lance work painting the electrical towers connecting power
lines over hundreds of miles of English landscape.
</P>
<P>
   In their spare time, these paint-smeared wretches hang out in
pubs where the musical fare is American country. While working as a
team at dizzying elevations, smacking paint against the girders of
power stations looming over the moors around Sheffield, they join
voices to sing American pop songs like ``Stand by Me.''
</P>
<P>
   It's no coincidence that these offbeat characters should have
the same hardy spirit as the unemployed miners in ``The Full
Monty.'' Both ``Among Giants'' and ``The Full Monty'' share the
same screenwriter, Simon Beaufoy. Like ``The Full Monty,'' ``Among
Giants'' goes out of its way to celebrate the earthy sexual
magnetism of good old blokes with craggy faces, some of whom are on
the far side of 40.
</P>
<P>
   Ray, the movie's weather-beaten central character, is played by
that wonderful British character actor Pete Postlethwaite, who
brings a characteristically gruff, low-keyed authority to his first
screen role as a romantic lead. Playing opposite him is Rachel
Griffiths, who makes an impressive turnabout from her portrayal of
Jacqueline du Pre's sweetly self-sacrificing older sister in
``Hilary and Jackie.''
</P>
<P>
   Here, she is Gerry, a wiry, curt, backpacking mountaineer from
Australia who is drifting around England pursuing outdoor adventure
and trying to avoid romantic entanglements. If Postlethwaite and
Ms. Griffiths don't exactly ignite the screen with white heat,
together they strike enough sparks to make you believe in an
attraction whose intensity catches them both by surprise.
</P>
<P>
   Ray and Gerry meet while she is hitchhiking around looking for
cliffs to scale, and she impulsively asks to join Ray's crew,
becoming its only female member. The love that develops between her
and Ray, who is divorced with two children and a bitter ex-wife, is
something that sneaks up on them. That bond has a lot to do with
their being fellow adventurers who share a fear of commitment.
</P>
<P>
   The film's boldest scene follows Ray and Gerry as they frolic
naked in the cascading waters of a nuclear power plant. And the
sight of a middle-aged actor's less than model-perfect body
un-self-consciously exhibited in this scene of romantic horseplay
strikes a small but welcome blow for movie realism.
</P>
<P>
   ``Among Giants,'' directed by Sam Miller, is essentially a group
portrait of working class Englishmen, their life style and their
love-hate relationship with a profession that's both dangerous and
financially insecure.
</P>
<P>
   That profession's cowboy mystique is embodied by Ray's much
younger best friend and roommate, Steve (James Thornton), a hothead
and womanizer of considerable charm who views Gerry with a mixture
of suspicion and suppressed desire. Thornton's performance gives
the movie a necessary Woody Harrelsonesque shot of adrenaline.
</P>
<P>
   ``Among Giants,'' which opens Friday in Manhattan, is breezily
entertaining, but fairly predictable. Until close to the end, it
successfully avoids the sort of aerial daredevil suspense that a
Hollywood version of the same story would have insisted on throwing
in within the first 15 minutes.
</P>
<P>
   Eventually, however, it succumbs to melodrama in several
tying-things-together scenes that feel rushed and halfhearted.
Fortunately, that loss of balance comes late enough not to ruin the
rest of the movie. &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   PRODUCTION NOTES
</P>
<P>
   `AMONG GIANTS'
</P>
<P>
   Directed by Sam Miller; written by Simon Beaufoy; director of
photography, Witold Stok; edited by Elen Pierce Lewis and Paul
Green; music by Tim Atack; production designer, Luana Hanson;
produced by Stephen Garrett; released by Fox Searchlight Pictures. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   WITH: Pete Postlethwaite (Ray), Rachel Griffiths (Gerry), James
Thornton (Steve), Lennie James (Shovel), Andy Serkis (Bob), Rob
Jarvis (Weasel) and Alan Williams (Frank). &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Running time: 93 minutes.
</P>
<P>
   ``Among Giants'' is rated R (Under 17 requires accompanying
parent or adult guardian). It has nudity (including full frontal
male), sexual situations and abundant profanity. &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
