<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-FINGERS-FILM-REVIEW-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
`THE STICKY FINGERS OF TIME': COOL, CHIC AND TRAVELING THROUGH
TIME 
</HEADLINE>
  (Eds: Publication notes appear at end of review.) 
(DW) 
 By ANITA GATES   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   Not every time traveler is a wide-eyed innocent (Michael J. Fox
in ``Back to the Future,'' Kathleen Turner in ``Peggy Sue Got
Married,'' Malcolm McDowell in ``Time After Time''), mouth agape at
the wonders on every corner. Some, like Tucker Harding in ``The
Sticky Fingers of Time,'' take the experience in stride.
</P>
<P>
   One morning in 1953, Tucker (Terumi Matthews, best known for
having played Madonna in two television movies), a New York writer
whose real name is Violet, gets up from her typewriter, kisses her
girlfriend goodbye, goes out to buy coffee and finds herself
transported to 1997. At a bar that evening, she runs into a woman
who has bought her novel from a secondhand book bin, but kept only
the cover.
</P>
<P>
   ``Too bad,'' says Tucker, taking a long, slow drag on her
cigarette. ``You could have helped me with the ending. I just
started writing it this morning.''
</P>
<P>
   Drew, an East Village type, is skeptical. ``This book is 40
years old,'' she says.
</P>
<P>
   Tucker explains, ``It's been a long day.''
</P>
<P>
   ``The Sticky Fingers of Time,'' written and directed by Hilary
Brougher and made for a reported $250,000, works, in its
deliberately low-key way. It is probably the first film to combine
the time-travel genre with an A-bomb-mutation plot (which in 1950s
horror movies resulted in giant ants and giant crabs) and lesbian
chic.
</P>
<P>
   Tucker travels through time because she viewed an atom-bomb test
(she was writing a lucrative magazine article about it) and the
fallout upset her ``code'' (which, as her friend Isaac explains, is
to the soul as DNA is to the body). There are a number of ``time
freaks'' like her, says Isaac (James Urbaniak), who is one himself
and manages to look hip and perfectly at home in both periods, a
fashion and attitude blend of Robert Oppenheimer and David Byrne.
In fact, some time freaks are dangerous, like the ones who attack
Drew's girlfriend, Gorge (Samantha Buck), in the dentist's chair.
Isaac has brought Tucker to the 1990s to help her escape whoever
was about to murder her in the 1950s, but things don't work out
exactly as he planned.
</P>
<P>
   Eventually the plot of ``Sticky Fingers,'' which opens Friday at
the Screening Room, becomes a little too existential for comfort,
and the villains seem too much like self-consciously odd
performance artists. But overall this is a satisfying film,
offering the true joy of time travel: the opportunity for a fresh
look at our culture, our moment in time. The humor works, and
Teresa Mastropierro, the production designer, deserves a round of
applause for the great period detail.
</P>
<P>
   PRODUCTION NOTES:
</P>
<P>
   `THE STICKY FINGERS OF TIME'
</P>
<P>
   Written and directed by Hilary Brougher; director of
photography, Ethan Mass; edited by Sabine Hoffman and Ms. Brougher;
music by Miki Navazio; production designer, Teresa Mastropierro;
produced by Isen Robbins and Susan Stover; released by Strand
Releasing and Good Machine.
</P>
<P>
   With: Terumi Matthews (Tucker), Belinda Becker (Ofelia), James
Urbaniak (Isaac), Amanda Vogel (Girl in Window), Nicole Zaray
(Drew), Samantha Buck (Gorge) and Leo Marks (Dex).  &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Running time: 81 minutes.
</P>
<P>
   This film is not rated.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-03-25-99 1744EST &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> NYT19990325.0191 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-03-25 17:45 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A4183 &Cx1f; ttj-z
u k &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-MEANS-COLUMN-HNS &LR;      03-25 0911
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-MEANS-COLUMN-HNS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
DRAGGING DOWN THE SUPREME COURT 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients.)  
 By MARIANNE MEANS  
 c.1999 Hearst Newspapers  
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON _ Of the three branches of government, only the
Supreme Court retains the institutional respect that used to be
automatic but now barely exists for the White House and Congress in
the wake of the nasty impeachment charade.
</P>
<P>
   Few voters are looking any more for principled leadership from
the disgraced, pragmatic president or the narrow-minded,
sermonizing conservatives who dominate Congress. But the nine
black-robed justices are still considered pillars of legal
integrity, influenced by philosophical outlook but essentially
reliable guardians of the Constitution and the law.
</P>
<P>
   The high bench is in grave danger, however, of toppling into the
partisan cesspool that infects the rest of official Washington.
Many politicians are determined to bring the judicial branch down
to their own low standards, undercutting the grand democratic
concepts of separation of powers and judicial independence.
</P>
<P>
   If we can't trust the Supreme Court to do the right thing simply
because it's the right thing, whom can we trust? If the court
develops a reputation for doing the political thing because it's
the political thing, this republic is in deep trouble.
</P>
<P>
   The high bench is not immune to political tides, shifting to the
right or left as presidents appoint justices in tune with their own
philosophy to replace those named by prior presidents with rival
ideologies. But philosophical approach is one thing. Putting on
that black robe with the specific goal of overturning a prior court
decision is quite another.
</P>
<P>
   Abortion is at the center of this. Antiabortion activists are
demanding that the Republican presidential candidates swear they
will put forward for the Supreme Court only those nominees who
pledge to overturn Roe vs. Wade, the 1973 decision that legalized
abortion.
</P>
<P>
   The inflexible specificity of this demand is a frontal assault
on our constitutional system. It would transform the high court
into a totally political rather than primarily judicial body. It
would trivialize and degrade the solemnity of a legal process that
must be legitimate if it is to be obeyed.
</P>
<P>
   Only once before has a president named Supreme Court justices
with the openly acknowledged task of overturning a previous court
decision. It is not a pretty precedent.
</P>
<P>
   In 1870, President Ulysses S. Grant named two new justices who
earned the honor by promising to reverse a prior decision that had
invalidated a legal tender act compelling the public to accept
paper money. With the addition of the pair, Grant had a majority on
the court and within one year he had his reversal.
</P>
<P>
   All the GOP candidates insist they are opposed to abortion, but
some are more dogmatic than others. Gary Bauer and Patrick Buchanan
are the chief advocates of restricting Supreme Court nominees to
committed antiabortionists who would sit in judgment with a
pre-ordained goal of criminalizing the procedure.
</P>
<P>
   They do not mention how they expect such a person to be
confirmed by a Senate sharply divided on the subject. (President
George Bush, remember, got Clarence Thomas and David Souter
confirmed in part because neither had a record on abortion and both
denied holding any opinion.)
</P>
<P>
   Texas Gov. George W. Bush is cagey, saying that he does not
think the nation is ready to overturn Roe vs. Wade and therefore
won't fight for it. An aide says his policy is to appoint ``judges
who share his philosophy that judges should interpret the law and
not legislate from the bench.'' So-called legislating from the
bench, of course, is in the eye of the beholder and can mean
whatever Bush wants it to mean.
</P>
<P>
   Elizabeth Dole is also vague, refusing to elaborate for the
moment on the details of where she stands. Sen. John McCain's
spokesman says McCain has an antiabortion record but that it's
``too early'' to address Supreme Court qualifications.
</P>
<P>
   Steve Forbes says that in naming Supreme Court justices ``my
model would be Justice Antonin Scalia,'' an outspoken abortion
opponent who is the court's most conservative jurist. Not a direct
commitment, but certainly suggestive.
</P>
<P>
   Former Vice President Dan Quayle has presumably forgotten that
he once said if his daughter had an unwanted pregnancy, he would
``support her in whatever decision she'd make.'' Now he insists he
would pick for the Supreme Court judges who ``share'' an opposition
to abortion that is ``rooted in conscience,'' as he claims his to
be.
</P>
<P>
   On the opposite side, President Clinton and Vice President Al
Gore also understand the importance of the Supreme Court in the
abortion debate. They both defend the constitutional right to
liberty and the implied right to privacy that form the legal basis
of Roe vs. Wade. Clinton's two high court appointees, Ruth Bader
Ginsburg and Stephen Breyer, fit that thinking.
</P>
<P>
   Clinton admits that he would never nominate an opponent of Roe.
But he insists that beyond protecting the principle of a woman's
right to choose, he would be ``uncomfortable'' quizzing a potential
nominee about his or her views on the various restrictions the
courts have been considering, and he has not done so.
</P>
<P>
   This is no small distinction. This is the difference between
trivializing the judicial system and treating it as a co-equal
governmental power that may be influenced but never subsumed.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
