<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-SWARTZ-COLUMN-$ADV01-NYTR </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
COLUMN: THE RISE OF THE ALL-AMERICAN BREAST FETISH 
</HEADLINE>
  
 (ATTN: Maine, Wash.)  (For release Thursday, April 1)  
(Eds.: Please note that the word AT in parentheses has been used in
the last graf instead of the symbol, non-transmittable to many
newspaper systems.) (rk) 
 By SUSAN SWARTZ   
 Santa Rosa (Calif.) Press Democrat   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   Large breasted women are thought to be less smart than small
breasted woman. Yet, large breasted women are desirable and small
breasted women are ignored. However, both get made fun of.
</P>
<P>
   It is commonly understood that breasts are designed for nursing
babies, yet the sight of a nursing breast offends some people.
Breasts are, however, available for public viewing in magazines,
movies, advertisements, on some TV programs and on the Internet.
</P>
<P>
   Men take their shirts off to work on scaffolding in the middle
of downtown. A woman needs a special law to whip her's off in her
own front yard.
</P>
<P>
   The term ``go figure'' comes to mind in considering the above
and any number of cultural behaviors regarding the female breast.
It is no wonder the breast bearer or barer, herself, feels
ambivalent about her breasts. They belong to her but become
everyone else's business as soon as they appear.
</P>
<P>
   In her book, ``Breasts, the Women's Perspective on an American
Obsession,'' writer Carolyn Latteier says, ``It is strange living
in a body with a sex organ that is also a public institution.''
</P>
<P>
   We could be going through a new breast awareness phase. As
Latteier, a free-lance magazine writer in Port Townsend, Wash., was
finishing her book last year she learned of another author writing
the history of the breast. Latteier now counts at least five new
books out about breasts, including one for little kids.
</P>
<P>
   In November the residents of Newport, Maine, voted down an
ordinance that would have punished women for displaying their
breasts in public. It was brought to a vote after a woman in her
30s decided one hot day to mow her lawn minus her shirt and a
neighbor woman called the cops, complaining it was indecent and
worrying that motorists might get distracted and cause an accident.
</P>
<P>
   Authorities said that while it was against the law to bare
genitalia or have sex in public, bare breasts don't fall into
either category. A vote to expand the law was required. Voters said
let her take her shirt off.
</P>
<P>
   Latteier's intent is to help women feel better about their
breasts and not let themselves be judged by their size, shape or,
in the unhappiest of cases, because of a lost one.
</P>
<P>
   She thinks society doesn't see enough normal, average breasts,
which hardly ever match the airbrushed, often silicone-pumped ones
that cause many a woman to glance toward her own cleavage with an
``Oh, well.''
</P>
<P>
   Latteier says that breasts are as different as faces, but most
women tend to think that only their breasts are the odd ones. Every
woman she photographed for the slides she shows when talking about
her book apologized for her breasts.
</P>
<P>
   And yet it's only been in recent history that the breast has
gotten such attention. Her research shows that during the Middle
Ages and the Renaissance a woman's stomach was considered a symbol
of sexuality. Vain women would walk around thrusting out their
bellies and holding back their breasts. Imagine that at a Miss
America pageant.
</P>
<P>
   Latteier found that in many cultures today breasts are not the
sex objects they are in America. The women of Mali in West Africa,
for example, think it's amusing that men would be aroused by
breasts, so clearly is the breast considered the exclusive property
of babies.
</P>
<P>
   Latteier, who says she's quite satisfied with her own small
breasts, found that women with large breasts often get branded as
hypersexual. Also as not smart, immodest and incompetent.
</P>
<P>
   ``The more bosom, the less brain,'' is the cultural assumption.
</P>
<P>
   The small-breasted get labeled asexual, but reliable and smart.
</P>
<P>
   In the '50s, breast size and even projection were part of
postwar propaganda. Latteier says the ideal female body type
portrayed by the media had ample, even pointy breasts, emphasized
by bras that looked like warheads and hood ornaments.
</P>
<P>
   ``It was during the time that we were containing Communism,
skeptical of anyone different and needed to protect the white,
heterosexual nuclear family which was headed by a man who was very
masculine and a woman was who very feminine.''
</P>
<P>
   It was also a way, she said, of leading Rosie the Riveter
factory workers back home and into dresses and traditional female
roles.
</P>
<P>
   Later came a few years of liberation in the '60s and '70s, when
women stopped wearing bras or at least took on the soft, natural,
hang-loose look. Starting in the '80s the trend favored what she
calls ``the machine-like body.''
</P>
<P>
   The ideal female form calls for tight buttocks, small waist,
slender legs and impossible, rarely-found-in nature, voluptuous
breasts. The solution, and for some women a resulting health
problem, was breast implants.
</P>
<P>
   It's encouraging to examine the rise and fall of the breast
throughout history. It offers hope that the pushed up, squeezed
together, over the top look could be a passing cleavage.
</P>
<P>
   Perhaps we'll go back to the adoration of the belly. Maybe
braless will return. Or there's always that fresh trend out of
Newport, Maine, which may, in future years, have us marking spring
with the first reported sighting of a bare-breasted weed whacker,
size 36B.
</P>
<P>
   (Susan Swartz is a columnist for The Press Democrat in Santa
Rosa, Calif. Her e-mail address is sfswartz(AT)pressdemo.com)
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-03-25-99 1754EST &QL; 
</TRAILER>
