<HEADER>
A4194 &Cx1f; taf-z
u v &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-SUNDAY-FINAL-BUDGET-N     03-25 2398
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-SUNDAY-FINAL-BUDGET-NYT </SLUG>
  
<TEXT>
<P>
   &QL;
</P>
<P>
   The New York Times News Service will move the following
entertainment/arts articles this week for release Sunday, March 28,
1999. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   &UR; ENTERTAINMENT &AMP; ARTS (Moved in `e' category) &LR;
</P>
<P>
   &UR; FEATURE stories &LR;  &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   WRESTLEMANIA (Undated) _ The red-hot growth sector for media
analysis in 1999 is the apocalpse theory. And the word
``Millenarianism'' is the belief in a battle between good and evil
at the end of the millennium that lays waste to the earth and is
then followed by a thousand years of peace and human perfection.
(Mill(italics)i(end italics)nerianism, on the other hand, is the
belief in, um, hats.) What better way for the pop-cult eggheads and
satraps to earn their living than by pointing out for us the early
warning signs to the death of civilization? One such harbinger, the
seemingly inexplicable resurgence of professional wrestling, is
already being written about and spoken of by those on the critical
edge of the crackpot apocalypse. Wrestlemania, apparently, is the
end of the world as we know it. In our Age of Incivility, it should
come as only a small surprise that professional wrestling is now
the hippest ticket in town and a regular ratings juggernaut on
cable television. By Jeff MacGregor. &UR;  &LR; (Moved). Photo.
</P>
<P>
   ARTISTS-MUSEUMS (Undated) _ Europe has more than 400
single-artist museums; in this country, there are fewer than 40. A
single-artist museum, as the clunky phrase implies, is a public
institution devoted to the work of one lone artist, and the
tradition has given rise to such universally beloved haunts as the
Musee Picasso in Paris, the Van Gogh Museum in Amsterdam, the Miro
Foundation in Barcelona and the Edvard Munch Museum in Oslo. And in
this country? Government indifference to the arts is an old story,
yet despite the obvious obstacles, artists' museums are finally
gaining some momentum. By Deborah Solomon. (Moved). Photo.
</P>
<P>
   &UR; FILM AND VIDEO &LR;
</P>
<P>
   ARCTIC-CIRCLE-FILM (Undated) _ Julio Medem, 40, makes
sophisticated, elegantly constructed films whose characters seem to
wander blindly through a maze of experience. The director has
earned a reputation as Spain's most promising auteur; but as an
artist, he prefers not knowing where he's going. Spanish audiences
have had no trouble connecting with ``Lovers of the Arctic Circle''
(``Los Amantes del Circulo Polar''), Medem's fourth feature and a
surprise hit. The movie will be presented in the New Directors/New
Films series at the Museum of Modern Art in Manhattan on April 7
and 8, and will open theatrically the next day. Highly stylized,
the film is a love story told alternately from the perspective of
each of the lovers, and it plays with the tension between the
lovers' fairy-tale idealism and the hazards of chance and will that
govern their fate. By Leslie Camhi. (Moved).
</P>
<P>
   TONY-GOLDWYN-FILM (Undated) _ About five years ago, the actor
Tony Goldwyn started getting restless. His performance in the 1990
off-Broadway play ``The Sum of Us'' had put him on the New York
theater map. The same year, his portrayal of the yuppie villain in
``Ghost'' had done the same in Hollywood. But he wanted more. His
response was perhaps inevitable for the son of the movie producer
Samuel Goldwyn Jr. and the grandson of the Hollywood legend Sam
Goldwyn. He would find a script he wanted to act in and produce it
himself. He saw it as something that might happen 10 years down the
road. But it didn't turn out the way he expected because of a
script called ``The Blouse Man,'' by a poet and playwright named
Pamela Gray. As ``A Walk on the Moon,'' the film opened on Friday,
and although Goldwyn does not act in it, he is indeed one of the
producers and, more important, its director. By Sylviane Gold.
(Moved). Photo.
</P>
<P>
   NO-FRILLS-CINEFEST (Liverpool, N.Y.) _ The phrase ``film
festival'' conjures glamorous images: the beaches of Cannes, the
slopes of Park City, Utah, and a crush of photographers aiming at
the latest starlet. Then there's Cinefest, which prides itself on
offering lots of films and not much festival. Held at a
standard-issue Holiday Inn here off Interstate 81, just northwest
of Syracuse, Cinefest has quietly developed a reputation as the
un-Cannes. For four days, several hundred people gather to sit on
banquet chairs in the hotel ballroom and watch movies that run from
9 a.m. until well past midnight. The films being screened are not
orphans in search of a distributor or indies hoping to generate
buzz, but rather spirits from the past: rarely seen movies from the
silent and early talkie era. By Ted Loos. (Moved). Photo.
</P>
<P>
   &UR; THEATER &LR;
</P>
<P>
   NONPROFIT-MUSICALS (subslug) (New York) _ For musicals with big
bold intentions, they certainly didn't make much noise. The first
to come and go quietly was ``Parade,'' the funereal $5.5 million
Lincoln Center Theater show about the lynching of Leo Frank. Next
was ``Bright Lights Big City,'' the $500,000 musical adaptation of
the Jay McInerney novel that opened and closed at New York Theater
Workshop in what seemed like the span of a single yawn. The last to
depart, ``Captains Courageous,'' a $1 million musical that opened
in mid-February to the equivalent of a citywide shrug, is to vacate
the Manhattan Theater Club next Sunday. There you have it. Over the
course of a few punishing winter months, the musical hopes of three
of New York's most successful nonprofit theaters were smothered in
a blizzard of mixed-to-negative reviews. By Peter Marks. (Moved).
Photo.
</P>
<P>
   NY-BALLET (Undated) _ Rehash or celebration? As a work in
progress, the New York City Ballet's 50th anniversary year looks
like both. The celebration is, in effect, a retrospective: Now
halfway through the 100 ballets it plans to present through June,
the company leaned toward the familiar in its recent winter season.
Yet the packaging was often different, and new contexts made for
new insights. By Anna Kisselgoff. (Moved).
</P>
<P>
   WEIR-THEATER (London) _ Ian Rickson says he admires auteur stage
directors like Robert Wilson and Anne Bogart, who leave their
emphatic imprint on a production. But he prefers to burrow out from
the inside of a play. And if people don't notice what he has done,
that may be the highest compliment. Rickson's work is on display in
``The Weir,'' by the 27-year-old Irish playwright Conor McPherson,
which opens on Thursday at the Walter Kerr Theater in Manhattan.
This meditative drama of barroom blarney that gives way to a sense
of loss and then of healing is the director's first Broadway
effort. By Matt Wolf. (Moved). Photo.
</P>
<P>
   RIDE-THEATER (Undated) _ Bizarre Murder!!! A Lesbian Forces
Blind Holocaust Victim on Roller Coaster!'' This phony headline is
trumpeted by Lisa Kron about herself halfway through her one-woman
show ``2.5 Minute Ride,'' directed by Mark Brokaw and opening
Sunday night at the Joseph Papp Public Theater in Manhattan. The
headline refers to an amusement-park ride that Ms. Kron takes with
her retired father, who lives in Lansing, Mich. The ride proves to
be a breeze compared with a trip to a concentration camp _ the
other major story in ``2.5 Minute Ride.'' By Steven Drukman.
(Moved). Photo.
</P>
<P>
   &UR; CLASSICAL MUSIC &LR;
</P>
<P>
   FORZA-OPERA (Milan, Italy) _ Last month under the direction of
Riccardo Muti, after an absence of 20 years, ``La Forza del
Destino'' returned to La Scala, where in 1869 Verdi introduced the
opera in its significantly revised, definitive form. By Matthew
Gurewitsch. (Moved).
</P>
<P>
   CHOPIN-MUSIC (Undated) _ Another anniversary is upon us, yet the
music business is strangely muted. Frederic Chopin died 150 years
ago, and the relative silence has less to do with our forgetfulness
than with our despair. For what are we to give the man who has
everything? Centennials _ bi-, tri-, sesqui- or of whatever nature
_ promise concentrated looks, resuscitations of neglected works,
re-evaluations of worth, new editions and musicological
discoveries. By Bernard Holland. (Moved).
</P>
<P>
   GRAND-MACABRE-OPERA (Undated) _ Probably no opera of the last
quarter-century has been seen by more people than Gyorgy Ligeti's
``Grand Macabre.'' Since its premiere in Stockholm in 1978, the
work has had several different stagings in Europe, though none so
far in this country. Now comes its second recording, taken from
public performances in Paris a year ago of the production made for
the 1997 Salzburg Festival (Sony SK2 62312; two CDs). Esa-Pekka
Salonen leads the Philharmonia Orchestra, the London Sinfonietta
Voices and an excellent cast, most of whom will be returning in
December, when the production moves into the newly reopened Royal
Opera House in London. By Paul Griffiths. (Moved).
</P>
<P>
   PHILLY-ARTS-CENTER (Philadelphia) _ An emphatic article in a
newspaper here stated that the Philadelphia Orchestra, the only
major American ensemble to play on a proscenium stage, should have
a proper hall of its own. That was in 1908. Successive generations
have taken up the cry. Plans for a new hall were drawn up during
the music directorships of Leopold Stokowski, Eugene Ormandy,
Riccardo Muti and now Wolfgang Sawallisch. Finally, a plan may be
realized. Ground was broken last November for a new Regional
Performing Arts Center, with a 2,500-seat symphony hall and a
650-seat recital theater, scheduled to open in 2001. By Anne
Midgette. (Moved).
</P>
<P>
   &UR; POP MUSIC &LR;
</P>
<P>
   ROSCOE-MITCHELL-JAZZ (Undated) _ Roscoe Mitchell, whose album,
``Nine to Get Ready'' has just appeared, is a leading member of
jazz's forgotten avant-garde. Once hailed as an heir to Ornette
Coleman and Albert Ayler, Mitchell found himself pushed to the
margins in the 1980s by Wynton Marsalis and his traditionalist
followers, who reviled free jazz as an evil second only to fusion.
Since the early 90s, Mitchell has been staging a comeback,
recording and performing at a furious clip. He might not be welcome
at Lincoln Center, where musicians are expected to adhere to
blues-derived forms and steer clear of European dissonances. But
among younger jazz listeners who chafe at such restrictions,
Mitchell's audience is expanding. By Adam Shatz. (Moved).
</P>
<P>
   ROCK-IMAGE (Undated) _ Today, rock-and-roll is having problems.
Promoters say there are no new bands with members under 40 that can
sell out stadiums the way wrestling can. Monster truck shows, on
the other hand, have no problem selling out stadiums night after
night. And monster truck shows don't even have real celebrities, as
wrestling does: just unseen drivers like Gravedigger, who is
basically loved because he takes his turns too fast and too tight
and likes to drive through stadiums destroying props. There's that
violence and danger again. And maybe that's what rock needs. By
Neil Strauss. (Moved).
</P>
<P>
   HIDDEN-MUSIC-TRACKS (Undated) _ The music of Whitney Houston,
the Offspring, Robert Earl Keen, Sheryl Crow, Korn, Beck and Jewel
has little in common, but the musicians do share one thing: they
all included hidden tracks on their most recent CDs. From
hip-hoppers to singer-songwriters to rockers, more pop artists than
ever are adding hidden tracks _ bonus tracks that are not listed on
the song lineup _ in an effort to surprise, delight, mock or annoy
fans. By Scott Sutherland. (Moved).
</P>
<P>
   &UR; ART &LR;
</P>
<P>
   HIGH-LOW-CULTURE (Undated) _ There is nothing these days that is
too Low for High thought: trailer parks, snuff films, Mickey Mouse.
Some of this is because of the unparalleled power of American
popular culture, its extraordinary influence with world audiences
and its aggressively democratic perspective. Boundaries are
dissolving so fast that even the lowly life of a cultural critic is
swept up in the maelstrom: in recent months I have written about
swimming pools, video games and lingerie as well as Arnold
Schoenberg, Isaiah Berlin and Shakespeare. By Edward Rothstein.
(Moved).
</P>
<P>
   &UR; TELEVISION &LR;
</P>
<P>
   TV-INFLUENCE (Undated) _ Americans got the message in 1961, when
the chairman of the Federal Communications Commission looked out
upon the television landscape and saw that it was bad. ``A vast
wasteland,'' he thundered. Everybody nodded in agreement, then
flipped through the TV Guide to see what was on that night. But the
phrase stuck _ became lodged, in fact, in the national corpus of
received wisdom and stock phrases. Finally, worn out, it was tossed
onto the ash heap of cliches, to be retrieved and reused thereafter
only with ironic intent. Television, it seems, had stopped being
the worst thing ever. That isn't to say we had learned to stop
worrying and love the tube. People, with good reason, have never
stopped beefing about television: there's too much sex, there's too
much violence, there are too many commercials, there's too much
Howard Stern. By William McDonald. (Moved).
</P>
<P>
   &UR; ANTIQUES &LR;
</P>
<P>
   ANCIENT-GAMES-ANTIQUES (Undated) _ On the surface, board games
seem intended to amuse and entertain, but on closer look they have
much in common with military campaigns or religious rituals.
According to a Chinese legend from the Qin Dynasty, to avoid
further bloodshed, a war between an uncle and nephew was settled by
a game of weiqi, a kind of chess. This and many other stories are
charmingly related through the nearly 100 objects exhibited in
``Games People Play: Ancient Pastimes of Asia'' at the E.&AMP;J.
Frankel gallery in Manhattan until May 1. By Paula Deitz. (Moved).
</P>
<P>
   BESTSELLERS (Undated) (Moved.)
</P>
<P>
   PAPERBACKS (Undated) (Moved.)
</P>
<P>
   &UR; TRAVEL (`t' category) &LR;
</P>
<P>
   TRAVEL-EURO-SKI (Paris) _ After the avalanches, Europe skis in
to spring. By Craig R. Whitney. (Moved).
</P>
<P>
   TRAVEL-LONDON-THEATER (Undated) _ Curtain up on a London
weekend. By Anita Gates. (Moved).
</P>
<P>
   TRAVEL-OAHU (Undated) _ Oahu, beyond Pearl Harbor and Waikiki.
By Howard W. French. (Moved).
</P>
<P>
   TRAVEL-BRIEFS (Undated) _ For wine livers, a palace in Portugal;
All about France on a telephone line; Long Island beachhead for
Southwest Airlines; Ancient Thracian art on view in Boston; Get
thee to a nunnery with a new Italy guide; Easter chase: bring your
own basket. (Moved).
</P>
<P>
   TRAVEL-Q&AMP;A (Undated) _ Travel questions and answers: Cranberry
bogs; Getting married in France; Seeing the lastes fashionns. By
Paul Freireich. (Moved).
</P>
<P>
   PRACTICAL-TRAVELER (Undated) _ In freewayland without a car. By
Martha Stevenson Olson. (Moved).
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
