<DOC>
<DOCNO> NYT19990325.0198 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-03-25 18:01 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A4196 &Cx1f; tad-z
u f &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-gates-0326-cox     03-25 0679
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-gates-0326-cox </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    MICROSOFT SETTLEMENT TALKS TO OPEN NEXT WEEK
 &HT;    Moving in (w) Washington and (f) financial categories
 &HT;    Editors: the states in the suit are N.Y., Calif., Conn.. Fla.,
Ill., Iowa, Kan., Ky., La., Md., Mass., Mich., W. Va., Wis., Minn.,
N. Mex., N.C., Ohio and Utah, plus Washington, D.C. Thursday
meeting did not include all 19, but apparently did include some
states that have not signed on
 &HT;    By ANDREW J. GLASS
 &HT;    c.1999 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON - Antitrust settlement talks between the government
and Microsoft will open in Washington Tuesday. But as they prepare
to begin face-to-face bargaining, both sides remain far apart on
key issues.
</P>
<P>
   If they prove unable to strike a deal, then the marathon
Microsoft antitrust trial, which began in October, will resume
before U.S. District Court Judge Thomas Penfield Jackson, probably
in mid-May.
</P>
<P>
   The upcoming talks were confirmed after a meeting of attorneys
general Thursday in Washington.
</P>
<P>
   ``We'll be sitting down with them on Tuesday,'' said New Mexico
Attorney General Patricia Madrid.
</P>
<P>
   The Justice Department and the 19 states that have sued
Microsoft are crafting a response to an initial four-page proposal
offered Monday by the software giant. They have rejected the
company's initial offer.
</P>
<P>
   ``Obviously, we've put on a very strong case,'' said Ohio
Attorney General Betty Montgomery. ``If we had not, they wouldn't
be sending us a (settlement) proposal.''
</P>
<P>
   Although a settlement remains in doubt, investors appeared
heartened by the news. Microsoft shares rose $8.50 to an all-time
high of $179.75. It was second most active stock on any U.S.
exchange.
</P>
<P>
   Neither the Justice Department nor the company would comment on
the upcoming talks, which are to alternate between a third-floor
conference room at the Justice Department and the Washington
offices of Sullivan &AMP; Cromwell_ Microsoft's trial lawyers _ near
the White House.
</P>
<P>
   Joel Klein, the Justice Department's antitrust chief, and
William Neukom, Microsoft's general counsel, will be the key
negotiators. Their initial session will be held at the Justice
Department at 2 p.m. Tuesday.
</P>
<P>
   The parties are also due to appear Wednesday (March 31) before
Jackson, who had urged them to seek an accord during the long trial
recess. Since Monday, Jackson has been presiding over a
two-defendant murder trial that his clerks (CQ plural) expect will
run seven more weeks.
</P>
<P>
   Microsoft Chairman Bill Gates visited Washington briefly
Thursday but never came near the Justice Department, which has
featured his videotaped deposition at the trial.
</P>
<P>
   On tour to promote his new book, ``Business (at) the Speed of
Thought,'' Gates did not take questions from the press after his
hour-long talk at Georgetown University's business school. He left
for London immediately after that session.
</P>
<P>
   ``By late 1995, we had made the Internet our top priority,''
Gates told his student audience. ``We drove to integrate Windows
standards into our products.''
</P>
<P>
   It was that move, centered on the browser wars with rival
Netscape Communications, that prompted the antitrust suit last May.
</P>
<P>
   In an interview Wednesday on NBC's Today show, Gates reiterated
his stand that Microsoft ``would love to settle the case as long as
there's a reasonable way to settle this thing, one that allows the
company to have integrity in our Windows product.''
</P>
<P>
   Microsoft has offered to end its long-standing policy of signing
exclusionary contracts with various vendors and to ease strict
licensing demands for its Windows operating system.
</P>
<P>
   But the company refuses to yield on what it views as a vital
issue: Allowing the government to dictate how it could weave new
technologies into Windows.
</P>
<P>
   The government, however, sees a need to insure a level playing
in the fast-moving industry, given Microsoft's de facto Windows
monopoly over the operating system that runs on 90 per cent of the
world's personal computers.
</P>
<P>
   ENDIT
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
