<SLUG> BC-FILM-MODSQUAD-SPI </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
REMAKE OF `MOD SQUAD' EXUDES A RETRO CHARM 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients.)  
 By WILLIAM ARNOLD  
 c.1999 Seattle Post-Intelligencer  
<TEXT>
<P>
   The movie version of ``The Mod Squad'' is one of the less
self-conscious and less pretentious of recent big-screen remakes of
vintage television shows. It plays very much like an extended
episode of the old series _ half-heartedly updated to the '90s.
</P>
<P>
   It has no inside jokes for former fans or splashy cameo
appearances by the former stars. It doesn't try to elevate its
material into something more significant. For that matter, it
doesn't show any undue respect for its source. It's just a
nostalgic exercise in early-'70s-style TV schlock.
</P>
<P>
   As you may recall, the series _ which ran on ABC-TV between 1968
and 1973 _ chronicled the cases of a trio of ex-juvenile
delinquents pressed into service by the Los Angeles Police
Department as spies within the youth counterculture: undercover
cops disguised as hippies.
</P>
<P>
   Two of those characters are back for the movie. There's the
pretty young female ex-addict, Julie (played by Peggy Lipton in the
series; Claire Danes in the movie), and the taciturn young black
man, Linc (played by Clarence Williams III _ with smoldering rage
and the world's tallest afro _ in the series; Omar Epps in the
movie).
</P>
<P>
   But the third character, Pete (played by Michael Cole with
tight-lipped '60s cool in the series), has been totally revamped
into a goofy comic-relief figure played by Giovanni Ribisi
(Juliette Lewis' mentally handicapped suitor in ``The Other
Sister'') who is only a step or two away from Curly of the Three
Stooges.
</P>
<P>
   The script has the trio staking out a trendy downtown rock club
that's a hangout for high-class pimps and prostitutes, and somehow
stumbling onto a huge conspiracy by rogue LAPD cops _ seemingly
half the department _ to traffic in drugs that have been seized as
evidence. Before long, every cop in Southern California is after
the kids.
</P>
<P>
   The characters are likable as they wriggle out of this
impossible situation, the story is fast-paced and not terribly
demanding, and the style is so sedate compared with today's
mean-spirited youth action movies that it all comes together with a
certain retro charm. High cinematic art it's not, but it is
something remarkably close to my memory of the TV ``Mod Squad.''
</P>
<P>
   The Mod Squad. Directed by Scott Silver. Written by Silver,
Stephen Kay and Kate Lanier. Cast: Claire Danes, Omar Epps,
Giovanni Ribisi, Dennis Farina, Josh Brolin. MGM. 94 minutes. Rated
R for prostitution and drug themes, and violence.
</P>
<P>
   Grade: C+
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
