<HEADER>
A4203 &Cx1f; taf-z
u e &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-ANTIQUES-COLUMN-NYT &LR;      03-25 1155
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-ANTIQUES-COLUMN-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
ANTIQUES: IT'S JADE TIME AT THE GALLERIES AND THE FAIR 
</HEADLINE>
   (bl)  
 By WENDY MOONAN   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEW YORK _ To the Chinese, jade is more than a gemstone.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's been part of their entire world for at least 4,000 years;
it's one of the most valuable things they had,'' said Robert
Ellsworth, a private New York City dealer who is showing an early
eighth-century Tang Dynasty white jade bull with gold and silver
trappings at the International Asian Art Fair, which runs through
March 30 at the 7th Regiment Armory on Park Avenue and 67th Street.
</P>
<P>
   ``Jade is synonymous with China,'' Ellsworth continued. ``It's
revered, respected and valued. It was used as currency. It was how
you put your wealth on display.''
</P>
<P>
   Alvin Lo, a fourth-generation dealer who owns the Lo Gallery at
5 E. 57th St., said, ``For the Chinese, jade is seen in terms of
ethics.'' He added: ``Jade has profound meaning, beyond monetary
return. It's part of Chinese culture. It protects you. It is a good
omen.''
</P>
<P>
   Lo said the best way to understand jade was to read Confucius
(551-479 B.C.), who compared the visual traits of jade to worldly
virtues. According to a translation in ``Jade'' (Lorenz Books,
1995), a collection of essays compiled by Roger Keverne, he wrote:
``Its polish and brilliancy represent the white of purity, its
perfect compactness and extreme hardness represent the sureness of
intelligence, its angles, which do not cut although they seem
sharp, represent justice.''
</P>
<P>
   He continued: ``Its color represents loyalty, its interior
flaws, always showing themselves through the transparency, call to
mind sincerity; its iridescent brightness represents heaven.''
</P>
<P>
   Collectors should be aware that jade can easily be faked and
should be bought only from dealers who guarantee its authenticity.
But this week, those who want to see the real thing are in luck
because it's Asian Art Week in New York, and there is heavenly
Chinese jade at the fair and at art galleries all over town.
</P>
<P>
   In China the ``Jade Age'' predated the Bronze Age. ``It came
before porcelain, painting and bronze,'' said Sam Bernstein, a San
Francisco dealer of Chinese antiques who is giving a seminar on
jade Saturday morning at 9 at the Four Seasons Hotel ($55). ``It
even came before pottery.''
</P>
<P>
   As early as 3500 B.C., the Chinese were shaping jade into
funerary ornaments and tools _ nephrite jade from China, not the
bright emerald green Burmese jadeite that arrived in China about
1750.
</P>
<P>
   Some of the finest early jades in town are at J.J. Lally &AMP; Co.
Oriental Art, 41 E. 57th St. in Manhattan, which this week opened
an exhibition of ancient Chinese jades, bronzes and ceramics that
runs through April 10. In their restraint and minimalist design,
these pieces appeal to collectors of contemporary art and the
Calvin Klein set as well as to connoisseurs of Chinese art. The
show is half sold out.
</P>
<P>
   The gallery has a squarish, thin, 4.5-inch-long, dark green jade
ax head from a Shang Dynasty (16th to 11th century B.C.) burial
site. ``I think it is a ceremonial ax,'' said James Lally, the
gallery owner.
</P>
<P>
   The ax may or may not have been used. ``It is the quality of
jade that makes it the toughest of gem materials,'' wrote Jill
Walker in the Keverne book. ``The toughness of gem material is not
the same as its hardness; toughness is the resistance to breaking,
chipping or cracking, while hardness is the resistance to
scratching or abrading.'' She continued, ``This attribute of
nephrite was recognized by prehistoric peoples, as evidenced by its
use in early tools.''
</P>
<P>
   Lally also has a Neolithic jade cong, a hollow cylinder in a
square body, like a square bangle. He says the cong was used in
rituals to worship the earth. These rituals were performed only by
powerful officials, so the cong became a status symbol.
</P>
<P>
   Dated 3300 to 2250 B.C., Lally's pale olive cong has four
stylized masks with huge round eyes incised in its corners. The
masks look like the faces on totem poles in the Pacific Northwest.
</P>
<P>
   Lally also has jade pendants with dragons and phoenixes incised
on them. The dragon is thought to represent the emperor; the
phoenix, the empress.
</P>
<P>
   ``In archaic China, pendants were worn as an emblem of power or
were used for burials,'' Lally said. ``They would be strung on a
cord on a belt or used as a toggle.''
</P>
<P>
   Lally also has a charming, yellow-green jade ram from the Sung
Dynasty (A.D. 960 to 1279). Nearly three inches long, the ram is
lying down, his head sharply turned back; it is priced at $40,000.
Lally said the piece ``has an extraordinary color and a good
provenance.''
</P>
<P>
   Many jade animals are in the Asian fair; Ralph Chait, Spink,
Sydney Moss, A.&AMP;J. Speelman, Alistair Sampson, S. Marchant &AMP; Son,
Gerald Hawthorn, Lo and Ellsworth all have them. ``The Chinese like
jade animals,'' Ellsworth said. ``They were like personal toys,
often touched during a person's life and then placed in his tomb.`
</P>
<P>
   Jade snuff bottles were also made to be held, said Robert Hall,
a dealer in them. ``Snuff bottles came into fashion in 1642 when
they were endorsed by the Emperor Kangzi,'' he said. ``The
literati, the well-connected and the imperial households all
collected them.''
</P>
<P>
   Hall is selling a late-18th-century uncarved green jadeite snuff
bottle for $20,000. ``They tended to leave the best jade uncarved,
to show off the color,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   Jade comes in many shades of green, yellow, white, lavender,
black, gray, brown, even red. ``For collectors of jade, the three
most important things are color, color, color,'' said Hawthorn, a
London dealer. ``If the carving is great, it's a bonus.''
</P>
<P>
   Lally agreed. ``The whole story is size and color in ancient
jade,'' he said. ``Yellow is very desirable because it's hard to
find. Dark green is the less sought after because it's more
plentiful.''
</P>
<P>
   Keverne, who is a dealer in London and will be at the fair,
said, ``Today brilliant white and yellow seem to be fashionable.''
He is selling a white jade sculpture of a boy with pomegranate,
which symbolizes fertility, at the Sampson booth.
</P>
<P>
   Michael Weisbrod, a Manhattan dealer, is selling 125 ancient
jades in his show, ``Jades From Traditional China,'' at 36 E. 57th
St. through April 6. He said, ``Spinach jade is a little out of
fashion now.''
</P>
<P>
   Jade likes to be touched.
</P>
<P>
   ``Jade is a little like pearls; it can dry up,'' Ellsworth said.
``It seems to be absorbent to a point. Wearing it does not enhance
the depth of the color but keeps it more translucent.''
</P>
<P>
   Ellsworth said he dangles an early Shang jade water buffalo from
his belt and wears a 2000 B.C. jade bead around his neck.
</P>
<P>
   Elizabeth Childs-Johnson, author of the 219-page catalog that
accompanies the Weisbrod show, said: ``Jade has a protective
function and brings good luck. It is seen as an auspicious symbol
because of its properties.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
