   TRIVIA-Q&AMP;A &QL;
</P>
<P>
   UNDATED _ Questions about the two writers named Robin Cook and
how to contact Bob Woodward and Carl Berstein of Watergate fame. By
ROGERS CADENHEAD. Story has moved in ``l'' lifestyle category. &QL; 
 &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   ANDERSON-COLUMN &QL;
</P>
<P>
   UNDATED _ It has been said that longevity has its place.
Obviously, that is an old aphorism. We are all aware that the trend
today is toward youth, youth and more youth. However, it is true
that there are times when even the most progressive among us would
prefer a seasoned veteran. By MONICA ANDERSON. Story has moved in
``l'' lifestyle category. &QL; 
 &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   E N T E R T A I N M E N T &QL; 
 &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   FILM-EDTV &QL;
</P>
<P>
   UNDATED _ Ron Howard, who probably understands as well as anyone
the problems of living one's life in the public eye, brings his
brand of sticky, predictable problem-solving to ``EDtv.''
Ironically, a movie about the dangers of TV made by a man who was
raised as a product of TV suffers from the conservatism of TV
thinking. By ELVIS MITCHELL. Story has moved in ``e'' entertainment
category. &QL; 
 &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   FILM-20 DATES &QL;
</P>
<P>
   UNDATED _ Myles Berkowitz's docucomedy ``20 Dates'' has
parallels with ``EDtv'': Both movies have a normal schmo dealing
with his love life on camera, in front of scores of strangers. Two
differences, though: ``20 Dates'' is nonfiction, and Berkowitz,
unlike the my-life's-a-TV-show Ed in ``EDtv,'' has trained his
camera upon himself. By ROBERT PHILPOT. Story has moved in ``e''
entertainment category. &QL; 
 &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   FILM-DOUGS 1ST MOVIE &QL;
</P>
<P>
   UNDATED _ Well, there aren't any rampaging 3-D dinosaurs in
``Doug's 1st Movie,'' but there is a silly-looking, gap-toothed,
reptilian swamp monster. It's a pity, really. Some man-eating
carnosaurs might have been just the ticket to salvage this
big-screen treatment of the popular Nickelodeon kid cartoon,
particularly if they devoured most, if not all, of the main
characters. By TODD CAMP. Story has moved in ``e'' entertainment
category. &QL; 
 &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   FILM-THE HARMONISTS &QL;
</P>
<P>
   UNDATED _ ``The Harmonists,'' directed by Joseph Vilsmaier, has
an interesting subject _ how the power of popular art won't set you
free _ though we get a lot of scenes with allegorical weight. In
the end, it's a movie with its feet planted too firmly on the
ground. By ELVIS MITCHELL. Story has moved in ``e'' entertainment
category. &QL; 
 &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   FILM-TINSELTOWN &QL;
</P>
<P>
   UNDATED _ ``Tinseltown,'' the directorial debut of screenwriter
Tony Spiridakis, plays like a sour-grapes screed from someone who's
frustrated that he can't get his ``good'' movies made even though
Hollywood keeps churning out junk. This might be OK if the movie
weren't junk itself. By ROBERT PHILPOT. Story has moved in ``e''
entertainment category. &QL; 
 &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   FILM-THE MOD SQUAD &QL;
</P>
<P>
   UNDATED _ Based on the late '60s TV series about a trio of
down-and-out criminals turned undercover cops, ``The Mod Squad''
comes off as a half-baked retread at best, a mushy TV dinner that
could have used another couple of minutes in the microwave. By TODD
CAMP. Story has moved in ``e'' entertainment category. &QL; 
 &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
