<DOCNO> NYT19990325.0207 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-03-25 18:10 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A4206 &Cx1f; tta-z
u i &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-KOSOVO-CLARK-PROFILE-     03-25 1054
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-KOSOVO-CLARK-PROFILE-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
NATO'S COMMANDER IN EUROPE KNOWS HIS ADVERSARY WELL 
</HEADLINE>
   (See also: KOSOVO-RDP, KOSOVO-MILITARY, KOSOVO-MILITARY-ASSESS,
KOSOVO-GERMANY, KOSOVO-POLICY, KOSOVO-BELGRADE, KOSOVO-PRISTINA,
KOSOVO-MACEDONIA, KOSOVO-REPORTERS, KOSOVO-CHINA,
KOSOVO-RUSSIA-ASSESS, KOSOVO-CLINTON, KOSOVO-ITALY, KOSOVO-VOICES,
KOSOVO-B2, KOSOVO-SANCTIONS, KOSOVO-EUROPE-REAX, KOSOVO-U.N.) 
(wg) 
 By CRAIG R. WHITNEY   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   BRUSSELS, Belgium _ Wesley Clark, the four-star American general
who as Supreme Allied Commander Europe is in charge of the powerful
NATO air offensive against Serbia for its attacks against ethnic
Albanians in Kosovo, knows his adversary well.
</P>
<P>
   Too well, perhaps, mused one allied diplomat, not an American,
who said on Thursday that he thought the general was intellectually
the most impressive commander the alliance had ever had, but
fixated on the idea that force is the only language the Serb
leadership understands.
</P>
<P>
   Clark, 54, arrived at that conviction through long experience
with Yugoslav President Slobodan Milosevic. It was Milosevic's
refusal to accept a peace agreement in Kosovo involving the
deployment of 28,000 NATO peacekeepers that made the bombing
inevitable, the general and other allied leader say.
</P>
<P>
   ``We are going to systematically attack, disrupt, degrade,
devastate and, ultimately, unless President Milosevic complies with
the demands of the international community, we're going to destroy
these forces, with their facilities,'' Clark said Thursday in
characteristically forceful language, describing a bombing campaign
that allied officials say could destroy the Yugoslav army as an
effective fighting force.
</P>
<P>
   He personified the battle, as generals often do. When reporting
that two American F-15 fighters and a Dutch F-16 had apparently
shot down at least three Yugoslav Mig-29s in dogfights Wednesday
night, Clark referred to the Yugoslav aircraft as ``some of his
most advanced and capable aircraft,'' with ``his'' referring not to
an abstract enemy, but to Milosevic personally.
</P>
<P>
   Clark's short, well-groomed gray hair and piercing eyes (he
wears contact lenses) bespeak an intensity he has shown throughout
his army career over the last three decades.
</P>
<P>
   His intimate familiarity with Milosevic and his thinking stems
from the hundreds of hours that he spent with the Serbian leader in
1994 and 1995, when Clark served as Richard Holbrooke's military
adviser during the American special envoy's diplomatic quest to end
the war in Bosnia.
</P>
<P>
   On one of their trips, three other members of their team were
killed in an accident on the dangerous Mount Igman road to
Sarajevo, forced to take that route because of the Bosnian Serb
refusal to guarantee their safety on a more direct one. Clark
rappelled down a steep mountainside to try to rescue the victims
from their burning armored personnel carrier.
</P>
<P>
   In the marathon peace negotiations that Holbrooke brokered in
Dayton, Ohio, in November 1995 after Milosevic abandoned the
Bosnian Serb cause, Clark personally oversaw the drafting of the
military chapter of an accord that gave free rein to a NATO
peacekeeping force in Bosnia.
</P>
<P>
   As NATO's senior officer, he now commands that peacekeeping
force, and the British commander of the similar force planned for
Kosovo under the peace plan would report to him, too.
</P>
<P>
   Was there a hint of exasperation in the general's remark on
Thursday that bombing Yugoslavia to make it willing to make peace
was the culmination of a long _ in fact, quite long _ planning
process?
</P>
<P>
   People who know him say that Clark is much too politically
astute to express publicly any impatience with the long _ in fact,
quite long _ hesitation President Clinton and other allied leaders
showed in reaching their decision to use force in Kosovo.
</P>
<P>
   Unusually, Clark had no military command experience in Europe
before Clinton put him in charge of the alliance's military
establishment, as well as the 100,000 American troops stationed in
Europe, in July 1997.
</P>
<P>
   Clark was director of strategic plans and policy on the joint
staff at the Pentagon when Holbrooke drafted him for his
negotiating missions in Bosnia. He then went to Panama to take
charge of the United States Southern Command for a year before
taking up his NATO duties at Mons, Belgium.
</P>
<P>
   Clark and Clinton both grew up in Arkansas, and both were Rhodes
Scholars at Oxford University in the 1960s, though they only got to
know each other well later.
</P>
<P>
   Clinton avoided military service, but Clark graduated, first in
his class, from West Point in 1966 and took a master's degree in
philosophy, politics and economics at Oxford before starting his
rise through the military ranks as a ``tanker,'' or armor officer,
in Vietnam.
</P>
<P>
   There, he received the Silver Star medal for bravery in combat
and was wounded four times. Later, he was selected to be a White
House Fellow in 1975 and 1976, when the young officer worked as a
special assistant to the director of the Office of Management and
Budget.
</P>
<P>
   He converted to Roman Catholicism after meeting his wife, the
former Gertrude Kingston of Brooklyn, N.Y., at West Point. They
have one son, Wesley, who after living in California and trying to
make a living writing film scripts is now preparing to go to
business school.
</P>
<P>
   Clark, though almost slight of build, is in superb physical
shape, as might be expected of an officer who wears the elite
Ranger and Airborne army badges on his uniform. Long laps in the
swimming pool allow him to indulge a weakness for popcorn, corn
chips and Coca-Cola, and friends say he has recently taken up golf.
</P>
<P>
   ``He is always totally focused on whatever he's doing,'' one old
friend said. ``When he skis, he wants to be first down the hill,
and he has gone into every job he has ever had with incredible
intensity. He has never had an easy job.''
</P>
<P>
   After commanding a battalion and a brigade of the Fourth
Infantry Division in Fort Carson, Colo., in the 1980s, he became
commander of the National Training Center from 1989 to 1991, one of
several such posts in which he played a key role in helping adapt
army big-battalion tactics and combat doctrines suited to the Cold
War to the more nimble, rapid-deployment needs of the less stable
era that succeeded it.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
