<DATE_TIME> 1999-03-25 18:11 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A4208 &Cx1f; taf-z
u v &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-KOSOVO-ADVISORY-1STLD     03-25 1024
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-KOSOVO-ADVISORY-1STLD-WRITETHRU-NYT </SLUG>
  
 (Eds: CHANGES story slugged KOSOVO-REFUGEES to KOSOVO-MACEDONIA;
DROPS KOSOVO-MILOSEVIC; ADDS new stories KOSOVO-RUSSIA-ASSESS,
KOSOVO-CLINTON, KOSOVO-ITALY, KOSOVO-VOICES, KOSOVO-B2,
KOSOVO-CLARK-PROFILE, KOSOVO-EUROPE-REAX, KOSOVO-U.N.; ADDS details
on expected graphics.) 
 (nk) 
<TEXT>
<P>
   EDITORS: The New York Times is planning four pages of stories on
the NATO air strikes in Yugoslavia for the paper of Friday, March
25. The New York Times News Service plans to move these stories
tonight in the ``i'' news file. For more information, call toll
free at (888) 346-9867. The day supervisor is Ned Kilkelly. The
night supervisor is Lynn Hoogenboom.
</P>
<P>
   KOSOVO-RDP (Washington) _ Scores of U.S. cruise missiles and
radar-evading bombers, leading waves of punishing NATO attacks,
struck Serb air defenses, power grids, arms factories, airports,
barracks and command and control centers across Yugoslavia and in
Kosovo. By Francis X. Clines. With photos.
</P>
<P>
   KOSOVO-MILITARY-ASSESS (Washington) _ NATO's air campaign
intends to bomb the Yugoslav leader, Slobodan Milosevic, into
submission or pound his military to the point where it can no
longer be an effective killing machine. But the United States has
seen before that air power may punish but it can rarely coerce a
defiant enemy into changing its behavior _ and this be a part of
Milosevic's calculation. By Eric Schmitt.
</P>
<P>
   KOSOVO-GERMANY (Berlin) _ For the first time since the end of
World War II, German fighter jets have gone to war, attacking
Yugoslavia as part of a NATO force and marking this country's
definitive emancipation from post-war pacifism. By Roger Cohen.
</P>
<P>
   KOSOVO-MILITARY (Washington) _ NATO forces began a second day of
air and missile raids on Yugoslavia, intensifying its attack on air
defenses that the Pentagon said were significantly damaged but not
destroyed on the first night. By Steven Lee Myers.
</P>
<P>
   KOSOVO-POLICY (Washington) _ The roles top administration
officials played in the planning and operation of the NATO strike.
By Jane Perlez.
</P>
<P>
   KOSOVO-BELGRADE (Kievo, Yugoslavia) _ Even after the air raid
sirens wailed, Sara, nearly 5, refused to go down to the basement
shelter until the ``Ninja Turtles'' program was over. Then the
night sky turned orange over this southern suburb of Belgrade, and
on a hill just a mile or so away, where a radar antenna sits, a
NATO missile or bomb exploded. ``There was a big cloud of dust and
a huge pressure of the air,'' said Sara's father, Mile. ``I told
Sara, `Where are our Ninja turtles to help us now?' and then we
went to the shelter.'' By Steven Erlanger.
</P>
<P>
   KOSOVO-MACEDONIA (Skopje, Yugoslavia) _ Giving vent to their
rage over NATO bombings of their neighboring country, thousands of
Serb sympathisers marched on the American Embassy here, throwing
rocks, setting embassy cars on fire and seeking to burn down the
compound with molotov cocktails. By Alessandra Stanley. With map.
</P>
<P>
   KOSOVO-PRISTINA (Pristina, Yugoslavia) _ After a night of heavy
explosions and fires, the city was subdued, the people bracing
themselves for worse to come. Black smoke still rose from burning
buildings on the south-western edge of the city, one of the main
casualties of the night. Another plume of smoke rose from the ridge
on the eastern edge of the city. By Carlotta Gall.
</P>
<P>
   KOSOVO-RUSSIA-ASSESS (Moscow) _ As the elder brother of Yugoslav
President Slobodon Milosevic and Belgrade's ambassador to Moscow,
Borislav Milosevic has done his best to drum up support for
Belgrade. So far, he does not have much to show for his efforts. By
Michael R. Gordon.
</P>
<P>
   KOSOVO-REPORTERS (Undated) _ All foreign journalists from NATO
countries were expelled from Yugoslavia Thursday, by an order from
the Serbian government that apparently none resisted. By Lawrie
Mifflin.
</P>
<P>
   KOSOVO-CHINA (BEIJING) _ China pressed an all-out verbal assault
on the NATO air strikes against Serbian forces Thursday, issuing
multiple demands that the attack be halted, while the flagship
state newspaper called the operation a ``dangerous precedent of
naked aggression.'' By Erik Eckholm.
</P>
<P>
   KOSOVO-CLINTON (Undated) _ Historians and Balkan specialists
said yesterday that while they generally approve of President
Clinton's decision to bomb Serbia, his use of history in justifying
the attack was imprecise and misleading. By Ethan Bronner.
</P>
<P>
   KOSOVO-CLARK-PROFILE (Brussels, Belgium) _ Gen. Wesley K. Clark,
the four-star American general who as Supreme Allied Commander
Europe is in charge of the powerful NATO air offensive against
Serbia for its attacks against ethnic Albanians in Kosovo, knows
his adversary well. By Craig Whitney.
</P>
<P>
   KOSOVO-B2 (Washington) _ The B-2 stealth bomber, the most
expensive and intricate aircraft ever built, made its combat debut
in a world far different from the one for which it was conceived.
By David Stout.
</P>
<P>
   KOSOVO-ITALY (Aviano, Italy) _ Security was high and the bars
and restaurants normally frequented by NATO service personnel were
swept clean Thursday night around this northern Italian air base
that is the launching pad for many of the NATO aircraft striking
Yugoslavia. By John Tagliabue,
</P>
<P>
   KOSOVO-EUROPE-REAX (London) _ Europeans reacted Thursday with a
mixture of dread at the return of large-scale combat to the
continent where two world wars were fought, apprehension that the
conflict could spread and widespread if sometimes grudging support
for the allied decision to take military action. By Warren Hoge.
</P>
<P>
   KOSOVO-U.N. (United Nations) _ Security Council meets on Kosovo.
</P>
<P>
   KOSOVO-VOICES (Various datelines) _ Times reporters interview
Americans around the country for their reaction to the bombing of
Yugoslavia.
</P>
<P>
   The New York Times Graphic Service expects to have the following
graphics:
</P>
<P>
   _ (BC-KOSOVO-RDP-NYT) Map showing targets of attack.
</P>
<P>
   _ (BC-KOSOVO-MILITARY-NYT) Number of missiles and bombs used so
far.
</P>
<P>
   _ (BC-KOSOVO-MILITARY-ASSESS-NYT) Issues surrounding the use of
surface to air missiles.
</P>
