<SLUG> BC-KOSOVO-CHINA-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
CHINA CONDEMNS NATO AIR STRIKES, DEMANDS ATTACKS BE HALTED 
</HEADLINE>
  (See also: KOSOVO-RDP, KOSOVO-MILITARY, KOSOVO-MILITARY-ASSESS,
KOSOVO-GERMANY, KOSOVO-POLICY, KOSOVO-BELGRADE, KOSOVO-PRISTINA,
KOSOVO-MACEDONIA, KOSOVO-REPORTERS, KOSOVO-RUSSIA-ASSESS,
KOSOVO-CLINTON, KOSOVO-ITALY, KOSOVO-VOICES, KOSOVO-B2,
KOSOVO-CLARK-PROFILE, KOSOVO-SANCTIONS, KOSOVO-EUROPE-REAX,
KOSOVO-U.N.) 
(jt) 
 By ERIK ECKHOLM    
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   BEIJING _ China pressed an all-out verbal assault on the NATO
air strikes against Serbian forces Thursday, issuing multiple
demands that the attack be halted, while the flagship state
newspaper called the operation a ``dangerous precedent of naked
aggression.''
</P>
<P>
   Several major newspapers in Beijing were delivered late Thursday
after they took the unusual step of holding up the presses for
several hours on Wednesday night, apparently so they could include
reports on President Jiang Zemin's condemnation of the NATO attack.
</P>
<P>
   One source of China's unease is resentment of its own history of
colonization and invasion by Western and Japanese forces. But even
more potent is China's concern that foreign powers might treat its
own sometimes violent ethnic conflicts in Tibet and the Muslim
province of Xinjiang as requiring international intervention.
</P>
<P>
   Jiang, who is also chief of the Communist Party, made his
remarks just after the attack began, at a banquet Wednesday evening
in Milan, part of a European tour.
</P>
<P>
   Jiang was the first of several officials to demand ``an
immediate end'' to the air strikes. Prominent on the front page of
People's Daily, alongside the report of the Jiang's remarks, was a
harsh, pre-prepared editorial that accused NATO of ``flagrantly
using barbaric military force to interfere in Yugoslavia.'' The
newspaper is the mouthpiece of the ruling Communist Party.
</P>
<P>
   China says the air strikes required approval by the United
Nations Security Council (where China and Russia could have vetoed
the plan).
</P>
<P>
   But Prime Minister Zhu Rongji still plans to visit the United
States in April, a foreign ministry spokesman said Thursday after
delivering his own broadside.
</P>
<P>
   Zhu recently said he hopes his visit will enable China and the
United States to resume progress toward the ``constructive
strategic partnership'' that both sides pledged last year. The
dispute over Kosovo joins human rights, accusations of Chinese
espionage, American research on missile defenses and China's huge
trade surplus with the United States as issues dividing the two
countries.
</P>
<P>
   But both governments hope to avoid a new Cold War. With Zhu's
visit weeks away, American and Chinese trade officials are
negotiating feverishly here to see if they can produce a plum for
the visit by agreeing on terms for China's entry into the World
Trade Organization. This would require China to reduce its trade
barriers.
</P>
<P>
   On the issue of Kosovo, at least, the People's Daily editorial
and other official statements revealed how far apart the two
countries are and hinted at why the Chinese feel so threatened by
the attack.
</P>
<P>
   Noting that ethnic conflict in Yugoslavia has ancient roots, the
editorial blames the recent violence in Kosovo on ``illegal
Albanian armed forces.'' Instead of condemning the brutal tactics
of Serbian forces as Clinton did, it says Serbian actions have been
``entirely appropriate and legitimate.''
</P>
<P>
   ``There are many countries with problems involving ethnic
minorities,'' the editorial says. ``If we encourage division, won't
the world fall into chaos?''
</P>
<P>
   China is also hypersensitive about international support for
Taiwan, which it considers a breakaway province.
</P>
<P>
   ``NATO's use of military force to meddle in Yugoslavia is
without reason or legal basis,'' People's Daily said, arguing that
the action was part of a dark new ``strategy for global
intervention'' by NATO.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
