<DATE_TIME> 1999-03-25 18:16 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A4216 &Cx1f; taf-z
u w &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-NURSING-HOMES-ART-NYT     03-25 0747
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-NURSING-HOMES-ART-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
CLINTON SIGNS LAW BARRING NURSING HOMES FROM EVICTING MEDICAID
RECIPIENTS 
</HEADLINE>
  (ART ADV: Photo of is being sent to NYT photo clients.
Non-subscribers can make individual purchase by calling (888)
603-1036.) 
(bl) 
 By ROBERT PEAR   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON _ President Clinton on Thursday signed legislation
that prohibits nursing homes from evicting people on Medicaid, as
some have done in recent years as part of an effort to recruit more
affluent patients.
</P>
<P>
   The bill, passed by Congress with bipartisan support, protects
Medicaid patients who live in nursing homes that decide to withdraw
from the program.
</P>
<P>
   Under the new law, if a nursing home decides to pull out of
Medicaid, it must continue to care for people who live in the home,
including those who may later qualify for medical assistance.
</P>
<P>
   Medicaid helps pay the bills for two-thirds of the 1.6 million
people in nursing homes in the United States. Though it is
generally perceived as a program for low-income Americans, it also
covers many middle-class people who deplete their assets in old
age.
</P>
<P>
   Families can easily exhaust their assets on nursing home care
because the costs average more than $110 a day nationwide, and much
more than that in urban areas like New York City.
</P>
<P>
   The legislation results directly from the efforts of a Florida
couple who fought back when a nursing home in Tampa tried to evict
54 Medicaid patients.
</P>
<P>
   The couple, Nelson and Geri Mongiovi, went to court to stop the
evictions last March. And they went to Congress for help. The
problem was well defined, and Congress responded faster than usual.
</P>
<P>
   Mongiovi, a retired letter carrier who was at the White House
for Thursday's signing ceremony, said the law came too late to help
his mother, Adela Mongiovi, who died in November at the age of 93.
But he said, ``This bill is a good memorial to her and will help
thousands of other people.''
</P>
<P>
   The bill was pushed through Congress by three lawmakers from
Florida: Sen. Bob Graham, a Democrat, and Reps. Michael Bilirakis,
a Republican, and Jim Davis, a Democrat.
</P>
<P>
   ``Nursing homes would accept Medicaid patients, then change the
rules in the middle of the game and dump them on the street,''
Graham said. ``These evictions have a devastating effect on senior
citizens. The death rate for people uprooted in this way is two or
three times as high as for those who receive continuous care.''
</P>
<P>
   Bilirakis said: ``This law closes a legal loophole that allows
nursing homes to evict their most vulnerable residents. It puts
patients ahead of profits.''
</P>
<P>
   The nursing home industry supported the bill. But Linda Keegan,
vice president of the American Health Care Association, which
represents nursing homes, said, ``We will see more and more nursing
homes opt out of Medicaid because of the inadequacy of Medicaid
payments,'' which are set by the states.
</P>
<P>
   Medicaid generally pays nursing homes less than the rates paid
by Medicare, private insurance and families who pay entirely with
their own money.
</P>
<P>
   Toby Edelman, a lawyer at the National Senior Citizens Law
Center, praised the bill signed Thursday. But she said Congress
should pass a comprehensive bill to prevent nursing homes from
discriminating against Medicaid beneficiaries.
</P>
<P>
   ``Few nursing homes withdraw entirely from Medicaid,'' she said,
``but many limit their participation by certifying only a small
number of beds for Medicaid. They discriminate against Medicaid
beneficiaries by denying them admission. And if a person is
admitted as a private patient and later becomes eligible for
Medicaid, the person may be told that `no Medicaid beds are
available.'''
</P>
<P>
   Whether a nursing home may enforce such restrictions has been a
question in several lawsuits around the country. States have taken
different positions on the issue.
</P>
<P>
   The new law would not require nursing homes to accept Medicaid
patients. But if a nursing home participates in Medicaid and
decides to withdraw, it may not evict those Medicaid patients it
already has. And it would have to inform new patients, at the time
of admission, that it did not accept Medicaid payments.
</P>
<P>
   As evidence of the inadequacy of nursing home rates, Bruce
Yarwood, legislative counsel for the American Health Care
Association, said that ``69 percent of nursing home residents rely
on Medicaid for their care, but Medicaid accounts for only 48
percent of nursing home revenue.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
