<DOCNO> NYT19990325.0212 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-03-25 18:19 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A4217 &Cx1f; taf-z
u e &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-ASIAN-ART-3TAKES-NYT &LR;      03-25 0954
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-ASIAN-ART-3TAKES-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
THE DIZZYING REALM OF ASIAN ART  
(DW)
</HEADLINE>
  
 (ATTN: Del., N.J. )   By HOLLAND COTTER   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEW YORK _ ``Asia'' doesn't exist and it never has. It isn't a
place or culture; it's a geopolitical fiction, a patchwork of
people, climates and languages stitched together lightly, and only
here and there, by the bright thread of Buddhism.
</P>
<P>
   Yet something called ``Asian art'' has taken New York by subtle
force in the last few years, sweeping aside cultural and political
distinctions. Its presence is especially evident during these early
spring days, in what has come to be known in the art world as Asia
Week.
</P>
<P>
   Asian auctions have been in progress at Christie's and
Sotheby's. The International Asian Art Fair has arrived _ with a
tinkle of cymbals and a rustle of big money _ at the Seventh
Regiment Armory. Asian work of every size, shape and function can
be found in galleries from the Upper East Side to Chinatown.
</P>
<P>
   All this hoopla is new. Just a few years ago, a graduate student
could visit Sotheby's Asian previews and puzzle undisturbed for
hours over Sanskrit inscriptions and the tantalizing odds and ends.
Now the odds and ends have been replaced by the ``important''
property, and a buzz of acquisitiveness is in the air.
</P>
<P>
   Why Asian art now? There are many reasons. Buyers, institutional
and private, are realizing that they can pick up a drop-dead
masterpiece from India, Tibet or China for a small fraction of what
a third-rate Italian Renaissance painting costs, not to mention a
goodish Picasso.
</P>
<P>
   Although Asian art is still widely considered a specialist's
realm, it is becoming clear that the scholar, the dealer and the
casual shopper are all, at some level, neophytes. Asian art is not
a field; it is a universe. If you are deeply conversant with one
facet of it, you are likely to be in the dark about another. In the
face of its endless beauties and challenges, everyone gets a chance
to be star-struck and enthralled.
</P>
<P>
   The International Asian Art Fair
</P>
<P>
   Being enthralled is a lot of what a visit to the International
Asian Art Fair is about. In its fourth year, it remains the
hands-down best art fair in New York. Many of the premier European
and U.S. dealers are present. The quality of the work is high, the
variety wide. The show feels good: the pleasure principle is at
work, but so is the intellectual excitement of seeing things for
the first time.
</P>
<P>
   The art of India, for example, may start to find the audience it
deserves. Visitors will be stopped in their tracks by the carving
of an 11th-century temple dancer, her hair a mass of twisting vines
and blossoms, at Doris Wiener. The South Indian bronze figure of
Kali, with her avid face and tiny fangs, at Chinese Porcelain Co.
along with the Gandharan head of a young man with cushiony lips at
Spink are also likely to cause a pileup.
</P>
<P>
   But there are also quieter rarities: an exquisite Gupta period
bronze Jain figure at John Eskenazi, for example, and a set of
pages from a 12th-century palm-leaf manuscript, with iconic
paintings and the most beautiful script you've ever seen, at the
booth of Sam Fogg, a London dealer who is one of this year's prize
new participants.
</P>
<P>
   Ancient China is represent by a Northern Qi limestone
bodhisattva at R.H. Ellsworth, as slender and upright as a sapling;
by a lustrous gilt Buddha, hands held above head, at A.&AMP;J.
Speelman, and by a pair of Tang period tomb doors etched with
figures at the booth of the Brussels dealer Gisele Croes.
</P>
<P>
   Scholars' utensils are on view in cool, clean installations at
Nicholas Grindley and China 2000 Fine Art. The latter gallery adds
contemporary work by the Chinese-American artist Arlan Huang to its
forward-looking mix. New work also finds a voice at Art Forum
Singapore, another first-time participant, and at Michael Goedhuis,
in calligraphic paintings by the Beijing artist Gu Gan.
</P>
<P>
   As a kind of preview to the exhibition of 19th- and early
20th-century Meiji period Japanese art set to open at the First USA
Riverfront Arts Center in Wilmington, Del., next month, the London
dealer Malcolm Fairley has brought examples of enameled vases that
are the Asian equivalent of high Victoriana. You may never have
seen much of this work before, and you may not be wild about it if
you have, but it is one more piece to add to the fascinating mosaic
that is the Asian Art Fair.
</P>
<P>
   Eskenazi at Pace Wildenstein
</P>
<P>
   Not all of the European dealers visiting New York are at the
armory. Giuseppe Eskenazi, who specializes in the art of ancient
China and is in from London, has set up shop in the Pace
Wildenstein premises on 57th Street.
</P>
<P>
   Eskenazi is at the top of the field, and anyone who saw his
first New York show in 1997 may still feel a bit lightheaded at the
memory. This year's selection of bronzes and ceramics is pretty
wonderful, too.
</P>
<P>
   Among the larger pieces is a bronze bell from the Shang period
(circa 1400 to 1000 B.C.), set upright, like a downward-tapering
vase, its surface studded with nipple-like nobs and incised with
animal-mask meander patterns. Imposing in a different way is a pair
of unglazed earthenware guardian figures from the Tang dynasty (7th
to 10th century A.D.), the ferocity of their faces softened by
their hands-on-hips disco poses and their dainty armor, all sashes
and ruffs and incised chrysanthemums
</P>
<P>
   Smaller pieces should not be overlooked. One is a bronze Shang
tiger plaque inlaid with wafer-thin chips of turquoise (the coiled
hemp twine that holds the turquoise in place is still visible);
another, a crouching male clay figure in a pill-box hat, seems to
bow in good-natured, deferential welcome.
</P>
<P>
   nn
</P>
<P>
   J.J. Lally &AMP; Company
</P>
<P>
   Several New York galleries have rustled up special displays for
Asia Week. China 2000 and M.D. Flacks have furniture, Weisbrod
Chinese Art a melange of jades, E &AMP; J Frankel a selection of board
games from the Tang dynasty to Made-in-Hong Kong modern. Opening
Friday at Taipei Gallery in midtown Manhattan is a survey of
contemporary ceramics from Taiwan.
</P>
<P>
   Outstanding is the exhibition at J.J. Lally &AMP; Co. Oriental Art
of jades, bronzes and ceramics in the Fuller Building on 57th
Street. One of its highlights is a minute phoenix pendant from the
Warring States period (475 to 221 B.C.), a frozen burst of
unfurling energy. Another is the tiny image of a mythical beast
known as a bixie, which looks like a cross between a toad and a pug
and is cut from a brown-and-green stone.
</P>
<P>
   Rossi &AMP; Rossi at Sotheby's
</P>
<P>
   Downstairs from Lally, the London gallery Rossi &AMP; Rossi, in
collaboration with Sotheby's, has installed ``Sacred Symbols: The
Ritual Art of Tibet,'' a spectacular gathering of objects, from
ceremonial implements to theater costumes to a priest's umbrella
made from peacock-feather filament wrapped around silk thread.
</P>
<P>
   One room is devoted to the psycho-symbolic dynamism of tantric
imagery and includes, among other treasures, an ebony ritual dagger
standing on point in its base, its surface alive with slithering
snakes and protectively repellent faces.
</P>
<P>
   In Tibetan art, the sacred and secular are impossible to
separate.
</P>
<P>
   Two gilt bronze kneeling deers look like fantastic garden
sculptures; in fact, they originally flanked a Buddhist Wheel of
the Law atop a temple. The same wheel appears in a silk embroidered
altar cloth of immense visual panache. A lama's glazed lacquer
summer hat exudes a haute couture flair. So does a pair of
his-and-hers silk and leather gloves with long, fabric fingernails;
they were meant to be worn by dancers portraying skeletons animated
by tantric bliss.
</P>
<P>
   If a New York museum had a permanent display of this material,
some of it unfamiliar even to experts, people would flock to see it
(as they should be doing to the stunning Tibetan collection at the
Newark Museum, a quick ride under the Hudson River on the PATH
train). As it is, ``Sacred Symbols'' runs only through next week.
</P>
<P>
   It leaves behind an excellent catalog by Robert Thurman and
David Weldon, a useful addition to the growing literature on the
art of Tibet, which has been one of the stronger sales fields in
the Asian market recently, and accounts for two awesome items at
this week's auctions: a large gilt bronze 14th- to 15th-century
guardian figure at Christie's and a 36-armed Tibeto-Chinese figure
of the deity Yamantaka at Sotheby's. Japan Society Gallery
</P>
<P>
   Anyone who assumes from the Eskenazi and Rossi &AMP; Rossi shows
that Europe has a corner on Asian riches need only visit
``Crosscurrents: Masterpieces of East Asian Art From New York
Private Collections'' at Japan Society to learn otherwise. Here the
world-class strength of New York collecting in this material is
confirmed once and for all.
</P>
<P>
   Organized with the Brooklyn Museum of Art by Amy G. Poster and
supplemented by a fine book, the show is a revelation. It opens,
appropriately, with a Japanese image: a heart-lifting 13th-century
wood carving of the bodhisattva Jizo, protector of travelers and
children. On loan from the collection of Dr. and Mrs. Robert
Dickes, he holds the wish-granting gem of wisdom in his hand and
closes his eyes in reverie.
</P>
<P>
   But on this occasion, Japan Society opens its arms to art from
across East Asia, tracing influences that connected cultures, yet
left them distinctive. Buddhism is one such link, embodied in the
Jizo figure, in a magnificent Korean hanging scroll, dated 1565,
from the Mary and Jackson Burke Foundation, and in a marble carving
of a seated Chinese lohan, or disciple of the Buddha, an emblem of
alert introspection, from the Robert Rosenkrantz Collection.
</P>
<P>
   Bonds are also found in tea connoisseurship and the literati
arts of painting and calligraphy. The tea ceremony is celebrated
with an installation of utensils from China, Korea and Japan owned
by Peggy and Richard Danziger; calligraphy in a set of rubbings
from the Chunhua Pavilion copybook, which preserves the work of the
fourth-century fathers of the Chinese calligraphic tradition. On
loan from the Robert Hatfield Ellsworth Collection, these volumes,
stamped with generations of imperial seals, are historical
documents beyond price.
</P>
<P>
   They certainly give a dramatic sense of an impressive base that
a new generation of American collectors is building on. And the
show points to promising directions that the Japan Society Gallery
is taking under its new director, Alexandra Munroe, who is putting
a treasured if sometimes reticent institution back on the art-world
map. Kaikodo
</P>
<P>
   A handful of other locations are firmly on that map. Kaikodo, a
gallery established three years ago by the Japanese-based art
historians Mary Ann and Howard Rogers, boasts one of the most
beautiful commercial art spaces in the city, and it is filled with
intriguing works for a show titled ``In the Company of Spirits.''
</P>
<P>
   Among them is a solid selection of classical Chinese painting,
not so often seen in bulk since Christie's and Sotheby's moved
their primary sales of this material to Hong Kong. Among the
standouts at Kaikodo are a delicate Southern Song fan painting,
pure distilled nostalgia, and an amusing 18th-century scroll of
cavorting frogs dressed as Shinto priests.
</P>
<P>
   As at Japan Society, Kaikodo's selection is ``Asian'' in the
cross-cultural sense, with a flair-mouthed Japanese Neolithic jar,
a Vietnamese pot and a snazzy little tiger-striped Chinese dish
keeping company. But the piece de resistance, concealed from
immediate view behind a screen, is a pair of furious-looking Tang
tomb guardians of glazed earthenware with rays of spiritual power
shooting straight up out of their heads.
</P>
<P>
   Kaikodo produces substantial catalogs with essays by leading art
historians that make a valuable contribution to Asian studies. (The
current catalog includes an article on Chinese erotica by James
Cahill and an interesting first-hand account of two decades of
auctions of Chinese art by Arnold Chang.)
</P>
<P>
   (MORE) nn
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
