<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-03-25 18:19 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A4219 &Cx1f; ttj-z
u w &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-KOSOVO-HISTORY-HNS &LR;      03-25 0643
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-KOSOVO-HISTORY-HNS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
KOSOVO HOLDS SPECIAL PLACE IN SERBIAN HISTORY 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients.)  
 By MARK HELM  
 c.1999 Hearst Newspapers  
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON _ With its rugged hills and poor villages, Kosovo
appears an unlikely place for Yugoslav President Slobodan Milosevic
to make his stand against NATO.
</P>
<P>
   But to Serbian nationalists, a bitter history spanning 600 years
has raised Kosovo's symbolic importance to that of Jerusalem for
Christians and Jews.
</P>
<P>
   ``Kosovo lies at the heart of who we are as a people,'' said
Jelena Budjevac, spokeswoman for the Serbian Unity Congress, a
Washington-based lobbying group.
</P>
<P>
   Kosovo is a province of Serbia, one of two states that make up
the Balkan nation of Yugoslavia.
</P>
<P>
   About 90 percent of Kosovo's 2 million residents are ethnic
Albanians, who are predominantly Muslim. Serbians are mostly
Orthodox Christian.
</P>
<P>
   Budjevac said every Serbian child grows up hearing the story of
the Battle of Kosovo Polje, or the ``Fields of Blackbirds.''
</P>
<P>
   In 1389, a powerful army of Ottoman Turks, intent on spreading
Islam to Europe, was pushing its way through southern Europe. But
on June 28, the Turks were met by Serbian Prince Lazar, a
Christian, and his much smaller army.
</P>
<P>
   Lazar and his men were defeated, although they inflicted immense
losses on the Ottomans. After the battle, Lazar was taken prisoner
and beheaded, and his men were executed. The Serbian defeat opened
the way for an Ottoman advance into Europe, an incursion that
lasted another 300 years until it was checked at the gates of
Vienna, Austria.
</P>
<P>
   The defeat in Kosovo became a central myth for Serbian
nationalists over then next five centuries, said Charles King, a
history professor at Georgetown University.
</P>
<P>
   For the Serbs, the Battle of Kosovo came to symbolize the choice
of death rather than compromise with an enemy, and the emotional
call to ``avenge Kosovo'' resonated during the Serbs' long struggle
for independence from the Ottoman Empire, King said.
</P>
<P>
   After a series of revolts, Serbia finally won autonomy from the
Ottomans in 1830 and was placed under the protection of Russia's
Slavic rulers. In 1878, Serbia was granted complete independence.
</P>
<P>
   But throughout this time Kosovo remained a part of the Ottoman
Empire, and the province's Albanian population increased and
eventually dominated the area as many Serbs migrated to other parts
of the Balkan region. The Ottomans and Albanians also
systematically destroyed dozens of Serbian churches and
monasteries.
</P>
<P>
   Then in 1914, as World War I engulfed Europe and the Ottoman
Empire, Serbia seized Kosovo, and its remaining Serbian residents
welcomed the troops as liberators.
</P>
<P>
   Following the war, the Balkan region's many nations and ethnic
groups, including Serbia and Kosovo, were cobbled together by the
victorious Allies to form what would become Yugoslavia. The
nationalities lived in a state of mutual hostility and sporadic
fighting until Nazi Germany and fascist Italy invaded during World
War II, brutally suppressing the Serbs.
</P>
<P>
   Following the war, Serbia and Kosovo became part of communist
Yugoslavia under the leadership of Josip Broz Tito, whose
strong-arm tactics kept the ancient ethnic hatreds at bay.
</P>
<P>
   In 1974, Tito granted Kosovo partial autonomy, a formula that
worked until Tito's death in 1980 and beyond.
</P>
<P>
   But as Yugoslavia started to unravel in the late 1980s,
Milosevic _ then the leader of Serbia _ dismantled the province's
freedom. That sparked a growing rebel movement, leading Milosevic
last year to send in police and army units to brutally crush the
ethnic Albanian independence movement.
</P>
<P>
   ``The fight to keep Kosovo a part of Serbia has been going on
for centuries, and that is something the American people should
know as they send their planes against us,'' Budjevac said.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-03-25-99 1819EST &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> NYT19990325.0215 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-03-25 18:19 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A4220 &Cx1f; taf-z
u e &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-ASIAN-ART-3rdTAKE-NYT     03-25 1031
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-ASIAN-ART-3rdTAKE-NYT </SLUG>
 
NEW YORK: Arnold Chang.)
<TEXT>
<P>
   China Institute in America
</P>
<P>
   Similarly, and immensely important, is the contribution of China
Institute, a few blocks away, which every season mounts
small-scale, closely focused exhibitions of a kind rarely seen in
museums, but are the lifeblood of art-historical research and a
connoisseur's delight.
</P>
<P>
   Its current offering, ``A Literati Life in the 20th Century:
Wang Fang Yu, Artist, Scholar, Connoisseur,'' is a scholarly show
within a show. It is dedicated to the life and work of Wang Fang Yu
(1913-1997), a Chinese-born linguist who come to the United States
in 1945 and gained a reputation as a pre-eminent calligrapher.
</P>
<P>
   In the venerable literati tradition, he was also an art
historian. He rediscovered the ouevre of the Qing painter Bada
Shanren, and championed the work of the modern painters Qi Baishi
and Zhang Daqian. When he died, Wang was planning an exhibition
that would compare the work of these artists, tracing a pedigree in
which he included himself. The China Institute show, organized by
H. Christopher Luce, goes a long way toward fulfilling his goal,
and touches on issues of imitation and forgery that have made
Chinese painting a commercial and academic minefield. Asia Society
</P>
<P>
   Like China Institute, Asia Society often concentrates on
in-depth investigations of specific topics. Such is the case with
``Bamboo Masterworks: Japanese Baskets From the Lloyd Cotsen
Collection.'' In this selection, organized by Mary Hunt Kahlenberg,
an art usually relegated to the category of craft is revealed to be
an astonishingly versatile sculptural medium in which light, space
and planar complexity play a dynamic role.
</P>
<P>
   Metropolitan Museum of Art
</P>
<P>
   The Metropolitan Museum, usually blockbuster country, also finds
room for pocket-size exhibitions, and one of them is a selection of
Indian drawings from the late 16th century to the early 19th
century, organized by Steven Kossak in the Irving Galleries for the
Arts of South and Southeast Asia.
</P>
<P>
   Whether done in Mughal ateliers or Rajput courts, the rough
sketches and half-finished paintings demonstrate the painstaking
process that underlies the art of the Indian miniature. Few of the
drawings are complete in themselves, as in a head of Krishna from
around 1800. With his eyes shaped like lotus petals and his nose,
ears and fashionable turban studded with jewels, he is both a
cartoon for a mural and a polished image that could not be improved
upon.
</P>
<P>
   The Fashion Institute of Technology
</P>
<P>
   Anyone with even a so-so appetite for jewels and fashion should
head straight downtown to the Fashion Institute of Technology where
the smashing ``China Chic: East Meets West'' will rattle any
remaining illusions about the sacrosanct, timeless character of
Asian culture.
</P>
<P>
   The museum's director, Valerie Steele, has assembled a
scintillating collection of Chinese and Chinese-inspired clothes.
It ranges from imperial Qing robes to a slinky 1934 Anna May Wong
gown (on loan from the apparently bottomless holdings of the
Brooklyn Museum). From the 1990s comes a Vivienne Tam Buddha dress,
Donna Karan's version of a Maoist worker's suit and Christian
Lacroix's take on the classic slit-skirt qi pao, itself a mix of
Chinese, Manchu and Western styles. Add an entertaining catalog and
you have a definite don't-miss list candidate.
</P>
<P>
   Arts of Pacific Asia Show
</P>
<P>
   Not far from the institute, the semiannual Arts of Pacific Asia
Show is in the 69th Regiment Armory. A downtown, down-market
version of the Asian Art Fair, the show is geared primarily to the
cash-and-carry transaction: it is light on big-time masterworks,
but dense with objects that might serve as decorative accessories
for the home.
</P>
<P>
   There is plenty to look at, particularly in the area of East
Asian export wares, fabrics (some beauties) and small Tibetan
objects (at Moke Mokotoff Gallery, for example). Viewers needing an
additional fix of Chinese chic should check out the booth of the
London textile dealer Linda Wriggleworth. Contemporary Chinese art
is well-represented at Ethan Cohen Fine Arts, where work by Wenda
Gu, Xu Bing and Lin Tian-miao, all of whom were in Asia's Society's
recent ``Inside/Out'' exhibition, can be found.
</P>
<P>
   Tibet House Cultural Center
</P>
<P>
   Farther west is the new headquarters of Tibet House, with a
pretty shrine room and a spacious gallery. On exhibit are 20 modern
embroidered thangkas produced in the Nechung Monastery, now in
Dharamsala, India.
</P>
<P>
   In Dharamsala, the Dalai Lama, who has tacitly encouraged the
collecting of ancient Tibetan art in the West as a means of
preserving the culture, is trying to keep a tradition of religious
art alive. The hangings at Tibet House, in silk and brocade
applique, adhere to long-established forms and techniques. And it
is interesting to remember that the glorious Tibetan fabric works
at Rossi &AMP; Rossi and the Art Fair were once as spanking new as
these.
</P>
<P>
   Museum of Chinese in the Americas
</P>
<P>
   Finally, what better place to end Asia Week than at the Museum
of Chinese in the Americas in Chinatown? The museum, under the
directorship of Fay Chew Matsuda, has an evocative permanent
installation, set in a lantern-shaped design by the architect
Billie Tsien, in which artifacts of Chinese life in New York
decades ago _ shop signs, irons, hope chests, passports, religious
objects _ sit side by side.
</P>
<P>
   The special exhibition on view, ``A Good Place to Land One's
Feet: Brooklyn's New Chinese Community,'' is documentary in
character. But the museum often highlights work by Chinese-American
artists, including Arlan Huang, who is at the International Asian
Art Fair. Chinatown is a vibrant Asian art fair in itself.
</P>
<P>
   In the Buddhist way of thinking, all things are interdependent,
and that is certainly true of art. The objects that fill the
windows of Chinatown's shops _ secular and religious, vivacious,
seductive, hilariously over the top _ have direct connections to
much of the high-priced fare on Park Avenue. Who is to say that the
art in Chinatown is less valuable or beautiful? Who could not be
grateful that it is in New York on permanent display?
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
