<HEADER>
A4224 &Cx1f; taf-z
u e &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-TV-WEEKEND-NYT &LR;      03-25 0862
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-TV-WEEKEND-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
A FEELING WE'RE NOT IN SPRINGFIELD ... 
</HEADLINE>
   (Eds: Production notes are at end of review)  
 (af)  
 By RON WERTHEIMER   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   Lisa Simpson would be charmed by ``Futurama,'' but her brother
Bart might reach for the clicker to see what else was on. That's
just a guess. For a better bead on Bart's preferences, you'd have
to ask a certified expert, like Matt Groening.
</P>
<P>
   He, of course, invented Bart, Lisa and their ubiquitous family.
Now, nine years (several generations in television terms) after
``The Simpsons'' became a national institution, Groening has put
his imprimatur on a second animated Fox series, ``Futurama,'' a
look at life in the year 3000.
</P>
<P>
   You can have your own look on Sunday night, when the new show is
introduced right after ``The Simpsons.'' (It gets one more booster
shot on the following Sunday before moving into its slot on
Tuesdays, starting on April 6.) In Sunday's pilot episode, the only
sample of the series provided for review, you'll meet Fry, a
slacker of the current era who delivers pizza.
</P>
<P>
   Making a delivery to a Manhattan cryogenics lab on New Year's
Eve 1999, he is accidentally frozen. When he thaws out exactly
1,000 years later, this mope doesn't seem to mind being in another
millennium: ``I had nothing to live for in my old life.''
</P>
<P>
   He is quickly befriended by an assertive alien named Leela, who
is comely despite having one eye (``I don't have good depth
perception''), and by a hard-drinking robot named Bender. He bends
things.
</P>
<P>
   Is it unfair to use ``The Simpsons'' as a yardstick to measure
the new show? Old Sophocles probably lamented: ``Come on, guys,
don't compare it to `Antigone.' Just tell me how you like the new
one, about the king and his mama.'' But the temptation is
irresistible.
</P>
<P>
   At first glance you'll see a similarity in the way the
characters are rendered on ``Futurama'' and ``The Simpsons.'' They
each have a pair of those trademark googly Groening eyes. (All
except Leela, of course.) And as Fry keeps getting bonked on the
head by malfunctioning high-tech doors of tomorrow, you may expect
to hear him groan a Homeresque ``Doh!'' But you won't. Because
you're not in Springfield anymore.
</P>
<P>
   Visually, the world of ``Futurama'' is much richer than that of
the Simpsons. Unlike their two-dimensional landscape, this one has
depth and a palette of richly subtle colors. The look is more
inviting and the animation more sophisticated, as in the scenes of
Fry's trip across town in the subway's successor, a giant pneumatic
tube.
</P>
<P>
   But the writing, from the conception of the characters forward,
lacks the bite of its predecessor. A root of the Simpsons' appeal
is that under their crayon-colored faces are people far more real
than those on any other current sitcom. They're lifted (with a bit
of inspired exaggeration) right out of real life. The characters in
``Futurama'' are right out of a hundred movies and television
shows.
</P>
<P>
   Fry and Leela are a couple of misfits hurled (but not too
roughly) by fate from adventure to adventure with their comical
sidekick. And while there is more wit in five minutes of
``Futurama'' than in five months' worth of most network series,
this feels like a good-natured, loving homage to the adventure
genre, from Flash Gordon to ``Speed.'' D'ja hear that, Bart?
Loving, for crying out loud.
</P>
<P>
   Is this the work of the same guy? Well, yes and no. Groening,
who makes a Hitchcockian cameo appearance on Sunday, ``developed''
the series and wrote the pilot with David X. Cohen, a veteran of
``The Simpsons'' and ``Beavis and Butt-head.'' But an animated show
like this is the work of many hands and minds.
</P>
<P>
   The ``Futurama'' credits list 13 people besides Groening and
Cohen whose titles include the word producer. This team clearly had
its own set of goals.
</P>
<P>
   It also had its own set of voices. Fry's comes from Billy West,
a hard-working cartoon actor who has played both members of some
famous pairs: Bugs and Elmer, Ren and Stimpy. His Fry has the sound
of a generic Saturday-morning good guy. His co-star has one of the
most familiar voices on television. She is Katey Sagal, who was Peg
Bundy on ``Married ... With Children.'' While her Leela is far
smarter and more sensitive, you may find it hard not to see Peg in
your mind's eye (with or without depth perception).
</P>
<P>
   Does ``Futurama'' work? The answer is, you should excuse the
expression, in the future. If those 15 producers and their
countless associates can bolster their good intentions with some
more comic fire, this richly drawn show could become, if not a
cultural watershed, at least a weekly habit. &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   PRODUCTION NOTES
</P>
<P>
   `FUTURAMA'  &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Fox, Sunday night at 8:30 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   (Channel 5 in New York) &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Created by Matt Groening and written by David Cohen and
Groening. Rich Moore and Gregg Vanzo, directors; Ken Keeler and
Eric Horsted, co-executive producers; J. Stewart Burns and Patric
Verrone, producers. Produced by the Curiosity Company in
association with 30th Century Fox Television. Cohen and Groening,
executive producers. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   WITH: Voices of Billy West (Fay), Katey Sagal (Leela) and John
DiMaggio (Bender).
</P>
</TEXT>
