<HEADER>
A4228 &Cx1f; taf-z
u i &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-BOLIVIA-CAR-BLESSINGS     03-25 0944
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BOLIVIA-CAR-BLESSINGS-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
BOLIVIAN DRIVERS INVOKE A SPECIAL SAFETY FEATURE: DIVINE
INTERVENTION  
(DW)
</HEADLINE>
   By CLIFFORD KRAUSS   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   COPACABANA, Bolivia _ They drive from all over Bolivia, Peru and
even northern Argentina to this remote town on the shore of Lake
Titicaca _ taxi drivers, truck drivers and other motorists seeking
a priest's blessings for protection against drunken drivers,
landslides, bad brakes and broken axles.
</P>
<P>
   Every morning and afternoon, but particularly on Sundays,
Copacabana's central plaza becomes a jammed parking lot of
rattletrap buses and minivans splotched with mud from long, arduous
journeys through the Andean highlands.
</P>
<P>
   The drivers drape their side-view mirrors and bumpers with
colorful ribbons and bushels of pink and white gladiolus. They
sprinkle their hoods with the petals of white roses. Then they give
their tires a spritz of Bolivian champagne, beer or, for those on a
budget, mineral water.
</P>
<P>
   The pilgrims don't drive home until one of six Franciscan
priests sprinkles holy water on their dressed-up vehicles and says
a prayer asking for divine intervention against everything from
accidents to faulty directions and gas shortages.
</P>
<P>
   ``This is better than car insurance,'' said Mario Kempy Avelo,
23, who drove his new minivan from La Paz as part of his
preparations in starting a taxi business. ``I can't afford any
accidents, so I came as an act of faith.''
</P>
<P>
   No one keeps exact statistics, but Bolivian experts on folklore
say the number of motorists who make the pilgrimage to this town
12,000 feet above sea level every year easily reaches into the tens
of thousands.
</P>
<P>
   The popularity of the pilgrimage makes it the most important
source of income for this town of 5,000 people. Banks stay open on
Sundays to accommodate travelers. Indian women selling miniatures
of the Virgin Mary, flowers and other paraphernalia for the vehicle
blessings do a brisk business.
</P>
<P>
   The makeshift grave sites that mark virtually every twist and
turn on Andean roads, often from head-on collisions between crowded
buses and impatient drivers trying to pass, offer ample motivation
for many to make the drive here as a preventive measure. Meanwhile,
drunk driving is also a big problem in the cities.
</P>
<P>
   ``Everywhere you look there are fender-benders, landslides and
worse,'' said Antonia Canaviri de Soliz, 30, who drove three hours
through a driving rain early one morning with her husband from La
Paz to christen their new taxi cab. ``But when you believe, the
Virgin remains by your side and protects you.''
</P>
<P>
   The custom of driving to Copacabana as a religious rite began in
the 1950s, when a sweeping government land redistribution program
put money in the pockets of the rural masses and created a new
class of drivers. But the ritual has its roots much further in the
past, with the ancient Aymara and Inca Indians, who made
pilgrimages to Copacabana a central part of their lives long before
the Spanish conquistadors arrived here.
</P>
<P>
   Copacabana's holiness originated from its proximity to where the
ancient Andean Indians believed the universe was created: on the
Island of the Sun, a short boat ride from the town's rocky beach.
</P>
<P>
   The Indians came to Copacabana from throughout South America's
central highlands _ journeys that sometimes lasted months _ to
sacrifice white llamas and vicunas to their gods, especially to
Pachamama, the Earth Mother, to whom they relied for the fertility
of their soil. They also had a custom, still called the Ch'alla
(pronounced CHAH-yah), of sprinkling sugary and alcoholic beverages
on their possessions for good luck, and burying llama fetuses under
their houses for divine protection.
</P>
<P>
   When the conquistadors arrived in the mid-16th century, the
Spaniards first tried to ban the Indian rituals as unsavory
paganism, and they covered Indian idols in the center of Copacabana
with a huge Moorish-style cathedral graced by tile domes that still
glisten in the sun. The Indians were largely won over to
Catholicism in the 1580s, after Francisco Tito Yupanqui, a grandson
of an Incan emperor, said he saw an apparition of the Virgin and
carved her likeness.
</P>
<P>
   The so-called Virgin of Candelaria, which is today lodged above
the Copacabana cathedral's altar, remains one of the holiest relics
in all of South America _ and, naturally, a must visit for all the
drivers who come here for divine guidance and protection.
</P>
<P>
   But despite the Virgin's almost immediate popularity in colonial
times, the Spanish were forced to accept a mixing of Indian
religion and Christianity, in part to suppress rebelliousness,
leaving customs that exist to this day. Bolivians still bury the
fetuses of llamas under their homes, and sprinkle alcoholic
beverages on each corner of their house foundations for good luck.
David Mendoza Salazar, a sociologist who works on government
culture programs, said those rituals and the customary drive to
Copacabana for auto blessings complete with alcohol and flowers
``shows that the Aymara traditions still live on in Bolivia.'' He
added, ``Obviously the customs do not take the exact form they did
in precolonial times, but the essence continues.''
</P>
<P>
   The drivers and priests here said they recognized the ancient
origins of their vehicle blessings. But they left no doubt that
their religious faith was unalloyed Catholicism.
</P>
<P>
   ``I respect the Indian past and traditions,'' said Mario Lara,
26, who made the six-hour drive from the Bolivian city of
Cochabamba to christen his newly bought used 1990 Toyota Corolla.
``But that's not why I am here. I'm here for the Virgin and her
protection.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
