u s &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-CAR-NASCAR-MONEYGAME-     03-25 0718
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-CAR-NASCAR-MONEYGAME-NYTR </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
NASCAR'S OTHER RACE IS FOR MONEY 
</HEADLINE>
  (rk) 
 By PATRICK ZIER   
 The Ledger, Lakeland, Fla.   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   NASCAR has become a money game. To win big in Winston Cup, you
need big bucks.
</P>
<P>
   So far this season, all five races have been won by drivers from
two multi-car teams.
</P>
<P>
   Jeff Gordon, who probably has more financial resources to draw
on than anyone in the sport, has won twice for Rick Hendrick.
</P>
<P>
   Jeff Burton also became a two-time winner Sunday in the
rain-shortened race at Darlington, S.C., and his teammate, Mark
Martin, has a win as well.
</P>
<P>
   Burton and Martin are the top cars in Jack Roush's five-car
stable, and while they do not have the money available to Gordon,
they are not far behind.
</P>
<P>
   Various estimates place the amount spent on Gordon's car at
around $50 million a year.
</P>
<P>
   And the cost to major sponsors looking to associate themselves
with name drivers has been rising steadily.
</P>
<P>
   Dale Earnhardt Jr., who has yet to drive a Winston Cup race, has
been signed by Budweiser for a reported $10 million a year.
</P>
<P>
   That figure now seems to be the going rate for a primary sponsor
on a top car.
</P>
<P>
   The huge financial discrepancy between NASCAR's top teams and
those struggling to keep up is a source of concern in the garage,
but Bill France, NASCAR's president, does not seem worried.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's the law of supply and demand,'' France said. ``We can't
regulate how much a company is willing to put into a car.
</P>
<P>
   France said that if a company's value has increased in recent
years, so should its willingness to spend more to sponsor a car.
``It's true the numbers have gone up considerably of late, but the
cost of a loaf of bread has increased, too,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   While that may be true, as sponsorship dollars shoot up, fewer
and fewer companies have the ability to support a Winston Cup
operation.
</P>
<P>
   And sponsors, no matter how much they're paying, still expect
their cars to compete with Gordon and Martin and Burton.
</P>
<P>
   They want exposure, and when they don't get it, they often drop
out.
</P>
<P>
   Budweiser, for example, is leaving Hendrick and driver Wally
Dallenbach to go with the young Earnhardt because it is
dissatisfied with the performance of its car in Hendrick's
operation, where it consistently runs a poor third to Gordon and
Terry Labonte.
</P>
<P>
   The same thing is happening at Roush Racing, where Jack Roush is
already looking for new sources of income for 2000.
</P>
<P>
   Outside of Martin and Burton, Roush's other three cars are
essentially not competitive and their sponsors are getting uneasy.
</P>
<P>
   ``When a company is putting millions into a car, they don't want
to hear that you'll be competitive in three years,'' France said.
``They want to see that car run up front now.
</P>
<P>
   ``What we try to do through the rules is keep everything as
equal as we can so a team getting $10 million doesn't have that
much of an advantage over somebody getting less,'' France said.
</P>
<P>
   ``While the best teams may have an advantage, I don't think the
gap between the cars up front and those running in back is that
much,'' France said.
</P>
<P>
   ``There isn't one huge drop. You don't go from cars getting $10
million to cars with virtually nothing.
</P>
<P>
   ``It goes down in increments. Somebody's getting $10 million,
somebody else is getting $8 million, and so on.
</P>
<P>
   ``I think it's remained pretty competitive,'' France said. ``If
you look at what's happening, the cars are all pretty close.''
</P>
<P>
   While that may be true in terms of qualifying, where the cars
often do run very close to the same speed from front to back, it
doesn't hold up once the racing starts.
</P>
<P>
   Then, the Gordons and Martins and a couple others move in to
take charge.
</P>
<P>
   That's because while everyone understands the basics of putting
a fast car on the track, it's the ability to fine tune, to adjust,
that usually makes the difference in the race. The top teams have a
decided edge there because they are better able to pay attention to
detail.
</P>
<P>
   And they are better able to pay attention to detail because they
have bigger budgets which allows them to come to the track better
prepared.
</P>
<P>
   In Winston Cup, money doesn't talk. It roars.
</P>
<P>
   (The Ledger of Lakeland, Fla., is part of the New York Times
Regional Newspaper Group.)
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
