<DOC>
<DOCNO> NYT19990325.0224 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-03-25 18:39 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A4244 &Cx1f; tad-z
u i &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-KOSOVO-B2-0326-COX     03-25 0659
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-KOSOVO-B2-0326-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    B-2: ALL DRESSED UP, FINALLY SOMEWHERE TO GO
 &HT;    With B2-BOX-0326; KOSOVO-STRIKES-0326.
 &HT;    By SCOTT SHEPARD 
 &HT;    c.1999 Cox News Service 
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON _ The B-2 stealth bomber, after two decades of
development, another decade of political wrangling, and a cost of
$2.1 billion a piece, still has not satisfied its critics despite a
near-perfect combat debut against Soviet-built air defenses in
Yugoslavia.
</P>
<P>
   The two B-2 bombers who joined the NATO air strikes against
Yugoslavia Wednesday night returned safely to Whiteman Air Force
Base in Missouri -- after logging 31 hours in the air -- prompting
proponents to suggest that the controversial aircraft has finally
answered its critics.
</P>
<P>
   ``This plane did everything it advertised and then some,'' said
Brig. Gen. Leroy Barnidge, commander of the 509th Bomb Wing at
Whiteman, the B-2's only operational base.
</P>
<P>
   But Bruce Cuthbertson, a spokesman for Rep. John Kasich, R-Ohio,
the House Budget Committee chairman who tried to kill the bomber
program, said the mission against Yugoslavia ``looked like make
work'' for the B-2.
</P>
<P>
   ``The irony is a plane that was developed to unleash nuclear
weapons on the Soviet Union makes its debut in a conventional
attack on Yugoslavia,'' Cuthbertson added. ``The plane should never
have been built in the first place.''
</P>
<P>
   Pentagon spokesman Kenneth Bacon told reporters Thursday that
the B-2 pilots were ``thrilled to be involved'' in the attack on
Yugoslavia.
</P>
<P>
   He also said the plane was included in the initial air strikes
not only because of its satellite-guided ordnance but also because
of its effectiveness in harsh weather.
</P>
<P>
   ``The advantage of the B-2 bomber is that it is an all-weather
plane . . . and therefore it was successful in dropping its
ordnance,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   Ironically, one of the biggest embarrassments to the Air Force
during the development of the B-2 was its sensitivity to weather.
The General Accounting Office (GAO), a congressional watchdog
agency, reported in 1997 that the bomber had ``significant
maintenance problems,'' mainly because of the sensitivity of the
plane's special coatings, which are supposed to make it invisible
to enemy radar.
</P>
<P>
   ``Exposure to water or moisture can damage some of the
low-observable enhancing surfaces on the aircraft,'' the GAO report
said.
</P>
<P>
   Subsequently, the Air Force cancelled plans to deploy B-2's to
Europe, where it would have required special environmentally
controlled shelters.
</P>
<P>
   Conceived in 1981 as the Reagan administration set out to topple
the ``evil empire'' of the Soviet Union, the B-2 was the subject of
an intense lobbying campaign by its prime contractor, Northrop
Grumman Corp. Its popularity in Congress rested in part on the fact
that 383 congressional districts across 46 states were home to
subcontractors.
</P>
<P>
   But the escalating price of the bomber -- the total cost for a
fleet of 21 is expected to be $44 billion -- gave pause to some
members of Congress. Back when he was a senator from Maine, for
example, William Cohen suggested that sending the B-2 into battle
would be like dispatching ``a Rolls Royce to pick up groceries.''
</P>
<P>
   On Wednesday, Cohen, now secretary of defense, said the B-2 had
performed ``according to its capabilities.''
</P>
<P>
   However, Bacon's comments the next day raised questions about
the extent to which the B-2's were challenged in Yugoslavia.
</P>
<P>
   Bacon acknowledged that no surface-to-air missiles were fired by
Yugoslavian forces at the attacking NATO war planes. ``We don't
know why that was,'' he said. When it was suggested that the
anti-aircraft firepower was being hoarded for the intensified
assault Thursday, he replied, ``That is a possibility but we can't
speculate on that at this stage.''
</P>
<P>
   More B-2's reportedly joined the renewed air assault in
Yugoslavia on Thursday.
</P>
<P>
   ENDIT
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
