<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-03-25 18:41 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A4248 &Cx1f; tad-z
u w &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-KOSOVO-CLARK-0326-COX     03-25 0723
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-KOSOVO-CLARK-0326-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    NO LOVE LOST BETWEEN NATO COMMANDER, MILOSEVIC
 &HT;    With CLARK-BIOBOX-0326; KOSOVO-STRIKES-0326.
 &HT;    By BOB DEANS 
 &HT;    c.1999 Cox News Service 
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON _ In August of 1995, U.S. diplomats on a peace
mission to the Bosnian capital of Sarajevo were forced to travel
the perilous mud road over Mt. Igman after Serbs laying siege to
the city refused to grant them the courtesy of safe passage.
</P>
<P>
   A French military vehicle carrying part of the delegation slid
off the edge of the rain-slicked pass, tumbled more than 200 feet
into a ravine and exploded, killing three American diplomats and a
French soldier.
</P>
<P>
   Traveling in another vehicle as part of the delegation, U.S.
Army Gen. Wesley Clark watched in horror, scrambled down the
rock-strewn hillside and jumped onto the smoldering armored
personnel carrier to begin helping four badly wounded survivors.
</P>
<P>
   He would never forget, though, the charred and broken corpses of
the four who didn't make it, missionaries of peace, casualties of
war.
</P>
<P>
   On Thursday, Clark stood before the cameras at NATO headquarters
in Brussels, ramrod straight and packed tight as a clenched fist
into his heavily-decorated uniform, and laid out his plans for the
Serbs who have turned their guns this time on the civilians of
Kosovo.
</P>
<P>
   ``There is no sanctuary for them,'' vowed Clark, who, as the
supreme allied commander in Europe, now oversees the NATO air
strikes on Yugoslavia, the most potent aerial assault on European
soil since World War II.
</P>
<P>
   ``We are going to systematically and progressively attack,
disrupt, degrade, devastate,'' he said. ``We are going to destroy
these forces.''
</P>
<P>
   A West Point graduate, first in his class, Rhodes scholar and
Vietnam veteran, Clark, 54, is the consummate professional officer.
He is exemplary of the finest military minds of his generation, a
man schooled, trained and disciplined to plan with precision and
execute to the last detail.
</P>
<P>
   ``He's bright, ambitious, willing to take some risks, incredibly
hard-working and very knowledgable,'' said former undersecretary of
Defense, Paul Wolfowitz, now dean of the School of Advanced
International Studies at Johns Hopkins University. ``I have a lot
more confidence in the whole operation than I would if he weren't
there.''
</P>
<P>
   On one point, though, there should be no mistake. Clark holds no
special place in his heart for Serb leader Slobodan Milosevic,
president of Yugoslavia.
</P>
<P>
   ``He is terribly failing the people of that very important
state,'' Clark testified last week before the House Armed Services
Committee.
</P>
<P>
   ``Unfortunately, President Milosevic continues to rely
primarily, it seems, on the use of force in dealing with the crises
that he's created in Yugoslavia,'' said Clark. ``And, in doing so,
he both strengthens his control among the remaining loyal Serbs and
hardens the lines of fractionation that have always existed in the
Balkan region.''
</P>
<P>
   A baby-boomer who grew up in Little Rock, Ark., and received his
master's degree in philosophy, politics and economics from
Britain's Oxford University the same year that Bill Clinton began
attending the school, Clark and his wife, Gertrude, have one son,
Wesley, who lives in California.
</P>
<P>
   Clark, who spoke directly to Clinton on Thursday, is said to
remain close to the president.
</P>
<P>
   He's certainly been close to Clinton's chief Balkan diplomat,
Richard Holbrooke, who was seated near Clark on the ill-fated 1995
passage over Mt. Igman.
</P>
<P>
   During the peace talks at the Wright Patterson Air Force Base
outside of Dayton, Ohio the following November, Clark was the
military compliment to Holbrooke's diplomacy.
</P>
<P>
   Clark's task at Dayton was as simple as it was difficult: to
present Milosevic with what amounted to an inch-thick plan of NATO
occupation for Bosnia, and stand there until the Serb leader signed
it unchanged. Or, as Clark later described it, ``without dotting an
'i' or crossing a 't.'''
</P>
<P>
   That took three weeks.
</P>
<P>
   Again in Kosovo, it's been Milosevic's refusal to sign on to a
plan for admitting NATO peacekeepers that has stalled diplomacy.
</P>
<P>
   The result has been NATO air strikes, which entered their second
punishing day on Thursday, under Clark's command.
</P>
<P>
   ENDIT
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
