<DATE_TIME> 1999-03-25 18:42 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A4252 &Cx1f; tta-z
u i &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-KOSOVO-MACEDONIA-825&AMP;     03-25 1220
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-KOSOVO-MACEDONIA-825&AMP;ADD-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
BOMBINGS SPARK ANGRY PROTESTS IN MACEDONIA
</HEADLINE>
   (See also: KOSOVO-RDP, KOSOVO-MILITARY, KOSOVO-MILITARY-ASSESS,
KOSOVO-GERMANY, KOSOVO-POLICY, KOSOVO-BELGRADE, KOSOVO-PRISTINA,
KOSOVO-REPORTERS, KOSOVO-CHINA, KOSOVO-RUSSIA-ASSESS,
KOSOVO-CLINTON, KOSOVO-ITALY, KOSOVO-VOICES, KOSOVO-B2,
KOSOVO-CLARK-PROFILE, KOSOVO-EUROPE-REAX, KOSOVO-U.N.) 
(wg) 
 By ALESSANDRA STANLEY   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   SKOPJE, Macedonia _ Giving vent to their rage over NATO bombings
of their neighboring country, thousands of sympathizers with Serbia
marched on the U.S. Embassy here on Thursday, throwing rocks,
setting embassy cars on fire and seeking to burn down the compound
with firebombs.
</P>
<P>
   There were also demonstrations and smashed windows outside the
British and German embassies. The riots were the most glaring sign
yet of the mounting tension in the surrounding Balkan states in the
wake of NATO's military action against President Slobodan Milosevic
of Yugoslavia. They were not the only one. Macedonia, the only
republic to emerge relatively unscathed from the breakup of
Yugoslavia, is a poor country with simmering ethnic rivalries of
its own.
</P>
<P>
   Thursday, Prime Minister Ljubco Georgievski warned against
rising anti-NATO and anti-American sentiment, as the Western
alliance's air war against neighboring Yugoslavia continued for a
second day.
</P>
<P>
   ``The two biggest problems the country is facing at the moment
are the inflow of refugees from Kosovo and the emergence of
anti-NATO and anti-American feelings among the Macedonian public,''
Georgievski said, according to the Associated Press.
</P>
<P>
   The presence of 10,000 NATO ground troops, once poised to help
keep a negotiated peace in Kosovo and now waiting edgily for some
sort of military or political denouement in Serbia, has raised
Macedonia's temperature.
</P>
<P>
   So has the arrival of more than 20,000 ethnic Albanian refugees
from Kosovo. Sheltered by friends and relatives in the large ethnic
Albanian community of Macedonia, they are nonetheless viewed with
alarm by some Macedonians of different ethnic origin.
</P>
<P>
   ``There are already too many of them, and we are so few,''
complained Aleksandar Ivanovik, a Serbian Macedonian who works as a
casino security guard. ``This is all an attempt by Albanians to
swallow Macedonia into some greater Albanian state.''
</P>
<P>
   Ethnic Albanians make up roughly one quarter of Macedonia's 2
million people, and their political leaders share power with the
Slav majority in a coalition government formed late last year.
Serbs make up a sliver of the Slav population here.
</P>
<P>
   Demonstrators seemed most preoccupied on Thursday with defying a
NATO show of force they view as humiliating. Brandishing signs that
read, ``Clinton Equals Hitler'' and ``Serbia, we are with you,''
protesters stood across the street from the U.S. Embassy, throwing
rocks and jeering at the sight of embassy employees, who prudently
left the building by mid-afternoon.
</P>
<P>
   An elderly matron, in a formal floral suit and elaborately
coiffed hair, stood among young people and grimly hurled an egg at
a passing humanitarian aid vehicle, screaming ``Fascists!'' A
handful of Macedonian police officers, assigned to guard the
embassy, stood impassively in front of the gate as rocks were
lobbed over their heads at office windows.
</P>
<P>
   At the same time, Macedonian riot police lined up Thursday
evening in front of the Hotel Alexander Palace to try to prevent
hundreds of demonstrators from attacking the jeeps of European and
American monitors, who took over the hotel earlier this week after
peace talks for Kosovo broke down and the monitors were evacuated
from the southern Serbian province, which is just a 45 minute drive
away.
</P>
<P>
   When the crowd there moved toward the embassy, the riot police
followed, lining up in front of the gates to prevent further damage
after a guard house was set afire, and eventually using tear gas to
disperse the demonstrators.
</P>
<P>
   Monitors from the Organization for Security and Cooperation in
Europe, who were morose after watching their peace efforts in
Kosovo go down in flames, silently watched the demonstrators from
their hotel windows.
</P>
<P>
   On Wednesday night, a small crowd of demonstrators threw rocks
at a small unit of Italian NATO troops stationed a few miles from
the Kosovo border, lightly wounding one Italian soldier and pelting
the ambulance that came to take him away. ``It was most
unpleasant,'' said Lt. Col. Giuseppenicola Tota, the commander of
800 troops from the Garibaldi Brigade, which are stationed in
Macedonia along with 4,000 British, 2,800 German and 2,500 French
soldiers.
</P>
<P>
   He said he believed most Macedonians were more relieved than
upset by the presence of NATO ground troops, which send small units
of armored personnel carriers on patrol along the roads _ in effect
taking the place of several hundred U.N. peacekeepers deployed here
since 1993 but disbanded this month after China vetoed the U.N.
force because impoverished Macedonia, apparently anxious for an
attached bounty of aid, established diplomatic ties with Taiwan.
</P>
<P>
   Tota said he was aware of a darkening mood. ``We are on alert
because there is a possibility that Serbian forces could make
reprisals against us,'' he explained. ``But we do not want to give
Macedonians any more feeling of malaise.''
</P>
<ANNOTATION>
   (STORY CAN END HERE. OPTIONAL MATERIAL FOLLOWS.)
</ANNOTATION>
<P>
   While the center of Skopje was overflowing with heated emotions,
the border with Kosovo was eerily quiet Thursday. At Blace, the
main border crossing between Kosovo and Macedonia, only a few cars
from Kosovo crept cautiously into the checkpoint.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's not safe to stay, but it is now not safe to leave,''
explained a 24-year-old who arrived by car from Pristina, Kosovo's
capital, and gave his name only as Ismael. He said he took the risk
to escort his wife and help a neighbor take his wife, mother, and
two children into Macedonia. Since the bombing began, he said,
Serbs in Kosovo have unleashed terror in ethnic Albanian
neighborhoods of Pristina, breaking windows, beating people, and
burning houses.
</P>
<P>
   ``They can't attack NATO, so they are attacking us,'' he
explained. He said that despite the danger, Kosovars are afraid to
flee because paramilitary groups have set up their own make-shift
checkpoints near the border and are harassing would-be refugees. He
said he had to pay a $60 bribe to a Serbian paramilitary officer to
get past.
</P>
<P>
   Hundreds of ethnic Albanian refugees who have fled Kosovo in the
last weeks teemed at the gates of a police station in the largest
ethnic Albanian neighborhood of Skopje Thursday. Most of them
arrived at dawn and waited in vain until late afternoon, seeking to
register as refugees, which entitles them to a three-month
residency card and some food and clothing from Macedonian and
international aid organizations.
</P>
<P>
   ``We stayed as long as we could, then we left,'' Sebahate
Ibishi, 34, who joined her mother in Macedonia last week with her
two children. She said that her eldest son, 17, stayed behind in
their village of Plesina, near Urosevac, to guard their house. Her
husband is a refugee in Germany, but she said she had no hope of
joining him. ``How can I? I have no visa, no money. I just hope we
can someday go home.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
