<HEADER>
A4258 &Cx1f; taf-z
u e &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-CORIGLIANO-ART-2TAKES     03-25 1133
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-CORIGLIANO-ART-2TAKES-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
JOHN CORIGLIANO'S `DYLAN THOMAS TRILOGY' AT CARNEGIE HALL 
</HEADLINE>
   (ART ADV: Photo is being sent to NYT photo clients. Non-subscribers
can make individual purchase by calling (888) 603-1036 or (888)
346-9867.)  
 (Eds: Production notes are at end of review)  
 (af)  
 By ALLAN KOZINN   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEW YORK _ After four decades as a composer of works that have
become increasingly complex and stylistically wide-ranging, yet
also increasingly popular for their lyricism and accessibility,
John Corigliano thought he had figured out how to keep his workload
from becoming overwhelming.
</P>
<P>
   Trim and young-looking at 61, Corigliano insists that he won't
accept a commission until he has asked himself a few crucial
questions.
</P>
<P>
   ``The most important is, why am I writing this work?'' he said.
``What do I want to do in it? What have I got to say that's worth
saying? And what is there new for me to discover in writing it,
either about specific technical problems or abstract musical ones?
For me, these questions are paramount.''
</P>
<P>
   Corigliano has been known to mull over commissions for close to
a year before getting the flash of inspiration that is his creative
green light. He has also turned down lucrative, high-profile offers
because a novel idea didn't come to him.
</P>
<P>
   Once he agrees to a commission, his method is no more rushed.
For example, his opera, ``The Ghosts of Versailles,'' commissioned
by the Metropolitan Opera in 1979, took 12 years to get to the
stage.
</P>
<P>
   But Corigliano says he is busier than he wants to be at the
moment, composing a vocal work for the soprano Sylvia McNair and
the New York Philharmonic and considering a ballet and a handful of
other commissions as well.
</P>
<P>
   Lately, though, his main focus has been his ``Dylan Thomas
Trilogy,'' an evening-long work that has occupied him, on and off,
for the last 40 years. He thought he had finished it in 1976. But
he has revamped it again, and Friday night at Carnegie Hall,
Leonard Slatkin is to lead the National Symphony Orchestra,
augmented by the Choral Arts Society of Washington, the baritone
Hakan Hagegard, the tenor John Aler and Anthony Costanzo, a
countertenor, in the New York premiere of the 1999 version.
</P>
<P>
   ``The thing I like about John's music,'' said Slatkin, who has
conducted most of Corigliano's major works of the last 20 years,
and recorded several, ``is that it's recognizably his. Within any
piece of his, within 25 seconds, you know who wrote it, and as
different as the next work is bound to be, you'll still know it's
him. It's music that has a face, and I admire that. And this
version of the trilogy is like a history of John Corigliano in a
single piece.''
</P>
<P>
   Corigliano began work on the trilogy in 1959, when he was 21 and
taking his first steps as a composer. With no commissions on the
horizon, and a new-found passion for Thomas' poetry, he wrote a
choral setting of ``Fern Hill'' as a gift for Bella Tillis, his
music teacher at Midwood High School in Brooklyn in the early
1950s, who encouraged him to compose at a time when his parents _
his father, also named John Corigliano, was concertmaster of the
New York Philharmonic _ were trying to dissuade him.
</P>
<P>
   When he composed ``Fern Hill,'' Corigliano had just graduated
from Columbia University, where he studied composition with Otto
Luening, and he was about to start on a series of jobs that would
take him through the byways of the music business. These included
radio programming at WQXR and WBAI; writing arrangements for rock
recordings at Kama Sutra and Mercury Records; working on music
programs for CBS television and directing a festival in Corfu.
</P>
<P>
   His first recognition as a composer, first prize at the Spoleto
Festival Competition in 1964 for the Violin Sonata he wrote two
years earlier, was just over the horizon.
</P>
<P>
   Charles Wadsworth, the founder of the Chamber Music Society of
Lincoln Center, knew Corigliano from Spoleto, and commissioned the
second panel of the trilogy, a tenor setting of Thomas' ``Poem in
October,'' for the society's inaugural season in 1969. By the
mid-1970s, Corigliano decided to reorchestrate his two Thomas works
and add a third, a choral setting of ``Poem on His Birthday.'' The
Cathedral Choral Society of the National Cathedral gave that
version of the trilogy its premiere in Washington in 1976.
</P>
<P>
   Corigliano was happy with this configuration at the time. But
when he revisited the score in 1996, he found it unsatisfying. He
was struck by the fact that Thomas' age, when he wrote the first
two poems, corresponded to his own age when he set them to music,
while the dark concerns of ``Poem on His Birthday'' reflected some
of his personal and professional doubts in the mid-1970s.
</P>
<P>
   And he saw the possibility of making the trilogy into a
meditation on youth, age and memory. As it stood, though, it was
three stylistically disparate works, with none of the symmetry and
architectural finesse that have been among Corigliano's hallmarks
since the late 1970s.
</P>
<P>
   `` `Fern Hill' was written when I was much more innocent,
musically,'' Corigliano said. ``The language that I loved at the
time was the American language of Copland, Barber and Bernstein. I
adapted it, utilized it, learned from it and then added other ways
of speaking. By the time of `Poem in October,' I was using more
irregular rhythms, and a harmonic language that had stretched a
bit, and in `Poem on His Birthday,' I was thinking differently
about sonority, and starting to build pieces architecturally.
</P>
<P>
   ``I knew that `Poem on His Birthday,' with some reorchestration,
could stand as the second half of the work,'' he added. ``Now I had
to build `Fern Hill' and `Poem in October' into a logical first
half. I wanted something that would foreshadow `Poem on His
Birthday,' and would make `Fern Hill' and `Poem in October' seem
like reminiscences. So I searched and searched through Thomas'
poems for something I could use, at first with no luck. Then I
found the `Author's Prologue,' which is an amazing poem, and one of
the last things he wrote.''  &QL;
</P>
<P>
   In its new form, the work is an oratorio of sorts. Hagegard, as
Thomas' spirit, sings the ``Author's Prologue'' _ which Corigliano
has split into two sections, each serving as a prelude to one of
the early works _ as well as ``Poem on His Birthday.''
</P>
<P>
   ``It's partly an actor's piece and partly a singer's piece''
Hagegard said of his role. ``There is a lot of music in the poetry
itself. When Thomas recited it, he did it in an almost chanting
kind of way. You can hear that in his recordings. And although we
aren't doing it this way, this time, I could see this piece
semi-staged, with the baritone sitting at a desk in a sweater as a
stage version of Thomas.''
</P>
<P>
   nn
</P>
<P>
   The deepening progression of the solo vocal lines, from the
countertenor of ``Fern Hill'' to the tenor of ``Poem in October''
and the baritone of ``Poem on His Birthday,'' suggests the
progression of age, as does the change in Corigliano's style, from
the unclouded Americana of ``Fern Hill'' through the complexities
of the ``Author's Prologue.''
</P>
<P>
   But style is largely an abstraction to Corigliano.
</P>
<P>
   ``Style is something in my music that I am not aware of,'' he
said. ``I recognize that it's there. People have pointed out to me
certain interval relationships, spacings and superimpositions I
have used in several works, but I haven't done it consciously.
Often, when people talk about style, they mean techniques. In the
Baroque era, there were common techniques that make Bach sound
similar to Handel, but there were also differences in personal
language that make Bach and Handel sound different. Style is more
like the way you sign your name. You scribble it without thinking,
but a handwriting expert can prove whether it's your signature or a
forgery.''
</P>
<P>
   But listen to a few of Corigliano's works, and a sense of his
style quickly emerges. It includes a fondness for extremes, notable
in concertos. Fast movements often push both the soloists'
technique and the ensemble's energy level to the edge, yet his slow
movements are meltingly lyrical.
</P>
<P>
   ``Ghosts of Versailles,'' too, balances hummable melodies
against the manic extroversion of supersonic patter arias,
recurring chase themes and an exploding statue.
</P>
<P>
   It is also eclectic music that touches on influences from Arabic
wind music, Renaissance styles and allusions to Mozart and
Beethoven, to 12-tone rows, Minimalist techniques and waves of
broad-boned Romanticism. And theatricality is a central trait.
</P>
<P>
   When James Galway asked for a flute concerto, Corigliano
supplied ``The Pied Piper Fantasy,'' a work in which the flutist,
costumed as the Pied Piper, leads a chorus of children off the
stage while the orchestra makes the sounds of scampering rats.
</P>
<P>
   Corigliano's working methods are exacting. First he writes prose
descriptions of the imagery and ideas he hopes to convey. He then
draws diagrams that look like annotated EKG's, with wavy lines
representing melodic shapes, proportions and structures, and
sometimes colors, representing shifts in instrumental timbre. When
he finally begins writing the music, he discards dozens of themes
for every one he keeps.
</P>
<P>
   He has a sense of humor under pressure. A few years ago, when he
was juggling a cello work for Yo-Yo Ma and a guitar concerto for
Sharon Isbin, and was late with both, he faxed Ms. Isbin a page
with the guitar chord symbols used in popular sheet music _ C, G,
B7 _ and a note implying that this was the first movement. The
actual work, ``Troubadours,'' was decidedly more demanding.
</P>
<P>
   These pieces have won Corigliano an enthusiastic following
evident in the performance history of some of his recent works.
``The Ghosts of Versailles'' has run two seasons at the Met, and
has been staged at the Lyric Opera of Chicago. It has its European
premiere in Hannover, Germany, next month.
</P>
<P>
   His concertos are performed frequently, and have been recorded
several times each, and the Symphony No. 1, which has had more than
100 performances in the United States and Europe, as well as two
recordings, won the Grawermeyer Award, one of most prestigious
American composition prizes, in 1991.
</P>
<P>
   Corigliano has his detractors, however. When his Symphony had
its premiere in 1990, some reviewers found its topicality to be
pandering, and compared the work to poster art.
</P>
<P>
   Others have been suspicious of Corigliano's eclecticism and
accessibility. Corigliano says he has not read a review, positive
or negative, since 1991, but he notes that younger composers,
including some of his students at Lehman College and the Juilliard
School, share his interest in having their music understood.
</P>
<P>
   ``I think this whole attitude is changing,'' he said, ``because
its roots are in a dogmatic, modernist view of art that is dying in
the United States and much of Europe. I think people are beginning
to realize that it's simple-minded to say that if something is
accessible, it's pandering or easy. I work hard on these pieces. It
takes me two years to write works that people will listen to for 40
minutes, but a lot of that work is clarifying my ideas so that
people want to hear the music again. The fact is, it's not all on
the surface, and if listeners are going to hear the complexities in
these pieces, they're going to have to hear them more than once.
</P>
<P>
   ``That's the way it has always been. Look at Beethoven. His
music is visceral; he can get any school kid to love him. But that
doesn't mean that this child understands him. He understands part
of him, the first layer of the music, and as he continues to
listen, he hears more and more. I want to have that first layer in
my music, too, but I also want the second, third, fourth and fifth.
I don't think it's fair to expect the audience to jump in at Layer
32.
</P>
<P>
   ``I compose to satisfy emotional needs and intellectual
curiosities that I have, and yes, I want the audience to come along
while I explore them. It's strange to me that anyone should think
of that as odd.'' &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   PRODUCTION NOTES
</P>
<P>
   `DYLAN THOMAS TRILOGY' &QL;
</P>
<P>
   The National Symphony will give the New York premiere of John
Corigliano's ``Dylan Thomas Trilogy'' Friday night at 8 at Carnegie
Hall in New York. Leonard Slatkin leads the orchestra, along with
the the Choral Arts Society of Washington, the baritone Hakan
Hagegard, the tenor John Aler and Anthony Costanzo, a countertenor.
Tickets: $17 to $65. Information: (212) 247-7800.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
