<SLUG> BC-O'HAIR-CASE-HNS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
FIGURE IN O'HAIR CASE ORDERED HELD ON WEAPONS CHARGES 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients.)  
 By JOHN MacCORMACK  
 c.1999 San Antonio Express-News  
<TEXT>
<P>
   AUSTIN, Texas _ A figure in the mysterious disappearance of
atheist Madalyn Murray O'Hair was ordered held without bond
Thursday after being arrested the day before on federal weapons
charges.
</P>
<P>
   David R. Waters, 52, appeared before U.S. Magistrate Stephen
Capelle after federal agents raided his Austin apartment and
confiscated more than 100 rounds of ammunition.
</P>
<P>
   ``Federal firearms charges are being filed against Mr. Waters
based on ammunition seized at his residence,'' said Assistant U.S.
Attorney Gerald Carruth in Austin.
</P>
<P>
   ``As a convicted felon, Mr. Waters is prohibited from possession
of firearms or ammunition,'' Carruth said.
</P>
<P>
   Waters has a record that includes convictions for murder, theft,
battery and forgery.
</P>
<P>
   The 119 bullets found by authorities included 49 rounds of 9-mm
hollow-tip bullets of which 13 were loaded into a pistol ammunition
magazine for a Browning High Power pistol, according to court
papers.
</P>
<P>
   The Wednesday raid was staged to occur simultaneously with
federal agents questioning people in Chicago, Michigan and Fort
Worth, Texas, about the O'Hair case.
</P>
<P>
   O'Hair and her two grown children have been missing since 1995,
but there has been no indication to date that they are dead. Waters
is a former office manager for the O'Hairs.
</P>
<P>
   Waters' lawyer, Patrick Ganne of Austin, said federal officials
told him that his client was being implicated by others.
</P>
<P>
   ``I've been in touch with the assistant U.S. Attorney, and he
said a bunch of people are rolling over on him and implicating him
in the murder of the O'Hair family,'' Ganne said.
</P>
<P>
   ``He said you can get the death penalty for solicitation to
commit murder. He said he'd better get right with God and tell his
side of the story,'' Ganne said.
</P>
<P>
   Carruth declined to comment on his conversations with Ganne.
</P>
<P>
   Waters, who has been the object of a federal investigation for
months, has not been named as a suspect in the O'Hair case.
</P>
<P>
   The search of his car and apartment by a dozen agents from both
state and federal forces began early Wednesday and did not end
until late in the day, when Waters was taken out a back entrance of
the apartment complex in handcuffs.
</P>
<P>
   ``Mr. Waters was present during the search. He was very
cooperative,'' FBI spokesman Darren Holmes said.
</P>
<P>
   O'Hair came to prominence three decades ago in the federal court
battles that removed prayer and Bible reading from public schools.
Until she vanished, O'Hair ran a tightly knit cluster of atheist
organizations in Austin.
</P>
<P>
   But in late September 1995, O'Hair, her son Jon Garth Murray and
daughter Robin Murray O'Hair all disappeared after spending a month
in San Antonio on a mysterious errand.
</P>
<P>
   Gold coins valued at $500,000 vanished at the same time.
</P>
<P>
   Theories about their disappearance have ranged from a
self-imposed foreign exile to kidnapping, robbery and murder.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
</P>
<ANNOTATION>
   (STORY CAN END HERE. OPTIONAL MATERIAL FOLLOWS.) &QL; 
</ANNOTATION>
<P>
   &QL;
</P>
<P>
   The series of coordinated police actions Wednesday are the first
public signs that leads may be developing in one of the century's
most baffling celebrity disappearances.
</P>
<P>
   And Waters appears to be key.
</P>
<P>
   Waters quit working for the O'Hairs in 1994 and a year later he
pleaded guilty to stealing $54,000 from atheist accounts.
</P>
<P>
   Although Waters was charged Wednesday with an offense not
connected to the O'Hair case, he has been the focus of police
interest for months.
</P>
<P>
   Waters has consistently denied any knowledge of the O'Hair
disappearance. He has also denied knowing anything about the
gruesome fate of Danny Fry, an old friend from Florida who came to
Austin in the summer of 1995 to work on a big money deal with
Waters.
</P>
<P>
   Fry's nude, beheaded body was found Oct. 2, 1995, near Dallas,
three days after the O'Hairs vanished in San Antonio.
</P>
<P>
   The corpse was discovered less than 48 hours after Fry made a
final call home from Waters's apartment in Austin, telephone
records show.
</P>
<P>
   But the corpse remained unidentified until earlier this year
when DNA testing solved the mystery. That case is being
investigated by the Dallas County Sheriff.
</P>
<P>
   At the Thursday hearing in federal court, Carruth urged that
Waters not be released.
</P>
<P>
   ``He has a lengthy criminal record including several crimes of
violence. If he is released on bond, he will be a danger to others
in the community,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   The judge ordered Waters held pending a bond hearing to be held
within 10 days.
</P>
<P>
   At the hearing, Ganne asked the judge to unseal the search
warrant affidavit that supported the raid on Waters' apartment.
</P>
<P>
   ``We need to see it so we can make some intelligent decisions,''
he told the judge.
</P>
<P>
   Carruth objected.
</P>
<P>
   ``There are other matters contained in the warrant that the
government does not want to disclose at this time, and probably
will not until time of trial,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   After the hearing ended, Ganne told reporters that the
ammunition found Wednesday did not belong to Waters. ``It belonged
to his former girlfriend. She left it when she moved out,'' Ganne
said.
</P>
</TEXT>
