<SLUG> BC-KOSOVO-ITALY-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
IN ITALY, THE CURIOUS GATHER TO WATCH THE WARPLANES TAKE OFF
</HEADLINE>
   (See also: KOSOVO-RDP, KOSOVO-MILITARY, KOSOVO-MILITARY-ASSESS,
KOSOVO-GERMANY, KOSOVO-POLICY, KOSOVO-BELGRADE, KOSOVO-PRISTINA,
KOSOVO-MACEDONIA, KOSOVO-REPORTERS, KOSOVO-CHINA,
KOSOVO-RUSSIA-ASSESS, KOSOVO-CLINTON, KOSOVO-VOICES, KOSOVO-B2,
KOSOVO-CLARK-PROFILE, KOSOVO-EUROPE-REAX, KOSOVO-U.N.) 
(wg) 
 By JOHN TAGLIABUE   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   AVIANO, Italy _ Security was high and the bars and restaurants
normally frequented by NATO troops were swept clean Thursday night
around this northern Italian air base that is the launching pad for
many of the NATO aircraft striking Yugoslavia.
</P>
<P>
   The day was calm, and low clouds hung over the base, blocking
the view of the ring of Alpine peaks to the north. But beginning
just before nightfall, and lasting for more than an hour, a steady
stream of NATO planes lumbered, whistled and roared off the
runways, heading east into the cloudy skies.
</P>
<P>
   Shortly before 6 p.m. here, a large American AWACs
radar-and-command plane took off; at about 6:15, with night falling
fast, eight B-2 stealth aircraft, whistling quietly, climbed into
the air, followed at intervals of about 30 seconds by dozens of
other NATO planes, including F-15s, F-16s, F-18s and EA-6B
Prowlers, jets that seek out and destroy air defenses. Shortly
after 7 p.m., under skies turned black, 14 F-16s took off within 15
minutes.
</P>
<P>
   In about 90 minutes, more than 60 planes _ or half the American,
Canadian and Spanish aircraft now based at Aviano _ took to the
air.
</P>
<P>
   Pilots were not made available to talk to reporters, but members
of flight crews who service the planes were.
</P>
<P>
   ``Last night it seemed everybody worked some,'' said Tech. Sgt.
Rosie Muniz, member of a support crew servicing an F-16 of the Air
Force's 510th Squadron, known as the Buzzards, that flew over
Yugoslavia Wednesday night. ``The tempo was higher than normal.''
</P>
<P>
   Because the raids took place at night, aircraft were refurbished
during daylight hours for Thursday night's raids.
</P>
<P>
   Senior Airman Jeremiah Sullivan, 23, of Nebraska, responsible
for armaments within the same support crew, said the goal was to
bring back the pilot and the plane safely. The F-16 returned with
its pilot and without a scratch, he said, so he had little work.
</P>
<P>
   The F-16 was parked in a Quonset hut-like hangar out at the edge
of the tarmac, past rows upon rows of F-16s, F-18s, and other
aircraft, all heavily armed with missiles and bombs, waiting for
the night's raids.
</P>
<P>
   Empty streets and depopulated bars and pizzerias in and around
Aviano suggested that the servicemen and women were under orders
not to leave the base or had little time to do so because of the
heavy strain on aircraft and flight and maintenance crews. The
California Beer Bar, a favorite hangout, was closed, and the
Western House bar and pizzeria was empty but for four American
servicemen who hunched over a table soccer game, but refused to
talk with a reporter.
</P>
<P>
   Along the road that leads under the flight path, hundreds of
curious Italians gathered to watch the departing aircraft, many
with binoculars or telescopes. Mirko Franzo, a 24-year-old house
painter, said he came often after work to watch the planes, but the
raids over Yugoslavia and the increased flights attracted him
Thursday night.
</P>
<P>
   ``Security is much tighter tonight than it was Wednesday,'' he
said. On Sunday, he added, a group of local pacifists marched to
protest the presence here of the NATO aircraft, and security
officials hung green mesh on the chain link fence surrounding the
base to prevent outsiders' peering in.
</P>
</TEXT>
