A4264 &Cx1f; taf-z
u e &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-FILMS4KIDS-NYT &LR;      03-25 1179
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-FILMS4KIDS-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
THAT CAREFREE ANNA AND HER ROYAL CHARGES 
</HEADLINE>
   (af)  
 By PETER M. NICHOLS   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   THE KING AND I &QL;
</P>
<P>
   An animated film with the voices of Miranda Richardson,
Christiane Noll, Martin Vidnovic, Ian Richardson, Darrell Hammond,
others &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Directed by Richard Rich &QL;
</P>
<P>
   G 100 minutes &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   With an aggressive sea serpent about to make kindling of their
storm-tossed ship, the resourceful Anna rallies herself and the
crew with a jaunty chorus of ``I Whistle a Happy Tune.'' On shore
she'll need that resolve and then some.
</P>
<P>
   Rich's film, based on the Rodgers and Hammerstein musical, is
drawn from the real-life 19th-century adventures of Anna Leonowens
by way of a novel (``Anna and the King of Siam'') adapted from her
memoirs. Among other modifications, the King doesn't die.
</P>
<P>
   Anna, of course, is still on her way to teach his children. Her
employer is a self-assured fellow who embraces science, exchanges
high-fives with his black leopard and obstinately clings to
traditions that restrict his people. But the children are appealing
enough to keep Anna on the job, even though the king confines her
and his brood to the palace.
</P>
<P>
   All is not suppression, however, and soon teacher and pupils are
getting along famously. Even the king lightens up slyly if stiffly.
Still, the old ways persist and the situation isn't helped by a
scheming prime minister who seeks to discredit the king and take
the throne himself. This leads to a chase and some action
sequences, with the king acquitting himself dashingly in his
hot-air balloon. Shall we dance? &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   VIOLENCE Some cartoon pratfalls. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   SEX None. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   PROFANITY None. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   For Which Children? &QL;
</P>
<P>
   AGES 3-5 The film supplies goofy sidekicks and works hard to
stay lively, but this isn't the most accessible story for very
young children. ``Hello, Young Lovers'' and palace politics aren't
exactly in their field of interest at this point and that could
make for a long sit. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   AGES 6-7 For many of them, too, the story will prove slow
going. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   AGES 8-11 There will exceptions, of course, but it's hard to
imagine boys flocking to this tale. Girls should find it
appealing. &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   THE DEEP END OF THE OCEAN &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Michelle Pfeiffer, Treat Williams, Whoopi Goldberg, Ryan
Merriman, Cory Buck, Jonathan Jackson &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Directed by Ulu Grosbard &QL;
</P>
<P>
   PG-13 108 minutes &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   While she steps to a hotel registration desk for a moment, Beth
Cappadora (Ms. Pfeiffer) leaves her 3-year-old son, Ben, in the
care of her 7-year-old, Vincent. When she returns, Ben is gone,
nowhere to be found, vanished. The police are summoned. ``Five
hours ...,'' someone says. At that point it is feared that harm has
come to a child who may have just wandered off.
</P>
<P>
   For Beth and her husband, Pat (Williams), those hours become
nine years. With two other children, she carries on with her
parenting as best she can and continues her career as a
professional photographer. But her anguish keeps her in a continual
state of distraction that affects her marriage and taints her
relationship with Vincent (Jackson), who has grown into a troubled
and resentful teen-ager.
</P>
<P>
   Then one day the doorbell rings and there stands a boy looking
for lawn-mowing jobs. Beth immediately recognizes Ben. He is now
named Sam (Merriman) and lives but two blocks away. At this point
Grosbard's film becomes a bit of a thriller as the who, what and
how get sorted out. After that it is a case of a family trying to
adjust to a miracle that soon becomes a trial.
</P>
<P>
   Sam is a mature, well-adjusted child with an adoptive father he
loves and doesn't want to leave. Vincent &UR;  &LR; has grave problems with
his mother and newfound brother. Pat carries on about being one
happy family again, though he knows better. Beth sees the realities
and takes action. &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   VIOLENCE None. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   SEX There are some references. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   PROFANITY A fair amount. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   For Which Children?  &QL;
</P>
<P>
   UNDER AGE 9 This isn't a movie that would appeal to young
children, nor is it appropriate. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   AGES 10-14 The film may not hold any immediate attraction for
older children either, but at least it has a brain in its head and
deals with an interesting situation. This is one of those movies
that would hold many (not all) young viewers if they gave it a
chance, especially its highly credible performance by Ms.
Pfeiffer. &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   ANALYZE THIS &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Robert De Niro, Billy Crystal, Lisa Kudrow, Joe Viterelli, Chazz
Palminteri &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Directed by Harold Ramis &QL;
</P>
<P>
   R 110 minutes &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   When the mob kingpin Paul Vitti (De Niro) says that he's ``not
thrilled with the level of service here, Doc,'' it gets the
attention of the psychiatrist Ben Sobel (Crystal). Change the first
two letters in Vitti and you get Gotti, which is the kind of
thought that immediately occurs to everybody in this movie.
</P>
<P>
   Vitti has come to Sobel with this little problem here: a
constriction in his chest, a shortness of breath. (Later they get
to the weeping jags and sexual dysfunction.) One doctor has already
been roughed up for suggesting that the trouble is not a heart
attack but intense and admittedly not altogether macho feelings of
anxiety that on occasion give way to total panic.
</P>
<P>
   That is not good news for Vitti, who has a pivotal gangland
confrontation coming up. ``I deal with animals, Doc,'' he says.
``They're very cunning and they smell weakness.'' He puts his life
expectancy at two weeks. Sobel tries to bow out. When Vitti won't
let him, Sobel feels obliged to administer treatment, which means
being on call whenever Vitti has the slightest manifestation.
</P>
<P>
   Vitti learns the ways of therapy. ``I pay you to tell you
something and you say it right back to me,'' he complains. He
dreams about black snow and weeps a lot, one time for 45 minutes
straight at the sight of puppies on television. A therapeutic
session in Miami results in a double homicide. Later Sobel is
forced to shoot his own way out of a hit attempt when Vitti lies
sobbing on the ground curled up in the fetal position.
</P>
<P>
   It all has to do with repressed feelings for his father. Told
about Oedipus, Vitti is afraid to call his mother. But gradually he
opens up to Sobel, begins to recognize his deeper self and regroups
to deal with his colleagues. If only he can stop crying. &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   VIOLENCE There is much gunfire and other kinds of assault, but
most of it is perpetrated in the spirit of comedy. While people get
hurt, nothing is very graphic. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   SEX Vitti has difficulty in bed with his mistress. ``Would you
stop talking? I'm trying to do this here,'' he tells her. At other
times, there are sexual references. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   PROFANITY No one is more prolific with expletives than a mobster
under duress. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   For Which Children?  &QL;
</P>
<P>
   AGES 12-14 The R rating is primarily for language, though it
could be argued that the violence and sex approach that level. In
sum, however, the film is often hilarious and has fine
performances. Parents might allow that the positive elements
outweigh the negative ones. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   AGES 15 AND UP There really shouldn't be any objection.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-03-25-99 1857EST &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> NYT19990325.0240 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-03-25 18:58 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A4265 &Cx1f; taf-z
u a &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-CARS-850&AMP;ADD-NYT &LR;      03-25 1024
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-CARS-850&AMP;ADD-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
HIGH-VOLTAGE BENEFITS OF IMPROVED BATTERIES
</HEADLINE>
   (rk) 
 By   MATTHEW L. WALD   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   One of the most primitive and troublesome components under a
car's hood, the battery, is due for an update, auto company
executives say. As a result, there could be a cascade of new
technologies that would make cars more fuel efficient and less
likely to turn up dead on cold winter mornings. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   For as long as cars have had batteries, they have stored
electricity with a chemical reaction involving lead and acid.
Although 6-volt systems were once common, automotive electrical
systems were standardized at 12 volts in 1955. Thus, the design now
in use has outlived such mainstays as carburetors, bias-ply tires
and leaded gasoline. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Engineers want to redesign the electrical system partly because
they would like to run more parts of a standard car on electricity,
even if the basic energy source is still a gasoline-driven engine.
</P>
<P>
   Two candidates for conversion to electricity are power-steering
units and some components of transmissions. Both now typically
operate on hydraulic power, which in turn is produced by a pump
driven by belts that run off the drive shaft.
</P>
<P>
   Electric pumps can produce hydraulic pressure more efficiently
in applications where the need for pressure is sporadic. And in
some applications, engineers think they can dispense with
hydraulics altogether and do the job with electricity.
</P>
<P>
   But 12-volt motors that pump hydraulic fluid or move mechanical
components like steering systems are relatively big and
inefficient. Further, the cables that move electricity around at 12
volts are thick and heavy, and the heavier the cable the more
energy is lost within the cable itself.
</P>
<P>
   With higher voltage, engineers could use thinner cables, saving
weight and energy.
</P>
<P>
   At 12 volts, ``we end up adding so many pounds of wire,'' said
Robert Stempel, an advocate of the change. Stempel, the former
chairman of General Motors Corp., is now chairman of Energy
Conversion Devices Inc. of Troy, Mich., which pioneered nickel
metal-hydride batteries, the kind used in cellular phones and
laptop computers. ``Isn't it time to raise voltage?'' he asked.
</P>
<P>
   The standard car battery is known in the industry as an SLI
battery, for starting, lighting and ignition. By adding cells,
lead-acid SLIs could be made to run at any voltage. But these
batteries are bulky already and would quickly become more so as
their voltage was increased.
</P>
<P>
   Stempel hopes to sell nickel metal-hydride batteries with more
than one pair of terminals, each pair giving off a different
voltage _ for example, 12 volts out of one pair, to run the radio,
and 42 out of the other pair, for the power steering. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   There are other reasons, experts at auto manufacturers say, to
move into more modern SLI batteries, like the ones that have
marched through a range of other consumer products like portable
tape players, cellular phones and laptop computers. Nickel
metal-hydride is a leading contender, but the answer might be
lithium ion, which is also in commercial use in portable electronic
devices. Or it could be some battery technologies that do not yet
exist in other products.
</P>
<P>
   Laptop and phone batteries store more energy per pound and
withstand deep discharges better. In contrast, the standard
automotive lead-acid battery is irreparably damaged by just a few
full discharges _ as when the driver leaves the lights on. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   And at extremely low temperatures, nickel metal-hydride loses
less of its ability to deliver current than lead-acid does, its
backers say. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   That is a consumer benefit that potential purchasers would have
to be convinced was worth the extra cost. But automakers might be
more likely to change the electrical system for a more direct
reason, better fuel economy, particularly in Japan and Europe. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Mark Verbrugge, a General Motors technology specialist now on
loan to the U.S. Advanced Battery Consortium, a research group
financed by the federal government and the auto companies, said
that continuously variable transmissions _ which are under
development by many leading car companies and offered in the United
States on the Honda Civic HX _ would be good candidates for
controls operated by an electric or electro-hydraulic source.
</P>
<P>
   This type of transmission does not use conventional gears, but
belts and pulleys, which could be manipulated by electric-powered
controls, he said. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Steering systems are also a candidate for change. Auto designers
would have new flexibility if the power steering did not have to be
connected to the drive shaft by a belt, he said. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Verbrugge said that these innovations might turn up first in
Japanese models, where fuel economy was more important. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Lead-acid has a significant advantage, though: its cost. The
business is so competitive that profits are measured in pennies per
battery, industry executives say. In a new car, the lead-acid
battery costs the auto company only about $25, said John Wallace,
director of environmental vehicles at Ford. A nickel metal-hydride
battery would cost more than $100 extra, he said, and at that price
it would be hard to justify. &QL;
</P>
<ANNOTATION>
   (STORY CAN END HERE. OPTIONAL MATERIAL FOLLOWS)
</ANNOTATION>
<P>
   Battery storage capacity is often measured in kilowatt hours.
One kilowatt hour is the amount of electricity needed to keep ten
100-watt bulbs lit for an hour; it sells at retail for about 8
cents.
</P>
<P>
   ``Your laptop battery costs thousands of dollars per
kilowatt-hour of capacity,'' Wallace said. ``An electric vehicle
battery of today costs maybe $1,000 a kilowatt hour. Your SLI
battery costs 50 bucks.''
</P>
<P>
   Stempel, though, predicted that prices would fall with mass
production. And if automakers choose SLI batteries using nickel
metal-hydride for even a small part of their production, he said,
the demand would drive output high enough to allow automation and
other cost-cutting technologies. That, he said, could make a
beefed-up battery in a gasoline car a stepping stone to a purely
electric car that would be more affordable than those now on the
market.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-03-25-99 1858EST &QL; 
</TRAILER>
