<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-03-25 18:59 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A4266 &Cx1f; tta-z
u i &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-KOSOVO-RUSSIA-ASSESS-     03-25 0732
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-KOSOVO-RUSSIA-ASSESS-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
ANALYSIS: FROM THE RUSSIANS, HARSH WORDS BUT NOT DEEDS
</HEADLINE>
   (wg) 
 By MICHAEL R. GORDON   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   MOSCOW _ As Yugoslavia's ambassador to Russia, the elder brother
of Yugoslav President Slobodon Milosevic has done his best to drum
up support for Yugoslavia in Moscow.
</P>
<P>
   So far, though, Borislav Milosevic does not have much to show
for his efforts.
</P>
<P>
   While Russian officials have railed against the Western alliance
in terms that recall the most tense days of the Cold War, and an
unruly mob protested at the U.S. Embassy here on Thursday, the
Kremlin has been careful not to match its angry rhetoric with
deeds. With the director of the International Monetary Fund set to
visit Moscow over the weekend to continue negotiations for a loan
the Russian government desperately wants, the Kremlin seems to have
calculated that this is no time to escalate its quarrel with the
West.
</P>
<P>
   President Boris Yeltsin signaled as much on Thursday when he
said that his aides had devised ``extreme measures'' to respond to
NATO's attacks but would keep them in reserve.
</P>
<P>
   ``We are above that,'' Yeltsin said. ``On the moral level, we
are superior to the Americans.''
</P>
<P>
   For a nation that waged a bitter and indiscriminate war in
Chechnya, a separatist region in southern Russia, the talk about
moral superiority seemed decidedly out of place. But it is not easy
for the Kremlin to explain its relative impotence to the public.
</P>
<P>
   As NATO began its second day of airstrikes, chauvinism and
indigination were the primary weapons of Russia's public relations
offensive. Russian Foreign Minister Igor Ivanov lambasted the
bombing attacks as an American attempt to bully the world.
</P>
<P>
   ``The true aims are obvious,'' Ivanov declared at a press
conference on Thursday. ``To impose on the world the political,
military, and economic dictate of the United States.''
</P>
<P>
   Gen. Anatoly Kvashnin, the chief of Russian General Staff, then
gave a skewed military briefing, noting incorrectly that two NATO
combat planes had been shot down and suggesting that NATO ground
forces were poised to invade the Balkan nation, a plan the alliance
denies.
</P>
<P>
   But in its deeds, Russia has been far more measured. It recalled
its ambassador to NATO and announced it would not attend a NATO
celebration next month in Washington, both symbolic steps. Prime
Minister Yevgeni Primakov said on Thursday that the ratification of
the START-2 treaty would be deferred, but not necessarily killed.
</P>
<P>
   Russia's political and military weakness is one reason for its
temperate response. Not even Belgrade takes Moscow's appeals
seriously.
</P>
<P>
   So is Russia's economic neediness, a fact driven home this week
by the continued slide of the ruble, which fell to 26 rubles to the
dollar Thursday from 22 last week.
</P>
<P>
   Seeking to assuage Russia, the United States encouraged the IMF
director to go to Moscow. Russia is seeking to receive a large
enough loan from the fund to offset the $4.8 billion it owes the
fund this year.
</P>
<P>
   So this is no time for the Kremlin to test the West's patience.
</P>
<P>
   At Yugoslavia's embassy, the gap between Russia's admonishments
and actions seemed clear. Borislav Milosevic, a dapper diplomat who
said he had not talked to his brother since the NATO strikes began,
thanked Moscow for its moral support.
</P>
<P>
   In addition to the Kremlin's public statements, thousands of
Russians have called to offer their services, including one Russian
army unit, according to an aide to the ambassador.
</P>
<P>
   Ragtag groups of volunteers, however, are unlikely to be of
great help to the Serbian military, and Borislav Milosevic said
there were no plans to actually transport them to Yugoslavia.
</P>
<P>
   But Yugoslavia is not receiving as much backing as it might.
Yugoslavia and Russia, for example, have a military agreement under
which Moscow services Soviet-era military equipment _ an accord
that has been shelved because of the U.N. sanctions.
</P>
<P>
   Yugoslavia says that Russia should no longer feel legally bound
by the sanctions. The Communists and Moscow Mayor Yuri Luzhkov have
urged the Kremlin to ignore the sanctions, but Primakov says Russia
will continue to abide by them, at least for now.
</P>
<P>
   At his embassy, Borislav Milosevic sought to put the best face
on the situation. ``The Russian response,'' he said hopefully, ``is
a process.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
