<DOCNO> NYT19990325.0247 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-03-25 19:11 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A4279 &Cx1f; kan-z
r k &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-GUSEWELLE-COLUMN-KAN &LR;      03-25 0538
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-GUSEWELLE-COLUMN-KAN </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
THE OSCARS: AND THE WHINER IS... 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By C.W. GUSEWELLE  
 c. 1999 Kansas City Star  
<TEXT>
<P>
   (Undated) Academy Awards night _ Hollywood's annual orgy of
puffery and preening _ I find an extravagant bore.
Self-congratulation, no matter how it's fancied-up in feathers,
sequins and rented jewelry, does not play well as entertainment.
</P>
<P>
   What I (ital)do(end ital) enjoy is the whining one hears
afterward.
</P>
<P>
   This year's award for best whiners went to the moguls at
Dreamworks, producers of ``Saving Private Ryan.'' Fox
Entertainment, maker of ``A Thin Red Line,'' took the honors as
best supporting whiner.
</P>
<P>
   The target of their wounded complaints was Harvey Weinstein,
boss at Miramax, whom they accused of an unwholesome lust for
Oscars.
</P>
<P>
   (But I seem to recall that we saw them sitting there, too,
dressed to the nines, faces alight with vanity and expectation.)
</P>
<P>
   Weinstein, they implied, had bought his prizes with extravagant
promotional campaigns for ``Life Is Beautiful'' and ``Shakespeare
in Love.''
</P>
<P>
   Do we detect, here, the faint flavor of sour grapes?
</P>
<P>
   I'm not, thank heaven, a professional motion picture critic,
condemned to spend my life watching the torrent of stuff the movie
industry churns out, much of it trivial.
</P>
<P>
   But in the course of a year we do spend a good number of
evenings at what I still like to call the picture show. A lot of
those are wasted evenings. A glorious few are not _ and it is the
hope of one of those, like the one good golf shot in a duffer's
round, that keeps us coming back.
</P>
<P>
   As it happens, I saw all four of the pictures mentioned above,
and my wife saw three of them, passing up ``Private Ryan'' because
of the violence it contained.
</P>
<P>
   Precisely because of that violence, the beginning of the movie
was riveting _ depicting with uncommon power the horrific agony of
combat. After that, though, there was only the most insubstantial
of stories to tell.
</P>
<P>
   ``A Thin Red Line'' was, to my mind, a tedious dog. Not a single
scene of it can be recalled.
</P>
<P>
   These, mind you, are only an amateur's opinions. The views of
the industry savants who touted both movies, especially ``Ryan,''
as front-runners in the Oscar sweepstakes no doubt carry greater
weight.
</P>
<P>
   But then we often disagree with the experts. They gave short
shrift to ``Analyze This,'' which we found wonderfully
entertaining. By contrast, an Irish picture called ``The General,''
proclaimed a wonder, seemed plodding and unoriginal.
</P>
<P>
   The response of ordinary movie-goers may not be very important,
but it must count for something. And my (ital)guess(end ital),
while it can't be proved, is that the public would say the awards
for the year's best actor and best picture were dead on the mark.
</P>
<P>
   The nights we were there, the audiences for Roberto Benigni's
miraculous ``Life Is Beautiful'' and for ``Shakespeare in Love''
remained in their seats until the last line of credits had scrolled
across the screen.
</P>
<P>
   And when finally they left the theater, they wore expressions
that suggested they'd been more than just entertained. They'd been
touched to their hearts.
</P>
<P>
   Or isn't that what movies are supposed to do?
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
