<HEADLINE>
ODDS ARE, SOMETHING ISN'T LEGAL 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By DIANE STAFFORD  
 c. 1999 Kansas City Star  
<TEXT>
<P>
   (Undated) March Madness wallpapered cubicles with tournament
brackets and filled break rooms with betting-pool banter. It's the
latest indicator that workplace wagering is rife.
</P>
<P>
   But is it wrong?
</P>
<P>
   Betting on the NCAA basketball tournament _ and even on the date
a baby will be born _ is a form of gambling that, technically, is
illegal in Missouri and Kansas. You could be charged with a
misdemeanor.
</P>
<P>
   In reality, though, law enforcement officials admit that office
pools aren't likely to land you in deep water.
</P>
<P>
   Johnson County, Kan., District Attorney Paul Morrison says that
when something of value is wagered on games of chance (such as
betting on sports events over which you have no control), that's
against the law. Ditto, says the chief deputy prosecuting attorney
of Jackson County, Mo., David Baker.
</P>
<P>
   The only forms of gambling that are legal in Kansas are
pari-mutuel wagering and lotteries sanctioned by the state. In
Missouri, only licensed gambling, such as games of chance on the
riverboats and the state lotteries, is legal.
</P>
<P>
   So if you put cash in a March Madness betting pool, you broke
the law.
</P>
<P>
   The odds, though, are heavily against your getting in trouble _
unless you're a bookie who skims profits off the top. Frankly,
prosecutors said, law enforcement priorities are elsewhere.
</P>
<P>
   More than 500 U.S. human-resource professionals, surveyed by the
Society for Human Resource Management, gave insight into the
prevalence of gambling on their job sites _ ranging from 58 percent
who had workplace Super Bowl bets down to 2 percent who had
employees participating in fantasy basketball leagues.
</P>
<P>
   In addition to NCAA basketball tournament pools, they cited
other common forms of workplace wagering, including football season
pools, group lottery purchases, golf tournament pools, and fantasy
baseball and football leagues.
</P>
<P>
   Sixty-three percent of the human-resource respondents said their
organizations had no written policies about workplace gambling.
Eleven percent said their organizations had policies that were not
written but ``understood.''
</P>
<P>
   Among the 34 percent of organizations that had written policies,
more than half of them prohibited workplace wagering. About
one-fifth ``permitted but discouraged'' it. Sixteen percent of the
written policies actually permitted on-site gambling.
</P>
<P>
   Overall, human-resource people weren't too worried about
gambling on the job. For one thing, they didn't see a productivity
loss because of wasted time. For another, few bosses want to be
hard-nosed meanies and steal a few moments of fun from employees.
</P>
<P>
   Neither Morrison nor Baker could remember a workplace gambling
case hitting their offices. But if some righteous individual chose
to file a complaint because of money changing hands illegally,
they'd have to look into it.
</P>
<P>
   Anyone worried about the potential consequences could do what
Morrison counsels for his office staff: Bet for pride, not money.
If no cash changes hands, there's no crime.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
