A4283 &Cx1f; kan-z
r w &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-ASHCROFT-VICTIMS-KAN &LR;      03-25 0854
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-ASHCROFT-VICTIMS-KAN </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
SENATOR RESPONDS TO GOVERNOR'S COMMUTATION OF A DEATH SENTENCE 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By KEVIN MURPHY  
 c. 1999 Kansas City Star  
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON _ Missouri Gov. Mel Carnahan's decision to spare the
life of a condemned killer has prompted Sen. John Ashcroft to
propose a change in a possible constitutional amendment on victims'
rights.
</P>
<P>
   Ashcroft, facing a challenge from Carnahan in Senate elections
next year, said Wednesday that relatives of victims have a right to
be notified if a governor decides to commute a death sentence. Two
months ago at the request of Pope John Paul II, Carnahan spared the
life of Darrell Mease, who had killed three persons.
</P>
<P>
   Ashcroft related the story of Mease to the Senate Judiciary
Committee, on which he serves, without mentioning Carnahan by name.
Later, he denied that his proposal had political underpinnings.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'm proposing this because this is the way to help victims of
crimes relieve the distress of being ignored in the criminal
justice system,'' Ashcroft said.
</P>
<P>
   Carnahan campaign spokesman Roy Temple saw it differently.
</P>
<P>
   ``He's dragging crime victims and their families into his
political gamesmanship,'' Temple said. ``It's pretty pathetic.''
</P>
<P>
   Ashcroft brought up the Mease case during a committee discussion
of a broader constitutional amendment on victims' rights. Ashcroft
proposed changing the amendment to ensure that relatives are
consulted before a commutation.
</P>
<P>
   Ashcroft said relatives of a couple and their paraplegic
grandson whom Mease shot to death ``did not get a phone call, even
a letter'' about Carnahan's decision to let Mease spend his life in
prison.
</P>
<P>
   ``That's just wrong, and it violates our basic sense of decency,
fairness and compassion,'' Ashcroft told the committee.
</P>
<P>
   But Chris Sifford, the governor's press secretary, said
Carnahan's office did contact some of the victim's relatives in the
hours before the governor signed the document to commute Mease's
sentence.
</P>
<P>
   ``We tried to inform as many family members as we could, but we
didn't reach all of them, due to human error,'' he said. The
Department of Corrections did not have adequate information on how
to contact relatives, Sifford said.
</P>
<P>
   Carnahan has said he is comfortable with the Mease decision and
made it because he was very moved that the pope paused in his visit
to St. Louis to seek mercy for one individual.
</P>
<P>
   ``The governor didn't make a politically calculated decision,''
Temple said. ``He did it based on the set of circumstances he was
faced with.''
</P>
<P>
   By the same token, a spokesman for the Missouri Republican Party
said, Ashcroft is not being political by using the case to make an
argument for greater victims' rights in death sentence
commutations.
</P>
<P>
   ``There is nothing political about the murder of a paraplegic
teen-ager,'' Daryl Duwe said. ``That's what the death penalty law
was written for.''
</P>
<P>
   Duwe said Carnahan could have told the pope, ``We have a law and
my job is to uphold the law.'' Carnahan has signed off on 26
executions during his six years in office.
</P>
<P>
   Ashcroft portrayed himself to the Senate committee as a
supporter of victims' rights when he was Missouri governor for
eight years. In his final year as governor in 1992, he said,
Missouri voters enacted a constitutional amendment on victims'
rights.
</P>
<P>
   But the lead sponsor of a resolution that put that issue on the
ballot said Wednesday he didn't recall that Ashcroft did anything
to help the measure pass. The resolution did not require or get
Ashcroft's signature to get on the ballot. He could have signed it
but did not, said Sen. Harold Caskey, a Butler Democrat.
</P>
<P>
   ``It was a victims' rights group that promoted it,'' Caskey
said.
</P>
<P>
   Sifford said Carnahan has the better record on victims' rights.
Carnahan proposed and helped pass a 1994 victims' rights bill that
required victims to be given more information about the sentencing,
pardoning or commuting of sentences of criminals, he said.
</P>
<P>
   Ashcroft told the Senate committee that the proposed federal
amendment allows victims to be heard at every critical stage from
trial to imprisonment, ``but it denies victims any rights when a
governor considers overturning a sentence with a stroke of his
pen.''
</P>
<P>
   He said later, ``This amendment can be improved by understanding
the pain that crime victims can suffer when they are not consulted
or informed or are not participants in a process that gets involved
in the executive branch.''
</P>
<P>
   Victim rights is not the only crime-related issue Ashcroft has
focused on in recent months. He pushed legislation earlier this
year that directed more money to Missouri to fight the
methamphetamine problem and he plans to hold a public forum in
Kansas City Tuesday to discuss meth legislation.
</P>
<P>
   He also sponsored a bill this month that would crack down on
those who use juveniles to commit crimes.
</P>
<P>
   Ashcroft had considered a bid for president but decided to focus
instead on getting re-elected after Carnahan declared last November
that he was running for the seat Ashcroft won in 1994.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
