<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-GUNS-POLL-KAN </SLUG>
  
 POLL TRACKS MISSOURIANS' RESPONSES On CONCEALED-WEAPONS ISSUE  
 (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By KIT WAGAR  
 c. 1999 Kansas City Star  
<TEXT>
<P>
   KANSAS CITY, Mo. _ With less than two weeks to go, the campaign
to legalize concealed weapons in Missouri appears to be too close
to call, a statewide poll by The Kansas City Star showed.
</P>
<P>
   The poll, conducted last week, found that 42 percent of voters
surveyed opposed Proposition B, which would allow Missourians to
carry a concealed gun for the first time in 124 years. Thirty-nine
percent supported it.
</P>
<P>
   Those numbers were well within the poll's margin of error of
plus or minus 4 points, making the race a statistical toss up.
</P>
<P>
   The overall findings, however, masked wide variations in the
proposition's appeal between African-Americans and whites, men and
women and voters in rural and urban areas.
</P>
<P>
   While whites were evenly split _ 41 percent for the measure vs.
40 percent against _ African-Americans opposed the proposition by a
ratio of nearly 4 to 1.
</P>
<P>
   Men were nearly twice as likely as women to support the measure.
</P>
<P>
   In Kansas City and St. Louis, solid majorities planned to vote
against it. The measure would pass in rural areas 43 to 37 percent,
but that support also was within the poll's error margin.
</P>
<P>
   Proposition B, by far the biggest issue on the April 6 ballot,
would allow Missouri residents to get a permit to carry concealed
guns after passing a background check and taking 12 hours of
firearms training. Permits could be denied to people convicted of
felonies, habitual drunks and the mentally incompetent.
</P>
<P>
   Supporters argue that the proposal would reduce crime and return
a fundamental privilege to law-abiding adults. Opponents say it
would increase the number of accidental shootings and cause minor
arguments to escalate into gunplay.
</P>
<P>
   The poll found, however, that substantial numbers of potential
voters question whether concealed weapons play a role in reducing
crime.
</P>
<P>
   Even among people who support concealed weapons, one in four
said they don't. Close to half of the gun owners _ 45 percent _
opposed the proposal.
</P>
<P>
   Nearly eight in 10 of the respondents had no plans to apply for
a concealed-carry permit. And fewer than half of those who would
get a permit ever expect to use their gun for protection.
</P>
<P>
   Among African-Americans surveyed, four in six opposed concealed
guns while just one in six supported them.
</P>
<P>
   Richard Rosenfeld, a criminology professor at the University of
Missouri-St. Louis, said those results were less a racial
difference than a reflection of the black community's experience
with guns.
</P>
<P>
   ``Those numbers reflect the hard-won experience of black people,
who face a significantly higher risk of gun violence than whites,''
Rosenfeld said. ``With no experience, it's easy to suppose that
with lots of guns, there is less violence. But people who deal with
it know that it's hard to support that myth.''
</P>
<P>
   Missouri crime statistics support Rosenfeld's observation.
African-Americans make up just 11 percent of Missouri's 5.4 million
people. But they made up 62 percent of the murder victims in 1997,
the latest statistics available.
</P>
<P>
   That experience with gun violence may help explain a paradox.
African-Americans don't support the concealed weapons law, but they
would be much more likely than whites to seek a permit if the
proposition becomes law. More than a third of the African-Americans
surveyed said they intended to apply for a permit compared with one
in five whites.
</P>
<P>
   While gun ownership rates were similar for African-Americans and
whites, their reasons for owning guns were very different. Among
whites, nearly half owned guns for hunting; less than one in four
owned guns for protection.
</P>
<P>
   Among African-Americans, 25 percent owned guns to hunt; 55
percent owned guns for protection.
</P>
<P>
   More than eight in 10 African-Americans also rejected the
argument that more guns means less crime. About 57 percent of
whites said guns fail to reduce crime.
</P>
<P>
   Rosenfeld said urban violence also helps explain the sharp
division in attitudes between the state's two major cities and the
rest of the state.
</P>
<P>
   In Kansas City and St. Louis, 57 percent of those polled opposed
Proposition B. Only one in three Kansas City voters supported it.
In St. Louis, support was only one in five.
</P>
<P>
   The rest of Missouri, where half the people surveyed own guns,
supported the proposal by a slim margin.
</P>
<P>
   In rural areas, Rosenfeld said, people see a low incidence of
crime and a high degree of gun ownership and conclude that a
concealed-gun law would be a good idea. Realities of urban life, in
which handguns are an integral part of gang activity, drug dealing
and other crime, put guns in a different light, he said.
</P>
<P>
   The Kansas City Star's poll surveyed 600 registered voters from
March 14 to 17. Calls were random except for controls to obtain an
accurate sampling by gender, county and age to match Missouri's
population.
</P>
<P>
   The poll is accurate with a 95 percent degree of confidence with
a margin of error of plus or minus 4 percentage points on each
figure. Therefore, when comparing two figures _ such as the total
supporting and the total opposing proposition B _ each figure could
be off by up to 4 points, creating as much as an 8-point difference
from the poll results.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
