<SLUG> BC-PARITY-MOVEMENT-KAN </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
FARM PARITY EFFORT RAISES CRITICISMS 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By JUDY L. THOMAS  
 c. 1999 Kansas City Star  
<TEXT>
<P>
   (Undated) In 1977, Eugene Schroder co-founded the American
Agriculture Movement, a group that later made headlines when
thousands of farmers drove their tractors to Washington, D.C., to
protest farm conditions.
</P>
<P>
   The movement fizzled in the 1980s after years of unsuccessful
attempts to change agriculture policy and help farmers get higher
prices for their products.
</P>
<P>
   Now, the Colorado rancher and veterinarian is back. Schroder
will be in northeast Kansas Thursday night to garner support for
what he says is a new grass-roots effort to resolve the current
farm crisis.
</P>
<P>
   Schroder said the campaign _ called The Parity Group _ began
about three weeks ago and has rapidly gained momentum. A March 4
meeting in Hereford, Texas, attracted 500 people.
</P>
<P>
   ``There are literally thousands of people working on this,''
Schroder said. ``There are meetings taking place every day all
across the country.''
</P>
<P>
   But those who monitor right-wing groups say the campaign raises
concerns. They say that Schroder's former organization was
influenced by the paramilitary Posse Comitatus group and that he is
taking advantage of the depressed farm economy to create a
political movement.
</P>
<P>
   ``Eugene Schroder has come up with a dozen schemes over the last
20 years, all of which he has said would help the farmer,'' said
Devin Burghart of the Center for New Community, an Illinois-based
group that monitors right-wing activity.
</P>
<P>
   ``None of them ever helped the farmer, and most of them pointed
farmers away from dealing with the real economics of agriculture
and toward cockamamie conspiracy theories.''
</P>
<P>
   Schroder, 51, said the concerns are unfounded and denies
involvement with any anti-government group.
</P>
<P>
   ``I really don't know what that group (Posse Comitatus) ever did
or what it stood for,'' Schroder said. ``I'm not a radical. I'm
just a farmer and a rancher and a veterinarian. I think I've
perceived some fundamental issues that are important, dealing
strictly with matters of the law.''
</P>
<P>
   Organizers are expecting at least 200 to attend tonight's
meeting in Seneca.
</P>
<P>
   According to press reports, some American Agriculture Movement
members _ including Schroder _ attended a three-day ``survival
school'' in Weskan, Kan., in 1982. One of the instructors was a
well-known Posse Comitatus leader.
</P>
<P>
   In 1983, Kansas Attorney General Bob Stephan released a report
indicating that the school taught sessions on knife fighting,
guerrilla warfare, bomb-making and hand-to-hand combat.
</P>
<P>
   Schroder says he doesn't remember whether he attended the
training session.
</P>
<P>
   In recent years, critics say, Schroder has become a proponent of
common-law courts _ those created by groups that deny the
legitimacy of the traditional court system. In June 1995, he helped
organize a National Common Law Grand Jury in Wichita that attracted
600 people.
</P>
<P>
   ``Yes, I was there,'' Schroder said. ``It was just an assembly
of people working on some of these matters that we felt needed to
be reviewed.''
</P>
<P>
   Schroder also has attended events in the Kansas City area. He
was a featured speaker at the Mid-America Constitution Conference
in 1995, 1996, 1997 and 1998. The conferences were attended by
hundreds of ``patriots'' who believe the government has overstepped
its constitutional bounds.
</P>
<P>
   Schroder and his followers are focusing their latest campaign on
a series of extraordinary measures passed by Congress decades ago
to deal with the Great Depression.
</P>
<P>
   One of the measures, the Agricultural Adjustment Act of 1933,
delegated authority to the executive branch to establish parity
between farm prices and the price of goods and services purchased
by farmers.
</P>
<P>
   According to Schroder's theory, the president still retains the
powers delegated under those emergency measures, and through an
executive order could restore agriculture commodity prices to a
fair and equitable level.
</P>
<P>
   As part of the effort, Schroder and others are circulating a
``Notice and Demand'' petition that they plan to serve President
Clinton, Secretary of Agriculture Dan Glickman and Treasury
Secretary Robert Rubin.
</P>
<P>
   If no action is taken, Schroder said, ``we're going to attempt
to organize the largest class-action lawsuit against this
government that maybe it has ever seen.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
