u a &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-HMO-LAWSUIT-HNS &LR;      03-25 0543
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-HMO-LAWSUIT-HNS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
RULING OPENS DOOR TO LAWSUITS AGAINST HMO DOCTORS 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients.)  
 By JOHN CAHER  
 c.1999 Albany Times Union  
<TEXT>
<P>
   ALBANY, N.Y. _ The family of a young father who died after he
was allegedly given the run-around by a health maintenance
organization and its affiliated physician can sue the doctor for
malpractice, New York's highest court ruled Thursday in a
ground-breaking decision.
</P>
<P>
   The Court of Appeals unanimously overturned a lower court and
held that the federal Employee Retirement Income Security Act
(ERISA) does not shield the HMO doctor from liability.
</P>
<P>
   That means the family of Glenn Nealy, a 37-year-old Bronx man
who died of a heart attack in 1992 and left behind a wife and two
small children, can take their case to court.
</P>
<P>
   Nealy's family contends that Dr. Ralph Yung failed to take
timely action to treat the patient. However, the family was blocked
by ERISA _ until Thursday _ from suing Yung.
</P>
<P>
   ERISA, which was enacted in 1974, is a federal statute that
governs the administration of all employee benefit plans, including
health plans. It effectively blocks state court lawsuits _ such as
medical malpractice lawsuits _ against HMOs. Thursday's ruling
punctures at least part of the ERISA shield.
</P>
<P>
   Chief Judge Judith S. Kaye, writing for the court, held that
since Yung's alleged conduct was not purely administrative, he is
not immunized by ERISA.
</P>
<P>
   ``I think it is opening the door a little bit for the next line
of cases,'' said Bhalinder L. Rikhye, the lawyer who represents the
doctor.
</P>
<P>
   Marc S. Oxman, the lawyer for the Nealy family, said that while
the court did not completely remove the ERISA shield, it indicated
it may be ``moving in that direction.''
</P>
<P>
   ``I would speculate they are sending a clear message to the
Legislature to get off their (rear ends) and pass a patient's bill
of rights,'' Oxman said.
</P>
<P>
   Records show Yung, a participating provider of US Healthcare,
examined Nealy, who had a history of heart disease, in April 1992.
</P>
<P>
   Yung, according to court records, recommended Nealy see a
specialist, but did not immediately handle the referral
requirements of the HMO. Consequently, the lawsuit alleges, Nealy's
treatment was delayed several days.
</P>
<P>
   Yung contends any delay in treatment was Nealy's own fault, and
alleges the patient was concerned with having to pay a deductible.
Nealy died of a heart attack on May 18, 1992, the day before he was
scheduled to see a specialist.
</P>
<P>
   Until Thursday, it appeared that the facts of the case would
never be decided by a jury. A mid-level appellate court, citing
ERISA, said the Nealy family was barred from suing Yung. The Court
of Appeals, however, disagreed.
</P>
<P>
   Kaye said the fact that Yung, as a primary care physician
associated with US Healthcare, was required to complete and submit
referral documents ``does not transform Dr. Yung into an ERISA plan
administrator.'' Consequently, he will have to answer the
allegations in court, Kaye said.
</P>
<P>
   The case attracted substantial attention from both the legal and
medical communities. Both the New York attorney general, Eliot
Spitzer, and the federal Department of Labor had urged the court to
overturn the lower ruling.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
