<SLUG> BC-SCAM-TEXAS-HNS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
TEXAS OFFICIALS NAB RINGLEADER OF ALLEGED SCAM 

</HEADLINE>
  
 (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  (Attn: Austin and El Paso, Texas) 
 
By POLLY ROSS HUGHES 
c.1999 Houston Chronicle 
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   AUSTIN, Texas _ A Houston man has been arrested in an alleged
insurance fraud scheme netting more than $10 million in settlements
for faked injuries and staged car wrecks.
</P>
<P>
   Alex Ferdman, 40, was in custody Thursday as the alleged
mastermind and ringleader of a scam that authorities say involved
cooperative lawyers and chiropractors in Houston, Austin and El
Paso.
</P>
<P>
   Arrest warrants also were issued for five others, although law
enforcement officials estimate that more than 30 people across
Texas participated.
</P>
<P>
   ``The integrity of the legal profession, the insurance process
and the medical profession are issues in which the public has an
abiding interest,'' said Travis County District Attorney Ronnie
Earl, whose public integrity unit led the yearlong investigation.
</P>
<P>
   ``What we have here is an effort to defraud insurance companies
that ends up victimizing not just the insurance company but ethical
honest lawyers, the medical profession and the rate paying
public,'' he added.
</P>
<P>
   Ferdman, who Houston officials said is charged with soliciting a
bribe, is accused of paying others to gather accident reports from
police in order to refer accident victims to lawyers involved in
the scam. The lawyers then sent the clients to chiropractors who
prescribed lengthy and often unnecessary treatments and then sought
settlements from insurance companies.
</P>
<P>
   In Houston on Wednesday, police armed with warrants conducted
searches of Ferdman's residence, and the business offices of
attorneys Mickey Altman, Donna McCarty and Lloyd Dunn. A search
also was conducted at the business office of Jack El Cubano Store,
a furniture and clothing outlet, which is suspected of laundering
millions of dollars from the scam.
</P>
<P>
   The five others named in the scheme include two employees of
Uptown Austin Rehabilitation Center: manager Victor Hugo Cuevas,
31, and clinic driver Juan Del Toro, 32. The others are Eric
Arriola and Raul Cucvas, of Austin, and Armando Casillas of El
Paso.
</P>
<P>
   Richard Pena, president of the Texas Bar Association, said
lawyers involved in the scheme could face disbarment.
</P>
<P>
   ``This situation, if proven to be true, is disgusting to Texas
lawyers because it adds to the deterioration of the public's trust
and confidence in the legal profession,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
XXXX END OF STORY &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
