<HEADER>
A4300 &Cx1f; tad-z
u w &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-TUTU26-COX     03-25 0501
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-TUTU26-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Telling the story of pain can be healing in Kosovo crisis, Tutu
says
 &HT;    By Rebecca Carr
 &HT;    c.1999 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON _ Archbishop Desmond Tutu came to Capitol Hill on
Thursday to deliver a five-volume report on the atrocities and
crimes committed in South Africa under white rule.
</P>
<P>
   But Tutu, now a visiting professor of theology at Emory
University, used the opportunity to discuss the crisis in Kosovo
and to tell an audience of more than 70 congressmen how to heal
wounds created by ethnic and racial divisions.
</P>
<P>
   Tutu said that Serbian nationalists seeking to ``cleanse''
Kosovo of its ethnic majority Albanian population should learn from
the struggle in South Africa, where a white minority ruled over a
black majority until 1994.
</P>
<P>
   ``God has not made a mistake in putting them together,'' said
Tutu, referring to Serbian nationalists and ethnic Albanians. ``God
hopes they will be able to learn they can live together. We are
going to have to learn to live together.''
</P>
<P>
   Tutu spoke at a forum sponsored by public policy group John
Quincy Adams Society and the Faith &AMP; Politics Institute, a
nondenominational organization co-chaired by Rep. John Lewis
(D-Ga.) and Rep. Amo Houghton (R-N.Y.). Over the last year, Faith &AMP;
Politics has worked on opening a dialogue about race relations in
America.
</P>
<P>
   Tutu urged Congress to encourage victims of racial prejudice in
America to tell their stories just as victims in South Africa told
their stories of persecution to the South African Truth and
Reconciliation Commission, which he headed.
</P>
<P>
   Tutu told the story of a young black woman in South Africa whose
father had been butchered by whites. Police kept the man's hand in
a jar as a warning to other blacks seeking equality under white
rule.
</P>
<P>
   After she told her story to the commission, Tutu asked her if
she could forgive the perpetrators who took her father from her.
</P>
<P>
   ``She said she would like to forgive, she just wanted to know
who to forgive,'' Tutu said. ``We can all learn so much by
forgiving.''
</P>
<P>
   A white woman told the commission about how a hand grenade set
off by a revolutionary group had badly maimed and disfigured her.
Tutu said the woman wanted to meet the person responsible for the
grenade attack so she could forgive him and so that he could
forgive her.
</P>
<P>
   ``There is pain sitting in the pit of tummies of
African-Americans and Native Americans, stories that have not been
told,'' Tutu said. ``You will never in this country have racial
peace until you give people a chance ... to tell their pain.''
</P>
<P>
   Lewis, a leader in the civil rights movement, said he found
Tutu's speech deeply moving. One of the ``most beautiful things''
during the civil rights movement was the way it brought people of
all races together for a united cause. Tutu's speech was a reminder
of what is possible when stories of persecution are aired, Lewis
said.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
