</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BRAZIL-BRADESCO-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
BRAZILIAN FINANCIAL INSTITUTIONS START BORROWING AGAIN  
</HEADLINE>
  (rk) 
 By SIMON ROMERO    
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   SAO PAULO, Brazil _ Testing an international aversion to
Brazilian debtors after the mid-January devaluation of the nation's
currency, a handful of Brazilian companies have resumed borrowing
in dollars on global debt markets.
</P>
<P>
   The trickle of new debt issues is being led by financial
institutions like Banco Bradesco SA, one of Brazil's largest, which
is selling $100 million to $200 million of notes that mature in one
year. The issue had been suspended since the currency, the real,
was devalued at the beginning of the year.
</P>
<P>
   The Brazilian unit of Citibank is selling $75 million to $100
million worth of six-month commercial paper. About half a dozen
other banks are considering similar issues in coming weeks.
</P>
<P>
   The renewed appetite for Brazilian debt reflects a less critical
view of this country's markets in recent days. Consumer price
increases have shown signs of slowing, and fears of a Russia-style
moratorium on domestic debt have subsided.
</P>
<P>
   The currency has strengthened here to 1.80 to the dollar, its
strongest since Feb. 4. Stocks have rallied, with the benchmark
Bovespa index surging 26 percent in the last month.
</P>
<P>
   ``We felt like we could wait no longer to pursue the sale,''
said Jose Guilherme Lembi de Faria, executive international
director at Bradesco. The bank, which plans to use the proceeds for
lending to agricultural clients, agreed to pay 11.5 percent to
11.75 percent interest on the notes _ roughly a percentage point
more than it would have before the devaluation.
</P>
<P>
   Lembi de Faria pointed out that is still much cheaper than
borrowing in domestic markets, where interest rates are hovering
above 40 percent.
</P>
<P>
   Yet, in a symbolic gesture that shows that officials recognize
the improved sentiment toward Brazil's markets, the central bank
shaved three percentage points off its overnight lending rate on
Wednesday, to 42 percent, the first such reduction in five months.
</P>
<P>
   ``I confess our maneuvering room is limited and we can't joke
around,'' said Arminio Fraga, the central bank president, on a
popular Brazilian talk show, ``Jo Soares Onze e Meia,'' and adding,
``But today, I am optimistic.''
</P>
<P>
   The reduction was seen by some investors as the beginning of a
downward trend in interest rates, which could allow a recession
economy to resume growth later this year.
</P>
<P>
   Companies that are eager to follow banks into foreign borrowing
markets are now awaiting further moves from Fraga and from the
Finance Ministry. So far, only one nonfinancial company, Vale do
Rio Doce, a large mining conglomerate, has succeeded in selling
dollar-denominated debt: a $50 million placement earlier this week.
</P>
<P>
   The situation is made more pressing with $2.2 billion of foreign
currency-denominated debt issued by Brazilian companies coming due
through the end of April, according to figures from Anbid, an
association of investment banks.
</P>
<P>
   If some of this debt is not refinanced in the form of new bonds
or notes, the currency could come under renewed pressure and its
movement upward could be reversed.
</P>
<P>
   As Brazil makes slow progress in gaining financial credibility,
other Latin American nations have taken advantage of improved
sentiment toward developing countries and have issued bonds with
relative ease.
</P>
<P>
   Mexico Thursday sold $1 billion of six-year bonds on
international markets, and on Wednesday Argentina sold about $270
million of nine-year bonds. Argentina, whose currency, the peso, is
kept in parity with the dollar, has shown greater resilience to the
wide changes in capital flows that have shaken Brazil. So far this
year, Argentina has raised roughly $2.8 billion in bond sales, more
than any other Latin American country.
</P>
</TEXT>
