<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-03-25 19:52 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A4308 &Cx1f; tad-z
u a &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-SEABASS-SHORTAGE26-CO     03-25 1171
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-SEABASS-SHORTAGE26-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    A fish in hot water
 &HT;    By John Kessler
 &HT;    c.1999 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   ATLANTA _ The most popular item on the menu at Fishbone _
Buckhead's vast, new seafood emporium _ is Patagonian toothfish.
</P>
<P>
   Over at the Atlanta Fish Market, chef Chris McDonald says his
customers can't get enough Patagonian toothfish. ``People like the
texture of it. We do it steamed, grilled, any way they want it. We
serve it Hong Kong style with sherry soy broth.''
</P>
<P>
   Of course, no one ever uses this name in America, even though it
is the only market name recognized by the Food and Drug
Administration. Here, unlike the rest of the world, we have a
user-friendly name: Chilean sea bass.
</P>
<P>
   The fish of the moment is sweet, buttery, snowy white and
difficult to overcook. With its high oil content, it feels
luxurious in the mouth. With its lack of pinbones and large flakes,
it feels safe.
</P>
<P>
   No wonder we are in love with this succulent, mysterious fish
that 20 years ago thrived undiscovered in deep Antarctic waters.
</P>
<P>
   And no surprise that it is quickly becoming so overfished that
observers predict the species, obtained from fisheries throughout
the Antarctic region, may become commercially extinct in as few as
three years.
</P>
<P>
   Just as surely as Paul Prudhomme's blackening pan decimated the
Gulf redfish population, this fish is a victim of its own
popularity. And we don't have a steady supply of Chilean sea bass
swimming around in breeding tanks like farm-raised catfish or
salmon.
</P>
<P>
   In January, ministers from 24 member nations of the Antarctic
Treaty met at Scott Base in Antarctica and pledged to combat the
rampant piracy and illegal overfishing of Chilean sea bass, called
``white gold'' in the industry.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's going the way of the pompano, the way of the swordfish,''
says Jean-Sebastien Gros, president of Chilean Seafood Exchange, a
Florida-based importer. ``This is a worldwide diminishing
resource.''
</P>
<P>
   Joel Knox, president of Atlanta's Inland Seafood Co., claims,
``I have seen the fish, in the eight years we've been selling it,
go down from 20 to 30 pounds on the average to 10 to 12 pounds,
which leads me to believe we are overfishing the resource.''
</P>
<P>
   In the past year, prices have climbed nearly 50 percent, while
the catch is down by half. But demand is at an all-time high. At
Inland Seafood, a 4,800-pound shipment disappears in a matter of
hours.
</P>
<P>
   Chilean sea bass first appeared in Los Angeles in 1982,
according to importer Doug Harbison. One of his suppliers brought a
frozen fillet of a specimen caught in deep waters off Chile. ``The
Chileans didn't even know it was there,'' claims Harbison, who
looked through every up-to-date South American fish encyclopedia at
the time and found no mention of it.
</P>
<P>
   By 1984, the small amount of fresh sea bass coming into Los
Angeles began showing up as a specialty item at high-end
restaurants. Michel Richard had it on the menu from day one at
Citrus, the soon-to-be sensation he opened there in 1986. ``It was
very new, but people loved it right away. They loved the texture.''
Richard, now making waves at Citronelle in Washington, says, ``We
still sell it like crazy.''
</P>
<P>
   Ironically, it was the overfishing of another deep-water
species, the North Pacific black cod, that pushed Chilean sea bass
onto the world stage. The Japanese, who had been major importers,
found that Chilean sea bass had the same high fat content as black
cod (about 16 percent, mostly those beneficial omega-3 unsaturated
fats) and could be used interchangeably.
</P>
<P>
   In 1991, when Chilean sea bass began emerging as a moderately
priced seafood alternative on restaurant menus throughout the
United States and was already a favorite in Japan, catch limits
were first set on the fishery near South Georgia island in the
South Atlantic.
</P>
<P>
   Fishers, looking elsewhere, discovered sea bass fisheries
throughout the far Southern Hemisphere. ``If you turn the globe
upside-down and draw a line around Antartica, that's where you find
Chilean sea bass,'' says Doug Harbison. South Africa, Australia,
New Zealand, France (with its islands in the South Indian Ocean)
and Argentina got into the toothfish business, and a world market
was established in Port Louis, Mauritius _ a sovereign
island-nation in the Indian Ocean.
</P>
<P>
   Port Louis emerged as a market not only for legitimate
longliners, but also for poachers. ``The problem,'' says
Jean-Sebastien Gros, ``is this stuff is as liquid as bonds.''
</P>
<P>
   David Bengis of Icebrand Seafood in Maine, who imports sea bass
from South African fisheries, concurs. ``It's impossible to track
the fish that has been pirated and where it goes.''
</P>
<P>
   During the 1996-1997 season, the harvest of Chilean sea bass
peaked and it had become a familiar staple in supermarket fish
counters and moderately-priced restaurants throughout America.
Prices slumped slightly. Nonetheless, the New Zealand Ministry of
Foreign Affairs estimates that more than $300 million of it was
illegally obtained. The Washington, D.C.-based Antartica Project
estimates the tonnage of illegal sea bass that season at 100,000,
or 10 times the legal catch.
</P>
<P>
   But executive director Beth Clark says that poaching is only
half the problem. ``Even the limits they're setting are beyond that
which is sustainable. They don't even start to reproduce until
they're 10 years old. It's like what happened to orange roughy 5
years ago. Now there are hardly any in the seas, and it's not
commercially viable.''
</P>
<P>
   During the 1997-1998 season, says Clark, established sea bass
fisheries began to ``crash.'' The illegal catch, according to her
estimates, decreased to 40,000 tons.
</P>
<P>
   Albatross are also threatened by Chilean sea bass fishing.
Attracted by the bait, these endangered birds are often hooked or
entangled and drowned. The Antartica Project estimates that over
200,000 birds, from more than 20 species of albatross and petrals,
have been killed by fishing boats.
</P>
<P>
   In 1998, with resources plummeting around its sub-Antartic
Prince Edward and Marion Islands, South Africa began patrolling its
fisheries with naval vessels and restricting licenses to boats with
South African registry.
</P>
<P>
   In January 1999, Greenpeace estimated the worldwide illegal
trade in Chilean sea bass to exceed $500 million, or more than 90
percent of the total trade.
</P>
<P>
   Last week, a chase between a Greenpeace vessel and a sea bass
poacher ended after 16 days and 2,700 nautical miles-chase across
the Southern Ocean to Mauritius, discovering 170 metric tons of
Chilean sea bass, worth more than $1 million.
</P>
<P>
   Prices are now at a 9-year high, but demand shows no sign of
abating. Says Jean-Sebastein Gros, ``Except for high-grade tuna and
black cod, there's not another fish that has a higher value in the
world market today.''
</P>
<P>
   ``But,'' says Gros, ``I see it becoming more and more of a
scarce resource enjoyed only by those who can afford top dollar.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
