A4310 &Cx1f; ttj-z
u a &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-TAX-RELIEF-HNS &LR;      03-25 0758
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-TAX-RELIEF-HNS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
LEGISLATORS LIKELY TO PASS SALES-TAX PROPOSAL, TEXAS LAWMAKER SAYS 

</HEADLINE>
  
 (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  By JOHN W. GONZALEZ 
c.1999 Houston Chronicle 
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   AUSTIN, Texas _ With Texas' economy thriving, lawmakers are
likely to approve temporary sales-tax exemptions for school
supplies and back-to-school clothing and permanent exemptions for
diapers and over-the-counter medicines, a ranking House member said
Thursday.
</P>
<P>
   Small businesses also will benefit from the state's rosy revenue
picture, though a proposal to end taxation of Internet services may
be doomed, said House Ways and Means Committee Chairman Rene
Oliveira, D-Brownsville. A tax credit for research and development
is also proving elusive, he said.
</P>
<P>
   His committee, which is awarding at least $500 million in tax
breaks, is mulling 259 proposals, many of which would lower tax
rates and authorize tax credits or exemptions. Lawmakers are
deciding which cuts to submit to the full House in mid-April, and
consensus is building to make sales-tax and small-business
franchise tax relief the top priorities, Oliveira said.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'm not going to be bound by $500 million We still have to
hear some testimony on some of these bills, but I think it will be
significantly more,'' he predicted.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's a tough balancing act because we want to pass tax cuts
that help the poor and middle class and working men and women. At
the same time, we want to try to have some economic development
incentives,'' Oliveira said.
</P>
<P>
   A Senate-approved bill that Oliveira is sponsoring, Senate Bill
5, would reward companies that conduct research and development and
allow job-creation tax credits for high unemployment areas. But
Oliveira said other tax breaks with wider appeal could take
precedence, especially since long-term tax breaks could prove
problematic if the economy deteriorates.
</P>
<P>
   ``The R&AMP;D tax credit is really a challenge,'' Oliveira said,
adding that experts don't agree on its effectiveness in luring
companies to Texas.
</P>
<P>
   The Internet sales-tax exemption is deemed too costly, he said.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's $20 million I think we could use elsewhere. I'm not going
to say it's dead, but I will say it doesn't have the priority with
me that the sales tax cuts do _ or the cuts for small business
do,'' the chairman said.
</P>
<P>
   Also taking a back seat to sales-tax breaks is the $2 billion
property-tax relief sought by Gov. George W. Bush, Oliveira
indicated, although some of the $3 billion proposed for new
school-related spending could be construed as relief for property
owners.
</P>
<P>
   ``The governor continues to aggressively seek property-tax
relief,'' Oliveira said, but ``our choice may be between funding
for education, accountability and teacher pay raises ... versus his
$2 billion in property tax relief.''
</P>
<P>
   Bush has acknowledged his objective is challenging. Oliveira
said ``to his credit, he's trying to find ways to do it.''
</P>
<P>
   Bush encouraged a GOP House member to submit a bill March 12
that would make an extra $400 million available to budget-writers
by shifting surpluses from the Texas Workers' Compensation Fund to
the state's general revenue fund. But that scenario was described
as unnecessary and unlikely by senior House members.
</P>
<P>
   ``My initial reaction is we have sufficient funds ... and if
that money has come from employers for purchasing workers' comp
insurance, we either need to reduce the rates or rebate that money
back to the employers,'' said Appropriations Committee Chairman Rob
Junell, D-San Angelo.
</P>
<P>
   Junell said the House's 2000-01 spending plan, which tops $94
billion, is nearly complete. He said it's more like a nice pickup
truck than a Mercedes-Benz.
</P>
<P>
   ``It goes beyond meeting the basic needs of Texans,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   His committee will make final adjustments next week before
sending the hefty document to the House floor for a mid-April vote.
</P>
<P>
   The Senate is expected to approve a more conservative budget,
forcing creation of a House-Senate negotiating committee that could
get a higher, new revenue estimate from Comptroller Carole Keeton
Rylander about May 1. With state government required by the Texas
Constitution to pay as you go, some of the low-priority tax-relief
proposals could get new life in May if Rylander finds more money.
</P>
<P>
   ``If we have to make adjustments in the conference committee
process, we'll do that, or we'll wait for the golden goose to lay
the golden egg and see what comes out of the Comptroller's
Office,'' Oliveira said.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
XXXX END OF STORY &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
