<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-KOSOVO-PRISTINA-575(2TAKES)-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
IN KOSOVO'S CAPITAL, VIOLENCE FINDS THE ETHNIC ALBANIANS
</HEADLINE>
   (See also: KOSOVO-RDP, KOSOVO-MILITARY, KOSOVO-MILITARY-ASSESS,
KOSOVO-GERMANY, KOSOVO-POLICY, KOSOVO-BELGRADE, KOSOVO-PRISTINA,
KOSOVO-MACEDONIA, KOSOVO-REPORTERS, KOSOVO-CHINA,
KOSOVO-RUSSIA-ASSESS, KOSOVO-CLINTON, KOSOVO-ITALY, KOSOVO-VOICES,
KOSOVO-B2, KOSOVO-EUROPE-REAX, KOSOVO-U.N.) 
(wg) 
 By CARLOTTA GALL   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   PRISTINA, Yugoslavia _ After a night of heavy explosions and
fires, this city was strangely calm early Thursday. Serbs seemed at
ease, if angry at the NATO bombing; Albanians were anxious, even
terrified of what was to come.
</P>
<P>
   Black smoke rose from buildings burning on the southwestern edge
of the city, one of the main casualties of the night. Another plume
of smoke rose from the ridge on the eastern edge of Pristina, the
Kosovo capital.
</P>
<P>
   Though Serbs said that much of the damage and fires around the
city had been caused by NATO missiles, it was the ethnic Albanians
who bore the brunt of the violence Wednesday, as Serbian forces
apparently used the NATO attacks as a pretext to go out overnight
and wreak still more havoc.
</P>
<P>
   By about 2:30 Thursday afternoon the order came that foreign
journalists belonging to all NATO countries should leave Serbia,
and about 20 men, recognized by journalists as the kind of
hard-core paramilitary Serb forces who became notorious in Bosnia
for the atrocities of ``ethnic cleansing,'' began to harass
journalists and force them leave, smashing equipment and setting
fire to an armored vehicle used by CNN.
</P>
<P>
   As the journalists departed, and with the NATO bombing already
begun, a deepening sense of fear took hold in Pristina that the
Serbs would now vent their their rage against ethnic Albanian
civilians in retaliation, a threat the Serbs themselves had issued
often in the past.
</P>
<P>
   If the first night of the bombing was any measure, they may be
good their word.
</P>
<P>
   Thursday, in one of two barracks within the city untouched by
the NATO strikes, near the Serb settlement of Kosovo Polje,
soldiers lounged in the sun on the top of a tank, looking out over
the fence on to the main road.
</P>
<P>
   Barely 50 yards from them, on the other side of an intersection,
the door had been forced open to the small plant of the ethnic
Albanian newspaper, Kosova Sot, which was closed down by the
Serbian authorities eight days ago after a court decision found the
paper guilty of ``running an editorial policy that was against the
Serbian regime.''
</P>
<P>
   The roof of the building was partially smashed and burned, the
debris lying among the big printing presses. Outside in the
courtyard stacks of newspapers on pallets were still burning. Bent
and broken metal printing plates lay on the ground.
</P>
<P>
   Nearby a long, low building that had housed private businesses _
a car repair shop and a plastics production laboratory _ smoldered.
Its whitewashed brick walls and a blue sign that read ``Autoservis
Dinor'' were still standing, but its roof had collapsed.
</P>
<P>
   NATO missiles, aiming at the barracks, had missed and instead
hit the car repair shop, said Radovan Urosevac, a Serb, though the
targets of the NATO bombing lay beyond Pristina, at the airport to
the south and barracks outside the city.
</P>
<P>
   ``They were targeting the airport, and they missed it,'' said
Urosevac, a director of the Serbian Media Center in Pristina, which
is closely connected to the Serbian authorities.
</P>
<P>
   ``They targeted the army base in Kosovo Polje and the hit the
Peugot car repair place,'' he added. ``I believe they were aiming
at a power plant and hit a surface coal pit, 15 kilometers from
Pristina.''
</P>
<P>
   While it was hard to tell what had caused the fire, it had begun
about midnight, not with an explosion but from a small pinpoint
glow, that could be seen growing rapidly into a major
conflagration. At the site, there was no crater from a missile
visible and no pieces of missile casing.
</P>
<ANNOTATION>
   (STORY CAN END HERE. OPTIONAL MATERIAL FOLLOWS)
</ANNOTATION>
<P>
   nn
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
