<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-MICROSOFT-ANTITRUST-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
THOUGH WARY, GOVERNMENT OFFICIALS TO DISCUSS MICROSOFT SETTLEMENT
PROPOSAL 
</HEADLINE>
   (bl)  
 By JOEL BRINKLEY   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON _ State and federal officials were dismissive
Thursday of Microsoft's proposal to settle its antitrust suit, but
they added that the two sides would meet for settlement talks,
probably beginning Tuesday.
</P>
<P>
   U.S. District Court Judge Thomas Penfield Jackson admonished the
litigants to try to settle the case during the trial recess that
began Feb. 26. As a result, officials said, even though the Justice
Department and the state attorneys general who filed the suit
question whether the settlement proposal they received Wednesday is
serious, they feel compelled to show a good-faith effort.
</P>
<P>
   Still, as one senior government official put it, ``the chances
are pretty good that all we're doing is a kabuki dance for the
judge.''
</P>
<P>
   The last time the two sides tried to settle the case, days
before the suit was filed last May, the talks broke down after a
day and a half. Justice Department officials called those talks off
after concluding, they said, that Microsoft's negotiators had not
been straight with them.
</P>
<P>
   Now, in a three-and-one-quarter page, double-spaced document,
Microsoft is offering to show flexibility in two broad areas raised
in the lawsuit: the company's restrictive contracts with Internet
companies, and the limits computer makers face in their ability to
customize the opening screen of the Windows operating system. Under
pressure from the government, Microsoft has informally loosened its
practices in these areas, and its settlement proposal offers to
make those changes formal.
</P>
<P>
   ``But there's not a lot more than that,'' said a senior official
involved with the government's case. ``It doesn't offer a lot of
specifics in the areas we think are important.''
</P>
<P>
   The 19 state attorneys general who are partners in the suit with
the federal government discussed Microsoft's proposal Thursday at a
previously scheduled meeting in Washington.
</P>
<P>
   As she left the meeting, New Mexico Attorney General Patricia
Madrid said the talks would begin Tuesday. Neither Justice
Department nor Microsoft officials would confirm that or otherwise
comment on the settlement proposal in any substantive way.
</P>
<P>
   Connecticut Attorney General Richard Blumenthal said: ``Our
policy at this point is to keep discussions totally confidential.
That's the only way serious settlement negotiations can take
place.''
</P>
<P>
   Microsoft's chairman Bill Gates, speaking at Georgetown
University on Thursday morning as part of a publicity tour for his
new book, made not even an oblique mention of the antitrust case,
and none of the students who asked him questions at the end of his
presentation brought it up.
</P>
<P>
   But Mark Murray, a Microsoft spokesman, said: ``We have made a
serious and substantive proposal that addresses the areas of
concern identified by the government.''
</P>
<P>
   State and federal officials say they believe no settlement will
be effective unless it restructures the company in some way. The
state Attorneys General favor forcing Microsoft to license the
source code for Windows to other companies _ instantly creating
competition in the operating system market.
</P>
<P>
   The Justice Department has not decided which sort of remedy it
favors. Options include the forced licensing idea and breaking up
the company, among other ideas. But one government official said
the Microsoft proposal ``doesn't discuss source code or anything
structural.''
</P>
<P>
   As they consider Microsoft's proposal, officials from the
federal government and the states say that ``conduct remedies'' of
the sort Microsoft is proposing have not worked in the past. With a
conduct remedy, Microsoft would remain intact, but the company's
ability to engage in specific illegal conduct would be limited
through contract restrictions or other means.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
