<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-ISRAEL-GENERAL-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
SEX WITH SUBORDINATE COSTS ISRAEL ARMY GENERAL A PROMOTION 
</HEADLINE>
   (bl)  
 By JOEL GREENBERG   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   JERUSALEM _ The Israeli Supreme Court ruled Thursday that an
army general disciplined for having sex with a female subordinate
three years ago could not be promoted.
</P>
<P>
   The decision barred the officer, Brig. Gen. Nir Galili, 43, from
becoming a major general and corps commander in the Israeli ground
forces, overruling the defense minister and army chief of staff,
who had approved the promotion.
</P>
<P>
   No replacement was immediately named, although Israel Radio
reported that one possible candidate was Brig. Gen. Effi Fein, who
has risen through the ranks despite his involvement in a beating
incident during the Palestinian uprising.
</P>
<P>
   The case of Galili was the first in which the court intervened
to block a promotion in the army, and it exposed ambivalent
attitudes in the military toward the problem of sexual harassment
in its ranks.
</P>
<P>
   While the army follows an active policy of punishing sexual
harassment, the promotion of Galili suggested a more lenient
approach at the army's highest levels.
</P>
<P>
   The general's appointment had been challenged by a 23-year-old
former soldier whose name has not been made public. She petitioned
the Supreme Court against the promotion on the ground that the
general, who is married and has three children, had improperly used
his authority to have sex with her when she was in the service
three years ago.
</P>
<P>
   Following a disciplinary hearing after the incident, Galili was
reprimanded and his promotion was delayed for three years. The
army's advocate-general said at the time that the general had
improperly exploited his ``status, position and rank'' to engage in
conduct unbecoming an officer.
</P>
<P>
   After the three years elapsed, Galili's promotion was approved.
The army chief of staff, Lt. Gen. Shaul Mofaz, told the Supreme
Court in an affidavit that although he condemned the general's
behavior and upheld a strict code of conduct in the army, he
considered Galili to be the best candidate for the job.
</P>
<P>
   ``I have the supreme duty of doing everything in my power to
insure the army's victory, should a war be imposed,'' he said.
``Therefore the finest commanders must be on the battle front.''
The promotion was supported by Defense Minister Moshe Arens.
</P>
<P>
   Galili made no public comment after Thursday's ruling. An army
spokesman issued a terse response: ``The army will honor the
decision of the Supreme Court.''
</P>
<P>
   Women's advocacy groups and several politicians from the left
and the right applauded the decision.
</P>
<P>
   ``A professionally outstanding soldier who has a low moral level
is not an outstanding soldier,'' said Haia Jamshy, director of the
Israel Women's Network. ``There's something of a conspiracy of
silence about these matters in the army, so I hope this ruling will
have a deterrent effect.''
</P>
<P>
   Transport Minister Shaul Yahalom, a member of the National
Religious Party, said it was ``unfortunate that such ethical
decisions, which are so important for the morals of the army, are
imposed by the court rather than by the internal policies of the
chief of staff and defense minister.''
</P>
<P>
   Ran Cohen, a lawmaker from the leftist Meretz party, said the
court had issued a ``courageous and moral'' ruling that had ``saved
the defense minister, the chief of staff and the army from the
disgrace of their own decision.''
</P>
<P>
   The woman who had challenged the general in court told a radio
reporter: ``I'm just happy it's over. Now I can move on.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
