<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-KEVORKIAN-TRIAL-580&AMP;ADD-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
JURY BEGINS DELIBERATIONS ON MURDER CHARGES AGAINST KEVORKIAN 
</HEADLINE>
  (rk) 
 By PAM BELLUCK   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   PONTIAC, Mich. _ It has been a strikingly short murder trial,
one in which the defense called no witnesses and presented no
evidence.
</P>
<P>
   After only half a day of testimony by prosecution witnesses and
a couple of hours of closing arguments, the jury began deliberating
Thursday on charges of murder against Jack Kevorkian, who is
accused of killing Thomas Youk, a 52-year-old man who was suffering
from Lou Gehrig's disease. After five hours of deliberation the
jury adjourned until Friday morning.
</P>
<P>
   Kevorkian, a 70-year-old pathologist who insisted on being his
own lawyer, fumbled most of his legal gambits. Judge Jessica
Cooper, of the Oakland County Circuit Court, repeatedly disallowed
his questions and arguments.
</P>
<P>
   And Thursday, she denied his request to call his only witnesses,
Youk's wife and brother, saying their testimony was not legally
relevant because it would shed light only on their feelings, not
Kevorkian's actions or intent.
</P>
<P>
   But in a theatrical closing argument, Kevorkian tried to
compensate for his legal difficulties by appealing to the jury's
emotions, launching a defense of euthanasia, and trying to convince
the jury that the law prohibiting euthanasia is wrong.
</P>
<P>
   ``He calls it a murder, a crime, a killing,'' said Kevorkian,
gesturing to the prosecutor, John Skrzynski. ``I call it medical
science. Tom Youk didn't come to me saying `I want to die, kill
me.' He said `Please help me.' There was medical affliction.
Medical service is exempt from certain laws.''
</P>
<P>
   Kevorkian's actions in the death of Youk, of Waterford Township,
Mich., are captured on a videotape that shows him injecting Youk
with lethal chemicals. The doctor was charged with first-degree
murder after the tape became public in November, when he brought it
to the CBS news program ``60 Minutes.''
</P>
<P>
   Cooper told the jury of seven women and five men that they
should consider whether Kevorkian's actions met the standards of
first degree murder, which requires premeditation, second degree
murder, which does not, or involuntary manslaughter.
</P>
<P>
   Kevorkian, whose medical license was revoked in Michigan, is
also charged with distributing a controlled substance.
</P>
<P>
   The judge told the jury that euthanasia was not at issue and the
notion that Youk consented to his death was not a legally
acceptable defense. Their job, she said, was to follow the criminal
statutes, not to try to change the law. But in his closing,
Kevorkian, who claims to have helped more than 130 people commit
suicide, still raised those points.
</P>
<P>
   Vehemently chopping one hand into the palm of the other,
Kevorkian said the method he used to end Youk's life was designed
``to end his torture finally and definitively.''
</P>
<P>
   ``You don't want to put him to sleep and have him reawake in the
same condition he was before,'' he said. ``That wasn't the aim. The
aim was a final solution to incurable agony.''
</P>
<P>
   Youk, he said, ``didn't want to die. Nobody does. But sometimes
we're forced into situations where you've got to die, somehow.''
</P>
<P>
   Skrzynski, the prosecutor, painted a different picture, saying
that Kevorkian ``came like a medical hit man in the night with his
bag of poison.''
</P>
<P>
   The trial, he said, is ``not about assisted suicide. It's not
about the right to die. It's about Jack Kevorkian's right to
kill.''
</P>
<P>
   He added, ``Jack Kevorkian murdered Thomas Youk. He killed
Thomas Youk and he does not have the right to kill.''
</P>
<ANNOTATION>
   (STORY CAN END HERE. OPTIONAL MATERIAL FOLLOWS)
</ANNOTATION>
<P>
   Kevorkian likened his cause to cases in which unfair laws were
ultimately changed, for example when women could not vote, or
drinking was illegal. He also invoked the civil rights struggle of
Rosa Parks and the Martin Luther King Jr.
</P>
<P>
   ``There are certain things that words on paper can never make a
crime,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   ``Just look at me,'' he said. ``Honestly now, honestly. Do you
see a criminal? Do you see a murderer? Do you see what's called a
killer? If you do than you must convict. And then take the harsh
judgment of history or the harsher judgment of your children and
grandchildren if they ever come to need that precious choice.''
</P>
<P>
   Skrzynski used historical images of his own, alluding to the
Nazi claims that the killing of Jews and other minorities was a
form of euthanasia.
</P>
<P>
   The prosecutor showed a moment in the videotape in which Youk
moaned just before he was injected, and he questioned whether Youk
had asked Kevorkian to stop at the last minute.
</P>
<P>
   ``There's nobody watching him doing this,'' Skrzynski said, ``He
chooses whose suffering is worth it. ... He's not accountable to
anyone. And when he asks you to give him that power, because he is
surely asking you to forget the law and give him that power, it
will be an unaccountable power.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
