<SLUG> BC-KOSOVO-AIM-HNS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
EXPERTS AGREE: IT'S HARD TO FIGURE OUT WHAT MILOSEVIC WILL DO 

</HEADLINE>
  
 (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  (Also see: KOSOVO-NATO and KOSOVO-DAMAGE) 
 
By BENNETT ROTH 
c.1999 Houston Chronicle 
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON _ When Yugoslav leader Slobodan Milosevic faced NATO
military pounding in Bosnia in 1995, it took slightly more than two
weeks of bombing before he had enough and a truce was reached that
laid the groundwork for the Dayton, Ohio, peace accord.
</P>
<P>
   The question this time for the United States and its military
allies is whether the stubborn but ultimately pragmatic dictator
will follow the same pattern in Kosovo as he did during the
previous Balkan conflict.
</P>
<P>
   It is not clear whether the U.S. goal includes trying to force
Milosevic to accept the peace accord reached earlier this year with
the Kosovars.
</P>
<P>
   In justifying the airstrikes to the American people, President
Clinton has cited the need to weaken Milosevic's military
capability and prevent him from continuing ethnic massacres, not
forcing him to accept the peace agreement that includes stationing
NATO ground troops in the troubled province of Kosovo.
</P>
<P>
   But Secretary of State Madeleine Albright said Thursday that the
agreement reached at Rambouillet, France, is still on the table
``and remains the best hope for a peaceful future in Kosovo.''
</P>
<P>
   Experts are not in agreement over whether history will repeat
itself and Milosevic will back down.
</P>
<P>
   Some who believe Milosevic will capitulate say he is behaving
perfectly in character right now, playing to nationalist
sentiments, but only as long as it does not risk his power base.
</P>
<P>
   ``Milosevic is a master of brinkmanship, ''said David Phillips,
director of the internal conflict resolution program at Columbia
University's School of International and Public Affairs.
</P>
<P>
   Phillips said the dictator is conforming to a ``pattern whereby
he confronts the international community seeking maximum
concessions and backs down at the last moment. He is smart and
stubborn and will hold out as long as it is politically expedient
to do so.''
</P>
<P>
   One expert said that Milosevic has a history of exaggerating his
public support and ability to take on his opponents.
</P>
<P>
   ``There is a tendency on his part to overstate his power and his
influence,'' said Donald Abenheim, a visiting fellow at Stanford
University's Hoover Institution.
</P>
<P>
   Abenheim said that while Milosevic ``is certainly willing to use
terror and war, he is able to pull back when necessary.'' He added
``one would hope that what happened in 1995 is predictive of the
future.''
</P>
<P>
   After the 17-day offensive in September of 1995 Milosevic and
Bosnian Serb leaders worked out an agreement, signed that November
in Dayton, which led to NATO peace forces being placed in Bosnia.
</P>
<P>
   Some scholars of the region say that it is misleading to look to
Bosnia for a sense of how Milosevic will act today.
</P>
<P>
   They argue that the situation in Bosnia was quite different,
with Milosevic having far less a personal and political stake in
that bordering country than in Kosovo, a part of Yugoslavia that
has deep cultural and historical significance for the Serbs.
</P>
<P>
   ``The 1995 bombing is no guidepost to predict his behavior,''
said Ivo H. Daalder, a visiting fellow at the Brookings
Institution. Daalder said that in Bosnia, Milosevic was more
amenable to a peace settlement but was initially thwarted by more
radical Bosnian Serb leaders.
</P>
<P>
   Furthermore, he said, Milosevic had an incentive to reach a
settlement in 1995 so that economic sanctions that were weakening
public support at home would be lifted.
</P>
<P>
   This time, Daalder and others argued, the NATO bombing may have
galvanized public support for Milosevic, who is viewed as standing
up to what many Serbs view as an assault on their country and an
attempt to meddle in a local dispute.
</P>
<P>
   Kosovo has long held an emotional tug on the Serbs as the site
where their forefathers lost a bloody battle with the Ottoman
empire armies in 1389.
</P>
<P>
   ``Even more than in Bosnia, Yugoslavs feel themselves in the
right insofar as they are trying to put down a rebellion in their
own country,'' said Charles King, a professor at Georgetown
University, who added that he believed that Milosevic was in this
latest fight ``for the long term.''
</P>
<P>
   Daalder believes that Milosevic can hold out much longer this
time and will only be forced to deal with NATO if he faces
significant erosion in public support or serious challenges from
his own military.
</P>
<P>
   ``Now bombing is increasing rather than decreasing the support
for him. But the moment that changes, this guy will do whatever he
needs to do to remain in power,'' Daalder said.
</P>
<P>
   Milosevic, who rose to power in Yugoslav's Communist regime in
the 1980s, has long played to nationalist tendencies in his bid to
consolidate power. Observers say, however, he has increasingly
isolated himself, relying heavily on the advice of his wife, who
wields considerable clout in the government.
</P>
<P>
   He also has suppressed the independent press and fired
dissenters in his government. And his critics have accused him of
tacitly supporting the ethnic massacres in Bosnia, Croatia and
Kosovo.
</P>
<P>
   ``He ain't a nice guy,'' said Hoover's Abenheim.
</P>
<P>
   Phillips was harsher in his assessment, noting that both of
Milosevic's parents had committed suicide.
</P>
<P>
   ``There is a long history of dementia,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
XXXX END OF STORY &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
