A4329 &Cx1f; taf-z
u f &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-PROCTER-AD-COLUMN-NYT     03-25 1216
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-PROCTER-AD-COLUMN-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
ADVERTISING: INNOVATIVE CAMPAIGNS BY PROCTER &AMP; GAMBLE? WONDERS
NEVER CEASE. 
</HEADLINE>
   (bl)  
 By STUART ELLIOTT   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   One of the hoariest of advertising devices, the
man-on-the-street interview, is being overhauled for a new
generation of consumers by one of the most traditional of
advertisers, Procter &AMP; Gamble Co.
</P>
<P>
   In a series of campaigns, P&AMP;G, the household products giant, has
been reinventing the tried-and-true tactic of sending out a
pitchman and a camera crew to capture actual consumers reacting
spontaneously to product demonstrations. The ads _ for detergents,
shampoos and antiperspirants _ update the device in a fresh and
frisky way, adding a contemporary appearance and a tone infused
with tongue-in-cheek humor.
</P>
<P>
   Until now, about the only tongue to be found in cheek in Procter
campaigns would have been as part of an oral-hygiene display to
prove the efficacy of a new mouthwash or toothpaste. That's because
the company has long prided itself on selling not the sizzle but
the steak, in the form of straightforward ads that asserted claims
of superior performance (``whiter whites'') by playing up product
benefits like technological improvements and so-called secret
ingredients (chlorinol and GL-70, to name but two).
</P>
<P>
   But decades of bombardment by such prosaic campaigns have
produced consumers remarkably resistant to the rational hard sell.
So even a staid, conventional marketer like P&AMP;G realizes that
creativity, in the form of emotion or entertainment, has become a
not-so-secret weapon against consumer boredom.
</P>
<P>
   ``We're looking for something distinctive,'' said Rob Matteucci,
vice president and general manager for North American hair care
brands at Procter in Cincinnati. ``This is very distinctive from
other campaigns and for P&AMP;G advertising in general.
</P>
<P>
   ``Consumer reaction was so like `Wow, this is really cool,''' he
added. ``I've been in this business for 21 years and you don't get
that kind of positive, spontaneous reaction.''
</P>
<P>
   One of his brands, Pert Plus shampoo, is indicative of the
trend. A television, print and Internet campaign features a
character named Sink Boy who pursues women in Miami Beach, New
Orleans and Las Vegas, offering to demonstrate the product by
washing their hair in a sink he shleps through the streets on a
hand cart.
</P>
<P>
   A key component of the spiel by Sink Boy, a glib actor named
Michael Collins, is his eliciting admissions from the women he
interviews of how much they dislike products like Pert Plus _
``2-in-1'' combinations of shampoo and conditioner _ for the
residues they leave that make hair limp and heavy-feeling. He then
describes how Pert Plus has been reformulated _ ``It's like
revolutionarily redesigned,'' in Collins' breezy argot _ and urges
them to give the brand another chance.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's not often you see an advertiser, much less P&AMP;G,
acknowledging how terrible the product was,'' said Bob Garfield, ad
reviewer for the trade publication Advertising Age. ``I think the
campaign is spectacular.''
</P>
<P>
   Matteucci said he agreed that the approach was ``highly
unusual,'' adding: ``People hear `New and improved' all the time.
But in this case, because we were brutally honest and up-front,
people tried the product.''
</P>
<P>
   The Pert Plus campaign was developed with funds allocated by
Procter for marketing approaches deemed to be offbeat.
</P>
<P>
   ``P&AMP;G has become a more experimental organization, trying new
stuff,'' said Kent Middleton, senior vice president and creative
director at Leo Burnett Co. in Chicago, the Pert Plus agency.
</P>
<P>
   ``We thought the personality of the brand could be enhanced and
the advertising could break through with a dash of irreverence, the
sheer joy of a guy trying to wash people's hair on the street,'' he
added. ``It's a fun thing to do, and it's more fun to see consumers
are responding to it.''
</P>
<P>
   The new and improved version of man-on-the-street began in 1993
with a campaign for Daz, a detergent sold by Procter in Britain, in
which a cheeky interviewer surprises customers by visiting them at
home and wooing them to take part in a judging of laundry
cleanliness called the Daz Doorstep Challenge.
</P>
<P>
   ``There's a saying here in England, `There's naught stranger
than folk,''' said Annabelle Manwaring, European creative director
for P&AMP;G at Leo Burnett London.
</P>
<P>
   ``The purpose is not to be the whiteness police, as it were,''
she added, ``but for us to show how confident Daz users are, the
confidence to show your whites to the nation.''
</P>
<P>
   The success of the campaign _ which has included commercials
showing the interviewer chased by a ferocious dog and rejected by
consumers who don't use Daz _ led P&AMP;G to export the device to sell
detergent brands in Europe and Latin America. Then the idea turned
up in the United States, in campaigns for Gain detergent.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's a reinvention of the genre, which gives it new life,''
said Gerry Miller, an executive vice president and managing
creative director at Burnett in Chicago, which is sending an
interviewer in a helicopter to drop bottles of Gain onto the
audience at a muddy rock concert.
</P>
<P>
   ``Fun is our difference,'' Miller said. ``We zig when they
zag.''
</P>
<P>
   Now the man-on-the-street has crossed the street, so to speak,
expanding into categories beyond detergents. For Sure Clear Dry
antiperspirant, an interviewer named Jon Melichar sweet-talks
passers-by into touching and applying the product as they are
filmed.
</P>
<P>
   ``Antiperspirant is a low-interest category that people don't
think about much,'' said Dave Cohen, senior vice president and
group creative director at Grey Advertising in New York, the Sure
agency. ``And Sure is an old brand and tired in a way.''
</P>
<P>
   ``When you made it seem real, seem fun,'' he added, ``it was
more relevant to them.''
</P>
<P>
   ``We're still selling a promise,'' Cohen said. ``When someone
says, `Wow, this even feels dry on my finger' _ bam! You've got
it.''
</P>
<P>
   ``It's a sign Procter is really opening up,'' he added,
``realizing you don't have to do everything the traditional way.''
</P>
<P>
   In one way the campaigns are still traditional: the interviewer
wielding the microphone is always a man, though almost always the
consumers being interviewed are women.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's still hard in our culture to find a woman who can strike
the right balance,'' said Barbara Lippert, ad critic for the trade
publication Adweek, ``a woman with an edge who can also be sincere
about shine and bounce.''
</P>
<P>
   Matteucci at Procter said that what matters more than sex is
``the personalities'' of the interviewers, adding that ``the real
heroines are the women'' being interviewed in the commercials.
</P>
<P>
   As for whether P&AMP;G has too many men out on the street for too
many products, he said: ``So far we are quite comfortable we are
not overusing this in any way. If a technique gets overused, the
consumer would say, `What's different about this?' We don't see
anywhere near that with man-on-the-street.''
</P>
<P>
   Garfield of Advertising Age was a tad skeptical.
</P>
<P>
   ``Giuliani got rid of the squeegee guys,'' he said, referring to
New York City Mayor Rudolph Giuliani's efforts to remove
panhandling car-window washers from the city's streets. ``Let's see
what he would do about the deodorant peddlers.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
