u i &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-KOSOVO-VOICES-LA-NYT &LR;      03-25 0586
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-KOSOVO-VOICES-LA-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
IN LOS ANGELES, DOUBTS, AMBIVALENCE AND PROTESTS 
</HEADLINE>
  (See also: KOSOVO-RDP, KOSOVO-MILITARY, KOSOVO-MILITARY-ASSESS,
KOSOVO-GERMANY, KOSOVO-POLICY, KOSOVO-BELGRADE, KOSOVO-PRISTINA,
KOSOVO-MACEDONIA, KOSOVO-REPORTERS, KOSOVO-CHINA,
KOSOVO-RUSSIA-ASSESS, KOSOVO-CLINTON, KOSOVO-ITALY, KOSOVO-B2,
KOSOVO-EUROPE-REAX, KOSOVO-U.N., KOSOVO-CLARK-PROFILE.) 
(ART ADV: Photos are being sent of people quoted in Calif. and NY
stories. Non-subscribers can make individual purchase by calling
888-603-1036 or 888-346-9867.) 
(DW) 
 By TODD S. PURDUM   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   LOS ANGELES _ The NATO attacks prompted a range of wary, often
ambivalent reaction here Thursday, with few voices offering
unqualified support for the allies and many Californians expressing
deep doubt about both tactics and goals.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's such a complicated region,'' said Daniel Palladino, 39, a
television writer who was plowing through a stack of newspapers
this morning at the Farmer's Market, in the heart of Los Angeles.
``God knows, even the names of the countries keep changing. I know
more about it than a lot of people, I think, and I still have
ambivalent feelings.''
</P>
<P>
   ``We're told atrocities are happening, and I'm sure that they
are,'' he added. ``But what is the goal? It just isn't that clear
right now.''
</P>
<P>
   Ka'imi Lee, 40, a flight attendant for Hawaiian Airlines who
traveled last summer through Croatia and Slovenia, two former
Yugoslav republics, also professed mixed feelings as he pored over
newspaper accounts at a nearby table.
</P>
<P>
   ``Just the whole issue of going into another country and using
the moral high ground,'' he said. ``It's a conflict between two
sides there. In recent years, with all the attention to the
Holocaust, these issues are more compelling, because you don't want
history to repeat itself. But it's always a tough issue. At what
point is it worth giving lives to save lives?''
</P>
<P>
   The Rev. Petar Jovanovic of St. Sava Serbian Orthodox Church in
San Gabriel, Calif., who has been in this country since 1977 and is
an American citizen, expressed no ambivalence whatever.
</P>
<P>
   ``You will find not one person of Serbian background who will
say that this bombing is necessary,'' he said in a telephone
interview. ``You cannot make a peace agreement with an ultimatum
from one side. The Serbian people will never agree with an
independent Kosovo.''
</P>
<P>
   He added: ``If the Americans go in, it will be a big problem.
The Serbians will not be pacified easily like in Bosnia. This
degrades America in the eyes of oppressed people around the
world.''
</P>
<P>
   Beulah Boyd, a retired nurse shopping at the Farmer's Market,
said: ``I think it's a bad idea. Many innocent people are involved
and it sort of seems like Vietnam. We don't need to be going into
their war.''
</P>
<P>
   Sidney Verba, 70, a retired state worker who immigrated from
Czechoslovakia after World War II, expressed similar doubts.
</P>
<P>
   ``I think it's kind of stupid,'' he said. ``I'm positive it
won't accomplish much. I wouldn't even dare to guess how it will
come out.''
</P>
<P>
   On Wednesday afternoon, as the raids began, some 200 protestors
gathered outside the federal building in Westwood, carrying signs
like ``Where Does it Stop? World War 3'' and ``World, Shame on
You.''
</P>
<P>
   One of the protestors, the Vietnam veteran Ron Kovic, whose
story became the movie ``Born on the Fourth of July,'' called the
NATO attacks a ``terribly insensitive policy,'' and added, ``We
must set a better example.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
