<SLUG> BC-KOSOVO-VOICES-MIAMI-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
IN MIAMI, `WHAT'S KOSOVO?' 
</HEADLINE>
  (See also: KOSOVO-VOICES-LA, KOSOVO-VOICES-N.Y.,
KOSOVO-VOICES-N.H., KOSOVO-VOICES-TEXAS) 
(ART ADV: Photos are being sent of people quoted in Calif. and NY
stories. Non-subscribers can make individual purchase by calling
888-603-1036 or 888-346-9867.) 
(DW) 
 By RICK BRAGG   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   MIAMI _ As bombs fell on Yugoslavia, indifference, mostly,
drifted in South Florida.
</P>
<P>
   In downtown Miami, businessmen chatting in Spanish just shook
their heads when asked if they had any special feelings about the
bombing by NATO forces.
</P>
<P>
   In neighboring Coral Gables, shoppers on Miracle Mile, a
historic shopping street that resembles a small-town Main Street,
barely paused long enough to mutter, ``No se,'' or ``Dunno.''
</P>
<P>
   Lying on the beach in Boca Raton, Alma Reyes was brutally
honest. ``What's Kosovo?'' said Ms. Reyes, 25, a waitress. ``I have
no idea where it is or what it is.''
</P>
<P>
   Her reaction was similar to those of others here on a beautiful
warm morning, where people in shorts and sandals found little
connection to either the cruelties that led to the bombing or the
prospect of further hostilities.
</P>
<P>
   ``What's Kosovo?'' said Todd Hunter Weiss, a shipping clerk at
Jacobson's Department Store in Boca Raton. ``I don't like to worry
about the world's problems. I'm a happier person if I stay centered
on myself.''
</P>
<P>
   It was the same further north, in Palm Beach.
</P>
<P>
   ``Last night we kept receiving calls to the station asking us
when President Clinton was going to stop speaking to the nation,''
said Jose Salvador, a television news producer at WPEC-TV, a CBS
affiliate in West Palm Beach. ``These people wanted their show back
on and they were really annoyed. They didn't think it affected them
in any way.''
</P>
<P>
   On South Beach, the trendy tip of Miami Beach, Latin American
and European tourists on Ocean Drive had no time to talk about
Kosovo, nor did Hispanic shoppers on Biscayne Boulevard in Miami.
</P>
<P>
   Not everyone dismissed the gravity of what is happening in
Kosovo. In the condominium canyons of Broward County and Palm
Beach, the Rev. George Mamangnkis, a retired Greek Orthodox priest,
had a strong opinion.
</P>
<P>
   ``We're making a mistake,'' said Mamangnkis, who served as a
priest in New Jersey before moving to Palm City. ``We are being
extremely unfair to the Serbian people. People should become more
aware of the history of the country. This country has had the same
problems since the 14th century.''
</P>
<P>
   In Delray Beach, 56-year-old Tony Prohaska had a personal
perspective on the conflict: His father was born in Montenegro, the
other republic in Yugoslavia, and he vacationed there last summer.
</P>
<P>
   ``It frightens me,'' he said of the bombing, which he fears
could expand into something much bigger. ``It should have been
worked out peacefully.''
</P>
<P>
   Mark Weaver, a vacationing National Guardsman from Indiana, had
a more military perspective. ``As long as the rules of engagement
aren't overly complex, we should be involved in order to reduce
their military capabilities,'' he said. ``There's nothing wrong
with what we're doing.''
</P>
<P>
   On the beach in Boca Raton, Ms. Reyes said she would try to
learn more about the conflict. ``I guess I should be reading the
newspaper,'' she said. ``Now maybe I will.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
