A4343 &Cx1f; taf-z
u i &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-KOSOVO-VOICES-TEXAS-N     03-25 0512
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-KOSOVO-VOICES-TEXAS-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
IN HOUSTON: `WHAT TO BELIEVE'? 
</HEADLINE>
  (Eds: See also KOSOVO-VOICES-NY, KOSOVO-VOICES-NH,
KOSOVO-VOICES-LA, KOSOVO-VOICES-MIAMI) 
(ART ADV: Photos are being sent of people quoted in Calif. and NY
stories. Non-subscribers can make individual purchase by calling
888-603-1036 or 888-346-9867.) 
(DW) 
 By RICK LYMAN   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   HOUSTON _ William and Mary Ellen Myers, married Thursday
morning, decided to celebrate by taking a stroll past the Water
Wall, a towering horseshoe-shaped fountain.. They acknowledged that
they had been a bit too wrapped up in the moment to pay close
attention to the situation in Kosovo, but it does worry them.
</P>
<P>
   ``I have a son who's a sophomore in high school,'' said Mrs.
Myers, an elementary-school music teacher, ``and he said they
announced it at school yesterday. It caught me by surprise, and I'm
finding it hard to know what to believe. After all that's happened,
can you trust President Clinton to tell you the truth?''
</P>
<P>
   Interviews Thursday with business executives, academics,
tourists, artists and passers-by suggested that the NATO bombing
was far away from most people's minds. Many said they were not only
unsure what was at stake, but had difficulty identifying which side
was being bombed.
</P>
<P>
   Edward Djerejian, director of the James Baker Institute for
Public Policy at Rice University, said he was not surprised by the
lack of understanding.
</P>
<P>
   ``It hasn't been explained to the American people by the
administration,'' Djerejian said.
</P>
<P>
   Bill White, a former head of the state Democratic Party, also
said it was not surprising that many people find it hard to fathom
what the United States and NATO are trying to do in Yugoslavia.
</P>
<P>
   ``Lots of folks don't fully realize how chaotic the world would
be without the military backbone provided by the United States,''
he said. ``So it's hard to explain sometimes the U.S. strategic
interest unless people realize that there has to be some worldwide
perception that there are boundaries that can't be crossed.''
</P>
<P>
   Dan Allison, a Houston-based artist who has traveled extensively
in the Balkans during the last decade, said it is important that
NATO ``do something and step in to stop Milosevic'' _ President
Slobodan Milosevic of Yugoslavia.
</P>
<P>
   Still, he said, he has ``torn feelings'' because he knows that
both ordinary Serbs and ethnic Albanians are at the mercy of armed
leaders who do not always tell them the truth. ``I'm sorry for
conscripts in the Serbian army going to attack places where they
used to go on vacation,'' he said. ``It's as if I were a conscript
in the army of Texas and had to attack Galveston.''
</P>
<P>
   One Houston resident with little doubt of where he stood was
Terry Minton, an accountant. ``I've been trying to follow it pretty
closely, and personally I think it was the appropriate thing to
do,'' he said. ``Ethnic aggression is just wrong and I think this
is the only way we're going to make the Serbs stop doing it. This
is the only language Slobodan Milosevic understands.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
