</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-DELTA-SELL26-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Delta agrees to sell 119 Boeing 727s
 &HT;    By Christopher Seward
 &HT;    c.1999 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   ATLANTA _ Delta Air Lines has signed a deal to sell 119 of its
Boeing 727s to Pratt &AMP; Whitney, the company that makes the engines
that power the planes.
</P>
<P>
   The deal comes as Delta begins taking delivery today of the
first of its new widebody Boeing 777s, the biggest plane in its
fleet.
</P>
<P>
   The narrower-bodied 727 will be replaced primarily by a new
version of the 737, a workhorse now being produced in updated
models.
</P>
<P>
   The deal announced Thursday with Pratt &AMP; Whitney provides the
carrier with a substantial cash flow as it retires its 727 fleet,
and the transaction will add to earnings, said Warren C. Jenson,
Delta's executive vice president and chief financial officer. Delta
also will sell Pratt &AMP; Whitney 39 spare engines.
</P>
<P>
   ``This agreement enables Delta to maintain our current schedule
for 727 retirements without concern for future fluctuations in the
used aircraft market,'' Jenson said in a statement.
</P>
<P>
   Delta's stock climbed $2.12 1/2, or 3 percent, to close at
$68.68 3/4 Thursday.
</P>
<P>
   While the Atlanta-based carrier didn't assign a value to the
deal, used Boeing 727s range in value from $4 million to $6
million, Bryant Lynch, manager of commercial aircraft appraisals at
Virginia-based AvSolutions Inc., told Bloomberg News.
</P>
<P>
   Delta has 125 of the 727s, more than any other passenger
carrier. About 20 of the planes will be retired this year, and the
remainder through 2005. The few remaining planes will be used for
spare parts, the company said.
</P>
<P>
   Delta and other airlines that fly the 727 face significantly
higher operating costs over the long run if they keep it in their
fleets. The 727 has three engines and requires three pilots, while
the new 737s have two engines and require only two pilots.
</P>
<P>
   Federal Aviation Administration rules have resulted in more
frequent mandatory inspections for some 727s. Last month the FAA
ordered inspections of 1,000 aging Boeing 727s for skin joint
fatigue cracks, a problem first noticed at Delta. The carrier said
100 of its 727s fall under the inspection order.
</P>
<P>
   Pratt &AMP; Whitney will convert the 727s to freighters and market
them with the help of Republic Financial Corp., an aircraft
equipment leasing firm in Denver. Pratt will refurbish the engines
at its Columbus maintenance center.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
