<HEADER>
A4346 &Cx1f; tad-z
u f &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-NORRELL26-COX     03-25 1002
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-NORRELL26-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Florida-based rival purchases Norrell
 &HT;    By Tammy Joyner
 &HT;    c.1999 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   ATLANTA _ Norrell Corp., the Atlanta-based temporary employment
service founded by former gubernatorial candidate Guy Millner, has
been acquired by a rival, Interim Services Inc. of Fort Lauderdale,
Fla., in a stock deal worth $553 million.
</P>
<P>
   The acquisition, announced Thursday, creates the nation's
third-largest temporary staffing firm. Worldwide, the combined
companies weigh in at No. 7, with $4 billion in revenue. The top
two U.S. firms are Manpower Inc. and Kelly Services.
</P>
<P>
   Norrell shareholders will get 0.9 shares of Interim stock for
each Norrell share on a tax-deferred basis. Interim assumes about
$55 million in Norrell debt. The deal, the latest in the rapidly
consolidating industry, is expected to be completed in the second
quarter.
</P>
<P>
   ``The combined companies will have enhanced capabilities to
serve clients on a global basis with the widest range of services
available in the industry,'' said Norrell Chairman and Chief
Executive Doug Miller. Miller, who will likely leave once the
transition is complete, and Ray Marcy, chief executive officer of
Interim, are longtime acquaintances.
</P>
<P>
   Millner, Norrell's single largest shareholder with 9.5 million
shares, will receive about 11 percent of Interim stock and a seat
on its board.
</P>
<P>
   ``I have a great deal of confidence in Interim management,''
Millner said. ``Ray Marcy has done an outstanding job in building
quite a leadership position in the industry.''
</P>
<P>
   Millner said he has no intention of leaving the Atlanta area.
</P>
<P>
   ``This merger will not change at all where we live,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   Millner lost races for governor in 1994 and 1998 and also lost a
bid for the U.S. Senate in 1996.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'm cured of politics. I look back with no regrets about my
political efforts,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   He relinquished an active role in Norrell several years ago.
</P>
<P>
   It is unclear if Norrell will retain its name or if there will
be layoffs.
</P>
<P>
   Interim spokeswoman Liza Palermo said the merger is about
``market expansion and revenue growth, not consolidation.''
</P>
<P>
   ``We will not be eliminating headquarters,'' she said.
</P>
<P>
   Analysts said the deal was a good strategic fit, with
complementary product lines for both companies. Interim inherits
Norrell's $300 million outsourcing unit and call center service,
two businesses it didn't have. The merger significantly enhances
Interim's technology, accounting and commercial staffing
operations. In turn, the Norrell name _ strong among Fortune 50
firms such as Coca-Cola, United Parcel Service and IBM _ will now
extend to European markets, where Interim is well-known.
</P>
<P>
   But analysts expressed concern about the merger, particularly
because Norrell has gone from an industry leader to a laggard in
the past year.
</P>
<P>
   ``I don't think there's a well-articulated strategy in terms of
integrating the two companies,'' said Peter Vozzo, a research
analyst at Interstate/Johnson Lane in Charlotte.
</P>
<P>
   ``Revenues have fallen in commercial staffing, and its IT
(information technology) staffing seems to have slowed down,''
Vozzo said.
</P>
<P>
   ``Norrell has been a puzzle to analysts for the last year. They
expected it to perform better. They haven't done exactly what they
were supposed to do in terms of earnings,'' said Peter Yessne,
editor of Staffing Industry Report in Los Altos, Calif.
</P>
<P>
   ``They're a company that could have continued on by themselves.
But they apparently see this as a way to maximize their value.''
</P>
<P>
   Like most of the industry, the stocks of both companies have
fallen sharply. Companies are spending less time and money on
temporary workers because they are so focused on Y2K problems. At
the same time, the temporary staffing industry has a difficult time
finding workers because of the low unemployment rate.
</P>
<P>
   That, coupled with poor earnings estimates, has put the brakes
on the industry's near-decade-long growth. Much of the industry is
consolidating as a way to control costs in such areas as
information technology, where it is becoming more expensive to be a
major player.
</P>
<P>
   Norrell's shares closed at $13.43 1/4 Thursday, up 81 1/4 cents.
The stock is down 8 percent from the beginning of the year and well
below its 52-week high of $24.75 in April 1998.
</P>
<P>
   Interim Services closed Thursday at $16, down $1.81 1/4.
</P>
<P>
   Norrell has wrestled with several poorly performing units.
</P>
<P>
   Vozzo said Norrell focused on its larger light-industry clients
at the expense of its midsize clients. A Norrell spokesman tied the
problems to internal and external factors: Several large clients
cut back on work, and Norrell went through a fairly significant
restructuring that involved splitting its sales and services
functions, said spokesman Gene Stevenson.
</P>
<P>
   ``We believe we've working our way out of that,'' Stevenson
said, citing the company's recent five-year, multimillion-dollar
agreement with Coca-Cola to provide staffing services for the
company's Atlanta headquarters.
</P>
<P>
   Millner defended the company's performance, particularly its IT
division.
</P>
<P>
   ``If you look at the whole staffing segment, they're all down.
It has nothing to do with the growth in the marketplace,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   There were more than 400 mergers and acquisitions in the
industry last year, according to the National Association of
Temporary and Staffing Services, an Alexandria, Va., trade group.
In August, the Dutch parent of Atlanta-based Randstad Staffing
Services bought part of Accustaff for $850 million.
</P>
<P>
   ``We expect that as the industry continues to evolve and mature,
we'll see significant consolidation and activities,'' said Richard
Wahlquist, NATSS executive vice president.
</P>
<P>
   There are about 7,000 companies in the industry providing people
and services ranging from clerical help to light assembly work to
information technology and even chief executives.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
