<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-KOSOVO-VOICES-NH-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
IN NEW HAMPSHIRE: `WHY ARE WE ALWAYS THE BIG BROTHER?' 
</HEADLINE>
  (Eds: See also KOSOVO-VOICES-NY, KOSOVO-VOICES-TEXAS,
KOSOVO-VOICES-LA, KOSOVO-VOICES-MIAMI) 
(ART ADV: Photos are being sent of people quoted in Calif. and NY
stories. Non-subscribers can make individual purchase by calling
888-603-1036 or 888-346-9867.) 
(DW) 
 By CAREY GOLDBERG   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   LONDONDERRY, N.H. _ From its antique apple orchards to its high
school principal's office, this New England hamlet showed not a
drop of jubilation Thursday over the NATO attacks on Yugoslavia.
</P>
<P>
   Trepidation, rather, seemed to reign, even among the festive
Hula Hoops and bells at Cindy Parente's Kindermusik class.
</P>
<P>
   ``I want to know, why are we there?'' asked Jennifer Croot, 32,
who was helping her daughter, Emily, through her paces. ``Why are
we always the big brother? I know the answer: We are the No. 1
power in the world.''
</P>
<P>
   But she was clearly not happy about it.
</P>
<P>
   ``I just hope there's a peaceful solution quickly,'' Ms. Parente
said. ``I don't want to believe the atrocities I'm reading about.''
</P>
<P>
   ``I don't see an end to it,'' Terry Akashian worried aloud as
she kept an eye on her daughter, Hailey.
</P>
<P>
   Elsewhere as well a willingness to accept the need to intervene
to defend ethnic Albanians in Kosovo seemed to mingle with deep
discomfort that such global interventions seemed to be becoming a
habit, and seemed always to be dominated by American force and
will.
</P>
<P>
   ``Should we be there?'' asked Bill Etter, a special education
instructor at Londonderry High School. ``I don't know. The idea
we're constantly called upon to do the dirty work of the rest of
the world becomes a major problem as a moral issue.''
</P>
<P>
   Tony Hanna, a technology teacher, commented similarly: ``I think
that we're probably one of the only countries in the position to do
that. But I don't think that necessarily makes it right that we're
always the financial and military back behind everything.''
</P>
<P>
   Etter said he was concerned that Russia might use the bombing as
an excuse to return to a more aggressive role in the world arena.
``It's a golden opportunity to get back into things,'' he said.
``It's very scary.''
</P>
<P>
   But at Mack's Apples, a 400-acre spread that has been a farm
since 1732, the farm manager, Mike Cross, noted, as he had heard
President Clinton say Wednesday night, that the alternatives are
scary, too.
</P>
<P>
   ``The president seems to be afraid that if they don't do
something, this will spread and turn into a major European war,''
he said.
</P>
<P>
   The president could be right, Cross said, but he questioned
whether bombing Yugoslavia would force President Slobodan Milosevic
to back down. ``That seems to be the big question today,'' he said.
``Is this guy going to stop, or will it be like Iran and Iraq,
where these guys just don't care? I don't imagine the Serbs are
going to stop _ not after one night's bombing, anyway.''
</P>
<P>
   The other big question, he said, was whether the United States
and other countries would decide they must send in ground troops as
the only way to impose their will. So far, NATO leaders seem to be
actively avoiding answering that question, he said.
</P>
<P>
   Over all, like a handful of others, Cross sounded torn:
uncomfortable with the global policeman role and yet, he said,
``Cleaning out villages, killing the men and making the women and
children refugees _ that seems like a pretty terrible thing to let
anybody get away with.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
