<SLUG> BC-KOSOVO-VOICES-NY-ART-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
IN NEW YORK, `MIXED FEELINGS' 
</HEADLINE>
 (Eds: See also KOSOVO-VOICES-LA, KOSOVO-VOICES-NH,
KOSOVO-VOICES-FLA, KOSOVO-VOICES-TEXAS.) 
(ART ADV: Photos are being sent of people quoted in Calif. and NY
stories. Non-subscribers can make individual purchase by calling
888-603-1036 or 888-346-9867.) 
DW) 
 By BARBARA STEWART   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEW YORK _ Many New Yorkers seemed to be debating with
themselves Thursday when trying to express their feelings about the
NATO strikes on Yugoslavia _ flipping quickly from pro to con to
simply puzzled.
</P>
<P>
   ``I have very mixed feelings,'' said Bill Burrows, as he and his
three daughters lingered in the lobby of the Times Square Disney
Store. ``I don't think we should stand by idly. But there have been
massive human rights violations everywhere _ Tibet, Rwanda,
Tiananmen Square.''
</P>
<P>
   ``They say we need a stable Europe for our national security,''
he added. ``But I'm not sure why a stable Africa or stable Asia
isn't just as important for us.''
</P>
<P>
   Dan Rarback, 53 and retired, was working on a crossword puzzle
in an Upper West Side coffee shop Thursday afternoon. ``That war's
been going on 1,000 years,'' he said. ``I guess our position is
that our national security is threatened. And there are the
humanitarian considerations _ people being tortured, a lot of
people dying. Maybe, here, it's a moral imperative.''
</P>
<P>
   But he fought in Vietnam for a year, which colored his feelings
about war indelibly. ``War is horrible,'' he said. ``We're going in
to help people, but people are going to get killed. And I don't
even know which side is which.''
</P>
<P>
   Some said they were too uninformed to assess the attacks, while
others said they had not really given the bombings much thought,
and felt troubled by that. ``I'm disturbed,'' said Reevan Trupin,
who teaches English to immigrants. ``These wars seem like such
nonchalant things. The Serbs are the bad guys _ killing innocent
Muslims, right? But if you look back, they were fighting Hitler,
right? It's very complex.''
</P>
<P>
   It is tempting to ignore the complexities and try to view the
situation in black and white, said Jackie Wildau, a theatrical
consultant and producer, who had stopped for a coffee break.
</P>
<P>
   ``You have the Vietnam picture and the Hitler picture,'' she
said. ``We're tossed between the two _ one or the other, right or
wrong.
</P>
<P>
   Richard Verdery, a retired U. N. official, walking home on upper
Broadway, said: ``I have some doubt they can solve this thing by
bombing. I bet they'll have to put troops in on the ground. But we
should have done this earlier.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
