<SLUG> BC-KOSOVO-BUSH-HNS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
BUSH SAYS HIS PRAYERS ARE WITH U.S. PERSONNEL 

</HEADLINE>
  
 (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  (Also see: KOSOVO-NATO, KOSOVO-AIM and KOSOVO-DAMAGE) 
 
(Eds.: Condoleezza Rice is cq) 
 
By R.G. RATCLIFFE 
c.1999 Houston Chronicle 
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   AUSTIN, Texas _ Gov. George W. Bush on Thursday said his prayers
are with the U.S. military personnel participating in the Kosovo
intervention, but Bush said he has doubts about America's role in
the conflict.
</P>
<P>
   ``The ultimate question is: Will this military action lead to
the goal of ending the conflict and bringing peace and stability to
the region? I fervently hope so, although I share the concerns and
misgivings of many Texans and Americans.''
</P>
<P>
   Bush was the last of the potential Republican presidential
contenders to weigh in on the Kosovo crisis this week.
</P>
<P>
   As a state governor, he has had little exposure to Balkan
conflict policy. Before making his statements Thursday, Bush
consulted with his presidential exploratory committee policy
adviser Josh Bolten and foreign policy adviser Condoleezza Rice.
</P>
<P>
   As the airstrikes against Yugoslavian forces entered their
second day, Bush said President Clinton had no choice but to go
through with the military action once he had threatened force, and
Yugoslav President Slobodan Milosevic had refused to back down.
</P>
<P>
   ``The mistake would have been to make threats and then not
follow through,'' Bush said. ``Once the president of the United
States makes a threat, he must or she must follow through.''
</P>
<P>
   Bush's father as president initiated the Persian Gulf War to
drive Iraq out of Kuwait. President Bush conducted that war by
saying the nation must have a clearly defined goal.
</P>
<P>
   Gov. Bush said the nation needs to ask that same kind of
question about the defense of Kosovo.
</P>
<P>
   ``My worry is the worry of a lot of people I've heard from in
Texas, and that is, will the airstrikes achieve the president's
stated mission of bringing Milosevic back to the peace table,''
Bush said. ``And if not, what next?''
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
 &QL; 
(STORY CAN END HERE. OPTIONAL MATERIAL FOLLOWS) &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Closer to home, Bush spent part of Thursday's meeting with about
30 politicians from around the nation who were interested in his
race for president. The group included former Massachusetts Gov.
William Weld, said Bush spokeswoman Mindy Tucker.
</P>
<P>
   Alex Arshinkoff, GOP chairman of Summit County, Ohio, came out
of the meeting sold on Bush as someone conservative enough to
satisfy all Republicans.
</P>
<P>
   ``Let's face facts, guys, moderates in Texas are more
conservative than most people across the country,'' Arshinkoff
said. ``For George Bush, who is a conservative, to be called
anything but a conservative is ridiculous.''
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
XXXX END OF STORY &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
