A4357 &Cx1f; tta-z
u w &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-BUDGET-U.S.-NYT &LR;      03-25 1069
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BUDGET-U.S.-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
HOUSE PASSES GOP BUDGET PLAN; CLASH WITH CLINTON LIKELY 
</HEADLINE>
   (bl)  
 By RICHARD W. STEVENSON   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON _ The House passed the Republican budget plan
Thursday night, driving toward a big tax cut and a showdown later
this year with the Clinton administration over the nation's
priorities in an emerging era of fiscal plenty.
</P>
<P>
   The Senate also worked into the night on a nearly identical
measure, and was all but certain to pass it, uniting Republicans in
the two chambers as they prepare for months of budget battles with
the White House and set out an agenda they hope to carry into the
2000 elections.
</P>
<P>
   Voting largely along party lines, the House adopted a budget
guideline that calls for a tax cut of nearly $800 billion over the
next 10 years, an increase in Pentagon spending and more money for
education. The final vote in the House was 221-208.
</P>
<P>
   But to remain within strict spending limits that both parties
have vowed to honor, the Republican plan would require deep cuts in
most other programs, prompting sharp criticism from Democrats and
leaving even some Republicans uneasy.
</P>
<P>
   In presenting their competing visions of how to divide up the
expected fiscal windfall in coming years, the two parties generally
agreed on setting aside the bulk of projected surpluses for Social
Security, which will come under increasing financial strain as the
baby boom generation ages and retires.
</P>
<P>
   But in a sign of the enduring sensitivity of Social Security as
a political issue, they battled furiously over whose approach
walled off more money for the retirement system and did more to
reduce the national debt. And Democrats attacked Republicans for
putting tax cuts ahead of dealing with the looming problems in
Medicare, which will start running short of money in less than a
decade.
</P>
<P>
   ``Making a budget means making choices,'' said House Speaker
Dennis Hastert. The Republican budget, he said, ``makes the right
choices for the American people.''
</P>
<P>
   In a statement Thursday night, President Clinton called the
Republican plan a series of missed opportunities at a time when the
country is facing the welcome prospect of years of federal budget
surpluses.
</P>
<P>
   ``It fails to lock in debt reduction, fails to extend the
solvency of Social Security and Medicare, and fails to protect key
investments for the American people, from Head Start to clean water
and law enforcement,'' Clinton said.
</P>
<P>
   The budget resolution passed Thursday night does not become law
but serves as the blueprint for the tax and spending bills Congress
will take up in the coming months. While it gives the Republicans a
chance to emphasize what they see as their core values _ fiscal
austerity, tax cuts and smaller government _ it leaves until later
in the year the question of how to implement the spending
reductions.
</P>
<P>
   Republicans on the appropriations committees that set spending
levels for specific programs say it will be politically difficult
if not impossible to pass spending bills requiring sweeping
cutbacks in the State Department, the environment, the FBI, Head
Start and NASA, among other programs.
</P>
<P>
   Indeed, much of the debate in both chambers Thursday involved
pleas from members of both parties for additional spending for
farmers, veterans and other powerful constituencies.
</P>
<P>
   The Republican budget plan does not specify what types of tax
cuts Congress should enact, leaving that decision to the
tax-writing committees in the House and Senate. The budget plan
allows for a tax cut of $15 billion next year, an amount that would
increase rapidly in subsequent years as the non-Social Security
surplus grows.
</P>
<P>
   The Republican leadership has backed off its pledge earlier this
year to cut income tax rates by 10 percent. Instead, Republicans
are now looking at packages that could include some rate
reductions; reductions in the so-called marriage penalty that leads
many two-income couples to pay more in taxes than if they were
single; a cut in inheritance taxes, and a reduction in capital
gains taxes.
</P>
<P>
   Rep. Bill Archer, R-Texas, chairman of the House Ways and Means
Committee, where tax legislation must originate, said he would not
draw up his tax bill until this summer and had not yet decided on
its composition.
</P>
<P>
   There are relatively minor differences in the House and Senate
versions of the budget resolution. Republican aides said they
expected the differences to be worked out quickly when Congress
returns after a two-week recess in April and for the final version
of the measure to win quick approval in both chambers.
</P>
<P>
   One of the biggest changes contained in the budget plan is a vow
to end the longstanding practice of using Social Security surpluses
to pay for spending or tax cuts.
</P>
<P>
   The Republican plan would require that all surpluses generated
by Social Security _ $1.8 trillion over the next decade under the
assumptions used by Congress _ be used only to reduce the national
debt or to help pay for an overhaul of Social Security, including
the establishment of private investment accounts.
</P>
<P>
   Republicans said their plan would do more for Social Security
than Clinton's proposal, which in the first few years would allow
some of the retirement system's money to be used for spending but
would make up for it in later years. Using the Congressional Budget
Office's assumptions about the size of the surplus, the
administration's plan would wall off $1.52 trillion over 10 years
for Social Security, $275 billion less than the Republican plan.
</P>
<P>
   But White House officials argued that their plan set aside more
for Social Security and Medicare combined over the same period.
Using the budget office's assumptions, the administration's plan
would reserve $370 billion for Medicare _ bringing the total for
Social Security and Medicare over 10 years to nearly $1.9 trillion
_ while the Republican plan does not have any money explicitly set
aside for Medicare.
</P>
<P>
   In a clear sign of how reluctant lawmakers are to be seen as
dipping into Social Security money, the House rejected Clinton's
budget proposal by 426-2 because it allowed some of the Social
Security surplus to be spent over the next few years.
</P>
<P>
   The House also rejected two other alternative budget proposals.
One was backed by the House Democratic leadership and the other by
a group of fiscally conservative Democrats.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-03-25-99 2040EST &QL; 
</TRAILER>
