r s &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-BKC-MEDIA-COLUMN-LADN     03-25 1515
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BKC-MEDIA-COLUMN-LADN </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
BIRD-MAGIC DISTORTED IN REAR-VIEW MIRROR
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By TOM HOFFARTH  
 c.1999 Los Angeles Daily News  
<TEXT>
<P>
   LOS ANGELES _ (begin ital)``The fans have poured into Salt Lake
City in record numbers and they're infected with basketball
fever.... Those who believe in Magic and those who appreciate the
beauty of a rare Bird have come to see basketball's best and
witness the crowning of a new basketball champion.... All the
superlatives have been used and all have been warranted.''(end
ital) &QL; 
_ NBC's Bryant Gumbel, during the opening of the Michigan
State-Indiana State NCAA Final telecast on March 26, 1979.
</P>
<P>
   It remains the highest-rated basketball telecast in TV history _
college or pro _ with a 24.1, seen in a then-record 18 million
homes. More than one of every three TV sets turned on at the time
were on this game.
</P>
<P>
   Maybe not Super Bowl-type numbers, yet 20 years later people
still talk about Michigan State and Magic Johnson's NCAA Tournament
final against Indiana State and Larry Bird as if it were yesterday.
</P>
<P>
   Although several televised hoopfests since then have had bigger
audiences _ simply because of the fact more people own more TV sets
than in '79 _ the rating shows that a higher percentage of people
then were drawn to it. And in these days of the cable-influenced
fragmented TV medium, it would take something highly unusual to
even equal it.
</P>
<P>
   OK, so it was a great matchup. A great game? Hardly. So is
revisionist history making it bigger than it really was?
</P>
<P>
   Trying to put this into context, two documentaries air this
weekend by two channels _ ESPN Classic and Fox Sports Net _ that
weren't even thought about when the event took place.
</P>
<P>
   Tonight, ESPN Classic has a two-hour program at 6 p.m. featuring
much of the original broadcast from opening tip to postgame
interviews, augmented with interviews of both players, Boston Globe
writer Bob Ryan, Indiana State coach Bill Hodges, Michigan State
coach Jud Heathcote and Michigan State All-American Greg Kelser.
</P>
<P>
   In the same way Classic's ``The Story of the Game'' series
works, there's no narration to this documentary. The viewer has the
pleasure of watching it all unfold. That in itself makes this look
back so enjoyable.
</P>
<P>
   But then there are quotes like these from Hodges: ``The two
became so intertwined by the electronic media that it evolved into
a showdown.''
</P>
<P>
   At that point, the only electronic media that really cared was
NBC, which did the weekly NCAA games and most of the tournament
after the first round _ not at all as CBS does now. Remember, most
of the media attention came from newspapers.
</P>
<P>
   Sunday night, on the eve of what could be Michigan State's first
visit to the NCAA Final since that game, Fox Sports Net Films has
an hour-long documentary at 9 p.m. (repeats Monday at 4 p.m. and
Tuesday at 9 p.m.) with the help of Black Canyon Productions and
Magic Johnson Entertainment called ``Magic vs. Bird: The Game That
Changed The Game.''
</P>
<P>
   The producers say this is the first time Johnson and Bird have
sat down together to look back on the game, with Chris Myers,
infected not so much with basketball fever but a case of
laryngitis, painfully croaking out the questions.
</P>
<P>
   The Fox piece brings in play-by-play man Dick Enberg and game
host Bryant Gumbel for their reflections as well.
</P>
<P>
   As for Gumbel's pre-Musburger-esque opening, he replies in the
documentary:
</P>
<P>
   ``Did we hype it? Yeah we hyped it. Did we have cause to? Yes.
When you have exceptional talent you're bringing to the floor, it's
not hype. It comes to a loftier end. It's called promotion.''
</P>
<P>
   Which is what Bryant's brother, Greg, will be doing for CBS on
Monday night.
</P>
<P>
   Twenty-plus-twenty years ago:!off! ESPN dispatches Jon Miller
and Joe Morgan to Cuba for Sunday morning's special broadcast of
the Baltimore Orioles' somewhat controversial exhibition game
against the Cuban national team _ the first time in 40 years a
major-league team has entered Fidel Castro's domain.
</P>
<P>
   At about the same time, Hall of Fame play-by-play man Vin Scully
will be doing what could be the Dodgers' last televised game from
Vero Beach, Fla., when the team faces the Atlanta Braves. The
Dodgers are talking of moving to Arizona next season after decades
in Florida.
</P>
<P>
   A connection between these two events: The last team to play in
Cuba was the Dodgers who, in 1959, briefly left Vero Beach because
of several days of rain in Florida and, without much attention,
hopped over to continue spring training. The Dodgers were the only
team with its own plane and owner Walter O'Malley decided it needed
the work. He flew his men to Havana, then went back to Tampa and
brought over the Cincinnati Reds as travel companions.
</P>
<P>
   Scully, who doesn't recall if he did a broadcast of that
Dodgers-Reds game or not, remembers the trip:
</P>
<P>
   ``It was really no big deal. Those were `Ozzie and Harriet'
times and I think we were all somewhat naive about Castro. In fact,
you could buy souvenir revolutionary hats and the fake beards and
glasses and have your picture taken dressed as Castro. It was all a
big lark.''
</P>
<P>
   The only scary thing Scully recalls about the trip was seeing
some soldiers with girls come into the national hotel in Havana
carrying their rifles with them as they went into the bar to start
drinking.
</P>
<P>
   ``That was our signal to get out of there,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   Another interesting sidelight Scully recalls was running into a
Cuban gentleman checking into the hotel. The Cuban, to Scully's
surprise, spoke fluent English. Scully found out the man happened
to be in his 1949 graduating class at Fordham University _ and was
now working for Castro as an expert on military law.
</P>
<P>
   ``When I read about the Orioles going over there, I thought, and
maybe I'm still naive, that baseball can help open some doors that
have been locked for quite some time,'' said Scully. ``But this
seems to have brought out a lot of feelings from people that we
don't quite understand. There's a lot of bitterness from people
here who lost everything there.
</P>
<P>
   ``Hopefully, this will become a plus and not a minus. I do know
if I was sent there today to do a game, I'd go because it's my
job.'' &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Staff Writer Tom Hoffarth's media column appears Friday in the
Daily News. He can be reached at (818) 713-3661 or sptmediaaol.com.
</P>
<P>
   WHAT SMOKES  &QL;
</P>
<P>
   _ The NHL's expansion Atlanta Thrashers hired sports-talk radio
host Scott Ferrall as its play-by-play radio announcer. He's never
done play-by-play, let alone speak in a decipherable tone of voice.
``I'll be the most bizarre announcer in the league,'' said Ferrall,
who will continue to do his sports-talk show for Westwood One
that's picked up locally on KXTA-AM (1150). &QL;
</P>
<P>
   _ NBC's NBA ratings. Charles Barkley can bark all he wants about
not wanting to see the Lakers on the network again, but there's no
question why it's done. NBC reports the Lakers' game against
Orlando last Sunday did a 5.1 rating and 14 share in an overnight
survey of 44 markets _ a 50 percent improvement over marks of a
regional telecast a year ago (a double OT game between Utah and New
York.) Sunday, the Lakers make their seventh NBC appearance in
eight weeks when they face the Knicks at 3:30 p.m. _ prime-time on
the East Coast. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   _ David Letterman to Don King , who made a surprise appearance
on ``Late Show'' Monday night: ``What are you doing here? Don't you
have a fight to fix?'' &QL;
</P>
<P>
   _ Irv Kaze. Starts his eighth year at KIEV-AM (870) doing his
sports interview show. That's somethin'. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   WHAT CHOKES  &QL;
</P>
<P>
   _ Just when you get comfortable with a late-night guilty
pleasure like ``Strongest Man'' competition, sumo wrestling or
Asian women billiards before the sports news, ESPN frets about the
competition. Saying it's doing it as a service to West Coast
viewers _ and trying not to lose any more of us to Fox Sports News
in the 10 p.m. hour _ ESPN will in effect start a two-hour
``SportsCenter'' at 10 p.m. beginning April 6. If you can handle
it, Rich Eisen and Stuart Scott anchor both hours. The 11
p.m.-to-midnight segment will continue to be repeated at 2 a.m.
Since Fox Sports News' growth, ESPN has added 16 hours a week of
``SportsCenter'' shows in the past two years. This better be worth
it. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   _ Dan Patrick was the guest _ not the host _ of ESPN's ``Up
Close'' on Monday. And Gary Miller actually gave what the show felt
was legit reasons for the booking. Next week: Chris Berman comes on
to talk about his childhood vaccinations. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   _ Anyone else hear the interview Lee ``Hacksaw'' Hamilton
</P>
<P>
   (not his real name) did with a Montreal broadcaster as part of
the ``Tour Around Spring Training Camps'' bit Wednesday on XTRA-AM
(690)? Twice during the interview, the broadcaster said he was
looking forward to the start of spring training in a couple of
weeks to see how the team resolves some of its question marks.
'Saw, of course, then thanked the guy ``for joining us tonight.''
He then should have thanked his producer again for not erasing the
tape.
</P>
