<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-03-25 20:47 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A4368 &Cx1f; tta-z
u i &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-KOSOVO-MILITARY-ASSES     03-25 1067
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-KOSOVO-MILITARY-ASSESS-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
ANALYSIS: SERB MISSILES ARE STRANGELY SILENT, BUT IS THAT GOOD OR
BAD?
</HEADLINE>
   (See also: KOSOVO-RDP, KOSOVO-MILITARY, KOSOVO-GERMANY,
KOSOVO-POLICY, KOSOVO-BELGRADE, KOSOVO-PRISTINA, KOSOVO-MACEDONIA,
KOSOVO-REPORTERS, KOSOVO-CHINA, KOSOVO-RUSSIA-ASSESS,
KOSOVO-CLINTON, KOSOVO-ITALY, KOSOVO-VOICES, KOSOVO-B2,
KOSOVO-EUROPE-REAX, KOSOVO-U.N., KOSOVO-CLARK-PROFILE.) 
(wg) 
 By ERIC SCHMITT   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON _ Call it the mystery of the missing missiles.
</P>
<P>
   After two nights of raiding Yugoslavia's air defenses with
bombers and cruise missiles, NATO military commanders are facing an
ominous question. Yugoslavia has fired one, only one, of its most
fearsome anti-aircraft weapons: the lethal SAM systems inherited
from the Soviet Union. And NATO's generals don't know whether they
should worry or breathe a sigh of relief.
</P>
<P>
   Was it because the generals overrated the vaunted Yugoslav
defenses or underrated them? One thing was clear on Thursday: For a
second day, NATO warplanes and cruise missiles bombarded Yugoslav
defenses in nighttime raids. And for a second day, Belgrade barely
put up a fight. (The one missile fired, a mobile SA-6, missed.)
</P>
<P>
   From Washington to Brussels, Belgium, commanders were puzzling
over why Yugoslavia's menacing missiles were largely silent. ``We
don't know why,'' said Pentagon Kenneth Bacon, who confirmed that
NATO forces had shot down at least three MIG fighters that,
surprisingly, were sent up instead of missiles to challenge the
attack on Wednesday. On Thursday, the MIGs were grounded
altogether.
</P>
<P>
   Some air force generals boasted that Yugoslavia's vaunted
Soviet-era defenses were overrated, and that the aerial assault had
blinded radars that guide the streaking missiles to their targets.
But other analysts said President Slobodan Milosevic of Yugoslavia
was waiting, hoping to lull NATO air forces into complacency and,
ultimately, a trap.
</P>
<P>
   ``It doesn't surprise me that he may be trying to protect his
SAMs,'' said Robert Osterthaler, a retired air force general and
former Pentagon official who dealt with Bosnia. ``His objective may
be to bring down one or two aircraft. That would create some real
problems for us to have Western pilots paraded through the streets
of Belgrade.''
</P>
<P>
   Indeed, many military and diplomatic analysts said Milosevic may
be trying to buy time by hiding his mobile missiles in forests,
hoping a prolonged air campaign splits the NATO coalition or that
Moscow intervenes with a diplomatic overture to rescue its longtime
Slavic ally.
</P>
<P>
   ``He's waiting to see what the Russians do,'' said Gen. George
Joulwan, a former supreme allied commander. ``He's trying to wait
it out.''
</P>
<P>
   NATO commanders are taking no chances with Yugoslavia's
formidable arsenal of Soviet-era SA-2, SA-3 and SA-6 missiles. Wave
after wave of NATO radar-evading warplanes, satellite-guided bombs
or unmanned cruise missiles pounded Yugoslav air defenses,
communications towers and military barracks.
</P>
<P>
   ``We have a lot of respect for the Serb air defense
capabilities,'' Gen. Wesley Clark, the supreme allied commander,
told reporters Thursday. ``It's a country that has long prepared
itself for war.''
</P>
<P>
   But some air force officers here said that NATO commanders were
overly consumed with caution, and missed an opportunity to send
low-flying, tank-killing U.S. A-10 or British Jaguar jets to attack
the Yugoslav armored forces that are assaulting villages in Kosovo,
sending a torrent of refugees fleeing the region.
</P>
<P>
   ``They restricted the target base over there,'' said one senior
officer, who spoke on condition of anonymity. ``We could have gone
in this afternoon and started going after fielded forces, but we're
not going full out, as we should be.''
</P>
<ANNOTATION>
   (STORY CAN END HERE. OPTIONAL MATERIAL FOLLOWS)
</ANNOTATION>
<P>
   Yet U.S. and NATO officials insist that if Milosevic does not
stop his army's rampage, the coalition will bomb Yugoslavia into
oblivion.
</P>
<P>
   Invoking unusually personal language that American commanders
have reserved for President Saddam Hussein of Iraq, Clark warned:
``President Milosevic and his military leaders should understand
that there is no sanctuary for them, their military forces, their
command-and-control elements, because they're part of the mechanism
of the Serb military and security forces and the repression.''
</P>
<P>
   But an air war of attrition may be a luxury NATO cannot afford.
After only two days of bombing, there are signs the 19-member
alliance is showing cracks. Greece and Italy suggested on Thursday
that the time might be ripe to reopen peace negotiations, and a mob
rioted outside the U.S. embassy in Macedonia.
</P>
<P>
   ``If Yugoslavia withstands a sustained bombing, then there will
be an erosion of support among the allies, but we not there yet,''
said one senior Western diplomat here.
</P>
<P>
   Of course, this is likely all a part of Milosevic's calculation.
The Yugoslav army reiterated its defiance on Thursday after a night
of airstrikes, saying the ``high morale of the units was
preserved.'' Milosevic congratulated the Yugoslav military commands
for their ``brave resistance.''
</P>
<P>
   But a crucial unanswered question here and in European capitals
is, how long will Milosevic's military commanders stand by him in
the face of escalating NATO strikes?
</P>
<P>
   ``Increasingly, as the military's capacity is degraded, there
will be possibility of military mutinies,'' said Janusz Bugajski,
the director of East European studies at the Center for Strategic
and International Studies here.
</P>
<P>
   Just a few months ago, Milosevic replaced the chief of staff of
the Yugoslav army and his secret service chief. Last week, he
replaced his military security chief with an army loyalist.
</P>
<P>
   ``Though evil, Milosevic is a survivalist,'' Sen. Joseph
Lieberman, D-Conn., said in an interview, repeating the analysis a
senior Pentagon official gave senators Thursday in a closed
briefing.
</P>
<P>
   ``At some point he's got to consider the devastation that NATO
will do to his county and that will topple him,'' Lieberman said,
reprising the Pentagon's assessment. ``And for that reason, he'll
sue for peace.''
</P>
<P>
   But Milosevic has confounded the West before, and Clark warned
of a long haul: ``We're going to grind away at him until we
accomplish the military objectives or until our political leaders
tell us to halt.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-03-25-99 2047EST &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> NYT19990325.0296 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-03-25 20:48 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A4369 &Cx1f; tad-z
u i &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-KOSOVO-STRIKES-0326-C     03-25 1409
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-KOSOVO-STRIKES-0326-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    U.S., NATO LAUNCH SECOND DAY OF STRIKES, MILOSEVIC REMAINS
DEFIANT
 &HT;    With KOSOVO-B2-0326; KOSOVO-CLARK-0326; B2-BOX-0326;
CLARK-BIOBOX-0326.
 &HT;    Moving in both (i) International and (w) Washington categories.
 &HT;    By BOB DEANS and CHARLES W. HOLMES 
 &HT;    c.1999 Cox News Service 
<TEXT>
<P>
   AVIANO AIR BASE, Italy _ Vowing ''no sanctuary'' for Serb
military forces, NATO commander Gen. Wesley Clark launched a second
punishing night of air strikes deep into Yugoslavia late Thursday,
pounding radar stations, air fields, barracks and other military
targets with scores of cruise missiles and guided bombs.
</P>
<P>
   In the southern province of Kosovo, thousands of Serb troops and
police backed by hundreds of tanks pressed their own offensive on
the ground, rolling up villages and torching homes in an unchecked
rampage that put untallied hordes of ethnic Albanians to a panicked
flight for their lives.
</P>
<P>
   The conflict spilled over Yugoslavia's boundaries, as U.S.
officials said Serb artillery was fired across the border into
Albania and angry ethnic Serbs protested the NATO bombings by
attacking the American Embassy in neighboring Macedonia.
</P>
<P>
   ``NATO out of Yugoslavia,'' some 2,000 protesters chanted.
Others pelted the embassy compound with stones and Molotov
cocktails, smashing windows and burning three cars, before riot
police dispersed them with tear gas.
</P>
<P>
   Hoping to foment more such attacks elsewhere, Serbian Deputy
Prime Minister Vojislav Seselj called on Serbs worldwide to
''strike at American interests as best they can,'' prompting
heightened security at federal buildings in Washington.
</P>
<P>
   President Clinton vowed to continue the U.S.-led NATO strikes,
however, until Serb leader Slobodan Milosevic, president of
Yugoslavia, halts his bloody offensive in Kosovo and agrees to an
international peace plan, or until allied bombs crush his ability
to wage war.
</P>
<P>
   ``President Milosevic and his military leaders should understand
that there is no sanctuary for them,'' Clark, the U.S. Army general
who is the supreme allied commander for Europe, told reporters at
NATO headquarters in Brussels.
</P>
<P>
   ``We are going to systematically and progressively attack,
disrupt, degrade, devastate,'' Serb military forces, Clark said.
Unless Milosevic capitulates, he added, ``we are going to destroy
these forces and their facilities and support.''
</P>
<P>
   Hours later, more than 60 warplanes -- including F-117A Stealth
fighters, F-16 Fighting Falcons and F-15 Eagles -- took off from
here in northwestern Italy, as U.S. Navy ships in the Adriatic Sea
launched at least 20 Tomahawk cruise missiles at Serb military
targets in Yugoslavia.
</P>
<P>
   The Pentagon was encouraged by preliminary assessments of the
opening night of raids on Wednesday. Some 40 targets were hit,
Pentagon spokesman Kenneth Bacon said, and at least three
Soviet-built MiG-29 fighters, the best the Yugoslav air force has,
were shot down: two by U.S. pilots in F-15s; the other by a Dutch
pilots flying a U.S.-built F-16.
</P>
<P>
   Maintenance crews here at Aviano spent Thursday surveying the
aircraft, rearming them for the evening's sorties and scrawling
their own messages on the side of laser-guided bombs.
</P>
<P>
   ``Have no fear,'' read one, ``B-flight is here!!!''
</P>
<P>
   But a weapons specialist, Senior Airman Perry McCiver, 30, of
San Diego, Calif., said he prayed as U.S. planes roared off toward
the Balkans.
</P>
<P>
   ``I prayed for our pilots. I prayed for the Kosovars,'' said
McCiver. ``I prayed for everybody.''
</P>
<P>
   His appeals seemed well-placed.
</P>
<P>
   Serb troops spent the day extending their year-long offensive in
Kosovo, where attacks on ethnic Albanians over the past year have
left more than 2,000 dead and another quarter of a million
homeless.
</P>
<P>
   ``He's escalated today,'' National Security Adviser Samuel
Berger told reporters at the White House, referring to Milosevic.
``There have been some further burning of villages, further sweep
operations, some shelling into Albania, and it's obviously very
disturbing to us.''
</P>
<P>
   Berger and Clark both affirmed that U.S. information on the
ground situation in Kosovo was limited by the absence of 1,400
international monitors who left Kosovo over the weekend, as NATO
air strikes loomed.
</P>
<P>
   Yet another layer of information was stripped away on Thursday,
when Yugoslavia expelled all journalists from NATO countries and
severed diplomatic relations with the United States, France,
Germany and Britain, the lead nations in the continuing air
strikes.
</P>
<P>
   In Kosovo's provincial capital, Pristina, a CNN television news
crew was jumped by a half-dozen armed thugs, who smashed equipment,
set fire to one of their cars, slapped producer Alessio Vinci
across the face and jammed an assault rifle under the nose of
correspondent Brent Sadler.
</P>
<P>
   Serb troops arrived, established order and escorted a caravan
carrying remaining Western journalists to the Macedonia border.
</P>
<P>
   The Pentagon asserted that the escalation of Serb attacks on the
ground could result in increasingly aggressive air strikes
targeting the troops carrying out the repression in Kosovo and
their supplies.
</P>
<P>
   ``We are focusing on the very forces that are being used, and
assembled for use, against the Kosovar Albanians,'' Bacon told
reporters.
</P>
<P>
   Ethnic Albanians make up 90 percent of the 2.2 million people in
Kosovo, a province in southern Serbia, one of two states that,
along with Montenegro, that make up Yugoslavia.
</P>
<P>
   Milosevic stripped Kosovo of broad political autonomy in 1989,
and ethnic tensions gradually rose. A year ago, Albanian rebels
favoring independence began guerilla attacks against Serb security
forces, which responded with a brutal crackdown targeting villages
and civilians they identified as ``terrorists.''
</P>
<P>
   In the face of the escalating violence Thursday, Berger stressed
that NATO military support for the Kosovars remained confined to
air strikes. There is no plan to send ground troops into Kosovo
from the United States or any other NATO country, Berger said,
unless a peace agreement is reached between Serbs and Kosovar
Albanians.
</P>
<P>
   Even as the United States pushed ahead with the largest air
campaign to hit Europe since World War II, Secretary of State
Madeleine Albright insisted that Milosevic could end the onslaught
with a phone call and a will to embrace peace.
</P>
<P>
   ``Diplomatic channels remain open,'' said Albright, noting that
U.S. envoy Christopher Hill was standing by at the U.S. Embassy in
Macedonia. ``They know his number.''
</P>
<P>
   Far from reaching out for peace, however, Milosevic remained
defiant.
</P>
<P>
   ``There is no indication that there is any change at all in
Milosevic's position,'' Albright told reporters at the State
Department. ``He has not gotten the message yet.''
</P>
<P>
   Extending a potential face-saving opportunity to Milosevic,
Berger opened the possibility of renewed negotiations with
Milosevic over the terms of an internationally-backed peace accord.
</P>
<P>
   The accord, signed last week in France by representatives of the
Kosovar Albanians but so far rejected by Milosevic, calls for
sending a NATO peacekeeping force of 28,000 troops, 4,000 of them
American, into Kosovo.
</P>
<P>
   While the administration has insisted that it would not end the
bombing campaign unless Milosevic agrees to the NATO peacekeeping
force, Berger appeared to suggest that other aspects of the peace
treaty might be open to discussion.
</P>
<P>
   ``Any changes that would be made would have to be accepted by
the Kosovars,'' Berger told reporters at the White House. ``If
there were proposed changes in the agreement, that would be
something that the Kosovars would have to accept.''
</P>
<P>
   On Capitol Hill, Senate Foreign Relations Committee Chairman
Jesse Helms, R-N.C., said war and diplomacy should be backed with
legislation.
</P>
<P>
   He proposed the Serbia Democratization Act, which would
strengthen existing economic sanctions against the Milosevic
regime, boost humanitarian aid for his victims and promote
democratic opposition to replace his government.
</P>
<P>
   ``As for Mr. Milosevic's future, I don't care one way or the
other if he lives out his days in sunny Cyprus or if he will agree
to step aside and make way for democracy in Serbia,'' Helms said in
a speech on the Senate floor. ``The important thing is that he be
removed from power, whether voluntarily or not, and now.''
</P>
<P>
   ENDIT
</P>
<P>
