<SLUG> BC-HKN-RANGERS-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
THE RANGERS' DREARY SEASON IS BRIGHTENED BY NEDVED 
</HEADLINE>
   (bl)  
 By JOE LAPOINTE   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   FORT LAUDERDALE, Fla. _ In a disappointing season, with playoff
hopes fading, it is easy to overlook improvements and positive
changes on a team like the New York Rangers. Although they are in
danger of missing the tournament for the second consecutive season,
their biggest upgrade has been the addition of Petr Nedved, who
scored his 20th goal in a 2-1 victory over the Florida Panthers on
Wednesday night.
</P>
<P>
   Nedved's game-winner was a classic of his style: a rising wrist
shot from the right-wing circle, on the power play, that beat
goalie Sean Burke high on the glove side the way an arrow from a
bow might find a spot on a target.
</P>
<P>
   ``One heck of a shot,'' said Rangers coach John Muckler. ``He
threaded the eye of a needle.''
</P>
<P>
   In the Rangers' last 19 games, their front-line center has 10
goals and 10 assists. He plays more minutes than any other forward,
he takes hits in heavy traffic to make plays, and he seems to get
better with extra work.
</P>
<P>
   ``I think Petr's having a lot of fun,'' Muckler said. ``He's
really enjoying himself. He likes to play a lot. He thrives on it.
He's our face-off guy in our end zone. He takes every important
face-off. He's on the power play. He kills penalties. He's doing it
all.''
</P>
<P>
   Nedved also assisted when Adam Graves scored the first goal of
the victory, which moved the Rangers 1 point ahead of the Panthers
for ninth place. Going into Thursday night's games, the Rangers are
still 5 points behind Boston, which holds the eighth and final
playoff spot in the Eastern Conference.
</P>
<P>
   Against the Panthers, Nedved won 24 of 28 draws. ``I don't think
I've won that many in any game before,'' Nedved said, seeming
surprised at his success. ``It was one of those nights.''
</P>
<P>
   As for Muckler's assertion about his enjoyment level, Nedved
agreed. ``For sure,'' he said. ``The key, personally, for me is
when I have fun, most of the time, I play well and I'm having fun
and I'm playing lots.''
</P>
<P>
   Nedved, who also has 27 assists, missed last season in a
contract dispute with Pittsburgh, playing in Europe and in the
minor leagues. He came to the Rangers in a trade with the Penguins
along with defenseman Chris Tamer, who has earned a regular role on
the blue line.
</P>
<P>
   Also coming to the Rangers was Sean Pronger, who is no longer
with the team. In exchange, the Rangers sent Aleksei Kovalev, Harry
York and a substantial sum of money. Kovalev has 19 goals and 28
assists. It appears to be a trade that has helped both teams.
</P>
<P>
   SLAP SHOTS:
</P>
<P>
   _ The Rangers stayed in Florida for a day off Thursday with no
practice. They will travel to Philadelphia on Friday and practice
there in preparation for Saturday afternoon's game with the Flyers,
the last of a three-game road trip.
</P>
<P>
   _ John Muckler was amused that defenseman Rumun Ndur jousted
with Florida's Peter Worrell while play continued in Wednesday's
victory. ``Rumun's into the game,'' Muckler said. ``Standing at
center ice, he wants to start a fight with a three-on-two going the
other way.'' Had the Panthers scored, the coach might not have been
as amused.
</P>
<P>
   _ Last season, after 72 games, the Rangers were 22-33-17 for 61
points. This season, they are 30-32-10 for 70 points.
</P>
<P>
   _ Defenseman Brian Leetch, showing signs of fatigue, has not
scored in 20 games and has 3 goals in his last 46 games and 9 for
the season.
</P>
</TEXT>
