<HEADER>
A4373 &Cx1f; taf-z
u a &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-GAMMA-BURST-NYT &LR;      03-25 0839
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-GAMMA-BURST-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
SCIENTISTS TELL OF CAPTURING IMAGES OF GAMMA-RAY BURSTS
</HEADLINE>
  
 (ATTN: Calif., Mich.)   (rk) 
 By JOHN NOBLE WILFORD   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   Thousands of times more energetic than ordinary exploding stars,
their visible light as bright as a million galaxies, gamma-ray
bursts are the most violent events in the universe, and radiation
from one of these events reaches the vicinity of Earth at a rate of
about one a day.
</P>
<P>
   Yet not until last January were astronomers able to capture the
first images in visible light of a gamma-ray burst in progress.
Now, the first results from the observations are being reported in
the journals Science and Nature and are being described in
interviews.
</P>
<P>
   The findings include surprises and new clues, but still no
solution to one of the most vexing mysteries in astrophysics: What
is causing the cataclysmic events that produce these explosive
flashes?
</P>
<P>
   ``For most phenomena, quasars, supernovas or black holes, maybe
we have some notion of what they are,'' said Carl W. Akerlof, a
University of Michigan astrophysicist and an author of one of the
reports in Nature. ``A gamma-ray burst is the most mysterious thing
about which we still have so little information.''
</P>
<P>
   Astronomers recently learned that these bursts originated at
extragalactic distances, but they were surprised by how far away
was the source of this burst. In Friday's issue of Science, a team
led by Michael Andersen of the Nordic Optical Telescope in the
Canary Islands reported that an analysis of the visible light
showed that its source had a ``red shift'' of at least 1.6, the
equivalent to a distance of some nine billion light-years, or
two-thirds of the way across the universe.
</P>
<P>
   The farther away a cosmic object is, the greater its light is
shifted toward the red end of the spectrum.
</P>
<P>
   ``We were stunned,'' George Djorgovski, an astrophysicist at the
California Institute of Technology in Pasadena, said in a
statement. ``This was much further than we expected.''
</P>
<P>
   Anything that distant and also that luminous must be the result
of an explosion of unimaginable power. Other Caltech astronomers
said the event of Jan. 23, designated GRB 990123, was 10 times more
luminous than the brightest gamma-ray burst seen so far.
</P>
<P>
   This seemed to confirm earlier descriptions of the bursts as the
biggest explosion ever seen, second only to the Big Bang at the
theorized birth of the universe.
</P>
<P>
   This made it even harder to conceive of an explosion that would
have such power. ``If the gamma rays were emitted equally in all
directions,'' Djorgovski said of the events, ``their energy would
correspond to 10,000 times the energy emitted by our sun over its
entire lifetime so far, which is about five billion years. Yet the
burst lasted only a few tens of seconds.''
</P>
<P>
   Gamma-ray bursts have been known for three decades, but only in
recent years have spacecraft sensitive to gamma radiation been
studying them closely. Gamma rays do not penetrate Earth's
atmosphere.
</P>
<P>
   A systematic hunt for them began in 1991 with the launching of
the Compton Gamma Ray Observatory by the National Aeronautics and
Space Administration.
</P>
<P>
   Three years ago, the Italian-Dutch satellite BeppoSAX made it
possible to pinpoint the position of the bursts so that other
telescopes could quickly join in the observations.
</P>
<P>
   The power estimates of the bursts have until now been based on
an assumption that the energy is being emitted in equal intensity
in all directions, but some of the new findings cast doubt on that
assumption.
</P>
<P>
   Two observing teams, one led by Shrinivas Kulkarni of Caltech
and the other by Alberto Castro-Firado of the National Institute of
Astrophysics in Madrid, found evidence that the energy from the
burst was not being uniformly distributed but concentrated in a
beam. If correct, this would reduce power estimates of the bursts
to more imaginable, but still mind-boggling levels.
</P>
<P>
   Another team, led by Jens Hjorth of the University of
Copenhagen, reported observations suggesting that the radiation
burst had not passed through the magnetic field that would have
been associated with a fireball sending out energy in all
directions. They took this as possibly indirect evidence of beamed
radiation.
</P>
<P>
   Indeed, Akerlof of Michigan said that observations of the active
nuclei of some galaxies showed that nature does things like
beaming. The observations have revealed jets of high-energy matter
being ejected from the events. But scientists said it was too soon
to tell.
</P>
<P>
   As for what causes the bursts, the new findings have not changed
the possible explanations. One is that the bursts are the
consequence of a sudden collapse of a massive star into a rapidly
spinning black hole, which is a center of exceedingly powerful
gravity. Other possibilities include a collision between two
neutron stars orbiting each other or a collision of a neutron star
and a black hole. Neutron stars are the extremely dense remnants of
exploded stars.
</P>
</TEXT>
