<DATE_TIME> 1999-03-25 20:55 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A4377 &Cx1f; tad-z
u a &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-VOUCHERS26-COX     03-25 0903
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-VOUCHERS26-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Florida nears school vouchers
 &HT;    By Mike Williams
 &HT;    c.1999 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   TALLAHASSEE, Fla. _ Some parents love it. Many teachers hate it.
Academics can't seem to agree on whether or not it works.
</P>
<P>
   But Florida's Republican-dominated government is poised to adopt
the nation's first statewide program of school vouchers, which
would allow parents to use tax dollars to send their children to
private schools.
</P>
<P>
   In a mostly partisan vote, the Florida House approved a limited
voucher program Thursday in a 71-49 vote. Seven Republicans voted
against the plan, and six Democrats voted for it. The proposal
still must be considered by the Senate, where resistance is
expected to be stronger. However, Republicans also dominate the
Senate, 25-15.
</P>
<P>
   The voucher proposal, which would apply only to students at a
few underperforming schools at first, has sparked a whirlwind of
debate.
</P>
<P>
   ``This levels the playing field,'' said state Rep. Alex Diaz de
la Portilla (R-Miami), who is shepherding Gov. Jeb Bush's bill
through the Legislature's lower chamber. ``It gives inner-city kids
_ African-American and Hispanic kids _ the opportunity for the same
education that privileged children from the suburbs get.''
</P>
<P>
   Not so, say critics.
</P>
<P>
   ``School vouchers are wrong, wrong, wrong,'' said Democratic
Rep. Lois Frankel of West Palm Beach. ``They propose taking kids
from the poorest-performing schools in the state and washing our
hands of them. We're basically giving up on those kids.''
</P>
<P>
   Bush has made vouchers _ which he calls ``opportunity
scholarships'' _ the top priority of his young administration.
</P>
<P>
   Around the country, only the cities of Milwaukee and Cleveland
have adopted voucher programs, although support for vouchers has
appeared in a number of states, including Mississippi, Louisiana
and Texas, where Bush's brother, George W. Bush, is governor. In
Texas, a Senate committee on Wednesday endorsed a bill that would
create a voucher pilot program.
</P>
<P>
   A number of private foundations have also set up voucher
scholarship programs that allow kids from poor backgrounds in
cities such as New York and Miami to attend pricey private schools.
</P>
<P>
   Bush made vouchers a centerpiece of his campaign last fall, even
though polls run by his opponents in the state teachers union
showed a majority of Floridians are wary of letting public money
fund private classrooms.
</P>
<P>
   David Clark, spokesman for Florida Teaching Profession, a
National Education Association affiliate, argues that the program
will draw revenues out of already underfunded public schools.
</P>
<P>
   But Diaz de la Portilla counters, ``We're not taking money away
from the public schools. What we're doing is issuing them a
challenge: If you educate these children adequately, we will not
have any children leaving with opportunity scholarships.'' In its
first year, the program would apply only to four Florida schools
that are classified as ``failing'' under the state's current school
evaluation system. But that system is being tightened next year,
and officials say 169 schools would soon be rated as ``failing'' if
they don't make significant improvements.
</P>
<P>
   Students at the failing schools would be able to withdraw,
taking an estimated $4,000 in tax dollars with them to any school
they choose.
</P>
<P>
   Critics point out that the program as currently proposed has
almost no checks in place to assure parents that the private
schools they might choose are any better than the failing public
schools they want their children to escape. Bush's plan is opposed
by the leading Florida teachers group, the state PTA, the NAACP and
several other groups, including People for the American Way and the
American Civil Liberties Union, both of which have vowed to
challenge it in court.
</P>
<P>
   In Milwaukee, the first major school district in the country to
experiment with vouchers, the program has been in place for nearly
a decade. After starting with a handful of students, it has
mushroomed into a $28 million endeavor with 6,200 students getting
vouchers.
</P>
<P>
   Follow-up studies on the students shifting from public to
private schools have been inconclusive, with some studies claiming
significant improvement but others showing little.
</P>
<P>
   There have also been unforeseen consequences. Originally aimed
at helping low-income children who couldn't afford to escape bad
schools, the program is now paying tuition for 2,250 students who
were already enrolled in private schools. Those problems _ along
with questions about the constitutionality of giving public money
to private schools with religious affiliations _ convince critics
that vouchers are a bad idea.
</P>
<P>
   Bush and his allies, however, remain convinced the program will
be a lifesaver for ambitious kids stuck in bad schools, as well as
a powerful incentive for bad schools to improve.
</P>
<P>
   Bush points out that the scholarships are only one part of a
massive education reform initiative he is proposing, which includes
tougher standards for kids, schools and teachers, a longer
mandatory school year and some $600 million in new state spending
on schools.
</P>
<P>
   ``It is going to be exciting,'' Bush told reporters as he
unveiled his plan earlier this year. ``The education debate, if
it's done with civility, offers the chance for this state to lead
the nation.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
