<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-MOD-REVIEW26-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    `Mod Squad' flunks the retro test
 &HT;    By Alison Macor
 &HT;    c.1999 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   AUSTIN, Texas _ The first shot in ``The Mod Squad'' is a title
card explaining the definition of the word ``mod.''
</P>
<P>
   It is never a good sign when an action movie feels the need to
stake out its semantic territory.
</P>
<P>
   Capitalizing on the cyclical nature of fashion and trends,
director Scott Silver (``Johns'') attempts to upgrade the old
television series ``The Mod Squad'' for a '90s audience. Silver
assembles three of the hottest young actors working today, puts
them in a movie with a strong supporting cast and punishes them all
with horrendous dialogue and the most mundane of action plots.
</P>
<P>
   For five years in the late '60s and early '70s, the Aaron
Spelling-produced series brought us hip dialogue, trendy fashions
and Peggy Lipton. Part of what made the hour-long drama so
watchable was its visual style and youthful vibe. ``The Mod Squad''
introduced millions of suburban kids like myself to the underbelly
of Los Angeles (sanitized for television) through its three
principals who worked as an undercover unit for the LAPD in
exchange for clean criminal records.
</P>
<P>
   In the movie version, Silver keeps the basic premise and
constructs a flimsy storyline that attempts to flesh out the
individual characters while solving a case that involves police
corruption and drug trafficking. As narratives go, this script
isn't the worst ever written. But lines such as ``For starters,
we've got to find that guy with the leather pants'' don't lend a
whole lot of legitimacy to the movie or the characters who speak
the dialogue.
</P>
<P>
   Claire Danes plays Julie, the role originated by the enigmatic
Lipton. Danes, like her co-star Omar Epps (``Scream 2''), does her
best to infuse some life into the character. Mimicking Lipton's
low-key delivery, Danes brings a touch more humor and compassion to
the role. As Linc, the partner of few words originally played by
Clarence Williams III (who makes a cameo), Epps isn't given a whole
lot to do. As characters, however, he and Danes definitely
represent the cool members of the trio.
</P>
<P>
   The problem is Giovanni Ribisi, who plays their partner Pete
Cochran. Ribisi wins the Dustin Hoffman ``I'm Still in Character
From My Last Film'' award for his ability to channel his mentally
challenged character from ``The Other Sister.'' Perhaps we're
supposed to think that Pete hasn't kicked his drug habit quite yet,
but the effect is disconcerting and inexplicably comic.
</P>
<P>
   On a brighter note, cinematographer Ellen Kuras (``I Shot Andy
Warhol,'' ``Unzipped'') re-creates the visual flourishes common to
'70s television shows, right down to the obligatory slow-motion
shot of the trio rounding a street corner. With film stock and
postproduction visual effects, Kuras captures well the grainy,
hard-edged look of the original program.
</P>
<P>
   Unfortunately, Silver's ``The Mod Squad'' is not stylish enough
to be retro nor reflexive enough to work as camp. What we're left
with is a hollow, 90-minute advertisement for the film's
alternative-rock soundtrack and trendy wardrobe.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'm getting too old for this (expletive),'' Julie says toward
the end of the film, and her comment is meant to be ironic. But the
truth is, we're all a little too old for it.
</P>
<P>
   ``The Mod Squad''
</P>
<P>
   1 star
</P>
<P>
   Starring: Claire Danes, Omar Epps, Giovanni Ribisi
</P>
<P>
   Director: Scott Silver
</P>
<P>
   Screenwriters: Stephen Kay, Scott Silver, Kate Lanier
</P>
<P>
   MPAA rating: R for language, violence, some sexuality
</P>
<P>
   Running time: 1 hour, 30 minutes
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
