<HEADLINE>
RUSSIANS ATTACKS US EMBASSY AS ANTI-WESTERN FEELING HEATS UP
</HEADLINE>
  (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By DAVID FILIPOV  
 c.1999 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   MOSCOW _ In a day of growing tensions and anti-American
sentiment, angry demonstrators hurled bottles, eggs, and paint at
the US Embassy here Thursday, and Russian leaders condemned NATO
airstrikes against Yugoslavia as proof of Washington's desire for
world domination.
</P>
<P>
   President Boris N. Yeltsin and other senior officials talked
tough but, keenly aware of their country's need for financial aid
from the West, avoided making direct threats of military help for
Yugoslavia that would further isolate Russia.
</P>
<P>
   Analysts said to expect a rise in the anti-Western mood here as
young men signed up to oppose NATO forces alongside the Serbs, who
are Orthodox Slavs like most Russians. Volunteers signed up at
protests held outside the US Embassy in Moscow and US consulates in
St. Petersburg and Vladivostok.
</P>
<P>
   Yeltsin, who on Wednesday night suspended Moscow's relations
with the North Atlantic Treaty Organization, Thursday called the
airstrikes ``a crude mistake of American policy.'' He indicated the
Kremlin had considered using force, but, despite pressure from the
pro-Communist majority in Parliament, had decided not to retaliate.
</P>
<P>
   ``Russia has a number of extreme measures in store, but we
decided not to use them so far,'' Yeltsin said in his Kremlin
office. ``Morally, we are above America.''
</P>
<P>
   Gennady Seleznyov, the Communist speaker of the State Duma, said
in Colombia that Russia would unilaterally pull out of a United
Nations embargo and begin supplying Yugoslavia with weapons, such
as advanced S-300 anti-aircraft missiles, and technical assistance.
</P>
<P>
   But Prime Minister Yevgeny Primakov, who still hopes to win
billions of dollars in loans from the International Monetary Fund
and plans to meet IMF Executive Director Michel Camdessus in Moscow
on Sunday, was more circumspect.
</P>
<P>
   Asked if Russia might lift the arms embargo, Primakov told a
television interviewer: ``I would not rule out anything.''
</P>
<P>
   ``We have different responses at our disposal. Regarding
military potential, our country is second to no one,'' Primakov
said, in an allusion to Russia's 7,000 nuclear weapons. ``But we
aren't taking those steps.''
</P>
<P>
   He also told Russian television that Moscow would maintain ties
with the West, continue market overhaul and not seek a policy of
isolation. As proof, Russia's Foreign Ministry Thursday said Moscow
had signed bilateral agreements on energy, trade, and security with
the United States.
</P>
<P>
   ``Yevgeny Maksimovich (Primakov) knows perfectly well that
cutting oneself off from the West . . . will first of all hurt
Russia,'' commented the daily Moskovsky Komsomolets.
</P>
<P>
   But commentators nonetheless said to expect a downturn in
US-Russia relations, as politicians here take advantage of
disenchantment with the West and hurt pride over the way Moscow,
once a superpower to be reckoned with, is now ignored.
</P>
<P>
   ``In the long run, (the NATO bombings) will mean further changes
in the domestic political climate in Russia, a growth of
anti-Americanism and anti-Western moods,'' said analyst Yekaterina
Stepanova of the Carnegie-Moscow Center. ``This is more important
than any measures that are taken now.''
</P>
<P>
   A glimpse of what that could mean was offered outside the US
Embassy. Crowds there burned a US flag, shouted anti-American
slogans, and threw paint and beer bottles at the embassy building,
shattering several windows and covering part of the wall with
multicolored splats. Riot police kept the protesters from rushing
to the entrance of the building and detained anyone caught throwing
bottles, but, in a departure from their usual practice, let the
unsanctioned rally go on all day and into the night.
</P>
<P>
   ``Serbia, Serbia, Yankee go home,'' cried the crowd. ``America
is a pisspot. Russia will be victorious.''
</P>
<P>
   Riot police broke up the demonstration Thursday &UR;  &LR; night.
</P>
<P>
   People in cars going by honked their horns and gestured their
approval to the crowd, which never got much smaller than 1,000
protesters as new protesters replaced those who had drifted away.
Soldiers in a police transport truck waved happily to the crowd, as
a riot police lieutenant grinned in approval. Some of the
demonstrators were the usual pensioners waving red flags often seen
at Moscow street protests, but many appeared to be college
students.
</P>
<P>
   ``We are against NATO's bombardment because we believe in
democratic ideals and a nation's right to self-determination,''
said Vitaly, a math student at Moscow State University. ``The
United States is violating that by leading the bombardment of a
sovereign state.''
</P>
<P>
   Russian Foreign Minister Igor Ivanov voiced a similar sentiment.
</P>
<P>
   ``Whatever reasons American strategists offer to justify their
actions, their true aims are clear _ to impose the political,
military, and economic dictatorship of the United States,'' Ivanov
said.
</P>
</TEXT>
