<SLUG> BC-MORGAN-STANLEY-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
MORGAN STANLEY REPORTS EXPLOSIVE EARNINGS GROWTH FOR QUARTER 
</HEADLINE>
   (bl)  
 By JOSEPH KAHN   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEW YORK _ Most Wall Street firms are enjoying the robust
profits that come hand-in-hand with a strong stock market, but
Morgan Stanley Dean Witter is enjoying the ride more than most.
</P>
<P>
   The securities firm blew past estimates of how much it would
earn in its fiscal first quarter, reporting that operating profits
increased half again over those for the comparable period of 1997.
That profit growth, rare for any established finance company, is
three to four times the pace that rivals Goldman, Sachs and Lehman
Brothers reported earlier this month.
</P>
<P>
   The profit growth helps solidify Morgan Stanley's status as the
earnings leader among securities firms, coming after a year in
which it breezed through stormy markets that caused several
competitors to post big losses.
</P>
<P>
   ``They are just knocking the cover off the ball,'' said Joan
Solotar, who follows Morgan Stanley at Donaldson, Lufkin &AMP;
Jenrette. ``The results appear to be strong across the board, with
records in quite a few areas.''
</P>
<P>
   Net profits from operations were $1.04 billion for the
three-month period ending Feb. 28, the firm reported. That was up
from a not-too-shabby $690 million in the the same period of 1997.
Earnings per fully diluted share increased to $1.76 from $1.10,
three times as fast as consensus estimates of Wall Street analysts.
Investors poured money in Morgan Stanley shares Thursday, pushing
the stock price up 5.59 percent to an all-time high closing price
of $103.875.
</P>
<P>
   Morgan's return on equity, one way to judge its profitability,
rose to 29 percent in the first quarter from 20 percent a year ago.
Other big Wall Street firms consider 20 percent as exceptionally
good.
</P>
<P>
   ``I don't expect that anyone else will beat that number,'' Ms.
Solotar said of Morgan's return on equity figure. But she added,
``I doubt it's sustainable at that level for more than a quarter or
two.''
</P>
<P>
   Tempering analysts' enthusiasm for the performance was the sense
that a hefty chunk of Morgan's profit growth came from trading,
which, to put it mildly, does not always produce a steady earnings
stream. Record revenue from trading stocks, bonds, commodities and
foreign exchange led a 55 percent gain in operating profits at
Morgan's securities division, its largest.
</P>
<P>
   The firm's fiscal first quarter included the month of December,
when markets staged a rapid recovery from the turmoil that followed
Russia's financial collapse. That suggests that Morgan benefited
from what would appear to be a one-time rebound in securities
prices, especially bonds.
</P>
<P>
   But every other Wall Street firm had the potential to benefit
from the same rebound, and many did not ride as high on the wave.
One reason: Morgan did not panic when bond prices plunged in the
fall. Analysts said the firm had a smaller bond inventory relative
to its capital than Goldman or another top rival, Merrill Lynch &AMP;
Co. And Morgan did not sell as much of its inventory when prices
were sinking.
</P>
<P>
   So, when the bond market recovered, Morgan benefited more from
the rebound.
</P>
<P>
   ``That's a hypothesis, but it has some logic to it,'' said
Robert Scott, Morgan's chief financial officer. ``It's fair to say
that our trading benefited from a much healthier environment than
we had in the quarter before.''
</P>
<P>
   He stressed, however, that trading gains were widespread _ not
just in the volatile bond market. Moreover, Morgan posted profit
growth in the final period of last year, when Goldman and Merrill
saw earnings fall, meaning that it did not suffer
disproportionately then only to recover more strongly now.
</P>
<P>
   ``I don't think you can explain away the result by saying it was
just a rebound after a bad period,'' he said. ``We did better than
everyone else in the fourth quarter as well.''
</P>
<P>
   Some outside analysts agreed. ``You had a combination of lots of
good things, not just a rebound in fixed income,'' said Richard
Strauss of Goldman. ``They are being driven by great results in
investment banking as well as trading.''
</P>
<P>
   Indeed, many other parts of Morgan's securities business posted
gains, if not as sharp as trading. Revenues from underwriting new
securities issues and advising companies on mergers and
acquisitions gained a healthy 20 percent to $957 million, a record.
Commissions earned on securities transactions for customers grew to
$655 million, up 22 percent.
</P>
<P>
   Morgan's market share in those key businesses seems to be on the
rise. It ranked No. 1 in stock underwriting for the first two
months of the year, one of the most lucrative Wall Street
businesses. It also earned record fees from its merger and
acquisitions business.
</P>
<P>
   The firm's merchant banking operation contributed heavily to its
bottom line for the quarter, with investment gains of $194 million
compared with $59 million a year ago. This was largely because it
sold part of its stake in Equant NV, a data communications company.
</P>
<P>
   The other major legs of Morgan's financial stool, money
management and credit cards, posted steady gains. Net revenue from
asset management rose 23 percent, to $712 million, with profits
from that division growing at twice that pace to hit $147 million.
</P>
<P>
   Morgan's credit card business _ the firm backs the Discover card
_ grew at a slower rate, with revenue increasing 16 percent and
profits up 36 percent, in part from a one-time asset sale.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
