<DATE_TIME> 1999-03-25 21:09 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A4393 &Cx1f; taf-z
u s &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-BBA-YANKS-STRAWBERRY-     03-25 0817
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BBA-YANKS-STRAWBERRY-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
STRAWBERRY GETS A LOOK IN LEFT FIELD  
(DW)
</HEADLINE>
  
 (ATTN: Ore., Texas, Mich., Calif. )   By BUSTER OLNEY   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   LAKELAND, Fla. _ Darryl Strawberry has caught hundreds of
thousands of fly balls in his lifetime, from his days at Crenshaw
High School in Los Angeles to his nights at Shea Stadium and Yankee
Stadium. Yet Thursday night, perhaps a dozen Yankees' evaluators,
including the owner George Steinbrenner, closely watched his
pursuit of every ball hit his way.
</P>
<P>
   Strawberry, 37, started in left field against Detroit, his first
appearance in the outfield of the spring, his first action in the
field since his treatment for colon cancer last fall. Strawberry
did not get a real chance in the first inning, moving in to pick up
a bloop hit, but the real action came when Steinbrenner and those
in the Yankee dugout screamed loudly at Durwood Merrill, the plate
umpire, drawing the ump's rebuke.
</P>
<P>
   Strawberry is trying to prove he is ready to be part of the
Yankees' opening-day roster, and to that end, the interim manager,
Don Zimmer, said Strawberry already has proved he can hit.
</P>
<P>
   ``He can still swing the bat, there's no doubt about that,''
Zimmer said. ``He's still got power, there's no doubt about that.''
</P>
<P>
   But the Yankees already have a designated hitter, Chili Davis,
who is having a great spring, and three left fielders, in Shane
Spencer, Chad Curtis and Ricky Ledee.
</P>
<P>
   Strawberry's best chance for making the Yankees, seemingly a
slim chance at that, is if he shows he can be adequate in left
field and hit better than Ledee, who has had a disappointing spring
training.
</P>
<P>
   Jose Cardenal, the Yankees' first-base and outfield coach, has
been hitting fungoes to Strawberry in the last few days. ``He
doesn't look any different than he has the last couple of years,''
Cardenal said. ``Whatever is hit to him, he's going to catch.''
</P>
<P>
   Sometimes Strawberry looks good going after fly balls, Cardenal
said, ``and another day, he probably doesn't feel too good.''
</P>
<P>
   Cardenal is astounded that Strawberry even has a chance to come
back following his treatment last fall. ``When I saw him at the
parade after the World Series,'' Cardenal said, ``I almost cried.
To see a big dude like him, and then to see him after the surgery
moving so slowly and so thin. . . .
</P>
<P>
   ``Now, that's the same old Straw. He's amazing. To come from a
cancer operation like he has, you have to give him some credit.''
</P>
<P>
   A significant hurdle remains even if Strawberry shows he can
play the outfield. Strawberry is to be paid $2.5 million this
season, and if the Yankees add him to their roster, the majors will
assess them $833,333. Whether that keeps Strawberry off the team
remains to be seen.
</P>
<P>
   Two Left-Handed Relievers Try Out
</P>
<P>
   Since trading Graeme Lloyd in the deal for Roger Clemens, the
Yankees have sought left-handed relievers. One arrived Thursday _
Trevor Wilson, formerly of the Anaheim Angels and San Francisco
Giants _ and another will arrive Friday, Tony Fossas. The Yankees
signed Fossas, 41, to a minor league contract, but he has no desire
to pitch in the minors. He will try out for the Yankees over the
last 10 days of spring training, and if he is good enough, the
Yankees will keep him, at a salary of $410,000.
</P>
<P>
   Fossas began spring training with the Texas Rangers but was
released Wednesday. Doug Melvin, the Rangers' general manager, told
Brian Cashman, the Yankees' general manager, that Fossas is still
good enough to be a specialist against left-handed batters but that
the Rangers needed a reliever who could throw a couple of innings
at a time.
</P>
<P>
   Wilson, 32, threw in the bullpen Thursday for the first time,
little more than a week after the Giants cut him. Some scouts
believe Wilson has lost arm speed and can't be effective, but
Wilson said that he felt great and was excited about pitching with
the Yankees. When Wilson was released, it never occurred to him
that the Yankees might have an opening. ``It surprised me,'' Wilson
said. ``I didn't think they needed anything.''
</P>
<P>
   Wilson has a connection with Scott Brosius, the Yankees' third
baseman: when they were high school players in Oregon, Wilson
crushed a home run off Brosius. ``A bomb,'' said Brosius, a former
pitcher for the Rex Putnam Kingsmen, who carries a distinct mental
image of the pitch he threw _ ``fastball'' _ and where it landed.
Wilson played for the Oregon City Pioneers.
</P>
<P>
   Another left-hander, Andy Pettitte, threw 32 pitches in batting
practice, the first time he has faced hitters of any kind since
straining his elbow March 7. Pettitte probably will begin the year
on the disabled list, because the Yankees will not require a fifth
starter until April 17. Until then, Roger Clemens, Orlando
Hernandez, Hideki Irabu and Roger Clemens will take all the starts,
with a liberal sprinkling of off days.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
