<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-NATO-TROOPS-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
AS NATO'S FUNCTION CHANGES, SOLDIERS FEEL THE CONSEQUENCES
</HEADLINE>
  (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By KEVIN CULLEN  
 c.1999 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   SKOPJE, Macedonia _ The grunts in NATO's army woke up to a new
dawn Thursday after the world's biggest military alliance went from
being a defensive organization to one capable of attacking a
country that defies the alliance's political leaders.
</P>
<P>
   Just a week shy of its 50th anniversary, NATO's mission was
dramatically reshaped when its ships and planes launched cruise
missiles and bombs to punish Yugoslav President Slobodan
Milosevic's defiance of Western demands to end the fighting in
Kosovo.
</P>
<P>
   Literally overnight, the perception of NATO changed, too, and
the alliance's foot soldiers here were among the first to feel the
consequences.
</P>
<P>
   ``Death to NATO!'' an enraged Serbian man shouted in English
Thursday as several thousand people surrounded the US Embassy in
Skopje, hurling epithets and rocks. Their anger seemed directed at
Americans as much as at NATO. One man carried a sign that said, in
Serbian, ``NATO equals AIDS.''
</P>
<P>
   What began as a crowd of a few dozen on Thursday afternoon
mushroomed to thousands by nightfall. Some tore down the
wrought-iron fence around the grounds. The Macedonian authorities
appeared to be caught off guard, calling in riot police only after
the crowd had swelled and had begun throwing rocks.
</P>
<P>
   Later, a US Embassy spokesman, Philip Reeker, described the
crowd as ``the usual embassy protest.'' A few hours later, as the
mob outside bayed for blood, Reeker said NATO troops were being
called in to rescue the embassy staff, which had huddled in the
basement during the assault.
</P>
<P>
   At least one protester got onto the grounds and, according to a
local police officer, used a Molotov cocktail to set a car on fire
in the parking lot. All the embassy's reinforced windows were
shattered.
</P>
<P>
   The ethnic mix in Macedonia means that the thousands of ethnic
Albanian refugees who have streamed across the border from Kosovo
in recent days are assured a welcome from the estimated 500,000 of
their ethnic counterparts who make their homes here. But there is
also a sizable Serbian community and a deep reservoir of sympathy
for the Serbs among Macedonians, who share their Slavic identity.
That point was made loudly and forcefully Thursday by those who
trashed the US Embassy.
</P>
<P>
   Earlier in the day, Serb sympathizers stoned a NATO vehicle,
causing minor injuries to two soldiers, said Major Jan Joosten, a
NATO officer.
</P>
<P>
   Joosten, who is Dutch, spent much of the last week assuring
Macedonians that NATO was not planning to use their country as a
launching pad for attacks against Serbs dug in across the border in
Kosovo. But, he added, ``We have the right of self-defense in
accordance with international law and will exercise that right if
required.''
</P>
<P>
   But if the new reality unsettled NATO soldiers, they were not
showing it as they went about the day-to-day work of soldiering,
digging in along the Macedonia-Kosovo border within shooting
distance of Serb forces.
</P>
<P>
   In Petrovac, about 15 miles outside Skopje, British, French,
Italian, Dutch and, for the first time since World War II, German
soldiers prepared for a potential Serb retaliatory attack on the
NATO troops.
</P>
<P>
   Captain Wayne Hennessy-Barrett, of the King's Own Border
Regiment of the British Army, downplayed suggestions that NATO's
essence had changed overnight.
</P>
<P>
   ``We are not here to invade Kosovo,'' he said, surveying a large
field near the military airstrip at Petrovac. ``We're here to
implement a peace agreement.''
</P>
<P>
   Hennessy-Barrett, wearing a helmet and body armor that he said
was a standard precaution, said the local population had been
mostly friendly, and he did not expect that to change.
</P>
<P>
   He dismissed the stoning of the NATO vehicle, saying, ``We get
stoned in England. That doesn't mean anything.''
</P>
<P>
   But Hennessy-Barrett turned deadly serious when asked how he
felt about Serb reports of civilians being killed in the NATO
airstrikes.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's distasteful,'' he said. ``It's extremely sad. We don't go
into this hype and jingoism when people are being killed. We're
soldiers, but we have wives and kids. There is nothing remotely
cool or glamorous about war. Any professional soldier will tell you
that. But we didn't start this conflict.''
</P>
<P>
   Captain Nigel Francis-McGann, a British officer, rejected the
assertion that NATO's bombing amounted to offensive actions.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's like what they say in American football, the best offense
is a good defense,'' he said of the airstrikes. ``I see what we're
doing as defensive. You can say what we're doing has killed people.
I know, and all these soldiers here know, that what we're doing is
going to save the lives of thousands of people. There are no easy
choices here.''
</P>
<P>
   As he peered out toward the border where Serb forces are dug in,
Corporal Darren Szymanski of the King's Own Border Regiment, manned
a laser range finder that can locate instantaneously any artillery
fired by the Serbs. Szymanski, 24, said the Serbs would be
foolhardy to do so.
</P>
<P>
   ``I think it's highly unlikely they'll attack us, but if they
do, we're ready,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   Szymanski said there was no reaction among the soldiers who
watched television with him Wednesday night as Yugoslav authorities
reported that 10 Serb civilians had been killed in the initial
bombing raids. Neither was there any great debate among the grunts
about the changing role of NATO.
</P>
<P>
   ``We've been expecting it,'' he said of the airstrikes.
``Otherwise, we'd be here for no reason.''
</P>
<P>
   On the border, Yugoslav troops could be seen walking on the
ridge of a mountain, in silhouette, as the sun went down.
Presumably, they are there for a reason, too.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
