<HEADER>
A4400 &Cx1f; taf-z
u s &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-BBO-CUBA-BASEBALL-2TA     03-25 1122
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BBO-CUBA-BASEBALL-2TAKES-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
CLASH OF CULTURES, PRIDE AND PASSION WHEN CUBA PLAYS UNITED
STATES 
</HEADLINE>
   (af)  
 By JAMES C. McKINLEY Jr.   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   HAVANA _ The 16-year-old boy in a New York Yankees cap lingered
outside the field at the Provincial Academy of Baseball here,
watching quietly with intense eyes as older players went through
batting practice.
</P>
<P>
   The boy, Geovani Poei, has attended special baseball schools
since he was 7, and this summer he will face a grueling tryout for
a slot at the academy, another rung on the long ladder toward the
Cuban national team. He already thinks and talks like a
professional ballplayer _ he is quick, for instance, to say he was
rated the fourth-best shortstop for his age in the nation.
</P>
<P>
   But if Poei embodies the government's aggressive Soviet-era
program to cultivate young talent, he is also emblematic of the
Cuban people's stubborn love for baseball, a passion that seems to
transcend politics.
</P>
<P>
   Poei said he worships major league players in the United States,
even though his only contact with professional baseball has been
through the newspapers or when he got to watch a bootleg tape of a
playoff game that a friend smuggled into the country.
</P>
<P>
   ``I want to see them with my own eyes,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   On Sunday he just might, for the Baltimore Orioles are coming to
Havana's Latinoamericano Stadium to play an exhibition game against
a team of Cuban all-stars.
</P>
<P>
   For the first time since the Cuban Revolution isolated this
nation of baseball lovers from the United States 40 years ago,
players at all levels and their fans are anticipating a game many
think will at last test Cuba's baseball prowess against some of the
best players in the world.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's a long time the Cubans have been waiting for this game,''
said Rafael Borges, 70, a retired musician. ``Because we like
quality baseball.''
</P>
<P>
   Despite decades of hostile relations between Fidel Castro's
Communist government and the United States, Sunday's exhibition
game has failed to stir up much nationalist sentiment here.
Instead, it has tapped feelings that many Cubans say run deeper
through their culture than Marxist ideology.
</P>
<P>
   Most Cubans, after all, consider baseball to be their national
sport, a game entwined in history with their struggle for
independence from Spain and the birth of their nation. Nearly
everyone here plays baseball starting at a young age, and talking
about the game is considered almost a patriotic duty.
</P>
<P>
   Through years of economic hardship and political repression, it
always has been a source of solace that the Cuban national team
dominated baseball in the Olympics and in other international
amateur tournaments.
</P>
<P>
   In recent years, however, baseball has engendered other feelings
of jealousy and uncertainty as several top players have defected to
the United States to make fortunes on professional teams there _
Orlando Hernandez of the Yankees and Rey Ordonez of the Mets, for
example. And for the first time, the Cuban national team, its
strength sapped by defectors and the loss of other players who have
gone to play in Japan and elsewhere, has faltered in some recent
international competitions.
</P>
<P>
   Against this backdrop, the game against the Orioles _ the
government has announced that the 55,000 expected to attend the
game, including some young players, will be by formal invitation
only _ has set off fierce debates among fans, who gather each
afternoon on street corners, in cafes and under the tall trees in
the Central Parque to argue over the intricacies of baseball.
</P>
<P>
   A constant theme runs through the talk: No matter how well
Cubans have fared against amateurs, the best players here have
never had a chance to compete against the professionals in the
United States, thus leaving many Cuban baseball lovers frustrated
and wondering just how good their players are.
</P>
<P>
   ``We have a lot of talent here but it's not developed or
matured,'' said Ariel Almeares, 31, a tour guide. ``The Cubans need
to compete against better teams to get better.''
</P>
<P>
   On the streets of Havana, it is not hard to see why Cubans are
among the best players in the world. Children use almost every
empty space to play the game _ empty streets, public monuments,
parking lots. Most use homemade bats and balls created from scratch
with a bit of cork or stone wrapped with medical tape. Only a few
have gloves.
</P>
<P>
   But even in the lowliest sandlot games, the level of play is
impressive. Watching a group of boys who gathered on a recent
afternoon to play a pickup game in Antonio Maceo Park, beneath a
massive monument to a revolutionary hero, nearly all the boys had
smooth, level swings and could make fluid, accurate throws on the
run. Even the younger children knew how to turn double plays.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's in our blood,'' Alexander Fajardo, 14, said. ``It's the
national sport.''
</P>
<P>
   Very few of the stars on the top teams in Cuba, however, come up
from the streets. Soon after Castro abolished professional sports
in 1961, the Cuban government instituted a Soviet-style system of
academies for children with athletic ability intended to cultivate
Olympic athletes.
</P>
<P>
   Grade school teachers and coaches spot children with baseball
talent early and begin to channel the most talented at the age of 7
up through a series of academies where they receive intense sports
training for half the day and study regular subjects in the
afternoon.
</P>
<P>
   By the time players finally reach the age of 22, they have
either been eliminated or they have earned a spot on what is known
as the national series, the Cuban equivalent of the major leagues.
Each province has a team on that level drawn from its geographical
area, supplied with talented athletes trained in the academies.
</P>
<P>
   ``The talent develops because they have the Soviet system,''
said Roberto Gonzalez Echevarria, a Yale professor who recently
published ``Pride of Havana: A History of Cuban Baseball.'' ``It's
a kind of funnel of success that leads to the major teams and the
national team.''
</P>
<P>
   Though they are called amateurs, the players at the national
level are professionals for all intents and purposes. They receive
salaries for no-show jobs as physical therapists. The stars among
them also receive cars, nice apartments and other benefits as gifts
from a grateful state. Most important, however, they are treated
like royalty by the population.
</P>
<P>
   ``They don't pay them for this,'' said Juan Brito, 46, a taxi
driver, ``but they don't work for anyone else.''
</P>
<P>
   For some veterans who have reached the top of the Cuban system,
the game with the Orioles promises to be a bittersweet exercise in
what might have been if the political climate were different.
</P>
<P>
   nn
</P>
<P>
   ``We have to meet with a team of this quality to test
ourselves,'' said the Industriales second-baseman, Juan Padilla,
33, who hit .322 this year. ``They have great players. But here we
also have great players.''
</P>
<P>
   The players on the Havana Industriales in recent years have seen
their colleagues defect to the United States and become
millionaires in the big leagues, while they continue to earn less
than $20 a month. Both Hernandez and Ordonez played for the
Industriales.
</P>
<P>
   German Mesa, considered the best shortstop in Cuba, was
suspended for two years after he was accused of talking with agents
in the United States about the possibility of playing for a
professional team. He was only recently reinstated, and it remains
to be seen if the government will permit him to travel abroad
again.
</P>
<P>
   An agile fielder and a consistent hitter, he has been a star on
the national team for years, consistently beating out Ordonez, who
despite his mediocre batting is making $1.65 million this year.
</P>
<P>
   Still, when asked in public if he feels any regrets, Mesa said
that he is content with his lot in Cuba. ``Everyone has to make his
own decision,'' he said before a playoff game Wednesday night. ``I
play for the love of the people, for the warmth of the Cubans.''
</P>
<P>
   That legendary spirit of the Cuban fans was very much in
evidence later that night at the semifinal playoff game between the
Industriales and Isla de la Juventud. It was the final and deciding
game of a four-of-seven-game series, and the winner would go on to
play Santiago de Cuba for the championship in Havana.
</P>
<P>
   A playoff game in Havana is like a carnival. An hour before the
game started Wednesday, fans began filling the 50,000-seat
Latinoamericano Stadium, packing its old-fashioned bleachers to the
rafters. The fans paid three pesos, less than 50 cents, to enter.
But it was a blood-roar that rose from the faded stadium when the
Industriales loaded the bases in bottom of the first inning and
rattled Isla's right-hander, Carlos Yanes.
</P>
<P>
   Ricardo Rojas, 39, a civil servant, watched the game with his
7-year-old son, Ricardo Jr., on his lap, because he could not
afford two seats. He held the boy up to see the game, which the
Industriales won, 3-2.
</P>
<P>
   ``The Orioles are a curiosity, but this is what matters,'' he
said. ``My father brought me here the same way I am bringing him.''
</P>
<P>
   Perhaps nothing underlines the game's enduring power here more
than the informal gatherings of fans on the streets and in the
central park, known as hot corners or tertulias. There, the
frustration of living in a tightly controlled dictatorship, where
political speech is censured, is relieved when fans begin to argue
about baseball.
</P>
<P>
   On the hot corners, one can find Yankees fans, Braves fans,
Marlins fans, all desperate for information about their teams. Men
argue about the relative merits of Mike Mussina and Roger Clemens,
whom they have never seen pitch. They have gleaned what they can,
they said, from scratchy radio broadcasts out of Miami, and from
newspapers and bootlegged tapes of games brought in to the country
by relatives. When they can, they loiter in hotel bars to catch a
major league game on ESPN.
</P>
<P>
   Some fans here also worry about what is seen as a slight decline
in the quality of baseball here since the collapse of the Soviet
Union sent the Cuban economy into a spiral. Since 1991, more than
30 top players have defected to seek fortunes in the United States,
draining the baseball program of some important talents.
</P>
<P>
   Morale among players also suffered two years ago, when, for the
first time, the national team failed to win important tournaments
in Japan and Spain, losing by humiliating scores like 11-2 and
16-6. The crisis plunged Cuban baseball into a funk and prompted a
purge of government officials who have run the sport for decades.
</P>
<P>
   Since then, things have improved somewhat, fans said. The
government has been taking better care economically of its baseball
stars, and the new minister of sports, Humberto Rodriguez, has
reinvigorated the game, in part by demanding that the top players
requalify for their teams annually.
</P>
<P>
   ``We have many people here who have the talent to get to the big
leagues, but the politics won't let them get there,'' said Salvador
Aguilar, a team official for the Industriales.
</P>
<P>
   As the sun began to set in Central Park on Tuesday evening over
the statue of Jose Marti, Cuba's national hero, a towering older
man wearing a frayed shirt was defending his argument that the
Cubans would win the exhibition game. The surrounding skeptics
descended on him like wolves around a wounded buck.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'm telling you the Cuban team will get at least a tie,'' he
screamed. ``You say it's the big leagues. The top. But it could be
a good game.''
</P>
<P>
   Another fan, a tall balding man, butted in, face to face with
the defender of Cuba's team.
</P>
<P>
   ``Are you crazy?'' he yelled. ``They are better than us. They
have better quality players. I am as Cuban as you are. I am as
Fidelista as you are. But tell me, when did Cuba ever play against
a team made up of the best players from Japan? Or from the United
States? Tell me when? When?''
</P>
<P>
   The tall man could not answer. The answer, though, will come, at
least in part, on Sunday.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
