<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-DIABETES-DRUG-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
DRUG INDUSTRY MONITORS FDA REVIEW OF REZULIN 
</HEADLINE>
  (ART ADV: A graphic is being sent to NYT graphic clients.
Non-subscribers can make individual purchase by calling
888-603-1036 or 888-346-9867.) 
(DW) 
 By DAVID J. MORROW   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   The market for oral diabetes drugs will soon become more
competitive _ but just how competitive may depend on what action
regulators take on a popular diabetes pill that has been linked to
28 deaths and seven liver transplants.
</P>
<P>
   Warner-Lambert Co., the maker of the pill, Rezulin, will defend
the drug Friday before an advisory committee for the Food and Drug
Administration. The review is being closely watched by
pharmaceutical executives, who are waiting to see if the Rezulin's
problems will put the brakes on Warner-Lambert's sizzling
performance.
</P>
<P>
   The FDA is unlikely to pull Rezulin from the market, analysts
say. But if the agency adds new cautions to its label, as expected,
that could slow a powerful force in Warner-Lambert's sales growth.
Rezulin achieved $748 million in sales in 1998.
</P>
<P>
   Last year, Warner-Lambert posted a 44 percent rise in earnings _
well ahead of the industry average gain of 16 percent. Executives
of rival drug companies have been so frustrated in trying to keep
up with Warner-Lambert, that there has been speculation in the
industry that some have rescheduled the release dates of quarterly
earnings to avoid comparisons with Warner-Lambert, a company once
known primarily as the maker of Dentyne chewing gum.
</P>
<P>
   Its stock price hit a recent high of $81.25 in November, but it
has slumped in recent months, as many investors grew concerned
about the impact of Rezulin's problems. It closed Thursday at
$69.34375.
</P>
<P>
   But even if the FDA puts new restrictions on Rezulin, several
analysts believe that Warner-Lambert will have new products in the
next two or three years to make up for any decline in sales of the
popular diabetes drug. The company should be able to propel its
existing brands to new highs, they say. Sales of Lipitor,
Warner-Lambert's cholesterol-reducing agent, are projected to swell
to $6.3 billion by 2002 from $2.185 billion last year, making it
the world's best-selling drug.
</P>
<P>
   ``The patients who are on Rezulin, and who already safely
tolerate it, will more than likely stay there,'' said Neil Sweig,
an analyst with Southeast Research Partners. ``But the company does
have other compounds. Right now, the market does not fully
understand Warner-Lambert. But soon it will.''
</P>
<P>
   Doctors liked Rezulin when it was introduced in 1997 because it
was a new class of drug that resensitized body tissue to insulin
instead of inhibiting the liver's production of sugar. Doctors said
both processes were generally effective but Rezulin tended to work
where it was most needed.
</P>
<P>
   ``Rezulin has a unique method of action,'' said Dr. Leonid
Poretsky, director of the diabetes center at the Sanford I. Weill
Medical College of Cornell University in Manhattan. ``It works
primarily in the muscle, where most of the insulin is used up.''
</P>
<P>
   In November 1997, Rezulin's label was changed to reflect the
possibility that it could cause liver damage. The label now
recommended that patients using the drug have periodic blood tests
to monitor liver enzymes. One month later, Glaxo-Wellcome PLC.
halted the sales of Rezulin's British equivalent, causing
Warner-Lambert's stock to plunge 18.5 percent in one day.
</P>
<P>
   While Rezulin was billed as a revolutionary treatment, the drug
never surpassed the Bristol-Myers Squibb Co.'s Glucophage, the
nation's leading oral diabetic pill. Even though Glucophage was
associated with 20 deaths during its first million uses, according
to the FDA, the pill had been used safely for many years and did
not cause liver damage. Poretsky said he used Glucophage first and
added Rezulin only when the drug did not work.
</P>
<P>
   Aside from safety questions, Rezulin is also expensive. The
average wholesale price for a daily dose of Glucophage is a scant
$1.81 compared with $4.74 for Rezulin, according to the companies.
</P>
<P>
   And new competitors are in the wings. Two treatments that are
similar to Rezulin _ Avandia, made by SmithKline Beecham PLC, and
Actos from Eli Lilly &AMP; Co. and Takeda Chemical Industries Ltd. _
are scheduled to be reviewed for approval by the FDA next month.
</P>
<P>
   Analysts believe that either drug could successfully challenge
Glucophage, provided that they do not cause liver toxicity.
However, Rezulin's troubles have given doctors reason for caution.
</P>
<P>
   ``I would consider prescribing one of the two new drugs,''
Poretsky said. ``But neither of them have a history. But you have
to remember that with any drug, including Rezulin, there are going
to be risks.''
</P>
</TEXT>
