<SLUG> BC-CAR-IRWINDALE-LADN </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
IRWINDALE TRACK REVS UP FOR OPENING
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By KEITH LAIR  
 San Gabriel Valley Tribune  
<TEXT>
<P>
   IRWINDALE -- Southern California's need for speed won't be
limited to just the freeways any more.
</P>
<P>
   Irwindale Speedway, the third race track to be built in the L.A.
area in this decade, opens Saturday with three open-wheel races.
Sixty-eight other racing events have also been scheduled on the
track's one-third and half-mile asphalt ovals. Racing will be for
sportsmen -- who have very limited budgets -- and professionals,
who tour the U.S. with team sponsors and multi-million dollar
budgets. In addition, a concert series is in the works.
</P>
<P>
   ``On opening night, I know when the green flag drops, all the
people who are sitting in the stands will be happy,'' track vice
president and chief operating officer Ray Wilkings says. ``A whole
bunch of people will be happy.''
</P>
<P>
   Auto racing has always been a big hit for Americans. The first
race in the U.S. was held in 1895. Shortly after the turn of the
century, racing fans flocked to Indianapolis for the Indy 500,
Daytona Beach, Fla. for racing on the beach and to various Southern
California tracks. But housing, malls and business projects
eventually led to the elimination of tracks, including five
previous Irwindale tracks since 1955: San Gabriel Valley Dragstrip
(1955-60 and 1961-63), Go-Kart Speedway (1959-78), Speedway 605
(1966-77) and Irwindale Raceway (1965-1977).
</P>
<P>
   However, the sport is making a huge comeback. Television ratings
for National Association for Stock Car Auto Racing events have
climbed steadily in the past decade as purses have eclipsed the $1
million mark.
</P>
<P>
   In the past five years, the 2-mile tri-oval California Speedway
has been built in Fontana, a half-mile dirt track has been built in
Perris, the National Hot Rod Association updated and expanded its
facilities at Fairplex Park and now, the $10 million, 6,500-seat
Irwindale project is ready. Also, the Long Beach Grand Prix, a race
for Championship Auto Racing Team cars, celebrates its 25th year of
racing on Long Beach city streets on April 18.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's not easy to build a race track in the L.A. area,''
Wilkings said. ``That's why there are not very many around.''
</P>
<P>
   California Speedway president Scott Atherton says there's no
real surprise to the sport's upsurge.
</P>
<P>
   ``There are no player strikes, holdouts over money or drivers
always in trouble with the law,'' he said. ``I think people
appreciate that.''
</P>
<P>
   Irwindale Speedway officials say they will not be competing for
L.A.'s racing dollar with the other tracks, but for L.A.'s
entertainment dollar.
</P>
<P>
   ``This is not football, baseball, basketball, hockey or
soccer,'' Wilkings said. ``It's not any of that stuff. It's auto
racing. What we want to do is appeal to not just the race fan, but
to those who are not fans and make fans out of them. We want to
show them that this is a wonderful family-type of place and
sport.''
</P>
<P>
   Those who have toured the 63-acre facility -- everyone from
sanctioning body presidents, car owners, drivers and fans -- are
calling it the finest short track in the country.
</P>
<P>
   ``I think it will be a big hit,'' said Chino Hills racer Butch
Gilliland, who will drive in two NASCAR Winston West series events
at the track. ``It's a key marketplace for our sponsor and for
other companies, too. The Southern California market has been short
of tracks after we lost Ascot, Saugus, Ontario and Riverside.''
</P>
<P>
   Companies bought all 12Irwindale Speedway luxury suites before
construction even began. All 54 billboards were sold before the
first car took the track, too. The speedway's opening has created
jobs for ticket-sellers and takers, concession workers, parking
attendants and various track-side workers. In addition, surrounding
businesses should benefit by pre- and post-race meals, and hotel
accommodations for those from out of the area.
</P>
<P>
   Bob DeFazio, who oversaw all phases of the construction, says
that the elevator was the final piece of the track to be up and
running. It was operational last week and received its permit on
Monday. His staff was putting the final touches on the luxury
suites Friday, installing televisions, refrigerators, setting up
chairs and tables.
</P>
<P>
   ``We'll add up the fan visits and local job hours in smaller,
more manageable numbers,'' Wilkings said. ``But they'll still build
up to a strong economic impact on Irwindale and its surrounding
neighbor communities.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
