<HEADLINE>
WITH JOURNALISTS OUSTED, AID AGENCY PROVIDES REPORTS FROM KOSOVO 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients.)  
 By RON REDMOND  
 c.1999 Seattle Post-Intelligencer  
<TEXT>
<P>
   Yugoslavia's expulsion of most foreign journalists Thursday left
a Northwest-based aid agency as one of the few remaining sources of
information on conditions in war-torn Kosovo.
</P>
<P>
   Mercy Corps International has administered about $25 million in
aid programs in the province since 1993 with the help of dozens of
local ethnic Albanian staff, according to president and co-founder
Dan O'Neill, who is based in Redmond, Wash.
</P>
<P>
   About 40 of Mercy Corps' local staff as well as Albanian
empoyees of partner agencies remain inside Kosovo, providing some
of the only first-hand information now available to the outside
world. They are in communication with Mercy Corps' office in
neighboring Macedonia and their information is being used in press
releases posted on the agency's web site.
</P>
<P>
   ``We've had lots of journalists coming to our office in Skopje
(Macedonia's capital),'' O'Neill said. ``I've noticed that we're
getting information that I haven't seen anywhere else.''
</P>
<P>
   On Wednesday, the Portland-based agency issued a brief press
release reporting NATO air strikes on Pristina.
</P>
<P>
   Thursday, it circulated a longer one reporting details of
killings, kidnappings, looting and burning by Serb forces in the
towns of Pristina, Prizen, Mitrovica and Pec.
</P>
<P>
   There was no independent verification of the reports from Mercy
Corps, which says its programs in Kosovo assist members of all
ethnic groups.
</P>
<P>
   Many analysts predicted widespread Serbian retaliation against
the majority Albanian population in the event of NATO air strikes.
</P>
<P>
   Mercy Corps' sources in Kosovo reported that Serbian military
and paramilitary forces Thursday began conducting house-to-house
searches in Pristina, destroying property and beating civilians.
</P>
<P>
   They also reported:
</P>
<P>
   _ Serb civilians were leaving their homes in the city ``for
points unknown.''
</P>
<P>
   _ Masked gunmen had reportedly kidnapped a member of the
Albanian delgation to the peace talks in France and his two sons.
</P>
<P>
   _ The water supply in Pristina was off, but electricity had been
restored. A few people were on the streets, mostly in search of
food, water and other provisions.
</P>
<P>
   _ In Mitrovica, four people, including a 12-year-old boy, his
mother and two activists, were killed in their home by army troops.
</P>
<P>
   Mercy Corps first made headlines earlier this week in a
Post-Intelligencer story about its Kosovo country director, Terry
Heselius. Heselius risked NATO bombs and Serb retaliation to help
some of the agency's local staff flee to Macedonia. He was one of
the last Americans to leave Kosovo before the beginning of air
strikes on Wednesday and his story has generated nationwide
interest, including from NBC Nightly News.
</P>
<P>
   The Mercy Corps program headed by Heselius is one of the oldest
and largest operated in Kosovo by a non-governmental organization.
O`Neill said the program has been ``temporarily suspended'' because
of the current crisis.
</P>
<P>
   Mercy Corps' latest reports from Kosovo and the region can be
found on its web site at:
</P>
<P>
   www.mercycorps.org.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
