<DATE_TIME> 1999-03-25 21:18 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A4408 &Cx1f; tdt-z
u i &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-YUGOSLAVIA-SCENE-BOS &LR;      03-25 0787
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-YUGOSLAVIA-SCENE-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
SERBIA OUSTS FOREIGN JOURNALISTS; SERB CIVILIANS REACT TO WAR
</HEADLINE>
  (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By SUSAN MILLIGAN  
 c.1999 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   BELGRADE _ No one calls him by his real name, Zeljko Raznatovic.
It is his nickname, ``Arkan,'' that instills terror in those who
incur the wrath of the leader of the Tigers, a Serbian special
military force believed to have participated in some of the nastier
atrocities of the wars in Bosnia and Croatia.
</P>
<P>
   So people paid attention when Arkan, surrounded by a few
thuggish-looking companions, wandered the lobby Thursday of the
Hyatt Hotel, where many foreign journalists were staying, mumbling
that he was ``in a bad mood.''
</P>
<P>
   Before dawn Thursday, several foreign reporters heard a knock on
their hotel doors, as nonuniformed police told them they had to
pack their bags quickly and leave. The journalists were taken to
the border and expelled from the country.
</P>
<P>
   Later, the Serbian Ministry of Information, citing the state of
war with NATO, ordered all journalists affiliated with news
agencies based in NATO member countries to leave Serbia. Nearly all
did.
</P>
<P>
   Vuk Draskovic, the Yugoslav deputy prime minister, insisted to
foreign media that they were welcome to stay and cover the war.
``We need you. We need you as a window'' to tell the West of the
impact of the bombings, Draskovic said.
</P>
<P>
   But the public declarations of government officials have had
little meaning in Yugoslavia, where unofficial threats can be far
more serious. Beefy locals were stationed all week in the lobbies
of major hotels, watching and listening to foreign journalists.
</P>
<P>
   Many civilians are armed, particularly the minority Serbs in
Kosovo, and there was little assurance that foreigners would be
protected.
</P>
<P>
   ``Today, in this country, lunatics are the biggest patriots,''
lamented a 58-year-old filmmaker, who would give only his first
name of Milan.
</P>
<P>
   Anti-Western sentiment _ particularly anti-American feeling _
went into overdrive Thursday as Belgrade dealt with the aftermath
of the first wave of NATO bombings.
</P>
<P>
   ``We are angry,'' said Mira Petrovic, whose children were home
alone Thursday because schools were closed. Even Petrovic's
7-year-old son is reacting, pointing his toy gun in the air and
pretending to shoot it at the enemy, Petrovic said.
</P>
<P>
   NATO ``thinks Serbs are guilty of everything _ the wars in
Croatia and Bosnia, even the economic crisis in Asia,'' said
Dragan, who would not give his last name. ``They think if they kill
all the Serbs, there will be no more problems in the world.''
</P>
<P>
   Belgrade, which had greeted warnings of an imminent attack with
an almost defiant disinterest, seemed in a state of shock Thursday
at the fact that NATO had bombed, and people got hurt.
</P>
<P>
   The Information Ministry reported that 10 people were killed and
38 injured during Wednesday night's cruise missile assault.
State-run Serbian TV, whose pre-bombing programming included
patriotic music and air raid directives, showed more somber images
Thursday.
</P>
<P>
   The footage included people hospitalized with apparent war
wounds, but officials would not allow foreign journalists to enter
to hospitals or provide clearance to reporters who wanted to view
the damage.
</P>
<P>
   ``We were completely unready for it,'' said Ismina Tanaskovic.
``Until the first bomb fell, I really didn't think it would happen.
We don't understand why we are guilty. Why are they doing that to
us?''
</P>
<P>
   The streets of Belgrade were nearly deserted Thursday, and many
shops were closed. The air was filled with an aura of menace and
fear, and Serbs were not shy about singling out their intended
victims of retribution.
</P>
<P>
   ``I have a 4-year-old daughter,'' said a worker at a large hotel
hosting many foreigners. ``If anything happens to her'' in the
bombings, ``I will shoot the first one of them,'' he said bluntly,
referring to natives of NATO countries.
</P>
<P>
   In this case, Serbs feel doubly hurt _ victimized by what they
see as unwarranted bombing, and betrayed by its partners from both
world wars.
</P>
<P>
   ``Unfortunately, a lot of people in Belgrade remember the
bombing in 1941'' by the Axis, ``and the Allied bombing in 1944,''
said Milan Bozic, a Yugoslav Cabinet minister. ``A lot of Belgrade
citizens can't believe that our former allies would like to bomb us
again.''
</P>
<P>
   ``My grandfather fought in the Second World War to save the
lives of American pilots,'' said Draskovic. Now, NATO ``is bombing
a sovereign state because the sovereign state committed a few
crimes.''
</P>
<P>
   Susan Milligan reported this story from Belgrade before she and
other Western journalists were ordered out of Serbia Thursday
night.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
