<DATE_TIME> 1999-03-25 21:20 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A4412 &Cx1f; taf-z
u i &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-KOSOVO-GERMANY-750&AMP;AD     03-25 0801
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-KOSOVO-GERMANY-750&AMP;ADD-(2TAKES)-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
GERMANY REACTS WITH CALM AS ITS PLANES ATTACK YUGOSLAVIA
</HEADLINE>
   (See also: KOSOVO-RDP, KOSOVO-MILITARY, KOSOVO-MILITARY-ASSESS,
KOSOVO-POLICY, KOSOVO-BELGRADE, KOSOVO-PRISTINA, KOSOVO-MACEDONIA,
KOSOVO-REPORTERS, KOSOVO-CHINA, KOSOVO-RUSSIA-ASSESS,
KOSOVO-CLINTON, KOSOVO-ITALY, KOSOVO-VOICES, KOSOVO-B2,
KOSOVO-EUROPE-REAX, KOSOVO-U.N., KOSOVO-CLARK-PROFILE.) 
(rk) 
 By ROGER COHEN   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   BERLIN _ For the first time since the end of World War II,
German fighter jets have gone to war, taking part in the attack on
Yugoslavia as part of a NATO force and marking this country's
definitive emancipation from post-war pacifism.
</P>
<P>
   Rudolf Scharping, the German defense minister, said four Tornado
jets took off from their Piacenza base in northern Italy late
Wednesday and participated in the NATO mission, before returning
safely. The German Parliament has authorized up to 15 military
aircraft to take part in the airstrikes.
</P>
<P>
   Indicating that the German planes had hit Yugoslav targets,
Scharping told Parliament: ``These planes have the capability to
confuse and knock out enemy radar installations. That capability
was made use of.''
</P>
<P>
   Germany reacted calmly, indicating a profound change in its
psyche since the fall of the Berlin wall. Throughout the period of
post-war reconstruction, the saying that ``only peace'' would go
out from German soil amounted to a kind of mantra. The one time
during the Cold War German troops marched in a foreign land was in
1968 when East German troops assisted in the Soviet-led invasion of
Czechoslovakia.
</P>
<P>
   The devastation, physical and moral, caused by Hitler's Reich
and the country's delicate position at the front line of the Cold
War contributed to Germany's peace-only outlook. But Europe has
changed and Germany has changed with it. ``The last victim of the
fall of the wall is German pacifism,'' columnist Stephan Speicher
wrote Thursday in the Berliner Zeitung. ``We have become what we
are: ready for war.''
</P>
<P>
   Not everyone is ready. There have been dissenting voices and
clear tensions within the governing coalition of Social Democrat
Chancellor Gerhard Schroeder.
</P>
<P>
   Gregor Gysi, the leader of the Party of Democratic Socialism, a
growing successor party to the East German Communists, Thursday
denounced Germany's participation. ``After what has happened this
century,'' he said, ``Germany above all has no right to drop bombs
on Belgrade.''
</P>
<P>
   Gysi was referring to Hitler's flattening of Belgrade, which
began on April 6, 1941, after Serbs tore up a pact with the Nazis.
This event is etched on Serbian consciousness as if it happened
yesterday.
</P>
<P>
   Still, Gysi's voice appeared relatively isolated amid what the
conservative newspaper Die Welt Thursday called ``a kind of public
emptiness.''
</P>
<P>
   German equanimity was clearly reinforced Thursday by the fact
that it was a ``Red-Green'' coalition of Social Democrats and
Greens that approved the decision to participate. In effect, the
very forces that were most vocal about pacifism in the 1980s _ all
the Greens and some Social Democrats _ ended up sending Germany
back to battle for the first time since 1945.
</P>
<P>
   ``The federal government has not easily taken the decision that,
for the first time since World War II, there are German soldiers in
an operational mission,'' Schroeder said. But ``our fundamental
values of freedom, democracy and human rights'' were being flouted
in Kosovo, and this could not be tolerated, he added.
</P>
<P>
   His statement reflected the way the barbarity of the Bosnian
war, combined with Germany's release from the constraints and
imperatives of the Cold War, has changed the attitudes of a country
no longer content to be an economic giant and a political midget.
</P>
<P>
   Just seven years ago, at the start of the Bosnian war, Joschka
Fischer, then a Green member of Parliament, opposed any Western
military intervention or deployment of German forces in Bosnia. But
Germany eventually played a role, both in the air and on the
ground, in the U.N. peace-keeping force in Bosnia. As foreign
minister since October, Fischer has argued passionately for the
West's responsibility to stop Serbian aggression in Kosovo in the
light of the refusal of Slobodan Milosevic, the Yugoslav president,
to accept peace proposals.
</P>
<P>
   ``It cannot be permitted that, in the middle of Europe, the
predominant population of Kosovo is collectively deprived of its
rights,'' Fischer said this week.
</P>
<P>
   Daniel Cohn-Bendit, a Green colleague of Fischer and a fellow
militant in the revolutionary struggles of the 1960s, said Bosnia
had ``simply transformed'' the way the foreign minister approached
the question of the use of force.
</P>
<ANNOTATION>
   (STORY CAN END HERE. OPTIONAL MATERIAL FOLLOWS)
</ANNOTATION>
<P>
   nn
</P>
<P>
   Still, the German participation in air raids on Yugoslavia is
potentially explosive, for it will confirm every dark Serbian
suspicion about the West. If there has been a single obsession in
Serbian policy this century, it has been to prevent what Belgrade
sees as German expansionism in the Balkans.
</P>
<P>
   ``We are not ready to make a distinction between the bombs of
Adolf Hitler from 1941 and the bombs of NATO,'' Vuk Draskovic, the
Yugoslavia deputy prime minister, said. It was a comment that
amounted to a summary of a widespread Serbian view of the reasons
for the country's plight.
</P>
<P>
   Strong German support for Croatian independence from Yugoslavia,
and Croatia's adoption of the hymn ``Danke Deutschland'' when that
independence came in 1991, only reinforced Serbian misgivings.
</P>
<P>
   The last time NATO bombed in the Balkans _ hitting Serbian
positions around Sarajevo in the late summer of 1995 _ the action
prompted a response very similar to Draskovic's on Thursday.
</P>
<P>
   ``By its length, this bombardment is even more brutal than the
bombardment conducted by Hitler on April 6, 1941, on Belgrade,
given the fact that Hitler's bombardment was stopped on April 8,
1941, to allow the burial of victims under Christian custom,'' Gen.
Ratko Mladic, then the commander of Serbian forces in Bosnia, wrote
to a Western general.
</P>
<P>
   With 2,500 German troops now in Bosnia, and another 3,000
stationed in Macedonia, the possibility of some Serbian reprisal
against German forces exists, especially if the NATO bombing proves
prolonged or erratic.
</P>
<P>
   This possibility has already created political tensions here.
Volker Ruehe, the former defense minister in the Christian Democrat
Government of Helmut Kohl, said that the troops in Macedonia had
been sent there as part of a peacekeeping force, and ``not to make
war.'' They should therefore be withdrawn, he argued.
</P>
<P>
   Within the coalition, the issue of Kosovo proved fraught before
the bombing began. It had much to do with the abrupt resignation
this month of the former finance minister, Oskar Lafontaine.
</P>
<P>
   Lafontaine was concerned that Germany's readiness to follow
America's Kosovo policy was reckless, according to a minister who
was present during the discussions. At one Cabinet meeting, shortly
before he quit, Lafontaine relentlessly probed Schroeder as to
where bombing would lead, what it would achieve, what its legal
basis was, and what it would cost.
</P>
<P>
   Later, when Scharping, the defense minister, asked for more
money because the preparations for Kosovo had used up the funds
earmarked for a pay rise for the military, Lafontaine refused,
officials said. At that point, Scharping threatened to resign.
</P>
<P>
   But when Schroeder sided with Scharping and ordered Lafontaine
to release the money, it was the finance minister who quit.
``Lafontaine objected to Kosovo policy in the same way as he
objected to the deployment of American Pershing II missiles on
German soil in the 1980s,'' said the minister who attended the
discussions and who spoke on the condition of anonymity.
</P>
<P>
   The deployment of the missiles was, of course, successful. It
was contentious, but it helped bring the Cold War to an end. This
week, America again enlisted Germany's help in a resolute course of
action, but the outcome, for Germany and for Europe, remains
uncertain.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
