<SLUG> BC-CAR-BUSCH-POLE-TEX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
BLANEY BLAZES TO BUSCH SERIES POLE IN TEXAS
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By Simon Gonzalez 
c.1999 Fort Worth Star-Telegram 
<TEXT>
<P>
   FORT WORTH, Texas _ Dave Blaney was the wrong person to talk to
about the problems some drivers were having in Turn 2 of Texas
Motor Speedway yesterday.
</P>
<P>
   ``Ask someone who wrecked,'' Blaney said.
</P>
<P>
   Blaney didn't wreck. Far from it. While six Busch Grand National
drivers got too close to the edge during practice and found the
wall, Blaney had no problems with the reconfigured surface.
</P>
<P>
   He drove his No. 93 Amoco Pontiac to the pole for tomorrow's BGN
Coca-Cola 300, with a one-lap speed of 183.082 mph. That shattered
the previous qualifying record of 180.054 set by Jeff Green before
the inaugural race in 1997.
</P>
<P>
   ``My car really likes this track,'' said Blaney, who is on the
pole for the third time in his 25-race BGN career and the second
time this season. ``The key to today was no mistakes. We put good
corners together in practice and knew if we could put a whole lap
together it would be close.''
</P>
<P>
   Mark Martin joined Blaney in the front row with a speed of
181.592 mph. Adam Petty, son of Winston Cup regular Kyle Petty and
grandson of NASCAR legend Richard Petty, and defending Cup champion
Jeff Gordon are in the second row.
</P>
<P>
   Points leader Matt Kenseth qualified fifth, while defending
champion Dale Earnhardt Jr. was 12th.
</P>
<P>
   Blaney had one of the fastest cars in practice, and was fourth
on the speed charts after the afternoon session. That gave him
reason to think he could put it on the pole.
</P>
<P>
   ``I didn't have any problems with my car,'' he said. ``I knew
what we had, and I just had to make it a little better than our
practice time.''
</P>
<P>
   Petty, a Busch Series rookie, was the 10th of the 61 entries to
make a qualifying run and gave Grandpa a thrill when he went to the
top of the scoring tower.
</P>
<P>
   ``He was pretty excited,'' Adam Petty said. ``It was pretty neat
for him to see me No. 1 on the tower there for a while.''
</P>
<P>
   That held up until Martin, the 29th driver out, bumped him.
</P>
<P>
   It appeared as though Martin would add a pole to his TMS resume
that includes a Busch victory in '97 and the Cup triumph last year,
but Blaney blew everyone away with his record-setting lap.
</P>
<P>
   Like Petty earlier in the day, Blaney made his record run on new
tires. Most of the drivers opted to qualify on scuffs, tires that
were warmed up with a few laps during practice, but crew chief Gil
Martin decided not to follow the crowd.
</P>
<P>
   ``Everybody went out there with scuffed tires, and we made our
best run on stickers,'' Martin said. ``We ran stickers in the
afternoon before the qualifying run and he said the car stayed
right up under him and was good and tight. We'd already run faster
than what most of the guys, so we felt pretty good about it.''
</P>
<P>
   Blaney is in the same car he used for the Yellow Freight 300 at
Atlanta Motor Speedway two weeks ago. He won the pole then, and
finished second in the race.
nn
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
