<HEADER>
A4416 &Cx1f; tth-z
r e &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-TV-FUTURAMA-SPI &LR;      03-25 0702
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-TV-FUTURAMA-SPI </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
LOOKS LIKE FOX HAS HIT A HOMER WITH GROENING'S `FUTURAMA' 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients.)  
 By JOHN LEVESQUE  
 c.1999 Seattle Post-Intelligencer  
<TEXT>
<P>
   Trying to reinvent the freshness, the irreverence and the
nose-thumbing smart-aleckness of ``The Simpsons'' is probably a
dumb idea. But if Fox is willing to pay the money, Matt Groening is
happy to take it.
</P>
<P>
   And if the number of laugh-out-loud moments in his new
``Futurama'' is a good way to measure success, Groening, who needs
more money like Bart Simpson needs more attitude, may be laughing
all the way to the banquette where TV execs do lunch.
</P>
<P>
   Maybe we shouldn't be too surprised. Laying claim to essentially
the same well-written provenance as ``The Simpsons,'' ``Futurama''
is smart but not pointy-headed, satirical but not annoying. It's
the hallmark of Groening and his people: sly, subversive humor
delivered with such who-me? guiltlessness that it's hard not to
like.
</P>
<P>
   For a couple of Sunday nights before moving to Tuesdays,
``Futurama'' takes us into the beyond with a 25-year-old pizza
runner named Fry, who accidentally freezes himself after making a
delivery to a New York cryogenics lab in 1999. Thawed out 10
centuries later, Fry finds himself in New New York, the old New
York having been destroyed a couple of times while he was on ice.
Upon emerging from the freezer, Fry encounters Leela, a foxy
one-eyed alien with depth-perception problems. Later, he meets
Bender, a robot who drinks too much, smokes cigars and isn't above
the occasional act of petty theft.
</P>
<P>
   After finding the only blood relative he has on Earth, a
great-to-the-40th-power-(give or take)-nephew named Prof. Hubert
Farnsworth, Fry and his only friends in the world decide to sign on
with the professor's moonlighting business, Planet Express Corp.,
which delivers packages to all five quadrants of the universe.
</P>
<P>
   Once again, Fry is a delivery boy. But it's amazing how a new
millennium puts a fresh coat of rationalization on the numbingly
familiar.
</P>
<P>
   One minor complaint about ``Futurama'': Billy West, perhaps best
known as the voice of both Ren and Stimpy, makes Fry sound a little
like an older Bart Simpson, which doesn't quite work here. Maybe
it's because Fry is supposed to be a dim bulb, certainly as dim as
Homer Simpson. But it's hard to see Fry as a dull knife when he
sounds like Bart, who's actually sharper than most of the cutlery
in Springfield.
</P>
<P>
   The voice of Katey Sagal (``Married ... With Children''), on the
other hand, is ideal for Leela: smoky, sexy, confident without
being cocky. And John DiMaggio gives Bender a great combo of
high-tech/low-brow sass.
</P>
<P>
   In the future, viewers can look forward to meeting these
additional characters:
</P>
<P>
   _ Dr. Zoidberg, physician in residence at Planet Express. He
looks like a lobster and knows nothing about human anatomy.
</P>
<P>
   _ Hermes Conrad, number cruncher at Planet Express. Of Jamaican
descent, Hermes was a member of Earth's limbo team in the 2980
Olympics.
</P>
<P>
   _ Amy Wong, an intern at Planet Express. An engineering student
at Mars University, Amy is the daughter of Leo and Inez Wong, who
own a ranch on Mars.
</P>
<P>
   _ Zapp Brannigan, the most decorated captain in the Democratic
Order of Planets. Zapp, who single-handedly defeated the Retiree
People of the Assisted-Living Nebula, likes wicker furniture and
velour.
</P>
<P>
   As with ``The Simpsons,'' nearly every scene of ``Futurama''
offers a tapestry of sight gags. They go by so quickly that
videotaping is a must for subsequent appreciation. But even if you
miss the preserved craniums of Gillian Anderson, David Duchovny,
Elizabeth Taylor, Barbra Streisand and, yes, Matt Groening in the
New New York Head Museum, ``Futurama'' offers plenty to laugh about
at first blush.
</P>
<P>
   Futurama. Half-hour animated comedy series about a pizza
delivery man who accidentally preserves himself in a cryogenics
lab, thawing out on New Year's Eve 2999. Created by Matt Groening.
Voices by Billy West, Katey Sagal and John DiMaggio. Premieres
Sunday night on Fox, airs again the next Sunday night, then moves
to Tuesday nights on April 6. Parental guideline rating: TV-PG.
</P>
<P>
   Grade: A-
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
