</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BKC-COACHK26-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Duke's Krzyzewski at top of his game
 &HT;    By Tony Barnhart
 &HT;    c.1999 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   ST. PETERSBURG, Fla. _ Less than two minutes remained in what
would become Duke's 85-64 win over Temple in Sunday's NCAA East
Regional championship game. With victory and a spot in the Final
Four assured, coach Mike Krzyzewski stood and applauded his team.
Krzyzewski then cleared the bench, giving each player a hug as he
came off the floor. He also delivered a message:
</P>
<P>
   ``Enjoy this,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   It was a minor gesture, really, but one that spoke volumes about
the man and his personal journey from triumph to tragedy and back
to triumph again during the decade of the '90s. It was a painful
process, both physically and emotionally. There were moments of
self-doubt. But today, on the eve of his eighth Final Four
appearance as a coach, Krzyzewski will tell you that he's a better
man for having made the trip. He finally has learned to enjoy the
moment.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'm happy,'' said Krzyzewski, who is a youthful 52. ``I'm very
comfortable with who I am.''
</P>
<P>
   If there is a basketball world, then Krzyzewski is the king of
it. The evidence is compelling:
</P>
<P>
   _ He brings the nation's No. 1 team (36-1) into Saturday's Final
Four game with Michigan State. The top eight players at Duke are
five sophomores, a junior, a freshman and one senior. Krzyzewski
already has signed three McDonald's All-Americans for next year.
</P>
<P>
   _ He has won two national championships, 1991-92, and if this
team gives him No. 3, Krzyzewski would become only the fourth coach
in NCAA history to win three or more titles. The others are John
Wooden (10), Adolph Rupp (4) and Bob Knight (3).
</P>
<P>
   _ With a win Saturday over Michigan State, Krzyzewski would pass
UCLA's Wooden and move into second place in all-time NCAA
Tournament wins with 48. Only former North Carolina coach Dean
Smith has more (65). But the numbers, as impressive as they are,
don't tell the complete story of a man who was at the top of his
profession, was forced to give it up, and then came back better
than ever as a different man and a different coach.
</P>
<P>
   ``I love coaching again,'' said Krzyzewski, acknowledging that
there was a time when his job was not a labor of love.
</P>
<P>
   After winning a second consecutive national championship in
1992, no coach in any sport was hotter than Krzyzewski. The Blue
Devils had been to six Final Fours in seven years, an unprecedented
achievement since the NCAA Tournament was expanded to 64 teams in
1985.
</P>
<P>
   But the former Army point guard, the product of working-class
parents in Chicago, had built a basketball machine at Duke and
never allowed himself to enjoy it. Instead, he was keeping a
frantic pace in an effort just to maintain it.
</P>
<P>
   ``He got in such a whirlwind and didn't know how to get out,''
Krzyzewski's wife, Micki, told The Charlotte Observer.
</P>
<P>
   In 1994, Krzyzewski almost won his third national championship
in four years, but Scotty Thurman of Arkansas hit a rainbow 3-point
shot with 51 seconds remaining, and the Razorbacks won 76-72 in
Charlotte. Still, Krzyzewski kept pushing himself.
</P>
<P>
   Nature finally stepped in on Oct. 21, 1994, when Krzyzewski, who
had been living with back pain for months, was forced to have
surgery to repair a herniated disc. Doctors told him to take
several weeks off and rest. He ignored them, holding a staff
meeting at his house two days after he left the hospital. Soon he
was back in the office.
</P>
<P>
   With Grant Hill having graduated to the NBA, the Duke team of
1995 was not as talented as in years past. But Krzyzewski, refusing
to slow down, coached the Blue Devils to a 9-3 record in the
opening weeks of the season.
</P>
<P>
   Then he hit the wall. Two days after a loss to Clemson at home,
Krzyzewski returned to Duke Hospital for a series of tests. Doctors
determined that he was physically exhausted and prescribed complete
rest.
</P>
<P>
   He didn't get a chance to ignore the doctors again. Duke
athletics director Tom Butters and president Nan Keohane
intervened, telling Krzyzewski that he had to take the rest of the
year off. Krzyzewski could only watch while Duke went 4-15 in its
remaining games under interim coach Pete Gaudet.
</P>
<P>
   ``At that point, I really didn't know what was going to
happen,'' Krzyzewski said. ``I thought we could get it back. But
honestly, I wasn't sure.''
</P>
<P>
   When Krzyzewski returned for the 1996 season, it was with a
stronger body, a rested mind, and a healthy dose of perspective.
Krzyzewski remembered the words of the late Jim Valvano, who had
become his friend during Valvano's unsuccessful fight with cancer
in 1993. Valvano told him to take time to enjoy his three
daughters, who were growing up quickly.
</P>
<P>
   Then in October 1996, just as preseason practice was under way,
Krzyzewski lost his mother, Emily, to cancer.
</P>
<P>
   Krzyzewski came back to lead Duke into the NCAA Tournament that
season, but he would never be the same. Oh, he still blisters the
officials when he thinks they deserve it. And he can still chew his
team out for what he perceives to be a lack of effort, as he did at
halftime of last week's East Regional semifinal against Southwest
Missouri State.
</P>
<P>
   ``Coach is still as passionate about the game as he's ever
been,'' said senior guard Trajan Langdon, the only player who has
been with Krzyzewski the past five years. ``He just takes time to
enjoy other things.''
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
