<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Crum reply on eligibility
 &HT;    By Tony Barnhart
 &HT;    c.1999 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   ST. PETERSBURG, Fla. _ Earlier this month, a district court
ruled that the NCAA's freshman eligibility requirements
discriminated against blacks. Since then, the NCAA has claimed that
schools will be thrown into ``chaos'' if they have to recruit
without a uniform standard.
</P>
<P>
   Louisville basketball coach Denny Crum isn't buying it. He
believes the old eligibility rules don't have to be replaced by
anything at all.
</P>
<P>
   Minimum eligibility requirements were created in 1986 in
response to some schools bringing in athletes who were poor
students and allowing them to take easy courses to stay eligible.
Four years later, those athletes were out of eligibility and
nowhere near a degree.
</P>
<P>
   Crum believes the satisfactory-progress rule, adopted in 1988,
eliminated the need for eligibility requirements. It sets
guidelines for progress toward a degree. If an athlete doesn't meet
that standard at any given point in his or her college career, he
or she is ineligible for athletics.
</P>
<P>
   ``If a kid's not making progress toward his degree, he's not
going to be eligible to play anyway,'' said Crum, incoming
president of the National Association of Basketball Coaches,
holding its annual convention at the Final Four.
</P>
<P>
   Let's get less physical
</P>
<P>
   Much has been made about the scoring in college basketball,
which is down about 13 points a game over the last eight years. One
coach's answer: Cut out the physical play.
</P>
<P>
   ``If you look at some of those old classic games, guys could
actually get open for shots without getting beat up along the
way,'' Kansas coach Roy Williams said. ``Today, it's like
hand-to-hand combat out there.''
</P>
<P>
   But Williams, chairman of the NABC rules committee, doesn't hold
out a lot of hope.
</P>
<P>
   ``We've let it come so far, it's hard to see how we can go back
to the old way of playing,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   Dooley arrives today
</P>
<P>
   Georgia athletics director Vince Dooley will be arriving in St.
Petersburg today as he continues to search for a new basketball
coach. Dooley's list includes former St. John's coach Fran
Fraschilla, Evansville's Jim Crews, Delaware's Mike Brey,
Appalachian State's Buzz Peterson and former Georgia assistant
Jerry Waters, who said Thursday that he plans to meet with Dooley
as early as today. Dooley and UGA president Michael Adams hope to
meet with as many of them as possible during their stay.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
