<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Barmore: White-McCarty worthy of award
 &HT;    By Wendy Parker
 &HT;    c.1999 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   SAN JOSE, Calif. _ When Stephanie White-McCarty lit up Louisiana
Tech for 21 points and seven rebounds in Purdue's 71-65 win on Dec.
19, her performance so impressed Tech coach Leon Barmore that he
voted for her for the Women's Basketball Coaches Association's
player of the year award.
</P>
<P>
   He was the only coach to buck the Chamique Holdsclaw bandwagon,
but Thursday Barmore maintained that the top-ranked Boilermakers
senior point guard has been more valuable to her team. And not just
because they're meeting again in a Final Four tipoff at 9:30
tonight.
</P>
<P>
   ``I respect that she took a team of less talent than say, a
Tennessee,'' Barmore said. White-McCarty ``has them knocking on the
door of a national championship, and I think it's due to her
ability to run a ballclub and her ability to think on the court.
What got her my vote was the reality that she got the job done.''
</P>
<P>
   Tiresome twin talk
</P>
<P>
   It's inevitable that Georgia's Andy Landers would be asked about
twins Kelly and Coco Miller, but even he got a little weary during
a news conference.
</P>
<P>
   ``This is my third set of twins,'' he said. ``I'm getting kind
of numb to it, really. I'm going to burst your bubble, because we
have really worked hard at treating them as individuals and
coaching them per their needs and the way we think they need to be
coached.''
</P>
<P>
   The other sets of twins are Camille and Miriam Lowe, who played
between 1990 and 1993, and Bernadette and Juliette Locke, who
played for him at Roane State Junior College in Tennessee.
Bernadette Locke also played for Landers his first two years at
Georgia
</P>
<P>
   Miller, Edwards honored
</P>
<P>
   Georgia's Kelly Miller was named to the 1999 Kodak All-America
team on Thursday, and former winner Teresa Edwards was chosen to
the Kodak silver anniversary team.
</P>
<P>
   Miller is one of four sophomores on this season's 10-player
team, joining Tamika Catchings and Semeka Randall of Tennessee and
UConn's Svetlana Abrosimova.
</P>
<P>
   Tennessee's Chamique Holdsclaw's selection made her just the
second four-time All-American, with Cheryl Miller of Southern Cal.
Also chosen were Becky Hammon of Colorado State, Maylana Martin of
UCLA, Michele VanGorp of Duke, White-McCarty of Purdue and
Louisiana Tech's Amanda Wilson.
</P>
<P>
   Edwards was a Kodak All-American in 1985 and 1986.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
