<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BKC-OHIOST-NOTES26-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Consistency carries Buckeyes
 &HT;    By Susan Vinella
 &HT;    c.1999 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   COLUMBUS, Ohio _ They sit in the same seats during every team
meeting and on every team bus ride. They get their right ankle
taped first _ always. They run onto the court for warm-ups in the
same order every time: Scoonie Penn first, Ken Johnson last. Penn
always takes the first shot in shoot-arounds.
</P>
<P>
   ``I think we're pretty superstitious,'' senior co-captain Jason
Singleton said. ``I think it just makes us feel a little more
comfortable to have our pre-game rituals.''
</P>
<P>
   The Buckeyes know it's their play that's responsible for Ohio
State reaching the Final Four. Nonetheless, they don't want to
change the little things that have accompanied their success.
</P>
<P>
   For example, Penn brought a boom box to a holiday tournament in
Puerto Rico in December and the Bucks won all three of games there.
He left the boom box home when the team traveled to the Big Ten
tournament in Chicago and OSU lost in the second game.
</P>
<P>
   ``We put two and two together and we figured we better bring it
to our tournament games,'' Singleton said.
</P>
<P>
   OSU coach Jim O'Brien said there was talk that he and the
players would shave their heads if the team made the Final Four. To
his relief, the players have decided such a drastic change might
disturb their karma.
</P>
<P>
   ``They don't want to change anything,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   How about 1:15 a.m., coach?
</P>
<P>
   O'Brien likes numerous things about this Buckeye squad and has
spoken frequently about how enjoyable it has been to coach this
group. He recalled a discussion about team curfew two days before a
game in Knoxville, Tenn., last week.
</P>
<P>
   ``I asked them what time they thought should be in,'' O'Brien
said. ``Somebody said, kidding around, '4 (a.m.)?' And I said,
Nooo. Next.
</P>
<P>
   ``I said what about 1? And Jason says, '1:15. We were thinking
about 1:15.' I said that's OK with me.
</P>
<P>
   ``That's what I like about them. They don't take advantage.
Maybe I've missed a lot of stuff but I don't sense that they've
taken advantage. They're fun to be around.''
</P>
<P>
   18 losses, but they were close
</P>
<P>
   UConn coach Jim Calhoun said observers shouldn't make too much
of the 18 straight losses O'Brien suffered to the Huskies while a
coach at Boston College. Many of the games were decided by just a
few points or were lost at the buzzer or in overtime.
</P>
<P>
   ``There's a quirkiness to it,'' Calhoun said of O'Brien's losing
streak. ``And it just seems like every single time he's been good,
we've been very good. And when he's been very good, we've been
excellent.''
</P>
<P>
   Penn says he'll be back
</P>
<P>
   Point guard Scoonie Penn says he will return for his senior
season instead of making himself available for the NBA draft.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'm thinking next year about coming back here and playing at
Ohio State,'' Penn said on Tuesday. ``The NBA has been a dream of
mine. But right now, I have no thoughts about leaving college
basketball at all.''
</P>
<P>
   Asked if he would change his mind if he were told he'd be taken
in the first round, he said, ``I don't believe everything I hear.''
</P>
<P>
   The Associated Press contributed to this report.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
