<SLUG> BC-BBN-DODGERS-NOTES-LADN </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
DODGERS EXPAND SEARCH FOR LEFTY
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By BRIAN DOHN  
 c.1999 Los Angeles Daily News  
<TEXT>
<P>
   KISSIMMEE, Fla. _ The Dodgers need a lefty in the bullpen and so
far the candidates in camp haven't knocked off anyone's socks. They
haven't even untied anyone's shoes.
</P>
<P>
   Sothe Dodgers are dipping into their minor-league camp in search
of a capable left-handed reliever.
</P>
<P>
   On a day in which lefty Pedro Borbon had his best, and longest,
outing of the spring, general manager Kevin Malone said 26-year-old
minor leaguer Jeff Williams would pitch today in relief for the
Dodgers against the Baltimore Orioles.
</P>
<P>
   Williams split time between Double-A San Antonio and Triple-A
Albuquerque last season.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'm anxious. I want to see him myself,'' Malone said during
the Dodgers' 8-5 win against the Houston Astros. ``We've had good
reports out of minor-league camp. We're possibly adding another
name to the mix.''
</P>
<P>
   The Dodgers' need to find a capable left-hander is getting more
immediate as opening day closes in. Williams' audition demonstrates
that. The Aussie, who pitched at Southeastern Louisiana University,
has appeared in 51 games _ all starts _ in his two years as a
professional. Last year he was 8-8 with a 4.98 ERA in Albuquerque.
</P>
<P>
   But Malone also said there's another reason for looking at
Williams. If 21-year-old Onan Masaoka makes the club, the Dodgers
need to know if they have reinforcements at the minor-league level
if he fails.
</P>
<P>
   ``We have to know what we have,'' Malone said. ``Most of us are
new here in the organization. You have to look at everything.''
</P>
<P>
   Manager Davey Johnson has been concerned about the role,
although he was encouraged by Borbon's performance.
</P>
<P>
   ``That's the best he's thrown,'' Johnson said of Borbon's two
hitless innings. ``To me, he moved right into the hunt.''
</P>
<P>
   It was the first time Borbon threw more than one inning, but his
fastball topped out at 87 mph, under the 89 to 91 mph range he was
at before 1996 elbow surgery. Johnson said he plans on using Borbon
more in the next week to test his arm.
</P>
<P>
   ``Every day I go out I get more confidence in my arm,'' said
Borbon (0-0, 2.25 ERA). ``I know if I'm healthy I'm going to play
in the big leagues.''
</P>
<P>
   Hundley to catch? Todd Hundley is expected to catch his first
game of the spring today as the Dodgers host the Baltimore Orioles,
although that could change.
</P>
<P>
   The Dodgers have been slow to allow Hundley _ who has been
scratched several times from the lineup this spring _ test his
surgically repaired elbow in game situations.
</P>
<P>
   Johnson wouldn't commit on the prospect of Hundley catching
today but did say when that time arrives, Hundley would start
slowly by catching three or four innings. Johnson said he may bat
Hundley second to get him two at-bats.
</P>
<P>
   ``Right now, the key isn't his arm or elbow,'' Malone said.
``It's his legs, making sure he can squat and run.''
</P>
<P>
   Balks, walks and chalk: Dodgers officials said they wouldn't
have any interest in signing right-hander Hideo Nomo, outrighted to
the minor leagues by the Mets, if he were a free agent. . . .
Malone strengthened his stance on the status of reliever Antonio
Osuna, who's recovering from elbow surgery last September. ``We're
probably looking at him starting the year on the disabled list,''
Malone said. . . . Gary Sheffield went 0 for 3 as his average
dropped to .095, but he isn't concerned. ``Once I get my balance,
I'm a lot quicker at the plate. I'm close,'' the left fielder said.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
