<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BKC-UCONN-CALHOUN26-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Penn, El-Amin keep teams focused on the court of emotion
 &HT;    By Susan Vinella
 &HT;    c.1999 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   ST. PETERSBURG, Fla. _ Mention the Ohio State-Connecticut
match-up in Saturday's Final Four, and the talk immediately turns
to the guard play.
</P>
<P>
   Can the Buckeyes stop two-time Big East Player of the Year
Richard ``Rip'' Hamilton? Can the Huskies take OSU's leader,
Scoonie Penn, out of his game? Will Ricky Moore, the
oft-overshadowed Husky guard, continue to be the defensive stopper
UConn needs? Will Michael Redd, snubbed by Big Ten media and
coaches as an All-Conference first team selection, show that he is
one of the conference's and nation's best guards?
</P>
<P>
   Guard play, coaches say, has become increasingly important in
college basketball. With the diminishing number of true, dominant
centers in the game and the use of three-guard lineups like UConn
and Ohio State employ, backcourt players wield more influence.
</P>
<P>
   ``Very simply, the people who have the ball in their hands the
most end up turning the game,'' UConn coach Jim Calhoun said.
</P>
<P>
   Penn has done that frequently this season. His ability to shoot
the 3-pointer as well dish out a clutch assist has proven
invaluable to the Buckeyes.
</P>
<P>
   But the Huskies have their own dangerous point man in Khalid
El-Amin. At 5-10, 205 pounds, he is often jeered by opponents' fans
who call him the ``Pillsbury Doughboy'' and wave empty Domino's
pizza boxes at him.
</P>
<P>
   Like OSU's Penn, El-Amin is the emotional leader of his team.
Even if he's not scoring a lot of points, as was the case in the
regional final against Gonzaga when he shot 0-for-12 from the
field, his energy and leadership still fuels the Huskies.
</P>
<P>
   ``He's our energizer,'' Calhoun said. ``He makes us go not only
physically but psychologically. He really truly is the guy who the
other kids turn to for energy, direction and sometimes for
courage.''
</P>
<P>
   Ohio State coach Jim O'Brien said it's the same way with Penn.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's uncanny how similar these point guards are,'' he said.
``It's interesting how Hamilton is the leading scorer but Khalid is
the leader. It's the same with us. Michael is our leading scorer
(19.7 points per game), but Scoonie makes us go.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
