<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BKC-UGA-DUKE26-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Lady Dogs must avoid Final Four fouls
 &HT;    By Wendy Parker
 &HT;    c.1999 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   SAN JOSE, Calif. _ Duke did a major favor to virtually everyone
in women's basketball by knocking off Tennessee behind one of the
strongest frontlines in the nation.
</P>
<P>
   That height advantage might cause the Georgia Lady Bulldogs
major problems here tonight in the first game of the women's Final
Four semifinals (7 p.m., ESPN).
</P>
<P>
   Duke's physical front line is anchored by 6-foot-6 center
Michele VanGorp, who played a critical role in dethroning the Lady
Volunteers. The Lady Bulldogs have improved their post defense, but
their chances to reach Sunday's championship game might depend on
how well they can avoid foul problems.
</P>
<P>
   VanGorp, who had 13 points and seven rebounds against Tennessee
and leads the team with a 16.9 scoring average, complements a solid
guard trio of Nicole Erickson and Hilary Howard and Georgia
Schweitzer.
</P>
<P>
   Georgia's starting inside combination of Tawana McDonald and
Angie Ball struggled with foul difficulties against both Clemson
and Iowa State last week in the regionals.
</P>
<P>
   Georgia coach Andy Landers saidhis team has been able to adapt
defensively to an array of postseason foes, but Duke presents a
special challenge.
</P>
<P>
   ``When you have inside people that Duke has, there's the
potential to have fouls,'' Landers said.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
