<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-03-25 21:24 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A4427 &Cx1f; ttj-z
u w &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-KOSOVO-NATO-HNS &LR;      03-25 1122
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-KOSOVO-NATO-HNS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
NATO FORCES LAUNCH ANOTHER ROUND OF AIRSTRIKES AT MILOSEVIC 

</HEADLINE>
  
 (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  (Also see: KOSOVO-AIM, KOSOVO-DAMAGE and KOSOVO-BUSH) 
 
By CRAGG HINES 
c.1999 Houston Chronicle 
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON _ NATO forces hurled a fresh rain of missiles and
bombs on Yugoslav targets Thursday as President Clinton expressed
confidence that the airstrikes would soften President Slobodan
Milosevic's refusal to negotiate peace and autonomy in Kosovo.
</P>
<P>
   Defense Department spokesman Kenneth Bacon said the second night
of assault from warships in the Adriatic Sea and jets above the
Balkans would be ``another substantive strike; it will be severe.''
</P>
<P>
   Bacon said the new round of strikes would hammer forces that
have been terrorizing ethnic Albanians in the southern province of
Kosovo.
</P>
<P>
   ``They will focus more and more on achieving our primary goal,
which is to reduce the ability of the Yugoslav forces to target or
repress the Kosovar Albanians,'' Bacon said.
</P>
<P>
   A fleeting sign of accommodation by Milosevic's government was
discounted by the Clinton administration, which also turned aside
an Italian proposal for another round of diplomatic talks.
</P>
<P>
   U.S. Army Gen. Wesley Clark, supreme allied commander in Europe,
said the bombardment overall would be ``just as long and difficult
as President Milosevic requires it to be.''
</P>
<P>
   ``We're going to systematically and progressively attack,
disrupt, degrade, devastate and ultimately _ unless President
Milosevic complies with the demands of the international community
_ we're going to destroy these forces and their facilities and
support,'' Clark said at NATO headquarters in Brussels, Belgium.
</P>
<P>
   Serb forces limited access to bombed areas Thursday, and damage
reports from the second wave of attacks were sketchy. But NATO
officials said all aircraft had returned safely despite Serb claims
that two planes had been downed. &UR;
</P>
<P>
   &LR; Milosevic's response to the air salvos seemed subdued, but
Samuel Berger, President Clinton's national security adviser, said
Yugoslavia was shelling Albania as well as continuing its campaign
against Kosovar Albanians.
</P>
<P>
   Allied leaders said little about the level of damage wrought by
the airstrikes but sounded pleased after the first night.
</P>
<P>
   ``It is obviously early to say this, but from what we can
gather, they have been successful,'' British Prime Minister Tony
Blair said.
</P>
<P>
   A Yugoslav commander said the first night's damage was
``minimal,'' but the Russian general staff in Moscow said the NATO
strikes badly damaged five military airfields, two factories, a
communications center, several barracks and a police training base.
</P>
<P>
   The Serbian health minister, Dr. Leposava Milecevic, said on CNN
that 10 civilians and one soldier were killed and 60 other people
were wounded in the first night.
</P>
<P>
   The air attacks began Wednesday after Milosevic refused to
accede to demands from Washington and other western governments
that he agree to a cease-fire in Kosovo, grant ethnic Albanians
broad autonomy there and allow a NATO force to police the deal.
</P>
<P>
   Kosovo is a southern province of Serbia. Two pieces of the old
Yugoslavia, Serbia and Montenegro, make up what now is formally
known as the Federal Republic of Yugoslavia.
</P>
<P>
   At the White House, Clinton was briefed by security advisers and
renewed his view that airstrikes, without follow-up ground
operations, could break Milosevic.
</P>
<P>
   ``I believe we can create a situation in which we have limited
(Yugoslavia's) ability to make war and thereby increase the
prospects that (the Kosovar Albanians) can protect themselves
better,'' Clinton said.
</P>
<P>
   As in the first night, the initial barrage Thursday was cruise
missiles fired from U.S. warships in the Adriatic, to the west of
the Balkans. The Associated Press said that the USS Gonzalez fired
first but that two of the 18 missiles launched from the destroyer
failed and fell into the sea.
</P>
<P>
   Secretary of State Madeleine Albright said the campaign against
Milosevic's installations continued because ``nothing has changed.
He has not gotten the message yet.''
</P>
<P>
   Albright said diplomatic challenges remain open, but NATO
Secretary-General Javier Solana said, ``We don't have any positive
response from President Milosevic.''
</P>
<P>
   After Albright's and Solana's briefings, Yugoslav Deputy Prime
Minister Vuk Draskovic suggested in a telephone interview with
Britain's Sky television that the Belgrade government was prepared
for new talks.
</P>
<P>
   ``Stop bombing us and we will stop all operations against the
people, the terrorists who provoked NATO strikes against Serbia,''
Draskovic said. In Serbian parlance, ``terrorist'' referred to the
Albanian guerrillas in Kosovo.
</P>
<P>
   Earlier, Prime Minister Massimo D'Alema of Italy, whose nation
is host to several NATO air bases, proposed a return to diplomacy.
</P>
<P>
   ``We think that the time to give politics and diplomacy their
say is approaching,'' D'Alema said, contending the initial air
attacks had forced Serbs to halt their assaults in Kosovo.
</P>
<P>
   Berger contradicted D'Alema on the point, saying: ``That's not
correct. We'll obviously point that out to him.''
</P>
<P>
   Clark said degrading Milosevic's military force was ``a tough
challenge.''
</P>
<P>
   ``We have a lot of respect for the Serb air defense
capabilities,'' Clark said, although there was little evidence much
use was made of the systems Wednesday and Thursday. ``It's a
country that has long prepared itself for war, and unfortunately
its armed forces have gained rather a lot of military experience
over the past decade.''
</P>
<P>
   Clark said that in the first night's bombardment there were not
strikes on central Belgrade, the Yugoslav capital, but he added:
``President Milosevic and his military leaders should understand
that there is no sanctuary for them, their military forces ...,
because they're part of the mechanism of the Serb military and
security forces, and the repression.''
</P>
<P>
   Across Kosovo's southern border, in the Macedonian capital of
Skopje, an angry crowd of about 2,000 massed outside the U.S.
Embassy and a hotel where international journalists and aid workers
are staying. The demonstrators threw fire bombs at the embassy and
hurled stones at cars in the hotel parking lot.
</P>
<P>
   The demonstration, at dusk Balkan time, ended soon after
Macedonian security forces arrived.
</P>
<P>
   ``They're all safe,'' Albright said of embassy personnel.
</P>
<P>
   Protesters also gathered outside the embassies of three other
NATO nations _ France, Britain and Germany. Police dispersed them
with tear gas.
</P>
<P>
   Macedonia, a former republic of Yugoslavia that was recognized
as independent in 1993, has a Serbian minority population.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
XXXX END OF STORY &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
