<HEADLINE>
DRIVERS LIKE `DRY' RUN IN RETURN TO TMS
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By JOHNNY D. BOGGS 
c.1999 Special to Fort Worth Star-Telegram 
<TEXT>
<P>
   FORT WORTH, Texas _ No rain. No major injuries. No complaints.
And the only ``weeping'' yesterday probably came from Mark Martin
fans, who saw Dave Blaney bump the two-time Texas Motor Speedway
winner off the Busch Grand National pole.
</P>
<P>
   After a $3.2 million revamping of the oft-maligned TMS, NASCAR
drivers gave a thumbs-up to the superspeedway Darrell Waltrip
compared to the Alamo last year.
</P>
<P>
   ``I think they did a good job,'' said Terry Labonte, a NASCAR
Winston Cup regular who is also competing in tomorrow's BGN
Coca-Cola 300.
</P>
<P>
   Added Kenny Irwin Jr.: ``The track is the best it has ever
been.''
</P>
<P>
   That's a far cry from last year, when NASCAR officials demanded
speedway improvements after drainage problems that had water
``weeping'' through the pavement. Or from 1997 and '98, when
drivers seethed over the transition coming off Turn 4. The only
blemishes on yesterday's events might have been five drivers
hitting the wall in Turn 2.
</P>
<P>
   Reconstruction on the 1.5-mile speedway began April 22 after
Martin won the NASCAR Winston Cup event on April 5. A new drainage
system was installed, and the entrances and exits of the turns were
modified.
</P>
<P>
   Eddie Gossage, TMS vice president and general manager, praised
speedway owner Bruton Smith for the speedway's new look.
</P>
<P>
   ``Bruton walked in my door last year and said we need to fix
it,'' Gossage said. ``And I said, `I agree. Give me a budget.' And
he said, `Fix it.' ''
</P>
<P>
   Yesterday, the main complaint from drivers seemed to be about a
bump between Turn 1 and Turn 2.
</P>
<P>
   But even that didn't bother Busch driver Adam Petty.
</P>
<P>
   ``Sure, it might be a fixable bump,'' he said, ``but it's also a
characteristic of this racetrack. It's just something you have to
work around.''
</P>
<P>
   Gossage said he sat in Jeff Gordon's motorhome yesterday and
``had a much different conversation than we had last year.''
</P>
<P>
   What did Gordon say last year?
</P>
<P>
   ``I can't repeat that,'' Gossage said.
</P>
<P>
   ``He was like a lot of the other drivers. ... When it was all
said and done, they apologized for what they said and we apologized
for what we said, and everything kind of snowballed last year.''
</P>
<P>
   Gordon said he found the track similar to how it was last year,
except that ``it's dry. There's no water on the track.''
</P>
<P>
   ``But I really don't have any complaints about the racetrack,''
he said.
</P>
<P>
   Gossage said the fact that practice started on time after a
half-inch of rain fell Wednesday night should put the ``weeping''
rumors to rest. But he's approaching the weekend with caution.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'm not about to stand here and tell you mission
accomplished,'' he said. ``We'll let \Rthe drivers\S tell you.''
</P>
<P>
   But yesterday was a good start.
</P>
<P>
   ``I think things are OK, but we've got to prove ourselves,''
Gossage said. ``And that's what we're going to try to do this
weekend.''
nn
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
