<SLUG> BC-CREDIT-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
TREASURY PRICES EASE AS FED MEETING IS AWAITED 
</HEADLINE>
   (bl)  
 By ROBERT HURTADO   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEW YORK _ Prices of Treasury securities sagged Thursday as
market participants awaited next week's meeting of the Federal
Reserve's policy-setting committee.
</P>
<P>
   The yield on the 30-year bond was up 5 basis points, or
hundredths of a percentage point, to 5.58 percent, from 5.53
percent Wednesday. Its price, which moves in the opposite
direction, fell 23/32, to 96 7/32.
</P>
<P>
   Most investors were also waiting for fresh signs that the
economy was indeed slowing before making a stronger commitment to
buy government securities. The rally in the stock market also meant
that some cash found its way out of Treasuries and into the
corporate debt and equity markets. The Dow Jones industrial average
gained 169.55 points, finishing at 9,836.39
</P>
<P>
   A heavy supply of competing paper also applied pressure to
Treasury securities, as Citigroup and Mexico led a pack of
borrowers to the public debt market. Corporations and other
borrowers have been offering higher yields than Treasuries have
been offering on new debt, and this week's sales showed decent
demand, according to some traders.
</P>
<P>
   Mexico sold $1 billion in global bonds Thursday through Morgan
Stanley Dean Witter with a 9.75 percent coupon at a price to yield
449 basis points more than Treasuries. Citigroup is expected to
price a two-part global bond deal Friday: $750 million each in
five-year and 10-year maturities. Salomon Smith Barney is the lead
underwriter.
</P>
<P>
   Anthony Chan, managing director and chief economist for Banc One
Investment Advisors in Columbus, Ohio, said, ``Perhaps the only
consolation that the credit markets can derive at present is that a
few fundamental factors should continue to lessen some of
investors' greatest fears.'' Looking toward Tuesday's meeting of
the Federal Open Market Committee, he said it was unlikely ``that
policy-makers will do anything to rock the boat,''especially given
the possibility that the military action against Yugoslavia could
have a negative impact on consumer sentiment.
</P>
<P>
   With investors alert for any signs that the economy is slowing
or that inflation is picking up, there has been little to change
expectations.
</P>
<P>
   Economic reports Thursday offered renewed signs of economic
strength. For the seventh consecutive week, movement in initial
unemployment claims kept the four-week moving average in claims
below 300,000.
</P>
<P>
   Although sales of existing homes were down somewhat, Chan said,
they were not soft enough relative to expectations to indicate that
the housing sector would put a damper on economic growth.
</P>
</TEXT>
