<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-03-25 21:30 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A4435 &Cx1f; taf-z
u i &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-EUROPEAN-UNION-NYT &LR;      03-25 0887
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-EUROPEAN-UNION-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
EUROPEAN UNION STRUGGLES TO AGREE ON BUDGET REFORM 
</HEADLINE>
  (mk) 
 By ROGER COHEN   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   BERLIN _ Leaders of the European Union struggled early Friday to
reach an agreement on a reform of the 15-nation bloc's $92 billion
annual budget that would eventually make it possible for Poland,
the Czech Republic and Hungary to join.
</P>
<P>
   A sometimes bitter conflict that took the summit meeting into
early Friday morning, more than 12 hours past its scheduled
conclusion at noon Thursday, pitted northern nations that tend to
be the main contributors to the budget against southern countries
that are its main beneficiaries.
</P>
<P>
   Germany, whose net annual contribution to the budget of about
$12 billion is by far the largest, appeared determined to complete
negotiations that have become an important test for the Social
Democratic chancellor, Gerhard Schroeder, but France, Spain and
Italy seemed unready to compromise.
</P>
<P>
   Joschka Fischer, the German foreign minister, described the
talks as ``extremely difficult,'' because they involve ``large
amounts of money and legitimate national interests.'' He added that
he was not ready to predict success.
</P>
<P>
   But having worked tirelessly on the budget issue over the past
10 days, visiting most European capitals, Schroeder seemed
unwilling to abandon an effort seen by Germany as critical to
cementing the unity of Europe by bringing in former East Bloc
members. After a shaky first six months in office, the chancellor
is also in acute need of a conspicuous diplomatic success.
</P>
<P>
   The chief stumbling blocks to an accord, officials said, were
French resistance to reforms of an expensive European agricultural
policy that benefits its more than 1 million farmers; Spanish
objections to cuts in a regional fund that provides European Union
money to poorer countries, and objections from several delegations
to a rebate Britain receives that is worth more than $3 billion a
year.
</P>
<P>
   European farm spending, under a system that is designed to
shield the Union's farmers from lower world market prices, accounts
for about half of the European Union budget. With its big
agricultural sector, and its highly vocal farmers, France is
extremely sensitive to any attempt to change the way agricultural
policy works.
</P>
<P>
   But Germany, with a much smaller farm sector and the absolute
conviction that without reform spending would spiral if new members
were admitted, has proposed that outlay on agriculture be capped at
about $44 billion a year for the period from 2000 to 2006.
</P>
<P>
   Like France, Spain also objected to reform, both in the farm
sector and in the various forms of regional aid that go to poorer
European countries. This aid, designed to bring all European Union
countries to broadly the same economic level, accounts for close to
a third of the European budget.
</P>
<P>
   ``Spain will not accept any cuts from the level of funding it
now receives,'' the Spanish finance minister, Rodrigo de Rato,
said. Greece's prime minister, Costas Simitis, also objected to any
change. ``Our per-capita income is 20 percent below the European
average,'' he said. ``You can't say we do not need help anymore.''
</P>
<P>
   Behind the squabbling, it was clear that lethargic economies in
Europe have made leaders extremely sensitive to any suggestion that
funding will be cut off. There is simply not enough money in
national coffers to compensate for any European funds that are
withdrawn.
</P>
<P>
   With money such a sensitive issue, several countries focused on
the more than $3 billion that Britain has been receiving as a
rebate each year since 1984. The payment, negotiated by Margaret
Thatcher, represents about 60 percent of the difference between its
contributions and the amount Britain receives in European Union
spending.
</P>
<P>
   ``Fourteen countries say Britain has to make an effort,'' the
Belgian finance minister, Jean-Jacques Viseur, said. ``If not, it
will be impossible for the others to be flexible in their budget
contributions.''
</P>
<P>
   The arguments inevitably seemed trivial as several of the
countries at the summit meeting pursued a bombing campaign in
Yugoslavia as part of the NATO force attacking there. Leaders
appeared aware that an agreement would amount to a critical display
of European unity at a sensitive time, while failure would be
ominous.
</P>
<P>
   As they talked, the leaders came under scathing criticism from
prime minister Benjamin Netanyahu of Israel, who said they were
about to ``dictate to Israel the results of the negotiations with
the Palestinians by supporting a Palestinian state.''
</P>
<P>
   Netanyahu's outburst was apparently based on a draft of a
statement the leaders intend to make on the situation in the Middle
East. Officials said the European leaders appeared to ready to
refer explicitly to a Palestinian right to a state and to say that,
while this state should emerge from negotiation, Israel had no
right to veto it.
</P>
<P>
   Such wording, if approved, would go beyond previous official
European positions and anything said up to now by the United States
about Palestinian statehood.
</P>
<P>
   ``It is especially regrettable that it is Europe, where one
third of the Jewish nation perished, that deems fit to impose a
solution that endangers the Jewish state and contradicts its
interests,'' Netanyahu said.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
