<SLUG> BC-KEVORKIAN-TRIAL-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
JURY DELIBERATES IN KEVORKIAN'S TRIAL ON MURDER CHARGES
</HEADLINE>
  (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By TATSHA ROBERTSON  
 c.1999 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   PONTIAC, Mich. _ Whether Dr. Jack Kevorkian is a martyr trying
to end the suffering of those close to death or a cold-blooded
killer who used a dying man to heighten his own political agenda
will be left for a Michigan jury to decide Friday.
</P>
<P>
   Legal analysts said there is a strong case against Kervorkian,
70, who videotaped himself administering a lethal injection of
chemicals to 52-year-old Thomas Youk. But they questioned whether
the jury would decide to send the elderly crusader to prison for
the rest of his life.
</P>
<P>
   Jurors discussed the case for five hours Thursday and will
resume deliberations this morning. Kevorkian was charged with
first-degree murder, but Judge Jessica Cooper told jurors they
could consider second-degree murder or involuntary manslaughter.
</P>
<P>
   By noon Thursday, Kevorkian and the prosecution had completed
spirited _ and often unorthodox _ final arguments, but the media
spectacle on the third floor of Oakland County Courthouse had just
begun.
</P>
<P>
   About 50 disabled protesters, calling themselves ``Not Dead
Yet,'' sat in the courtroom and lined the court halls in their
wheelchairs. Some stood outside the courthouse chanting ``Jail
Jack.'' Dozens of reporters, from all over the world, packed into a
tiny room to watch the trial unfold.
</P>
<P>
   Part of the chaos resulted from the fact that the man known as
``Doctor Death'' was acting for the first time in five trials as
his own lawyer. Believing that only he could argue the case with
the proper passion, Kevorkian insisted on leading his own defense,
a condition that was unacceptable to his former attorney, Geoffrey
Fieger.
</P>
<P>
   Kevorkian, who says he has presided over 130 assisted suicides,
including four Massachusetts residents since 1996, has been at the
forefront in the debate over physician-assisted suicide. He has
been tried four times on assisted-suicide charges, three ending in
acquittal, and one in a mistrial. This was the first time he was
charged with murder.
</P>
<P>
   ``Just look at me,'' Kevorkian said in his final arguments,
which lasted 25 minutes. ``Honestly, do you see a criminal and a
murderer? If you do, you must convict. And then, take the harsh
judgment of history. And if you don't, then you must acquit.''
</P>
<P>
   When Circuit Judge Jessica Cooper threw out Kevorkian's request
to allow Youk's family to testify, he was left to convince the jury
that he did not deliberately kill Youk, who suffered from
amyotrophic lateral sclerosis, better known as Lou Gehrig's
disease.
</P>
<P>
   Wearing a gray suit and maroon tie, Kevorkian rambled in his
final arguments and seemed exasperated as the prosecution hammered
away with objections. At one time, he apologized when the
prosecution argued that Kevorkian was testifying rather than given
his final statement.
</P>
<P>
   He seemed the antithesis of John Skrzynski, the smooth-talking
prosecutor who characterized Kevorkian as a man on a fatal mission.
</P>
<P>
   ``He came like a medical hitman in the night,'' said Skrzynski,
who argued that Kevorkian staged Youk's death last September, when
he gave the videotape to CBS News's ``60 Minutes.''
</P>
<P>
   ``But that wasn't a movie. That was a man killed before your
eyes,'' Skrzynski said.
</P>
<P>
   But Kevorkian, comparing himself to civil rights leaders, told
jurors that he was anything but a criminal. ``When Rosa Parks sat
on the bus, was that a crime?'' Kevorkian asked. ``Did Martin
Luther King want to go to jail?''
</P>
<P>
   Kevorkian argued that he was doing his duty as a physician when
he injected Youk with the lethal dose of chemicals.
</P>
<P>
   Irving Tukel, a Michigan defense lawyer, said that if the jury
focuses on the facts of the case, they would convict. But if they
acquit, it could be an example of ``jury nullification,'' in which
jurors essentially declare the law invalid.
</P>
<P>
   ``He has a message that a lot of people like,'' Tukel said. He
added: ``He himself makes it very difficult to like him.''
</P>
<P>
   When the jury broke for lunch Thursday, Youk's widow told
reporters that she was hurt when the judge refused to allow her to
speak on Kevorkian's behalf.
</P>
<P>
   Several minutes later, Kevorkian sat at a table in the
courthouse lunchroom with his legal advisers and Youk's relatives.
While he ate a hot dog and chips, protesters sitting near him
prayed aloud that he would lose the case.
</P>
<P>
   Don Downey, 30, said that when he was paralyzed 10 years ago
after an accident, he thought his life wasn't worth living.
</P>
<P>
   ``I probably would have accepted Kevorkian's offer,'' he said.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
