<SLUG> BC-KOSOVO-DAMAGE-HNS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
NATO COMMANDER CALLS AIRSTRIKES `SUCCESSFUL' 

</HEADLINE>
  
 (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  (Also see: KOSOVO-AIM, KOSOVO-NATO and KOSOVO-BUSH) 
 
By GREG McDONALD 
c.1999 Houston Chronicle 
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON _ Allied commanders offered a cautious but positive
assessment Thursday of NATO's bombardment of Yugoslav targets as
the second round of air attacks ended, saying that the strikes had
cost Serb forces several fighter aircraft and had seriously damaged
their military infrastructure.
</P>
<P>
   Speaking to reporters at NATO headquarters in Brussels, Belgium,
Gen. Wesley Clark, the alliance's supreme commander, called the
strikes against dozens of targets ``successful'' and insisted that
the aerial assault dubbed Operation Allied Force will continue
until Yugoslav President Slobodan Milosevic ends the violence
against ethnic Albanians in the Serbian province of Kosovo and
agrees to a peaceful settlement.
</P>
<P>
   ``We are determined to continue until we have achieved our
objectives to hold the violence and to stop further humanitarian
catastrophe,'' Clark said.
</P>
<P>
   Contrary to claims by the Belgrade government that some U.S.
planes had been shot down, Clark said that the allied forces had
suffered no casualties and all aircraft involved in the operation
had returned to their bases safely on both nights of the assault.
He said the Serbs had put up little resistance to the attacks
Wednesday and again Thursday night from their air defense systems,
which is one of the primary targets.
</P>
<P>
   ``We know (the Yugoslav military) has some formidable
capabilities. We just didn't see them,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   But the Yugoslav air force, he said, did send up at least three
Russian-made MiG-29s, which are the most sophisticated aircraft in
Milosovic's arsenal, to engage two U.S. F-15s and a Dutch F-16
during the initial air strikes Wednesday night. The MiGs, he said,
were shot down.
</P>
<P>
   ``The principle opposition seemed to be some fighter aircraft
that were brought up against us. At least three were destroyed,''
he said.
</P>
<P>
   Clark also acknowledged that one U.S. plane was forced to make
an emergency landing in Bosnia, but it was because of a maintenance
problem unrelated to the NATO air assault. A Pentagon official said
the plane had been on a routine mission over Bosnia in connection
with the ongoing peacekeeping mission there.
</P>
<P>
   Serb military leaders claimed Thursday that two NATO aircraft
had been shot down in the second round of attacks. But Defense
Secretary William Cohen told reporters that no NATO planes had been
downed, and all had returned to their bases.
</P>
<P>
   Clark and other U.S. military officials at the Pentagon refused
to provide specific details of the attacks or the damage done. They
said satellite surveillance and film taken of the bombardments from
the aircraft involved would be analyzed before any definitive
damage assessments are offered.
</P>
<P>
   But Clark nonetheless said that the nearly 400 aircraft and
several warships participating in the operation were fairly
accurate in carrying out their attacks on military command and
control facilities throughout Yugoslavia and on air defense
facilities, including fixed and mobile anti-aircraft installations.
</P>
<P>
   Pentagon officials said that three military airfields were hit
as well as one or two military-related factories near Belgrade.
</P>
<P>
   Yugoslav military officials told reporters, however, that little
damage had been done, and that many of the bombs and cruise missile
fired by the allies had missed their targets and struck in civilian
areas. They said at least 10 people were killed and 60 wounded by
the attacks.
</P>
<P>
   Russian military officials in Moscow said that the NATO strikes
had inflicted severe damage on five airfields, two factories, a
large military communications facility, and several bases housing
army and police security personnel.
</P>
<P>
   Lawmakers on Capitol Hill also said that the first night's
assault had apparently been successful in delivering blows to
Milosevic's military systems. Emerging from a briefing by State
Department and Pentagon officials, Sen. Kay Bailey Hutchison,
R-Texas, said she felt that the strikes had been ``successful at
this point, and it appears that we did well in combat.''
</P>
<P>
   But she quickly added that no one is is ready ``to declare
victory'' yet.
</P>
<P>
   ``The obvious effort is to go for military targets that would
curb the capability for Mr. Milosevic to harm his own people. And I
think that will be the first target and the second target, and the
third target,'' Hutchison said.
</P>
<P>
   The attacks Wednesday and Thursday both began with a barrage of
more than 50 cruise missiles launched from warships and from
aircraft. The missile attacks were followed by bombardments from
high-flying B-52s from bases in England. A number of F-117 stealth
bombers and various other aircraft based in Italy and at other NATO
facilities delivered their payloads over Kosovo and throughout
Yugoslavia.
</P>
<P>
   Two B-2 stealth bombers based in the United States also were
used to deliver 32 satellite-guided one-ton bombs. It was the first
combat test of the sophisticated aircraft, and Pentagon officials
said their targets included air defense systems and military
command facilities.
</P>
<P>
   In his briefing, Clark emphasized that the attacks would
continue to focus on ``carefully chosen military targets'' and that
every effort would be made to avoid damage to civilian areas. But
he refused to rule out the possibility of the allies going after
military targets in civilian areas, including various army and
government facilities in downtown Belgrade.
</P>
<P>
   He suggested that Milosevic could end up being a primary target.
</P>
<P>
   ``We're going to grind away at him until we accomplish the
military objectives, or until our political leaders tell us to
halt,'' Clark said.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
XXXX END OF STORY &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
