<HEADLINE>
MESSAGE COMES ACROSS WELL IN `DOUG'S 1ST MOVIE' 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients.)  
 By PAULA NECHAK  
 c.1999 Seattle Post-Intelligencer  
<TEXT>
<P>
   There's a nice message for kids at the heart of the animated
film, ``Doug's 1st Movie'': do the right thing and the truth will
eventually come out, no matter how unpopular the decision.
</P>
<P>
   That's sometimes a difficult concept for kids and preteens to
understand because they're suffering under peer pressure at school
and among their friends and don't always know what to do in a
crisis. Especially when the crisis concerns a powerful adult who is
doing the wrong thing. Who will believe a 12-year-old when his
nemesis is the town's richest man?
</P>
<P>
   Doug lives in the small burg of Bluffington, has an equally
nerdy best friend named Skeeter and a nifty little dog named
Porkchop.
</P>
<P>
   He also has a major crush on Patti Mayonnaise. But every time
Doug creates a plan to get close to Patti, it backfires in his
face.
</P>
<P>
   Take the Valentine's Day dance, for example. Doug and Patti sign
up to do decorations together but upperclassman Guy Graham, the
school newspaper editor and the minion of millionaire Bill Bluff,
has his eye on Patti as well.
</P>
<P>
   Doug and Skeeter have been occupied researching the legend of
the monster of polluted Lucky Duck Lake. And when they discover the
monster really exists and isn't scary at all, just a sweet-natured
goof, the boys are faced with a dilemma.
</P>
<P>
   If Doug doesn't rescue Herman the monster from Bluff's evil plan
designed to cover up his illegal dumping of industrial waste into
the town's water, he could lose Patti to Guy. He's confronted by a
tough decision: can he expose Bluff's bluff and save Herman and
risk losing the girl of his dreams?
</P>
<P>
   The screen adventures of Doug originate from the popular
Saturday morning TV series, ``Disney's Doug.'' It was the
brainchild of creator Jim Jinkins, who admits that he's pulled
Doug's adventures from many of his own experiences growing up, and
that he believes one of the biggest fears kids face is looking
foolish in front of their peers.
</P>
<P>
   Jinkins blended that idea into the movie's plot and ``Doug's 1st
Movie'' nicely conveys, and puts into context, a worthy moral ideal
that compensates for its ho-hum animation, and which kept kids (and
adults) in a preview audience involved _ and listening.
</P>
<P>
   Doug's 1st Movie. Directed by Maurice Joyce. Written by Ken
Scarborough. Walt Disney Pictures. 77 minutes. Rated G.
</P>
<P>
   Grade: B-
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-03-25-99 2135EST &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
