</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-KOSOVO-POLICY-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
THE STEPS, AND MISSTEPS, BEHIND THE DECISION TO USE FORCE
</HEADLINE>
   (See also: KOSOVO-RDP, KOSOVO-MILITARY, KOSOVO-MILITARY-ASSESS,
KOSOVO-GERMANY, KOSOVO-POLICY, KOSOVO-BELGRADE, KOSOVO-PRISTINA,
KOSOVO-MACEDONIA, KOSOVO-REPORTERS, KOSOVO-CHINA,
KOSOVO-RUSSIA-ASSESS, KOSOVO-CLINTON, KOSOVO-ITALY, KOSOVO-VOICES,
KOSOVO-B2, KOSOVO-EUROPE-REAX, KOSOVO-U.N., KOSOVO-CLARK-PROFILE.) 
(wg) 
 By JANE PERLEZ   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON _ In the last week, before the decision was made at
the White House that force would be used against Yugoslavia, the
impending visit of Prime Minister Yevgeny Primakov of Russia became
a focal point that helped push the administration to act sooner
than it had planned, according to officials.
</P>
<P>
   And as the White House moved closer to using the force it did
not want to, the most hawkish member of the foreign policy team,
Secretary of State Madeleine Albright, whose public reputation had
been blemished by failed peace talks in France, was able to hold
her own in the inner sanctums, officials said.
</P>
<P>
   Even so, National Security Adviser Sandy Berger has probably
carried the most clout with President Clinton on Kosovo, as he has
on all foreign policy, administration officials said.
</P>
<P>
   The Primakov trip was important because initially the White
House had thought it would delay military action against Yugoslav
President Slobodan Milosevic until after the Russian leader's
visit.
</P>
<P>
   But as the situation on the ground in Kosovo deteriorated
dramatically last Friday and Saturday, Vice President Al Gore, who
was to be Primakov's host, argued forcefully that the credibility
of NATO was more important than paying attention to the
sensitivities of the Russians.
</P>
<P>
   ``He made the case that you do do not want to subordinate NATO's
interest to Russia and give Milosevic another week to clean up,''
an administration official said of the vice president, who has been
the administration's chief liaison with Russian prime ministers.
</P>
<P>
   Piecing together the steps that led the administration to make
the decision to back NATO action against Yugoslavia, officials
describe an unfolding series of milestones and missed opportunities
that stretch all the way back to the beginning of the wars in the
former Yugoslavia.
</P>
<P>
   It would have been preferable, for example, some officials now
acknowledge, if Milosevic's side-kick in Serbian-held Bosnia,
Radovan Karadzic, had been arrested by NATO troops in Bosnia three
years ago and taken to the international tribunal at the Hague,
Netherlands, where he could have been ``squeezed'' for information
on Milosevic.
</P>
<P>
   But more immediately, as Milosevic took aim at the ethnic
Albanian guerrillas in Kosovo early last year, the administration
paid only sporadic attention.
</P>
<P>
   Ambassador Robert Gelbard, a State Department official whose
portfolio included Kosovo, warned Milosevic in February of last
year that he was at a ``crossroads'' as the Yugoslav leader massed
troops for a campaign against the guerrillas.
</P>
<P>
   Milosevic unleashed his forces last spring, and some
administration officials look back at that moment as one of several
missed opportunities to curb the conflict early on.
</P>
<P>
   By early summer, Gelbard was replaced by Clinton's special
envoy, Richard Holbrooke, who believed that it was possible to
negotiate with the Yugoslav leader.
</P>
<P>
   Holbrooke visited Kosovo in May and June, described the village
of Kijevo as ``the most dangerous place in Europe,'' and declared
that NATO was prepared to carry out airstrikes against Serbia.
</P>
<P>
   But as Clinton's choice as representative to the United Nations,
Holbrooke was never on the Kosovo case full-time.
</P>
<P>
   And at the State Department, the Kosovo problem was swept into
the Bureau of European Affairs where Milosevic's summer offensive
using tanks and artillery against ethnic Albanian villages was
noticed but not dramatized.
</P>
<P>
   By last September, Milosevic appeared to have overstepped the
bounds of acceptability when on one day alone, his police units
massacred an entire family of more than 20 people and summarily
executed 13 men.
</P>
<P>
   At NATO headquarters, political support rallied for airstrikes
against Milosevic, and NATO's Supreme Commander Gen. Wesley Clark
pulled together an armada of aircraft ready for attack in October.
</P>
<P>
   Backed by the threat of NATO force, Holbrooke was sent to
Belgrade to talk with Milosevic. He haggled for nine days in
Belgrade, and at the end flew to Brussels, Belgium, arriving at 2
a.m., to announce a deal that involved the dispatch of unarmed
European monitors but not NATO forces.
</P>
<P>
   In Washington, with the exception perhaps of Albright, who has
always argued that Milosevic only responded to force, there was
relief. Holbrooke's package, which included the drawdown of Serbian
forces, was broadly welcomed.
</P>
<P>
   But at the same time, the steam went out of NATO's resolve and
the White House, relieved that force did not have to be used,
settled back into hoping that Milosevic would keep his commitments.
</P>
<P>
   By January, it was clear he would not. President Clinton was
reluctant to counter with NATO airstrikes, officials said.
</P>
<P>
   First, Congress was fragmented, although Sen. John Warner,
D-Va., and the chairman of the Armed Services Committee, backed
NATO intervention. Second, there was the specter of a failed
mission like that in Somalia when 19 American Army Rangers were
killed, reinforced by the fear of getting involved in a
little-known corner of the world, even though it was Europe.
</P>
<P>
   ``There was a desire to believe that the threat of force was
better than the use of force,'' said an official who has watched
the White House policy evolve.
</P>
<P>
   After the peace talks in France ended with only the ethnic
Albanians signing, Holbrooke was sent to Belgrade to deal with
Milosevic for a ``last chance.'' The engines of the NATO planes
were warming up but there were hopes in the White House that a
final collision course could be avoided, a senior official said.
</P>
<P>
   Afterward, a muted Holbrooke said that Milosevic had not even
engaged himself and had repeated his own propaganda that the
violence in Kosovo was between ethnic Albanians killing ethnic
Albanians and ethnic Albanians killing Serbs.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
