<DOCNO> NYT19990325.0352 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-03-25 21:43 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A4447 &Cx1f; tad-z
u i &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-US-BUSH-ON-KOSOVO26-C     03-25 0793
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-US-BUSH-ON-KOSOVO26-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Bush offers conditional backing of Kosovo bombing
 &HT;    By Ken Herman
 &HT;    c.1999 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   AUSTIN, Texas _ A day after other GOP presidential hopefuls
weighed in, Gov. George W. Bush on Thursday dipped a toe into
complex foreign policy and announced conditional support for
U.S.-backed military action in Yugoslavia.
</P>
<P>
   When the bombs began falling Wednesday, Bush went jogging
instead of attending what have become customary meetings with
reporters after his private sessions with backers of his
presidential campaign. Later Wednesday, he issued a noncommittal
statement and evaded reporters' questions after an appearance in
Grapevine.
</P>
<P>
   In between that and his regular duties, Bush was fielding advice
from policy advisers. By Thursday afternoon, after being pressed by
reporters, Bush had a press conference to make his views known on
the unfolding drama in the Balkans.
</P>
<P>
   ``As governor of Texas, I do not have access to all the
information and military intelligence available to the commander in
chief,'' said Bush, adding that he knew enough to ``share the
concerns and misgivings of many Texans and Americans.''
</P>
<P>
   ``Any time we commit American troops, I believe we must have a
clear mission, an achievable goal and a credible exit strategy,''
he said. ``The ultimate question is, will this military action lead
to the goal of ending the conflict and bringing peace and stability
to the region.''
</P>
<P>
   Bush said his misgivings concern whether there is a plan that
will avoid leaving the military ``mired into a region without an
exit strategy.''
</P>
<P>
   But the governor and probable presidential candidate also said
the United States and its allies had to carry through on threats to
use force. Asked if the threats were reasonable, Bush said, ``I
don't have enough information to be able to make that type of
criticism at the present.''
</P>
<P>
   ``My worry is the worry of a lot of people I have heard from in
Texas, and that is, will the air strikes achieve the president's
stated mission of bringing Milosevic to the peace table to sign an
accord with Kosovo,'' he said. ``And if not, what next?''
</P>
<P>
   Before Bush offered his views, other GOP presidential candidates
and likely candidates took to the air waves and their Web sites to
offer their opinions on the NATO effort. Elizabeth Dole said the
action ``can be instrumental in forging a peaceful solution to a
dangerous, escalating military conflict.'' Pat Buchanan blasted it
as an unnecessary intervention into ``an ugly civil war inside
Yugoslavia.''
</P>
<P>
   Steve Forbes backed the bombing and said the defenders of Kosovo
should be provided arms to defend themselves. Dan Quayle said he
and Bush's dad handled it better than President Clinton is.
</P>
<P>
   ``I can tell you what we did when I was vice president with
George Bush. We said privately and publicly, but more importantly
privately to Milosevic, stay out of Kosovo,'' Quayle said on CNN.
</P>
<P>
   Gov. Bush's only comments Wednesday dealt with the safety of the
troops, not the merits of their mission. ``My thoughts and prayers
are with our American fighting men and women and their families.
And I wish our troops a safe and speedy return,'' he said in a
statement issued by his office.
</P>
<P>
   Wednesday evening, as Clinton spoke to the nation about the
decision to begin the bombing, Bush was at a ribbon-cutting
ceremony for an outdoors store in Grapevine.
</P>
<P>
   It took more than one attempt by reporters to get Bush to
respond to questions about the bombing.
</P>
<P>
   ``I hope the men and women come back safely,'' he said, before
hustling to a waiting car.
</P>
<P>
   While other candidates were quicker to respond, Bush advisers
felt the weight of working for a man who may be on a direct path to
the White House, polls indicate. They wanted to make sure Bush was
as informed as possible before offering his views on a delicate and
complicated situation. An aide said privately that Bush advisers
realize his words, even 20 months before the presidential election,
could carry far more weight than those offered by contenders who
polls indicate have little chance of becoming president.
</P>
<P>
   Input to Bush came from Condoleezza Rice and Josh Bolten,
advisers to his presidential exploratory committee. Rice, who will
leave her post as Stanford University provost in June to dedicate
more time to the Bush campaign, was a top adviser to President Bush
when the Soviet Union fell apart and Germany came back together.
</P>
<P>
   Bolten, most recently with Goldman Sachs in London, is new to
the Bush campaign. In addition to private law practice, Bolten has
worked for the State Department and the U.S. Senate Finance
Committee.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
