<DOCNO> NYT19990325.0353 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-03-25 21:45 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A4449 &Cx1f; tdt-z
u a &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-MEDIA-COVERAGE-BOS &LR;      03-25 0858
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-MEDIA-COVERAGE-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
EXPULSION OF JOURNALISTS COULD AFFECT US REACTION TO ATTACKS
</HEADLINE>
  (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By MARK JURKOWITZ  
 c.1999 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   Thursday's expulsion of Western journalists and continuing
crackdown on the media by Serbian authorities could have major
political implications for the Clinton administration's military
campaign in the Balkans.
</P>
<P>
   In an era when televised images of conflict _ from the unrest in
Tiananmen Square to US casualties in Somalia _ can galvanize public
opinion, what happens if this war provides nothing more dramatic
than chatty pundits, NATO briefings, and blurry shots of distant
explosions?
</P>
<P>
   Some observers say a war that can't be seen and felt on live
television benefits the White House by keeping Americans
emotionally detached from the conflict and preventing the hot
breath of public opinion from affecting its strategy.
</P>
<P>
   Fordham University communications professor Everette Dennis
said, ``I think the visual connection is absolutely vital Friday''
to engage citizen interest in military action. ``Maps, charts, and
talking heads . . . it's not compelling.''
</P>
<P>
   Unless public interest in the Kosovo crisis ratchets up, ``I'd
say it's advantageous for the White House,'' added Richard
Falkenrath, assistant professor at Harvard's Kennedy School of
Government. ``The more benign and apathetic the public response,
the better. You don't run military strikes by town meeting.''
</P>
<P>
   Even the dramatic television moments relayed back from Operation
Desert Storm and Somalia were only snapshots provided by
journalists whose access to combat was constrained. But at least
they were there. In Yugoslavia, the images will be even more
constrained.
</P>
<P>
   After its shutdown of television transmission facilities Monday,
Serbian authorities further tightened control of the media Thursday
by expelling reporters.
</P>
<P>
   Amid reports of threats, harassment, and detention (and the
torching of a CNN vehicle), many network journalists were forced to
leave the scene. ABC's last five staffers in Belgrade made it to
Hungary Thursday. The CBS crew ended up in Macedonia and Croatia.
CNN's team headed for Macedonia, Croatia, and Belgium. It was from
Brussels Thursday that Christianne Amanpour said the forced exodus
``denies the world an opportunity to see what's going on.'' Only
NBC managed to keep two correspondents _ Ron Allen and Jim Maceda _
in Belgrade.
</P>
<P>
   With journalists headed for safety, Thursday was a surreal day
in the coverage of the conflict, with much more talk than action.
NATO, State Department, and Pentagon briefings were carried only by
the cable news networks. Word of the launching of a second day of
strikes against Serbian forces came not from reporters on the
ground, but from the Pentagon's press spokesman Ken Bacon. At one
point, CNN aired reports of possible NATO attacks posted on the
Internet by Belgrade-area residents who heard explosions.
</P>
<P>
   ``It seems like there's a dearth of knowledge and pictures,''
said WCVB-TV (Ch. 5) director of programming Elizabeth Cheng,
summing up the problem for network affiliates.
</P>
<P>
   If this modified news blackout continues, several competing
forces could control the spin from the battlefield. ``I think that
obviously, everyone's going to try and manage you guys,'' said
Richard Shultz, director of the Security Studies Program at the
Fletcher School of Law and Diplomacy.
</P>
<P>
   One obvious candidate is Yugoslav President Slobodan Milosevic,
who could provide a stream of pictures of civilians injured or
killed by errant NATO bombing.
</P>
<P>
   ``This guy learned the lesson from the Gulf War,'' said retired
Marine Corps General Bernard Trainor. ``He's manipulating things.
The networks, everybody, is depending on the coverage he's
providing.''
</P>
<P>
   Conversely, the US military could begin to dictate the tone of
coverage with upbeat damage assessments similar to those during the
Gulf War. That would help a Clinton administration seeking public
support, said John MacArthur, publisher of Harper's Magazine and
one of the plaintiffs in a lawsuit that accused the US military of
unfairly restricting the media during the Gulf War.
</P>
<P>
   US policymakers ``want the usual sort of nonemotional surgical
strikes in which we hit 16 of 19 targets Friday and successfully
hit an ammunition dump, and there'll be no one to contradict
them,'' he said. ``The less emotional and the less bloody the whole
thing is, the better it is for people who make war.''
</P>
<P>
   Still, some analysts say the volatile military situation _ and
NATO's strategy of bombing Serbia into submission _ could easily
and quickly transform the conflict into a public relations and
political nightmare.
</P>
<P>
   Keeping the story contained and the public disengaged might make
it ``easier to deal with complicated internal warfare like this,''
Shultz said. But ``I don't think it's realistic.''
</P>
<P>
   ``All you need is one picture,'' said MacArthur, recalling the
effect of the photo of a US serviceman being dragged through the
streets of Somalia. ``One downed pilot being held prisoner and you
can turn the whole thing around.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
