<DOC>
<DOCNO> NYT19990325.0354 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-03-25 21:47 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A4450 &Cx1f; ttj-z
u s &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-BKC-BIRD-MAGIC-HNS &LR;      03-25 1763
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BKC-BIRD-MAGIC-HNS </SLUG>
  
 (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
<TEXT>
<P>
   &QL;
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
``Those who believe in Magic and those who appreciate the beauty of
a rare Bird have come to see basketball's best and witness the
crowning of a new national champion.''
</P>
<P>
   _ NBC broadcaster Bryant Gumble, 1979 &QR;
</P>
<P>
   &UR; By JEROME SOLOMON &LR;  &QL; 
 &UR; c. 1999, Houston Chronicle &LR;  &QL; 
ST. PETERSBURG, Fla. _ They were the first of their kind.
</P>
<P>
   Few, if any, before them had the imagination to even dream of
doing what they could do. They scored, they rebounded, they passed,
they dribbled they did it all.
</P>
<P>
   They did it with too much flair for men their size. Too much,
that is, for it to be fair to compare them to anyone else. All
great athletes hate to lose, but to these two, losing was not an
option.
</P>
<P>
   They are why the 1979 NCAA Tournament championship game between
Michigan State and Indiana State posted the highest Nielsen
television rating of any game in college basketball history.
</P>
<P>
   Earvin ``Magic'' Johnson and Larry Bird. College basketball has
not been the same since.
</P>
<P>
   ``What made us so compelling to others was we were so different,
but to each other we were just alike,'' Johnson said. ``Both of us
would do whatever it took to win. And we were both doing it like no
one had done it before.
</P>
<P>
   ``Larry was a guy that could tear you up from 30 feet out with
fancy passes, a deadly jumper and a heart you can't match. Then
there I am, a 6-8 point guard running the show, making plays that
little guys used to, then going down low with the big guys, too.
People had never seen guys as big as we were doing it like that.
</P>
<P>
   ``Everybody wanted to see us get it on, and so did we.''
</P>
<P>
   The buildup to the most memorable NCAA Tournament final ever was
not about Michigan State, a school whose best NCAA finish had been
fourth place 22 years earlier, or Indiana State, a school that
prior to 1979 had never even been to the Tournament.
</P>
<P>
   It was about Magic vs. Bird, Bird vs. Magic.
</P>
<P>
   ``The talk started to build once the Tournament got going,''
then-Michigan State coach Jud Heathcote said. ``Before then, no one
was thinking about a No. 2 seed (Michigan State) playing in the
final against a No. 1 seed (Indiana State), but as we started
winning games, people got to thinking we could be there, then
started hoping we would be there.''
</P>
<P>
   By the time the two teams advanced to the Final Four in Salt
Lake City, the hype reached an unprecedented level.
</P>
<P>
   ``That was the first time the media descended upon the Final
Four en masse like that,'' said Heathcote, who arrived in St.
Petersburg on Thursday to attend his 27th consecutive Final Four.
``All the stories written that week were Magic vs. Bird, not
Michigan State against Indiana State or any of the other two teams
in the Final Four.
</P>
<P>
   ``And people are just dumb enough to believe what they read in
the newspaper, so there was no question in most people's minds that
they wanted to see Magic play against Bird. Even if it was
one-on-one, that was the only contest worth seeing in their
minds.''
</P>
<P>
   In the semifinals, Michigan State pummeled Penn, and Indiana
State survived a battle against DePaul.
</P>
<P>
   So the people got their wish, and the landscape of college
basketball changed forever.
</P>
<P>
   Now 20 years later, as the country focuses on whether Michigan
State, Duke, Ohio State or Connecticut will claim the last NCAA
basketball crown of the 1990s, the college game continues to
thrive, thanks to that Monday night in March 1979.
</P>
<P>
   The right tournament, the right time
</P>
<P>
   The NCAA Tournament had built a solid following by 1979, but
there were signs it was about to become an event as opposed to a
tournament.
</P>
<P>
   In 1973, the championship game was moved to Monday night and
televised nationally in prime time for the first time. Only
conference champions could play in the Tournament until 1975, when
the field jumped to 32 teams. Forty teams participated in the 1979
Tournament.
</P>
<P>
   Terms as commonplace in basketball as jump shots and free throws
were just being coined at the time. The phrase Final Four was not
part of the lexicon of college basketball until it appeared
capitalized in the Official Collegiate Basketball Guide prior to
the 1978-79 season.
</P>
<P>
   When the Tournament brackets come out now, all the talk is of
seeding. The 1977-78 season was the first time seeding was used in
the Tournament, and the following year all the teams were seeded in
the bracket, another first.
</P>
<P>
   Tickets used to be sold on a you-want-'em, you-got-'em basis,
with thousands given out complimentary. In 1978, complimentary
tickets were eliminated, and in 1979 the first public lottery for
Final Four tickets was held.
</P>
<P>
   Yes, the Tournament's popularity was increasing, but like the
Super Bowl, it needed that one special year to lift it from being
something of interest to sports fans to a happening that attracted
non-sports fans.
</P>
<P>
   Joe Namath and the New York Jets' victory over the Baltimore
Colts in Super Bowl III did it for pro football. Johnson and Bird
did it for the NCAA.
</P>
<P>
   ``The game was already on the launching pad,'' said
coach-turned-broadcaster Al McGuire, who teamed with Dick Enberg
and Billy Packer on NBC's television broadcast of the game. ``Then
Bird and Magic came along and pushed the button.''
</P>
<P>
   The NCAA championship game had its share of superstars prior to
Johnson and Bird.
</P>
<P>
   Famous basketball names such as Wilt Chamberlain, Bill Russell,
Jerry West, Lew Alcindor (Kareem Abdul-Jabbar), Elgin Baylor, Bill
Walton, Bill Bradley and David Thompson are among those who have
been named Most Outstanding Player of the Tournament.
</P>
<P>
   The title game also had its share of historic moments. Many
blacks had starred in the NCAA Tournament, but it wasn't until
Texas Western and its all-black starting five topped an all-white
Kentucky squad in the 1966 championship game that all the racial
barriers came tumbling down.
</P>
<P>
   UCLA's win over Villanova in the 1971 title game before 31,765
fans in the Astrodome proved that if the seats are there, people
will come. But when Bird and Johnson took to the court in 1979,
people who did not watch college basketball were fighting for seats
in front of the television.
</P>
<P>
   The right players, the right time
</P>
<P>
   NBC, which had purchased the rights to broadcast the Tournament
for a then-record $1.1 million a year in 1973, knew it had
something special with the Michigan State-Indiana State final.
</P>
<P>
   ``Knowing star value and entertainment value and the fact that
the millions that were tuning in, many of them probably had not
watched a game all season long, and this was a way to sell the game
to them,'' NBC's Enberg said in Fox Sports Net's documentary Magic
vs. Bird: The Game That Changed the Game, which will air Sunday.
</P>
<P>
   Nearly 18 million homes tuned in, representing a Nielsen rating
of 24.1 and a share of the total television audience of 38, meaning
nearly two of every five televisions that were turned on were tuned
in to the game.
</P>
<P>
   The anticipation, according to those who were there, was
tremendous.
</P>
<P>
   ``The anticipation of the championship game was extraordinary,''
said Boston Globe columnist Bob Ryan in another retrospective on
the game that airs at 8 tonight on ESPN Classic, which will show
the game from start to finish. ``It was the longest Sunday between
the semifinals and the finals ever, and it was the longest Monday
ever.''
</P>
<P>
   Since that final, the Tournament has become a financial bonanza
for the NCAA. The field increased to 64 teams in 1985, helping make
1998's total attendance more than twice that of 1979.
</P>
<P>
   This year's attendance should be strong as well. The Trans World
Dome in St. Louis broke records for regional semifinals and
regional finals with a combined 86,000 fans for the two sessions of
the Midwest Regional last weekend.
</P>
<P>
   When the Final Four is played in the Georgia Dome in 2007, it
will mark the 11th consecutive year the hosting stadium will be a
domed facility with a seating capacity of more than 40,000.
</P>
<P>
   Recognizing the value of NCAA basketball, CBS paid $1.72 billion
to broadcast the Tournament through 2002.
</P>
<P>
   ``As big as the Tournament is, I am surprised that our game is
still the most watched one,'' Johnson said. ``It says a lot about
how big the hype was for Magic vs. Bird.''
</P>
<P>
   The right game, the right time
</P>
<P>
   Hindsight proves the hype was deserved, as Johnson and Bird went
on to the NBA, where they have been credited with saving the pro
game and were named two of the league's 50 greatest players.
</P>
<P>
   Unfortunately, their 1979 meeting was not as spectacular as the
hype, though few remember it as such.
</P>
<P>
   Johnson and the Spartans were in control from the opening tap.
They led by as many as 11 points in the first half and by nine at
the break.
</P>
<P>
   Bird, slowed by an injured thumb, could find no open looks
against the Spartans' matchup zone and finished just 7-of-21 from
the floor. He was 16-of-19 when he scored 35 points against DePaul
in the semifinals.
</P>
<P>
   ``We wanted to have two men on him every time he touched the
ball and then have the other three defenders protect the passing
lanes because he was such a good passer,'' Heathcote said. ``But I
think the main thing people forget was _ as I told reporters before
the game _ they had one superstar, and we had two.''
</P>
<P>
   Indeed Bird, the national Player of the Year for the 33-0
Sycamores, was matched by Greg Kelser, the high-flying Robin to
Johnson's Batman, with 19 points in the championship game. Johnson
scored a game-high 24 points.
</P>
<P>
   Michigan State opened a 16-point advantage and looked as if it
would blow open the game when Kelser picked up his fourth foul in
the second half.
</P>
<P>
   Indiana State made one final run, pulling to within six points
on Bird's baseline jumper, before Johnson and Kelser switched roles
to turn the play that proved to be the final nail in the coffin of
the Sycamores.
</P>
<P>
   Kelser, known more for finishing Johnson's alley-oop passes with
dunks, fed a cutting Johnson with a pass that led to a poster dunk
over Bob Heaton, who was charged with an undercut foul that
resulted in two free throws and possession of the ball for the
Spartans.
</P>
<P>
   That one game was over, but the new game had just begun.
</P>
<P>
   ``I think the game would have reached its peak without Magic and
Bird, but it would have taken a heck of a lot longer to get
there,'' Heathcote said. ``That day will always be remembered as a
special day in college basketball. I am just proud to have been a
part of it. There will probably never be a final that is that
special again.'' &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
