<DOC>
<DOCNO> NYT19990325.0355 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-03-25 21:48 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A4452 &Cx1f; tta-z
u i &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-KOSOVO-BELGRADE-2NDLD     03-25 1258
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-KOSOVO-BELGRADE-2NDLD-WRITETHRU-700&AMP;ADD-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
SERBS, TAKING SHELTER, EXPRESS ANGER TOWARD THE WEST 
</HEADLINE>
   (EDS.: subs to correct spelling in dateline (KIJEVO sted Kievo) and
correct spelling of a town in the 4th and 16th grafs (ZARKOVO, sted
Zarkova). 
 (See also: KOSOVO-RDP, KOSOVO-MILITARY, KOSOVO-MILITARY-ASSESS,
KOSOVO-GERMANY, KOSOVO-POLICY, KOSOVO-BELGRADE, KOSOVO-PRISTINA,
KOSOVO-MACEDONIA, KOSOVO-REPORTERS, KOSOVO-CHINA,
KOSOVO-RUSSIA-ASSESS, KOSOVO-CLINTON, KOSOVO-ITALY, KOSOVO-VOICES,
KOSOVO-B2, KOSOVO-EUROPE-REAX, KOSOVO-U.N., KOSOVO-CLARK-PROFILE.) 
(wg) 
 By STEVEN ERLANGER   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   KIJEVO, Yugoslavia _ Even after the air raid sirens wailed,
Sara, nearly 5, refused to go down to the basement shelter until
the ``Ninja Turtles'' program was over.
</P>
<P>
   Then the night sky turned orange over this southern suburb of
Belgrade, and on a hill just a mile or so away, where a radar
antenna sits, a NATO missile or bomb exploded. Sara's father, Mile,
ran to his balcony, a little stupidly, he admits.
</P>
<P>
   ``There was a big cloud of dust and a huge pressure of the
air,'' he said. ``I told Sara, `Where are our Ninja turtles to help
us now?' and then we went to the shelter.''
</P>
<P>
   Mile, his wife, Biljana, Sara and her brother, Nemanja, 6, slept
in a tiny concrete storage area in their basement. There were more
explosions to the south and near Zarkovo, where there are aircraft
plants and technical compounds, and Sara was very frightened, her
mother said.
</P>
<P>
   ``She huddled in the corner, and she said, `I don't want to die,
Mommy.' We calmed her by saying it was just explosions in the stone
quarry nearby, and she said, `I was afraid they were Americans.'''
</P>
<P>
   Thursday morning, hot and sunny, was Biljana's 32nd birthday.
``The Americans arranged these fireworks for you,'' her husband
said.
</P>
<P>
   Her face crumpled, but she stifled tears and managed a wan
smile. ``I'm the guilty one, then,'' she said.
</P>
<P>
   Who is guilty, really, she was asked. President Slobodan
Milosevic of Yugoslavia? The ethnic Albanians? The Americans?
</P>
<P>
   ``There is plenty of guilt to go around,'' she said. ``No one
need feel left out.''
</P>
<P>
   A neighbor called up to the balcony and asked in English,
``Where are you from?'' A colleague said, truthfully, ``Austria.''
</P>
<P>
   The neighbor said bitterly, ``Well, you're still neutral, at
least so far.''
</P>
<P>
   Serbian anger at the West, and especially the United States, is
both media-fed and genuine. Ordinary Serbs like Mile, 37, who works
in an electrical-engineering plant, are both stupefied that the
bombs are falling and outraged that the world is treating them
``like savages,'' he said, ``just because we want to keep our
country.''
</P>
<P>
   ``We don't try to take territory away from any other country,''
Mile said, getting angrier. ``America is intervening 100 percent on
the side of the Albanians in Kosovo. It is supporting separatism
and terrorism and trying to take away our state. Who gives them the
right to bomb anybody they want?''
</P>
<P>
   Biljana patted him on the hand, and he reverted, almost
instantaneously, to being the genial Serbian host, offering Turkish
coffee and homemade plum brandy, colored golden by the wooden cross
embedded in the bottle. ``We call this our Tomahawk,'' he said
cheerily. ``It's a precision-guided weapon.''
</P>
<P>
   Then he darkened once more. ``We'll be in the shelter again
tonight,'' he said. ``And how many more nights? And what will be
the end? We enter the 21st century in this country with bombs
falling on us, as if we are the last and most savage place on the
earth. We used to have a good life here. Is it just Milosevic, or
is it someone else?''
</P>
<P>
   Their friend, Alexander, lives close by in Zarkovo, also a
target of NATO. A missile hit near a heating plant less than a mile
from his apartment building, shaking the chandelier and the
furniture like an earthquake, he said.
</P>
<P>
   His family and his sister, who lives in the same building, went
down to the shelters. ``The whole situation in my family changed
immediately,'' he said. ``All the foreigners, the Americans and the
English, all look like enemies now. Before the bombings, my father
didn't know what to think. Now he says, `Don't talk to these
foreigners; don't work with them; their money is dirty.'''
</P>
<P>
   He shook his head. ``It's like they've bombed an opinion into
our brains, and it will only help Milosevic. I don't like him, but
this bombing unifies all the Serbs against the world.''
</P>
<P>
   It is strange, he said, and primitive when war begins. ``Now
Clinton and all the Americans are all the same in this moment: they
are criminals. It's not just because the television said so. People
are afraid. They didn't expect this to happen. They just didn't
think it could happen.''
</P>
<ANNOTATION>
   (STORY CAN END HERE. OPTIONAL MATERIAL FOLLOWS)
</ANNOTATION>
<P>
   Thursday morning, when the air raid sirens wailed again in
Belgrade, his wife finally managed to get through to him on his
cell phone, to tell him to take shelter. ``I am empty,'' he said.
``My wife and my mother are full of sedatives.''
</P>
<P>
   Miles away, in the elegant center of old Belgrade, in an
exquisite apartment stuffed with every modern convenience, Slavko
Curuvija waits for the police to come. He is the publisher of the
independent newspaper Dnevni Telegraf and the newsmagazine
Evropljanin and has been sentenced to five months in jail after
refusing to pay enormous fines under a new media law, passed in
October.
</P>
<P>
   His appeal is pending, suspended by the declaration of war
Yugoslavia issued on Wednesday night. His wife, Branka Prpa, is a
well-known historian at the Institute for Modern Serbian History.
</P>
<P>
   ``He will go to jail for five months, and after this bombing,
who will care?'' she asked. ``The West can't help him _ that's
another effect of this bombing. Milosevic can act like a dictator
and lock us all up, and who will care for us? I agree the West
should care for the human rights of ethnic Albanians, but do they
also care for mine?''
</P>
<P>
   Yugoslavia is a European nation a millennium old, she said.
``You can't rub it out with an eraser and pretend it's some nation
without culture, without reason, without civilization, that we are
all savages, because of a Milosevic.''
</P>
<P>
   The West is degrading itself by using Milosevic's own tactics of
force and diktat against him, she said. ``You cannot use evil
against evil or you become the same. I only hope Serbia can survive
this one man and the madness he's done in this moment.''
</P>
<P>
   Her husband, Curuvija, said it is impossible now for any
democrat or dissident to raise up their heads in this war fever.
</P>
<P>
   ``The Serbs feel under a collective guilty verdict, and the
democratic forces are pushed into their mouse holes because of this
permanent state of emergency,'' he said. ``In this moment, you
cannot say you want to change something, or bring Serbia closer to
the West, which is bombing your country _ it makes you a traitor.''
</P>
<P>
   He pointed to his soft yellow sweatshirt, with a Gant logo and
its red-white-and-blue colors, on his chest. ``I'd be afraid now to
wear this outside in the street,'' he said. ``There are a lot of
crazy people right now.'' He rubbed his hands over his beard and
straightened his shoulders.
</P>
<P>
   ``All this helps Milosevic,'' he said. ``Everything Western is
terrible right now.''
</P>
<P>
   Another air raid siren sounded. When it died away, Ms. Prpa, his
wife, said softly, as the sunlight hit polished wood: ``The worst
of all is to feel you have no future. What kind of future do we
have?''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
