<P>
   The Seattle Post-Intelligencer plans to move the following
stories for clients of the NYTimes News Service for editions of
Friday, March 26, and thereafter. If you have any questions, please
call Mary Downes on the national-foreign desk at (206) 448-8158.
</P>
<P>
   AID-REPORTS (Undated) _ Yugoslavia's expulsion of most foreign
journalists left a Northwest-based aid agency as one of the few
remaining sources of information on conditions in war-torn Kosovo.
</P>
<P>
   By Ron Redmond. (Story will move in the ``i'' category.)
</P>
<P>
   AIRLINE-ILLNESS (Seattle) _ For 10 years, Alaska Airlines flight
attendants have complained that the air they breathe at work is
making them sick. But after a decade of concern, the cause of their
illness remains elusive: Federal investigators and the airline's
own consultants have looked, and found nothing.
</P>
<P>
   with AIRLINE-ILLNESS-ATTENDANT (Seattle) _ Deby Bradford and her
fellow Alaska Airlines MD-80 flight attendants used to call it
``skypoxia.'' They had the giddiness of three martinis, without
taking a sip. A simple remark would double them over in laughter,
tears rolling down their cheeks. It might be comical if it weren't
so serious. Bradford believes she was exposed to toxic fumes,
damaging her health and her cognitive abilities.
</P>
<P>
   By Scott Sunde. (Story will move in the ``a'' category.)
</P>
<P>
   FASHION-SPRING (Undated) _ ``Eclectic'' became a buzzword in
home furnishings several years ago. This spring it's a perfect
description of fashion offerings.
</P>
<P>
   By Susan Phinney. (Story has moved in the ``l'' category.)
</P>
<P>
   ROCK-WILSON (Undated) _ Long before she became famous in the
'70s as a member of Seattle hard-rock band Heart, singer and
guitarist Nancy Wilson sang simple, expressive folk songs at
college coffeehouse ``hootenannies.'' Wilson returns in spirit to
her coffeehouse days with her first solo album, ``Live at McCabe's
Guitar Shop.''
</P>
<P>
   By Gene Stout. (Story has moved in the ``e'' category.)
</P>
<P>
   THEATER-HUMANA (Louisville, Ky.) _ Every year, scores of theater
critics, producers and aficionados from around the world descend
upon this Ohio River town to find out what's up in American
theater. Why here? The answer lies in the Humana Festival of New
American Plays, which provides a platform for fully staged
productions of otherwise untested dramatic works. Nowhere else
gives such concentrated exposure to newly minted theater.
</P>
<P>
   By Jeffrey Erik Jenkins. (Story has moved in the ``e''
category.)
</P>
<P>
   FILM-EDTV (Undated) _ Thematically and structurally, ``EDtv'' is
so similar to ``The Truman Show'' that it's impossible not to
compare them, and ``EDtv'' loses out. ``Truman'' actually made us
believe its outlandish premise to the point where we gave a
considerable emotional investment to its characters. ``ED'' never
does. It is amusing, but finally tiresome and then instantly
forgettable.
</P>
<P>
   By William Arnold. (Story has moved in the ``e'' category.)
</P>
<P>
   FILM-MODSQUAD (Undated) _ The movie version of ``The Mod Squad''
is one of the less self-conscious and less pretentious of recent
big-screen remakes of vintage television shows. It plays very much
like an extended episode of the old series _ half-heartedly updated
to the '90s.
</P>
<P>
   By William Arnold. (Story has moved in the ``e'' category.)
</P>
<P>
   FILM-DOUG (Undated) _ There's a nice message for kids at the
heart of the animated film, ``Doug's 1st Movie'': do the right
thing and the truth will eventually come out, no matter how
unpopular the decision. The movie nicely conveys, and puts into
context, a worthy moral ideal that compensates for its ho-hum
animation, and which kept kids (and adults) in a preview audience
involved _ and listening.
</P>
<P>
   By Paula Nechak. (Story will move in the ``e'' category.)
</P>
<P>
   TV-FUTURAMA (Undated) _ Trying to re-invent the freshness,
irreverence and nose-thumbing smart-aleckiness of ``The Simpsons''
is probably a dumb idea. But if Fox is willing to pay the money,
Matt Groening is happy to take it. If the number of laugh-out-loud
moments in his new ``Futurama'' is a good way to measure success,
Groening may be laughing all the way to the banquette where TV
execs do lunch.
</P>
<P>
   By John Levesque. (Story will move in the ``e'' category.)
</P>
<P>
   BKC-COUGER-COACH (Undated) _ The Washington State Cougars named
as their new men's basketball coach Paul Graham, an assistant of
Eddie Sutton's at Oklahoma State.
</P>
<P>
   By Angela Bruscas. (Story will move in the ``s'' category.)
</P>
<P>
   BKN-THIEL-COLUMN (Seattle) _ Nate McMillan might be the first
player in NBA history to have his jersey retired for making his
teammates better and for being a good guy. A tribute to No. 10,
which was retired Wednesday at KeyArena.
</P>
<P>
   By Art Thiel. (Story will move in the ``s'' category.)
</P>
