</P>
<P>
   &UR; STREET  &LR; _ (column) Strolling the streets of San Francisco's
Financial District, you would hardly know that we were at war.
</P>
<P>
   The market was rebounding robustly while big-league investors
were impervious to the fact that cruise missiles were slamming
around Belgrade. And while Montgomery Street matter-of-factly went
about its business, emotions about the Balkan intervention ran high
at the venerable Tadich Grill _ the California Street institution
founded by the Buich family upon arrival from Croatia 150 years
ago. By columnist Mark Veverka
</P>
<P>
   &UR;  &QL;  &LR; 
 &UR; WORKPLACE package &QC;  &LR; 
 &UR;  &QL;  &LR; 
 &UR; INTERNS &LR;  _ Supervisors at United Behavioral Health, a San Francisco
insurance company, were less than thrilled last spring when its
chairman announced plans to hire seven high school interns to work
in the office all summer.
</P>
<P>
   ``At first we couldn't get managers to sign on,'' said Pam
Russo, vice president of human resources. ``They didn't feel they
had time to train a new person.''
</P>
<P>
   But the students' arrival quickly changed all that. ``They were
so enthusiastic it was contagious,'' said Russo. Longtime staffers
even began reassessing their attitudes. ``It was like, `Wow, look
how much fun they're having and how come we're not? What did we
lose and how did we lose it?''' she said. By Carol Emert
</P>
<P>
   &UR; WORKWAYS &LR;  _ (column) Question: I've worked for the same company
for 35 years, but our new management would like to see all the
old-timers leave. Recently, I was called into my boss' office,
reprimanded for yelling at a secretary while we were at lunch and
told that I would be terminated if there were any more complaints
about me.
</P>
<P>
   It's true that I did have a verbal disagreement with this
secretary, but I didn't raise my voice. My boss was unpleasant to
me and implied I was a liar, but a week later, he said he would
drop the complaint from my file. I believe that management
exaggerated the secretary's complaint to make me look bad. How can
I find out what the secretary actually said about me? Isn't it true
that discussions during lunchtime, away from the office, are
private and can't be used against employees? What recourse do I
have? Ilana DeBare has the answers.
</P>
