<DOCNO> NYT19990325.0359 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-03-25 21:53 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A4460 &Cx1f; tad-z
u i &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-KOSOVO-TV26-COX     03-25 0719
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-KOSOVO-TV26-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Targets of anger: Foreign journalists leave Yugoslavia
 &HT;    By Phil Kloer
 &HT;    c.1999 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   ATLANTA _ CNN staffers and other Western journalists were
arrested, interrogated, threatened at gunpoint and had a car full
of equipment set on fire in Kosovo early Thursday. As a result of
the violence, nearly all journalists from NATO countries have left
or been expelled from Yugoslavia, with no clear idea when they will
return.
</P>
<P>
   Although no journalists were physically harmed, CNN
International President Eason Jordan called it ``an extremely
dangerous situation. CNN is being singled out for especially rough
treatment.''
</P>
<P>
   ``We absolutely intend to return to Yugoslavia,'' Jordan said
Thursday. ``It's not clear when that will be prudent. We're trying
to get a sense as to whether or not security will be provided to
get back in.''
</P>
<P>
   ``We want to go back and report this story,'' CNN correspondent
Christiane Amapour said Thursday in a report from Brussels,
Belgium, where she fled after Belgrade became unsafe. ``We
certainly will be trying to do that.''
</P>
<P>
   In addition to Amanpour, among those who have left are CNN's
Brent Sadler and CBS's Allen Pizzey, both of whom went to
neighboring Macedonia.
</P>
<P>
   Three New York Times reporters _ Carlotta Gall, Steven Erlanger
and Blaine Harden _ were expelled, spokeswoman Nancy Nielsen said.
</P>
<P>
   CBS correspondent Mark Phillips said he was detained in a police
station for six hours in Belgrade and then driven, along with Peter
Finn of The Washington Post, to Yugoslavia's border with Croatia.
</P>
<P>
   Phillips said officials wanted to know what he was reporting and
who his contacts were in Belgrade.
</P>
<P>
   ``I felt occasionally threatened,'' he said. ``Physical violence
was never used, but the threat of it was constantly in the air.''
</P>
<P>
   ABC said its nine employees in Belgrade and Kosovo left.
</P>
<P>
   BBC reporters Monica Guerin, Ben Brown and Jacky Rowland were
ordered out of Pristina.
</P>
<P>
   ``They have not yet in Pristina expelled the entire press corps,
but as we were leaving other people were having their visas
revoked,'' Guerin said. ``Certainly, freedom of movement has been
severely restricted and our ability to go find out what's going on
in the country has been reduced.''
</P>
<P>
   Two NBC reporters, Jim Maceda and Ron Allen, remained in
Belgrade. Despite the government order, they decided to stay
because nobody directly asked them to leave, spokeswoman Alex
Constantinople said.
</P>
<P>
   Several staff members of The Associated Press were leaving the
country Thursday but the news agency was still able to do some
reporting from Yugoslavia, said Thomas Kent, AP's international
editor.
</P>
<P>
   Serbian television has conducted a campaign against CNN in
recent weeks, calling the Atlanta-based news channel ``a factory of
lies'' and saying it should be prosecuted for war crimes.
</P>
<P>
   In Pristina, Serbian paramilitary units entered the Grand Hotel
early Thursday and began looking for CNN personnel, Jordan said.
Three CNN staffers were forced into one room, their passports and
much of their equipment taken.
</P>
<P>
   Later, the door to the hotel room was broken down by a different
mob and a shot was fired into the ceiling. As the CNN people and
other journalists were preparing to leave Kosovo in a convoy, a
crowd set fire to a CNN car.
</P>
<P>
   Meanwhile, in Belgrade, about 30 journalists on the roof of the
Grand Hotel watching NATO bombing were arrested by Yugoslavian
police and interrogated.
</P>
<P>
   Amanpour, CNN's most visible correspondent in Yugoslavia for
years, was not among those arrested, but Jordan said CNN decided
she should leave immediately.
</P>
<P>
   ``It was an exceptionally dangerous situation,'' Jordan said.
``She has a long history in Yugoslavia and the leadership has a
very low regard for her.''
</P>
<P>
   Yugoslav Deputy Prime Minister Vuk Draskovic told CNN in a
telephone interview Thursday that all foreign journalists were
being allowed back into Yugoslavia.
</P>
<P>
   ``Journalists are not our enemies,'' Draskovic said. ``We need
foreign journalists as a window to foreign opinion.''
</P>
<P>
   But Jordan said the problem has been Serbian ``paramilitary
units or thugs, call them what you want,'' rather than the Yugoslav
government.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
