<DATE_TIME> 1999-03-25 21:54 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A4461 &Cx1f; tad-z
u s &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-BKC-UGAWOMEN26-COX     03-25 0742
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BKC-UGAWOMEN26-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Hard work earns Georgia title shot
 &HT;    By Wendy Parker
 &HT;    c.1999 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   SAN JOSE, Calif. _ This time a year ago, Georgia coach Andy
Landers was in the unusual position of being happy to see a
basketball season come to an end.
</P>
<P>
   The Lady Bulldogs, with only eight scholarship players, had been
eliminated in the first round of the NCAA Tournament after a 17-11
season he said was his worst ever as a coach.
</P>
<P>
   During the summer, he seriously considered a head coaching job
in the WNBA before deciding to stay put. On occasion, even late
into the current season, he struggled to find the right combination
to vault the Lady Bulldogs back to national prominence.
</P>
<P>
   While the Final Four is all that he has in mind when he employs
the word ``back,'' this may be the most improbable Final Four team
of all for Georgia (27-6), which meets Duke (28-6) at 7 tonight at
the San Jose Arena.
</P>
<P>
   And yet, this also may be Landers' best chance to capture the
NCAA title that has painfully eluded him since Georgia made the
first of its five Final Four trips in 1983.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'm not at all surprised that we're here,'' he said. ``I
really like our basketball team. We're not as good as we want to
be, but we've outworked a lot of teams to get here.''
</P>
<P>
   Some say Landers has done one of his best coaching jobs in his
20 seasons at Georgia, prodding a sophomore-dominated team (there's
only one senior on the roster) to go beyond what it probably
thought it could achieve. He did the same thing four years ago,
when Saudia Roundtree joined La'Keshia Frett, Kedra Holland and
Tracy Henderson got to the Final Four in 1995, then lost to
Tennessee the following year despite being the favorite.
</P>
<P>
   This season, the challenge has been markedly different.
</P>
<P>
   While twin guards Kelly and Coco Miller provide the kind of
competitive spirit that Frett, Henderson, et. al, lacked, their
emotional outbursts during games have been a great source of
consternation. And it is only now that Georgia players are
developing the camaraderie that was nonexistent most of last
season.
</P>
<P>
   ``Our relationships on and off the court were not what we wanted
them to be,'' junior forward Angie Ball said. ``I don't think there
was any animosity between anyone, I just think that we didn't know
each other very well. We've done a lot to change that, and I think
it's helped us get better as a team.''
</P>
<P>
   This year, Georgia got off to a 14-0 start, the best in school
history, then lost the first of three games to Tennessee. It was
after that 102-69 drubbing in Knoxville that Landers declared he
wanted his team to think about being worthy of the Final Four.
</P>
<P>
   It seemed an absurd notion, especially after the Lady Dogs went
through a nasty 1-4 slump in late January and early February. ``We
were never bad, we just lost a couple of games to teams that were
pretty good,'' he said, referring to Kentucky and Mississippi
State, both of whom got NCAA bids.
</P>
<P>
   The Lady Dogs turned things around just as quickly, hammering
Florida 91-66 and then giving Tennessee a good first half in the
SEC championship game before losing by 16. That helped unlock their
postseason confidence, especially on defense. In four NCAA
Tournament games, the Lady Dogs have limited opponents to an
average of 58 points and 34 percent shooting.
</P>
<P>
   ``Deep inside, I knew we had the opportunity to be here because
we have so much talent,'' Kelly Miller said. ``After that Florida
game, we have never looked back.''
</P>
<P>
   Someone who has witnessed all of Georgia's Final Four
manifestations is John Sewell, an assistant to Landers from 1982 to
1984.
</P>
<P>
   ``This team has an advantage because they're playing with their
hearts and not according to other people's expectations,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   And that's exactly what Landers likes about his present bunch.
</P>
<P>
   ``I have the ability to flip the switch and make sure we are the
intense and aggressive basketball team that we want to be,'' he
said. ``With a veteran team, I haven't had that approach in the
past. If I get serious with some of these kids, they will call
their mother.
</P>
<P>
   ``I just want to make sure that they have the mentality that
they can keep coming along,'' Landers said. ``I've pushed them
really hard this year. But now, it's not about pushing. It's about
feeling good about who we are and playing our best.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
