<HEADER>
A4462 &Cx1f; ttd-z
r f &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-WORKWAYS-SFCHRON &LR;      03-25 1094
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-WORKWAYS-SFCHRON </SLUG>
  
 Disputes Away From The Office
<TEXT>
<P>
   &UR;  &QL;  &LR; 
 &UR; By Ilana DeBare &QL;  &LR; 
 &UR; c 1999, San Francisco Chronicle &QL;  &LR; 
 &QL; 
 &UR; Question: &LR;  I've worked for the same company for 35 years, but our
new management would like to see all the old-timers leave.
Recently, I was called into my boss' office, reprimanded for
yelling at a secretary while we were at lunch and told that I would
be terminated if there were any more complaints about me.
</P>
<P>
   It's true that I did have a verbal disagreement with this
secretary, but I didn't raise my voice. My boss was unpleasant to
me and implied I was a liar, but a week later, he said he would
drop the complaint from my file. I believe that management
exaggerated the secretary's complaint to make me look bad. How can
I find out what the secretary actually said about me? Isn't it true
that discussions during lunchtime, away from the office, are
private and can't be used against employees? What recourse do I
have?
</P>
<P>
   &LR;   &LR;   &UR; Answer: &LR;  Let's start with your specific questions before we
get to the bigger issue here. Companies do have a right to
investigate disputes between employees that take place outside the
office _ particularly if one employee is a manager.
</P>
<P>
   Think about how many lawsuits there are these days involving
charges like sexual harassment or discrimination. If a manager
harasses a secretary during a lunch hour, the company could face
just as big and nasty a lawsuit as if the harassment happened in
the office. So companies have not only a right, but an obligation
to look into complaints of abusive behavior that take place among
employees outside the office.
</P>
<P>
   How can you find out what the secretary actually said in her
complaint? Frankly, I'd forget about it. The complaint already has
been dropped from your file. I'd put this particular episode behind
you as fast as you can and focus on the future.
</P>
<P>
   Here's where the big picture comes in _ the forest rather than
the trees.
</P>
<P>
   You need to get some kind of a reality check on your performance
and how you're viewed by management. Ask your boss _ or someone
high up in the company whom you respect _ to sit down and have an
honest talk about your future with the firm.
</P>
<P>
   It could be that company officials value you and want to keep
you on board but have some serious criticisms of your work. If
that's the case, you need to listen carefully and try to respond
without defensiveness or paranoia.
</P>
<P>
   On the other hand, maybe the company really doesn't want you
around. Then maybe you should acknowledge that it's time to move on
_ and negotiate a good severance or early retirement package to
help ease your transition to a new job.
</P>
<P>
   One more note: Consider talking to a lawyer who has handled
age-discrimination cases, especially if other old-timers feel that
they're being pushed aside, too. Age-discrimination cases are hard
to win. But having some good legal advice certainly would
strengthen your negotiating position.
</P>
<P>
   Quick-Change Artist
</P>
<P>
   Q: For the past 20 years, I've been involved with publishing
but, with all the media mergers and downsizing in the publishing
industry, I've been thinking about changing careers into high tech.
What kinds of jobs are available in the industry? What are the
salary ranges? And what kinds of training are available for someone
who works full time?
</P>
<P>
   &LR;   &LR;  A: Have I got the book for you: ``High-Tech Careers for
Low-Tech People,'' by Sun Microsystems manager William Schaffer.
</P>
<P>
   This gives a terrific overview of the kinds of jobs available in
technology, the workplace culture of high-tech companies and how to
get your foot in the door. It's been out of print for a while but
is about to be reissued by Ten Speed Press in Berkeley.
</P>
<P>
   For salary information, check out the JobStar Web site (formerly
known as JobSmart) at  &LR; jobstar.org.  &LR; It has links to salary surveys
for more than 200 professions, including a variety of high-tech
ones.
</P>
<P>
   For training, many community colleges offer tech-related courses
on evenings and weekends. But before you start signing up
willy-nilly for classes, think about what kind of work within high
tech you want to do: Someone who wants to become a C++ programmer
needs very different skills than someone who wants to go into
high-tech sales, marketing or human resources.
</P>
<P>
   Some general tips? Think about how your current skills and
experience in publishing could be translated into a high-tech
setting. (For instance, what specialized software does your
publishing company use? You might be a great salesperson for that
software manufacturer.)
</P>
<P>
   Also think about skills that you don't use in your current job,
but would be marketable in the tech world. (Do you love planning
family and high school reunions? You might consider work as a
corporate-event planner at a tech firm.)
</P>
<P>
   The most important thing, according to Schaffer, is simply
getting in the door. That might mean taking a job where you feel
overqualified or a job that isn't exactly what you want. High tech
is fast-paced and flexible enough that, once they're in the door,
motivated people can quickly move ahead.
</P>
<P>
   ``Get in any way you can,'' Schaffer said. ``Once you're in, you
can branch out and get training in whatever you want, whether
that's sales or becoming a computer engineer.''
</P>
<P>
   &UR; BAD-MOUTHING THE BOSS, PART TWO: &LR;  Last week, I said never to
bad-mouth your old boss when interviewing for a new position.
Here's one reader's response:
</P>
<P>
   ``Keeping quiet about evil former bosses is a standard piece of
advice for job candidates. However, perhaps this should be amended
when the candidate stood up against the evil, for in doing this,
the candidate displayed integrity. Integrity is one of strongest
predictors of on-the-job success, in my opinion. Would you amend
your advice for Serpico, the New York City police officer who made
waves by refusing to take bribes, was ostracized and shot in the
head but did not relent until he had reformed the entire New York
City police force? Would you advise him to prevaricate about this
experience?''
</P>
<P>
   Good point. For every piece of advice, there are situations
where it shouldn't apply. And when navigating the tricky waters of
job-hunting, be sure to keep in touch with your own intuition,
character and conscience.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
 &QL; 
Send your work and career questions to Ilana DeBare, Workways, San
Francisco Chronicle, 901 Mission St., San Francisco 94103. Or send
e-mail to workways(at sign)sfgate.com. &LR;   &LR; Or call (415) 764-2815. We
can't respond to each query, but we will answer as many in print as
we can. &LR;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
