<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-STREET-SFCHRON </SLUG>
  
 Column: American Investors Are Barely Fazed by NATO's
Bombing  Blitz 
<TEXT>
<P>
   &UR;  &QL;  &LR; 
 &UR; By Mark Veverka &QL;  &LR; 
 &UR; c 1999, San Francisco Chronicle &QL;  &LR; 
 &QL; 
Strolling the streets of San Francisco's Financial District, you
would hardly know that we were at war.
</P>
<P>
   The market was rebounding robustly while big-league investors
were impervious to the fact that cruise missiles were slamming
around Belgrade. And while Montgomery Street matter-of-factly went
about its business, emotions about the Balkan intervention ran high
at the venerable Tadich Grill _ the California Street institution
founded by the Buich family upon arrival from Croatia 150 years
ago.
</P>
<P>
   Tadich is about as close to the Balkans as you're going to get
with a Muni or BART pass. And on most any day, you'll find a
handful of Croatian waiters working along side other immigrants
from Central Europe. (In fact, on occasion, you might even find a
Serbian working next to a Croat.)
</P>
<P>
   As you might expect, Tadich attracts numerous descendants of the
Slavic tribe _ Croatian or otherwise. And yesterday, Betty Sardelis
of Perrysburg, Ohio, could be found at the counter brimming with
conflicted feelings about Kosovo.
</P>
<P>
   Sardelis, who was visiting town with her husband, is a
second-generation Slovenian. Her mother was born in Slovenia, and
her sister has a home there.
</P>
<P>
   Slovenia was among the first former Yugoslavian provinces to
declare independence after the Berlin Wall fell. It was also among
the first to get pounded by Serbian armies as a result.
</P>
<P>
   We bonded. Both of my mother's parents emigrated from Slovenia
shortly after the turn of the century. Needless to say, Sardelis
was a little more worked up about the Balkan bombings than your
average day trader.
</P>
<P>
   ``The whole thing just makes me sick,'' she said.
</P>
<P>
   ``Innocent people are dying. It's just really sad.''
</P>
<P>
   But the human element doesn't always register on Montgomery
Street. Kosovo is of little economic significance _ at least for
now.
</P>
<P>
   As was the case with the Pentagon's most recent dusting of
Baghdad late last year, the investment pros are hardly concerned by
our latest global gunfight with a pesky third-world strongman.
</P>
<P>
   Of course, there is good intellectual reason for all of this.
Few of them really care about Kosovo. And why should they?
</P>
<P>
   Most barely know where it is. It has no oil. It is not perched
on the edge of a critical international shipping lane or some other
location of economic importance.
</P>
<P>
   Thus, it's not surprising to find the military attack against
Serbia of little imminent concern to American investors, notes
former White House economic adviser Laura D'Andrea Tyson, dean of
the Haas School of Business at the University of California at
Berkeley.
</P>
<P>
   ``I think the lack of response by the market is a reflection of
the fact that the (bombings) have no immediate impact on the U.S.
economy or global economy,'' Tyson says.
</P>
<P>
   That said, if American lives are lost or the conflict spreads to
neighboring nations, ``the situation has the potential to become a
more unsettling factor,'' Tyson adds.
</P>
<P>
   In fact, American investors are barely fazed by NATO's air blitz
in the Balkans. Folks in San Francisco's Financial District say the
bombings aren't weighing on the minds of salesmen peddling stocks
or portfolio managers making trades.
</P>
<P>
   Yet, if one pauses for a moment, isn't that just the least bit
unsettling? Have we become so inebriated by our own financial good
fortune that we have grown callous to the world around us, ignoring
any event that doesn't impact our stock portfolios?
</P>
<P>
   That's not to say investors should make stock decisions in
reaction to world events. But perhaps it would be good karma to at
least acknowledge them.
</P>
<P>
   No matter where you stand on the issue of intervention in
Yugoslavia _ and there is no right or wrong position _ the age of
televised war seems to have desensitized us to our government's
aggressions.
</P>
<P>
   But the Dow ticker keeps on ticking. And as long as China, Korea
or Russia aren't involved, military actions like the current ones
against Serbia aren't of dire importance to the financial world.
</P>
<P>
   Perhaps, they have no reason to be. But if Russia were to get
dragged into this, you can bet that war again would matter on
Montgomery Street.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
 &QL; 
Street Smarts runs every Tuesday, Wednesday and Friday. Mark
Veverka can be reached by mail at 901 Mission St., San Francisco,
Calif. 94103, by phone at (415) 777-8444 or by e-mail at
mveverka(AT SIGN)sfgate.com
</P>
</TEXT>
