u w &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-CLINTON-JUROR-INTERVI     03-25 0833
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-CLINTON-JUROR-INTERVIEW-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
GRAND JURY FOREWOMAN WOULD HAVE INDICTED CLINTON 
</HEADLINE>
   (bl)  
 By FRANK BRUNI   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON _ The grand jury forewoman in the Monica Lewinsky
scandal said Thursday night that she would have indicted President
Clinton for perjury if she had been asked to.
</P>
<P>
   In the first public comments by any of the grand jurors, the
forewoman, Freda Alexander, added that she was relieved, however,
that her panel was not charged with considering Clinton's actions
as a criminal matter. And she said that she did not think his
offenses warranted his removal from office.
</P>
<P>
   Her primary misgiving about Clinton's impeachment and Senate
trial, Ms. Alexander said in a telephone interview, was the degree
to which it must have taken the president's and other lawmakers'
attention away from other tasks.
</P>
<P>
   ``I wonder what would have happened _ I wonder what kind of
legacy he would have been able to leave _ if he hadn't been
distracted by all the investigations,'' she said. ``I still have a
great deal of respect for him.''
</P>
<P>
   In fact, Ms. Alexander said she emerged from her 18 months of
grand jury service, which ended last week, with sympathetic
feelings toward almost all the main players who came before her.
</P>
<P>
   Independent Counsel Kenneth Starr was a stickler for rules and
morals simply doing what he felt was his job, she said. Clinton's
advisers and aides were simply looking out for their boss. And Ms.
Lewinsky was simply any young girl, out for adventure and in thrall
to temptation.
</P>
<P>
   ``Here is a young woman who could be any one of us if we were to
truly admit it,'' Ms. Alexander said. ``We conveniently forget this
stuff once we get mature. I don't think she's a hussy. I think
she's a young person full of enthusiasm, willing to try new
things.''
</P>
<P>
   Although federal grand jurors are technically forbidden to speak
about what they heard and saw even after they are released from
service, Ms. Alexander, who is 46 and lives in Washington, D.C.,
said she felt that once her service was over, it was her ``First
Amendment right'' to talk about it.
</P>
<P>
   But she said she did not approach news organizations. During her
service, she said, she lost her job as a hotel manager, and in
recent interviews for new jobs, she explained that she had been out
of work so long because of the grand jury.
</P>
<P>
   That information, she said, found its way to a hotel industry
trade publication, USAE News, and from there to other news
organizations.
</P>
<P>
   Ms. Alexander said her belief that Clinton perjured himself
stemmed from his insistence that he did not have sexual relations
with Ms. Lewinsky, as well as his statements that oral sex did not
fall within his understanding of the meaning of sexual relations.
</P>
<P>
   ``Say, for instance, my boyfriend and I define the fact that we
won't have sexual relations with any other person,'' Ms. Alexander
said. ``Now, I come home or we meet somewhere and I find him and
oral sex is being performed. That would be curtains, that would be
it, because to me that's sexual relations.''
</P>
<P>
   But Ms. Alexander said that while she believed that Clinton
committed perjury, she did not want to see him prosecuted. In fact,
she said, her strongest criticism of his behavior in regard to Ms.
Lewinsky was that he exercised poor judgment.
</P>
<P>
   ``I think he made an awful, awful choice, because of her age,''
Ms. Alexander said. ``A young person that age loves to talk, and
because they love to talk, there's a certain discretion that you
would be missing.''
</P>
<P>
   She added that as president, a person is obliged ``to use
discretion in its highest form in everything that you do.''
</P>
<P>
   Ms. Alexander said that she did not feel that her year and a
half on the grand jury was wasted, because it was a legitimate
inquiry that indeed got at the truth.
</P>
<P>
   What made the experience difficult, she said, was that she had
always admired Clinton and wanted to hold onto that regard.
</P>
<P>
   ``I care about a lot about some of the things he's done,'' said
Ms. Alexander, who is black. ``Look at the White House, look at the
staff. You have disabled Americans there. You have blacks. Have you
ever seen such an array of nationalities in previous
administrations?''
</P>
<P>
   She said she was not at all convinced from the evidence
presented to her that Clinton obstructed justice, the charge in the
second article of impeachment against him.
</P>
<P>
   She also said that she was often deeply moved by the obvious
fear and embarrassment that many of the witnesses brought before
the grand jury were experiencing. She said the most upsetting
moment was hearing Ms. Lewinsky talk about the day that Starr's
investigators confronted her at a hotel, told her they knew about
her relationship with the president, and detained her for
questioning for hours on end.
</P>
<P>
   ``When Monica retold her story about her detainment at the Ritz
Carlton,'' Ms. Alexander said, ``everyone was crying in the room,
including the court reporter.''
</P>
</TEXT>
