<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-PACBELL-SFCHRON </SLUG>
  
 Pac Bell Stumbles With DSL
<TEXT>
<P>
   &UR;  &QL;  &LR; 
 &UR; By Deborah Solomon &LR;
</P>
<P>
   &UR; c 1999, San Francisco Chronicle &QL;  &LR; 
 &QL; 
Some Pacific Bell customers who signed up for the company's
high-speed Internet service say they are not getting what the
company promised.
</P>
<P>
   Pac Bell's digital subscriber line service uses existing phone
lines to deliver Internet service at speeds up to 50 times faster
than with traditional modems. It also lets users talk on the phone
and surf the Web simultaneously.
</P>
<P>
   But some DSL customers say they can't access the Internet after
it is installed. Others complain that technicians miss their
appointments for installations. And some customers who are told
they can get the service are then told on installation day that
their wiring can't accommodate it.
</P>
<P>
   Pac Bell acknowledged that the DSL rollout has not gone as
smoothly as planned and attributed it to enormous demand and
growing pains associated with deploying a new technology.
</P>
<P>
   &UR;  &LR; The company said yesterday it is canceling a contract with
Livermore's Prime Services Group, the firm it hired to help install
DSL service in California. Prime Services had no comment.
</P>
<P>
   ``We decided in order to be world class and deliver the customer
care the people of California expect, we'd be better served to have
Pac Bell employees doing'' the installations, said Mike McLeland,
Pac Bell's vice president of business service operations.
</P>
<P>
   Pac Bell has been selling DSL service since last year. Last
month, it cut the price from $89 to $39 a month, prompting a huge
increase in customer demand. Company officials said Pac Bell got
three times as many more  &LR; customer calls as it expected and has
been struggling to deal with all the requests.
</P>
<P>
   The company would not disclose how many DSL customers it has.
</P>
<P>
   ``We have experienced some process problems, as customers called
in in greater numbers than we expected,'' said McLeland. He added
the company has ``all but fixed these problems.''
</P>
<P>
   McLeland said the average number of days a customer must wait
for DSL installation has fallen to seven days from 18 days in
February.
</P>
<P>
   Pac Bell spokesman John Britton said the company is learning as
it goes. He said Pac Bell has a 94 percent customer satisfaction
rate with DSL but admits that's not high enough.
</P>
<P>
   ``Any time you're doing something new, obstacles come up that we
have to overcome. Are we happy with 94 percent? No. We intend to
improve that and get that better.''
</P>
<P>
   The complaints about DSL have made their way to state regulators
and consumer groups. Linda Woods, manager of the state Public
Utilities Commission's consumer affairs branch, said the PUC isn't
being deluged with complaints about DSL but is taking the ones it
does get seriously.
</P>
<P>
   ``I wouldn't be surprised if we were getting half a dozen
(complaints) a day,'' she said.
</P>
<P>
   &UR;  &LR; The Office of Ratepayer Advocates, the PUC's consumer arm,
also has received about a dozen complaints from upset customers,
according to Kelly Boyd, senior telecommunications analyst at ORA.
</P>
<P>
   One frustrated customer is Jeremy Smith, who has been trying to
get a DSL line installed in his San Mateo home for three weeks.
</P>
<P>
   Smith was told the service would be installed March 17 and
stayed home from work to wait for the technician. Nobody showed up
and the company never called to explain.
</P>
<P>
   After leaving five messages with Pac Bell, Smith finally reached
someone who apologized and said a technician would be there the
next day.
</P>
<P>
   A Prime Services Group representative arrived the next day and
told him that installation was going to be a problem because
Smith's wiring was bad. Smith left for work and when he came home,
he found a note telling him the service couldn't be installed. He
complained to Pac Bell, which sent two technicians out to fix the
wiring and install DSL, but the service never worked.
</P>
<P>
   This week, Smith's DSL service finally started working, but at a
cost: It nearly destroyed the voice quality on Smith's phone line,
something that's not supposed to happen.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's been a darn disaster,'' said Smith, who ordered the line
so he could do more work from home. ``They shouldn't be offering
the service if they don't know how to make it work.''
</P>
<P>
   Peter Kelton, who lives in San Francisco, has had similar
problems with his DSL line.
</P>
<P>
   He ordered the service about a month ago but has been forced to
use his regular dial-up modem because the DSL service doesn't work.
</P>
<P>
   ``A technician came out three weeks ago and told me my service
would be up in two days,'' Kelton said. ``It's still not working.''
</P>
<P>
   The problems appear similar to those experienced by customers
when Pac Bell's ISDN service was new. Pac Bell technicians often
missed customer appointments and failed to install the technology,
which also gives users fast Internet service. Last year, the
company was fined $309,000 by the state for providing
``inadequate'' ISDN service. The PUC established service quality
guidelines and ordered Pac Bell to waive installation fees on ISDN
if customers surveyed by the PUC continued to rate the service as
``poor'' or ``terrible.''
</P>
<P>
   Bob Larribeau, who runs the California Broadband Users Group in
San Francisco, said the DSL problems sound eerily familiar.
</P>
<P>
   ``The company has to learn how to do DSL,'' Larribeau said.
``ISDN was the start, DSL is just a next step and people are going
to demand and want more and better services. Pac Bell needs to
learn to do it right.''
</P>
<P>
   While the company shouldn't offer a service it cannot deliver,
Larribeau said there are significant challenges to deploying the
technology that might account for some of the problems.
</P>
<P>
   Customers must live within three &UR;  &LR; miles of a central switching
office to receive DSL. Within that radius, customers who live
closer to the switching office will get higher-quality service than
those who live farther away, Larribeau said. By year end, about 50
percent of Pac Bell's customers will be able to get the service.
</P>
<P>
   Also, many of Pac Bell's phone lines are old and need to be
upgraded to handle DSL. In some cases, the company may not know
there's a problem until they attempt to install the service and
find they can't.
</P>
<P>
   ``There are a lot of issues and a lot of processes that we've
been reviewing'' McLeland said. ``These are growing pains. And for
every customer that has a bad experience, there are 95 that have
had a wonderful experience.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
