<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-03-25 21:56 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A4467 &Cx1f; ttd-z
r f &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-INTERNS-SFCHRON &LR;      03-25 1303
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-INTERNS-SFCHRON </SLUG>
  
 Learning and Earning
<TEXT>
<P>
   &UR;  &QL;  &LR; 
 &UR; By Carol Emert &LR;
</P>
<P>
   &UR; c 1999, San Francisco Chronicle &QL;  &LR; 
 &QL; 
Supervisors at United Behavioral Health, a San Francisco insurance
company, were less than thrilled last spring when its chairman
announced plans to hire seven high school interns to work in the
office all summer.
</P>
<P>
   ``At first we couldn't get managers to sign on,'' said Pam
Russo, vice president of human resources. ``They didn't feel they
had time to train a new person.''
</P>
<P>
   But the students' arrival quickly changed all that. ``They were
so enthusiastic it was contagious,'' said Russo. Longtime staffers
even began reassessing their attitudes. ``It was like, `Wow, look
how much fun they're having and how come we're not? What did we
lose and how did we lose it?''' she said.
</P>
<P>
   According to Russo, some of last year's reluctant supervisors
now want two or three interns this year.
</P>
<P>
   With summer just around the corner, it is time for interested
employers to start planning for the arrival of high school interns,
who are available to virtually any company with entry-level work to
be done.
</P>
<P>
   Employers that don't want to do their own recruiting can tap
into myriad Bay Area groups that develop programs, recruit from
schools, screen candidates and give young workers basic training
and support.
</P>
<P>
   Some internship programs are designed for high school students
to learn about professions &LR;   &LR; that interest them. For example, San
Francisco's Enterprise for High School Students, a nonprofit that
matches students and companies, places teens with landscapers,
plumbers, environmental scientists and oncologists.
</P>
<P>
   Other programs, such as the Mayor's Summer Jobs Program in
Oakland, are designed simply to give kids their first taste of the
working world. Typical jobs are in retailing, fast food, clerical
or customer service.
</P>
<P>
   When internship programs are run well, they can boost the morale
of everyone in the office, teach young people important skills and
even be cost-effective for the employer.
</P>
<P>
   But there are also some common pitfalls that businesses should
be careful to avoid.
</P>
<P>
   The most common mistake employers make in approaching high
school interns is to view them as nothing more than cheap labor,
said Susan Hoganson, executive director of Enterprise.
</P>
<P>
   ``The programs that aren't that successful are ones where a
supervisor says, `Oh great, I can have a kid come in and do my
filing and Xeroxing for two months,''' she said.
</P>
<P>
   While mundane tasks like photocopying or moving boxes may be
perfectly acceptable intern duties, there should also be an
educational component to the job, said Hoganson. ``Anybody who
supervises a young person in a new venture really has accepted the
responsibility for that person's learning and development.''
</P>
<P>
   Eva Cheng, a senior at Abraham Lincoln High School in San
Francisco, said her clerical internship last summer at Aon Risk
Services, an insurance broker, was such a learning experience.
</P>
<P>
   ``Just being part of an actual work environment is very helpful
for me because later on I'll know how to work with people and what
to expect from people,'' said Cheng, who is planning to go to
college and then pursue a career in business.
</P>
<P>
   One important lesson for Cheng, who has continued working for
Aon after school, was learning she could ask questions about things
she didn't know.
</P>
<P>
   Internship experts say there are certain key guidelines
employers should follow to help make their internship programs
successful:
</P>
<P>
   &UR; _Look for motivation above skill.  &LR; Employers should resist the
temptation to hire the fastest typist or most accomplished
programmer while ignoring the applicant's attitude.
</P>
<P>
   Many internship programs let companies interview job candidates,
a process that should help identify eager students.
</P>
<P>
   Employers should also look for students who have shown an
interest in the field through other jobs or courses, or those who
have demonstrated their initiative through after-school activities,
said Hoganson.
</P>
<P>
   &UR; _Put some effort into designing the program.  &LR; Once a business
has decided it wants to sponsor an intern, the next step is to make
sure there is enough work, on an appropriate skill level, to keep a
teenager challenged for a summer.
</P>
<P>
   Aon started preparing for its first interns last year by looking
at an existing entry-level job description. Human resources staff
and section heads then altered it to meet the needs of different
departments and the skill level of teens.
</P>
<P>
   ``The key factor in making the internships a success was the
prep,'' said Tamra Green, Aon's human resources director. ``If we
had just brought the bodies in and waited to see what happened, it
probably wouldn't have worked.''
</P>
<P>
   &UR; _Don't underestimate the students.  &LR; While it is important to
not assign teenagers tasks beyond their abilities, managers should
also be open to giving them more responsibilities if they prove
themselves capable _ and have plenty of work on hand.
</P>
<P>
   Brian Washington, a student at Thurgood Marshall High School in
Bayview, was asked to create an Intranet site last summer during a
stint at Charles Schwab Corp. in San Francisco.
</P>
<P>
   Washington, who plans to attend college and get work in a
computer-related field, worked diligently and nearly finished the
project the first week. Most of the rest of the summer was spent
doing clerical tasks, although Washington has been asked to return
during breaks from school to add material to the site.
</P>
<P>
   &UR; _Assign projects.  &LR; Ideally internships should revolve around
special projects that give students something concrete to show for
their efforts at the end of the summer, said Hoganson.
</P>
<P>
   ``If they can say, `Wow, I produced this brochure' or `I did a
survey,' it gives them a sense of accomplishment,'' as well as
teaching them what the profession is like,'' said Hoganson.
</P>
<P>
   &UR; _Assign mentors.  &LR; Each intern should have one employee assigned
as a mentor and a second, backup supervisor in case the mentor
misses work. Both overseers should be willing volunteers rather
than reluctant draftees.
</P>
<P>
   ``One of the biggest things our kids are lacking is a
supportive, caring adult in their lives,'' said Hoganson. ``This
adult (mentor) hopefully will be someone who really cares.''
</P>
<P>
   &UR; _Pop the bubble gently.  &LR; Interns may have unrealistic
expectations of glamour on the job. ``At first, they often don't
understand that we adults in the work world don't have people doing
photocopying and errand running for us,'' said Hoganson. ``The
stars in their eyes on the first day are gone by the end of the
first week.''
</P>
<P>
   To help interns make the transition, employers should make sure
the students know their work is appreciated, even if it seems
mundane.
</P>
<P>
   &UR; _Realize that sometimes it simply won't work out.  &LR; Like any
other employee, interns may have personality conflicts with their
co-workers. They may be immature, or they may hate the work they
thought they would enjoy.
</P>
<P>
   At Aon, a special position was created in the information
services department for an intern who wanted to work with
computers. But she turned down each task she was assigned, saying
it bored her.
</P>
<P>
   ``She was counting the days till the six weeks were over and she
could get the check and go clothes shopping,'' said Green. ``From a
maturity standpoint, she just wasn't ready.''
</P>
<P>
   Students and employers interested in internships should contact
their school career center, their mayor's office or their local
chamber of commerce. County private industry councils typically
administer federally funded job programs such as the Summer Youth
Employment Training Program.
</P>
<P>
   Employers are generally expected to pay high school interns
between $6 and $8 an hour, although the U.S. government pays for
disadvantaged teens who find jobs through the SYETP.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
