<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-03-25 21:57 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A4471 &Cx1f; taf-z
u a &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-NUTRITION-KIDS-550&AMP;AD     03-25 0860
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-NUTRITION-KIDS-550&AMP;ADD-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
NEW FOOD GUIDE FOR CHILDREN HAS SODA COMPANIES IN A FIZZ 
</HEADLINE>
  (rk) 
 By MARIAN BURROS    
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   The Department of Agriculture Thursday issued its first
guidelines on how to feed young children a nutritious diet,
emphasizing the value of grains, fruits and vegetables.
</P>
<P>
   A soft drink can that illustrates the recommendation that
children should ``eat less'' sugar in their diets has outraged the
soda companies, which annually sell an average of 56.1 gallons of
soda per person in the United States.
</P>
<P>
   The new guidelines are in the form of a pyramid, with grains at
the base, fruits and vegetables on a narrower level above, meat at
a still narrower level above that, and a soda can at the top. A
similar food pyramid for the general population issued in 1992
shows sugar at the top.
</P>
<P>
   The meaning of ``less'' is not spelled out in the new Food Guide
Pyramid for Children, which is intended for 2- to 6-year-olds, or
in any of the accompanying literature, but the under secretary of
agriculture for Food, Nutrition and Consumers Services, Shirley
Watkins, said the department had long held that the most a young
child should drink is half a 12-ounce can of soda a day.
</P>
<P>
   Ms. Watkins said that any additional source of extra sugar, like
sugary cereals, cookies or cupcakes, would put the child over the
recommended limit.
</P>
<P>
   According to Agriculture Department statistics, on any given day
37 percent of children 2-6 years of age in the United States
consume an average of 10 ounces of soda.
</P>
<P>
   At the same time that the consumption of soft drinks has risen
almost 34 gallons per person annually since 1970, the National Soft
Drink Association disputes the department's consumption figures for
all 2- to 6-year-olds, saying the average is 2 to 4 ounces of soda
a day.
</P>
<P>
   In a letter to the secretary of agriculture, Dan Glickman, the
association accused the department of ``demonizing'' soft drinks
with its new guidelines for children.
</P>
<P>
   The letter, from the association's president, William Ball III,
said that by singling out soft drinks the department ``appears to
have made an abrupt shift in philosophy'' that ``there is no such
thing as a good food or a bad food.''
</P>
<P>
   Ms. Watkins disputed that. ``Somehow people perceived food at
the tip of pyramid should not be eaten, and that is not true,'' Ms.
Watkins said. ``Anything on the pyramid should be eaten, but
children should eat more of certain foods than others.''
</P>
<P>
   What they should eat most of are grains, which form the base of
the pyramid, followed by fruits and vegetables, then milk and meat,
topped by fats and sweets.
</P>
<P>
   The argument did not persuade the Agriculture Department to
remove the soda pop can from the top of the pyramid, so the soft
drink industry sent its lobbyists to press members of the House and
Senate Agriculture committees, who hold the department's purse
strings.
</P>
<P>
   ``We felt Congress should be involved in this departure in
nutritional philosophy,'' Ball said.
</P>
<P>
   In a letter to Glickman, the chairmen and ranking members of the
two committees said they were ``concerned about lack of
consultation'' on the pyramid for young children. ``Based on
reports, there are several concerns with the depiction of certain
foods in the graphical presentation of the guide,'' a reference to
the soda can.
</P>
<P>
   The only change the agency made was in the colors of the soda
icon, which originally made it look like a can of Pepsi.
</P>
<ANNOTATION>
   (STORY CAN END HERE. OPTIONAL MATERIAL FOLLOWS)
</ANNOTATION>
<P>
   At the news conference Wednesday announcing the new children's
pyramid, Glickman and Ms. Watkins responded to the complaints by
repeatedly emphasizing the Agriculture Department's decades-old
philosophy that there are no good foods or bad foods, and that
people should eat a variety of food.
</P>
<P>
   These messages were greeted with outrage by an advocacy group in
Washington that has urged a stronger federal role in promoting
healthy diets. Margo Wootan, a senior scientist for the group, the
Center for Science in the Public Interest, said she was very
disappointed in the pyramid, which features such high saturated fat
foods as hamburgers in the meat group, cheese and ice cream in the
dairy group and not a single whole grain product in the grain
group.
</P>
<P>
   ``They are basically promoting unhealthy choices,'' Ms. Wootan
said. ``USDA seems to think the two most important messages to
promote are to eat a variety of foods and that there are no bad
foods. But the most important messages for promoting health are to
eat more fruits and vegetables, eat more whole grains, choose
low-fat and fat-free dairy products and lean meats or meat
alternatives. No wonder Americans are eating a lousy diet.''
</P>
<P>
   Based on the increasing obesity in the United States, experts
say the new guidelines for children are unlikely to have any more
impact than dietary advice has had on adults.
</P>
<P>
   A graphic of the pyramid and a the booklet that accompanies it
may be downloaded from www.usda.gov/cnpp, or bought for $5 from the
Superintendent of Documents, U.S. Government Printing Office,
Washington, D.C. 20402.
</P>
</TEXT>
