   (NYT22) NEW YORK -- March 25, 1999 -- KOSOVO-VOICES-1, 3-25 --
The NATO attacks in Yugoslavia prompted a varied reactions around
the U.S. The owner of a Manhattan pizzeria, an Albanian immigrant,
hung a sign outside his store on Thursday. (James Estrin/New York
Times Photo)
</P>
<P>
   (NYT21) SKOPJE, Macedonia -- March 25, 1999 -- KOSOVO-MACEDONIA,
3-25 -- Giving vent to their rage over NATO bombings of their
neighboring country, thousands of Serb sympathisers burn a U.S.
flag after marching on the American Embassy. The riots were the
most glaring sign yet of the mounting tension in the surrounding
Balkan states in the wake of NATOs military action against Yugoslav
president Slobodan Milosevic. (Alan Chin/New York Times Photo)
</P>
<P>
   (NYT20) SKOPJE, Macedonia -- March 25, 1999 -- KOSOVO-MACEDONIA,
3-25 -- Ethnic Albanian refugees who fled Kosovo crowd in front of
police headquarters on Thursday waiting to receive documents that
will allow them to remain in Macedonia. Sheltered by friends and
relatives in the large ethnic Albanian community of Macedonia, the
refugees, some 20,000 to date, are nonetheless viewed with alarm by
some Macedonians of different ethnic origin. (Alan Chin/New York
Times Photo) *LITE
</P>
