</P>
<P>
   (NYT13) NEW YORK -- March 25, 1999 -- ADV. FOR SUN., MARCH 28 --
INVEST-NASD-BROKERS-2, 3-25 -- Ira Lee Sorkin, a lawyer who has
served in both regulatory and prosecutorial roles, says disclosure
by the National Association of Securities Dealers and its
affiliated regulators already goes too far. He is particularly
concerned about publication, in any form, of customer complaints
that are not substantiated. (Barbara Alper/New York Times Photo)
</P>
<P>
   (NYT12) WASHINGTON -- March 25, 1999 -- ADV. FOR SUN., MARCH 28
-- INVEST-NASD-BROKERS-1, 3-25 -- As regulators establish policies
for on-line publication of their records about stockbrokers, Laura
Polacheck of AARP is among the advocates of full disclosure. ``Our
view is it should be up to the investor,'' she says. ``If the
investor sees they had some conviction that occurred decades ago
that doesn't seem to compromise their integrity, that's up to the
investor to make that determination.'' (Marty Katz/New York Times
Photo)
</P>
<P>
   (NYT11) BOSTON -- March 25, 1999 -- ADV. FOR SUN., MARCH 28 --
BIZ-PROFILE-D'ALESSANDRO, 3-25 -- David D'Alessandro, president of
John Hancock Mutual Life Insurance, has not withdrawn the insurer's
sponsorship of the Olympics, but he has removed the Olympic logo
from its TV ads. ``They lied to us,'' says D'Alessandro of the way
the International Olympics Committee, the governing body of the
Games, has dragged its feet. ``They told us the scandal would be
put behind us. But their version of reform doesn't appear to be
anybody else's.'' (Jim Bourg/New York Times Photo)
</P>
<P>
   (NYT10) SAN JOSE, Calif. -- March 25, 1999 -- ADV. FOR SUN.,
MARCH 28 -- BIZ-ASIAN-ENTREPRENEURS-2, 3-25 -- Sung Kim, head of
Nextream Inc., a San Jose start-up company that is developing
software to link banks to the Internet. Kim found that he had to
leave a stifling corporate environment in his native South Korea to
build a business based on the World Wide Web. (Peter DaSilva/New
York Times Photo)
</P>
<P>
   (NYT9) TORRANCE, Calif. -- March 25, 1999 -- ADV. FOR SUN.,
MARCH 28 -- BIZ-ASIAN-ENTREPRENEURS-1, 3-25 -- Mike Morishita, who
left Nippon Telephone and Telegraph to start a Web consulting
