<DATE_TIME> 1999-03-25 21:58 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A4476 &Cx1f; ttx-z
r i &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-KOSOVO-REPORTER-TEX     03-25 0295
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-KOSOVO-REPORTER-TEX </SLUG>
 
(For use by NYTimes News Service Clients) 
By MARISA TAYLOR 
c.1999 Fort Worth Star-Telegram 
<TEXT>
<P>
   Peter Finn, a Washington Post correspondent and former Fort
Worth Star-Telegram reporter, was detained and interrogated for at
least eight hours by Serbian police, then was released unharmed on
Thursday.
</P>
<P>
   Finn was driven in a van to the border of Croatia by Serbian
police and expelled from Yugoslavia, said a Post assistant managing
editor, Philip Bennett.
</P>
<P>
   During his detention, the Serbian police interrogated Finn,
without offering him food and water, Bennett said. The police
officials asked him his views of the conflict and who he had been
interviewing.
</P>
<P>
   Serbian Police escorted Finn from his Belgrade hotel at 4 a.m.
Thursday, telling a clerk that he would be expelled, Bennett said.
</P>
<P>
   Finn's wife, Nora Fitzgerald, who was in Warsaw, Poland, said
she was relieved when she heard of his release.
</P>
<P>
   ``We were up all night,'' she said.
</P>
<P>
   Finn, who worked for Star-Telegram Northeast edition for 2 1/2
years from 1993 until 1996, was recovering from the ordeal in
Budapest, Hungary, on Thursday. The Post plans to send Finn back to
cover the conflict as soon as he is allowed back into the country,
Bennett said.
</P>
<P>
   The Post does not know why the Serbian police singled out Finn,
Bennett said. R. Jeffrey Smith, the Post's lead correspondent for
the Balkans, was not detained by Serbian police. Smith also left
Yugoslavia on Thursday.
</P>
<P>
   ``It has become extremely hazardous there,'' Bennett said.
``Almost no (American) reporters are left.''
</P>
<P>
   Finn has been the Post's Warsaw Bureau chief for the last 10
months, Bennett said.
</P>
<P>
   (Visit the Star-Telegram's online services on the World Wide
Web: www.star-telegram.com) nn
</P>
</TEXT>
