<HEADER>
A4478 &Cx1f; taf-z
u s &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-BKN-KNICKS-NYT &LR;      03-25 1050
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BKN-KNICKS-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
HOUSTON'S VIEW FROM THE BENCH: WATCHING THE KNICKS UNRAVEL  
(DW)
</HEADLINE>
   By SELENA ROBERTS   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   PHOENIX _ Allan Houston could lay back, stretch out his legs and
let his perspiration dry. He could be himself on the bench, where
there was no one to tell him to stand up straight, puff out his
chest or snap to attention.
</P>
<P>
   Coach Jeff Van Gundy didn't have time for that Wednesday night
in Sacramento. There was a game to be played and an attitude that
was required. After three years of mentally challenging Houston to
search for the hidden edge inside of his soft shell, Van Gundy
decided to bench his star shooter for the fourth quarter.
</P>
<P>
   Instead of being a part of the Knicks' habitual unraveling,
Houston watched as helpless as a witness to an accident as his team
lost its third game in a row.
</P>
<P>
   For the fourth time in the last week, the Knicks let a
fourth-quarter lead slip away. For the fourth time this season _
and third time alone for Patrick Ewing _ the Knicks were left to
take and miss a shot at the buzzer.
</P>
<P>
   For the second time this year, Latrell Sprewell's mental mistake
in the final seconds aided the collapse.
</P>
<P>
   Two weeks ago, Sprewell left Milwaukee's Del Curry alone for a
game-winning 3-pointer.
</P>
<P>
   Against the Kings, he inexplicably lost control of his dribble,
allowing the ball to escape off his left hand, in front of the
Sacramento rookie Jason Williams in a tie game with 12.1 seconds
remaining. Out of frustration, Sprewell fouled Williams and sent
him to the free-throw line where he made one of two to provide the
Kings with a 92-91 victory.
</P>
<P>
   ``I just lost it,'' said Sprewell, who scored 16 points and took
several panicked shots while hitting 3 of 7 attempts in the fourth
quarter. ``I wasn't sure what I wanted to do. I got going one way
and the ball went the other. It's the same old story. Another loss
in a close one. I think we're at the bottom of the barrel.''
</P>
<P>
   That's where you could find Houston's psyche as well. Slumped on
the bench, Houston never felt so isolated. He would have rather had
Van Gundy berate him than bench him. But deep down, Houston knew he
hadn't responded when the nondescript Tariq Abdul-Wahad defended
him chin-to-chin, and he realized his lethargic defense and
careless ball handling had left him where he belonged.
</P>
<P>
   ``If I had been playing well, I'd have been in the game,''
Houston said after shooting 3 for 8 and committing 3 turnovers in
26 minutes. ``I think the team needs me, and that's what's
frustrating. It's like I'm leaving the team out to dry right now.
I'm not worried about me.''
</P>
<P>
   But he is concerned with himself at times. Lately, he has seemed
torn between what kind of player he should be for the Knicks.
Should he run with Latrell Sprewell or wait for Patrick Ewing? Many
times, Houston's mind is cluttered with indecision.
</P>
<P>
   He wants to reveal a flashy side, but with 71 turnovers to just
89 assists, he does not possess the ball-handling skills to pull
off a jaw-dropping, no-look pass off the break. He longs to be a
consistent threat on the wing but often forgets to barge to the
basket when his jumper is not falling. When he gives up the ball to
Sprewell, there is no assurance that he'll get it back. When he
dumps the ball into Ewing, he becomes a plodding bystander.
</P>
<P>
   With time, Houston will probably find his niche and discover his
groove. In each of his four previous seasons, it has taken him
about two months to get going.
</P>
<P>
   But this year, there is no time. It's now, or it's over.
</P>
<P>
   Two months into the season, the Knicks are 15-13 as they prepare
to face the Suns on Friday. With less than half a season to go, the
Knicks are in danger of missing the playoffs for the first time in
more than a decade.
</P>
<P>
   It's a level of mediocrity borne, in part, out of unfamiliarity.
In the past, the Knicks have known who they can count on in a
difficult situation. Now, they don't appear sure. So far, Sprewell
has yet to prove he can be a money player on a winning team, and
Marcus Camby hasn't shown he's capable of finishing a physical
layup on a consistent basis.
</P>
<P>
   At core of the team, Ewing, Larry Johnson and Houston still
remain. Ewing, at age 36, is producing enough to keep his team in
games but has looked more and more deflated as the losses pile up.
Instead of bravado, you hear uncertainty.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's been a long time,'' Ewing said when asked when he could
remember a Knick team at 15-13. ``A real long time. But we have to
stay strong. What doesn't kill you makes you better.''
</P>
<P>
   Pain is all but killing Johnson. He has been close to
unstoppable early in games, but in a crammed schedule, the
tendinitis in his knee flares up on a nightly basis and his
mobility tends to plummet. He gritted his teeth to save two
rebounds by the Knicks in the last 48 seconds of the game to no
avail.
</P>
<P>
   Houston watched it all unfold from the bench. Maybe it was just
a one-time thing. Maybe it will inspire Houston.
</P>
<P>
   Right now, there are no signs that Van Gundy is ready to start
the frenzied Sprewell _ who has grumbled about his sixth man role _
and risk damaging Houston's confidence further by using him off the
bench.
</P>
<P>
   Houston's role is too important. He is the one player who is
healthy enough, young enough and talented enough to pick up his
team. You just wouldn't know it by looking at him when he lopes by.
He doesn't carry himself with a leader's attitude.
</P>
<P>
   For three years, Van Gundy has tried to coax Houston out of his
laid-back nature. He has clapped his hands, limited his minutes and
pulled out every tough love method he can find. Through it all, Van
Gundy has watched the affable Houston dig deep to unearth a defiant
mean streak, just as he did when he scored 30 points for an
undermanned Knick team to take the first-round playoff series last
year in Miami.
</P>
<P>
   But his dominant streaks are often followed up with a hiccup in
his mentality as he reverts back to form. Faced with Sacramento, in
a game the Knicks desperately needed for a self-esteem boost,
Houston couldn't snap out of his malaise. Van Gundy had little
option but to put him on the bench.
</P>
<P>
   ``Obviously, it didn't work because we didn't win,'' Van Gundy
said. `'I don't think it was one of Allan's better nights.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
