<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-03-25 21:59 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A4480 &Cx1f; tdt-z
u w &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-KOSOVO-CLINTON-BOS &LR;      03-25 1213
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-KOSOVO-CLINTON-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
AIR ATTACK CONTINUES AS US EMBASSIES ARE TARGETED
</HEADLINE>
  (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By ANN SCALES AND LOUISE D. PALMER  
 c.1999 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON _ NATO forces launched a second round of airstrikes
Thursday against Serbian military targets in Yugoslavia as
protesters pelted US embassies in Macedonia and Russia and US
officials worried that the violence was spreading into neighboring
Albania.
</P>
<P>
   US officials, seeking to build public support for the mission,
said Thursday that the forces of Yugoslav President Slobodan
Milosevic had not let up their attacks on the ethnic Albanian
population in Kosovo, even after the US-led NATO strikes heavily
damaged Serb military bases and ammunition storage sites in the
first bombing wave on Wednesday.
</P>
<P>
   ``There have been some further burning of villages, further
sweep operations, some shelling into Albania,'' said National
Security Adviser Samuel R. ``Sandy'' Berger. ``And it's obviously
very disturbing to us.''
</P>
<P>
   Several US officials pointed to Serbia's continuing aggression
against the Kosovar Albanians and the spread of fighting beyond
Yugoslavia's borders as evidence the airstrikes were necessary.
</P>
<P>
   ``These developments are unfortunately exactly what we have come
to expect from President Milosevic,'' Secretary of State Madeleine
K. Albright said at a news briefing. ``They underscore the need for
sustained military action to limit the capability of his military
to threaten innocent people in Kosovo.''
</P>
<P>
   Albright said ``diplomatic channels remain open'' for Milosevic.
``He knows how to get in touch with us.''
</P>
<P>
   President Clinton joined other US officials in dismissing the
possibility of using US ground troops to help the Kosovars,
insisting that NATO's air power was sufficient to damage Serbia's
military capacity.
</P>
<P>
   US officials said the NATO bombing campaign would continue until
Milosevic's ability to wage war is diminished, or until he ends the
fighting in Kosovo and accepts the peace agreement recently
negotiated in France and signed by the ethnic Albanian separatists
but rejected by the Serbs.
</P>
<P>
   Shortly after the second day of airstrikes began Thursday, the
Yugoslav government announced it was breaking off diplomatic
relations with the United States, France, Germany, and Britain.
</P>
<P>
   The airstrikes had ``humiliated and embarrassed'' relations
between Yugoslav and those four countries, said a statement read on
Serbian state television.
</P>
<P>
   Berger and Albright insisted that the NATO alliance of 19
nations was not showing signs of strain with the mission, though
Greece and Italy suggested a return to the negotiating table.
</P>
<P>
   ``I can assure you that the allies are united and supported by
many NATO partners behind forceful and sustained NATO action,''
Albright said.
</P>
<P>
   Pentagon spokesman Kenneth H. Bacon said the second day of
strikes, which began at noon, would be ``substantive'' and
``severe.''
</P>
<P>
   Having focused the first wave of strikes on neutralizing
Serbia's air defenses, the second phase is designed to destroy the
Yugoslav military and police forces responsible for attacking
Kosovar Albanians, he said.
</P>
<P>
   The strikes also would rely more heavily on manned aircraft
rather than missiles. By late Thursday afternoon, 60 warplanes had
taken off from Aviano Air Force Base in Italy, and 20 Tomahawk
cruise missiles were launched. There was another appearance by two
batwing B-2 Stealth bombers, which successfully dropped 2,000-pound
bombs Thursday &UR;  &LR; night.
</P>
<P>
   Missiles and bombs blasted army barracks used in the campaign
against ethnic Albanians, an airport, and communications and air
defense centers across the country, witnesses told Reuters.
</P>
<P>
   At NATO headquarters in Brussels, NATO Secretary General Javier
Solana and US Army General Wesley Clark, the top commander of NATO
forces, said they were satisfied with the initial round of strikes.
</P>
<P>
   Forty targets, including command and control systems, and
facilities of the ministerial police forces and the Yugoslav
military, were hit during the first phase of the action, dubbed
``Operation Allied Force.''
</P>
<P>
   Yugoslav forces did not unleash the expected wave of
antiaircraft battery against NATO aircraft, most of which were
flying above their shooting range, but there was some air-to-air
combat, with losses only on the Serbian side.
</P>
<P>
   Clark and Solana, however, warned of the considerable strength
and firepower of Yugoslav forces, and the danger the weather and
terrain posed to NATO forces.
</P>
<P>
   Clark predicted that Serb forces would be brought to their knees
before the operation ended.
</P>
<P>
   ``We're going to systematically and progressively attack,
disrupt, degrade, devastate and ultimately _ unless President
Milosevic complies with the demands of the international community
_ we're going to destroy his forces,'' Clark said.
</P>
<P>
   In Macedonia, which borders Yugoslavia, thousands of
demonstrators chanting ``NATO out of Macedonia'' reacted angrily to
the military action and attacked the US Embassy there.
</P>
<P>
   Macedonia has a NATO presence of about 10,000 troops that could
be used to implement the peace agreement, if and when Milosevic
signs it. Under the agreement, US troops would be part of an
international peacekeeping force of nearly 30,000.
</P>
<P>
   Concern is mounting over the safety of NATO soldiers in Bosnia
and in Macedonia. Members of Congress were told during a briefing
Thursday that it appeared Serbian forces were also shelling
Macedonia.
</P>
<P>
   In Moscow, protesters yelling ``fascists'' burned the US flag
and smashed windows, illustrating widespread anger with the attacks
on the Serbs, who have cultural, historical, and religious ties to
Russia. Russia introduced a UN Security Council resolution Thursday
demanding an immediate halt to the attacks.
</P>
<P>
   In Washington, the administration fended off criticism in
Congress. Senators pointed to mounting Serb aggression against
Kosovar Albanians as evidence that Milosevic might not submit.
</P>
<P>
   ``We need to have an end game, an exit strategy, and clearly
articulated goals,'' said Senator John McCain, Republican of
Arizona.
</P>
<P>
   Thursday, Clinton maintained, ``The exit strategy is what it
always is in a military operation: It's when the mission is
completed.''
</P>
<P>
   Some senators, however, are looking for new strategies to
resolve the conflict. Senators Joseph I. Lieberman, a Democrat in
Connecticut, and Mitch McConnell, a Republican in Kentucky,
introduced a bill Thursday calling for $25 million to arm the
Kosovars to defend themselves against the Serbs.
</P>
<P>
   Senator Jesse Helms, Republican of North Carolina, also proposed
legislation to make the overthrow of Milosevic official US policy.
</P>
<P>
   Polls show that about half of all Americans support the
airstrikes. But Clinton said he was not concerned the public is not
more strongly behind the action. ``I believe that many Americans
really have not thought a lot about this until the last two days.''
</P>
<P>
   Serbia ordered out foreign journalists Thursday from countries
participating in NATO airstrikes, accusing them of aiding the
bombing campaign.
</P>
<P>
   A Globe correspondent was among those ordered out, but Globe
reporters remain in the Yugoslav republic of Montenegro and in
neighboring Macedonia.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
