John Hancock Mutual Life Insurance, has not withdrawn the insurer's
sponsorship of the Olympics, but he has removed the Olympic logo
from its TV ads. ``They lied to us,'' says D'Alessandro of the way
the International Olympics Committee, the governing body of the
Games, has dragged its feet. ``They told us the scandal would be
put behind us. But their version of reform doesn't appear to be
anybody else's.'' (Jim Bourg/New York Times Photo)
</P>
<P>
   (NYT10) SAN JOSE, Calif. -- March 25, 1999 -- ADV. FOR SUN.,
MARCH 28 -- BIZ-ASIAN-ENTREPRENEURS-2, 3-25 -- Sung Kim, head of
Nextream Inc., a San Jose start-up company that is developing
software to link banks to the Internet. Kim found that he had to
leave a stifling corporate environment in his native South Korea to
build a business based on the World Wide Web. (Peter DaSilva/New
York Times Photo)
</P>
<P>
   (NYT9) TORRANCE, Calif. -- March 25, 1999 -- ADV. FOR SUN.,
MARCH 28 -- BIZ-ASIAN-ENTREPRENEURS-1, 3-25 -- Mike Morishita, who
left Nippon Telephone and Telegraph to start a Web consulting
business in Torrance, stands behind a pane of glass in his office.
He says Nippon Telephone viewed the Internet not as an opportunity
but as a reason to raise charges. (Edward Carreon/New York Times
Photo)
</P>
<P>
   (NYT8) NEW YORK -- March 25, 1999 -- CORIGLIANO, 3-25 -- John
Corigliano, who has finished, again, his ``Dylan Thomas Trilogy.''
Trim and young-looking at 61, Corigliano insists that he won't
accept a commission until he has asked himself a few crucial
questions. ``The most important is, why am I writing this work?''
he says. ``What do I want to do in it? What have I got to say
that's worth saying? And what is there new for me to discover in
writing it, either about specific technical problems or abstract
musical ones?'' (Fred R. Conrad/New York Times Photo) *LITE
</P>
<P>
   (NYT7) NEW YORK -- March 25, 1999 -- CLOSER-THEATER-REVIEW, 3-25
-- Natasha Richardson and Ciaran Hinds in ``Closer,'' written and
directed by Patrick Marber, which opened last night at the Music
Box. ``Closer'' is the latest in a series of anti-romantic comedies
from England about the joylessness of sex. (Sara Krulwich/New York
Times Photo)
</P>
<P>
   (NYT6) NEW YORK -- March 25, 1999 -- NY-POLICE, 3-25 --
Protesters in support of police pass by demonstrators calling for
the arrest of cops who shot Amadou Diallo outside police
headquarters on Thursday. Protests continued over the death of
Diallo, an unarmed black man killed in a hail of 41 bullets fired
by four white officers last month. (Librado Romero/New York Times
Photo)
</P>
<P>
   (NYT5) BUDAPEST, Hungary -- March 25, 1999 -- KOSOVO-RDP-2, 3-25
-- Richard Holbrooke talks on a cell phone while walking along the
Danube River on Thursday. Holbrooke, who was sent by President
Clinton to Belgrade earlier this week to make a last minute bid for
a peaceful solution to the Kosovo problem, said on Thursday that
NATO air strikes against Yugoslavia would be sustained and severe
unless Belgrade signed the Kosovo peace agreement. (Edward
Keating/New York Times Photo)
</P>
<P>
   (NYT4) WASHINGTON -- March 25, 1999 -- MICROSOFT-ANTITRUST, 3-25
-- Bill Gates, chairman of Microsoft, during a talk at Georgetown
University School of Business on Thursday. State and Federal
officials were dismissive of Microsoft's proposal to settle its
antitrust suit, but they added that it was likely that the two
sides would meet for settlement talks nonetheless, probably
beginning next Tuesday. (Marty Katz/New York Times Photo)
</P>
<P>
   (NYT3) WASHINGTON -- March 25, 1999 -- NURSING-HOMES, 3-25 --
President Clinton signs the Nursing Home Resident Protection Act of
1999 as legislators, sponsors and supporters of the legislation
look on, Thursday in the Oval Office. The law prohibits nursing
homes from evicting Medicaid patients from nursing homes in favor
of patients who can pay more privately. (Paul Hosefros/New York
Times Photo)
</P>
<P>
   (NYT2) CERVIA, Italy -- March 25, 1999 -- KOSOVO-RDP-1, 3-25 --
A crew chief helps an F-15C pilot strap in before taking off for
his mission over Yugoslavia on Wednesday. With 11 NATO bases on its
soil, Italy is at the heart of the NATO bombing campaign against
Yugoslavia. (TSgt Greg Suhay/U.S. Air Force/New York Times Photo)
</P>
<P>
   (NYT1) KATY, Texas -- March 25, 1999 -- LLAMAS-CARTING, 3-25 --
Trainer Lee Lawrence runs his llama at a llama-cart-driving school.
Llamas, members of the camel family, can be trained to pull carts
in less than an hour. ``Their curiousity makes them very easy to
train,'' says Lawrence, a financial planner who runs about 80 head
of llamas as a hobby. (Carlos Antonio Rios/Houston Chronicle) *LITE
</P>
