<DOCNO> NYT19990325.0377 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-03-25 22:00 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A4483 &Cx1f; tad-z
u a &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-JASON26-COX     03-25 0945
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-JASON26-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    `Jason' star blames lawyers for mega-bust
 &HT;    By Alex Clough
 &HT;    c. 1999 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   WEST PALM BEACH, Fla. _
</P>
<P>
   He was ``Jason in Friday the 13th, Part 2,'' victimizing hapless
teens.
</P>
<P>
   Now, F. Warrington Gillet III says he's the victim _ of a Fort
Lauderdale-based law firm that cheated him, and his Palm Beach
friends, out of millions.
</P>
<P>
   Gillet, of Maryland, might not be known to those who vote for
the Oscars, but his family is very well known by those in the local
monied crowd.
</P>
<P>
   His father and stepmother, F. Warrington and Elesabeth, are
active in Palm Beach society and in the horsey set in Maryland. The
late cereal heiress Marjorie Merriweather Post is the younger
Gillet's great-grandmother.
</P>
<P>
   Gillet, 40, tapped this crowd when he came up with an idea for a
company, Discovery Studio Inc. Gillet says in a federal lawsuit
that his company was torpedoed by the fraud and negligence of the
law firm he hired _ Atlas, Pearlman, Trop &AMP; Borkson.
</P>
<P>
   An attorney for Atlas Pearlman, which has an office in Boca
Raton, denied the charge and said Gillet's problems resulted from
bad luck, not fraud.
</P>
<P>
   ``He had a grandiose dream and ideas about making huge profits.
But he came into the market when it was volatile. . . . It didn't
work out,'' said James Kaplan.
</P>
<P>
   Discovery's plan was to set up photography studios in malls.
Those looking to break into modeling would pay small fees to get
their photos taken and sent to top agencies. Discovery also would
peddle cosmetics and perfumes _ the real revenue source of the
business.
</P>
<P>
   Gillet, who left acting after his stint as Jason in the 1981
movie, pulled out all the stops to launch his new business. He
brought on board Palm Beach resident Joseph Cornacchia, who
manufactured the board game Pictionary and was a top marketer of
Trivial Pursuit. Cornacchia, who acted in an informal advisory
role, invested $50,000.
</P>
<P>
   Socialite Mary Lou Whitney also was involved as a member of the
company's beauty advisory committee. Two European princesses, Bea
Auersberg of Austria and Loretta Wittgenstein of Germany, signed on
to help market and distribute Discovery products overseas,
according to the company's business plan.
</P>
<P>
   Gillet then struck a deal with shopping center developer Al
Taubman to place Discovery Studios in his malls, according to the
business plan. Gillet also received a $6 million commitment from
Select Capital Advisors in Miami.
</P>
<P>
   Everything was in place. All Gillet needed was a public company
shell into which he could merge his idea. The public company then
would sell stock to raise the millions needed to launch his venture
and reward Gillet's backers.
</P>
<P>
   Gillet found such a shell in Universal Licensing. But Gillet
said his lawyer was suspicious of the deal. So Gillet said he
ditched the lawyer and hired the law firm that represented
Universal Licensing.
</P>
<P>
   Atlas Pearlman was the firm. The problem, according to Gillet,
was the firm had a conflict of interest: Atlas Pearlman didn't tell
him that two of its partners also were shareholders in Universal
Licensing.
</P>
<P>
   Only after the deal was done did Gillet learn of the law firm
partners' involvement _ and that Universal Licensing was under
investigation by the National Association of Securities Dealers, he
says in his suit.
</P>
<P>
   Gillet filed suit last year in U.S. District Court in Fort
Lauderdale and amended his complaint this month.
</P>
<P>
   Gillet said an investigation revealed Universal Licensing wasn't
a public company after all. The deal was called off, but Gillet
says Universal Licensing didn't return the Discovery Studio name.
</P>
<P>
   Now, Gillet wants $50 million from Atlas Pearlman; Joel
Mayersohn, the Atlas Pearlman lawyer who worked on the deal; and
James Falacaro, an owner of Universal Licensing.
</P>
<P>
   In his amended complaint filed March 9, Gillet says Atlas
Pearlman ``owed a duty . . . to discuss their conflict of interest
and make full disclosure,'' as well as conduct due diligence on
Universal Licensing.
</P>
<P>
   Gillet says his damages include money lost by investors and on
start-up costs, as well as the revenue he expected from the
business.
</P>
<P>
   ``I hired Atlas Pearlman to do the deal. . . . I just didn't
know they had a vested interest as well,'' Gillet said.
</P>
<P>
   Atlas Pearlman's Kaplan doesn't deny that two of the firm's
partners had an interest in Universal Licensing. But he said the
firm had no duty to tell Gillet because Gillet wasn't a client.
Discovery Studio hired Atlas Pearlman after the deal was done to
handle reporting requirements for the public company, Kaplan said.
</P>
<P>
   But Gillet said he hired Atlas Pearlman before the deal was
closed and has a cancelled check to prove it.
</P>
<P>
   Kaplan insists that ``at no time did Atlas Pearlman represent
both sides of the transaction. . . . I don't know that Discovery
Studio had counsel.''
</P>
<P>
   Kaplan also maintains that Universal Licensing was a publicly
traded company and had assets _ which Gillet disputes.
</P>
<P>
   At least one investor, Cornacchia, seems resigned to his loss.
``When you invest in start-ups, you hope you get a fair shake, but
90 percent of them fail,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   Gillet says he's determined to make Atlas Pearlman pay for a
debacle that nearly ruined his life.
</P>
<P>
   Gillet said he not only lost $500,000 of his own money, as well
as a home in New York, but his misfortune might cost him his
marriage as well.
</P>
<P>
   ``Even though I have had well-off family in Palm Beach, I've had
to struggle and work my way up like everyone else,'' Gillet said.
``I'm a regular guy just trying to make it.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
