<DOCNO> NYT19990325.0380 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-03-25 22:01 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A4486 &Cx1f; taf-z
u f &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-LYCOS-USA-MARKETPLACE     03-25 1170
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-LYCOS-USA-MARKETPLACE-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
IN THE LYCOS DEAL, OLD RULES DO NOT APPLY  
(DW)
</HEADLINE>
   By LAURA M. HOLSON   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   Not every deal maker could finagle a merger agreement that
forbids his proposed partner from negotiating with other interested
parties. If his betrothed does get an unsolicited offer, requires
it to sell him nearly 20 percent of the company. But those are the
terms that Diller, chief executive of USA Networks, has extracted
from Lycos Inc., the Internet portal company.
</P>
<P>
   Investors have reacted negatively to the proposed union, which
would give Lycos shareholders 30 percent of a new company combining
the portal business with USA's home-shopping and other
electronic-retail businesses.
</P>
<P>
   Upset over the stock's decline _ now down more than 25 percent
since the deal was announced last month _ Lycos' largest
shareholder, David Wetherell, quit his post on the board of
directors in protest and has said he is seeking alternatives.
</P>
<P>
   This complex transaction may say less about Diller, though, than
about the world of deal-making when a traditional media company
crosses paths with an Internet company. The old rules and
assumptions do not seem to apply; deals may be struck in days, not
months; the value of combinations can be so hard to understand that
stock prices swing erratically, and cash-poor Internet companies
may be willing to sacrifice standard protections.
</P>
<P>
   ``This is going to happen again and again,'' said Paul Noglows,
an analyst at Hambrecht &AMP; Quist. ``You are seeing the collision of
two very different worlds.''
</P>
<P>
   Merger agreements typically include a provision barring the
seller from seeking another suitor. But the seller usually can
consider an unsolicited offer that is better than the one on the
table. The Lycos agreement is quite restrictive, merger lawyers
say, making it nearly impossible for Lycos executives to negotiate
if a more favorable suitor comes along.
</P>
<P>
   Why would management agree to such terms?
</P>
<P>
   Robert J. Davis, chief executive of Lycos, would not comment on
the agreement, saying he was prohibited from doing so because of
the pending deal. Representatives of Wasserstein, Perella, the
investment adviser to Lycos, and Testa, Hurwitz &AMP; Thiebeault, its
law firm, also refused to comment.
</P>
<P>
   But one answer might be found in Lycos' desperation to find a
partner. The company was shopped to as many as 30 potential
partners _ including Time Warner, CBS and Walt Disney _ over 15
months. Only General Electric's NBC network considered buying a
stake, people close to Lycos said.
</P>
<P>
   Talks with NBC faltered in early January. Then Lycos reached out
to USA Networks, beginning eight days of intense negotiations with
Diller. Several other Internet portals had announced deals that
month, putting more pressure on Lycos, analysts said. If the
company did not move quickly, opportunities might be lost.
</P>
<P>
   Davis spent the first weekend of February _ while his team was
negotiating with Diller _ talking with executives he had previously
approached to make sure they hadn't changed their minds, a person
close to Lycos said. With no other interested parties, limiting its
ability to talk with others later ``didn't seem that important,''
this person said. Besides, negotiators for USA Networks pressed the
point, the person said.
</P>
<P>
   Diller echoed some of that sentiment Thursday. ``I think they
felt after all those conversations Nippon Steel wouldn't come in
and make an offer,'' he said. ``It was not one of the points I got
involved in.''
</P>
<P>
   The negotiations were not the first time Davis and Diller had
faced off. A year and a half ago, Lycos was interested in USA
Networks' Internet assets and talked with Diller about an alliance.
As part of that deal, Davis discussed offering Diller a seat on the
board, said Wetherell, the disgruntled former Lycos board member
and the chairman and chief executive of CMGI Inc., which invests in
Internet companies.
</P>
<P>
   To further complicate negotiations, the New York law firm of
Wachtell, Lipton, Rosen &AMP; Katz advised Lycos in its failed
discussions with NBC. But when USA Networks entered the picture,
the firm officially switched camps. Testa, Hurwitz was hired to
represent Lycos, but several people involved in the talks said
Wachtell continued to counsel Lycos.
</P>
<P>
   It is not illegal to advise both companies in a deal _ Wachtell
has done it before _ but some industry experts say it is
ill-advised if a deal goes awry. Lawyers from Wachtell did not
return repeated phone calls seeking comment.
</P>
<P>
   While USA Networks worked to keep other bidders out of the
picture, Lycos executives were concerned about another standard
part of the merger contract. A person close to Lycos said the
company was wary of agreeing to an astronomical breakup fee, which
compensates an intended partner if the deal falls apart.
</P>
<P>
   ``Cash is in short supply in the Internet world,'' said Samuel
Hayes, a professor of finance at Harvard University's business
school. ``Over-priced stock is the currency of choice.''
</P>
<P>
   So the two companies agreed that USA Networks would get the
option to buy a 17.5 percent stake in Lycos for $127.14 a share if
an unsolicited offer emerged or if the Lycos board decided to bow
out, according to Securities and Exchange Commission filings and
people close to the talks.
</P>
<P>
   On Feb. 8 _ the night before the deal was announced _ Lycos
stock closed at $127.25. In the next two days, the stock price sank
31 percent, to $87.25 a share. The confusion over the stock's value
can be chalked up to the different ways investors assess Internet
and media companies. ``I've yet to hear anyone say the assembling
of assets for these two companies doesn't make sense,'' Diller
said.
</P>
<P>
   Even Wetherell admits he might not be making such a fuss if the
stock price had not collapsed. Of course, Diller's option is
worthless at the current stock price of $92.625. (If the majority
of shareholders vote against the deal in July as Wetherell expects,
Diller loses his option entirely.)
</P>
<P>
   ``I think people got so preconditioned to the thought there was
going to be a huge premium paid, they forgot to look at the
facts,'' said Noglows of Hambrecht &AMP; Quist. In a Feb. 11 report, he
noted that Lycos stock had risen 127 percent since the start of the
year and more than 14 percent since Yahoo's Jan. 28 announcement
that it was buying Geocities. ``I don't think anyone was prepared
for investors' reactions to what was a complicated transaction.''
</P>
<P>
   Since leaving the board, Wetherell has said he has talked to
others about forming a group of strategic investors to buy the
company and has even considered waging a proxy battle. He also said
he would support spinning off several Lycos divisions to increase
shareholder value.
</P>
<P>
   For now, investors can only sit back and watch the gamesmanship.
</P>
<P>
   ``It becomes a game of chess for Diller,'' said Noglows. ``He
has to determine does he have a clear majority or does he have to
come back with a sweeter bid?''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
