<SLUG> BC-MONTENEGRO-REACTION-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
NOW TARGETED, MONTENEGRINS ARE CRITICAL OF US
</HEADLINE>
  (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By CHARLES M. SENNOTT  
 c.1999 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   PODGORICA, Yugoslavia _ Three explosions rocked this city just
after nightfall Thursday as a second and more severe wave of NATO
attacks on Yugoslav military positions got under way.
</P>
<P>
   In the last light of day, the streets emptied and grew quiet,
except for the pounding of boots on pavement as fatigue-clad troops
fanned out across this city, the capital of the Yugoslav Republic
of Montenegro.
</P>
<P>
   Just before the bombing started, Violeta Vlasic, 31, rushed to
buy supplies at a grocery store.
</P>
<P>
   ``We are very afraid,'' she said, clutching her 2-year-old
daughter Dara in one arm and a bundle of groceries in the other.
``Now we are going to hide.''
</P>
<P>
   Vlasic lives in a neighborhood adjacent to a military base on
the outskirts of this city, and she feared that the area was a
likely target. So she and her family moved in with cousins who live
downtown.
</P>
<P>
   ``Does America feel good about this, making mothers with their
children run for cover?'' she asked as she hurried on her errand.
</P>
<P>
   The display of NATO's firepower has unleashed a pervasive fear
on the streets of this city of 120,000, even though government
radio was reporting a relatively limited civilian death toll of 10
across Yugoslavia.
</P>
<P>
   Air raid sirens wailed intermittently Thursday night as dozens
of cruise missiles launched from the US Navy's 6th Fleet off the
coast arced through the sky and fighter jets and stealth bombers
silently cruised high overhead, seeking their targets.
</P>
<P>
   With the light of day Thursday, Montenegrins got their first
look at the damage caused by the initial night of NATO bombing, and
along with it came a rising anger and resentment toward the United
States and NATO.
</P>
<P>
   Sitting in the sunshine of his garden barely half a mile from an
army radar station that was bombed in Zagrade, just north of the
port of Bar, Tony Mijo, 63, described what he had seen the night
before. He was watching television at about 8:30 p.m. when the
first cruise missile slammed into a radar station perched on a
rocky bluff overlooking the Adriatic Sea, he said.
</P>
<P>
   He stepped out on his porch after hearing the explosion and saw
a second missile score a direct hit on a cluster of military
buildings, as an orange plume of fire shot through the clear night
sky. The blast shook the frame of his house, cracking the plaster
walls.
</P>
<P>
   ``You bloody Americans still think you're fighting Indians. You
are cowards with your big smart bombs,'' said Mijo in the raw
English he learned in the coal mines of Australia, where he worked
for nearly 20 years.
</P>
<P>
   ``You sit there with your bloody warships and you call us an
aggressor while you bomb our own land. This is your bloody
justice?'' he asked, shaking with anger.
</P>
<P>
   His torrent of hatred against the United States suggested the
emergence of a new sentiment in Montenegro. The population of
600,000 has long seen itself as separate from the 8 million Serbs
under Yugoslav President Slobodan Milosevic.
</P>
<P>
   The republic was moving toward democracy. Its parliament was
talking of independence from Milosevic's repressive, autocratic
regime and what many Montenegrins feel is Milosevic's
unconstitutional federal government in the Serbian capital of
Belgrade.
</P>
<P>
   ``We tried to play nice with America. We smiled and talked about
democracy. We bloody crawled for America,'' said Mijo. ``Then you
bombed us. All American promises are lies. Milosevic knows that. He
will lose this war, but at least he is standing up.''
</P>
<P>
   The fact that US and NATO forces did not spare Montenegro
infuriates the people here, and may end up playing to Milosevic's
nationalistic aspirations if it helps him unify what remains of
Yugoslavia in its resentment toward the United States. The republic
was hard hit, its airports, radar stations, and military compounds
battered.
</P>
<P>
   Milka Tadic, managing editor of Montenegro's respected and
independent news magazine ``Monitor,'' said, ``After these
bombings, the feelings are different. We didn't expect America to
strike us. And it puts the (Montenegrin) government in a very
strange situation. The country it thought was an ally is now
bombing it.''
</P>
<P>
   An interview with Tadic was interrupted by the first two
explosions in the capital as the second night of bombing began. She
ran to a hotel balcony and looked out across the lights of the city
as a plume of smoke rose over a distant cluster of buildings.
</P>
<P>
   ``Look at that. This ends up helping Milosevic. It helps him
unify the country, in the sense of us having the same enemy. But I
have to hope that it will not last, and that Montenegrins will know
that Milosevic is the devil.''
</P>
<P>
   Olivera Nikolic of Montenegro's independent broadcast station,
Radio Antenna M, said the Montenegrin Parliament was in its second
day of marathon meetings over whether the republic would secede
from the federation under Milosevic. The possibility, she said,
leaves the disintegrating Yugoslavia again on ``the brink of civil
war''
</P>
<P>
   ``There's anger against America, but mostly there is confusion.
How it will sort itself out is the key. It could be a move toward
independence, it could trigger civil war, or it could be that
Milosevic gets greater unity. But that will take a while. For now,
we are just in shock.''
</P>
<P>
   Just before the bombing began anew Thursday &UR;  &LR; night, a young
couple was hurrying home.
</P>
<P>
   ``How can America do this? What do you think this
accomplishes?'' asked Lyca Beshica, 24, with his wife Paula, 21, as
they walked quickly down the street. ``We need an independent state
here, and we thought America would help us.''
</P>
<P>
   Lyca, who faces a call-up for the draft in the Yugoslav Army,
said the only way he would take up arms is to fight for an
independent Montenegro. But he succinctly described the conundrum
the Montenegrins face.
</P>
<P>
   ``We need America,'' he said. ``But now we don't trust them.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
