<SLUG> BC-MICH-SCHOOLS-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
CONTROL OF DETROIT SCHOOLS IS TRANSFERRED TO MAYOR AND GOVERNOR 
</HEADLINE>
   (af)  
 By KEITH BRADSHER   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   DETROIT _ Michigan's House and Senate voted Thursday to transfer
control of Detroit's schools from the city's elected school board
to the city's mayor and the state's governor, the latest in a
series of efforts by state legislatures to improve test scores by
taking authority away from school boards.
</P>
<P>
   Gov. John Engler said he would sign the legislation on Friday.
It calls for Mayor Dennis Archer to appoint six members to a new,
seven-member board; the state superintendent of education, Arthur
Ellis, an Engler appointee, will be the seventh member.
</P>
<P>
   The bill immediately eliminates all of the current board's legal
and budgetary authority. The current board's 11 members will serve
out their staggered terms, but they will only have an advisory
role. City residents will vote in five years on whether to replace
the new, appointed board with another elected board.
</P>
<P>
   The votes Thursday by the two Republican-controlled chambers
represented a political victory for the Republican governor, who
has emphasized education issues during his eight years in office
and in his increasingly frequent appearances at national Republican
events. But until Republicans took control of the Michigan House
last November, he was unable to intervene in the state's largest
city, where half the children do not graduate from high school and
half those who graduate have trouble meeting state standards for
high school graduates.
</P>
<P>
   Early versions of Thursday's bill called for Archer, a moderate
Democrat, to name all seven members of the new board. But the
mayor's political opponents, mainly Democrats from the populist
wing of the local party, strenuously fought giving him any more
power and ended up calling for the governor to play a role on the
new board, even though this meant turning to a Republican outside
the city.
</P>
<P>
   Opponents said that removing an elected board was undemocratic
denial of voting rights in a mostly black city by the all-white
Republican majorities in the Michigan House and Senate. Still,
polls showed considerable public support for the takeover, which
was backed by the city's two most powerful political forces,
municipal unions and the largely black Council of Baptist pastors. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   The presence of Ellis on the new board will effectively give the
governor veto power in the selection of the city's next school
superintendent, or chief executive officer, as Thursday's
legislation renames the position. The legislation requires that the
new board be unanimous in choosing the next chief executive
officer.
</P>
<P>
   State legislatures have removed school boards in Chicago,
Cleveland and five school districts in New Jersey, including
Newark. Similar plans have been proposed for Oakland, Calif., St.
Louis, Los Angeles, Philadelphia and Milwaukee.
</P>
<P>
   Darryl L. Redmond, the Baptist pastor who is the current board
president, declined to comment on Thursday's vote. But Ben
Washburn, a school board member, questioned whether an appointed
board could be more effective than an elected board in addressing
issues like mustering community support for tighter discipline in
schools.
</P>
<P>
   ``You might get a little more technical expertise, but what have
you given up?'' he asked.
</P>
<P>
   Republicans had repeatedly attributed the poor performance of
Detroit students to the school board's financial management
problems. Redmond had responded that urban poverty and crime were
mainly responsible for the schools' troubles, and that the board
was changing its ways.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
