<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-OHAIR-SUSPECT-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
POSSIBLE BREAKTHROUGH IN CASE OF MADALYN MURRAY O'HAIR 
</HEADLINE>
  
 (ATTN: Texas)  (mk) 
 By RICK LYMAN   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   HOUSTON _ In what may be a breakthrough in the disappearance of
atheist leader Madalyn Murray O'Hair, an Austin lawyer representing
a former office manager for the missing woman said federal
officials told him that his client is suspected of being part of a
plot to rob and murder Ms. O'Hair.
</P>
<P>
   David Waters, 52, appeared before a federal magistrate in Austin
Thursday on weapons charges following an eight-hour search
Wednesday of his car and apartment, which uncovered a cache of 119
rounds of ammunition. It is illegal for Waters, a convicted felon,
to have the ammunition in his possession.
</P>
<P>
   Following the appearance, Patrick Ganne, the lawyer representing
Waters, said that federal officials suspect his client of
complicity in Ms. O'Hair's mysterious disappearance four years ago,
as well as in the disappearance at the same time of her son, Jon
Garth Murray; her granddaughter, Robin Murray O'Hair, and $500,000
in gold coins that belonged to the O'Hair family.
</P>
<P>
   Ganne told reporters that assistant U.S. attorney Gerald Caruth
had told him that on Wednesday the authorities had also questioned
others with knowledge of Ms. O'Hair's disappearance, and that they
were pointing the finger at Waters. ``He told me, `People are
rolling over on your client and he better get right with God,'''
Ganne said.
</P>
<P>
   A spokesman for the U.S. attorney declined to comment.
</P>
<P>
   A federal judge ordered Waters held without bond Thursday on the
weapons charges, but no mention was made of the O'Hair case.
</P>
<P>
   An affidavit that supported the warrant used to search Waters'
home _ and which presumably explains the reason for the search _
remained under court seal Thursday.
</P>
<P>
   Waters' name had arisen early in the speculation over what might
have happened to Ms. O'Hair. Before going to work for Ms. O'Hair,
Waters had served several years in an Illinois penitentiary on a
murder charge, and in 1994 he pleaded guilty to theft following the
disappearance of $54,000 from American Atheists Inc., the
Austin-based group Ms. O'Hair founded.
</P>
<P>
   Agents from the FBI, the IRS, the Bureau of Alcohol, Tobacco and
Firearms, and the Dallas County sheriff's office spent eight hours
searching Waters' home on Wednesday before discovering the cache of
ammunition. ``Mr. Waters was present during the search,'' said
Darren Holmes, an FBI spokesman. ``He was very cooperative.''
</P>
<P>
   After the ammunition was found, Waters was handcuffed, led from
the house through a cluster of reporters and charged with the
weapons violations.
</P>
<P>
   Waters has repeatedly said that he had nothing to do with the
disappearance of Ms. O'Hair or the others. His lawyer said Thursday
that the ammunition found in Waters' apartment belongs to a former
girlfriend, who recently moved out.
</P>
<P>
   Ms. O'Hair first came to national attention when she filed suit
in 1960 to have prayer removed from the public schools in
Baltimore. Three years later she was one of the parties in a suit
that reached the U.S. Supreme Court and led to a federal ban on
school prayer.
</P>
<P>
   In subsequent years, she became a prominent proponent for the
widest possible separation of church and state and a frequent
target of religious fundamentalists. She once proudly described
herself as ``the most hated woman in America.''
</P>
<P>
   By the time she disappeared, however, Ms. O'Hair had dropped
from the national spotlight and was ill and bitter over her
frustrated attempts for greater political prominence.
</P>
<P>
   Speculation about what might have happened to Ms. O'Hair and the
others has varied widely, from those who believe they were robbed
and murdered to those who believe they fled the country with money
purloined from the organization's coffers. Ms. O'Hair has not been
seen in public since she left Austin in September 1995 with her son
and granddaughter. She apparently spent a month in San Antonio
before all of them fell from sight completely.
</P>
<P>
   Little new had been heard about the case in recent years until
the auction earlier this year of the missing family's household
effects, to pay a portion of their back taxes. Around the same
time, the San Antonio Express-News reported that, at the urging of
the newspaper, the authorities had genetically tested the remains
of an unidentified body found in Dallas in October 1995 and
discovered that it was that of Danny Fry, a former convict and a
friend of Waters.
</P>
<P>
   One of the theories being explored by the authorities was that
Fry had been involved in the disappearances and was killed in a
falling out with others involved.
</P>
<P>
   Waters has told reporters that he knows nothing about what
happened to Fry.
</P>
<P>
   Ganne asked Thursday how the authorities could believe his
client was involved in a plot to steal hundreds of thousands of
dollars from the O'Hair family, and kill them to cover it up, when
he is clearly strapped for cash. If Waters did it, Ganne asked, why
didn't he flee Austin with the money? Where is the money?
</P>
<P>
   ``Someone's got a bunch of money out of this,'' Ganne told The
Associated Press. ``It's not Waters. He's about to be evicted from
his apartment.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-03-25-99 2213EST &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> NYT19990325.0386 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-03-25 22:17 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A4498 &Cx1f; tdt-z
u w &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-KOSOVO-STRATEGY-BOS &LR;      03-25 0760
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-KOSOVO-STRATEGY-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
POLITICAL STRATEGY SHIFTS AS BOMBING CAMPAIGN CONTINUES
</HEADLINE>
  (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By ANNE E. KORNBLUT  
 c.1999 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON _ When airstrikes were only a threat, US officials
talked endlessly of reaching a peace agreement with Yugoslav
President Slobodan Milosevic. But just two days into the bombings,
the stated goal has shifted, and the term ``peace treaty'' seems to
have all but disappeared.
</P>
<P>
   Instead, the mission is being increasingly described in strictly
military terms as a campaign to get Milosevic to stop repressing
his people. What would have originally prevented the bombing _ his
signing a treaty in Rambouillet, France _ is now not enough to end
it unless he decisively stops his campaign in Kosovo.
</P>
<P>
   ``We could go through this whole campaign and still see him not
sign that peace agreement,'' said Representative Tom Allen, a Maine
Democrat on the House National Security Committee.
</P>
<P>
   ``The goal is not to drive him back to the negotiating table,''
said Senator John F. Kerry. ``If you get that, great, that's a
bonus. But there's no guarantee of that. What I do believe we can
achieve _ and what I do believe is rational _ is diminishing his
military capacity.''
</P>
<P>
   One US defense official indicated that the rhetorical shift is
taking place mostly at the top of the political pyramid, where
officials have only recently realized that ``if you set objectives
you can't achieve with military means, you set yourself up for
almost certain failure.''
</P>
<P>
   ``From the military perspective, the objective has always been
to degrade Milosevic's ability to use military force,'' said the
official, who spoke on condition of anonymity. ``Other objectives,
in terms of what Milosevic does, are policy objectives.''
</P>
<P>
   So far, Milosevic has shown no signs of wanting either to sign a
peace treaty or withdraw his troops despite two days of intense
bombing. Thursday &UR;  &LR; night's raids continued to hit the Yugoslav
military's sophisticated air defense system as well as other
military infrastructure targets, defense officials said.
</P>
<P>
   In an attack similar to the one Wednesday night, two B-2
bombers, F-117 Stealth fighters, and F-16 jets swooped in on
targets across Yugoslavia. Cruise missiles again rained onto the
mountains. The chief difference from the first night of the
mission, defense officials said, was that no B-52 bombers _ six of
which helped launch the first round of missiles the night before _
were used.
</P>
<P>
   Although they refused to release details of specific hits,
officials said the strikes had so far been ``successful,'' hitting
components of the air defense system as well as some groupd troops.
</P>
<P>
   But officials conceded that most of the Yugoslavian military's
surface-to-air missile capacity _ one of its best assets _ remained
an unknown quantity. As of early Thursday &UR;  &LR; night, not a single SAM
missile had been spotted by NATO pilots, which meant that either
the missiles had been destroyed in the attacks or were being held
in reserve by the Yugoslavs. Several officials said they believed
the latter was the likelier case.
</P>
<P>
   Another growing concern was reports of increasing attacks on
Albanians by Yugoslav ground troops, which would serve a dual
purpose for the Serbs: eliminating their ethnic enemy and luring
NATO planes closer to the ground, making them an easier target.
</P>
<P>
   It was the military goal, as opposed to the political one, that
took center stage throughout the day, as numerous officials,
including President Clinton, avoided focusing on an eventual peace
treaty and instead urged Milosevic to stand down his forces in
Kosovo.
</P>
<P>
   Their messages were in near unison. NATO Secretary General
Javier Solana said his forces ``are determined to continue until we
have achieved our objective, to hold the violence and to stop a
further humanitarian catastrophe.'' US Defense Secretary William
Cohen said the strikes would stop only when Milosevic chose ``the
path of peace.'' And British Prime Minister Tony Blair said the
Yugoslav president had only to ``stop the repression of the people
of Kosovo.''
</P>
<P>
   NATO should take no other course than that, said defense
specialist John Pike of the Federation of American Scientists.
</P>
<P>
   ``It would be kind of silly for us to agree in advance that all
he has to do is sign a piece of paper and we'll stop,'' Pike said.
This change in NATO rhetoric, Pike said, ``means it's not simply a
question of, if he puts his initials on a piece of paper, that will
put an end to it.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
