<DOCNO> NYT19990325.0387 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-03-25 22:18 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A4499 &Cx1f; taf-z
u a &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-NY-POLICE-INDICT-600(     03-25 0635
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-NY-POLICE-INDICT-600(2TAKES)-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
MORE PROTESTS OVER THE NEW YORK POLICE AS GRAND JURY FINISHES ITS
WORK
</HEADLINE>
   (wg) 
 By JODI WILGOREN   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEW YORK _ As the Bronx grand jury considering last month's
police shooting of Amadou Diallo finished its work Thursday, 219
people calling for justice in the case were arrested for disorderly
conduct in front of police headquarters, and a high-profile group
of black and Hispanic leaders scheduled a meeting to plot strategy
for upcoming meetings with Mayor Rudolph Giuliani.
</P>
<P>
   A lawyer involved in the case said Thursday night that the four
white police officers who killed the West African immigrant in a
hail of 41 bullets had been indicted on charges of second-degree
murder. But the Bronx district attorney's office would not confirm
that the men had been indicted, and lawyers for the four officers
said they had not been informed of any imminent charges against
their clients.
</P>
<P>
   The Rev. Al Sharpton, who has led near-daily demonstrations
since the Feb. 4 shooting, said protests at 1 Police Plaza would
continue until indictments are unsealed, with the Rev. Jesse
Jackson scheduled to be among those arrested on Friday.
</P>
<P>
   ``I plan to be with a coalition of conscience that has come to
protest not only the slaying of Diallo, but in fact a mood of
permissive violence toward people of color,'' Jackson said in an
interview Thursday night. ``The atmosphere is toxic. We are in a
very explosive moment.''
</P>
<P>
   Even before reports of impending indictments filtered out, two
months of activism over the shooting seemed to reach a crescendo on
Thursday, with the largest crowd yet turning Police Plaza into
political theater at lunchtime.
</P>
<P>
   Among the marquee names on the roster of those arrested were the
actress Susan Sarandon and the Rev. Floyd Flake, a former
congressman who has been among Giuliani's strongest black
supporters. And for the first time, off-duty police officers staged
a counter-demonstration to protest what they said was increasing
anti-police sentiment in the city, though they were largely
overshadowed by the boisterous crowd of more than 500 chanting,
among other things, ``Arrest the killer cops.''
</P>
<P>
   As diverse crowds of students, religious leaders and workers on
their lunch breaks began to fill Police Plaza starting at 11 a.m.,
the protesting officers somberly read the names of 100 colleagues
slain in the line of duty since 1977, marking each with the ring of
a small bell. Later, they were mostly quiet as they watched the
theatrics, but when Sharpton passed, they hissed, ``Shame on you.''
</P>
<P>
   James Higgins, a board member of the Patrolmen's Benevolent
Association, organized the vigil. ``While the Diallo death was
certainly a tragedy, there is no excuse for turning it into a
full-scale attack on police officers,'' he said. ``If you're not
engaging in cop-bashing, why are you here?''
</P>
<P>
   The officers said the daily demonstrations had made their jobs
harder. ``As you ride through the streets, you can actually see
people look at you funny,'' said Officer Damian Gilsanen, 29, who
works in Staten Island. ``You know they're wondering, `Are these
guys going to shoot me 41 times?'''
</P>
<P>
   Officer Stephen Burgarella, 33, a 13-year veteran, complained
that the public was ``labeling the whole department for a few
mistakes a couple of officers made.'' Officer James Osborne, 35,
who has also spent 13 years on the force, said, ``There's a lot of
questions people ask you that you don't have answers to.''
</P>
<P>
   Sharpton, ebullient in the success of his daily demonstrations,
invited the officers up to his Harlem headquarters to conduct civil
disobedience. ``I'll even serve them coffee and cake,'' he said.
</P>
<ANNOTATION>
   (STORY CAN END HERE. OPTIONAL MATERIAL FOLLOWS)
</ANNOTATION>
<P>
   nn
</P>
<P>
   Sharpton led four separate groups on Thursday down the aisle
created by blue police sawhorses to the doors of Police
Headquarters, where they lined up quietly before being taken inside
to be handcuffed and sent to local precincts for processing.
</P>
<P>
   The first was a group of Hispanic, Asian and African-American
students, followed by Ms. Sarandon and other members of the Center
for Constitutional Rights, a New York civil liberties group. Flake
and his supporters came next, followed by a group of Episcopalians,
including a priest who had previously been arrested for civil
disobedience protesting apartheid outside the South African
embassy, and Chloe Breyer, the daughter of Justice Stephen G.
Breyer of U.S. Supreme Court.
</P>
<P>
   ``Safety at the expense of civil liberties is unacceptable,''
said Ms. Sarandon, who wore a black turtleneck sweater and
double-breasted leather jacket as she walked to her arrest, singing
``We Shall Overcome'' quietly. ``I'm here to protest racial
profiling and a lot of other issues that have made it unsafe for
people of color in this city.''
</P>
<P>
   Flake said he had spoken to Giuliani two days ago about his plan
to get arrested, and said that he hoped to act as a liaison between
the mayor and Sharpton, who was standing at his side. ``It's not
just Diallo, it is the overall weight of what has happened in the
past,'' Flake said. ``We can't afford to have another case like
this.''
</P>
<P>
   Diallo's mother, Katiadou, said in a telephone interview from
her home in Conakry, Guinea, that she plans to return to New York
next week, when indictments against the four officers are expected
to be unsealed, and expressed gratitude for the daily protests.
</P>
<P>
   ``Why this has touched so many people is because the way this
thing happened,'' she said. ``Never have we heard about such a
crime.''
</P>
<P>
   Lawyers for the four officers involved in the shooting said
Thursday night that they had not been notified of any decision by
the grand jury, but said indictments would not come as a surprise.
All four decided this week not to testify before the grand jury, in
part because they said criminal charges seemed inevitable.
</P>
<P>
   ``I've said all along that there's no doubt in my mind that the
Bronx district attorney, being a political animal, is going to
indict the defendants,'' said Marvyn Kornberg, who represents
Officer Sean Carroll. ``And there's no doubt in my mind that when
the case finally goes to trial that my client will be exonerated.''
</P>
<P>
   As the criminal case moves to a new stage, the political shock
waves caused by the shooting continue, with some of the city's
black and Hispanic leaders discussing how to capitalize on the
sudden open-door policy the Giuliani administration has adopted in
the wake of the intense protests.
</P>
<P>
   According to organizers, the strategy session, scheduled for
Saturday, will include elected officials as well as dozens of
religious, civic and labor leaders. Among those expected to attend
are Sharpton, former Mayor David Dinkins, Rep. Charles Rangel, and
state Comptroller Carl McCall, all of whom have been arrested
during the series of protests at police headquarters.
</P>
<P>
   The group plans to write a list of demands to be presented to
Giuliani, possibly including the establishment of a civilian
commission with subpoena powers to oversee the police department _
a concept the mayor has fought for years _ as well as a requirement
that police officers live in the city, and a greater commitment to
integrating the predominantly white police force, the organizers
said.
</P>
<P>
   In addition, they will either recommend or demand that the mayor
meet with Sharpton, who is considered by some to be the catalyst
for the administration's recent interest in establishing stronger
ties to the city's black and Hispanic officials, but is also
Giuliani's most vociferous antagonist. The mayor has steadfastly
refused to meet with him.
</P>
<P>
   ``He will not choose black leadership or Latino leadership in
this town,'' Sharpton said of the mayor.
</P>
<P>
   Giuliani is scheduled to see McCall Saturday morning, ending the
mayor's four-year pattern of refusing to meet with the state's
highest elected black leader. That follows Giuliani's private
session Wednesday night with Manhattan Borough President Virginia
Fields, another black leader that the mayor had previously shunned.
</P>
<P>
   The mayor's efforts to improve relations with black and Hispanic
political leaders have generated skepticism among some minority
leaders, who note that he had reached out before, in the wake of
the Abner Louima case; that effort was brief and turned rancorous.
</P>
<P>
   His latest approach has also sparked some disagreements among
minority leaders.
</P>
<P>
   For example, Giuliani extended an invitation to meet with a
contingent from the City Council Thursday afternoon to discuss the
Diallo shooting. But some Council members wanted to postpone the
meeting until after Saturday's ``action plan'' summit. The City
Council spokesman Michael Clendenin said he was still trying to
arrange a meeting for Friday, but might have to wait until next
week.
</P>
<P>
   In fact, Saturday's gathering, to be held in midtown Manhattan,
was decided upon after Sharpton and others learned of Giuliani's
meeting with Ms. Fields. Sharpton suggested Thursday that people
wanted to make sure that black leaders who are being ``picked off''
by the mayor for the meetings all voice similar demands.
</P>
<P>
   ``We want to make sure that everybody understands that if they
meet with the mayor, we should all be saying the same thing,''
Sharpton said. He added: ``No one minds if they have a meeting, but
they should all be coming out saying the same thing.''
</P>
<P>
   Thursday night, Ms. Fields defended her decision to meet with
Giuliani. ``This was an important meeting on several levels,'' she
said, adding that ``elected officials have to make their own
decisions.''
</P>
<P>
   In a separate interview, Dinkins said that ``any meeting with
the mayor is meaningless if it doesn't result in his commitment to
do the things that we have all been talking about.''
</P>
<P>
   Giuliani, meanwhile, said Thursday that he had agreed to these
meetings in part because he thinks there is a ``serious difference
here between perception and reality.''
</P>
<P>
   If people are interested in ``informing that perception with
reality,'' he said, then he would meet with them. ``If there isn't,
then there's no point in doing that because all you do is feed the
false perception even more.'' &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
