<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-YELLOWSTONE-MICROBES-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
JUDGE HALTS YELLOWSTONE ROYALTY AGREEMENT WITH BIOTECHNOLOGY
COMPANY 
</HEADLINE>
   (af)  
 By ANDREW POLLACK   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   A federal judge has ordered a temporary halt to a
precedent-setting arrangement under which a biotechnology company
is paying Yellowstone National Park for the rights to search its
geysers and hot springs for commercially valuable microbes.
</P>
<P>
   U.S. District Judge Royce C. Lamberth in Washington, D.C., said
that such a commercial agreement was a ``dramatic change'' in
policy for the National Park Service and required an environmental
impact assessment.
</P>
<P>
   In a decision released on Wednesday, Lamberth ordered the
agreement suspended until the Park Service complied. The decision
is a blow to what the Park Service has hailed as a major new
approach ensuring that the parks and the public benefit from
commercially useful products derived from the natural resources of
the national parks.
</P>
<P>
   In the past, officials said, scientists who took samples of
plants or microbes were free to exploit valuable discoveries
without having to compensate the park.
</P>
<P>
   A microbe discovered in a hot spring in Yellowstone in 1966
yielded a heat-resistant enzyme that was crucial to a technique,
polymerase chain reaction, that enabled scientists to replicate
DNA. The technique is so important in molecular biology that its
inventor won a Nobel Prize and patents related to the enzyme
generate an estimated $100 million a year for the drug company
Hoffmann-LaRoche. Yellowstone received nothing because there was no
requirement for royalties.
</P>
<P>
   But with the recognition that genes of wild plants and animals
can be raw materials for the biotechnology industry, countries have
begun demanding compensation for what is called ``bioprospecting.''
Many environmentalists think that such payments, by putting a value
on wildlife, can provide an incentive for the preservation of
biological diversity.
</P>
<P>
   Under the Park Service's first bioprospecting agreement, Diversa
Corp. of San Diego is paying Yellowstone $100,000 over five years
plus royalties ranging from 0.5 percent to 10 percent on any
commercially useful discovery. The money is to go to preservation
of the park's resources and for public education.
</P>
<P>
   Yellowstone has talked to as many as 18 other parties about such
agreements, and other national parks are exploring them as well.
But any new agreements are likely to be delayed by Lamberth's
decision.
</P>
<P>
   The agreement with Diversa was challenged in court by some small
environmental groups, which argued that the agreement should have
been open to public comment and an environmental impact statement
prepared. The groups also argued that the National Park Service did
not have the authority to enter into an agreement commercializing
the resources of the national parks.
</P>
<P>
   ``This isn't somebody doing a master's thesis,'' said Mike
Bader, executive director of the Alliance for the Wild Rockies, one
of the groups that filed the suit. ``This is big business.''
</P>
<P>
   ``What we're talking about is a modern-day Gold Rush,'' Bader
added, saying that too much bioprospecting would threaten the
park's environment. But with the court decision, he said, ``The
scheme will now undergo the close scrutiny it deserves.''
</P>
<P>
   Lamberth agreed that an environmental assessment was needed.
</P>
<P>
   ``Essentially, the future of bioprospecting on federal lands in
the United States appears to be a work in progress,'' Lamberth
wrote, ``but the government as of yet has not engaged in any public
debate on the issue nor made any definitive policy statement
through regulations or less formal means.''
</P>
<P>
   The judge has not ruled on whether the Park Service has the
authority to enter such an agreement, but he rejected the
government's effort to have many of the claims dismissed. Others
filing the suit were the Edmonds Institute of Edmonds, Wash., and
the International Center for Technology Assessment in Washington,
D.C., both non-profit organizations dealing with biotechnology
ethics, and Phil Knight, a guide who lives near Yellowstone.
</P>
<P>
   David Barna, a Park Service spokesman, said the agency would not
appeal the decision and would begin the environmental assessment.
He said the process could take six months, or perhaps a lot longer,
depending on whether a complete environmental impact statement or
only a simpler assessment was needed.
</P>
<P>
   He said the Park Service did not think that environmental
assessments would be needed for the hundreds of research permits
granted for purely academic work.
</P>
<P>
   Mike Finley, the superintendent of Yellowstone, said in a
statement, ``Research permits have been issued to study Yellowstone
resources for decades, with no harm to the park and great benefit
to science.''
</P>
<P>
   Finley said that action limiting agreements like the one with
Diversa ``only deprives the park of money that would be used to
protect park resources.''
</P>
<P>
   Diversa declined to comment, saying it had not seen the
decision. The company, which was not named as a party in the suit,
specializes in searching in extreme climates for natural enzymes
that could be used in industrial processes.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
