<SLUG> BC-LIBYA-LOCKERBIE-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
LIBYA WILL TURN OVER SUSPECTS IN THE LOCKERBIE BOMBING, U.N. TOLD  
(DW)
</HEADLINE>
   c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   UNITED NATIONS _ Prince Bandar bin Sultan, the Saudi ambassador
to Washington, expressed confidence Thursday that Libya would honor
its pledge to turn over by April 6 the two suspects wanted in the
1988 bombing of Pan Am Flight 103 over Lockerbie, Scotland.
</P>
<P>
   ``The details of the agreement are being worked out,'' Bandar
told reporters following a meeting with Secretary General Kofi
Annan and the five permanent representatives on the Security
Council. ``Everybody's on the same wavelength.''
</P>
<P>
   Bandar, who traveled to Libya seven times to persuade the Libyan
leader, Col. Moammar Gadhafi, to turn over the suspects for trial
before a Scottish court in the Netherlands, said the agreement he
helped negotiate would ``kill two birds with one stone'' _ justice
would be served when the two men accused of the bombing were
brought to trial before an independent court; and the deal would
help alleviate the suffering that economic sanctions have imposed
on the Libyan people.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's a win-win situation for everyone,'' the prince said.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
