<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-EDIT-KOSOVO-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
EDITORIAL: AIMS OF AN AIR WAR IN KOSOVO 
</HEADLINE>
  (See also: KOSOVO-RDP, KOSOVO-MILITARY, KOSOVO-MILITARY-ASSESS,
KOSOVO-GERMANY, KOSOVO-POLICY, KOSOVO-BELGRADE, KOSOVO-PRISTINA,
KOSOVO-MACEDONIA, KOSOVO-REPORTERS, KOSOVO-CHINA,
KOSOVO-RUSSIA-ASSESS, KOSOVO-CLINTON, KOSOVO-ITALY, KOSOVO-VOICES,
KOSOVO-B2, KOSOVO-EUROPE-REAX, KOSOVO-U.N., KOSOVO-CLARK-PROFILE.) 
 (bl)  
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   The New York Times said in an editorial for Friday, March 26:
</P>
<P>
   As NATO air raids on Yugoslavia moved into a second night, both
sides seemed to be settling in for a long campaign. President
Clinton and other NATO leaders say they are prepared to continue
the attacks until Yugoslav President Slobodan Milosevic accepts the
international peace plan for Kosovo. Milosevic says he will do no
such thing.
</P>
<P>
   But even if he continues to reject a diplomatic solution,
Milosevic's military ability to repress Kosovo's ethnic Albanian
majority is likely to be steadily eroded. NATO's commanding
general, Wesley Clark, pledged Thursday ``to systematically attack,
disrupt, degrade, devastate and ultimately . . . destroy'' Yugoslav
military forces unless Milosevic accepts and carries out the Kosovo
peace plan. Clark has the air power and the authority to make good
on that threat, and Yugoslavia should take it seriously.
</P>
<P>
   Dishearteningly, the Serbian public has initially rallied to
Milosevic, as have traditional allies like Russia. The Yugoslav
leader seems determined to carry out further repression in Kosovo
while he still has the military strength to do so.
</P>
<P>
   In America, most of Congress and the general public warily
support continued bombing, but strongly oppose more risky steps
like the introduction of NATO combat troops. That defines the right
policy for now. Conventional wisdom holds that air power alone
cannot bring Belgrade to the bargaining table. But it may well be
able to ease Yugoslav military pressure on Kosovo.
</P>
<P>
   To achieve that goal, NATO must move quickly to destroy
Yugoslavia's remaining anti-aircraft defenses and then move on to
Yugoslav tanks and troops in Kosovo. The risk of casualties among
NATO pilots will increase as cruise missiles and stealth fighters
and bombers are now joined by more vulnerable aircraft. Yugoslav
military casualties are certain to inrease as well.
</P>
<P>
   Milosevic could avoid these dangers by yielding now. The
reasonable terms of the international peace plan are still
available to him. By proceeding and risking the destruction of his
armed forces, he could create a situation where Albanian guerrillas
feel emboldened to push for full independence, rather than the
autonomy that they are now willing to accept.
</P>
<P>
   But such a show of statesmanship would be out of character for
the Yugoslav dictator. NATO must plan instead for sustained air and
missile attacks.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-03-25-99 2222EST &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> NYT19990325.0392 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-03-25 22:23 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A4505 &Cx1f; taf-z
u a &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-PARADE-CATHOLICS-NYT &LR;      03-25 0785
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-PARADE-CATHOLICS-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
STREET THEATER TROUPE IRKS SAN FRANCISCO CATHOLICS 
</HEADLINE>
   (bl)  
 By BILL STAGGS   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   SAN FRANCISCO _ The Sisters of Perpetual Indulgence, an
irreverent and largely gay street theater group whose members dress
like nuns and use elements of Roman Catholic ritual in their
performances, have angered Catholics here with plans for an Easter
street party to celebrate the troupe's 20th anniversary.
</P>
<P>
   The bawdy group, which was started on Easter weekend in 1979 by
four gay men from Iowa, has long been a fixture here, taking part
in gay pride parades, holding parties and contributing to
charitable causes. The troupe includes 30 gay, lesbian, bisexual
and transgender people who call themselves nuns and use such names
as Sister Phyllis Stein and Sister Reyna Terror.
</P>
<P>
   As their celebrations have grown in popularity, drawing
thousands of onlookers, they have also come under growing scrutiny
from some Catholics, unhappy about such theatrics as the troupe's
``Condom Saviour Mass'' and ritual exorcisms.
</P>
<P>
   Two weeks ago, an editorial in the San Francisco Archdiocese's
official newspaper, Catholic San Francisco, criticized the city's
Board of Supervisors for allowing one block on Castro Street, the
heart of San Francisco's gay district, to be closed for the Easter
performance.
</P>
<P>
   The paper's editor and spokesman, Maurice Healy, called the
board's decision ``extraordinary insensitivity to people of all
faiths,'' and asked that the performance be scheduled on a day
other than Easter.
</P>
<P>
   One performer, who gave her name only as Sister Ann R. Key, said
Thursday that the attacks on the troupe and its street party were
mean-spirited and missed the point.
</P>
<P>
   ``We do not mock nuns,'' she said. ``We are not drag queens. We
are nuns, and that is an important distinction. The work we do is
the same as Catholic sisters do. We educate, we minister to the
sick.''
</P>
<P>
   The players do volunteer work in hospices and help people with
AIDS.
</P>
<P>
   Urged on by the editorial, readers of the newspaper have been
contacting members of the Board of Supervisors to complain.
</P>
<P>
   In a board meeting Monday, Supervisors Alicia Becerril and Amos
Brown asked that the Easter celebration be delayed until April 11.
</P>
<P>
   But Board President Tom Ammiano said Tuesday that the decision
would stand because rescinding it would require a unanimous vote,
which he asserted was ``all but impossible.''
</P>
<P>
   ``Asking for a change in the date of the celebration sidesteps
the real issue here, that of the separation of church and state,''
Ammiano said. ``The board's vote is not an endorsement of the
sisters. It's an endorsement of the process that allows the sisters
or any group to apply for a permit and be granted due process. The
fact that the actions of one group are not popular with another
group is no reason to deny anyone their rights.''
</P>
<P>
   Ammiano, who is gay, called the editorial ``over the top,'' and
added: ``The archdiocese has been on something of a jihad against
gays and lesbians anyway. The archdiocese has been against the
city's domestic partners legislation for years, as far back as
1988. I feel that this is all homophobic.''
</P>
<P>
   Brown, who is also the pastor of the Third Baptist Church here,
said Tuesday that he would not have voted for the permit if he had
known more about the group.
</P>
<P>
   ``They may have a right to do what they want to do,'' he said,
``but the celebration. while well-intentioned, has caused a lot of
friction in the Catholic community, particularly on this most
important day in Christendom.''
</P>
<P>
   Kandace Bender, the spokeswoman for Mayor Willie Brown, said he
was asking that all parties show mutual respect.
</P>
<P>
   William Donohue, president of the Catholic League for Religious
and Civil Rights, a lay organization based in New York, said it
would place an advertisement in The San Francisco Chronicle asking
Catholic groups not to do business with the city unless the street
party was moved to another date.
</P>
<P>
   ``This is not just a bunch of gay guys dressed up as nuns in
some sort of `Saturday Night Live,''' Donohue said of the
performers. ``Their attacks on holy communion and the eucharist
demonstrate that we're dealing with an invidious, vicious
anti-Catholic group that does some good things like throwing money
at charities. I don't give a damn about their fund-raising. They're
a bunch of bigots.''
</P>
<P>
   Sister Ann R. Key said no offense to real nuns was intended and
defended the use of what she called twists on rituals.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's sometimes crazy stuff that we do, but there's meaning
behind it,'' she added. ``We integrate sacred elements of organized
religion in a lighthearted way.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
