<SLUG> BC-BBA-ANGELS-NOTES-LADN </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
HOLLINS MAKES PUSH FOR THIRD-BASE JOB
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By JOE HAAKENSON  
 San Gabriel Valley Tribune  
<TEXT>
<P>
   MARYVALE, Ariz. _ Manager Terry Collins, general manager Bill
Bavasi and the Angels coaches met late Wednesday night to discuss
the club's options as camp nears an end. There were many
disagreements, and quite possibly none more debated than the third
base job.
</P>
<P>
   Troy Glaus, 22, has done everything possible to win the job.
He's hitting .439 (18 for 41) with two homers and a team-leading 17
RBI. But Dave Hollins, 32, is finally healthy, his sore left
hamstring apparently better and his surgically repaired right
shoulder no longer an issue.
</P>
<P>
   Hollins will make $2.4 million this season, but Collins said
salary won't play into the decision. What matters, Collins said, is
how Hollins plays now that he's healthy.
</P>
<P>
   Thursday afternoon against the Milwaukee Brewers at Maryvale
Baseball Park, Hollins hit two home runs (one from each side of the
plate), walked, stole a base, hit a sacrifice fly, scored three
runs and drove in six in the Angels' 11-4 victory.
</P>
<P>
   On defense, Hollins made four plays without an error.
</P>
<P>
   ``It don't count; it starts at zero opening day,'' Hollins said,
before being reminded that it does count because he's competing for
a job. ``I'm happy right now. I was coming off shoulder surgery,
then I pull a hammy halfway through camp. My thing is I know what I
have to do to get ready. If I'm not healthy, I'm not going to help
you.''
</P>
<P>
   ``I know one thing _ he got everybody's attention today,''
Collins said. ``He's making a statement that he's not dead. There's
a lot of baseball left in Dave Hollins. We knew that going in.
</P>
<P>
   ``He's a veteran. He came into camp thinking if he's healthy
he's the third baseman.''
</P>
<P>
   Hollins, who is hitting .321 (9 for 28) with two homers and
seven RBI, added that he doesn't concern himself with what Glaus is
doing.
</P>
<P>
   ``That's the only way I know how to play _ get ready and do my
job,'' he said. ``I can't do anything about the other guy, or
guys.''
</P>
<P>
   Angels starter Omar Olivares gave up three runs and eight hits
in five innings against the Brewers to get his second spring
victory. He came out after his shoulder stiffened up, but Collins
said it was nothing serious.
</P>
<P>
   The Angels optioned left-handed pitchers Jarrod Washburn and
Scott Schoeneweis to triple-A Edmondton on Thursday. Washburn, who
began camp in competition for the No. 5 spot in the starting
rotation, was 0-0 with a 7.82 ERA in six spring games.
</P>
<P>
   Schoeneweis, 11-8 at triple-A Vancouver last season, was 1-1
with a 4.26 ERA in five spring games.
</P>
<P>
   Pitcher Jason Dickson underwent arthroscopic surgery to repair a
torn labrum in his right shoulder Thursday. He will be out a
minimum of three to four months.
</P>
<P>
   The Angels have lost two Freeway Series games against the
Dodgers, who will play the New York Yankees on April 3 and 4. The
Angels get a Mexican League team and Cal State Fullerton instead.
</P>
<P>
   The Angels are trying to attract as many fans as possible
knowing that most in Southern California would rather see the
Dodgers and Yankees at Dodger Stadium.
</P>
<P>
   So before Saturday's game against the Aguascalientes
Railroadmen, WBC welterweight boxing champion Oscar De La Hoya will
throw out the first pitch. In Sunday's game, actor Kevin Costner
will play for Fullerton against the Angels. Sunday's game is free
of charge.
</P>
<P>
   Costner, 44, is a 1978 graduate of Cal State Fullerton.
</P>
<P>
   The Angels return home to Tempe today to play the San Diego
Padres at 12:05. Chuck Finley will start for Anaheim against San
Diego's Matt Clement. Singer Garth Brooks, playing with the Padres
all spring, is expected to play today.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
