</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-ART-NOTES-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
SHORT ITEMS ON THE ART WORLD 
</HEADLINE>
   (af)  
 By CAROL VOGEL   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEW YORK _ The Solomon R. Guggenheim's SoHo branch, whose
closing in January was rumored to be permanent, will reopen _ 7,000
square feet smaller _ on May 12. Most of the ground floor occupied
by the museum at 575 Broadway, at the corner of Prince Street, will
soon become a Prada store, the Italian retailer's third in SoHo.
</P>
<P>
   The Guggenheim SoHo's opening show _ an exhibition of 60
paintings from Andy Warhol's late ``Last Supper'' series _ is about
as fashionable as art can get. The works come from the collections
of Heiner Friedrich and Peter Brant.
</P>
<P>
   Friedrich is a Manhattan dealer who was one of the founders of
the Dia Center for the Arts. Brant is a collector who has sold
major portions of his collection recently _ works by Robert
Rauschenberg, Jackson Pollock and Jasper Johns. He also happens to
be the Guggenheim SoHo's landlord. He owns 575 Broadway.
</P>
<P>
   ``We understand that their intention is to make these works
available to the public, and we're comfortable with that,'' said
Judy Cox, a deputy director at the Guggenheim. ``We have been
assured the paintings are not for sale.''
</P>
<P>
   Friedrich bought the Warhols from the Andy Warhol Foundation for
the Visual Arts, which is the sole beneficiary of the artist's
estate. He then sold some of them to Brant with an understanding
that the two men would give each other right of first refusal if
one wanted to sell any portion of the collection.
</P>
<P>
   ``We wanted to find an institution that would take them
long-term and we wanted them to stay together,'' Brant said. ``If
the show is successful, they'll stay there.''
</P>
<P>
   Guggenheim officials say the Warhols are on long-term loan and
they have set no formal closing date for the show, saying only that
it will be sometime in the fall.
</P>
<P>
   Two of the monumental ``Last Supper'' paintings were included in
a show at the Dia Center for the Arts in Chelsea in the 1994-1995
season. The entire collection was later on view in Munich.
Friedrich also rented a Chelsea gallery space owned by Dia to show
some of the ``Last Supper'' paintings privately. ``This will be the
first time they will have been shown as a group in New York,''
Brant said.
</P>
<P>
   The ``Last Supper'' series represents Warhol's reflections on
Leonardo da Vinci's ``Last Supper'' (1495-97), and the works are
based more on reproductions of the famous image than the image
itself. Working from photographs, drawings and plastic models, the
artist created variations on the scene, which depicts Jesus
surrounded by his disciples.
</P>
<P>
   Lisa Dennison, a deputy director at the Guggenheim and its chief
curator, said the museum had been rethinking its SoHo museum and
wanted more of the exhibitions there to be long-term and drawn from
the museum's permanent collection. ``We're deeply committed to late
Warhols,'' Ms. Dennison said.
</P>
<P>
   Would the museum like Friedrich and Brant to donate the
paintings? ``Yes,'' Ms. Dennison said. ``That's our hope.''
</P>
<P>
   What will happen in the fall, when the Warhols are taken down?
``We'll probably do something else from the permanent collection,''
Ms. Dennison said. She suggested that after the exhibition, the
Warhol works ``will be tied to the identity of the museum.''
</P>
<P>
   By that time, the Guggenheim may well have firm plans for
another site in Manhattan, and it could include a special gallery
for the ``Last Supper'' series. The museum hopes to build a huge
new museum designed by Frank Gehry, the California architect
responsible for the Guggenheim in Bilbao, Spain.
</P>
<P>
   One site in which the Guggenheim is interested is Pier 40, a
15-acre site owned by New York state along the Hudson River off
Houston Street. The museum is also looking at other sites, one of
which is thought to be on three piers near the South Street
Seaport.
</P>
<P>
   The Economic Development Corp. of New York City called for
proposals for building on the piers; Bernadette O'Leary, a
spokeswoman for the agency, declined to say who responded.
</P>
<P>
   ``We have been in discussions with the city about a variety of
sites along the waterfront,'' Ms. Cox said. ``We haven't ruled out
any potential sites. We're working with the city to determine what
would be the best possible location for a museum.''
</P>
<P>
   Boston Debut, in Japan  &QL;
</P>
<P>
   In the making for more than seven years, the Nagoya/Boston
Museum of Fine Arts is finally scheduled to open on April 17 in
Japan. It will be the first museum in Japan to provide an
encyclopedic view of art from all cultures and time periods.
</P>
<P>
   In much the same way that the Guggenheim persuaded officials in
the Basque region of Spain to pay for its Bilbao branch, the Museum
of Fine Arts has won financing from Nagoya's Foundation for the
Arts, its city government and the Aichi Prefecture.
</P>
<P>
   The project has faced delays compounded by economic shakiness in
Japan and political battles within the foundation. It was
originally supposed to have opened three years ago.
</P>
<P>
   Over the next 20 years, $50 million will be given to the Boston
museum for operations, capital expenses, special projects and its
endowment. In exchange the Nagoya museum will receive a 20-year
commitment for loans from the Museum of Fine Arts collection.
(Boston received the first $5 million when a letter of intent was
signed in 1991, and used it to pay off bonds.)
</P>
<P>
   The new museum will present two shows a year from Boston as well
as one five-year loan exhibition. The opening exhibitions include
``Monet, Renoir and the Impressionist Landscape'' (April 17 through
Sept. 26) and ``Art of the Ancient Mediterranean World'' (April 17
through March 2004).
</P>
<P>
   The new museum has about 15,000 square feet of exhibition space
on three floors and will also have a shop, lecture room, library,
offices and storage. It will be operated by the foundation under
the direction of Tadao Ogura, who was previously the director of
the Kyoto National Museum of Modern Art.
</P>
<P>
   The Boston museum has a long history of collaborations with
Japanese institutions. It has been collecting Japanese art since
the 1890s and has been sending shows to different parts of Japan
for 15 years.
</P>
<P>
   Changes in St. Louis &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Brent Benjamin, the deputy director for curatorial affairs at
the Museum of Fine Arts in Boston for the last five years, has been
named director of the St. Louis Art Museum. On May 1 he replaces
James Burke, who is retiring after 19 years in the director's post.
</P>
<P>
   Benjamin takes over just as the museum is undergoing a
transformation. Over the next 10 years it plans a capital campaign
to make its structure in Forest Park earthquake-safe and add a new
building of gallery space.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
