<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-KOSOVO-REPORTERS-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
AMERICAN JOURNALISTS ARE HARASSED BY SERB AUTHORITIES 
</HEADLINE>
  (See also: KOSOVO-RDP, KOSOVO-MILITARY, KOSOVO-MILITARY-ASSESS,
KOSOVO-GERMANY, KOSOVO-POLICY, KOSOVO-BELGRADE, KOSOVO-PRISTINA,
KOSOVO-MACEDONIA, KOSOVO-REPORTERS, KOSOVO-CHINA,
KOSOVO-RUSSIA-ASSESS, KOSOVO-CLINTON, KOSOVO-ITALY, KOSOVO-VOICES,
KOSOVO-B2, KOSOVO-EUROPE-REAX, KOSOVO-U.N.) 
(bl) 
 By LAWRIE MIFFLIN   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   Within hours of secretly transmitting fluorescent green
``nightscope'' camera images of the first NATO air strikes on
Kosovo on Wednesday night, CNN correspondent Brent Sadler and his
three crew members heard their hotel room door being broken down at
3 a.m. In came a man brandishing a rifle and a flashlight.
</P>
<P>
   ``I thought it was curtains,'' Sadler said Thursday by telephone
from Skopje, Macedonia, where he and about 50 other Western
journalists fled after the Serbian government ordered all members
of the press from NATO countries to leave.
</P>
<P>
   That intruder and another an hour later merely ripped out wires
and rummaged through files. But the next morning, as Sadler and his
crew began to load their armored car to leave, a gang of six or
seven armed men accosted them, slapping a CNN producer, Alessio
Vinci, across the face and poking a Kalashnikov rifle under
Sadler's nose. The assailants then began smashing the crew's
equipment and set it and the car on fire as crowds of Serbian
passersby cheered, and frightened fellow journalists watched from
the lobby.
</P>
<P>
   Sadler said police officers and Yugoslav army soldiers restored
order and escorted a caravan of about 15 armored cars carrying
Western journalists from Pristina to the Macedonian border.
</P>
<P>
   While the atmosphere in Pristina, the capital of Kosovo
province, was reportedly more tense than elsewhere in the country,
other journalists also faced harassment. In Belgrade, two
Americans, Mark Phillips of CBS News and Peter Finn of the
Washington Post, were taken from their rooms at the Hyatt Hotel in
the middle of the night, held at a police station for 11 hours,
then driven to the Croatian border and released.
</P>
<P>
   An expulsion order issued by Serbian Information Minister
Alexander Vucic said: ``Journalists of foreign public media from
the countries that took part or allowed their territories to be
used in NATO aggression on our country will be expelled.''
</P>
<P>
   But there were reports of conflicts within the Yugoslav
government about whether to enforce the order, with some officials
arguing that showing the impact of the air strikes would create
sympathy for the nation.
</P>
<P>
   While most journalists left Yugoslavia on Thursday, NBC News
said that its two correspondents, Jim Maceda and Ron Allen, and
their crews had decided to stay in Belgrade.
</P>
<P>
   Phillips of CBS News had no choice. By telephone from Zagreb on
Thursday, he said he had heard a knock on his door around 3:30 a.m.
and had peered through the peephole to see a hotel clerk, who said,
in English, ``Room service.''
</P>
<P>
   ``I said `I didn't order room service,' and a gruff voice next
to the clerk said, `State security police _ open up,' '' Phillips
said. Told to pack, he asked where he was going and was told, ``No
questions; this is war.''
</P>
<P>
   In the hotel lobby, while the officers went upstairs to get
Finn, Phillips said he managed to get a message to his producer in
another room, before being taken to a local police station. There,
Phillips said, he and Finn were questioned separately.
</P>
<P>
   ``They asked what I had written, whom I had spoken to, and they
asked who we were working with in terms of local people,
translators and such, which was very worrying,'' Phillips said. ``I
danced a very awkward line, saying I only knew the guy's first
name, he'd been hired by someone else in our group _ giving them
enough to keep them from getting angrier, but at the same time not
incriminating anyone.''
</P>
<P>
   But, he said, the three ``inquisitors'' got ``angrier and
angrier,'' and one said to Phillips: ``Why is it that someone like
me who loves American rock music and wears jeans and Nikes feels so
furious at the U.S. for this barbarous and uncivilized act?''
</P>
<P>
   At that moment, air raid sirens sounded, Phillips said, and he
thought, ``I'm toast.'' But after about 11 hours at the police
station, he said, they were put into a Serbian militia vehicle with
barred windows and driven to the border.
</P>
<P>
   Because Phillips' producer had gotten word to London about his
detainment, a CBS News employee was dispatched from Zagreb to the
border crossing, and met the three journalists there about 20
minutes after they were released, he said.
</P>
</TEXT>
