<DATE_TIME> 1999-03-25 22:52 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A4523 &Cx1f; taf-z
u a &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-SIERRA-CLUB-DISPUTE-N     03-25 0448
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-SIERRA-CLUB-DISPUTE-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
STATE SIERRA CLUB IS THREATENING TO TAKE OVER NEW YORK CITY
CHAPTER  
(DW)
</HEADLINE>
   By JOHN H. CUSHMAN Jr.   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEW YORK _ The Sierra Club's New York state chapter is
threatening to suspend its New York City group in a dispute over
the local group's political and financial independence, according
to leaders of the environmental organization.
</P>
<P>
   The schism between state and local leaders of one of the
nation's most influential environmental lobbying groups reflects
deep divisions over issues including political endorsements,
revenue sharing and fund raising. The leadership of the city group,
for example, is interested in creating a Hudson River park on the
West Side of Manhattan, while the state organization, called the
Atlantic chapter, is more interested in issues like land
conservation upstate.
</P>
<P>
   The board of governors of the 34,000-member Atlantic chapter is
scheduled to vote Saturday on whether to take control of the
12,000-member city group and its finances and oust its leadership.
The board's executive committee approved the action last Saturday,
with the approval of the club's national headquarters.
</P>
<P>
   The state chapter's leaders are upset because for the second
year in a row the New York City group mailed a fund-raising letter
to its members after the state chapter's board of governors voted
to forbid it. The club's rules limit fund-raising activities in
order to prevent a competition for funds among the club's local
chapters and groups.
</P>
<P>
   The Sierra Club is unusual among major environmental groups
because its leaders are elected annually by the entire membership.
</P>
<P>
   When the statewide chapter endorsed Gov. George Pataki's bond
referendum to pay for environmental programs, the New York City
group went its own way, publishing criticism of the spending
priorities in its newsletter.
</P>
<P>
   ``They can't make an environmental decision without checking
with the chapter, as we can't make an environmental decision
without checking with the national club,'' said Rhea Jezer, the
chairwoman of the Atlantic chapter.
</P>
<P>
   When it comes to fund-raising, she said, ``The national club
does not want us penny-anteing everybody. They don't want every
chapter sending out requests for money when they are sending theirs
out.''
</P>
<P>
   Chapters, however, are allowed to solicit money from their
members during March, and the New York City group decided that it
was entitled to do the same thing, said Moishe Blechman, its
chairwoman.
</P>
<P>
   ``We told them in no uncertain terms not to do it,'' Ms. Jezer
said of the mailing. ``But being a New Yorker myself, I know the
mentality _ they knew better.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-03-25-99 2252EST &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> NYT19990325.0402 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-03-25 22:52 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A4524 &Cx1f; tic-z
r s &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-BKC-FINAL4-BICKLEY-AZ     03-25 0728
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BKC-FINAL4-BICKLEY-AZR </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
HE'S THE DIFFERENCE  
 SPARTANS OWE SEASON'S SUCCESS TO GUARD CLEAVES 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by N.Y. Times News Service clients)  
 By DAN BICKLEY  
 c.1999 The Arizona Republic  
<TEXT>
<P>
   TAMPA, FLA. - Sorry, but Jason Terry isn't the guy. An
eye-popping season, no doubt, and never has a toothpick carried so
much weight without snapping. But the Pac-10 has been exposed and
Arizona has long departed, unable to grasp a tournament victory or
anything else worth engraving.
</P>
<P>
   To select Elton Brand is like glorifying one string of Jimi
Hendrix's guitar, completely ignoring that Duke is good enough to
win an NCAA championship and escape the NBA lottery.
</P>
<P>
   And while a wonderful talent, Wally Szczerbiak only passes the
ball with implicit instructions: That it's returned to sender
within seconds, if not sooner.
</P>
<P>
   No, the Player of the Year is a guy who will clang shots off the
rim until it matters, a guy whose game has been scrutinized,
criticized, dissected like a lab frog. The guy who has simply
willed the other school in Michigan to a place it hasn't been in 20
years.
</P>
<P>
   Mateen Cleaves isn't pretty. He doesn't play over the rim or
drop 30-point bombs when Dick Vitale is sitting at the scorer's
table. He is destined for a nice career in the Continental
Basketball Association.
</P>
<P>
   But if you're looking for steely substance, this is your guy.
The 90s version of a consummate point guard, complete with tattoos
honoring his mother and his hometown. A guy who can dominate
without raw statistics, from a generation weaned on numbers.
</P>
<P>
   Sorry, there is no Magic surrounding this bunch from Michigan
State. Just a leader who defers to everyone else until it's time to
win, and a basketball team that usually does.
</P>
<P>
   ``There aren't many point guards like Mateen Cleaves,'' Duke
Coach Mike Krzyzewski said.
</P>
<P>
   Michigan State arrives at the Final Four with little celebration
and even less chance at derailing Duke. They are a nice story, a
team that overthrew their rivals in Ann Arbor and disrupted the
balance of power in the Big Ten.
</P>
<P>
   They are led by a coach, Tom Izzo, who practically begged Jud
Heathcote for an assistant's job worth $7,200 a year. After a pit
stop at Tulsa, Izzo waited eight years for the big dog to retire.
And now he breaks down film with 49ers Coach Steve Mariucci.
</P>
<P>
   The Spartans also arrive with a few grease smudges. They are
frowned upon for a lack of aesthetics, for clutching and grabbing,
for incorporating a football mentality into a game of grace. Before
the advent of style points and SportsCenter, a blue-collar team
such as this might've been championed.
</P>
<P>
   The Spartans are nobody's darling, but this much is certain:
They will not be intimidated by Duke, and their fearlessness stems
from one guy.
</P>
<P>
   Cleaves hit last-second, game-winning shots at Minnesota and
Penn State, and did the same against Northwestern in the conference
tournament. He led the Spartans to 15-1 record in the nation's
toughest conference, a team that has lost once in the past 30
games. He personally foiled Mississippi's upset bid in the final
five minutes of a second-round battle in Milwaukee. And, by now,
you know what he did against Kentucky.
</P>
<P>
   He is tough, physical, strong. A former high school quarterback.
An All-American content to take eight shots a game. A point guard
who believes in putting his teammates first. Owner of a back-alley
jumpshot, yet when it's time for heroes, somehow ugly finds the
bottom of the net.
</P>
<P>
   Cleaves isn't without baggage. On a recruiting trip to Michigan
three years ago, he was involved in a roll-over car accident with a
few Wolverines players. Last year, he was arrested for carrying
open alcohol in a car. And this season, after a 4-3 start, he
landed on the grill for his lack of production.
</P>
<P>
   But on the 20th anniversary of the 1979 championship team, Magic
Johnson pulled aside Cleaves. A few pointed words from the most
famous Spartan to ever wear shorts, and the rest is on the resume.
</P>
<P>
   He is not the best college basketball player in the country, but
no one had a better year. No one had the game or his teammates on a
string like this guy. And before his season ends Saturday, there
should be one more triumph.
</P>
<P>
   Mateen Cleaves, puppet master, player of the year. &QL; 
Dan Bickley can be reached at 602-444-8253 or at
dan.bickley(at)pni.com. &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
