<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-NY-MALPRACTICE-SUIT-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
SUIT AGAINST DOCTOR ALLOWED OVER REFERRAL TO A SPECIALIST 
</HEADLINE>
   (af)  
 By ALAN FINDER   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEW YORK _ In a decision that could make it easier for patients
to bring malpractice suits against doctors in managed-care
programs, New York state's highest court ruled Thursday that the
widow of a man who died of a heart attack could sue her husband's
primary-care doctor for failing to refer him quickly enough to a
heart specialist.
</P>
<P>
   The court of appeals, in a unanimous decision, did not determine
whether the primary-care physician was actually guilty of
malpractice, leaving that to be decided by a jury in state supreme
court in the Bronx.
</P>
<P>
   The court of appeals did rule, however, that a federal law that
had often blocked consumers from suing managed-care providers did
not pre-empt the widow from suing her husband's doctor.
</P>
<P>
   The lawsuit was brought by Susan Nealy, whose husband, Glenn,
died in 1992. Nealy, who was 37, was diagnosed with coronary
disease and had an angioplasty in March 1992. Not long after the
procedure, Nealy's employer, Photocircuits Corp., replaced its
health insurance company with three HMOs. Nealy enrolled in one of
the HMOs, U.S. Healthcare, paying a premium so he could also go to
doctors outside the plan.
</P>
<P>
   Nealy's participation in the HMO went into effect on April 1.
His widow said that he tried to see Dr. Ralph Yung, the Bronx
doctor whom he selected as his primary-care physician in the HMO,
on April 2 and April 3 because of chest pains. But Nealy was turned
away each time because of disagreements over whether he was
properly enrolled, Mrs. Nealy said.
</P>
<P>
   Nealy was examined by Yung on April 10 and asked to return three
days later for more tests, according to the court of appeals
decision. Yung told Nealy during one and perhaps both of these
visits that he should see a cardiologist.
</P>
<P>
   Nealy asked to be referred to the cardiologist who treated him
previously, Dr. Stephen Green, who was not in the HMO. Yung agreed
to submit a request to U.S. Healthcare to approve a referral to
Green and to waive a co-payment that Nealy would ordinarily have to
pay. But Yung did not submit the form to the HMO until about a week
later, the court of appeals said.
</P>
<P>
   The HMO turned down the request about two weeks later,
suggesting that Nealy see one of the plan's cardiologists. He
agreed, obtained a referral on May 18 and made an appointment for
the following day. But Nealy died later on May 18 of a massive
heart attack.
</P>
<P>
   Mrs. Nealy sued Yung, U.S. Healthcare and two subsidiaries,
among others, for malpractice and breach of contract in state
supreme court in the Bronx. All but Yung were removed from the case
in federal court, on the ground that federal law pre-empted a
patient from suing a managed-care company for administrative acts.
Because Yung did not seek action by the federal court, the case
against him remained in the state courts.
</P>
<P>
   For more than two decades, insurance companies, health
maintenance organizations and doctors involved in managed care have
been largely protected from malpractice lawsuits because of the
federal law, the Employee Retirement Income Security Act.
</P>
<P>
   The law says that its provisions cannot be superseded by state
laws since they involve employee benefit plans. State and federal
courts had often interpreted this to mean that patients and their
relatives could not sue for malpractice.
</P>
<P>
   ``It is clear that Congress did not intend to pre-empt claims
such as those now before us,'' Chief Judge Judith Kaye wrote in the
decision.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
