<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-OPEN-PHX-AZR </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
CROWD SIZE WON'T BE LIM ITED AT PHOENIX OPEN
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by N.Y. Times News Service clients)  
 By BILL HUFFMAN  
 c.1999 The Arizona Republic  
<TEXT>
<P>
   Phoenix Open organizers will not limit the crowd size, but they
will attempt to better control the behav ior of fans once they get
to the course.
</P>
<P>
   The Phoenix Thunderbirds said Thursday that daily tickets priced
at $20 will remain a fixture of the Phoenix Open. The decision was
made after the Thunderbirds and the PGA Tour worked out a strategy
for handling crowds and security for next year's tournament.
</P>
<P>
   In the wake of an incident at this year's Phoenix Open, in which
an armed man scuffled with police, there was speculation that the
tour nament would switch to a more expensive, weeklong badge in
order to cut down on the largest galleries in professional golf.
</P>
<P>
   Tournament chairmen say the PGA Tour didn't direct them to
significantly reduce future crowds at the TPC of Scottsdale or to
change the atmosphere of golf's most free-spirited tournament. The
Thun derbirds and PGA Tour Commis sioner Tim Finchem reached those
conclusions during meetings the past two days at the PLAYERS
Championship in Ponte Vedra Beach, Fla.
</P>
<P>
   ``The most important thing that came out of our meetings is that
the tour has asked us to take the lead on establishing crowd size
and security at the Phoenix Open,'' said Steve Matteucci, chairman
of the 2000 Open. ``There is no mandate from the tour that we
reduce the size of the crowds, only an emphasis on how our fans
behave once they get to the course, specifically their alcohol
consumption and decorum.
</P>
<P>
   ``As far as daily tickets go, they are very much alive. Anyone
will be able to walk up to the front gate next year and purchase a
daily ticket.''
</P>
<P>
   Finchem was attending the PLAYERS Championship and was
unavailable for comment.
</P>
<P>
   Matteucci and Artigue acknowl edged that the Thunderbirds had
been reeling from the flak created from an article in The Arizona
Republic that said the PGA Tour had called for sweeping changes in
the tournament.
</P>
<P>
   Perhaps the most controversial involved modeling the Phoenix
Open after the GTE Byron Nelson Classic in Dallas, which caps
crowds at 250,000 for the week by offering only a limited number of
$150 badges. The Byron Nelson also confines alcohol consumption to
specific areas.
</P>
<P>
   Artigue said the Thunderbirds made it clear that limiting crowds
by eliminating daily badges wasn't an option.
</P>
<P>
   ``Apparently that was just one (tour) staff member's idea on how
to rectify what happened this year,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   On Jan. 31, the final day of the Open, Brian K. Murphy of
Phoenix was arrested for being intoxicated and scuffling with a
Scottsdale police officer. The incident made national news because
Murphy was carrying a concealed .380-caliber semiautomatic pistol
while follow ing a group that included golf icon Tiger Woods.
Subsequent fears ex pressed by Woods and other players put the onus
on the PGA Tour to bring changes.
</P>
<P>
   During a PGA Tour policy board meeting March 2 in Miami, the
Phoenix Open was the No. 1 topic of conversation. One unidentified
tour official told the policy board that ``something has to be done
about Phoenix.'' Three days later, the Thunderbirds announced a
task force to study crowd and security issues, as well as the
alcohol question.
</P>
<P>
   ``The final word from the task force on all of these issues
still will come on June 1, just as we planned,'' Matteucci said.
``At the moment, we're still gathering ideas.''
</P>
<P>
   Matteucci said fans will notice that the biggest changes at next
year's tournament will involve alco hol, although he stopped short
of saying that such beverages will be confined to certain areas of
the course. Precedence was set at this year's Open when the
Thunderbirds banned alcohol sales around the notorious 16th tee,
where fans tend to get louder and crazier as the day wears on.
</P>
<P>
   Banning sales around the 16th ``was met with limited success, as
a lot of those fans just brought (alcohol) in with them,''
Matteucci said.
</P>
<P>
   ``That won't happen next year, and if someone has had, or is
about to have, too much to drink, we'll cut them off and ask them
to leave,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   ``We'll adopt some other meas ures to refine that, but at the
moment, I'm just not ready to say what they'll be because we're
still looking into them.''
</P>
<P>
   To that end, Artigue said, several Thunderbirds plan to visit
the Byron Nelson in mid-May to see how the sponsoring Salesmanship
Club of Dallas deals with its galleries.
</P>
<P>
   ``We don't want to make (the Phoenix Open) a fortress, because
we want our fans to enjoy the tournament as they always have,''
Artigue said. ``At the same time, we will adopt some measures to
refine the way we do things out there.''
</P>
<P>
   Matteucci added that security will increase significantly for
next year's tournament, ``although at this point, I'm not sure by
how much.''
</P>
<P>
   Artigue and Matteucci agreed that the record crowds that once
roamed the TPC of Scottsdale are a thing of the past.
</P>
<P>
   ``This is not about being knocked off the hill or even being
king of the hill,'' said Artigue, noting that this year's
attendance of 422,650 fans was down 10 percent from a year ago.
</P>
<P>
   ``Actually, if the crowd shrinks a little bit again, that's not
a negative, it's a positive. We're not trying to set attendance
records, and even if we only draw 350,000 to 400,000 fans, we'll
still be the largest tournament in professional golf. I don't think
that crown will ever be wrestled away from us.''
</P>
<P>
   Artigue and Matteucci both said that crowds probably will be
even smaller next year because some of the ``freebies'' _ daily
tickets that are doled out by the thousands to corporate entities
and consignment brokers _ will be reduced or possibly eliminated.
Artigue illus trated that point by noting that skybox patrons get
100 daily tickets for each of the seven days of the tournament,
while corporate and presenting sponsors receive thou sands of daily
allotments.
</P>
<P>
   ``I think the PGA Tour under stands the uniqueness of our tourna
ment based on the size of it,'' Artigue said. ``We're still working
together with them, and (the PGA Tour) will have some input on the
changes that we come up with.
</P>
<P>
   ``But the reins of this stagecoach are now in the hands of the
Thunderbirds.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
