<SLUG> BC-PATAKI-BUDGET-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
IMPASSE ON NEW YORK STATE BUDGET WORSENS AS PATAKI THREATENS
VETOES
</HEADLINE>
   (rk) 
 By RICHARD PEREZ-PENA   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   ALBANY, N.Y. _ The state's budget impasse worsened Thursday as
Gov. George Pataki declared the Assembly and Senate proposals
unacceptable, threatening a repeat of last year's sweeping vetoes
unless the Legislature drastically scales back its spending plans.
</P>
<P>
   With the April 1 start of a new fiscal year a week away, the
three sides are so thoroughly stalemated that none claims to know
the next move. The Senate and Assembly were long since supposed to
have begun meeting in conference committees to hash out their
differences, but they have not, and the leader of each house is
blaming the other.
</P>
<P>
   ``The Assembly spending plan is just much, much too high, and
unacceptable,'' Pataki said Thursday in a news conference called to
make his first extensive comments on the Legislature's work toward
a budget. ``Even the Senate, in my view, spends at a rate that
creates very real problems in the years 2000, 2001, 2002 and
beyond.''
</P>
<P>
   ``I'm just saying very plainly that I will not accept a budget
that drives huge out-year expenditures and that threatens to undo
the progress that we've made over the last four years,'' he said,
seated in the ornate corner room of the Capitol that was Franklin
D. Roosevelt's office. ``I think everybody knows that if the level
of spending is unacceptable, then I will veto.''
</P>
<P>
   After two years in which he increased spending steeply, the
Republican governor has made a firm commitment to restraining
spending in the next fiscal year, proposing a 1.8 percent increase,
to $72.66 billion, despite the state's $2 billion surplus.
</P>
<P>
   The Senate's Republican majority wants to raise spending by at
least 2.7 percent, while the Assembly's Democratic majority has
proposed an increase that it puts at 4.6 percent but that the
governor's office says is closer to 8 percent.
</P>
<P>
   The governor's statement appeared to dash the hopes of Joseph
Bruno, the Senate majority leader, that his plan had struck a
balance that could win over the Assembly speaker, Sheldon Silver, a
Democrat, while staying within bounds that were acceptable to
Pataki.
</P>
<P>
   Bruno, clearly taken aback by Pataki's comments, said, ``I'm
very conscious of next year and the year after, and we're trying to
be responsible, we're trying to be prudent.''
</P>
<P>
   The state appears headed for a repeat of 1994 through 1997, when
bitter, highly partisan clashes led to the four latest budgets in
state history. The 1996 budget, approved 104 days late, and the
1997 one, 126 days overdue, were believed by independent
researchers to be the two tardiest state budgets in American
history.
</P>
<P>
   A protracted fight would carry a new twist this year because,
under a salary increase law enacted in December, legislators'
salaries will be withheld as long as there is no budget.
</P>
<P>
   Until 1997, the governor and legislative leaders negotiated the
budget in secret meetings. Last year, the Senate and Assembly, in a
bid to make the process more public and involve more legislators,
met in conference committees to negotiate a budget publicly with
little direct input from the governor.
</P>
<P>
   Pataki lauded the process, then vetoed more than 1,000 line
items, well over $1 billion in spending, most of it in Democrats'
pet projects. The vetoes stunned lawmakers of both parties, and
they continue to roughen his already abrasive relations with the
Legislature.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-03-25-99 2257EST &QL; 
</TRAILER>
