<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-03-25 23:00 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A4530 &Cx1f; taf-z
u s &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-BKW-FINAL-FOUR-NYT &LR;      03-25 0782
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BKW-FINAL-FOUR-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
SUDDENLY, WOMEN'S FIELD IS FULL OF INTRIGUE 
</HEADLINE>
  (jt) 
 By BILL PENNINGTON    
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   SAN JOSE, Calif. _ Tennessee is gone, its Final Four challenge
having become a frantic quest to pawn $50,000 worth of hotel rooms
and tickets to the Final Four games that the school and its
boosters no longer need.
</P>
<P>
   But on the scene are four teams itching to lead a new order in
the NCAA's women's basketball tournament. As Louisiana Tech's Leon
Barmore, the only coach left in the field who has won this
tournament, said Thursday: ``I've never been to a Final Four like
this, where nobody knows who's going to win. There's not much
difference between the four teams. Purdue is ranked No. 1 and
Georgia is a great team and we're playing our best and Duke is so
high they could probably take on the NBA and beat them. These girls
are tying their shoes real tight and saying, `I'm going to whip
you.'''
</P>
<P>
   It is also a field with a web of unusual, and in some cases,
interlocking, story lines, from a tough-love coach to a lame-duck
coach, from loyal twin sisters to feelings of disloyalty caused by
a firing.
</P>
<P>
   Duke (28-6) plays Georgia (27-6) in the first game Friday night
at the San Jose Arena, and then Purdue (32-1) faces Louisiana Tech
(30-2). As parity infiltrates women's college basketball, nothing
else seems guaranteed.
</P>
<P>
   ``It proves there are more than one or two teams to watch in our
game,'' Purdue coach Carolyn Peck said.
</P>
<P>
   Fresh off its upset of Tennessee in Monday's East Regional
final, Duke swept into the Bay Area Thursday.
</P>
<P>
   Two Duke players also provide the most intriguing subplot to the
tournament. Duke's star center, Michele VanGorp, and guard Nicole
Erickson each transferred from Purdue to Duke in 1997 because Lin
Dunn, the coach who brought them to Purdue two years earlier, had
been abruptly fired.
</P>
<P>
   ``What they did was wrong, and there was no reason for it,''
VanGorp said after Duke's practice Thursday. ``And when I asked for
a reason, I got odd-ball answers from the school. They never
explained anything to anybody.
</P>
<P>
   ``I knew I wanted to leave Purdue, and Nicole and I wanted to go
together. I don't ever regret it.''
</P>
<P>
   Dunn was the winningest coach in Purdue's history and her
departure was extremely controversial. University officials never
went into detail about her exit, which sparked lawsuits that ended
with Dunn accepting a $100,000 settlement.
</P>
<P>
   Should Duke and Purdue advance to Sunday night's championship,
VanGorp said she would not be more motivated to defeat her former
school. But she added, ``They still haven't had the decency to
personally tell me why my coach was fired.''
</P>
<P>
   Meanwhile, the Louisiana Tech senior forward Monica Maxwell has
her own history with the Purdue program. Coming out of Central High
School in East Chicago, Maxwell narrowed her choices to Purdue and
Louisiana Tech.
</P>
<P>
   She called a news conference to announce her decision but did
not know that she would pick rural Ruston, La., until moments
before she faced reporters. She knows many of the current Purdue
players, but said coolly, ``When I play Purdue Friday, I'm not
going out there to rekindle any friendships.''
</P>
<P>
   Purdue and Louisiana Tech have their own history. Purdue
defeated Louisiana Tech by 71-65 in December. Louisiana Tech
eliminated Purdue in a regional final in last year's NCAA
tournament.
</P>
<P>
   Maxwell has led the charge in the last two months for Louisiana
Tech, which has won its last 22 games. Early in the season, Maxwell
scored only 19 points in six games, but her play improved after a
Barmore scolding.
</P>
<P>
   ``He calls it tough love,'' Maxwell said. ``It's definitely
tough.''
</P>
<P>
   In Purdue, Louisiana Tech faces a team that hasn't lost since
Nov. 22, when Stanford edged the Boilermakers by 1 point. Guards
Stephanie White-McCarty and Ukari Figgs make up what most consider
the best backcourt in women's college basketball. And they have
kept their composure in difficult circumstances, weathering a
season of questions about Peck, who is leaving Purdue to join the
Orlando franchise of the Women's National Basketball Association
later this year.
</P>
<P>
   At Georgia, the twins Kelly and Coco Miller are the double image
that can't be double-teamed. Kelly has had the better tournament so
far. She was the Mideast Regional most valuable player after
averaging 27.5 points, 7 rebounds and 6.5 assists in four games.
</P>
<P>
   The Millers have always played on the same team and let
recruiters know they came as a package. Georgia coach Andy Landers
had no problem with that, since the Millers are the third set of
twins he has coached. ``I've gotten numb to it,'' Landers said.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
