<DATE_TIME> 1999-03-25 23:07 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A4599 &Cx1f; taf-z
u a &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-CT-WILTON-SUICIDE-NYT     03-25 0713
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-CT-WILTON-SUICIDE-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
A PERFECT GUY DOUSES HIMSELF WITH GASOLINE AND STRIKES A MATCH .
 WHY?  
(DW)
</HEADLINE>
   By PAUL ZIELBAUER   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   WILTON, Conn. _ To everyone in this small, affluent town, Sam
Hingston was just about the finest young man they had ever seen: a
courteous A student at Wilton High School, a captain on the
football and wrestling teams, and as handsome as any 17-year-old
kid on television.
</P>
<P>
   ``He was, like, the perfect guy,'' said Allison Dymnicki, 16, a
junior who passed Hingston in the hallways each day. So there was
no explaining why, shortly before 3 a.m. Wednesday, Hingston gulped
down a shot of gasoline from an old Gatorade bottle, doused himself
with fuel and struck a match, setting his body ablaze in the locked
bathroom of his family home. Before his parents could get to him
and extinguish the flames, most of Hingston's body had been
scorched by third-degree burns. Paramedics airlifted him to the
Westchester County Medical Center in Valhalla, N.Y., but the burns
were too severe. He died that evening.
</P>
<P>
   The news spread almost instantaneously through Wilton, a town of
20,000 shrouded by wooded hills, a place Connecticut magazine
ranked as the third-best small town in the state last year. ``We're
all trying to grapple with: `Why a young death? Why a suicide?'''
said Deborah Low, Wilton High's principal. ``He didn't give any
signs. If you had a list of people least likely to have this happen
to, he would be on the list.''
</P>
<P>
   To his parents, Margie and Richard Hingston, Sam was something
of a boy wonder with a promising future. After the family moved to
Wilton from Woodstown, N.J., in April, Hingston established himself
as an outstanding student athlete at Wilton High. Classmates
described him as charming and friendly in class and a warrior on
the football field, where he was a starting linebacker, and on the
wrestling mat, where he earned a 14-1 record and a regional
championship last year at 160 pounds. Next fall, Hingston was
planning to attend Boston College, his family said. His twin
sister, Sarah, also a senior at Wilton High, plans to attend the
University of Delaware.
</P>
<P>
   Hingston had been complaining of headaches for a few weeks, said
his grandmother Dorothy Czulewicz. But it did not seem serious, she
said. Tuesday evening had started and ended just like any other
night inside the warmly decorated Hingston home.
</P>
<P>
   ``He had dinner with us at the table,'' Mrs. Czulewicz, who
lives in the family's four-bedroom house, said Thursday as she
tended to a table filled with photos of her grandson. ``We watched
`Jeopardy!' together.''
</P>
<P>
   Everyone went to bed around 11 p.m. Tuesday, she said; Hingston
had a cold compress on his head to relieve another headache.
Sometime before 3 a.m., though, he padded into the garage, filled
the Gatorade bottle with gasoline from a gas can and locked himself
in the bathroom with a book of matches.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's incomprehensible,'' said David Clune, superintendent of
the Wilton School District. ``He had everything _ looks, brains,
friendships.''
</P>
<P>
   Hingston's death hit many of his classmates hard. ``People go
through the stairwells and don't say a word,'' said Theresa
Dalessandro, 16, a junior. ``You can actually hear footsteps, which
is strange.''
</P>
<P>
   Thursday morning, Hingston's French teacher broke down in class
and sobbed, students said.
</P>
<P>
   Crisis counselors took turns speaking to groups of the school's
930 students in the school library.
</P>
<P>
   ``They told us the Sam we knew wasn't the Sam that did this to
himself,'' said Jackie Sherman, 16, who knew Hingston from her
American history class.
</P>
<P>
   Hingston's body will be cremated Friday; a funeral service is
scheduled for 11 a.m. Saturday at Our Lady of Fatima Roman Catholic
Church, two miles from Wilton High. The family agreed to donate
some of Hingston's organs for transplant, his grandmother said.
</P>
<P>
   Wilton police do not plan to investigate Hingston's death.
Residents say that no matter how long they think about it, they are
not sure they will ever understand what was going through Sam
Hingston's young mind in that locked bathroom.
</P>
<P>
   ``The only person that really knows,'' said Capt. Ronald
Beliveau of the Wilton police, ``is the person that's dead.''
</P>
</TEXT>
