<HEADER>
A4656 &Cx1f; taf-z
u e &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-AT-THE-MOVIES-2TAKES-     03-25 0805
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-AT-THE-MOVIES-2TAKES-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
FROM GODS TO A QUEEN 
</HEADLINE>
   (af)  
 By BERNARD WEINRAUB   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   HOLLYWOOD _ Bill Condon successfully tackled a provocative
subject when he adapted and directed ``Gods and Monsters,'' a
fictionalized account of the last days of the filmmaker James
Whale, creator of the Frankenstein movies.
</P>
<P>
   On Sunday Condon won an Academy Award day for best adapted
screenplay. But his first studio film, which he hopes to begin
shooting later this year, may be even more provocative, especially
for New Yorkers. He is undertaking the life story of Bess Myerson.
The movie is tentatively called ``Queen of the Jews.''
</P>
<P>
   ``Her life is amazing,'' Condon said. ``She was the first Jewish
Miss America, and was named that moments after people were exposed
for the first time to the images of the concentration camps. She
was one of those women famous for being famous. In the '70s she
reinvented herself as a city official ... And then came scandal.''
</P>
<P>
   Ms. Myerson was charged with trying to bribe a New York state
judge who was handling her lover's divorce. She and two
co-defendants were acquitted on Dec. 22, 1988.
</P>
<P>
   ``She's actually one of the most complex characters I've ever
come across,'' Condon said.
</P>
<P>
   The script was written by John Hoffman, a New York playwright,
and studios executives are already interested. Condon has not yet
approached actresses, but his targets include Meryl Streep,
Sigourney Weaver and Glenn Close, and possibly even Jane Fonda, who
has been in retirement in recent years.
</P>
<P>
   Condon, who attended Regis High School in Manhattan and later
majored in philosophy at Columbia University, said he had not met
Ms. Myerson. ``She once said, `I'm like an onion: You peel and peel
and can't get to the middle of it,''' Condon said. ``It's an
extraordinary story.''
</P>
<P>
   Condon may have been the most stunned person at the Academy
Awards when his name was announced as the winner for the best
adapted screenplay. He has struggled for years in Hollywood as a
screenwriter and journalist and is unaccustomed to the hoopla that
is now around him.
</P>
<P>
   The other day he boarded a flight to London to attend the
opening there of ``Gods and Monsters.'' He said he hoped there
would be a telephone on the plane.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'm leaving the country with 150 unanswered phone calls,'' he
said.  &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Graduating to Producer &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   ``There are very few good scripts around,'' said Dustin Hoffman.
``By definition leading roles are written mostly for people in
their 30s and 40s, not people like me. So you become a friend of
who the movie is about, or you carry a gun in those action things,
which I won't do.''
</P>
<P>
   Hoffman, who is 61, was explaining his decision to produce the
first film in which he is not appearing. (His company, Punch
Productions, was a producer of ``Tootsie'' and ``Rain Man,'' in
which he starred.) The new film, ``A Walk on the Moon,'' to be
released on Friday, is a drama, set in the summer of 1969, about a
family vacationing in the Catskills and the restlessness of the
mother, played by Diane Lane, who feels that life is passing her
by.
</P>
<P>
   The cast includes Liev Schreiber as her husband, Anna Paquin as
her adolescent daughter and Viggo Mortensen as a hippie who seduces
her.
</P>
<P>
   Hoffman said he had been tracking the script, by Pamela Gray,
for a while and even thought of directing it until he heard that
the actor Tony Goldwyn had already signed on to make the movie.
</P>
<P>
   ``We talked on the phone, and I said, `Please let us produce
it,''' Hoffman said. ``It didn't take long before we realized that
we saw the film in the same way.''
</P>
<P>
   Hoffman was attracted to the writing as well as to the
underlying theme of a middle-class family in the grip of personal
upheaval.
</P>
<P>
   ``The main issue is timeless,'' he said. ``In the same ways that
it's hard to make marriages work, it's also hard to make families
work. Especially in a year like 1969, when you had Woodstock, the
Apollo mission, the war in Vietnam.''
</P>
<P>
   Hoffman has a reputation as a meticulous, some say obsessed,
perfectionist who has had his share of run-ins with directors. He
decided early on not to be too intrusive and not to go to the set.
The film was made on a tight budget of $8 million in the Laurentian
Mountains north of Montreal where the resort scene is remarkably
similar to the Catskills.
</P>
<P>
   ``He didn't need me there; the actors didn't need me there,''
Hoffman said. ``I've been around producers 30 years, and usually
what a producer does is tell you what you can't do. I didn't want
to be that kind of producer. I don't like the idea of hovering.''
</P>
<P>
   But Hoffman said he received videotapes every day of the scenes
being made and spoke to Goldwyn each evening. He added that he was
stunned from the first day he began viewing the scenes.
</P>
<P>
   nn
</P>
<P>
   ``I called Tony and said, `Look at the work you're getting from
the actors,''' Hoffman said. He gave the novice 38-year-old
director one bit of advice: Keep the camera rolling sometimes even
before and after a scene technically starts and ends. ``Some of the
best stuff happens when the camera is on and the actors don't know
it,'' Hoffman said.
</P>
<P>
   Goldwyn said that whatever nervousness he first had about
working with Hoffman vanished overnight.
</P>
<P>
   ``He said, `It's your movie, you do your thing,''' Goldwyn said.
``He'd give exhaustive notes. We talked for hours. But he kept
saying, `It's your decision.' What more could I have asked for than
to have an artist of Dustin's caliber and creative instincts who
did everything to help the creative process and gave me freedom to
do what I wanted.'' &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Those Mortal Fools &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   The triumph of ``Shakespeare in Love'' as best picture at the
Academy Awards is viewed by Michael Hoffman as an especially good
omen.
</P>
<P>
   Hoffman, director of ``One Fine Day,'' ``Restoration'' and
``Soap Dish,'' has been consumed for the last year in filming ``A
Midsummer Night's Dream,'' Shakespeare's most magical comedy.
</P>
<P>
   He gathered an all-star cast, including Michelle Pfeiffer as
Titania and Rupert Everett (Oberon), Calista Flockhart (Helena),
Kevin Kline, Sophie Marceau (Hippolyta) and Stanley Tucci (Puck).
The movie was shot in northern Italy and is set to be released on
May 7.
</P>
<P>
   ``In broad strokes, `Shakespeare in Love' will certainly help
us,'' said Hoffman, 43, who lives in Boise, Idaho. ``That film made
people close to Shakespeare in a very clever way.''
</P>
<P>
   He continued: ``The more you read biographies of Shakespeare,
the more distant you feel from Shakespeare the poet. But in
`Shakespeare in Love,' by essentially falsifying all the
biographical data and recasting Shakespeare as one of the
characters in his plays, you open up a way for audiences to feel
connected to the genius of Shakespeare, which was his ability to
create characters.''
</P>
<P>
   The director became involved with the project in 1995 when he
had a conversation with Kline, a friend.
</P>
<P>
   ``I was in the never-ending post-production of `Restoration,'
and he was doing `Fierce Creatures,' the sequel to `A Fish Called
Wanda,' and neither one of us was at our happiest,'' Hoffman said.
``We were commiserating and looking for solace, and we began
talking about Shakespeare and how much we loved those plays.''
</P>
<P>
   Hoffman's involvement with `A Midsummer Night's Dream' really
began more than two decades ago when he was among the students from
Boise State University who began the Idaho Shakespeare Festival,
which is still flourishing. In the first production, ``A Midsummer
Night's Dream,'' Hoffman played Lysander.
</P>
<P>
   Several years later, while studying Renaissance Drama as a
Rhodes Scholar at Oxford University, he directed a version of the
play, which led to film work.
</P>
<P>
   Hoffman said that for him ``A Midsummer Night's Dream'' was
Shakespeare's loveliest and most poetic play. Shakespeare set his
story in an English version of ancient Greece, but the movie is set
in Tuscany around 1900. The play itself deals with love, in all of
its comical and fantastical forms.
</P>
<P>
   ``I became very intrigued by the way all these characters seem
to be balancing the desire for love with the desire for dignity,
the desire to maintain their pride and the degree to which each
character is willing to sacrifice or compromise their dignity to
have love,'' said Hoffman, who also adapted the play for the
screen.
</P>
<P>
   He said he proposed the idea for the movie to Fox Searchlight, a
division of 20th Century Fox that releases artier films. After
reading the adaptation, studio executives quickly agreed to make
the movie for about $13.5 million, a relatively small amount for a
film with such high-profile names.
</P>
<P>
   The actors worked for only three weeks or so and hardly took
their usual salaries to appear in the film.
</P>
<P>
   There have been at least six film versions of ``A Midsummer
Night's Dream,'' including one with an 11-year-old Mickey Rooney
playing Puck, and an animated one in 1965 with Magoo as Puck. The
character of Puck, the fairy trickster, was, at least initially,
the central image in Hoffman's mind.
</P>
<P>
   ``At the beginning I just had an image of fat little Puck riding
in the Tuscan countryside on the back of a turtle,'' he said.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
