<SLUG> BC-RAC-MODESTI-COLUMN-LADN </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
TIMBER'S STANDING STILL PRIME
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By KEVIN MODESTI  
 c.1999 Los Angeles Daily News  
<TEXT>
<P>
   ARCADIA _ A few things have changed since we ranked the Kentucky
Derby contenders for the first time in February.
</P>
<P>
   Then-undefeated Exploit has been not only defeated but retired
with a knee injury. Florida's Three Ring has become the fourth
filly to merit consideration this year. Del Mar Futurity winner
Worldly Manner, out of sight and virtually out of mind while
training in Dubai, has restored his reputation by winning a fast
``trial race.''
</P>
<P>
   One thing hasn't changed.
</P>
<P>
   Prime Timber remains No. 1 in our book.
</P>
<P>
   Here's an updated top 10 heading into the last round of preps
for the May 1 Kentucky Derby _ Saturday's Gallery Furniture.com
Stakes at Turfway Park, the April 3 Santa Anita Derby, and the
April 10 Blue Grass at Keeneland and Arkansas Derby at Oaklawn.
</P>
<P>
   1. Prime Timber: He'll be ridden again by David Flores when he
heads a three-horse team for trainer Bob Baffert in the Santa Anita
Derby. Baffert is also aiming General Challenge (Chris McCarron)
and Finder's Gold (to be determined) for the race. Prime Timber
threw off Exploit _ whom we ranked No. 2 at the time _ and a
reputation for cutting it close when he won the San Felipe Stakes
by two lengths.
</P>
<P>
   2. Vicar: He cuts it close but keeps winning _ the Fountain of
Youth by a neck, the Florida Derby by a nose. Next: Blue Grass.
</P>
<P>
   3. Wondertross: Everybody's wise-guy pick in the Florida Derby
ran second despite some trouble. It wouldn't be a Kentucky Derby
without trainer Nick Zito. Next: Blue Grass.
</P>
<P>
   4. Cat Thief: It wouldn't be a Santa Anita Derby without trainer
D. Wayne Lukas, but his only good 3-year-old will stay back east
for the Blue Grass, leaving Lukas without a starter here for the
first time since 1978.
</P>
<P>
   5. Worldly Manner: If it's legitimate, his reported track-record
1:46.59 clocking in winning a 1[-mile trial in Dubai makes the
``Arab horse'' a factor, despite his handlers' unorthodox approach.
</P>
<P>
   6. Three Ring: After dominating her division in Florida, she's
only the second filly to sign up for the Derby since Winning
Colors' 1988 victory.
</P>
<P>
   7. Straight Man: Two flashy victories give owners Bob and
Beverly Lewis (Exploit) new hope. Next: the Gallery Furniture race,
for which he drew post 1, helpful to a front-runner.
</P>
<P>
   8. Excellent Meeting: Still Baffert's top filly after narrow
Santa Anita Oaks win.
</P>
<P>
   9. Desert Hero: Two for two going into Santa Anita Derby with
new trainer Richard Mandella, and facing same obstacle as Straight
Man: lack of experience.
</P>
<P>
   10. General Challenge: Fifth in the Louisiana Derby, he then
worked in a sizzling :57 3/5 at Santa Anita after blinkers were put
on.
</P>
<P>
   Hello, Dubai: Fans at Santa Anita will be able to bet on
Sunday's $5 million Dubai World Cup throughout Saturday's card.
Windows will reopen at 7:15 a.m. Sunday. The race will be shown at
8:15 a.m.
</P>
<P>
   Silver Charm and jockey Gary Stevens drew post 3 and were made
2-1 favorites to repeat their 1998 victory in the 1\-mile race.
Victory Gallop and Jerry Bailey got post 4 and 5-2 odds. Malek and
Alex Solis got post 7 and 12-1.
</P>
<P>
   The top non-U.S. horse _ one of four Dubai-trained runners in
the field of eight _ is '98 Epsom Derby winner High Rise. He and
Frankie Dettori drew post 1 and are 11-4 third choices.
</P>
<P>
   Jock switch: Everybody who predicted Stevens would replace Kent
Desormeaux aboard 1998 Kentucky Derby and Preakness winner Real
Quiet is right, but much later than expected and for the wrong
reason.
</P>
<P>
   Baffert said Stevens will ride Real Quiet in the April 3 Oaklawn
Handicap in Arkansas, but not because of any failing by Desormeaux,
real or imagined. It's just that Desormeaux had already committed
to ride Honest Lady for trainer Bobby Frankel in the Santa Anita
Derby the same day.
</P>
<P>
   As long as Stevens will be in Arkansas, he'll also take over
from Desormeaux aboard Excellent Meeting in the April 2 Fantasy
Stakes for 3-year-old fillies.
</P>
<P>
   Back-markers: After The Blood-Horse magazine named the century's
top 100 thoroughbreds, Bill Finley of the New York Daily News
spoofed the whole exercise by naming the 10 worst.
</P>
<P>
   No. 1 was Bum, who finished last in all three starts, beaten a
combined 105 lengths, before being retired in 1989. Others on the
Finley list: Zippy Chippy, 0 for 85 when Finger Lakes banned him;
Ricks Natural Star, the not-so-great pretender of the '96 Breeders'
Cup; Glue Pot, earner of $0 in the '50s, and Snaafi Dancer, the
$10.2 million yearling who never raced.
</P>
<P>
   It's amazing how really bad names go with really bad horses, or
at least the ones we remember.
</P>
<P>
   The voice: Michael Wrona is coming back to Hollywood Park, and
this time he'll stay like a mother-in-law.
</P>
<P>
   The witty Australian was a popular choice to call the races in
Inglewood beginning April 23, replacing Luke Kruytbosch, who left
for Churchill Downs. Wrona, 33, worked at Hollywood for three weeks
in the fall of 1991, and has been at Golden Gate Fields for seven
years.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'm ecstatic to be coming full circle after almost a decade,''
said Wrona, who'll spend the Hollywood offseason at Turf Paradise
in Phoenix.
</P>
<P>
   Wrona is distinguished by his creativity, which gave us his
oft-quoted call of a victory by a front-runner with unproven
stamina: ``Will he stay? He'll stay like a mother-in-law!'' &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-03-25-99 2312EST &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
