<DOCNO> NYT19990325.0412 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-03-25 23:17 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A4661 &Cx1f; taf-z
u s &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-BKN-NETS-NYT &LR;      03-25 0469
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BKN-NETS-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
NETS SIMPLY CAN'T SHOOT STRAIGHT 
</HEADLINE>
  (rk) 
 By RON DICKER   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   Among the New Jersey Nets' problems in their 5-21 season is
their awful shooting, which has mushroomed from a slump to a trend
to a lifestyle.
</P>
<P>
   Excuses about the short training period no longer apply. Every
other team in the NBA has faced the same condition, and not one has
a worse shooting percentage than New Jersey's 38 percent heading
into Friday night's game against Indiana at Continental Arena.
</P>
<P>
   With a few more games like Wednesday night's 32 percent shooting
in a loss against Detroit, the Nets (5-21) will have the Milwaukee
Hawks standing a little taller in their history. The 1954-55 Hawks
own the league's worst team shooting percentage at 36 percent.
</P>
<P>
   Not surprisingly, the Nets' misses are adding up to one of the
worst offenses in league history. Their 86 points a game and the
Bulls' 84.1 would be second and first for the fewest points in
league history, with those same Milwaukee Hawks holding the season
record at 87.4.
</P>
<P>
   Kerry Kittles and Kendall Gill, the Nets' perimeter shooters,
are at 35 and 37 percent, respectively. Keith Van Horn's 20.2
scoring average cannot mask his 42 percent accuracy.
</P>
<P>
   Different Nets have different solutions to their shooting
problems.
</P>
<P>
   Van Horn said the answer is practice, so he was one of three
starters _ Kittles and Jayson Williams were the others _ to show up
for an optional workout Thursday at Champion Center in East
Rutherford, N.J.
</P>
<P>
   Kittles said of the shooting slump: ``The main thing is to stay
aggressive and work through it.''
</P>
<P>
   Coach Don Casey believes intensified defense would help create
easy baskets off a turnover or in transition.
</P>
<P>
   ``We need a breakout,'' Casey said. ``And with the teams we're
playing _ Indiana and Cleveland _ certainly defensively, we're
going to have to make our own breakout. So if we don't get to the
foul line, if we don't take it to the hole, then the misery will
continue.''
</P>
<P>
   Stephon Marbury, who has shot 43 percent in seven games with New
Jersey, said part of the problem is hesitancy. ``I'm penetrating
and I'm kicking out, but they're not shooting,'' he said about his
teammates.
</P>
<P>
   Casey agreed, saying that slumping players often pass up a good
shot for a sure shot, which often does not come.
</P>
<P>
   Williams said the team hopes nightly for a player with a hot
hand, but that player has rarely materialized. Van Horn said good
shooting can be just as contagious as bad shooting.
</P>
<P>
   While the Nets' shooting problems show no sign of abating, Casey
has adopted the philosophy of Indiana's Larry Bird, against whom he
will be coaching Friday night.
</P>
<P>
   ``You shot till you miss or you shoot till you make,'' Casey
said. ``So we're shooting until we make.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
