<SLUG> BC-FBC-USC-LADN </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
BIG QUESTIONS FACE USC DEFENSE
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By SCOTT WOLF  
 c.1999 Los Angeles Daily News  
<TEXT>
<P>
   LOS ANGELES _ As USC begins spring practice today, coach Paul
Hackett envisions a completely different team than just three
months ago, when the Trojans ended their season at the Sun Bowl.
</P>
<P>
   ``The outlook is we have flip-flopped this team in terms of the
offense now has experience and the defense does not have
experience,'' Hackett said. ``It's the opposite of a year ago. I am
extremely concerned about the defense.''
</P>
<P>
   Linebacker and Butkus Award winner Chris Claiborne is noticeably
gone, but several other key starters, including Rashard Cook, Marc
Matock, Daylon McCutcheon and Grant Pearsall, will need to be
replaced on defense.
</P>
<P>
   ``We have a lot of young guys that have to come on and have
great springs,'' Hackett said. ``That is a huge priority for us.''
</P>
<P>
   On offense, there are far fewer questions, especially now that
wide receiver R. Jay Soward has returned from his self-imposed
exile from the program.
</P>
<P>
   ``Offensively, the expectation level ought to be considerably
better than last year,'' Hackett said.
</P>
<P>
   Although quarterback Carson Palmer started five games last
season, Hackett said his main objective in spring practice will be
to keep the offense as uncomplicated as possible.
</P>
<P>
   ``We're going to be simpler than we've ever been,'' Hackett
said. ``The reason is the quarterback. He was not a starter until
midway through the season and never had a spring.
</P>
<P>
   ``We're going to to go slower than last spring and try to
emphasize the fundamentals.''
</P>
<P>
   There already have been several position changes before spring
practice has started. Defensive end Sultan Abdul-Malik, a two-year
starter at defensive end, is going to spend at least part of the
spring at outside linebacker.
</P>
<P>
   Freshman Miguel Fletcher of Alemany High has switched from
tailback to defensive back. True freshman tight end Jacob Rogers of
Oxnard, who enrolled in the spring, will also be used as a punter
in spring to back up Mike MacGillivray.
</P>
<P>
   Other previously reported changes include tight end Lonnie Ford
and quarterback John Fox to linebacker.
</P>
<P>
   Other than Soward, the only experienced wide receiver is
senior-to-be Windrell Hayes, who caught 24 passes last season.
</P>
<P>
   ``He's the man now,'' Hackett said. ``He should catch more balls
than anybody else on the offense.''
</P>
<P>
   One player who will not participate in spring but is expected to
return to USC this summer is offensive lineman Faasea Mailo. A
part-time starter in 1996, Mailo is finishing up a two-year Mormon
mission in Japan and is expected to attend summer school at USC.
</P>
<P>
   USC will hold 15 practices spread out over the next four weeks,
with a public scrimmage scheduled for April 10 at Howard Jones
Field.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
