u s &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-BKC-SCOONIE-PENN-NYT &LR;      03-25 0872
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BKC-SCOONIE-PENN-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
TRANSFER FROM BOSTON COLLEGE GIVES BUCKEYES A BIG BOOST
</HEADLINE>
   (rk) 
 By   JUDY BATTISTA   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   TAMPA, Fla. _ They knew this point guard was coming to Ohio
State, hard on the heels of the new coach, and they knew fast that
he would be a shot of adrenaline for a dying team.
</P>
<P>
   He and a bunch of walk-ons were killing the starters in practice
last year, the short muscular water bug who had followed Jim
O'Brien from Boston squirting through the first team's defense.
</P>
<P>
   They had heard his unusual name _ a derivation of ``uno''
because he was the first son _ and they had heard he was the Big
East rookie of the year and the most valuable player of its
tournament as a sophomore, in 1997.
</P>
<P>
   But they had no idea he was nuts until Scoonie Penn, the
transfer who played in practice with more ferocity than the team
showed in games, announced at the start of this season that Ohio
State was going to go from last in the Big Ten to the tournament
this season.
</P>
<P>
   Not the National Invitation Tournament, as O'Brien had hoped,
figuring his team might somehow finish above .500. No, Penn meant
the NCAA tournament, the one Ohio State had not sniffed for six
years but that now, with the Buckeyes facing Connecticut in the
Final Four on Saturday, features one of the most remarkable
turnarounds in college basketball history.
</P>
<P>
   ``Coach O'Brien told me to turn it down,'' Penn said, referring
to his talk. ``But I honestly felt that way. Last year, it was
tough, going 8-22 and knowing I couldn't help them out. We were a
young team and we just needed some experience. I watched them work
during the summer and they got experience last season. I just had
this feeling we could do something really good this season. I never
imagined it being this good.''
</P>
<P>
   Who could have? Certainly not O'Brien, the former Boston College
coach who sweated out a few weeks two years ago after he accepted
the Ohio State job while Penn decided what to do.
</P>
<P>
   A tightening of admission standards had scorched O'Brien's
recruiting efforts at BC and led to a bitter split with the
administration of his alma mater. Penn, after starting every game
as a freshman, had been ruled academically ineligible for the first
five games of his sophomore season.
</P>
<P>
   By the end of the season, after Boston College had won the Big
East tournament and with his coach on the way to a place Penn knew
nothing about, he knew he was through, too.
</P>
<P>
   ``It was a very tough decision because it was my home area and
things were going very well for me at Boston College,'' Penn said.
``After seeing the direction Boston College was going in,'' the
future of the basketball program ``wasn't a direction I wanted to
be a part of.''
</P>
<P>
   Penn, from Salem, Mass., barely had a clue where Ohio State was
situated, let alone whether a kid who had the recognition of his
hometown could adjust to a strange place with a failing team.
Penn's decision, which forced him to sit out a year, meant
everything, O'Brien says. He is the only change in Ohio State's
starting lineup from last season.
</P>
<P>
   Penn is averaging 17 points a game and was named the Big Ten
player of the year. After he bruised his hip in the regular-season
finale against Penn State, he struggled in the conference
tournament, and Ohio State lost to Illinois. Penn, now recovered,
and Michael Redd make up one of the best backcourts in the nation.
They have scored more than half of Ohio State's points in the NCAA
tournament, 154 of 296.
</P>
<P>
   Against St. John's in the South Regional final, Penn outplayed
Erick Barkley, scoring 22 points and, with a subtle hand to
Barkley's hip, causing the turnover that clinched Ohio State's trip
here.
</P>
<P>
   Now Penn is the subject of a song on Columbus radio and has been
making statements that he is not leaving for the NBA, even though
he has been told he would be a first-round pick. His play dazzles
even his teammates.
</P>
<P>
   ``Every play he makes is `Wow!''' Redd said.
</P>
<P>
   ``He's the difference in that team from last year to this
year,'' Auburn coach Cliff Ellis said. ``He's not a good guard.
He's a great guard.''
</P>
<P>
   As much as Penn's ability to break a press and shoot were
important to Ohio State's resurrection, his attitude was more
critical. O'Brien arrived to find a group of moribund players, who
had practically come to accept losing.
</P>
<P>
   Penn changed that. He took some of the defensive attention off
Redd, who ceded his role as the offensive star to someone who could
get him into better position to score, and laid some responsibility
on his teammates.
</P>
<P>
   Penn would not accept losing, not even in practice. He was
outspoken but endearing, quickly becoming a leader without
alienating those who had been there before him _ largely because he
already knew O'Brien's system better than the Buckeyes did.
</P>
<P>
   Redd says a number of the players thought they could make the
tournament, but only Penn had the guts to say so publicly. Here was
competitive fire that had been lacking at Ohio State for years.
</P>
<P>
   ``When you have a couple of years in a row, where losses are
piling up, there's a feeling, `That's what we do, we don't win
games.''' O'Brien said. ``He came with a totally different
approach.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
