<SLUG> BC-CANADA-ACCOUNTANTS-500&AMP;ADD-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
KPMG'S CANADIAN UNIT IS PREPARING TO BOLT
</HEADLINE>
   (rk) 
 By MELODY PETERSEN   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   Concerned that their giant accounting firm is not staying
competitive at a time many companies have global operations, the
5,000 accountants and consultants working at KPMG &UR;  &LR; in Canada are
planning to move to the firm of Arthur Andersen, top partners at
both firms in Canada said Thursday.
</P>
<P>
   If the merger of the two Canadian firms takes place as planned,
Arthur Andersen will become the largest accounting firm in Canada,
while KPMG will suffer a blow, possibly losing most of its Canadian
business.
</P>
<P>
   KPMG is now the second-largest accounting firm in Canada and
expects to have revenue of $682 million (Canadian), $452.3 million
(United States), this year.
</P>
<P>
   Upon hearing the news, Colin Sharman, the chairman of KPMG
International, issued a statement saying that the firm would
aggressively fight to keep its most valued Canadian clients.
</P>
<P>
   ``We do not believe this action will have any measurable impact
on KPMG International,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   J. Spencer Lanthier, chairman of KPMG in Canada, said Thursday
that KPMG's top Canadian partners had decided to merge with Arthur
Andersens because of their frustrations that KPMG's hundreds of
offices worldwide were poorly connected, hurting the firm's ability
to serve multinational companies.
</P>
<P>
   For example, KPMG does not have a global e-mail system or voice
system that connects its professionals, as Arthur Andersen does,
although it is working on them. And, while Arthur Andersen operates
as a global partnership, KPMG International is a loose federation
of smaller partnerships in each country.
</P>
<P>
   ``KPMG has been structured as a federation of firms rather than
a global business,'' Lanthier said. ``Although KPMG International
embarked on a global restructuring program last year, we have had
concerns about the high cost of the reorganization and the number
of years it would take to complete.''
</P>
<P>
   Lanthier said that he thought most of the firm's clients in
Canada would move with the accountants and consultants to Arthur
Andersen.
</P>
<P>
   The merger must still be voted on by all partners at both
Canadian firms and be approved by Canadian regulators. The firms
plan to join their operations on Oct. 1.
</P>
<P>
   Sharman of KPMG International said that he was surprised by
Thursday's decision by the 35 partners who manage KPMG's Canadian
operations.
</P>
<P>
   ``The incident was fostered by a leadership that may not be in
touch with the interests of most Canadian partners,'' Sharman said.
``We've already opened a dialogue with key practice leaders among
Canada's partners to insure that the most respected and valuable
portions of the entity remain within KPMG International. We will be
aggressive in preserving the practices and the clients that are
most important to KPMG.''
</P>
<P>
   Sharman said that the partners' decision might have been
prompted by the significant cost of financing the Canadian firm's
pension plan. The Canadians had also been unwilling to help pay for
the costs of uniting KPMG's global offices, he said.
</P>
<ANNOTATION>
   (STORY CAN END HERE. OPTIONAL MATERIAL FOLLOWS)
</ANNOTATION>
<P>
   The Canadian firm had the lowest average net income per partner
of any KPMG firm in North or South America last year, he said.
</P>
<P>
   The proposed Canadian merger is a boost for the international
operations of Arthur Andersen, which is battling its sister firm,
Andersen Consulting. The two Andersen firms make up the global
giant known as Andersen Worldwide. But Andersen Consulting wants to
take its thousands of consultants and become a separate firm.
</P>
<P>
   The last year, Arthur Andersen partners have been aggressively
courting other accounting firms, especially in countries like
Germany and Canada, where they do not have a significant presence.
</P>
<P>
   KPMG now has 5,300 employees in Canada, while Arthur Andersen
has 1,600.
</P>
<P>
   Under the firms' plans, Lanthier would become chairman and chief
executive of the new Arthur Andersen firm. Russel Robertson,
managing partner of Arthur Andersen in Canada, would become a
deputy chairman at the new firm.
</P>
<P>
   Last year, another crack in KPMG's global operations appeared
when many of KPMG's consultants in France left the firm to join the
French consulting practice of the Computer Sciences &UR;  &LR; Corp., which
is based in El Segundo, Calif.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
