<SLUG> BC-GLF-PLAYERS-CHAMPIONSHIP-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
WATTS ,  ESTES SHARE LEAD AT PLAYERS CHAMPIONSHIP
</HEADLINE>
   (rk) 
 By   CLIFTON BROWN   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service  
<TEXT>
<P>
   PONTE VEDRA BEACH, Fla. _ After his first three holes Thursday,
Brian Watts was already 4-over-par.
</P>
<P>
   What was he saying at that point?
</P>
<P>
   ``You probably can't print what I said,'' Watts said.
</P>
<P>
   Fortunately for Watts, his anger became a catalyst. Playing his
last 15 holes in 8-under-par, and climbing to the top of a tightly
bunched leader board, Watts shared first place with Bob Estes after
Thursday's first round of the Players Championship.
</P>
<P>
   Watts and Estes shot 4-under-par 68s, one stroke better than
David Duval, Hal Sutton, and Joe Ozaki. Tiger Woods, Davis Love III
and Jeff Sluman were among nine players tied at 70.
</P>
<P>
   It was an eventful round at the TPC of Sawgrass, and the famous
island green at No. 17 was not surprisingly in the thick of things.
It was kind to some and cruel to others.
</P>
<P>
   Joey Sindelar (72) had a hole-in-one there using a sand wedge
off the tee. Greg Norman (72) tripled-bogeyed the hole, hitting
into the water to hurt what had been solid round. Nick Faldo (71)
played his strongest round in months, but he bogeyed both No. 17
and No. 18. And a frustrated Fred Couples (77) made par the hard
way at the 17th, hitting his first shot into the water, then
hitting his next shot from the tee directly into the cup.
</P>
<P>
   But for Watts, Thursday's blistering finish was the latest
example of his flair for the dramatic.
</P>
<P>
   At last year's British Open, Watts forced a playoff with the
eventual champion Mark O'Meara by hitting a seemingly impossible
shot at Royal Birkdale's 18th hole _ a 50-foot bunker shot, out of
a tough lie from an off-balance stance, that stopped less than a
foot from the hole to save par.
</P>
<P>
   Thursday, Watts pulled the neat trick of tying for the lead,
despite having an 8 on his card. That does not happen often on the
PGA Tour. And it said something for Watts' character that he
refused to fold after such a rugged start on a demanding course.
</P>
<P>
   ``I was 4-over, and then the miracle happened,'' said Watts,
describing his round. ``I tried not to get down on myself. The
worse thing that can happen is either I shoot in the 80s or I miss
the cut. I'm still going to live through the day, most likely.''
</P>
<P>
   Teeing off on the back nine, Watts immediately flirted with
disaster with a triple bogey at the par-5 11th, followed by a bogey
at the par-4 12th.
</P>
<P>
   ``I was like, `What a great start this is going to be,''' Watts
said.
</P>
<P>
   But over his final 15 holes, Watts played like the man who
finished second at last year's British Open, a performance that
earned him $309,260 and a place on the PGA Tour after five years on
the Japanese tour.
</P>
<P>
   Teeing off on the back nine, Watts began his comeback by making
four consecutive birdies, starting at No. 13. And when Watts made a
50-foot chip for birdie at No. 14, he figured his luck might be
changing.
</P>
<P>
   It was also a fun day for Estes, who made six birdies and only
two bogeys. Despite having only one tour victory, the 1994 Texas
Open, Estes is coming off a strong 1998, when he won a career-best
$987,930, including seven top 10 finishes.  &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-03-25-99 2324EST &QL; 
