<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BKN-CLIPPERS-NOTES-LBPT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
MARTIN IS DAY TO DAY
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients)  
<TEXT>
<P>
   &UR; By RANDY HILL &LR;  &QC; 
 &UR; Long Beach Press-Telegram &LR;  &QC;
</P>
<P>
   LOS ANGELES _ When you're 2-23, hype is a ghost, unless judges
will allow the hyperextended left knee of point guard Darrick
Martin.
</P>
<P>
   This injury was accomplished near the benediction of Wednesday's
92-80 loss to Golden State at the Sports Arena. Thursday's MRI
revealed no serious damage, so Martin was given treatment and
listed as ``day to day.''
</P>
<P>
   After Thursday's workout at Carson, he accompanied the team to
Seattle, where tonight it will take on the unsettled SuperSonics.
Martin is scheduled for more treatment, and if all is well enough,
he'll be able to take on Sonic Gary Payton, considered by many
(those who factor in defense) to be the league's best point guard.
</P>
<P>
   ``I won't know until about 7 (p.m.),'' Martin said of his
availability. ``It (the knee) was sore today. I was more scared
last night (Wednesday), because it jerked so fast.''
</P>
<P>
   Should Martin be unable to answer the gong, Troy Hudson will be
the lucky recipient of his first NBA start. Hudson arrived from
Planet CBA on Tuesday with a 10-day contract. He had three
rebounds, one assist, one turnover and no points in Wednesday's
five-minute cameo. Most of his time was spent chasing the vapor of
5-foot-3 Muggsy Bogues.
</P>
<P>
   ``It would be pretty unfair to make a determination on him after
that,'' Coach Chris Ford said. ``But he looked quick and strong.
Maybe he can really play; you never know.''
</P>
<P>
   Hudson still may not know Ford's complete offensive catalog, but
does know he's prepared to play.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'll be ready to go,'' said Hudson, who feels confident of
improving upon his debut performance. ``It felt great to be back
out there, although I was a little shaky on offense.''
</P>
<P>
   Apparently, there's an epidemic. The Clippers scored just 13
points in Wednesday's fourth quarter.
</P>
<P>
   Subhead No `F' for effort
</P>
<P>
   Despite their knack for collapsing, Ford remains pleased with
the attitude and effort demonstrated by his players.
</P>
<P>
   ``I think it's been good,'' he said. ``They're trying to win
games. I'm proud of the way they continue to come to work.''
</P>
<P>
   The weakness du jour was Wednesday's inability to duplicate the
crisp and timely passing that led to Sunday's victory at Minnesota.
</P>
<P>
   ``We spent most of the workout going over our offense,'' Ford
said following Wednesday's practice, ``making sure the ball doesn't
die. We also added a few more options.''
</P>
<P>
   And failing to show up still is not an option.
</P>
<P>
   Subhead `Pike' not in peak form
</P>
<P>
   Eric Piatkowski attended Wednesday's practice, but a strained
right knee prevented the shooting guard from participating.
</P>
<P>
   Piatkowski's knee absorbed two nasty bumps in a recent game
against the Knicks and became a bit tender during the Golden State
game.
</P>
<P>
   He is listed as ``probable'' for tonight's tussle with Seattle.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
