<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-UCONN-HOOP-MANIA-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
TRIP TO BASKETBALL'S FINAL FOUR PUTS CONNECTICUT IN FRENZY 
</HEADLINE>
   (bl)  
 By MIKE ALLEN   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   STORRS, Conn. _ Faced with dark-tinted windows on the charter
bus packed with University of Connecticut basketball players, Steve
Rowe stood on tiptoes, pried open a vent, then stuck his video
camera in to catch some blurry players jostling in the aisles.
</P>
<P>
   Rowe, a machinist from Plainville, had made the hourlong drive
in the rain with his 11-year-old daughter, Chelsea, who began
shrieking for Khalid El-Amin, the star guard. As the bus lurched
away, Chelsea began crying so loudly that she could be heard above
the hundreds who had packed the sidewalk for Wednesday's send-off
to St. Petersburg, Fla., and the team's first trip to the Final
Four.
</P>
<P>
   She'll live. Husky fans have to be resilient. The stats, which
would elate most schools, merely taunt the UConn faithful: ranked
in the final top 10 for six of the last 10 seasons . . . a 1990s
record of 255-74 . . . one of only three schools with at least
seven appearances in 10 years in the Sweet 16 of the NCAA finals .
. . four trips to the Elite Eight.
</P>
<P>
   But until now, never the Final Four. A result is a state
possessed, a place where the Siberian husky has practically become
the state mascot and where hoops is the new common language.
</P>
<P>
   The signs are everywhere.
</P>
<P>
   _ The CBS television station in Hartford, which now calls itself
``Connecticut's Huskies station,'' has broadcast a half-hour
``March Magic'' special every night this week.
</P>
<P>
   _ Optimists, confident that the Huskies will win the semifinal
game on Saturday against Ohio State, are desperately trying to
unload tickets to a Rolling Stones concert in Hartford on Monday
night, when the final will be played.
</P>
<P>
   _ A lawmaker has called for an ``honorary state holiday,''
regardless of how the team does.
</P>
<P>
   _ Patrons of coach's, a sports bar in Hartford, have said they
expect to be at the bar by noon Saturday so they will be sure to
have seats for the 5:42 p.m. tipoff.
</P>
<P>
   _ The state's largest newspaper, The Hartford Courant, started a
front-page feature called ``Final Fourcasts,'' illustrated by an
ice-blue crystal ball. Prognosticators for Saturday's game have
included an actuary (UConn ``a slight favorite'' over Ohio State),
a meteorologist for a St. Petersburg television station (UConn
wins) and a psychic picked randomly from the Yellow Pages (UConn
loses).
</P>
<P>
   _ Throughout the tournament, Gov. John Rowland received updated
NCAA brackets in his daily news summary.
</P>
<P>
   After trying to play it cool all week, Rowland got swept along
and said Thursday that he would fly to St. Petersburg for the
games. As for the idea of statewide holiday, he offered to go one
better. ``Why not take the whole weekend?'' he asked. ``Forget just
Saturday. Let's make it Saturday through Monday.''
</P>
<P>
   While it is not that unusual for cities to go a bit ga-ga when
the local team hits the NCAA jackpot, the UConn frenzy seems a
little broader, with little regard for where people actually went
to college or to their proximity to this tiny college town tucked
away in the rolling hills of eastern Connecticut.
</P>
<P>
   Part of it has to do with the fact that since 1997, when the
Whalers hockey team left for the Sun Belt, Connecticut has had no
professional sports franchise.
</P>
<P>
   Part of it has to do with the state's size; only Rhode Island
and Delaware are smaller. ``Everyone else thinks Connecticut's a
nothing state, so we stick together,'' said Lynn Czernicki, a
third-grade teacher in West Hartford who has attached four speakers
to her television set, the better to hear the Husky sneakers
squeak.
</P>
<P>
   And clearly part of it has to do with the vindication that many
fans feel after all the years of yearning and at-the-buzzer
heartbreak.
</P>
<P>
   ``We always said, `We've got a great team _ they're going to
make it this time,' and then they choked,'' said Susan Killian, 28,
a member of the class of 1992 who is a technology marketer in
Manhattan. ``This should shut a lot of people up.''
</P>
<P>
   Returning to the campus in Storrs this week, coach Jim Calhoun
saluted the disappointed teams of previous years. ``The win on
Saturday was as much for them as it was for this present group,''
he said, referring to UConn's victory last week to secure a spot in
the Final Four.
</P>
<P>
   But there was an edge to his voice in another interview. ``Maybe
people look at what you've done,'' he said, referring to reaching
the Final Four, ``as opposed to what you haven't done.''
</P>
<P>
   In recent years, the basketball fever has also been stoked by
the women's team. This year, both the men and women were
simultaneously No. 1 in the nation for five weeks of the season.
Just a few hours before the men's triumph last Saturday, however,
the women were upset by Iowa State to finish the season 29-5.
</P>
<P>
   Lawrence Gramling, a UConn accounting professor, said that when
he visits other parts of the state for seminars and professional
meetings, people always walk up and start talking about basketball.
``I ask them what year they graduated, and then I find out they
didn't,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   The school's reputation has spread beyond the state's borders.
Other schools have been overwhelmed by the UConn press entourage,
which has become known nationwide as ``the horde.'' The team's
press corps includes reporters from 15 daily newspapers, 5 of which
send two writers.
</P>
<P>
   Now, the Husky rooting section is releasing at least a decade of
pent-up partying. More than 1,000 people bought a $1,300 travel
package through the Alumni Association, which has chartered three
jets to go to St. Petersburg.
</P>
<P>
   If the Huskies make it past Ohio State, and then beat their
opponent in the final, most likely the awesomely strong Duke Blue
Devils, the celebration on the campus seems likely to be limited
only by imagination and the police.
</P>
<P>
   ``When they won the Big East tournament, people burned sofas in
the quad,'' said Mike Longo, 21, a junior from South Windsor. ``I
can't imagine this weekend.''
</P>
<P>
   The university set aside 700 tickets for students, who were
issued lottery numbers. This week, officials posted a list of 350
winners (from reliable No. 10 to lucky No. 2086), who had the
chance to buy two tickets for $100 each.
</P>
<P>
   The list was as scrutinized as anxiously as draft numbers in an
earlier generation. Doug Rumanoff, 18, of Cheshire was a loser, but
a brother in Alpha Sigma Phi knew someone who did not want to use
his winning number and was willing to give it to someone else. ``A
connection,'' Rumanoff said triumphantly.
</P>
<P>
   Some students waited in line for three days for the chance to
buy any leftovers. A brick breezeway outside the gym became a Husky
City as students pitched tents and hauled in recliners and sofa
cushions. They were relieved to discover that Domino's delivers to
hallways.
</P>
<P>
   Drew Humphrey, 22, a senior from Stamford who spent the night in
the breezeway, bought a plane ticket to St. Petersburg last fall.
``I took a big leap of faith,'' he said. ``That's part of being a
Husky.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
