<HEADLINE>
VENUS WILLIAMS GAINS; AND YES, SO DOES SERENA 
</HEADLINE>
   (bl)  
 By ROBIN FINN   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   KEY BISCAYNE, Fla. _ It's not nice to jerk the defending
champion of the Lipton Championships around the court like a
wayward puppy on a leash, but that's precisely what Jana Novotna,
the 30-year-old defending Wimbledon champion, did Thursday to
18-year-old Venus Williams in the opening set of their titanic
2-hour-20-minute Lipton quarterfinal.
</P>
<P>
   For more than an hour, the veteran toyed with the teen-ager,
running her from corner to corner and yanking her rudely toward the
net only to waft a tempting but untouchable lob just over her
beaded head.
</P>
<P>
   For more than an hour, it seemed that the fourth-seeded Novotna
would stretch her reign over the sixth-seeded Williams to 4-0 and
that the Lipton would miss out on a double dose of Williams sisters
in Friday's semifinals and, horrors, be deprived of the potential
for a historic sister-sister finale Sunday.
</P>
<P>
   But Williams, who covets the chance to defend this title the way
she successfully retained her first career title last month in
Oklahoma City, refused to be treated like a novice. With her pride
and her title at stake, she cranked up the power in the second set,
banged her way to a 5-0 lead, and then completed her 5-7, 6-2, 6-3
comeback. She will next face Steffi Graf, who advanced when Lindsay
Davenport withdrew with a sore wrist.
</P>
<P>
   ``I actually had to work for my points; that was a good thing, I
suppose,'' said Williams, who is fighting a cold and withdrew from
the doubles competition Thursday night.
</P>
<P>
   In the upset-riddled men's field, the seventh-seeded Richard
Krajicek, the 1996 Wimbledon champion and the highest-seeded man
still in contention for this title, served himself into Saturday's
final with a 6-4, 6-2 dismantling of the 1999 Australian Open
runner-up, Sweden's 14th-seeded Thomas Enqvist. According to
Enqvist, you can't hit what you can't see. The 27-year-old Krajicek
served blurs on the first serve, winning 20 of 22 points, and
encore blurs on the second, dropping 8 of 27 points. Enqvist's
baselining instincts needed to be superhuman. Instead, he suffered
in silence for 1 hour 16 minutes.
</P>
<P>
   ``I really feel at the moment my game is going up, together with
my confidence,'' said Krajicek, who played himself into form by
downing top-ranked Pete Sampras. He served just nine aces but
produced them at the most opportune moments: his third and fourth
aces converted the first set and he blasted his ninth and final
bullet at match point.
</P>
<P>
   ``I have to take my hat off to Richard, of course,'' said
Enqvist, who encountered zero break chances. ``But I think I made
it a little too easy for him.''
</P>
<P>
   Graf's path to the semifinals became automatic after her
intended opponent, the second-seeded Davenport, abruptly withdrew
from contention, citing the left wrist sprain she incurred hitting
a two-handed backhand during practice five days ago.
</P>
<P>
   ``That's a good thing for her that it's only the left hand, it's
nothing serious, but it makes it not easy if you have to withdraw
out of a quarterfinal; that's a stage where you don't want to
withdraw,'' said Graf, a five-time Lipton champion who has reached
the semifinals or better on all 11 visits here and is 2-1 against
Williams.
</P>
<P>
   Friday's other semifinal features the other Williams sister,
17-year-old Serena, who will test her tour-leading 15-match
unbeaten streak against Martina Hingis. The top-ranked Hingis has a
2-0 edge in their rivalry, but Venus Williams said the odds were
good for a Williams sister final on Sunday.
</P>
<P>
   ``Serena's just come so far just in the past four weeks,'' she
said of her 16th-seeded sibling's back-to-back title spree.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
