<SLUG> BC-BBN-METS-PITCHING-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
METS' PITCHING MATH: ADD HERSHISER AFTER SUBTRACTING NOMO 
</HEADLINE>
   (bl)  
 By JASON DIAMOS   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   JUPITER, Fla. _ One day after officially evicting Hideo Nomo
from their starting rotation, the New York Mets acquired another
former Los Angeles Dodger ace Thursday, signing Orel Hershiser to a
guaranteed one-year $2 million contract.
</P>
<P>
   With the start of the season just a week and a half away, both
moves can be considered fairly radical this late into camp. They
were made in an attempt to stabilize the back end of a pitching
rotation that has looked shakier and shakier as the spring has
progressed.
</P>
<P>
   Hershiser's signing, coupled with Nomo's assignment to the minor
leagues on Wednesday, came amid indications that the Mets were
still interested in making another move to upgrade their starting
rotation, possibly by replacing the team's other struggling
Japanese starter, Masato Yoshii, before the season begins April 5.
</P>
<P>
   According to one person familiar with the Mets' scouting
interests this spring, the team has been taking long looks at a
pair of Seattle Mariners left-handers, Jeff Fassero and Jamie
Moyer, as well as the Oakland left-hander Kenny Rogers and a
Minnesota right-hander, Brad Radke. A Mariners scout was in
attendance here Thursday night.
</P>
<P>
   By bringing in the 40-year-old Hershiser, the Mets add a pitcher
who can provide five or six innings a night and replace one in Nomo
who in less than a year with the Mets could not regain the form
that he had displayed with the Dodgers early in his career.
</P>
<P>
   The day culminated with a pair of scoreless innings from
Hershiser against the Montreal Expos here Thursday night in his
first appearance in a Mets uniform.
</P>
<P>
   Hershiser, who is 10 victories shy of 200 for his career, said
that contrary to popular opinion, he and his family love New York,
which was one reason he spurned higher offers from other teams.
Hershiser had gone to spring training with Cleveland but received
his release; Atlanta, Florida, Philadelphia and the Chicago Cubs
had also sought him.
</P>
<P>
   Meanwhile, Phillips and manager Bobby Valentine tried to dispel
any notions that they may have disagreed on the decision to
outright Nomo to the minor leagues. Phillips went so far as to ask
Valentine if he thought he had been undermined.
</P>
<P>
   ``No, I did not think I was undermined,'' Valentine insisted
Thursday.
</P>
<P>
   One high-ranking member of the organization who spoke on
condition of anonymity said that there was no rift between the
manager and the general manager but that there may have been some
disagreement as to how to proceed with Nomo, with Valentine hoping
that Nomo could have one more chance this spring to pitch.
</P>
<P>
   ``It was a timing thing,'' Valentine said, explaining that he
wanted Nomo to have one more start _ to have 10 more starts, for
that matter. But Valentine also said that Phillips asked him if he
needed to see Nomo pitch one more time before Phillips put Nomo on
waivers. And Valentine said he said no.
</P>
<P>
   Semantics aside, Nomo's agent, Don Nomura, said Thursday that he
and the pitcher were discussing whether to accept the assignment to
the minors. ``We still have until Saturday,'' Nomura said. The Mets
apparently believe that Nomo will accept the assignment rather than
declare free agency, which would exempt the Mets from paying him
this season.
</P>
<P>
   The Mets could still release Nomo. However, Phillips said that
he has been given permission by the team's owners to keep Nomo in
the minor leagues, even though he is scheduled to make $2.925
million this season.
</P>
<P>
   The question now is whether the Mets miscalculated in their
belief that they could resurrect Nomo's career. All spring long,
Nomo struggled with his control, as he had all of last season. Nomo
struggled mightily against Atlanta last Saturday night.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
