<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-SKATE-MEN-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
YAGUDIN CAPTURES GOLD MEDAL AT WORLD CHAMPIONSHIPS, WEISS EARNS
BRONZE 
</HEADLINE>
  (rk) 
 By CHRISTOPHER CLAREY   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   HELSINKI, Finland _ He still had a combination spin and a flying
spin remaining, but as soon as Aleksei Yagudin landed his last
triple jump cleanly Thursday night, he was already pumping his
fists.
</P>
<P>
   Yagudin knew. He knew despite the fact that four men had yet to
skate in the final group, including the younger Russian who had
beaten him in the short program and the Russian national
championship.
</P>
<P>
   Tatyana Tarassova, his coach, knew, too, and she was hunched
over with emotion at rinkside as Yagudin, 19, put the finishing
touches on one of the finer free programs in world championship
history: a program that earned him the unanimous approval of the
nine judges and his second consecutive world title.
</P>
<P>
   Tarassova already had helped one teen-aged Russian with all the
jumps win the gold medal at the 1998 Olympics. But Ilya Kulik
elected to miss the major championships this season, and now, in
less than a year, Tarassova has helped an even better pupil refine
his self-expression.
</P>
<P>
   ``She added so many things, and the most important thing was
feeling all the music,'' Yagudin said. ``The jumps are the same.''
</P>
<P>
   In all, Yagudin landed eight triple jumps and a quadruple toe
loop tonight (the same total Kulik had in Nagano, Japan), and when
he stopped skating gracefully to music from the ``Lawrence of
Arabia'' soundtrack, he dropped to his knees and kissed the ice.
</P>
<P>
   Yagudin, who left his coach, Aleksei Mishin, to train with
Tarassova last year, received no mark lower than a 5.8 from the
judges, and he received a perfect 6.0 from the Polish judge for
technical merit.
</P>
<P>
   The silver medal went to Yevgeny Plushenko, the 16-year-old
Russian who won the short program but could not match his former
practice partner Yagudin's blend of explosiveness and artistry
Thursday night.
</P>
<P>
   The bronze medal went to Michael Weiss, the 22-year-old American
whose performance in the free program was enough to vault him past
Elvis Stojko of Canada, the three-time world champion. It was
Weiss' first medal in a world championship.
</P>
<P>
   Though the Russians have won the first two gold medals awarded
in Helsinki, they are not the overwhelming favorite for a third in
the ice dancing. Friday, the French team of Marina Anissina and
Gwendal Peizerat won the original dance, finishing ahead of the
reigning world champions Anjelika Krylova and Oleg Ovsyannikov of
Russia.
</P>
<P>
   The French team had never beaten the Russians in any phase of an
ice dance competition, but the two teams are now even heading into
Friday's decisive free dance.
</P>
<P>
   In the wake of Wednesday's pairs competition, in which the
Russian team of Yelena Berezhnaya and Anton Sikharulidze won the
gold medal over the Chinese pair of Shen Xue and Zhao Hongbo, there
were allegations of possible collusion among the judging panel.
</P>
<P>
   The Canadian television network, CTV, has video footage showing
communication between a Ukrainian judge, Alfred Korytek, and a
Russian judge, Sviatoslav Babenko, during the competition. Such
communication is against International Skating Union rules, and the
footage was made available to the ISU pairs referee Hely Abbondati
on Wednesday night.
</P>
<P>
   Both Korytek and Babenko placed the Russians first and ranked
the top seven teams in the same order. Abbondati will file a report
to the ISU figure skating technical committee, which will then
review the conclusions and make a recommendation to the ISU
council, which could suspend the judges.
</P>
<P>
   Even without the two judges' votes, the Russians would still
have won the gold, because their first-place margin after the free
skating was 7-2.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
