<SLUG> BC-EDIT-GIULIANI-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
EDITORIAL: THE MAYOR REACHES OUT
</HEADLINE>
   (rk) 
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   The New York Times said in an editorial for Friday, March 26:
</P>
<P>
   New York City Mayor Rudolph Giuliani has finally begun to reach
out to African-American leaders concerned over his administration's
handling of the Amadou Diallo killing. The mayor met this week with
Manhattan Borough President C. Virginia Fields, announced plans to
talk with state Comptroller H. Carl McCall and expressed through
his spokeswoman a desire to begin ``building bridges.''
</P>
<P>
   This is something of a breakthrough for an administration that
insisted for a long time that there were bridges aplenty, and only
a lack of politically objective black leaders willing to march
across them.
</P>
<P>
   This change represents a welcome turnabout by the mayor, and
black and Latino leaders should reject the Rev. Al Sharpton's
attempt to delay the meetings. McCall was right to stick with his
plan to meet with Giuliani.
</P>
<P>
   City Council Speaker Peter Vallone deserves praise for helping
to broker the meeting between Ms. Fields and the mayor, a
discussion that apparently was cordial and involved a sincere
exchange of views. But the fact that Giuliani needed a high-level
mediator to get him to sit down with the highest-ranking black
official in New York City is a sign of how far he still has to go.
</P>
<P>
   To his credit, the mayor has already met privately with church
and youth groups in the minority community. He says he intends to
continue those meetings and take unannounced neighborhood walks.
There is value in these activities and in more public outreach
efforts that show he is listening to people who live in the
communities where resentment of the police is highest.
</P>
<P>
   Police Commissioner Howard Safir has also increased his
outreach, meeting with a group of black ministers that included an
administration critic, the Rev. Calvin Butts, and attending a City
Council meeting on the shooting of Diallo, a West African
immigrant, by police officers.
</P>
<P>
   That does not wipe out the dreadful lapse of judgment Safir
showed in trying to duck the Council meeting while jaunting to
California on a private jet paid for by a Revlon executive.
Although Revlon does not directly do business with the city, the
commissioner's acceptance of expensive transportation and hotel
rooms is too reminiscent of the old, discredited street-cop
practice of taking free meals or sandwiches from friendly
neighborhood grocers and restaurateurs.
</P>
<P>
   The city corporation counsel will decide whether Safir broke any
ethics rules by his conduct. Meanwhile, the commissioner has plenty
of opportunities to demonstrate his sincerity in attempting to
respond to community complaints about the police.
</P>
<P>
   Under this administration, the Police Department has made a
practice of keeping as much information as possible from the press
and public. Like Giuliani, Safir's efforts to win the trust of his
critics will be more successful if he works in the open.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
