A4690 &Cx1f; taf-z
u e &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-THEATER-NOTES-NYT &LR;      03-25 1012
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-THEATER-NOTES-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
NEWS OF THE GREAT WHITE WAY 
</HEADLINE>
  
 (ATTN: Fla.)   (af)  
 By JESSE McKINLEY   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   In what union officials called a victory for directors' rights,
the Society of Stage Directors and Choreographers said it had
completed an out-of-court settlement with a theater in Florida over
its production of ``Love! Valour! Compassion!'' The union said the
theater had used the work of Joe Mantello, the play's director on
Broadway, without his permission.
</P>
<P>
   The settlement, between the union and the Caldwell Theater Co.
of Boca Raton, ends a three-year legal battle. As part of the
agreement, Mantello is to receive about $7,000 as well as a written
acknowledgment that the theater had inadvertently used his work
without his permission.
</P>
<P>
   William McCarthy, the development director and lawyer for the
Caldwell, confirmed the settlement but said it was premature to
comment on it. While the agreement does not resolve the murky
questions of how much of a director's work is protected by law, Ted
Pappas, the president of the union, said he hoped it would set a
precedent.
</P>
<P>
   ``We want our work to be done,'' he said. ``But we want to be
paid for it.''
</P>
<P>
   The case began in March 1996 when Mantello was told by a friend
that the Caldwell's production of ``Love! Valour!'' bore an uncanny
resemblance to the Broadway staging. Mantello saw the show and
agreed.
</P>
<P>
   Mantello later filed a federal action, contending that when a
theater obtains rights to do a play, the director's staging isn't
included. In July 1997 a federal judge upheld the complaint and
cleared the way for a trial. But this week's settlement avoids that
route.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's never been my point to pull apart the collaborative
process of putting together a play,'' Mantello said. ``But a
director can provide original elements to a production and deserves
to be compensated for them.''
</P>
<P>
   &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Happiness? Not Yet &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   NEW YORK _ Producers of ``You're a Good Man, Charlie Brown''
have seen the show's revenues sharply decline in the last few
weeks, and so this week they are undertaking an unusual gambit,
sacrificing evening performances in favor of a more child-friendly
schedule and beginning a pricey advertising campaign.
</P>
<P>
   The effort was formally announced Thursday as producers staged a
news conference complete with representatives of Actors Equity and
the cast singing a version of a song from the show, ``My New
Philosophy,'' with revised lyrics to reflect the production's
revised schedule. (Ah, publicity!)
</P>
<P>
   But the strategy has been in the works since producers saw the
weekly ticket sales for the $4.2 million production fall at the end
of February. Last week the show's gross was $194,550, which
represents a loss of about $30,000. That is not crippling, but not
good.
</P>
<P>
   To counter this, the show petitioned and received special
permission two weeks ago from Equity and the other theater unions
to allow a third Saturday performance, at 11 a.m., in addition to
two on Sunday and a Thursday matinee. (The show will be dark Monday
through Wednesday.) The idea is to target the show's demographic:
children.
</P>
<P>
   ``Kids get up at 7 a.m. on Saturdays,'' said Mick Leavitt, one
of the show's producers. ``Eleven is matinee time for them.''
</P>
<P>
   The show also spent some $400,000 on its first television
campaign, buying time on cable channels like Nickelodeon.
</P>
<P>
   ``Our feeling is we did something very risky: we opened in early
February,'' Leavitt said. ``It's like wearing a T-shirt in winter.
But we're looking forward to starting this campaign, and finally
getting into the tourist season.'' &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Real Prize: Survival &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   NEW YORK _ Producers banking on the magic of a Tony Award may
want to consider this: With Sunday's closing of ``Titanic,'' which
won the prize for best musical in 1997, there is only one survivor
of the bumper crop of musicals that opened that year.
</P>
<P>
   Which one? ``Jekyll and Hyde,'' which was shut out at the 1997
awards, celebrates its 800th performance Saturday.
</P>
<P>
   ``Titanic'' won five Tonys; also nominated for best musical of
1997 were the long-departed ``Steel Pier,'' ``The Life'' and ``Juan
Darien.''
</P>
<P>
   Beyond Marge
</P>
<P>
   NEW YORK _ When Julie Kavner replaces Mo Gaffney in Paula
Vogel's ``Mineola Twins'' on Tuesday, she is stepping into Ms.
Gaffney's sizable shoes, literally, she says.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'm wearing three Dr. Scholl's innersoles,'' Ms. Kavner said.
``They're too big. But there's something kind of nice in the
literalness of it.'' Ms. Kavner's arrival in the show at the
Roundabout Theater was an unexpected twist resulting from Ms.
Gaffney's pregnancy. Ms. Kavner didn't see it coming.
</P>
<P>
   ``I hadn't read the play, and I knew nothing about Paula Vogel's
style,'' she said. ``That's why I'm waking up at 3 in the
morning.''
</P>
<P>
   Ms. Kavner, who splits her time between homes on eastern Long
Island and in Los Angeles, has just begun her 11th season as the
voice of Marge on the animated television series ``The Simpsons.''
While she calls her cartoon persona ``the greatest gig in
America,'' she said she was happy to be onstage for a change.
</P>
<P>
   ``Being animated, you only have control over the performance of
the voice,'' she said. ``You have no control over the body
movement. I prefer to have the whole enchilada.''  &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Along the Way &QL;
</P>
<P>
   _ Boneau-Bryan Brown, the theatrical publicity agency, recently
received a fax from a reporter asking for press seats to a play
called ``Near.'' The staff was flummoxed; the agency handles no
such show. But after several minutes, one employee discerned the
true title the intrepid journalist sought: ``Closer.''
</P>
<P>
   _ Expect a few aching bones on this crew. Producers for ``Night
Must Fall'' said Thursday they will close at the Lyceum after the
matinee on April 11, pack up and aim to reopen a mere two days
later at the Helen Hayes.
</P>
<P>
   _ ``Ancestral Voices,'' a new play by A.R. Gurney, will receive
staged readings at the Mitzi E. Newhouse at Lincoln Center on
Sunday and Monday nights through June 7. Mary Louise Wilson stars.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
