<SLUG> BC-RAC-DRIVER-LADN </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
PARAPLEGIC SECOND AT LOS ALAMITOS
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By KEVIN MODESTI  
 c.1999 Los Angeles Daily News  
<TEXT>
<P>
   O.J. Waddell achieved a larger victory when he drove an
8-year-old mare to second place in a $2,700 harness race Thursday
night at Los Alamitos in Orange County.
</P>
<P>
   Waddell, 37, became the first paraplegic to compete in a
parimutuel race, capping a 17-year licensing battle with California
authorities and other drivers, who had expressed safety concerns.
</P>
<P>
   ``I think I showed them that I do belong,'' said Waddell, a
former Fontana High wide receiver who lost the use of his legs in a
1979 shooting.
</P>
<P>
   Starting from the rail at 10-1 odds, Waddell and the pacer Hutt
Girl followed 3}-length winner Canterbury Tower and driver Steve
Desomer throughout the incident-free race on a sloppy track.
</P>
<P>
   Hutt Girl finished 2\ lengths ahead of third-place Kudos for
Ahab, driven by Jim Lackey, who had criticized Waddell's quest.
</P>
<P>
   ``He (Lackey) told me I did a good job, and that meant a lot,''
Waddell said. &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
