</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BIZGLANCE-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
BUSINESS AT A GLANCE  

</HEADLINE>
  (rk) 
 
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   MICROSOFT OFFER TO SETTLE RECEIVES A COOL RECEPTION
</P>
<P>
   State and federal officials were dismissive of Microsoft's
proposal to settle its antitrust suit, but they said the two sides
would meet for negotiations, probably beginning on Tuesday.
</P>
<P>
   Judge Thomas Penfield Jackson of U.S. District Court has asked
both sides to try to settle the case. As a result, officials said,
even though the Justice Department and state attorneys general
question whether the Microsoft proposal is serious, they feel
compelled to show a good-faith effort.
</P>
<P>
   UNITED AIRLINES PARENT NAMES CHIEF
</P>
<P>
   James Goodwin was appointed chairman and chief executive of UAL,
the parent of United Airlines. The decision by UAL's board ended a
five-month search that had narrowed the choice to Goodwin and a top
executive at General Motors. Goodwin appears to have had the edge
because he was an insider and had cultivated strong relations with
United's unions. He was the unanimous choice of the six-member
executive committee.
</P>
<P>
   STOCKS RALLY ON STRONG EARNINGS
</P>
<P>
   The Dow Jones industrial average surged 169.55 points, or 1.75
percent, to 9,836.39, and the Nasdaq composite index climbed 69.52
points, or 2.94 percent, to 2,434.80, as investors reacted to a
profit surge at Morgan Stanley Dean Witter. The Standard and Poor's
500-stock index gained 21.40 points, or 1.69 percent, to 1,289.99.
</P>
<P>
   Treasury prices sagged as investors awaited next week's Federal
Reserve policy meeting. The yield on the 30-year bond climbed to
5.58 percent.
</P>
<P>
   DIABETES PILL COMES UNDER SCRUTINY
</P>
<P>
   The market for oral diabetes drugs will soon become more
competitive _ but just how competitive may depend in large part on
what action regulators take on Warner-Lambert's Rezulin, a popular
pill that has been linked to 28 deaths and seven liver transplants.
</P>
<P>
   NASD PANEL PROPOSES CHANGES
</P>
<P>
   The board of the National Association of Securities Dealers,
which governs Nasdaq, approved a rule that would allow officials to
halt trading in a stock in response to market news or rumors, even
if the officials cannot immediately reach the company's executives.
It also proposed steps intended to rein in excesses among day
traders and cut fees that investors pay for real-time stock
quotations.
</P>
<P>
   AUDITORS IN CANADA TO JOIN RIVAL
</P>
<P>
   Concerned that their accounting firm is not staying competitive
at a time many companies have global operations, the 5,000
accountants and consultants working at KPMG in Canada are planning
to move to the firm of Arthur Andersen, partners at both firms
said.
</P>
<P>
   BRAZILIAN COMPANIES BORROW AGAIN
</P>
<P>
   Although the mid-January devaluation of Brazil's currency, the
real, initially left foreign investors wary, a handful of Brazilian
companies have resumed borrowing in dollars on global debt markets.
Among them are Banco Bradesco, one of the nation's largest banks,
and the Brazilian unit of Citibank.
</P>
<P>
   The real's devaluation made money for banks that anticipated the
move, like Banco Matrix of Brazil and Chase, JP Morgan and Citibank
in the United States.
</P>
<P>
   P&AMP;G PUTS CONSUMERS IN ADS
</P>
<P>
   It's new and improved! Procter &AMP; Gamble, long known for prosaic,
factual advertising campaigns, has trotted out the old device of
man-on-the-street interviews, but it has updated the device in a
fresh and frisky way.
</P>
<P>
   In one of the largest partnership deals in the short history of
the World Wide Web, online auction site Ebay said that it would pay
$75 million for prominent placement on several services owned by
America Online.
</P>
<P>
   MOBILE PHONE MAKERS TO SHARE DATA
</P>
<P>
   Ericsson of Sweden, the world's No. 3 mobile telephone maker,
and Qualcomm, a US rival, agreed to share access to each other's
technology.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
